<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SPREEWELL ARRIVES, WILLIAMS DEPARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When No. 8 from the University of Alabama was
introduced on Wednesday night at Madison Square Garden, the
smattering of boos were drowned out by the raucous applause. So
much for disgust and indignation. Latrell Sprewell, back from
basketball purgatory after more than a year, received the loudest
ovation of any New York Knick.
</P>
<P>
   A buzz fell over the arena every time he touched the ball in the
first quarter. It was four minutes into the game when he hit his
first shot, a medium-range jumper from 17 feet. People pumped their
fists. Two hand-drawn ``Go Spree'' signs went up.
</P>
<P>
   All net. All forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks came back to the Garden for the first time since last
May, bringing all their assets and liabilities to bear in a
preseason game that meant nothing and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long wait,'' said Sprewell after he brought the
Garden to its feet in his debut. He had 27 points, including 17
during a third-quarter explosion. Putting a slow first half behind
him, he was mostly awesome in 30 minutes. The Knicks won, too,
holding off the New Jersey Nets, 88-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen months,'' he added. ``It's been an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a risky, Off Broadway production that needed excellent
opening-night reviews to make it through the next few months, the
producers that gambled on Sprewell opened their doors, free of
charge, and then prayed no one missed a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward took the public-address microphone and welcomed
everyone back, the referee Don Vaden looked at Knicks Coach Jeff
Van Gundy in the first period and said: ``Nice to see you. I could
kiss you.'' And, for a few brief moments, everything seemed as it
was when we last saw this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, the basketball was awful. From slow-footed
veterans like Patrick Ewing to lost-looking Marcus Camby, the
Knicks were out of sync. The Nets were not much prettier, though
Jayson Williams clearly ate his Wheaties during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Given the layoff and the time it takes for chemistry to develop,
to gauge either of these teams' playoff hopes less than three weeks
into the regular season is premature.
</P>
<P>
   But even on Wednesday, times were changing. Three hours before
Sprewell was introduced, Buck Williams said goodbye. Another aging
warrior committed to memory, making way for the young and the
restless.
</P>
<P>
   During his news conference _ attended by a half-full room of
reporters, Van Gundy and the Knicks president Ernie Grunfeld _
Williams would not bite when asked to draw distinctions between
players from his era and, well, the new guys.
</P>
<P>
   That Williams's last day at the Garden was Sprewell's first did
not resonate with Buck. This was not a morality play. This was the
end of a long, distinguished career, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   He found satisfaction in the fact that the son of a North
Carolina sharecropper might one day send his daughter to the same
Connecticut private school that President Bush's children attended.
The National Basketball Association, he said, had been good to him.
</P>
<P>
   And, in turn, he was good for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players have an obligation to the public to carry themselves
in a certain way and be held accountable,'' Williams said. ``I've
never wanted to do anything to embarrass myself, the organization
and my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things really weighed a lot heavier than some of the
other issues I was confronted with through my career. It made me
want to be a role model and do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   No one garnered more intrigue or attention than Sprewell, the
guy who choked his coach and missed the last 68 games because of
it.
</P>
<P>
   He got a new start with a new team on Wednesday night. In the
first half he had hit 2 of 5 shots, had 2 rebounds and lost 3
turnovers. He was looking as if he was trying too hard to fit in.
But less than a half-hour later, the roar of the arena had opened
up possibilities for him. He went back to being the same aggressive
player who carried a franchise at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third quarter, feeling that rush again after
hitting two shots in a row, he began waving his arms on the
perimeter, yelling at Ward to pass him the ball. Catch. Release.
Swish.
</P>
<P>
   He could not miss, and the Garden could not stay quiet for
several seconds, chanting his name as if he had played in New York
for eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, when he was asked if it felt good to be asked
questions pertaining to the game again, he smiled and said: ``Yeah,
it's all about basketball now. I don't want to rehash the past and
relive everything over and over. I know I'll have to do it
sometimes, but I want to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his second-half binge, it's way too early for
proclamations. Who knows where he goes from here, whether or not
the incident becomes the focal point, a footnote or somewhere in
between.
</P>
<P>
   The best he _ and perhaps any player in the NBA _ can hope for
is to play hard for 17 years, go to the finals twice and make three
All-Star teams and gain and keep the respect of your peers. Just
like Buck Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a great career. Perhaps because he played only the
past two seasons in New York and because of Sprewell's debut, that
fact was overlooked. He scored more than 16,000 points and grabbed
more than 13,000 rebounds and always comported himself like he
cared.
</P>
<P>
   Buck's last night at the Garden. Sprewell's first. An ending, a
beginning and a season of uncertainty ahead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
