<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     01-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ He sleeps soundly again, the pressures and demands of yet
another Super Bowl week notwithstanding. Gary Kubiak's life has
returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
   He's back in his comfort zone, a place of clear focus and easily
deciphered objectives. It's all X's and O's again _ no ?'s.
</P>
<P>
   That Kubiak will be a head coach someday remains a foregone
conclusion. He might even become the first head coach of an NFL
expansion franchise in Houston, should one be forthcoming for the
2002 season. But for now, he would rather follow than lead. He
would rather be charged with implementing a plan than scripting one
from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, he still considers himself ``a young guy with a lot more
to learn.'' In his heart, he didn't believe he was ready to take
over at the University of Colorado. And so, never mind all the
money and prestige on the table, right there for his asking, he
chose to remain at the right hand of Mike Shanahan, his mentor and
the Broncos' mastermind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``this is not a bad gig.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't. Kubiak is one of the highest-paid assistants in
the NFL, pulling down a very comfortable six-figure income, and he
works for a class organization that is a 7{-point favorite to
defend its world championship in Super Bowl XXXIII on Sunday.
Shanahan gives him a sizable piece of the (play) action, too.
Kubiak is more than a clipboard-toting, headphone-wearing parrot.
</P>
<P>
   While Denver's offense may be Shanahan's, it's heavily seasoned
with Kubiak's input. Which, of course, is why he has become such a
hot prospect for any program seeking a fresh face with a winning
pedigree. This is Kubiak's sixth Super Bowl, three spent as John
Elway's backup and three as the middle man between Shanahan and his
quarterback. (One of those came with San Francisco, where Shanahan
was offensive coordinator and Kubiak the quarterbacks coach.)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones talked to Kubiak last year about taking over the
Cowboys. Carmen Policy talked to him this year about the new
Cleveland Browns' post. Colorado did more than talk. The Buffaloes
all but put a contract in front of Kubiak and handed him a pen.
</P>
<P>
   It blew his mind. Literally. He tossed and turned for five
nights. The circles under his eyes grew bigger and darker, causing
the Broncos to kid him about ``how bad I was looking.'' Ultimately,
after enduring extreme anxiety, he concluded he wasn't ready to
take the jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest football decision I've ever had to make,'' Kubiak
said. ``It was a very tempting situation. Dick (Tharp, Colorado's
athletic director) could not have treated me any better. But what I
learned about myself is that I can't go in two directions at once,
and it wouldn't have been smart for me to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed my gut feeling. That was Mike's advice to me: Go
with my gut.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan didn't want to lose Kubiak, whom he trusts implicitly,
but it was Shanahan who made the original phone call to Tharp after
Kubiak expressed interest in the job. Because it's understood every
coach's goal is to be a head coach, those who have achieved said
stature are reluctant to stand in an assistant's way, no matter how
prized he may be.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Shanahan, although he admits he was
``pleasantly surprised'' when Kubiak told him he would be staying
put.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's a heck of a football coach,'' Shanahan said. ``I didn't
want to lose him. But as his friend, I had an obligation to help
him if that's what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it wasn't. Some now wonder if Kubiak's
reluctance to break out on his own, to cut the figurative umbilical
cord that has long bound him to Shanahan, will retard his chances
in the future. There has been fallout speculation that Kubiak lacks
the self-confidence and/or dynamism to head up a program, be it at
the professional or college level.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches are expected to be utterly cocksure in order to be able
to impart same to their players. They're not supposed to be overly
introspective. That's for pointy-headed intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   But Kubiak says he is what he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys could have made that transition (from the Broncos to
the Buffaloes) and never missed a beat,'' he said. ``They could
have taken care of business on both fronts at once without any
problems. But it would have been very hard for me, and I knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kids (at Colorado) needed a coach who was ready to jump
in with everything he had and get them going on their offseason
program. What I would have had to do wouldn't have been fair to
them or to Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems both the Broncos and the Buffs profited from Kubiak's
sending his regrets to Boulder. Colorado wound up hiring a proven
commodity in Northwestern's Gary Barnett, a gung-ho native of the
state, and the AFC champions got to keep their high command fully
intact _ sans distractions _ for the most important game of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Another much-coveted ring is in the offing here. As Kubiak said,
it's not a bad gig.
</P>
</TEXT>
