<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HN     01-28 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ When Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. walked into the Texas
Sports Hall of Fame on Wednesday night, he made it clear that
trying to acquire Toronto Blue Jays pitcher Roger Clemens still was
in his plans.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I had looked forward to talking to Roger tonight,'' McLane
said. ``I wanted to apologize for what transpired in December and
say we still would love for him to be a Houston Astro.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane said he still hopes a trade can be worked out that would
bring Clemens, one of Wednesday's TSHF inductees, to Houston before
the start of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will be a real challenge,'' McLane said. ``Nothing new
has developed, but (Astros general manager) Gerry (Hunsicker)
continues to talk to Gord Ash (the Toronto GM). He told Gerry about
three weeks ago he would get back to us but it would take several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to reactivate it sometime next week and just see what
happens. The first step is you have to make a deal with Toronto.
He's not a free agent. We would have to make a trade that is
agreeable to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is one of the premier players in all of baseball, so
they are going to want some real talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros talked to the Blue Jays in December about a trade,
but the negotiations became acrimonious when Hunsicker held a news
conference to say that Clemens' financial demands for a contract
extension as part of the deal were unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Clemens said he never would play for the
Astros as long as the current management team of Hunsicker and team
president Tal Smith was in place.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens softened his stance last week in comments he made while
playing golf in the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic in California, saying
he still would like to play for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   McLane said he was encouraged by Clemens' comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said when we had the difficulties that time heals a lot of
problems,'' McLane said. ``Then, Roger did a bold step Friday at
the Bob Hope tournament. I was shocked when I picked up the paper
Saturday and saw the positive things he said. Time has healed some
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who won his fifth Cy Young Award in November, said
Wednesday he still has mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My (original) statements still hold true,'' he said. ``I
thought there was a lot of distress for no reason, especially for
my family. But in our profession you have to have fairly thick
skin, and I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going on right now as far as I know, but as spring
training gets closer, we may know more. I'm not worried about
things that aren't in my control.''
</P>
<P>
   One reporter asked Clemens about a published report that said he
had called Astros second baseman Craig Biggio to apologize for his
earlier comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where that came up, but I haven't talked to any
of those guys,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   The question infuriated Alan Hendricks, one of Clemens' agents.
``That may have been the jackass question of the offseason,''
Hendricks said. ``That was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks was asked where the situation stands between Toronto
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's undetermined and dormant,'' Hendricks said. ``But I'm
never surprised by anything in this business. It's unknown until
it's over. I can't say if anything is on or anything is off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks emphasized that no serious discussion would take place
at the TSHF banquet, even though McLane and Hunsicker were in Waco
to see Astros manager Larry Dierker be inducted into the Hall.
Clemens sat next to Dierker on the dais.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know the rules, we are not allowed to talk,'' Hendricks
said. ``We'll say hello (to McLane), and that's it. Besides, I went
to UH. I'm here for (1999 inductees) Hakeem (Olajuwon) and Clyde
(Drexler). Roger is just an added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said he continues to be in contact with Toronto about
Clemens' status and wouldn't rule out a trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it's still within the realm of possibility,''
Hunsicker said. ``The first thing that has to happen is Toronto has
to make a decision whether they are going to trade him. We have let
them know all along, and have continued to let them know, that we
are interested in bringing Roger to Houston if they are interested
in trading him. Our interest has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the ball is in Toronto's court. ``They clearly
have not been very aggressive in their efforts,'' Hunsicker said.
``Where it goes from here, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane said the Astros can't be proactive on Clemens because
commissioner Bud Selig stated Dec. 18 that the discussions must
come from Toronto. Anything else would be tampering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a grasp for where it is, but we certainly would
like to do it,'' McLane said. ``But we can't hurt our team in order
to do this. Toronto knows we can't give up a significant number of
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the summer, when we were trying to make a trade before
the first of August, they wanted five of our top players,
particularly our young players. They wanted (outfielder) Richard
Hidalgo and (pitcher) Scott Elarton, two people who we think are
going to be two of the best in baseball in a few years. We can't
trade away talent like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
