u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-28 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHARLES Barkley took one for the team, all right, but, hey, the one
he took did have six zeros behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley realizes this. He might be bald and his intentions pure,
but he's no Gandhi. He understands. He laughs about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that is not so much fun about the game anymore is
too many people are complaining about money,'' Barkley said. ``It's
all about money for too many guys. I know young guys have to try
and make money, but I was in a situation where I could do something
and help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did. He took one. Million. He put his money where his
mouth was, literally. He signed with the Rockets at the bargain
price of $1 million, knocking down the first domino that cascaded
to Scottie Pippen's feet and helped make the Rockets what they are,
legitimate NBA title contenders.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Barkley agreeing to the cheaper contract instead of
the $2 million or $3 million contract he could have had, Pippen
would not be a Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets should thank Barkley and have. If Pippen earns his
seventh NBA championship ring in Houston, he should point to
Barkley as one of the biggest reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was a selfless act, sure. But it was not selfless like a
Secret Service agent taking a bullet or a father pulling three
shifts at the plant in order to sock away some bucks for his kid's
college fund.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley realizes the irony of it all, the skewed righteousness
of being a Million-Dollar Martyr.
</P>
<P>
   If taking a $1 million salary is the greatest act of
selflessness this state has seen since the battle of the Alamo,
like some would say Barkley's move was, then we should all don
coonskin hats, raise our muskets and take one for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Chuckster!
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should remember this instead: The grandest thing
Barkley did during the long offseason had nothing to do with money
or ``sacrificing'' a couple of million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It had to do with the game Barkley always has loved and the way
he committed himself to it quietly during the lockout, when the
notepads were shut and the cameras off.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley sacrificed himself the way he did as a kid, the way
youngsters on the way to a scouting combine would sacrifice
themselves _ with the lonesome thumping of a basketball in a gym,
working on his game.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every day since undergoing offseason double hernia
surgery, Barkley would run in the morning, play golf in the
afternoon and lift weights in the evening. He put in the hours. He
mixed in some O'Doul's.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough regimen, and for this Hall of Fame-bound
multimillionaire, it might have been a tougher sacrifice than
taking a mere $1 million for one season.
</P>
<P>
   It was about basketball. It was about still playing, being
embarrassed about the way his play all but became a series of
predictable post-up moves a year ago. It was about chasing the
championship ring he craves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy took care of his body,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``He was on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest sacrifice Barkley made and maybe the reason a
championship is indeed on the horizon for these Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the bad Charles Barkley last year,'' he said,
referring to the pain in his lower abdomen that kept him from
flying to the basket, blocking shots or slashing through bigger men
to tip in an offensive rebound. ``I've been a quickness player my
whole career. I didn't feel explosive at all last season. When I've
got my back to the basket, I'm really not in an aggressive mode. I
don't want to back it in so much this year. I want to beat guys off
the dribble.''
</P>
<P>
   And there he was Tuesday night against the San Antonio Spurs,
taking it high over Tim Duncan, blocking shots, slashing through
the lane and beating guys off the dribble. After only one full day
of training camp, Barkley was trim, dominant and looking like a
Million Dollar Man and then some.
</P>
<P>
   The sacrifice looks like it will pay off, but not the sacrifice
that had to do with money. The likes of Cleveland Cavaliers star
Shawn Kemp and others entered the shortened preseason practically
sweating cheeseburgers; Barkley entered in the best shape in which
he has been in years and must have the league sweating bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs center David Robinson raved. He called him ``Mr. Barkley''
after Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said Barkley was ``very frisky'' and ``Charles
Barkley at his best.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 22 points and 11 rebounds in 36 minutes. There was
all sorts of potential flying across the Compaq Center floor, and
Barkley, as much as Hakeem Olajuwon and Pippen, was at the center
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else can you make a million dollars for playing
basketball and people are complaining about it?'' Barkley said.
``You're making a million dollars for two hours of work a night.
There's something wrong if you don't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   He took one for the team _ one shot, one sprint and one plate of
weights at a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
