<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSEN-     01-28 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Atlanta kicker Morten Andersen has to visualize each field
goal. At practice, he gets a scenario in his mind _ usually it's a
game-winner he's attempting _ then pictures the defenders rushing
at him as the ball leaves his foot and invariably flies smoothly
through the uprights.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a ritual that worked in the NFC Championship Game as he
booted a 38-yarder in overtime to send the Falcons past Minnesota
and into the Super Bowl. Overall, it has worked 25 times for the
NFL's record holder for game-winning kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing went through my mind,'' Andersen said. ``I was just
reacting. I was on automatic at that point, and I just became a
kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the record for game-winners, it was Andersen's first in
a postseason contest. Then again, after playing his entire 17-year
NFL career in New Orleans and Atlanta, he has been in only seven
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only tougher situation he faces is in training camp, when
if he misses the field goal in practice, the guys have to run
conditioning,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves joked.
</P>
<P>
   After the points go on the board, or in the rare instance the
kick misses, Andersen erases his mind, focusing instead on the rest
of the game. It's this ability that allows him to kick without
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball leaves your foot, and the kick leaves your mind,'' he
said. ``The pressure associated with important kicks is a perceived
notion, something created by the fans and media. As long as I'm
relaxed and at peace, then pressure is nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen finds peace in unusual places such as Nepal, where in
the not-too-distant past he took a mountain-climbing expedition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was the thin air, but it was an amazing experience,''
he said. ``The air was so crisp and clear. You're up in thin air.
It was a very spiritual thing _ the Buddhists, the Hindus. It
changed my life completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there, and it cleared my mind. It opens you up to a
whole different world how silly you sometimes are when you take
yourself too seriously. A simple life is what it's all about; a
simple life is a happy life.''
</P>
<P>
   It also gave him perspective on his career, which should
eventually lead to a spot in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 1 billion people in China who could care less about
what I do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are several million in Georgia, however, who care a great
deal.
</P>
<P>
   And Andersen admits he's enjoying the records he's compiling. He
holds seven NFL records, including consecutive games scoring at
least one point (237), most 50-yard field goals (35), most
50-yarders in a game (three), most 100-point seasons (12) and most
Pro Bowl appearances by a kicker (seven).
</P>
<P>
   He is third on the career scoring list with 1,761 points, 241
behind leader George Blanda and 84 behind the Vikings' Gary
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, 38, has two more years on the three-year, $2.7 million
contract he signed with the Falcons. He would need to average 121
points in those two years to surpass Blanda. He has scored 120 or
more four times in his career and 91 or more every year since his
rookie season in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, any time I thought about the scoring record,
it was like, `Well, that's so far out there that it's pie in the
sky,''' Andersen said last February when he signed his most recent
deal. ``But suddenly, it's not so far off. I feel like I've put
myself in a special position, and getting the record has become my
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting records in the United States isn't exactly what Andersen
pictured as a boy. Born in Copenhagen, Denmark, he was raised in
Struer, a town of 9,000. At age 17, he came to the United States as
a foreign-exchange student in Indianapolis. He was a star soccer
player with dreams of making the Danish national team when he was
first exposed to football through the family who housed him.
</P>
<P>
   His high school coach asked him to attempt a field goal, and he
easily booted a 50-yarder. He joined the team and eventually earned
a scholarship to Michigan State, where he set a Spartans record
with a 63-yard field goal during his final season.
</P>
<P>
   But while Andersen has had a spectacular NFL career, he hasn't
enjoyed a lot of team success. He was in the league six years
before the Saints made their first postseason appearance, and New
Orleans went to the playoffs four times during Andersen's 13
seasons there, losing each game. He was in Atlanta during the 1995
playoff season, and the Falcons also lost in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has made 11 consecutive postseason field goals,
including the game-winner in Minnesota, and is 14-for-16 for his
playoff career. He is perfect on 12 extra points in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the patience (to wait for postseason success),''
Andersen said. ``The longer you play, and it's not happening, you
start saying, `Man, another year's gone by, and it didn't happen.'
But then you line up the next year, and you go again. You get busy
in the offseason, and you prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt when Dan came in here that something special was
going to happen with this football team, and I never lost faith.
That's why we play, believe me. This right here is 17 years of
faith and hard work, and I'm just thrilled to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Andersen could script it, he would love to have a shot at
winning the Super Bowl with a kick, just as he did the NFC title
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Dan (Stryzinski) and Adam (Schreiber), who are two
very important people in my professional career _ the snapper and
holder _ and they said it would be OK with them if we repeated it
this week,'' Andersen said. ``So we're going to try to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
