<HEADER>
A1839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ELAM-HNS &LR;      01-28 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ELAM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Denver kicker Jason Elam would like nothing more than to
line up for a field goal that would give the Broncos their second
consecutive Super Bowl victory.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He would love an opportunity to kick the biggest field goal of
his life before the largest television audience, a field goal that
would give Broncos-crazy Colorado back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a little bit crazy to be a kicker in the first
place, so naturally you'd love to be in that situation,'' Elam said
Wednesday. ``As a kicker, you're going to be under a lot of
pressure sooner or later, so you might as well enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam is enjoying the best season of his six-year career. Not
only did he kick a 63-yard field goal to tie Tom Dempsey's NFL
record, but he scored 127 points and was voted to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Elam has a chance to earn a second Super Bowl ring.
If it were not for him, the Broncos might not have made it beyond
the AFC Championship Game. In a wicked wind at Mile High Stadium,
Elam kicked three field goals in Denver's 23-10 victory over the
New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, I envision every situation I could face in the
game,'' he said. ``When I get to the stadium, I look at every
angle. I want to know where the wind can be blowing from, where the
sun will be. I don't want to leave anything to chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I make every kick. I never envision myself
missing. It's the power of positive thinking. Be positive, and you
will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam, who played at the University of Hawaii, says he has missed
only one game-winning kick in his career. That's enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was Matt Bahr who said, `The joy of making a kick
is nowhere near the anguish of missing one,' and I believe that,''
Elam said. ``Thank goodness I've only missed one big one in my
career. I know how bad I felt about that one, and it was in the
regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam felt terrible for his friend, Minnesota kicker Gary
Anderson, whose only miss in an otherwise perfect season helped
cost the Vikings the NFC Championship Game against the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I really felt for Gary,'' Elam said. ``He's a great
kicker and a great guy. He's had a great career, and that was
something every kicker hopes never happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's miss wasn't all bad for Elam. He grew up in
Snellville, Ga., and the Falcons were his favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I've been a Falcons fan for as long as I can remember,''
he said. ``I was a fan when Steve Bartkowski was the quarterback
and Mick Luckhurst was the kicker. I used to live and die with what
the Falcons did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always look on ESPN to see what they did. It's going to be
tough to root against them, but I'm going to have to root against
them one time. This game is going to be pretty special for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After each season, Elam packs up his family and returns to
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We U-Haul it,'' he said. ``That long drive gives me time to go
back over the season. It's actually very relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we do it? Because that's my home. That's where my
family and friends are. I'm just Jason. I'm not Jason the football
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam's Super Bowl counterpart is Morten Andersen, one of the
greatest kickers in NFL history. But Andersen, whose overtime field
goal beat Minnesota, has kicked indoors in nine straight games,
which some believe will be an advantage for Elam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, but Miami's not a bad place to kick,'' Elam said.
``There's not a lot of swirling wind down here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does make a difference when you kick in conditions
you're used to. I know I have a problem kicking off (artificial)
turf if I haven't kicked on it in a while. When I was in college, I
had a problem going onto grass. It's a case of what you're used to,
but the best kickers don't have much problem adjusting.''
</P>
<P>
   When he tied Dempsey's record this season, Elam got more
attention than for anything else he has done in a successful
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' he said. ``Nobody's going to get mad if you miss
a 63-yard field goal, so I just relaxed and crushed it. It was fun
when I made it, and it was fun for the week after it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elam would give up that record-tying field goal for one
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? I'd rather have a perfect season than the
63-yard field goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos won their first 13 games before they were upset by
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told some people that, and they think I'm crazy,'' Elam
said. ``They wonder why I'd give up that field goal for a perfect
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why: The field goal made history, but it's an
individual thing. A perfect season would make history, too, and
it's a team thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
