<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT NETS, 88-87 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As his awkward early appearance morphed into a sight
so sleek and silky on Wenesday night _ a Knick vision formerly
uncommon in Madison Square Garden _ Latrell Sprewell rode the
swells and curls of the crowd's mood swings like a surfer.
</P>
<P>
   He hung in there. And he went from the bumbling and booed
Sprewell who turned over the ball on an isolation play in the first
half to the supremely confident former All-Star who slashed to the
basket and dared anyone to play him on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   So it was true. Sprewell was prone to dangerous outbursts. This
one manifested itself as basketball excellence as he went on a
17-point spurt in the third quarter against a mystified and
injury-riddled New Jersey Nets team. Sprewell's game-high 27 points
led the New York Knicks to an 88-87 victory in their first of two
exhibition games before the regular season begins next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When Sprewell, who shot 11 of 14, went to the bench for a
breather with less than 11 minutes left, he received a standing
ovation. His teammates crowded around him, chest-bumped him and
embraced their new star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let fans know what he was before the Golden State
incident,'' Larry Johnson said. ``He was a player in this league.
And with the moves he made tonight, he brought all those memories
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The welcome mat had been extended, and Sprewell's 14-month exile
from basketball had come to a rousing end.
</P>
<P>
   Any dust that had settled on his acrobatic game had been shaken
off. But Patrick Ewing, who was 3 of 9 for 6 points and had 4
turnovers, was not so fortunate. He plodded through a clumsy
performance, looking like a soft shell of his former self.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sprewell, Ewing had not played a regular season game in
over a year. Like Sprewell, he was greeted with mixed reviews. One
All-Star had choked his coach. The other had squeezed the trigger
on the National Basketball Association lockout. Neither act was
forgotten by the crowd. But the treatment was relatively mild. Few
hecklers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the admission was free. Perhaps that made the Knicks'
unsightly appearance in the first half a little easier to take. At
that moment, the redesigned Knicks looked far removed from a
completed project.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were harder to judge. They were facing the Knicks
without a Keith Van Horn, who had food poisoning, and Kerry
Kittles, who had back spasms and a knee injury. But they did have
Jayson Williams (9 points, 7 rebounds) springing up and down on the
court for 26 minutes, revealing why the Nets spent nearly $100
million to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Williams was proving himself, so was Sprewell. After he
blew an open 3-pointer and nearly missed a double-pump dunk in the
first half, Sprewell leaned on his good defense for inspiration and
turned in a shockingly strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my legs at first,'' said Sprewell, who made his
last nine shots. ``But the crowd, I thought, was still there for
me. It was great to get them behind me. I couldn't have asked for
anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing couldn't do it, Sprewell picked up the entire team.
His third-quarter performance _ decorated with back-to-back jumpers
and a nifty driving layup _ sent the Knicks into a groove. Until
then, the Knicks had been misfiring. They went from an 8-point
deficit to start the third quarter to a 72-63 lead as Sprewell
departed with 10 minutes 27 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's explosive,'' Allan Houston said. ``He makes
everyone around him better.''
</P>
<P>
   As union president, Ewing had spent the last six months in a
boardroom discussing revenue sharing. In his isolation, his weight
ballooned and muscles softened. At age 36, his body does not snap
to form the way it used to. That was visible as he began panting in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I was rusty,'' Ewing said. ``But I think I played
better than people thought I would.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. A livelier Williams was circling him for rebounds as
if he were a traffic cone for rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Paging Charles Oakley. Oakley's absence was noticeable from the
beginning as the Nets had no fear in driving to the basket. The
more Ewing struggled with his ball-handling _ turning the ball over
and mishandling rebounds _ the more the Knicks needed his old
sidekick to prop him up. The Knicks were outrebounded, 44-37, for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who said we wouldn't be able to rebound this year
were right tonight,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Right now, we
have about three guys who we're going to rely on but who are not in
NBA shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Sprewell looked like a man who had not played in over
a year. As expected, his layoff showed in his offense more than
defense. He rebounded well, but his shooting and timing were out of
sync. Still, Sprewell's conditioning was not the issue, not as it
was for Ewing. As the game went on, Sprewell looked stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did some good things,'' Van Gundy said. ``He attacked the
basket, which is good. I thought offensively, he was better than I
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   For one night, whatever reservations the crowd had about
Sprewell at tip-off _ when he was received with a tepid response _
quickly disappeared by the end of the game. What incident with P.J.
Carlesimo? The way he played last night was a perfect indication of
how quickly fans can forget and forgive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
