<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT UPSET BY UNSEEDED MAURESMO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ The brush fire that has transformed
unseeded men's tennis players into world beaters jumped genders on
Thursday, and Lindsay Davenport was the star who got burned in the
semifinals of the Australian Open against a 19-year-old Frenchwoman
named Amelie Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo's 4-6, 7-5, 7-5 upset of the No. 1-seeded Davenport on
a humid afternoon at Melbourne Park sent yet another shock wave
through the year's first Grand Slam tournament and earned Mauresmo
a place in Saturday's final against No. 2 seed Martina Hingis or
No. 6 seed Monica Seles, who were to play in Thursday's second
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I got my foot through the door and thought I was
going to get through to the end, it got shut on my foot,''
Davenport said. ``It's disappointing. I haven't had a match slip
through my hands in a long time, so it's hard to take, especially
in the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   The match was a struggle from the beginning, when Davenport had
to save five break points just to hold her serve at 0-1. She would
soon take a 5-2 lead, often pushing the French teen-ager onto her
back foot with her relatively flat power from the baseline. But the
first sign that it would be an unusual afternoon came when
Davenport served for the set and was broken when Mauresmo fired a
forehand return winner cross court.
</P>
<P>
   The American would close out the set but she would prove unable
to close out another one against the athletic Mauresmo, ranked
29th, whose aggressive ground strokes, well-struck first serves and
line-to-line court coverage created problem after problem for
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   In their only previous match, Mauresmo defeated Davenport in
straight sets on clay in at the German Open last spring. That
tournament, one of the more prestigious on the WTA Tour,
represented Mauresmo's breakthrough as a professional. She had to
qualify to reach the main draw and though she lacked the
consistency to back up that performance the rest of the year,
Yannick Noah thought highly enough of her abilities to select her
to play Fed Cup singles against Switzerland in July, passing over
Wimbledon finalist Nathalie Tauziat in the process.
</P>
<P>
   With her broad shoulders and strong chin, Mauresmo is a
physically imposing figure, but unlike other power players, she
flows around a tennis court. Her footwork is one of her strengths,
and she is not afraid to take risks by pushing forward.
</P>
<P>
   After saving two match points in the first round against Corina
Morariu of the United States, she has upset No. 8 seed Patty
Schnyder, No. 11 seed Dominique Van Roost and now Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back from match point, my coach told me that
usually when it happens like this, players are winning the
tournament and going very far, so I guess he was right,'' Mauresmo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo's coach, Christophe Fournerie, has not been with her
for long. She hired him in December, shortly after separating from
her South African coach Warwick Bashford. She came to Melbourne
with Fournerie and her friend Sylvie Bourdon, who works in the
Saint-Tropez and is the reason Mauresmo moved there recently.
</P>
<P>
   A former world junior champion, Mauresmo is part of the fine
generation of young French women's players known as the ``class of
`79'' for the year of their birth dates. It also includes
Anne-Gaelle Sidot and Nathalie Dechy, but Mauresmo is now in a
class of her own, as her poised and powerful performance on Center
Court made clear.
</P>
<P>
   In her first Grand Slam semifinal, she showed few signs of
nerves, and in the third set, in which she was twice down a break,
she rallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's acting like a champion out there,'' Davenport said.
``For as good as she played, I still let it get away at the end,
which is disappointing. But all credit to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
