<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Gold as a standard of stability  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One traditional January staple that has been conspicuously
absent from the airwaves is the blitz of commercials touting gold
as a good investment bet.
</P>
<P>
   Usually about this time of year the glories of gold are being
pitched regularly by radio hucksters to those looking for a hot New
Year's tip on how to make some quick money.
</P>
<P>
   Past ad campaigns seemed designed to appeal to two basic groups.
One was clueless novices, who perhaps awakened New Year's morning
thinking now is the time to start building a nest egg after
delaying for too long. The other was die-hard goldbugs, who were
being reminded to recommit because the end of gold's blahs was
near.
</P>
<P>
   Could the dearth of gold investment commercials be a contrarian
signal of a buying opportunity because gold's price has actually
hit bottom? It would be hard to make a convincing case for this
argument. Besides, with the Internet-related sector of the stock
market making such fantastic gains, gold is starting to look
downright quaint.
</P>
<P>
   The price of gold now is pretty much where it was last year.
It's trading in much the same range as last January, while the
performance of gold investments has generally tracked the metal
itself.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting insights to emerge concerning gold
from the welter of recent investment analyses came from John
Dessauer, who's one of the more prescient seers in the business.
Dessauer predicted in a recent client advisory that as the dollar
recovers this year, gold would come under increasing pressure.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that as lackluster as gold was during the past year,
its price still had held up better than most other commodities.
This may change, however, and gold could begin the same sort of
slide as oil and other commodities have experienced. If so, he
mused, $200 an ounce ``is possible'' in 1999, which would be about
30 percent off its current price.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario, he said, also would lead to lower interest
rates, because the Federal Reserve would have no choice but to
follow the trend of the markets and cut rates again.
</P>
<P>
   The bane of goldbugs is what is making the world so much
brighter for most other investors and speculators. Inflation at the
retail level is under control because business competition has
diminished the pricing power of most consumer-oriented enterprises.
Meanwhile, many of the commodities and other inputs used to bring
products to retail market are in a deflationary mode.
</P>
<P>
   As long as inflation isn't a threat, it's nearly impossible for
gold and other precious metals to yield any significant investment
rewards. Gold, silver and other precious metals are currently
nothing more than commodities in a world of commodity deflation.
Thus, gold's historic role as a store of value has become a tenuous
thing for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The price of gold has historically been viewed as a barometer of
the world's anxiety level. If this is still a valid economic role
for gold, its price behavior over the past couple of years is
conveying a welcome message: Despite problems in Asia, Russia and
Latin America, the world remains relatively calm in the face of
turmoil that in the not-so-distant past would have sent the price
of gold soaring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 0020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORD-VOLVO-NYT &LR;      01-28 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-VOLVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SEEN IN DEAL FOR VOLVO CAR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. plans to announce on Thursday that it will
acquire the passenger car operations of Sweden's A.B. Volvo for
between $6 billion and $7 billion, the latest step in the
consolidation of the global auto industry, people close to the
talks said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers around the world are rushing into deals because they
fear a coming shakeout in the industry, in which the only survivors
will be the lowest-cost producers with the greatest economies of
scale from large-scale production.
</P>
<P>
   Close to a decade of massive investment in new assembly plants
in places like South Korea, Thailand and Brazil have left the
global industry with the capacity to produce 75 million cars and
light trucks a year, yet global demand is only 50 million vehicles
a year and steadily eroding as a result of economic crises in East
Asia, Russia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's deal follows last year's $33 billion
acquisition of the Chrysler Corp. by Daimler-Benz A.G. of Germany
and a series of smaller deals, like Volkswagen A.G.'s acquisition
of Rolls-Royce. More deals seem likely: the Nissan Motor Co.,
deeply in debt, has been in talks to sell a stake to the new
DaimlerChrysler A.G. or to France's Renault, while Fiat S.p.A. has
been looking for ways to expand through acquisitions, including an
unsuccessful bid for Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly noteworthy about the Volvo and Chrysler
deals is that they involve financially strong companies with many
popular models. Neither company had to merge to remain independent.
Yet in each case, the costs of developing new cars and new engines
for a global market seemed enormous, and too difficult to spread
over the limited number of vehicles they sold.
</P>
<P>
   Feverish speculation about further mergers in the auto industry
is actually increasing the likelihood of additional deals. Big auto
makers like Ford have been reassessing whether they can buy
well-known but low-selling brands like Volvo and then expand sales
dramatically by using their own huge and often underutilized
factories to build the new models.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that other auto makers might snap up the remaining
independents first has prompted executives to move much faster than
they would have otherwise, and with a less thorough examination of
acquired companies' ledgers than might otherwise be the case, said
a top Detroit auto executive who insisted on anonymity. ``Once one
girl on the dance floor has been taken, the rest suddenly look
prettier,'' said the executive, using a sexist analogy popular in
the Motor City.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques A. Nasser, Ford's chief executive, said two weeks ago at
an industry conference that auto makers selling fewer than a
million cars a year could not remain independent indefinitely.
Volvo sold 399,700 cars worldwide last year, while Ford sold 6.8
million and Fiat sold 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's purchase of Volvo could still face obstacles in Sweden. A
planned merger of Renault and Volvo collapsed in late 1993 after
mid-level Volvo managers publicly complained that French auto
executives were already ordering them around, and small Swedish
investors in Volvo responded by organizing a campaign against the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of similar protests this time was a critical
factor in Volvo's decision to reject a slightly higher bid from
Fiat earlier this month, people close to the negotiations said.
Volvo executives were worried that Fiat would try to play a more
direct role in managing the Swedish auto maker than Ford, which
bought Jaguar a decade ago and has spent billions of dollars to
revive it while replacing relatively few managers.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat is not nearly as wealthy as Ford, and would have been under
much more pressure to cut Volvo's costs and start reaping profits
quickly to recoup its investment. Fiat has only $1.5 billion in
cash, compared with Ford's massive $23.8 billion, one of the
largest corporate cash hoards anywhere in the world, accumulated
mainly from eight years of steeply rising sales of high-profit
sport utility vehicles in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is the world's second-largest auto maker, but the addition
of Volvo will not be enough to make it bigger than the General
Motors Corp., the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has long been interested in buying Volvo's car operations.
Volvo is strong in northern Europe and among affluent urban buyers
in the northeastern United States, two markets where Ford is weak.
Ford also hopes that Volvo's reputation for safety can be
transfered to other Ford brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
