<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-HERO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, 4, GETS EARLY START ON GOAL TO BE FIREFIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FERNANDO, Calif. -- Andrew Quezada wants to be a firefighter
when he grows up, just like his grandfather. But the 4-year-old
didn't have to wait nearly that long to be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the little boy from suburban Sherman Oaks in the
San Fernando Valley area northwest of downtown Los Angeles was
honored for discovering a fire in a relative's home New Year's
night and getting everyone out. Firefighters said he saved the home
and was probably the reason why all 25 people at a family
celebration were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said he wasn't afraid. He just followed what his granddad
told his preschool class during a fire-safety presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandpa told me to say FIRE! He told me to go out and save
all the people. I said FIRE! FIRE! FIRE! FIRE!'' Andrew emphasized
the word, as he had done that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud of him,'' said his grandfather, Ed Gonzalez, an
18-year veteran in the Los Angeles Fire Department. ``I couldn't
wait to see him and let him know how important that was. Andrew is
a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Other firefighters, sponsoring the ceremony, agreed with
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy with a crew cut and gleaming brown eyes was with
relatives celebrating New Year's Day in Hollywood. During a
barbecue that night at a cousin's home, Andrew was playing inside
with two cousins, Elena Lopez, 5, and Gabriela Maraga, 4. ``We were
trying to make a tent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he heard a smoke detector blaring, so he left to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I smelled fire, and I heard the bell ringing. That means there
was fire,'' Andrew said matter-of-factly. ``I went looking and I
saw fire, and I went to get all the people.''
</P>
<P>
   He spotted flames where a candle had tipped onto a heater and
ignited. He closed the door behind him -- as his grandfather had
instructed -- and went to get his cousins. Then he led the other
kids outdoors to alert the adults, again on his grandfather's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us were outside the house when these kids started
screaming there's a fire, there's a fire!'' said his paternal
grandfather, Luis Quezada. ``At the beginning we didn't pay too
much attention because kids say so many things. Then I could see
the look on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed to the blaze, the adults managed to extinguish it
themselves. It caused only minor damage to the house and was out by
the time firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times we teach our kids, not knowing if they're going
to remember anything. You hope one thing sinks in,'' said Gonzalez,
47, of Canyon City. ``That day Andrew remembered everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department spokesman Capt. Steve Ruda said the incident
illustrates the need for working smoke detectors in the home. More
important is knowing what to do if one goes off.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate Andrew's deed, Gonzalez and the other firefighters
from Station 75 returned Wednesday to St. Mark's Preschool in
suburban San Fernando in the valley, where they had given a safety
presentation to Andrew's class in October. This time they brought a
replica fire helmet and yellow firefighter's coat for the
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``My little hero,'' said Andrew's mother, Alishea Quezada. ``He
knew not just to run out himself, but to get his little cousins out
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her son clamors to visit Gonzalez at the fire station.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves to wear my dad's stuff. He loves to put his feet in
the boots. He won't take his hat off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As Andrew donned his own miniature turnout coat Wednesday,
someone asked what he wants to do for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a fireman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attaboy,'' said his beaming grandfather. ``I hope I'm still on
the job when he's old enough to be.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
