<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHANDLER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRIS CHANDLER FINDS MORE THAN SUCCESS IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Chris Chandler is doing his darndest to focus on the
now.
</P>
<P>
   In four days, the quarterback from Everett (Wash.) High School
and the University of Washington will lead the Atlanta Falcons into
Super Bowl XXXIII against the defending champion Denver Broncos.
It's a tossup as to which is more surprising: His team's rise to
its elite status, or the fact that Chandler has been so vital to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody pinch this guy, right? It wouldn't help. Chandler's
skin has turned tortoise tough during a trying NFL career that saw
him play for five teams in his first nine seasons before finally
finding a home, and feeling at home, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It's a past that won't let Chandler forget. No matter how hard
he tries.
</P>
<P>
   Each day this week, his interview sessions have started with,
and been peppered with, questions about events that prompted him to
bounce from the Indianapolis Colts to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers to
the Phoenix Cardinals to the Los Angeles Rams to the Houston
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, Chandler attempts to stay his current course by
explaining how his attention must be on the Broncos, and the
biggest game of his career and that of a franchise with a past as
dreary as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, there has been another question about what happened
in Indy. Or Tampa. Or Arizona. Or L.A. Or Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They are stories worth retelling, if only because they tell so
much about how far Chandler has come.
</P>
<P>
   Those were emotional times and, unfortunately for Chandler, he
was an emotional player. Too emotional for his own good on too many
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handled it better as I got older,'' Chandler said Wednesday.
``Early on, I was probably the worst guy at handling it. I talk
about being immature, and that's kind of what I'm talking about. I
became the effect of things that happened to me that were actually
out of my control.''
</P>
<P>
   It almost did him in.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who grew up the ninth of 10 childrren, credits a
couple of people with helping him become the player and the man he
is. But even that didn't come easy for him.
</P>
<P>
   The first was Jerry Rhome, his quarterbacks coach with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his background caused him to be very, very suspicious
and not trusting,'' said Rhome, who has coached for several NFL
teams including the Seahawks. ``I don't think he trusted coaches.
He was kind of fighting the world.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 season, Rhome met with Chandler to suggest that
the quarterback take part in Rhome's offseason program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Chris, I don't think you're really listening to me.
I'm having trouble coaching you. I don't think you're going to be
successful the way you are,' '' Rhome recalled this week.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, of course, bristled and walked out of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still kind of felt like I knew everything that I needed to
know,'' Chandler said. ``I kind of left that meeting with the big
ego that I had at the time, thinking, `Maybe I'll be back, maybe I
won't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rhome: ``I didn't think I'd ever see him again.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Chandler was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make football fun,'' Rhome said. ``He needed
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The next to offer helpful hints was John Brodie, the former
49ers quarterback who is Chandler's father-in-law. When Chandler
married Diane Brodie in 1994 he didn't plan on also getting
surrogate parents in the deal. It just happened. Chandler's own
father died of lung cancer in 1991 and his mother of breast cancer
a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``John just really makes me feel good about what I can do on the
football field after I talk to him,'' Chandler said. ``It's not any
one specific thing he says ... he just has a way of talking and
after I get done talking to him I feel confident and I know I can
go out and do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodie first started tinkering with Chandler's shaken confidence
in 1993. He continues to supply regular maintenance with
twice-weekly telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   It must be working. Chandler's career has settled into a purr
that was definitely missing during the rocky road that led him to
the Falcons before the start of the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Chris is how he feels about himself, not how
we feel about him,'' Falcons wide receiver Terance Mathis said.
``If he feels comfortable with himself, he can be a great player
without Terance Mathis, Tony Martin or Jamal Anderson. He has a
home. It's his team. All he's wanted throughout his career is to
have his own team, not to be looking over his shoulder at some
youngblood looking for his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler not only has found a home, he's making himself at home.
He signed a four-year, $25 million contract extension in September,
and used some of the $6 million signing bonus to buy a new house
for Diane and their three children. On the field, he has earned
back-to-back Pro Bowl berths and is 19-4 over the past two years in
games he has started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea Chris was as good a player as he is,'' Falcons
coach Dan Reeves has said several times this week. ``I mean, I'd
love to say I knew all along. But I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler has been so good, in fact, that the talk this week is
that John Elway will not be the best quarterback in Sunday's game.
Of course, you won't catch Chandler saying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an absurd thing to say that anybody is going to
play better than John Elway,'' said Chandler, shaking his head as a
smile spread across his face. ``I've been playing really good
football the last two years. But to say I'm playing better than
John Elway, I think that's stretching it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it is good to see Chandler finally be able to smile
after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELS AND TRAVAILS
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Washington quarterback Chris Chandler
played for five teams in his first nine NFL seasons before finally
finding a home in Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   Team (years) What went wrong
</P>
<P>
   Colts (1988-89) An all-rookie pick after being a third-round
draft choice,
</P>
<P>
   the Colts made Jeff George the No. 1 pick overall in 1990
</P>
<P>
   Bucs (1990-91) Tampa Bay gave a first-round pick in trading for
him, then
</P>
<P>
   released him at midseason in '91 to go with Vinny Testaverde
</P>
<P>
   Cards (1991-93) Started 13 games in 1992, but the Cardinals then
signed
</P>
<P>
   Steve Beuerlein as a free agent and started him in 1993
</P>
<P>
   Rams (1994) Despite signing him as a free agent, the Rams
decided
</P>
<P>
   to go with Chris Miller and Chandler was released
</P>
<P>
   Oilers (1995-96) He passed for then career-highs of 2,460 yards
and 17 TDs
</P>
<P>
   in 1995, but the Oilers already had drafted Steve McNair
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
