u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     01-28 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUGGLE NEVER WAIVERED DESPITE FALCONS' STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ People used to take one look at Jessie Tuggle and shake
their heads. They felt sorry for the guy. Pity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans in other stadiums would always tease me. I'd hear it in
malls, grocery stores. `Jessie, I can't believe you're still
playing with the Falcons. Why don't you go and get yourself on a
good football team?''' Tuggle said Wednesday, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And players on other teams would do the same thing. `Man, you
think you guys can win six games this year?' I would tell `em we
were going to win 10, but there were a few 3-13 years, a few 6-10
seasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? This year, we made believers out of
everybody. The Dirty Birds are for real.''
</P>
<P>
   As we wade through the rivers of hype and glibness that engulf
Super Bowl XXXIII, we come upon this man named Jessie Tuggle.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one reason to root for the Falcons come Sunday _ and
we're not suggesting there aren't others _ look no further than
this linebacker with a penchant for hard hitting and idealistic
living.
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia native, Tuggle was born in a place called Spalding and
played Division II ball at Valdosta State _ not your basic football
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 12 seasons, after five Pro Bowls and after racking up
so many tackles he is the NFL leader among active players, Tuggle
has made it to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   He is here in the belly of one of sports' biggest events,
smiling and strong and charismatic in bringing an important message
about pride and loyalty, about paying your dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to be part of the solution,'' he said. ``It's
easy to walk away and try to jump on a team through free agency and
be an instant winner. But you can appreciate it more when you've
been part of a team so long, and all of a sudden the work really
pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sporting year saw Tony Gwynn and the Padres in the World
Series, we now have Tuggle and the Falcons in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle, like Gwynn, is a one-franchise player. He is a throwback
in an era when 23-year-old NBA players and major league baseball
stars squawk for a trade to a contender the minute they smell
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy, man. That next generation behind us is a now
generation. They want everything now, more so than being willing to
work hard, pay the price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with free agency and everything in all the sports,
everyone wants to be a champion right now. But sometimes you have
to pay the price. It's sweeter. It's so sweet to me right now, it's
unbelievable. I can hardly put it into words because I know what it
takes to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he does know. This Falcon organization can be summed up as
33 years of bloopers, bleeps and blunders.
</P>
<P>
   It has had not one Hall of Famer to call its own. It has never
produced back-to-back winning seasons. The Falcons also have had to
live with knowing they once had Deion Sanders and Bret Favre _
arguably the best defensive and the best offensive players in the
NFL in the '90s _ only the Falcons didn't see much reason to keep
the fellas on board.
</P>
<P>
   Their history is studded with ``Typical Falcons'' anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, when running back Dave Hampton racked up a 1,000-yard
rushing season, he handed the ball to the trainer for safekeeping,
then went back onto the field where he was dropped for a 6-yard
loss on the next carry. Hampton finished the season with 997 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, after coach Marion Campbell was fired, assistant Jim
Hanifan was asked to take over for the last four games. At which
point Hanifan asked, ``Will this count against my overall NFL head
coaching record?''
</P>
<P>
   Why, yes it will, Hanifan was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I don't want the job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1991, the Falcons suffered the ``California State
Trophy'' incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when Jerry Glanville was the coach. We played almost
every team out there on the West Coast and beat all five of them.
So the next year we brought back the California State Trophy,''
Tuggle said.
</P>
<P>
   This trophy was not an official piece of NFL hardware. This was
a Glanville invention, something he was using to motivate his team.
Not a very good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``That trophy was a mistake. The next year, every team in
California really beat us up,'' Tuggle said.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. Glanville had the temerity to lug the outrageous
trophy out to San Francisco and stick it on the sideline during a
game against the 49ers. What happened that day at Candlestick?
</P>
<P>
   ``We got waxed,'' Tuggle said about the 56-17 drubbing. ``So we
put that trophy thing behind us. I never saw that trophy again.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the worst was yet to come. In '96, a year after the
Falcons went to the playoffs, they unraveled in a disastrous 3-13
season. Jeff George was seen (by millions on TV) screaming at
then-coach June Jones, weeks before George was released without the
Falcons getting any players or draft picks in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what direction this organization was going,''
Tuggle said, until Dan Reeves was hired as coach and the same old
Falcons started turning into contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Without complaint, Jessie Tuggle has waited 12 years for this
day.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, when Tuggle and his crew line up against the defending
champion Denver Broncos, the Falcons might gain some confidence
knowing that, next to upending 33 years of their own futile
history, stopping Terrell Davis is like a day at Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
