<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1866 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-RESTRICTIONS-2TAK     01-28 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-RESTRICTIONS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CITY COUNCIL APPROVES ORDINANCE TARGETING GUN TRAFFICKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN, TERRI HARDY AND DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In an effort to crack down on gun violence, Los
Angeles became the first city in the nation Wednesday to limit
handgun purchases to make it harder for criminals and gang members
to obtain weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council unanimously approved an ordinance that takes
aim at ``straw buyers'' of handguns who resell the weapons to
felons, children or other people prohibited from owning firearms.
</P>
<P>
   By banning multiple handgun sales, officials hope to slash the
number that enter the black market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will have a significant effect,'' said Councilman
Mike Feuer, the author of the ordinance. ``By preventing straw
purchasers from reselling guns illegally on the street it will
reduce the flow of guns that get into the hands of criminals and
kids, and as a result will help reduce gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun owner rights activists challenged the ordinance, saying it
trespasses on state authority to control firearms, will be
ineffective and unfairly restricts the rights of legitimate gun
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all political smoke and mirrors,'' said Ed Worley,
California grass-roots coordinator for the National Rifle
Association. ``Before we start passing more ordinances we can't
enforce, perhaps they should use some elbow grease and track down
illegal gun sales under existing laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance is part of an explosion of local gun control laws
that officials say stems from frustration at a plague of gun
violence and lack of state action to regulate firearms access.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 California cities have gun control laws on the books,
and proponents are hopeful that a recent state Supreme Court ruling
and Democratic gains in the state Legislature will revive efforts
to draft a statewide policy.
</P>
<P>
   Prior municipal ordinances limit types of guns, such as assault
weapons or cheap Saturday night special handguns, restrict
ammunition sales, or require the sale of safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles became the first city to restrict how many guns
people can buy in a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Between 25 percent and 30 percent of guns recovered by the LAPD
are purchased legally, often in bulk, and then sold on the street,
police and other experts said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 multiple handgun sales take place each year, out of
an estimated 2,000 total firearms sales a month, said LAPD
Detective Steve Mulldorfer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those sales involve three to six handguns, Mulldorfer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But registration records have documented purchases of up to 70
guns at a time, some of which later turn up at the scenes of
shootings, homicides and other violent crimes, said Julius Wachtel,
a former investigator with the U.S. Department of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms, who compiled a landmark study on sources of crime
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Between 25 percent and 30 percent of handguns recovered by the
Los Angeles Police Department are purchased legally, often in bulk,
and then sold illegally on the street, according to Wachtel and
Mulldorfer.
</P>
<P>
   While police can track those guns back to their original owners,
they must witness the unlawful sale of a weapon to prosecute. That
requires costly and time-consuming investigations, Mulldorfer said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new ordinance, Los Angeles gun dealers will be
required to check a state Department of Justice database to see
whether a prospective buyer has purchased a handgun anywhere in the
state in the previous 30 days. If so, the person can't buy another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has got to be the finest ordinance written to
attack gun trafficking anywhere in the state,'' Mulldorfer said.
``It's specifically targeted for the gun trafficker. I find it very
equitable for everyone. It still allows the citizen to buy one gun
a month for protection. I don't know of any situation that would
require a person to buy more than 12 guns a year for protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But gun rights advocates say such limits violate the rights of
law-abiding citizens to bear arms, and suspect the real aim is to
disarm the public entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States one is innocent until proven guilty,''
said Alan Gottlieb, founder of the Second Amendment Foundation in
Washington state. ``You don't take people's rights away if they're
not doing anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA and the Second Amendment Foundation also plan to sue the
city, arguing that the new ordinance is pre-empted by the state's
power to control gun trade.
</P>
<P>
   The State Supreme Court recently refused to hear an appeal of
the city of West Hollywood's ban on Saturday night specials, a
decision local gun control advocates say vindicates their position.
But gun control opponents said they believe that ruling won't
affect their complaints against the Los Angeles ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb also took issue with exemptions in the new law, which
allow multiple purchases for collectors or entertainment industry
companies who need the handguns for productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we don't have equal protection under the law,'' he
said. ``They've created two classes of people: People who can buy a
product based on the occupation they're involved in and other
people who can't.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, some 200,000 handguns were purchased in 1997, the
most recent year for which statistics are available from the
California Department of Justice. During that year, about 1,800
attempted purchases were denied. Total sales have dropped more than
half since 1993, when handgun purchases peaked at 433,000.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, has introduced a
bill that would put a stop to gun dealers selling multiple handguns
to a single person. The lawmaker said the Los Angeles Police
Department has found that a significant number of the handguns used
in street crime are purchased legally through licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Knox said some buyers then resell the guns to gang members, drug
dealers and underage youths who cannot obtain them through legal
channels.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: who cannot obtain them through legal channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no legitimate reason why anyone needs to
purchase an unlimited number of handguns in a very short time
period,'' Knox said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers this year have proposed their own gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, wants to make it a
misdemeanor to manufacture, import or sell cheap handguns known as
Saturday night specials.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Tony Strickland, R-Thousand Oaks, has introduced a
bill that would establish a tax credit for purchasers of firearm
trigger locks. Strickland said quality trigger locks can cost in
excess of $70, making them too expensive for some, especially those
in disadvantaged areas who need more protection.
</P>
<P>
   And during his campaign Gov. Gray Davis promised to sign a bill
that would strengthen a current law banning assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Knox cited statistics from the California Department of Justice
and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, covering
1988-1995:
</P>
<P>
   Handguns sold as part of a multiple sale made up 24 percent of
handguns sold in California.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven percent of all purchasers of handguns in California
purchased more than one gun in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   People under 21, the legal age for purchasing or possessing a
handgun, possessed 16 percent of the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-two percent of those involved in the survey _ 13,181 guns
_ were part of two-gun purchases; 18 percent were from purchases of
three or more.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
