<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK REMAINS CATALYST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In a part of his mind, Joe Nieuwendyk is flashing down
the ice as fast as ever, his legs strong, his head crystal clear,
his shot among the deadliest in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the back of his mind _ and in his aching right knee _
that the Curse of Bryan Marchment still haunts him.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after Marchment ran the Stars' center into the end
boards, wrecking Nieuwendyk's knee and, essentially, Dallas'
chances to go all the way in the playoffs, there's still no
forgetting the San Jose bad boy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there never will be.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, however, Nieuwendyk and the Stars gave a sellout
crowd at Reunion Arena a taste of what might have been _ and what
yet might be _ by opening the second half of the season with a 3-2
victory against the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, it was Nieuwendyk, back on the ice after missing five
games with tendinitis in the knee he had surgically repaired in
May, who rammed home the game-winning goal in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between our team with him and without him is
dramatic,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock pointed out. ``When you take
a quality player like that out of your lineup, you go back to the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the play he made tonight. We hammer that play all the
time and can't get it in, but it always seems to go in for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Nieuwendyk's 10th goal of the season and perhaps his most
satisfying, because it comes at a time when he needs a shot of
confidence. He is still feeling his way with a knee that sometimes
aches like a rotten tooth.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't have it yanked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strong tonight,'' he said, the knee wrapped in an ice
pack after the game. ``I didn't feel any weakness in the knee at
all. Now, I have to be smart about it and keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not the player he was before Marchment so rudely
interrupted a terrific season. That does not mean he can't be as
good as he ever was.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget that Nieuwendyk was seventh in the league
with 39 goals last season and second with 11 game-winners, a
specialty of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he got hurt, he was our best player last year,''
Hitchcock said. ``He was a 40-goal scorer and those people are hard
to find. If he's even three-quarters of the player he was for us
last year, then he can be huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that 75 percent of the player he was is the
best that Nieuwendyk can hope to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mental adjustments that he has to make now,''
Hitchcock said. ``He's been very stubborn at times. He wants to
practice every practice, play every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing for us is to be sure that he's ready for the
playoffs. On the other hand, there's no point in having him ready
for the playoffs if his game is not in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Nieuwendyk has to get smarter. He has to learn when
to give it everything he has and when to ease up and rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a stretch where we're playing four games in six
nights and I don't know that I'll play all of them,'' Nieuwendyk
conceded. ``Maybe it's best, if I'm feeling some fatigue in the
knee, to sit out for a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words do not come easy for a player like Nieuwendyk, who
has always prided himself on playing full out, every ice minute of
every game. But that was B.M.
</P>
<P>
   Before Marchment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to understand that I'm probably different from the
other 23 guys in this locker room now,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Two
knee surgeries in the last year \Rthe left was operated on, too\S
will do that to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I still want to go out there every game. But now I
have to listen to my body and play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   He played both smart and good last night and it was the
difference in the Stars getting a win, instead of turning a sure
victory into a tie or a loss with a couple of dumb plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to turn a pretty comfortable win into a very
intense finish,'' Hitchcock said. ``But I thought Nieuwendyk's
group gave us a lot of energy. I thought Joe went into some tough
areas and paid the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars led 2-1 when Nieuwendyk skated in on the right side,
took a feed from Richard Matvichuk from behind the nets and beat
Kings' goalie Stephane Fiset at point blank range.
</P>
<P>
   ``A highlight film goal,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   It came from a highlight film kind of player who may be just as
big a key to the Stars' playoff hopes this year as he was B.M.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we all know what that stands for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
