<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT TO GET LUCARATIVE EXTENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kobe Bryant says he's a ``Laker for life,''
and soon he'll be set for life as well, with a lucrative contract
extension. The Lakers are aiming to have a multi-million dollar,
multiyear deal wrapped up before the season begins Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll have something pretty soon with that,'' Lakers
executive Jerry West said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal is not complete, Bryant is expected to earn
the maximum allowed under the NBA's new labor agreement _ $9
million in the first year of the contract, with annual raises of
$1,125,000.
</P>
<P>
   If he signs for the maximum six years, Bryant will earn
$70,875,000 _ the same deal signed this week by fellow class of '96
stars Allen Iverson and Shareef Abdur-Rahim. Alternatively, Bryant
could opt for a three-year deal, then sign a more lucrative
contract after that _ as a six-year veteran, he'd be eligible for a
starting salary of at least $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Without an extension, Bryant would become a free agent this
summer. Teams have until about mid-March to sign players to
extensions, then the negotiating window closes until the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the window will close on this,'' West said. ``I
think that's something that's imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is in the last year of his three-year rookie contract,
which pays him $1.3 million this season. His new deal should make
him the team's second-highest paid player behind Shaquille O'Neal,
whose seven-year contract averages $17.1 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being just 20 years old, as a rising star, Bryant
figured to net a deal well over $100 million. But the league's new
labor deal, reached after the six-month lockout, imposed maximum
salaries for all players, costing Bryant at least $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I didn't really like the (labor) deal too much,''
Bryant said recently, though he declined to confirm reports he
voted against it. ``I still get paid a lot of money to play
basketball. I mean, I'd play this game for a penny. Just to get
paid, period, feels like I'm robbing somebody. . . . I'm not going
to demand something astronomical.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last spring, it seemed uncertain whether Bryant would make
his fortune as a Laker or elsewhere. With West contemplating
retirement, some believed Bryant might bolt. West has since signed
his own contract extension, but Bryant said he never planned to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be here for my whole career,'' he said. ``Jerry West .
. . is kind of like a father figure to all of us. To see him leave
would have been disappointing, but at the same time, it's the
Lakers. I have to be loyal to my team. I wasn't going to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he said, ``I'm a Laker for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Said West, ``That sounds good to us.'' And with Bryant vowing
never to leave, maybe the Lakers could keep him for less?
</P>
<P>
   Joked West, ``What's the living wage, $12.50 an hour?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Exhibitionists: O'Neal scored a game-high 31 points, and Rick
Fox hit seven 3-pointers and scored 26 points _ 16 in the final
period _ in a five-period intrasquad scrimmage before about 8,500
at the Forum. The event was free.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant had 23 points, Travis Knight and rookie Ruben
Patterson scored 20 apiece, and Derek Fisher had 18.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Sam Jacobson played just one quarter before leaving with
a strained hip flexor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played a little better (than in Monday night's
scrimmage),'' coach Del Harris said. ``All in all, a little more
under control, a little less sloppy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
