<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-DEPTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS HAVE FULL COURT OF PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Because Cedric Ceballos surprisingly came crawling
back, the Mavericks might shockingly be inching closer to the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to attract a long-term, big-money contract from any team,
Ceballos settled yesterday for a one-year deal worth approximately
$2 million. As recently as Friday, Mavericks coach/general manager
Don Nelson closed the door on re-signing Ceballos when the 1995
All-Star rejected an offer of three years at $6.75 million in
search of a three-year deal worth $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ended up with them making us an offer we couldn't refuse,''
Nelson said. ``As the market spoke and he didn't get one of the big
contracts and then the $1.75 million exceptions started
disappearing, we found ourselves back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but the Mavericks might have too much depth.
</P>
<P>
   Their first unit is Steve Nash, Michael Finley, Dirk Nowitzki,
A.C. Green and John Williams, backed up by a second team of Robert
Pack, Hubert Davis, Cedric Ceballos, Samaki Walker and Shawn
Bradley. That leaves Gary Trent, Erick Strickland, Chris Anstey and
Reeves looking for playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ceballos' arrival, Nelson said he was tinkering with
the idea of using a 10-man rotation, one or two more than most NBA
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth is certainly our strength,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos, who generated minimal interest from New York, Orlando,
Atlanta and Miami, retains his Bird exemption rights by signing the
one-year deal, meaning the Mavericks will be able to offer him more
money than any other team can after he becomes a free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Nellie flipped a coin, and it came up Ced,'' Ceballos
joked of the on-again, off-again negotiations. ``I didn't want to
wait an eternity and I didn't want to be locked into a long-term
deal. I knew I'd fit in here, so I took the most comfortable offer.
This gives me a chance to prove myself now, and then test the
market next summer when things aren't so out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   It also gives the Mavericks a proven backup to rookie Nowitzki
and adds fuel to their playoff optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is'' a playoff team, said Ceballos, who was
acquired Feb. 18 from Phoenix for Dennis Scott. ``We have a lot of
talent and a whole lot of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ceballos' arrival, the Mavericks played their best
basketball last season. They went 4-5 in his nine starts,
increasing their scoring average from 89 to 99. Ceballos and Finley
combined to average 41 points per night before Ceballos tore knee
ligaments March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Should the 20-year-old Nowitzki, whom Nelson indicated would
remain the starter, falter, the Mavericks now have a veteran scorer
to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes us a better team; it's that simple,'' Finley said.
``Last year, we saw what we could do together, and I think we liked
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos' arrival also gives the Mavericks 14 players with
guaranteed contracts. Given the extenuating circumstances created
by the lockout, the league is allowing teams to keep 14 players on
the active roster the first two weeks of the season. When that
number drops to 12, however, the Mavericks will likely trade backup
guard Khalid Reeves and put a couple of players on the temporary
injured list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with our team before. Now the talent level has
certainly gone up,'' Nelson said. ``Ced lessens the pressure on
Dirk and really makes us solid at every position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
