<HEADLINE>
CHANDLER BLOSSOMS INTO A TRUE BLUE-LIGHT SPECIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Last week, John Elway was the second-most prominent
American to be publicly accused of high crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   But once Dan Reeves backtracked and decided to drop all charges,
this seashore Super Bowl gathering has settled into bipartisan
harmony and bliss among the Denvers and the Atlantas. Some would
also call it forced hype.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Henry Hyde shows up, it figures to stay this way until
Sunday's kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   But even as strange as it would have been for Elway to be
continually defending his character this week, the future
Hall-of-Famer is now dealing with yet another oddity.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to national media ink and air time, Elway rates a
distant second to the ``other'' Super Bowl quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Chris Chandler is the better story, but it's also not
exactly a SportsCenter scoop to declare Chandler the better
quarterback than Elway _ for this one season, plus playoffs,
Chandler has been. That's just football fact, without any shock
element attached. And once the two clubs kick it off Sunday, the
only Elway-Chandler comparison that matters will be performance
over the next 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Flip, however, to the NFL big picture.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a coach or scout in the NFL who at the moment isn't
attempting to figure out the puzzle that is Chandler's 11-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of futuristic scouting, talent evaluation and
coaching, how could so many NFL types been so wrong for so long
about a player at the most important position on the field? This
kind of talent isn't supposed to drift aimlessly for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was dumped by five teams during his first nine years in
the league. Think how stupid the whatever-they-call-them-now
Houston Oilers must feel. They traded Chandler to Reeves two years
ago for various trinkets. Officially, it was fourth- and
sixth-round draft picks, which amounts in football to key chains
and fingernail clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves looks like a genius, but he's too honest to lead anyone
in that direction. Every day this week, and about every week for
the entire season, Reeves has been quick to say, ``I had no idea he
was this good.''
</P>
<P>
   And Chandler himself may have to start paying copyright fees to
the estate of Jerry Gracia, if there is such a thing. The
quarterback's stock answer on his career is something along the
lines of ``It's been a long, strange trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves saw enough after the '97 season to reward Chandler
with a four-year, $25 million contract, including a $6 million
signing bonus. Not exactly Elway-Young-Aikman-Favre money, but more
than Chandler ever dreamed of making. And at the moment, an
outrageous bargain for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, a former NFL head
coach, chuckled yesterday, saying, ``I bet there wasn't a GM or
coach in the league who didn't privately wonder if Dan had gone
crazy when they heard about that money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks added that the contract may have been the final
turning point in what had been Chandler's Kmart career:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more than the amount of money, which was ample, this was
the first time a coach and a team had ever made the complete
commitment to Chris. Here was Dan saying to him, `You're our guy.
You are our franchise quarterback. Our team is in your hands.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris had been a vagabond quarterback. Always the stop-gap
quarterback while a team looked for or groomed a guy to take over.
Dan gave him a football home.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the question of how the Colts,
Buccaneers, Cardinals, Rams and Oilers completely blew it. And why
a dozen other teams weren't wise enough to grab him. The talent is
obvious. At least now it is. There's arm strength, smarts, enough
mobility and size, and for aerial accuracy, Reeves puts him in Troy
Aikman's class.
</P>
<P>
   But there wasn't always health. Chandler had a career problem
answering the work whistle over 16 games. Plus, he's the first to
admit the heart and the head weren't always in the right place. He
says he was headstrong and became discouraged easily.
</P>
<P>
   But four years into the NFL, Chandler hooked up with Jerry
Rhome, the Dallas native who was the quarterback coach in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who turned my whole career around,'' Chandler
said. ``He taught me how to play quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Chandler waited for the right opportunity. Reeves
finally provided that. Next stop: the Super Bowl on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
