<HEADLINE>
PARADE MAGAZINE SLIGHTS TEXANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE IVEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If I were, though, I would be embarrassed. And not simply
because it happens to rain dirt here every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I would be embarrassed is because only three of the
56 student-athletes on this year's ``Parade'' magazine All-American
high school football team hail from the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   Three!
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a statistic to hang your Stetson on, is it?
</P>
<P>
   The only Texans deemed worthy of the honor this season were
defensive back Gerome Sapp, linebacker Cory Redding and offensive
lineman Alfio Randall (who all happen to be from Houston, by the
way), at least according to the Jan. 24 issue of ``Parade''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute,'' you say. ``Perhaps the editors at ``Parade''
are trying to put together a geographically balanced team _ one
that encompasses players from all over the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice thought, but it is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the players are from California and five are from
Florida, the two states other than Texas that are generally
considered to be the major hotbeds of high school football. As if
that were not a big enough slap in the face of Texas football, even
Alabama boasts four players on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama? Whoa, Nellie!
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, ``Parade''? This is Dave Campbell speaking. Immediately
cancel my subscription.''
</P>
<P>
   The only good news, Texans, is that your high school football _
the fabled institution chronicled by Pulitzer Prize-winning author
H.G. (Buzz) Bissinger in ``Friday Night Lights'' and by Hollywood
in the current MTV film ``Varsity Blues'' _ is not considered the
worst in America.
</P>
<P>
   With three All-American selections, Texas is equal to Georgia
and slightly ahead of Arkansas, Louisiana, Maryland, Michigan, New
Jersey, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, South Carolina and Virginia,
which all have only two.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah! In your face, Maryland!
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury is that one high school in California _
Long Beach Polytechnic _ produced two All-Americans. And a single
community in Louisiana _ Monroe and West Monroe _ also produced two
All-Americans. That is one fewer than the entire, football-mad
state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Surely this is a joke. (It is certainly more laughable than the
magazine's lame ``Howard Huge'' cartoon, anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   The publication's 56 All-Americans are broken down by position
as follows: linemen (17), running backs (10), linebackers (8),
quarterbacks (7), wideouts (6), defensive backs (4), kickers (2)
and all-purpose players (2).
</P>
<P>
   Their top quarterback is Texas-bound Chris Simms. It is hard to
argue with that choice, based on his superb statistics and NFL
bloodline, but were there really six other quarterbacks who had
better seasons in 1998 than Brownwood's Colby Freeman?
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, the ``Star-Telegram'' Offensive Player of the Year,
piled up more than 2,700 yards of offense and accounted for 29
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly where is Wyatt defensive end Donald Burrell? The
``Star-Telegram'' Defensive Player of the Year registered 108
tackles, including 48 tackles for loss and an incredible 21 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Other area players who could make a strong case to be included
on the All-American list include defensive linemen Kevin Young of
Duncanville and Cedric Hilliard of Lamar, defensive back Sterling
Kazee of MacArthur and the record-breaking Stephenville combo of
quarterback Kelan Luker and wide receiver Cody Cardwell.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. What more could one really expect from a magazine that
generally is found in the Sunday paper somewhere between the comics
and a Wal-Mart ad? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ivey writes about the high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 548-5481. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
