<HEADLINE>
JEFF BURTON READY TO START `BEATING UP' ON OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR stars Mark Martin and Jeff Burton not only settled in as
Winston Cup teammates last year, they also apparently began cloning
their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Martin tells everyone who asks that Burton, the 1994 Winston Cup
rookie of the year, is the series' best driver.
</P>
<P>
   Burton says that Martin remains the undisputed champion of Roush
Racing, despite the fact he never has won the seasonlong Winston
Cup points chase.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing shop space in Mooresville, N.C., week after week
undoubtedly has allowed some of Martin's self-incriminating outlook
to rub off on Burton. Because even though he won two races and
finished fifth in Cup points last year, Burton admittedly spent the
off-season beating up on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the most positive person in the world,'' said Burton,
rising star of team-owner Jack Roush's five-car Ford Taurus stable.
``Yeah, we spent the off-season beating ourselves up. We spent a
lot of weeks last season beating ourselves up. A lot of races we
let ourselves down last year. We can't do that, and perform at a
level that is going to make us happy.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how can Burton and crew chief Frankie Stoddard find
happiness in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is a multiple-choice answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is I've got to be a better qualifier,'' said
Burton, who scored his initial career Cup victory at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth in April 1997. ``I can't get us into stupid
wrecks, and I got us into some stupid wrecks last year. We've got
to be better at making changes during the race, to make our car
better. We've got to be better on pit road, and we can't have
mechanical problems. And our superspeedway program has got to be
better. Those are things that are real clear to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That also is the type of no-nonsense check list made famous by
Martin, who finished second to Jeff Gordon by 364 points for the
Cup championship in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's a lot to be said about being very humble about
your team and yourself,'' said Burton, who at 31 is nine years
younger than his mentor. ``Because when you are willing to look at
the negative things, then you can fix stuff. If you're willing to
look at the things that aren't working _ including yourself _ then
you can make the deal better. If you aren't willing to do that,
then how's your deal ever going to get better?''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, how's your deal ever going to close the
Gordon gap?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's third championship in four years was punctuated by a
record-tying 13 victories in 1998, a whirlwind season that more
than offset Martin's career seven-win year. Count Burton among
those who refuse to buy into the theory that Gordon and crew chief
Ray Evernham are due for a bruisin' in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look at Gordon and his race team and say, `This
is what they did. They have the possibilities of doing it again.
What are we going to do to stop them?' '' Burton said.
QUICK HITS
IROC FIELD SET
</P>
<P>
   Seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion Dale Earnhardt and his
son, reigning NASCAR Busch Grand National champion Dale Earnhardt
Jr., will race against each other for the first time in America in
the upcoming International Race of Champions series.
</P>
<P>
   The four-race schedule matching 12 of the world's best drivers
in identically prepared stock cars kicks off at the Daytona
International Speedway on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and Little E. did compete against one another in the
NASCAR exhibition race at Twin Ring Motegi in Japan on Nov. 22.
This will be their first run against each other in the United
States, with Earnhardt Jr. scheduled to make his official Cup debut
during the Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte Motor Speedway on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the field for IROC XXIII features NASCAR stars
Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin, Dale Jarrett, Rusty Wallace and Jeff
Burton; Kenny Brack and Eddie Cheever Jr. of the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League; and Al Unser Jr., Greg Moore and Adrian Fernandez of
the Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series.
ROLEX 24 TO ROLL
</P>
<P>
   An 83-car field has been entered for the 37th annual Rolex 24 at
Daytona, North America's premier sports car endurance race.
</P>
<P>
   The car-count, as sanctioned by the U.S. Road Racing
Championship, includes 22 entered in the headline open-cockpit
Can-Am class. It is the second-largest prototype field at Daytona
International Speedway, trailing only the 29 GTP cars entered in
1985 under the International Motor Sports Association banner.
</P>
<P>
   A Ferrari 333SP co-driven by Gianpiero Moretti of Italy, Arie
Luyendyk of the USA, Mauro Baldi of Monaco and Didier Theys of
Belgium was the overall victor by eight laps around the 3.56-mile
combined oval-road course last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 314 drivers expected to compete in Can-Am, GT3, GT2 and GTT
encompass 22 nations, 2,078 victories and 185 titles. And 137 alarm
clocks.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to knock Jeff Gordon off of his throne, or
anything else. I'm just looking for a teenie-weenie little bitty
piece _ a little slice _ a little corner of the pie. That's all I'm
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Darrell Waltrip, three-time Winston Cup champion, and driver
of the new No. 66 Big Kmart-Route 66 Ford Taurus
RECORD ATTENDANCE
</P>
<P>
   Motorsports fans in Fort Worth-Dallas, you're hardly alone.
</P>
<P>
   Auto racing attendance in North America recorded another
increase in 1998, when 17,079,004 fans filled grandstands, suites
and infields at 12 series monitored by the Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber
Co. The figure is up from 16,861,291 in 1997 and represents an
increase of 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, NASCAR's 33-race Winston Cup Series _ which included a
stop at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth _ topped the overall
attendance chart at 6,301,027. That is an increase of 3.4 percent.
In addition, approximately 188,979,000 loyalists tuned in to Cup
races on ABC, CBS, ESPN, TNN and TBS.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series enjoyed a stout
8.2 percent increase. A total of 2,102,000 fans witnessed the
maturation of Dale Earnhardt Jr. into a third generation champion,
beginning with his first career BGN victory at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   The Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Championship drew
2,529,995 fans on four continents _ an increase of 1.6 percent over
1997. Two new events, including a street race in downtown Houston,
aided CART's rise.
</P>
<P>
   National Hot Rod Association attendance also increased 1.6
percent to 2,204,194. Average attendance for 22 national events,
including two drag races at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis, was
100,191 per race.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series posted a 2.0 percent increase
over 1997 as 938,775 fans attended the season's 27 races, including
a June night visit to the reconfigured and repaved TMS.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, two notable attendance declines among
events contested in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Pep Boys Indy Racing League expanded its schedule from eight
to 11 races in 1998, including a September date in Fort Worth. But
the IRL's overall attendance of 1,291,653 represented a drop of 4.1
percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rain forced the Pennzoil World of Outlaws Series to cancel seven
of its scheduled 72 Sprint Car races, including the annual fall
extravaganza at the Devil's Bowl Speedway in Mesquite. That led to
an attendance drop of 1.7 percent to 1,575,200.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Stu Grant, Goodyear's general manager of worldwide
racing, announced that after 27 years, the company was ceasing
publication of the report. Goodyear would like the sanctioning
bodies to crunch their own numbers next off-season.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   1998 major auto racing series attendance figures (estimated):
Series Race dates Total attendance Pct. gain/loss NASCAR Winston
Cup 33 6,301,027 3.4 CART Champ Cars 19 2,529,995 1.6 NHRA drag
racing 22 2,204,194 1.6 NASCAR Busch GN 31 2,102,000 8.2 World of
Outlaws 65 1,575,200 -1.7 IRL Indy-cars 11 1,291,653 -4.1 SCCA
Trans-Am 13 1,136,834 23 Craftsman Trucks 27 938,775 2 ASA stock
cars 20 597,062 2.8 IROC stock cars 4 401,802 22.9 Sports Car 8
293,969 -43.1 IHRA drag racing 10 227,873 -41.1
</P>
<P>
   Figures are estimates compiled from Goodyear Racing Division
race reports, event promoters, official sanctioning body statistics
and other sources. Total event attendance includes practice and
qualifying days.
</P>
</TEXT>
