<P>
   SCHOOL-PILLS (Boston) _ The world of school nurses has changed
greatly. Nowadays, they juggle the traditional triage of student
who feel sick with a host of growing demands: handle drugs for
attention deficit disorder and increasingly common asthma inhalers;
help medically fragile students with catheters or tube feedings;
teach children to wash their hands frequently, or persuade
teenagers to quit smoking and consider celibacy; and much, much
more. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
