<P>
   SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ When 130 million or so viewers
tune in on Sunday for Super Bowl XXXIII, they will watch first-time
enthusiasm confront longtime experience, with players new to the
big game pitted against those who have learned the hard way what it
takes to win. Oh yes, and a couple of teams will play football,
too. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   TINABROWN-MAGAZINE (Washington) _ When Tina Brown left the New
Yorker and Ronald Galotti left Vogue last summer to start a new
magazine, ``Talk,'' with financing from the Disney-owned film
company Miramax, many complex questions were unresolved. Now new
facts are emerging about how the celebrated editor and publisher
and their financial backers are keeping the project on track toward
a planned first issue next fall. By Geraldine Fabrikant and Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   PRESTO-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ National Presto Industries rarely
calls attention to itself. The Eau Claire, Wis., company has the
reputation of being run more like a private company than a publicly
held one. But that is due to change, now that a group of analysts
has chosen the company as the subject of an educational project on
how small investors can benefit from shareholder activism. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA-LEGAL (Undated) _ Some business executives have argued for
years that large jury verdicts against big companies show that
American courts are out of control. Now a Canadian company that
lost a huge case against a competitor in Mississippi is using a
novel legal tool to seek at least $725 million from the U.S.
government. By William Glaberson.
