   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-ROOMS (Undated) _ Let us consider the dwindling
circumstances of the American living room, once so commodious and
central to the domestic universe that Tom Wolfe, writing in acid
admiration in ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' in 1987, described it as
``this gloriously stuffed little planet.'' Yet during a recent
visit to the Mt. Kisco model home, not one person in a steady
stream of visitors stepped across the threshold into the living
room. Instead, they made a beeline straight back to the
double-height family room, a congenial open space adjacent to the
kitchen, where they chatted amiably on Dumbo-sized couches or
gathered about its unlit fireplace as if it were a 51-inch
television screen. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   MANHATTAN-RENT (New York) _ In Manhattan these days, finding the
rental apartment you want is only the beginning. Prospective
renters can find themselves in a bidding war _ for a rental _ and
by the time the dust settles, agreeing to pay hundreds of dollars a
month more than the asking price and putting up one month's rent
and three months' security in advance. And finding themselves
required to produce the extraordinary financial credentials that
made them acceptable candidates to pay a high rent. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LENS-CREDIT-CARD (Undated) _ The LensCard, currently marketed by
Chase Manhattan, is a credit card designed with a flat, one-inch
window that magnifies three and a half times _ enough power to
enlarge a line on a restaurant bill from a blur to legibility. By
Phlip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-FEVER (New York) _ Spring fever can begin in strange
ways. It hit me hard last week, when a friend brought over a bunch
of Swiss chard purchased at an expensive natural-foods store. The
leaves were a deep plush green, with vermilion veins coursing
through them like rivers bursting with life. And in my memory at
least (alas, we ate the evidence), they were not crinkled and
glossy like most Swiss chard, but smooth, almost as if crossed with
a collard green. As we chopped the leaves and sauteed them with
garlic, the sensual pleasures of spring on the farm rushed into my
Red Hook kitchen. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-LOFT (New York) _ Two years ago, when Arnold Lehman
left Baltimore to become the director of the Brooklyn Museum of
Art, he and his wife, Pamela, knew exactly what kind of home they
wanted. In Brooklyn, they found what they wanted: a
3,000-square-foot floor-through loft on a high floor in what was a
1920's Gothic Revival office building. It's two blocks from the
Boro Hall subway stop and 10 minutes by car or subway from the
museum. And light? It pours in through 30 windows. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
