<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE OUTLASTS NO.1 UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now it can be told: Al Scates voted for
Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest USA Today/American Volleyball Coaches Top 15 poll,
No.5 Pepperdine received one first-place vote.
</P>
<P>
   It was Scates, coach of No.1 UCLA. His reasons? ``They're
undefeated and they have the returning player of the year in George
Roumain. Everyone above them lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, No.3 Brigham Young is listed as 6-0. But maybe other
coaches will follow Scates' lead and vote for the Waves after their
15-13, 15-11, 5-15, 4-15, 15-11 Mountain Pacific Sports Federation
Conference victory over UCLA on Wednesday at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   And, true to form, Roumain led Pepperdine (6-0, 2-0) with 39
kills, including four in the deciding fifth game, when the match
went to rally scoring (teams score a point on every serve).
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, Scates said, that rally scoring hurt the Bruins
(3-2, 1-1) after thoroughly dominating the Waves in the third and
fourth games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fifth game is a coin toss,'' Scates said. ``Momentum is a
funny thing. The team that serves first loses about 70 percent of
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess who served first? UCLA, and the Bruins actually took a 1-0
lead on a Danny Farmer kill. He finished with a team-high 23.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine looked beaten after the fourth game but tightened up
its serve-receiving, which Waves coach Marv Dunphy said made the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a second wind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some might think Roumain did, too, but UCLA always brings out
the best in the 6-foot-6 senior. His career high in kills was 42,
against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best team in the nation,'' Roumain said. ``You
always want to bring out your best. We had to bring it together. I
guess they got a little overconfident on their court.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Roumain, rally scoring meant nothing. Neither did the
ease with which UCLA won the third and fourth games.
</P>
<P>
   Roumain made sure the Waves would be competitive in the fifth
game, getting the team's first point on a kill.
</P>
<P>
   He also made a block for a 4-2 lead, a kill that made it 8-5,
and two straight kills to put the Waves at match point. Brandon
Taliaferro hit wide to end the 2 hour, 20 minute match.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wong and Don Killian each had 16 kills for Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Williams had 19 kills and Adam Naeve added 18 kills for
UCLA, followed by Evan Thatcher with 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
