r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-BACKS-     01-28 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-BACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT SLIGHTS ARE FUEL FOR DAVIS, ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The NFL draft's late rounds are traditionally about
``throwing darts'' and ``taking fliers,'' about ridiculous long
shots, about selecting somebody's cousin and the gimmicks that
allow John Havlicek and Carl Lewis and Dave Winfield to forever
include ``drafted by the NFL'' on their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the NFL draft's late rounds are about Terrell Davis and
Jamal Anderson, currently football's two most successful running
backs. Super Bowl XXXIII's marquee matchup is Davis vs. Anderson,
both selected in the last two rounds of the draft and both making a
splash in the NFL because of their I'll- show-you-mentality in
addition to their running prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two years in the league, I think people looked down
on me,'' Davis said. ``I think now they don't see me as a
sixth-round pick. I think now people look at me as Terrell Davis.
There's not a label on me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Anderson was discussing the label and the place in
the NFL pecking order that goes with it with the Super Bowl media
in Miami. He compared his perspective to that of an NFL rookie this
season who was passed over in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys talk about Randy Moss being mad. I've got five years'
worth of anger,'' Anderson said. ``People make mistakes. Boy, do
they make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was chosen in the sixth round of the 1995 draft, Anderson
in the seventh round of the 1994 draft. Their draft-day snubs seem
so obviously mistaken now. But how did these two _ each of them a
Pro Bowl player, each of them finalists for the league MVP award,
each of them the likeliest of candidates to be selected the
standout of Sunday's finale should their team win _ begin their
professional careers as second-day second thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   Two similar tales of two similarly successful NFL superstars:
Davis, the 196th player taken in his draft, and the 21st running
back; and Anderson was the 201st player taken, and the 25th running
back.
</P>
<P>
   Davis seems an ideal combination of speed, power, athletic
ability and character _ and now, performance. He's a muscularly
built 5-foot-11, 210 pounds. He's the 1998 NFL MVP after being
honored as last year's Super Bowl MVP. As a rookie in 1995, he
rushed for 1,117 yards and scored eight touchdowns. In '96, he
totaled 1,538 and 15 touchdowns. In '97, he totaled 1,750 and 15
touchdowns. And this season he finished with 2,008 yards and 23
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the pros, having elevated himself from an
underprivileged background (his family members have been jailed for
violent crimes numerous times) to earn a spot at the University of
Georgia should have counted for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my background gave me a certain toughness, a certain
resilience,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Georgia's history of producing great running backs may
have hurt Davis. Recent first-round runners from the University of
Georgia include Herschel Walker, Rodney Hampton, Robert Edwards and
Garrison Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was largely an unknown quality coming out of Georgia
because of the excellence of the guy who, in Davis' junior year,
played ahead of him. ``Terrell didn't have the speed of Garrison,
and the feeling was that there was a dropoff when he came in,''
said Georgia athletic director Vince Dooley. As a senior, the job
was Davis'. But he missed three games because of a groin injury and
that, along with a feud with his coach, Ray Goff, cemented his
subpar reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But Broncos assistant Gary Kubiak had a friend at Georgia who
recommended Davis. And Kubiak and Denver coach Mike Shanahan viewed
Davis as a decent fit into their system.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 234-pound Anderson comes in a Davis-like package,
lacking only blazing speed. The bullish runner finished fourth in
this season's MVP voting after rushing for 1,846 yards and 14
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   His celebrity-studded background (his father has served as a
bodyguard for everyone from Muhammad Ali to Richard Pryor to Diana
Ross, and Jamal considers many of those stars his pals) should have
counted for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was from those kind of people that I learned how to have
respect for others, and for myself,'' Anderson said. ``Those people
are winners. They all knew how to try to persevere. That rubbed off
on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as with Davis, scouts saw the negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fact he came out of the University of Utah, hardly a
mecca for NFL talent, Anderson was derided as a ``tweener,'' he was
too small to be a fullback and too slow to be a halfback. ``A
bowling ball,'' Falcons personnel director Reed Johnson calls him.
</P>
<P>
   Even upon his arrival in Atlanta, his skills went somewhat
unnoticed. In '94, the Falcons were careful to re-sign Erric
Pegram, a running back. And they acquired Craig Heyward, another
running back. And in '95, they traded to get Eric Metcalf, a
part-time running back. And they acquired Blair Thomas, another
running back. In '96, they drafted Richard Huntley, a running back,
in the fourth round. In '97, they drafted Byron Hanspard, a running
back, in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they stuck with me,'' Anderson said. ``And I stuck with
it. Eventually, coach \RDan\S Reeves came along and realized I
could be a featured back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons clearly didn't know what they had right under their
noses, though. In Anderson's rookie year, he totaled three games
played, started none and had two carries for minus-1 yard. Even in
his second year, he appeared in all 16 games, mostly as a kick
returner, carrying the ball just 39 time for 161 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It still stuns. Does it still sting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think you can see it in the way guys run,'' Anderson
said. ``Run with a purpose. Run hard every down. Run hard every
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Low-Pick Team An assemblage of NFL standouts, many of
them taken from the rosters of the NFL's final four playoff teams,
who made it despite being underrated coming out of college: OFFENSE
Position Player Current Team Round Selected QB Doug Flutie Bills 11
Boston College RB Terrell Davis Broncos 6 Georgia RB Jamal Anderson
Falcons 7 Utah TE Shannon Sharpe Broncos 7 Savannah State WR Rod
Smith Broncos UFA Missouri Southern WR Wayne Chrebet Jets UFA
Hofstra OL Tony Jones Broncos UFA Western Carolina OL Ephraim
Salaam Falcons 7 San Diego State OL David Dixon Vikings 9 Arizona
State OL Kevin Gogan 49ers 8 Washington OL Tom Nalen Broncos 7
Boston College DEFENSE John Randle Vikings UFA Texas A&AMP;I Leon Lett
Cowboys 7 Emporia State Travis Hall Falcons 6 BYU Mike McCrary
Ravens 7 Wake Forest Jessie Tuggle Falcons UFA Valdosta Jessie
Armstead Giants 8 Miami Bryce Paup Jaguars 7 Northern Iowa Dave
Thomas Jaguars 8 Tennessee Mark McMillian Chiefs 10 Alabama Eugene
Robinson Falcons UFA Colgate Tyrone Braxton Broncos 12 North Dakota
</P>
<P>
   UFA _ Undrafted Free Agent /
</P>
</TEXT>
