</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHA-GRAHAM-LEGACY-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBUILDING THE MARTHA GRAHAM LEGACY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for MARTHA-GRAHAM-DANCE)  
 (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The incestual bed that Isamu Noguchi designed for
Jocasta and her son, Oedipus, in Martha Graham's ``Night Journey''
is no longer parked in a corner of a studio; it has been packed
away. Outside, the earth in Graham's beloved garden has been dug up
in anticipation of the wrecker's ball.
</P>
<P>
   Monday one day before opening a three-week season at the Joyce
Theater, the Martha Graham Dance Company will vacate the school and
studios at 316 East 63rd Street where Graham taught and
choreographed for 40 years before she died in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The small brick building will be demolished and sold to pay off
debts, retire a $1.5 million mortgage and establish an endowment.
The original gate that welcomed thousands of dancers and students
from around the world to the Martha Graham Center for Contemporary
Dance has already been torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all these dramatic omens are only a preface to the
remarkable story of the Graham company's institutional turnaround
in the last year. The artistic health of the troupe, held together
against all odds by Ron Protas, Graham's handpicked successor, is
not in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The onstage hosts for a gala benefit on Tuesday will include
Twyla Tharp, Tony Randall, Anne Jackson and Eli Wallach (Graham
students all), who will introduce a season that has an unusually
strong cluster of Graham's greatest works.
</P>
<P>
   The financial picture in recent years has been more uncertain.
Rebirth, nonetheless, is a favorite Graham theme, and the story to
be told is one of renewal, ostensibly providential but achieved
through determined effort.
</P>
<P>
   At its most evocative, it is a tale of two daughters. One is
Rose Caiola, who as a child studied with Graham. Now director of
her own dance school, she persuaded her father, Benedetto Caiola,
an East Side developer, to buy the Graham building when it came on
the market and to rehouse the company and school in the apartment
house that her family's firm will build on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the $3 million sale and a donation from Caiola, the
company can afford its first New York season since 1995 and plans
to return in a year from a temporary location in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   The company's other major benefactor in recent years has been
Delores Barr Weaver, who became a board member after her daughter,
Leigh, spoke of her admiration for Graham's work and dancers. That
Mrs. Weaver and her husband, Wayne Weaver, are owners of the
Jacksonville Jaguars, the Florida football team, and contributors
to the Graham company, does not strike anyone who knows them as
odd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like personal challenges,'' Mrs. Weaver said recently,
adding that the Weaver family will announce a $250,000 challenge
grant to the company. ``If we believe in something, we'll stand toe
to toe to the very end. Ron is the reason Martha Graham is still on
the scene, and we can't let Graham die a second time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the stiff-jawed world of corporate and foundation giving,
such personal touches are rare. In her lifetime, Graham's charisma
attracted individual patrons like Katherine Cornell, Baroness
Bethsabee de Rothschild, Lila Acheson Wallace, Doris Duke and
Halston.
</P>
<P>
   But government and foundation grants came her way infrequently
in the 23 years before she died at 96. In 1984, she publicly
protested that the issue was age discrimination. Who could believe
that a 90-year-old woman, even if acknowledged as one of the 20th
century's greatest artists, could still choreograph and oversee her
repertory?
</P>
<P>
   The dance world waited for Graham to die, but she did not, and
the Joyce Theater season includes major productions from the 1980s
and the works from the 1920s and 1930s that she agreed to revive at
Protas' urging.
</P>
<P>
   In their abstract form and spare structures, early works like
``Heretic'' and ``Steps in the Street'' can stun with their fusion
of strict form and deep emotion. Simplicity masks complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The 1931 ``Primitive Mysteries'' is an initiation rite from the
American Southwest, symbolized by the adoration of the Virgin. It
is also one of modern dance's most celebrated masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at a time when she herself should have been celebrated in
her later years, Graham was criticized in modern-dance circles for
changing a ruffle on a dress or for changing her own choreography.
``If the dance will be destroyed, it will come from within,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel that initially rejected her challenge grant
application at the National Endowment for the Arts in 1984
consisted mainly of dancers and choreographers. That the
modern-dance world parodies Graham through a good-natured female
impersonator in a downtown club today is true to form. The child
rebels against the parent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet modern dance has only one international icon of Graham's
stature. The ballet world is shrewder, identifying itself with the
Balanchine it deified after his death.
</P>
<P>
   It is for a future generation to discover Graham in all the
genius of her repertory, and it is to this end that the company has
just undergone a major reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   As described by Protas, the company's artistic director, and
Todd Dellinger, formerly development director and now managing
director, a new institutional framework will clearly define the
fiscal and artistic responsibilities of the company directors for
donors. It will also place the rights to Graham's dance works, now
owned by Protas, in a foundation after his death.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Protas, who was Graham's closest associate starting in the
1970s, said he would resign as artistic director by the summer of
2000. He will be succeeded by Janet Eilber, a former leading dancer
in the company. Protas heads the newly formed Graham Trust. Modeled
after the Balanchine Trust, it will license the rights of Graham
works to other dance companies. Like the Balanchine Trust, the
Graham Trust can withdraw a work if it is not performed according
to agreed-upon standards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Merce Cunningham and Paul Taylor have allowed their
modern dance pieces to be performed by ballet companies, Protas was
skeptical about ballet dancers' ability to master the Graham idiom.
But the Colorado Ballet's production last fall of ``Appalachian
Spring,'' which was coached by leading Graham dancers and Protas,
as well as Graham productions at the Paris Opera Ballet, convinced
him otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Under the trust conditions, at least 60 percent of the Graham
company's repertory must consist of Graham's choreography. New
works, however, will be commissioned. The Joyce season includes the
New York premiere of ``Not for Me'' by the Broadway choreographer
Susan Stroman.
</P>
<P>
   A suite titled ``Duets for Martha'' includes a commissioned work
by Lucinda Childs and an excerpt from Maurice Bejart's ``Notre
Faust'' as well as excerpts by Twyla Tharp and Robert Wilson; both
created premieres for the company after Graham's death.
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger said the best news is that the sale of the studio
building allows the company to start the year clear of all debt in
his three-to-five-year plan. Last spring, he said, the Graham
company was $800,000 in debt and was also required to pay back the
$1.5 million it had borrowed against its building. U.S. Trust held
the mortgage, and while banks have been known to partly forgive
loans to arts organizations (American Ballet Theater is an
example), U.S. Trust did not.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to appeals made directly to the mayor's office from
Graham loyalists like Gregory Peck and Betty Ford, and advice from
Schuyler Chapin, the cultural affairs commissioner, the city came
up with a $200,000 challenge grant. If the city gives a variance to
the Caiola firm, M-1 Properties, that relaxes zoning restrictions,
two floors will be added to the new six-story building, adding more
studio space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the Graham school will stay open at Musical
Theater Works, a studio space at 440 Lafayette Street opposite the
Public Theater. Dellinger said that the $3 million sale and an
additional gift of $300,000 from Caiola will wipe out the debts and
mortgage, as well as start an endowment with $400,000 and leave
money to apply to the Joyce season and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Tour bookings have also jumped now that the company, considered
as expensive as a ballet company, has agreed to appear as a smaller
unit, as does American Ballet Theater. It will have 17 dancers
instead of 24 on tour, an arrangement that Protas and Dellinger
call temporary but cuts the company's tour fee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid the facts and figures there is also a human face. Alfred
Caiola, Caiola's son and a partner in M-1 Properties, will lease
5,000 square feet back to the Graham company for high-ceilinged
basement studios at a ``modest rent.'' If the city grants
permission to build extra floors, the company will own, not rent,
7,500 square feet of which 2,500 will be on the ground floor. The
firm will also build a black-box theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caiola, who owns Studio Maestro, a dance school and
rehearsal space at 48 West 68th Street, had no difficulty
explaining why she talked her father into the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started at the Graham School when I was 8 and was inspired
by Martha when she came in to teach,'' she said. ``The building is
not an optimum business investment but the company must continue. I
told my father something must be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone, her father agreed. ``I'd like to do something,
I'm getting bored,'' Caiola said with a laugh. ``It's also because
of Rose. She takes after me. She works hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
