<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOENBERG-MUSIC-ART-     01-28 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOENBERG-MUSIC-ART-3TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD SCHOENBERG: HE DIDN'T WANT TO HURT MUSIC, JUST HELP IT
EVOLVE
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 31) 
(bl) 
By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a brief period in the spring of 1898, Arnold
Schoenberg, then 23, thought that his music just might be received
by the public with some degree of sympathy. His String Quartet in
D, a piece steeped in Brahms but using a more wide-ranging harmonic
language, was performed by a new-music ensemble in Vienna and
greeted with something approaching enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not to last. Schoenberg's ruminatively beautiful
string sextet ``Transfigured Night,'' the next work he submitted
for the ensemble's consideration, was rejected as too radical. And
when several of his songs were presented in Vienna in late 1900,
vehement protests erupted in the audience. Schoenberg soon became,
as he put it, ``everyone's whipping boy.'' For the rest of his
life, he met with incomprehension at best, outright hostility at
worst.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Schoenberg probably gets the nod as the most reviled
composer in history. So when the Metropolitan Opera presents its
first production of his masterpiece ``Moses und Aron'' on Feb. 8,
more of the animosity the composer's music has always attracted
will undoubtedly be whipped up.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Schoenberg tried to numb himself to the attacks. ``I
have become indifferent to public abuse,'' he wrote in 1915 to
composer Alexander Zemlinsky, who, though just three years older,
was the closest thing the essentially self-taught Schoenberg had to
a teacher. In truth, the abuse embittered him. When it came from
musicians and critics, he suffered pangs of self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And the abuse could be merciless. ``I suffered physical pain, as
one cruelly abused,'' a Berlin critic wrote in 1909, on hearing the
composer's Second String Quartet. New York Times critic James
Gibbons Huneker, reporting on a performance of ``Pierrot Lunaire''
in 1913, wrote that Schoenberg's music conveyed an ``aura of
original depravity, of subtle ugliness, of basest egoism, of hatred
and contempt, of cruelty and of the mystic grandiose.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schoenberg clung to his belief that however radical, the
evolution of his musical language into free atonality, and his
subsequent invention of the technique of 12-tone composition,
represented inevitable stages in the development of the great
European classical tradition. That is not the way things panned
out. Still, Schoenberg would probably be amazed by the imposing
place he now occupies in music history.
</P>
<P>
   Though Huneker's condemnation may seem laughably excessive
today, many present-day listeners essentially agree. The Met
production of ``Moses und Aron'' will be seen as a brave act of
principled programming. But the New York City Opera proved that
``Moses und Aron'' does not have to be box-office poison when it
presented the work's New York stage premiere in 1990. Ticket sales
were strong, though they were driven in part by a daring
production, which included a steamy enactment of Israelites
engaging in orgiastic dancing and naked coupling before the idol of
the golden calf.
</P>
<P>
   Little word has emerged about the Met's production, by Graham
Vick, but publicity photographs suggest a spare, vividly colorful
approach. James Levine, who reveres the opera, will conduct.
</P>
<P>
   If anything of Schoenberg's has the potential to engage those
unfamiliar with his music _ intimidated by the 12-tone idiom,
perhaps, but at least curious _ it is this viscerally powerful,
dauntingly complex yet often hauntingly beautiful opera, for which
Schoenberg also wrote the libretto. It is the composer's most
directly personal statement.
</P>
<P>
   The drama turns on a debate. God has instructed Moses to lead
His chosen people from the bonds of oppression. Moses profoundly
understands that the omnipresent God is ultimately ``unperceived
and unrepresentable,'' but he despairs of being able to communicate
this idea to his wary, downtrodden followers. God tells Moses to
seek help from Aron, his verbally adroit brother. But Aron
empathizes with the doubting Israelites and their need for
something tangible to believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Aron represents graspable reality, which can be perceived
through the senses and shared. Schoenberg, accordingly, conceives
the role for a plaintive and, ideally, powerful tenor. Philip
Langridge is the Met's Aron. Moses deals with incomprehensible
phenomena, which cannot be explained. In a bold stroke, Schoenberg
conveys Moses' lack of verbal eloquence by having him deliver his
part in a sort of notated speech. (Rhythms are exact, but pitches
are marked on the staff with X's, to indicate that they should be
spoken and suggested.) The bass John Tomlinson, in his Met debut,
portrays Moses.
</P>
<P>
   The biblical story spoke to Schoenberg's deep spiritual
cravings. Perhaps because his life's work involved contesting the
absolutes he had inherited in music, Schoenberg sought others in
religion. He completed two acts of the opera in 1932. (A third was
intended but never composed.)
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Hitler's rise to power in Germany and the Nazis'
persecution of Jews provoked a powerful reaction in Schoenberg.
Born and raised Jewish in Vienna, he had converted to Lutheranism
in early adulthood. But in 1933, at 59, he openly re-embraced the
Jewish faith. ``Moses und Aron'' anticipated his reconversion and
grippingly expressed the fervor behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospect of hearing ``Moses und Aron'' will no doubt
evoke terror in many listeners. Why has Schoenberg's musical
radicalism engendered such continuing hostility, when the
radicalism of Stravinsky and Bartok has long been embraced?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because Schoenberg is viewed, simplistically, as the
main culprit behind the powerful challenge to the system of
tonality that had for centuries brought at least some degree of
commonality to music from diverse cultures, and because he is
blamed, rightly or wrongly, for driving a wedge between
20th-century composers and the public. Even Schoenberg's
pre-12-tone music represented, in the words of a Berlin critic in
1910, a ``methodical negation of all heretofore accepted musical
rules.'' Schoenberg ``kills tonal perception,'' the critic added.
``Debussy only threatens; Schoenberg carries out the threat.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, to be sure, an element of truth in this critique, and
Schoenberg has never been forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, he revered the tradition and the stylistic unity
it made possible. Despite his defensiveness about his work, he
never intended to tear down the entire tonal system. He moved to
the United States in 1933 and eventually settled in Los Angeles,
where he briefly became a friend and tennis partner of George
Gershwin, whom he respected immensely. There was nothing
patronizing about this respect. Schoenberg simply felt that the
serious music of high culture operated on a different plane from
other music, and radical currents had been sweeping through serious
music for some time.
</P>
<P>
   He felt compelled, almost against his will, to dismantle
existing procedures and devise new ones. It was a dirty job, in
other words, but somebody had to do it.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, needed to be done? Before the century was a
decade old, the system of tonality was in crisis, and whatever one
ultimately thinks of Schoenberg's solutions, his analysis of the
problem was astute, convincing and courageous.
</P>
<P>
   Although tonal music is ubiquitous, the concept of tonality is
hard to describe. In its most common manifestation, music using
major and minor keys, tonality is a system of organizing pitch in
accordance with acoustical principles. A certain pitch (say, the C
of the C major scale) is fundamental. The other pitches of the
scale relate to that fundamental in an audible hierarchy of
importance. Whatever happens, the music has to keep referring back
to that fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   Variety and creativity in the tonal system come from playing
with expectations and introducing ambiguity. By the mid-19th
century, this game was getting out of hand. Schoenberg correctly
perceived a work like Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde'' as music that
daringly and ingeniously frustrated, even negated, the sense of a
clear tonal center. In the music of Richard Strauss and Max Reger,
Schoenberg felt, the system of major and minor tonality had lost
all its functionality. He knew that such was the case with his
music as well, and although others had made similar observations,
few dared to face the daunting implications.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Schoenberg tried to write in a harmonic language
unhinged from tonality: atonality, it has been called, although
Schoenberg hated the term. Works like his Three Piano Pieces (Op.
11), from 1909, were written with the harmonic equivalent of free
association. It is not coincidental that during this period of a
free-roaming musical language Schoenberg wrote a lot of vocal works
with texts: most famously, ``Pierrot Lunaire.'' A text would give a
listener at least something to hang onto; in similar fashion, movie
audiences will accept all manner of dissonance and chaos in a
score, because it is heard as lending expression to a cinematic
story.
</P>
<P>
   But Schoenberg tired of writing music with texts and knew he had
reached a dead end. So he took a conceptual leap that was audacious
yet, in a sense, thrillingly logical: if all 12 pitches in the
octave (together, the chromatic scale) are to be used more or less
equally, he reasoned, then why not devise a system that insures
equality.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the old hierarchy or his new free-for-all, he
specified that the 12 pitches be put in an order, or row, or set.
Once a pitch was sounded, it was not to be repeated until the
entire row had unfolded. And since chords, the vertical element of
music, were also built from the tone row, the system would insure
absolute equality between the horizontal (or melodic) and vertical
(or harmonic) elements of music.
</P>
<P>
   There were many ways around this system. A composer could
transpose the rows, go through them backward or upside-down, break
them into halves or thirds, and play mix-and-match.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds brainy and mathematical, and in a way it is. But for
Schoenberg it was liberating. With equivalency of pitch made almost
automatic, he could achieve subtlety, complexity, nuance, tension,
tenderness or whatever quality he was after through other musical
elements: rhythmic gesture, texture, density, contrapuntal
inventiveness, accent, dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as crazy as it sounds. When I taught music appreciation
in college, I won over a lot of skeptics with a simple
demonstration. I would play a Bach musette on the piano, then play
the Musette from Schoenberg's Suite for Piano (Op. 25), a
thoroughly 12-tone work. In every aspect except for the way the
pitches were picked, the Schoenberg musette was just like Bach's:
the same short-short-long rhythm; the same bagpipelike drone
characteristic of this 17th-century French dance form; the same
skipping, playful character. And when students stopped fretting
about tone rows, they would hear the elements of the Bach musette
in Schoenberg's stunning transformation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, pleased with the facility his new technique afforded,
Schoenberg wrote to a colleague, ``I find myself positively enabled
to compose as freely and fantastically as one otherwise does only
in one's youth, and am nevertheless subject to a precisely
definable esthetic discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, then and now, would scoff, and charge that Schoenberg
was simply writing by default, according to the dictates of some
pitch chart. But whole spans of tonal music in Haydn, Mozart and
Beethoven are written with an equivalent degree of automatic
selection: standard accompanimental patterns; passage work based on
scales; rhythmic riffs; even melodies (to say nothing of
automatic-pilot sonata form and the like). Invention and
ingeniousness lie in the music's details, just as they do in
Schoenberg's 12-tone works.
</P>
<P>
   In his initial excitement, Schoenberg wrongly predicted that his
system would insure the continued supremacy of Germanic music for
at least another century. Yet his work and that of his disciples
Alban Berg and Anton Webern captured the imagination of countless
composers in later decades. During the 1960s and '70s, their method
was championed in many of the most prestigious university music
departments, though with a dogmatism that is, in retrospect,
regrettable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were other ways to inject freshness into
tonality, as Stravinsky, Bartok, Shostakovich, Britten and others
showed. And the universe of music is probably destined to be, if
not strictly tonal, at least tonally rooted, since the hunger for
tonality is built into the properties of sound and, thus, into the
ear itself. So Schoenberg's 12-tone music and that of his followers
are best heard as playing with (or against) the innate expectation
of tonal grounding. Music written with 12-tone procedures
discombobulates, befuddles, challenges and, ideally, delights the
ear.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, Schoenberg was a visionary musical
genius, as would have been clear whatever his method of
composition. He would have wanted us to experience ``Moses und
Aron'' without even thinking about tone rows.
</P>
<P>
   Why the opera was never completed is a sad tale. Schoenberg
eventually got a job at UCLA. The man who had once taught Berg and
Webern now had classes of relative beginners. But he forged on. In
1944, at 70, he was forcibly retired. Since he had taught for just
eight years, his pension was a pitiful $38 a month. From his second
marriage, he had three children to raise, aged 13, 8, and 4. In a
heartbreaking letter to the Guggenheim Foundation he applied for a
grant so that he could, among other things, complete ``Moses und
Aron.'' He was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   In the draft Schoenberg left for the third act, the power
conflict shifts. Moses imprisons his brother, charging that by
misrepresenting the unknowable God, Aron has led his people into
the wilderness, literally and metaphorically. When Moses orders
Aron's release, Aron falls dead. Moses affirms that in the desert,
paradoxically, his people will truly find unity with God.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two acts composed are powerful and do not seem
incomplete. At the end of Act II, the anguished Moses confronts the
fact that God is ultimately unknowable, and that people, craving
proof, will always be vulnerable to leaders, like Aron, who give
them what they want. True faith requires an intuitive, almost
irrational commitment. Moses understands this but cannot convey it.
So what else is new? End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg may have used systematic procedures to compose this
work, but the resulting music is often sensuously beautiful, as in
the eerie, soft-spoken, sustained passages for chorus. Schoenberg's
text is stern and preachy, but the words are set with a humane
poignancy. At one point, for example, Aron asks Moses, ``How can
you worship what you cannot represent?'' On the page the question
is blunt. But as set musically, Aron's words are plaintive and
moving.
</P>
<P>
   And for sheer, driving, ferocious power, nothing in opera _ not
the opening storm scene of Verdi's ``Otello,'' not the music that
evokes Siegmund fleeing his enemies through the wind-swept forest
in Wagner's ``Walkure,'' not the angry crowd scene in Britten's
``Peter Grimes'' _ packs the wallop of Schoenberg's frenzied music
depicting the sacrifices and sex before the golden calf.
</P>
<P>
   For some listeners, the difficulty with ``Moses und Aron'' may
come less from the 12-tone idiom than from the composer's extensive
use of speech and quasi-speech, not just for Moses but also for
extended passages in the chorus. All that shouting can seem
melodramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses und Aron'' lacks the dramatic sophistication of Berg's
``Wozzeck'' and ``Lulu.'' Unlike Schoenberg, Berg was a born man of
the theater, who devised a way to soften his mentor's 12-tone
technique with hints of tonal harmony. The music of ``Moses''
retains some two-dimensional qualities, suggesting the oratorio
Schoenberg first thought it might be. But a good production can
leave a listener shattered. And under Levine's direction, the Met's
superb orchestra and chorus are presumably poised to give one.
</P>
<P>
   Some opera fans will pass the poster for ``Moses und Aron''
outside the Met, curse Schoenberg's name and go inside to buy
tickets for ``Aida.'' They will miss the work of a composer placing
everything on the line, maybe crossing that line but not caring, so
powerful was his compulsion to create this opera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
