<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1902 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAKEOVERS-THEATER-ART     01-28 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEOVERS-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING MOUTH-TO-MOUTH TO `THE PIMPERNEL' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Maine)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31)  
 (af)  
 By SYLVIANE GOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather like the hero of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' who rescues
doomed French aristocrats from the jaws of the guillotine, Robert
Longbottom seems to have saved the musical by Frank Wildhorn and
Nan Knighton from certain death.
</P>
<P>
   After opening to overwhelmingly negative reviews in November
1997, and playing for months to dwindling audiences at the Minskoff
Theater on Broadway, the show was on the brink of closing when new
producers, led by Radio City Entertainment, bought the production.
They asked Longbottom, the director and choreographer of last
season's ``Side Show,'' to resuscitate it, and when it reopened
this past November, most critics agreed that he had done just that.
</P>
<P>
   The retooled ``Scarlet Pimpernel'' has given theatergoers a rare
glimpse of the critical role played by the directors of Broadway
musicals. Yet when you talk to them about what they do for a
living, they resort to simple metaphors that belie the complexity
of their task. They will tell you the job is about finding a
rhythm, seeing a picture, hearing a motor. Or maybe making an arc,
weaving a spell, taking a journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a musical succeeds, it looks effortless,'' said James
Lapine, the director and writer, with Stephen Sondheim, of the
musicals ``Sunday in the Park With George'' and ``Into the Woods.''
``But it's a totally bizarre art form. There are no rules to go
by.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the form's most venerable practitioners, like Harold Prince
and Tommy Tune, have had to contend with fiascoes; artists of
genius, like the choreographers Twyla Tharp and Mark Morris, have
been humbled in their attempts to direct Broadway musicals
(``Singin' in the Rain'' and the recent ``Capeman,'' respectively);
and for young directors trying to gain a foothold in the
profession, it has become harder and harder to find an acknowledged
master to understudy.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of the century, directors of musical comedy,
as the genre was called, usually staged book scenes, while the
choreographer attended to dance sequences and the musical staff
took care of the songs. The results would not pass muster today,
Prince once said in an interview: ``Big stars stood center stage,
legs nicely apart, and belted great songs greatly. And you went to
hear that great music and have a nice buoyant experience.'' The
director was a minor part of the success _ or failure _ of a given
show.
</P>
<P>
   As musicals came of age in the middle of the century, shows like
``Oklahoma!,'' ``Carousel'' and ``Pal Joey'' pushed the form into
darker, more dramatic territory, giving directors new importance.
And concept musicals like ``West Side Story,'' ``Company'' and
``Sweeney Todd'' completed the transformation of the director into
the musical's primary creative force. But the old guidelines, which
had been pioneered by Prince's mentor, George Abbott, could no
longer guide.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was as renowned for his ability to prescribe remedies for
other directors' ailing shows as he was for staging his own. But
Longbottom did not want to doctor ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.'' Still
heartsick about the failure of ``Side Show,'' which had not won an
audience despite critical support, and eager for a new project, he
told the producers that Peter Hunt's original staging would need a
complete overhaul. ``You can't fix a few moments,'' he said he told
them. ``You need to really address the beginning, middle and end.''
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that someone who has been
sharpening the musty Radio City Christmas show since 1994 _
Longbottom is the director _ would be able to put a glossy finish
on an old-fashioned period musical. But, he said, the most useful
skill he got from working at the Music Hall was the ability to
direct and choreograph quickly.
</P>
<P>
   So his bosses knew he could do the job in the 75 hours they gave
him to rehearse the ``Pimpernel'' cast. Another help was his
background in summer stock: ``Putting up `South Pacific' in nine
days is not very fulfilling, but it's good to know you can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Longbottom, whose passion for the theater first manifested
itself when, as an 8-year-old in Maine, he began tap-dance lessons,
also apprenticed as a gypsy in touring Broadway shows. ``Watching
the process, how shows were put together, fascinated me much more
than dishing in the dressing room,'' he said. ``When I wasn't
onstage, you'd find me out behind the tech table, eavesdropping as
much as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing may help, noted Jerry Zaks, who directed the current
``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' and is preparing the next Wildhorn musical,
``The Civil War,'' scheduled to open on April 22 at the St. James
Theater on Broadway. ``But the only way to learn is trial and
error. Music has its own power and its own set of rules. And
learning to integrate all of a musical's elements is very much an
ongoing process,'' he said. ``There are so many pieces. You learn
how each one can tell the story and you learn to make sure they're
not fighting each other. The task is always to weave some sort of
spell, and in a musical, you have more tools to help _ and more
things to coordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   The coordinating is a skill in itself. ``The director walks a
fine line between being a visionary and a diplomat,'' Longbottom
said. ``You've got to make sure everybody on the team is seeing the
same show. But you need the skills of the diplomat to navigate the
different egos and temperaments, because they make contributions
that are essential to its success. You don't write music, and you
don't write lyrics. So it's critical that these people be totally
inspired to do their best work.''
</P>
<P>
   The confidence to put together a team and manage it well is
rarely given to neophytes. In an interview before Julie Taymor won
the Tony Award last June for directing her first effort for the
commercial Broadway theater, she pointed out that she had been
honing her skills for more than two decades in the nonprofit arena:
``I had the experience, the guts to be able to say, `Believe me,
I've done this before, I know it works,' '' she said of being in
command of the many contributors to ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   With its visual splendor, ``The Lion King'' is a persuasive
example of the importance of a director's design sense to the
overall effect of a musical. Prince has said that ``visual concepts
are probably the largest part of the concept musical.'' And like
many directors, Longbottom thinks in images: ``If I can't see
something once I've read a scene, it usually means there's a
problem with the way it's written.''
</P>
<P>
   Picturing ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' was easy for Longbottom,
since the sets and costumes were already in place. But what made
him believe he could improve it? ``I have no idea,'' he said. ``I
was terrified. But I knew I couldn't make it any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking on the project, he watched Hunt's original
version, which he had first seen when it was still in previews.
(Hunt did not respond to several requests for an interview.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Since everyone else was focusing on what was wrong with the
show,'' Longbottom said, ``I went in there deliberately making
myself focus on what appealed to me about the story. And there was
a lot.'' He was most taken by two of its elements: the comfortable
English aristocrats so moved by the plight of their French
counterparts during the Reign of Terror that they risk their lives
to help them escape, and the triangular love story.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Material, Lapine said, is the key to directing a musical: ``If
the material doesn't work, I don't think (italics)anybody(end
italics) can make it fly. But you have to help shape it. Nobody's
ever handed in a show that didn't need more work.''
</P>
<P>
   Longbottom felt he knew exactly how he could make the
18th-century adventure story meaningful to a contemporary audience.
``I wanted to highlight what it takes for all of us, as citizens,
to get involved, to do more than just write a hundred-dollar check
at Christmas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he wanted to accentuate the character of Marguerite, the
French actress who is suspected by her bridegroom, Sir Percy
Blakeney, of being in cahoots with his enemies in France, both
personally and politically. ``She was the center of the story,''
Longbottom said. ``To me, the motor of the show was the love
triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   To let the audience in on this, he replaced the musical's
opening, in which a vengeful Parisian mob had literally sung the
praises of the guillotine as blue bloods went to their deaths. ``I
had real problems with that,'' Longbottom said. ``I didn't object
to the gore. But I had no idea what was going on. And I thought
that that song had such a singular point of view that it should
belong to one character, not an ensemble. Within the first five
minutes of any show, you've got to know where to look and what the
characters want. I felt a better door to get into that was through
Marguerite.''
</P>
<P>
   So he turned a street song she sang in the second act into a
fanciful Ziegfeld-style number for the character, whose final
performance in a Paris theater now opens the show as Percy and her
former lover, the heartless radical Chauvelin, watch. Longbottom
also recast the roles of Marguerite and Chauvelin, hiring Rachel
York and Rex Smith to join Douglas Sills, whose Percy in the
original production had earned him a Tony nomination. (Sills is
scheduled to leave the musical on March 7.)
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring the ``Pimpernel'' book with Ms. Knighton,
Longbottom recalled, they ``didn't really shuffle the songs so much
as think, `What's the new thrust here? How are we going to propel
these three people into this journey?' The plot came first.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Galati, the director of plays and operas, who turned his
hand to the Broadway musical for the first time with the current
``Ragtime,'' said that narrative is the crucial ingredient in
directing a musical, as it is in directing a play. ``There are so
many elements that contribute to the experience _ songs, scenery,
costumes, dance, lighting, special effects, atmosphere. But in
order to really engage and lift an audience out of themselves, the
fundamental is to tell a story. The key is storytelling,
storytelling energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Longbottom discovered that getting the right energy into the
Pimpernel story required extensive cutting _ the script went from
112 pages to 80 _ and many of his cuts were jokes. ``People looked
at me like I was crazy when I said there were too many laughs,'' he
said. But he felt they were distracting the audience from the arc
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Directing a musical is just about rhythm,'' said George C.
Wolfe, the director of ``Jelly's Last Jam'' and ``Bring In da
Noise, Bring In da Funk,'' whose recent revival of ``On the Town,''
closed this month after mixed reviews on Broadway. In ``On the
Town,'' he was troubled by two scenes that took place in the
apartments of two of the show's New York women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious parallel structure,'' he said, ``but it was
crafted with the rhythms of 1944. By intercutting the two scenes, I
was able to infuse them with a much more contemporary feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time that first note is hit, you're off on this
journey that is defined exclusively by rhythm. You need that rhythm
_ of music, of dance, of words, of scenery _ to keep the audience
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the audience. ``If there's anything that makes me a good
director of musicals,'' Lapine said, ``it's that I have a short
attention span.''
</P>
<P>
   When, in ``Passion,'' he and Sondheim did a show that tried to
ignore the familiar rhythms of scene-song-scene-song, they found
audiences unwilling to go along. ``It's important to let the
audience laugh,'' Lapine said. ``It's important to let the audience
applaud. It's an incredible release for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Longbottom felt that ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' ``needed to have
a real infusion of Broadway sensibility. It didn't have a bona-fide
production number or showstopper, even though the ingredients were
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A good number,'' he said, ``has an agenda, takes the story
from one place to another. Even in the Christmas show, where most
of the numbers are divertissements, I try to infuse them with
storytelling. So from the top of a number to the end, the Rockettes
will go somewhere.'' In ``Pimpernel,'' he decided that the best
opportunity was ``The Creation of Man,'' the song in which Percy
persuades his aristocratic friends to disguise their
counterrevolutionary activities by pretending to be fops. But he
was puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to the costume designer, Jane Greenwood, `Why is your
statement such a soft one here?' And she said, `There was a whole
set of costumes that were rejected.' Bingo!'' said Longbottom. New
costumes based on what Ms. Greenwood described as her
``over-the-top'' sketches help the restaged number ``land'' every
night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience needed that. There's a great deal of exposition
in the first act. So by the time you put the pieces together,
you're an hour and 10 minutes into the show. You need a reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Longbottom sees these as ``the seismic ups and downs'' of a
musical. ``If there are too many flat lines, you have a problem.
You need to have a steady climb to the end of the first act, and
you have to make sure the second act gets back up to where the
first left off. It's all very tricky,'' he said. ``It's
instinctual. It's not anything you can read anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
