<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV31-C     01-28 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HIGH TECH COMES TO THE HIGH ALPS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ Each year, a bunch of big shots gathers at
this ski resort to ponder the fate of the world. When I first
started attending these meetings four years ago, wearing a plain
white badge that identified me as a ``media leader,'' few of the
poohbahs who plunk down upwards of $40,000 to spend a week here
with their fellow poohbahs paid any heed to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, in this rarefied realm, keyboards that link users to
the Internet were seen as best left to flunkies. To allow the
leaders stay in touch between annual
</P>
<P>
   meetings, Geneva-based organizers of the World Economic Forum
pushed a proprietary contact system. But it was poorly received by
the attendees, not because it was quite costly but because it would
have required them to use a video monitor.
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed. This year, anyone with access to the
Internet can watch the main proceedings as they occur by clicking
on an Internet site (http://live99.weforum.org).
</P>
<P>
   Having been asked to park their security teams away from this
crowded Alpine campus, the visiting brass appear quite content to
parade before virtual crowds. In any event, they do their real
business behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Of late, Davos has been discovered by the digital divas. Rich
folks seen plodding through the snow include such founding fathers
of cyberspace as Microsoft's Bill Gates, computer maker Michael
Dell, Steve Case of America Online, Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com and
Scott McNealy of Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   They skirt Russia's Yevgeny Primakov and South Africa's Nelson
Mandela to join in seminars on how to spread the ``info
revolution'' and how to deal with the ``technology trap.''
(Research shows that the new technologies, while speeding contacts
and compressing time, can also aggravate conflict and foster an
``argument culture.'')
</P>
<P>
   The info-billionaires have also plunged into a seemingly
continual round of hi-tech schmooze sessions. (Their informal
discussions would no doubt be of interest to Joel Klein, who heads
the antitrust division of the U.S. Justice Department. Klein,
invited to attend, felt obliged to stay back in Washington to
monitor the Microsoft trial, where the ``argument culture'' remains
on display.)
</P>
<P>
   No matter what their exalted station in life might be, each
participant at this year's gathering walks around carrying a tiny
networked computer, hidden within his or her credit card-sized
plastic badge.
</P>
<P>
   These ``smart cards,'' the organizers assure us, ``allow a
superior level of identification and security within the (meeting
hall). They will be further developed in
</P>
<P>
   future years to become the central piece of an integrated
computing structure allowing participants to seamlessly register
for sessions, access their e-mailbox, and
</P>
<P>
   perform several other personalized applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Such computerized badges must make the Dells and the McNealys
and their kindred cybersouls feel at home in the Swiss Alps.
Thoroughly in touch, they trudge off to inform the forum about how
to do business in the digital economy, at a session televised on
the Internet and aptly moderated by Kim Clark, dean of the Harvard
Graduate School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
