<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF     01-28 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS AND FEATURE No 2516 - January 28, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BUDDHISM AND SCIENCE The ancient teachings of Buddhism have
some remarkable similarities with modern science. Both are founded
on profound scepticism and both seek explanations to the great
questions. While science is steadfastly objective and Buddhism
highly subjective, both lay claim to understanding the universe in
ways that may be complementary. From GEO Magazine. By Hanne Tugel.
1,700 words. (English translation available.)
</P>
<P>
   2. WHEN CHILDREN LEARN A SECOND LANGUAGE Surprisingly good
things happen when kids are exposed at home and at school to a
second language : increased self-esteem, better concentration,
improved scores in mathematics and an appreciation of different
cultures. Children are best able to absorb a second language when
they are under 6 years old. By Lynne S. Dumas. Child magazine.
1,400 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
INTRUDER IN THE HEART Miguel never recalled when his feeble,
quivering heartbeats actually began. The first attacks were brief.
Doctors finally determined he was suffering from Chagas disease,
caused by Tryponasoma cruzi, a single-celled protozoan that can
burrow into heart muscle. Claire Panosian, a professor of medicine
in the division of infectious diseases and director of travel and
tropical medicine at UCLA Medical Centre, reports on treating
Miguel. From Discover magazine. 1,100 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
FAT-BLASTERS FOR MIDDLE-AGED METABOLISMS Is your weight giving you
a midlife crisis? This article explains how you can fight back (and
offers a helpful sidebar on ways to cut 100 calories.) By Julia
Califano. McCall's. 900 words + 200-word sidebar.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
RUSSIAN DRIFT Today Russia is closer to bloody conflict than it has
ever been since the terrible civil war of 1918-20. For 70 years,
the Soviet Union operated a strong state apparatus, anchored by the
KGB and the Communist Party. Now its disintegration has created a
power vacuum that has yet to be filled. By Steven R. David. Foreign
Affairs Magazine. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. WATCH OUT, RUSSIA IS STILL ON THE BRINK Winston Churchill's
description of Russia as a ``riddle wrapped in a mystery in an
enigma'' was a reference to the total obsessive secrecy of Stalin's
regime. That's all gone, but Russia remains a dilemma. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
From NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. UNLOCKING THE MIND : Even people who are completely paralysed
can teach their brains to type. By Jonathan Knight. 500 words. B.
TURNING THE TIDE : Italy has abandoned a plan to erect giant
barriers to protect Venice from flooding. Has it surrendered the
city to the sea, or is it taking the first step to an ecological
solution? By Fred Pearce. 1,500 words. C. JAM PACKED : Strange as
it sounds, adding more cars might help to clear congested roads.
Two physicists have come up with a method for optimising traffic
flow that gets traffic moving safely and quickly by sometimes
increasing the number of vehicles on the road. By Charles Seife.
300 words. D. IN THE SHADOW OF THE MOON : If you thought the
Babylonians had nothing to offer 20th-century science, think again.
Their records of ancient eclipses are helping modern astronomers to
chart the Earth's movement with amazing precision. By Marcus Chown.
2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   8. FOUR CURES FOR CABIN FEVER By the time February arrives, the
holidays are long gone and mid-winter blues are centre stage. Here
are some ideas on how to get creative about your leisure time with
the kids. By Lori B. Murray. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   9. ANTI-CANCER VACCINE SHOWS PROMISE AGAINST COLON CANCER
Patients with colon cancer who received an experimental anti-cancer
vaccine after undergoing surgery were less likely to see their
cancers return. Researchers conclude that such vaccines may help
many patients with this deadly disease. By Michael McCarthy. The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
CHOCOLATE LOVERS ARE MADE, NOT BORN An international team of
researchers found that the peculiarly female lust for chocolate
appears not to be physiological but cultural. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
New York Times Science Times. 750 words + photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
