<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Mom and Pop play the market
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is at least one thing on which Bill Clinton and the
congressional Republicans are somewhat in agreement: The Clinton
plan to allow baby boomers to invest a portion of their Social
Security taxes in the stock market. Whatever that portion turns out
to be in dollars, Republicans already don't think it's enough.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's too much. Although the total dollars amount to only
a fraction of Wall Street holdings, by any other human standard the
amount is huge. Mom and Pop ought to have lots of fun playing the
market, which lacks only neon to rival Las Vegas for amusement
value. It finally fell to good old cautious Alan Greenspan to ask
if this wasn't a tiny bit much.
</P>
<P>
   There are already enough fly-by-night stock schemes being
offered America's seniors from phone boiler rooms on any given
morning to give you the terminal willies. What will happen to Mom
and Pop's retirement savings if the market blows them out? They
must be drooling in the shark pools.
</P>
<P>
   What will we say to Mom and Pop? Sorry folks, but you should
have known better than to put everything into goldbubble.com? Lost
the old homestead? Awful sorry, but you can't live here?
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
