<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN31-COX     01-28 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Is the American political system heading South?
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a fair amount of chin-pulling and other
histrionic musings in recent years over the suspected
``Southernization'' of America, by which it is generally meant that
the whole nation is taking on the characteristics associated with
the South _ and usually its worst ones: a hidebound moralism,
anti-intellectualism and a social and political conservatism that
stops, if it stops at all, just a hair short of the outright
reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those supposed characteristics are more like stereotypes
than archetypes and the anecdotal evidence often looks more
assembled than weighed. Still, if you're after further suspicious
trends, consider the drift in national attitudes toward treating
politics mainly as a spectator sport, useful only for whatever
passing entertainment it provides and otherwise meaningless or even
damaging.
</P>
<P>
   For generations after the Civil War, the South's one-party
Democratic politics and its dead weight of leaden racist
demagoguery reduced elections to an empty exercise in form without
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Laws and custom both drove potential voters away from the polls.
The South's turnouts were usually the nation's lowest. Personal
rivalries and cooked-up differences substituted for the honest
differences of honest partisanship. Voters were walk-ons in staged
dramas. The ``big mules'' _ major landowners and others with
business interests _ used political gofers to keep schooling weak
and labor cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Politics became not a means for working a broad public will for
the better but instead the occasional source of mere treats for its
players _ a road here, a dinky college there. With most voters
fatalistic and sidelined, the electorate settled for political
gossip and tales of the shenanigans of elected characters. Voters
traded their franchise for good seats.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. The old South swapped its political yarns in barber shops
and courthouse halls. The new America hears its political stories
from late-night TV jokers, radio slimers and political wrestling
shows like ``McLaughlin Group.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 Pew Research Center poll found that a fourth of voters
learned about the presidential campaign from Leno, Letterman and so
on. And since the biggest targets are the easiest, presidents are
the butts of most yuks and cheap outrage. Last year, according to
the Center for Media and Public Affairs, President Clinton was hit
1,721 times on the four leading late-night TV shows; Kenneth Starr
139 times.
</P>
<P>
   National voter participation has fallen to historic lows. After
all, why not? Politics, we are tutored, is pointless _ didn't
Ronald Reagan teach us no problem is so bad it can't be made still
worse by any effort to solve it? _ and politicians are only a
troupe of scamps, charlatans and clowns.
</P>
<P>
   Hyper partisanship is as off-putting as one-party politics once
was. Since politics is a means to no end but itself, why not study
it in the circle of Hollywood detritus assembled nightly by
``Politically Incorrect''?
</P>
<P>
   We are selling our franchise for channel-surfing. Southern or
not, it's a lousy deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIXIE-CARTER29-COX     01-28 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIE-CARTER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dixie on Dixie
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Who ever would've guessed that Julia
Sugarbaker _ she of ardent opinion and arched eyebrow _ was a woman
of minced words?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the fewest lines of anyone on the show,'' drawls Dixie
Carter, discussing her role as the cynical grande dame on Designing
Women. ``I'm actually quite proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud because subtle asides and nail-on-the-head facial
expressions (``they cut to me a lot for reaction'') made her
character memorable. Not reams of sitcom blabber or slapstick
antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show was written just for us,'' she says, referring to
original cast co-stars Delta Burke, Annie Potts and Jean Smart.
``We all thought we were the prettiest and the funniest.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, Carter doesn't have to vie for prom queen.
That's because her cabaret act of comedy, song and Southern
anecdotes is a solo gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing now is the real McCoy,'' she says. ``A live
audience is the reason I went into performing. It's just me, the
material and the people in the room. I can't get that from a
camera.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carter, by the way, is chatting by phone from Beverly Hills.
She's just gotten her hair ``cut off, off, off''' and has a
BellSouth Yellow Pages shoot today. ``I am,'' she jokes, ``tres
chic.'')
</P>
<P>
   The actress, it seems, has always been on stage _ and not just
in a theater.
</P>
<P>
   She was valedictorian at her high school in Huntingdon, Tenn.
(and nabbed the math award, too). Swept cooking competitions at the
fair. Won beauty pageants through college. And even took first
prize in a 4-H Club personality contest (``now that was
something!'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a total goody-two-shoes, but I had this spirit that made
me see how much I could do,'' recalls Carter, 59. ``I've always
been nice, but kind of bossy. I was an ambitious little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The middle kid of retailer Halbert Carter and his wife,
Virginia, the actress was born and raised in McLemoresville, Tenn.,
about 100 miles northeast of Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is still home
</P>
<P>
   She spends several months a year in the Volunteer State,
fiddling with her home in Harrison (the one in the BellSouth
commercials) and filling up on Southern cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even, by the way, get her started on food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, I just plunge in! Bacon drippings. That's the
great thing to put in the skillet. I love fried catfish. I love
turnip greens cooked with a little fatback. I love a wonderful
crust on my cornbread that you cannot get without grease. Oh,
honey!
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you have to break off an ear of corn in the garden,
run to the house while you're stripping the silk and throw it right
into the pot. If you do that, you don't need butter. Save that for
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yes, lemon meringue pie. And icebox pudding. You know,
with black walnuts, not English. And sausage and country ham and
fresh stewed tomatoes. Oh, baby!''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my! How does she stay so thin?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoga,'' replies Carter, who released a workout video in 1992.
``And I don't eat that way in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabulous vittles though, ain't all she hankers for from her
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the kindness. Even from strangers, you'll hear `I'm
sorry' or `excuse me.' In an ordinary day _ at the supermarket, a
department store, a traffic snarlup _ people are polite and
considerate. I can't imagine being from anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in New York, you may get a punch in the kisser, but at
least you know where you stand. In California, though, there's this
surface adoration. `Have a good day!' `We love you!' Then you'll
hear later what was really said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, in the South, we talk about people, too,'' she
concedes. ``But if you end your comments with `bless her heart,'
you're off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Followed her big dreams
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a Southern belle with big-city ambition, moved to New
York in the early '60s. She had an English degree from then Memphis
State University (now the University of Memphis) and had been a hit
in college theater, but she yearned to sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was four, I started dreaming that I'd perform at the
Met,'' recalls Carter, who listened to Metropolitan Opera radio
programs as a kid. ``I was sure that was my destiny. As I got older
I felt a little less secure because I started to realize that my
voice was not this enormous sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carter did have enormous presence, which didn't escape
Joseph Papp, founder of the New York Shakespeare Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that some of the biggest successes in New York were
country bumpkins because they were so unsophisticated, they'd try
anything. I began to think I was in some pretty tall cotton.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after her 1963 off-Broadway debut in ``A Winter's
Tale,'' the hazel-eyed brunette met her first husband, newspaper
publisher Arthur Carter. ``The day after I met him he sent me a
dozen dozen roses.'' (That's 144.)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, y'all, his name was also Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember not wanting to get married because I didn't want to
change my last name,'' she says. ``Back then, you didn't think
about another option. So I became Dixie Virginia Carter Carter.
Talk about luck!''
</P>
<P>
   After about eight years, though, her luck ran out _ at least
where Arthur was concerned. So Dixie left her husband and took her
two daughters, Ginna and Mary Dixie (now 28 and 26), to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out to L.A. scared to pieces, but I just kept plugging.
I couldn't very well live off my ex-husband for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter quickly found an agent, a TV job and a new man.
</P>
<P>
   A brief second marriage to actor George Hearn followed in 1978,
along with her first TV sitcom role, April Baxter on CBS's ``On Our
Own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Designing Women'' a hit
</P>
<P>
   Then came small parts on ``Out of the Blue,'' ``Filthy Rich,''
``Diff'rent Strokes'' and finally, her big break: ``Designing
Women'' from 1986-93.
</P>
<P>
   Carter never lost her Southern accent, though, unless a role
demanded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, people who went North and lost their
accents were considered turncoats,'' she says. ``That was never
actually spelled out, but the implication was that if they talked
different, they weren't proud of where they'd come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride, obviously, was never much of a problem for Carter. Until,
that is, she met actor Hal Holbrook, now 73, on the 1981 set of the
CBS flick ``The Killing of Randy Webster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I blushed. I was totally strange. I was humiliated and
embarrassed, and I was sure he could tell I'd lost my cool,'' she
recalls. ``I figured he'd think I was Southern phony. Super polite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I ended up with the flu, and I was so sick I didn't care.
I started to relax, and he started to laugh at me.''
</P>
<P>
   And fall in love with her. The pair married three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Universal themes
</P>
<P>
   Whether she ran a fever because of Holbrook or the flu, she's
not sure. But tales like these, Carter says, unite everyone _
regardless of where you're from or what you do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't talk about show business in my act because that
experience is particular to me,'' she says, referring to her
cabaret show. ``I talk about love lost and love found. Innocence
lost and innocence reclaimed. Families. Childhood memories ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Has saucy Dixie Carter, aka Julia Sugarbaker, softened up a
smidgen?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been one to like aggressive tactics,'' she replies.
``The nice people of the world, those who were raised as I was, do
not get up and yell and scream. So yes, I speak my mind, but in a
gracious way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentility is a very good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   BOX
</P>
<P>
   From Carousel to cabaret ...
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Carter's career highlights include:
</P>
<P>
   1961: Made stage debut as Julie in ``Carousel'' at the Front
Street Theatre in Memphis
</P>
<P>
   1963: Made off-Broadway debut as Perdita in ``A Winter's Tale''
</P>
<P>
   (Left stage for eight years to marry and have kids)
</P>
<P>
   1974: Co-starred on Broadway in the musical ``Sextet''
</P>
<P>
   1974-76: First appeared on TV in the role of Brandy Henderson on
``The Edge of Night''
</P>
<P>
   1976: Appeared as Melba in N.Y. stage revival of ``Pal Joey''
</P>
<P>
   1976-79: Performed with the N.Y. Shakespeare Festival in ``Jesse
and the Bandit Queen,'' ``Fathers and Sons,'' ``Taken in Marriage''
and more
</P>
<P>
   1977-78: Played copywriter April Baxter on CBS comedy ``On Our
Own''
</P>
<P>
   1979: Portrayed Aunt Marion on ABC comedy ``Out of the Blue''
</P>
<P>
   1980: Played Hannah Mae Bindler in N.Y. stage production of ``A
Couple of White Chicks Sitting Around Talking''
</P>
<P>
   1981: Met third husband, Hal Holbrook, (they wed in '84) while
starring with him in CBS flick ``The Killing of Randy Webster''
</P>
<P>
   1982-83: Played Carlotta Beck on CBS' ``Filthy Rich''
</P>
<P>
   1983: Made London stage debut as Liz Conlon in ``Buried Inside
Extra''
</P>
<P>
   1983: Film debut in supporting role (as Angela) in comedy
``Going Berserk''
</P>
<P>
   1984-85: Played recurring role of Maggie McKinney, Mr.
Drummond's girlfriend, on NBC's ``Different Strokes''
</P>
<P>
   1986-93: Played interior decorator Julia Sugarbaker on CBS
comedy ``Designing Women;'' now syndicated on Lifetime network
</P>
<P>
   1989: Began annual nightclub engagements singing at the Cafe
Carlyle in New York
</P>
<P>
   1992: Released ``Dixie Carter's Unworkout'' exercise tape 1993 _
Performed at White House for President Clinton
</P>
<P>
   1994: Portrayed Lillie Langtry in ``The Gambler V: Playing For
Keeps,'' a CBS miniseries
</P>
<P>
   1994: Acted with Holbrook in NBC's ``A Perry Mason Mystery: The
Case of the Lethal Lifestyle''
</P>
<P>
   1997: Played opera diva Maria Callas in Broadway's ``Master
Class''
</P>
<P>
   1998-present: Performs cabaret show, ``An Evening with Dixie
Carter''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
