<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENSITIVITY-TRAINING2     01-28 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENSITIVITY-TRAINING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sensitivity alert: Classes dissect world of -isms
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Think you're pretty sensitive? Not if
you commit linguism. Yes, linguism, yet another new, politically
correct buzz phrase: It means prejudice or discrimination against
people who speak another language.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time you're staring (or glaring) at an
uncomprehending store clerk from Pakistan or a cabdriver from Iran.
One false grunt, and you could be accused of being a . . .
linguist?
</P>
<P>
   It's not a capital offense, so far, but it's enough to set off
Ilene Allgood's diversity radar. ``People are pretty closed to
foreigners,'' she says. ``Even if they're trying to learn the
language, we're impatient with them.''
</P>
<P>
   You think Allgood should keep her lectures to herself?
</P>
<P>
   Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Allgood is the new assistant regional director of the
Anti-Defamation League. She's also in charge of education there.
One of her major goals is to bring the ADL's diversity programs to
more people in more places, particularly schools.
</P>
<P>
   So, there's a good chance that even if you don't hear from her,
your kids will. She'd rather talk to them anyway. ``Adults are used
to being comfortable,'' she says. ``Most kids are more receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   What they're receptive to are the lessons of ``diversity
education,'' the latest twist on what used to be called sensitivity
training. Maybe you call it something that can't be printed here.
</P>
<P>
   By whatever name, the idea is that most of us can learn to work
and even live harmoniously with people of different ethnic
backgrounds, colors, religions and sexual preferences with a little
reprogramming.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that sort of thing vanished with the '80s, but
it didn't. Increasingly complex laws and court rulings have kept
the heightened sensitivity business booming, and the ADL has been
at or near the fore.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to thousands of corporate employees, police officers
and bureaucrats, the ADL estimates nationally that it has trained
more than 110,000 teachers, who have passed along what they learned
to more than a million students. Their job is to spread the message
to others.
</P>
<P>
   And what is the message?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a right to your attitudes,'' Allgood says. ``The
problem is when you act. We don't tell you that you have to like
everyone. But you can't discriminate or break the law.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be a tad more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The ADL's World of Difference Institute hones its programs to
fit a variety of settings: a workplace of difference; a campus of
difference; a classroom of difference. (You get the idea: we're all
different!)
</P>
<P>
   Brochures for each are illustrated by PC-perfect pictures of
smiling participants.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unreal, until Allgood offers a real-life illustration
when she brings her training program to the Adult Education Center
in West Palm Beach. There, crowded into Room 403, is the new
portrait of America, spanning several continents and the entire
skin-tone palette.
</P>
<P>
   These approximately 30 students, ranging from late teens to
mid-60s, were chosen by their teachers because they appear to be
class leaders capable of replicating the exercises with other
students. Most are working toward high school equivalency diplomas.
They're from Peru, Haiti, Colombia, Korea, Finland, and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of white, native-born Americans are very much the
minority.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone appears to be as happy as the people in the brochures,
but it's a little hard to tell: Most don't speak much English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some were well-educated, professional people in their own
countries, but here, they're the ones who don't get the job or the
apartment,'' Allgood explains. ``This should help give them
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Allgood tackles the two-day seminar with help from two
experienced trainers, Morris McDaniel and Miriam Lorenzo. McDaniel
is certain this will be an easier audience than the cops he's used
to dealing with. (``There's a reason we don't let them bring their
guns into the room.'')
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel conducts a lesson in the vocabulary of prejudice by
asking the class to supply definitions.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotype? ``When you tell people you're from Colombia, they
think you smuggle drugs,'' says a Colombian student.
Discrimination? ``No one will deliver pizza to my house in Riviera
Beach,'' another offers.
</P>
<P>
   When he asks about racism, a Peruvian interrupts with a
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What race I am?''
</P>
<P>
   Others jump in, all wondering about this peculiar American
insistence on ethnic labeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me: `You're Hispanic, but are you white
Hispanic or black Hispanic?' '' says Yohanka Cabezas. ``Why do they
care? I tell them, `You're looking at me. You decide.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There's little lecturing, and white males sensitive to being
demonized would hear little to wince about.
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, the ``linguism'' matter.
</P>
<P>
   Allgood offers the term in response to a Haitian grocery cashier
who says she's often taunted by a co-worker because of her accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not have to accept a hostile work environment,''
McDaniel explains.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but the workshop also offers examples of why
multilingual endeavors lead to frustration.
</P>
<P>
   When Lorenzo leads an outdoor exercise that requires
participants to move from place to place depending on their
answers, she finds many simply follow others.
</P>
<P>
   And when she asks who would feel uncomfortable working with
people of another race, Peter Hiltunen, who arrived from Finland a
month before, steps out boldly. His movement is so sure, his answer
so much in the minority, that he is asked to tell the class more
about his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say,'' he answers. ``I don't speak well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lorenzo moves on, Hiltunen asks someone behind him to
repeat Lorenzo's original question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' he says. ``I thought she asked if you are
comfortable, not uncomfortable. I gave the wrong answer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cabezas, though, the class is an American marvel. It is not
only her first lesson about diversity, it is her first experience
with it. After leaving Cuba, her family moved to Idaho and has been
in Florida for just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cuba, I was with Cubans,'' she says. ``In Idaho, we were
the only Cubans. This is really the first time I met so many
different people from different places. I was afraid, but now I'm
not. I felt confident in this group.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what Allgood had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   How sensitive are you? Here are some terms the ADL uses in
diversity training, with abbreviated definitions:
</P>
<P>
   _ STEREOTYPE: A stereotype is a preconceived or oversimplified
generalization about an entire group of people without regard for
individual differences. Although not always negative, stereotypes
always have a negative impact and can feed into discrimination.
Even when stereotypes are positive, the impact of stereotyping is
negative.
</P>
<P>
   _ PREJUDICE: Prejudice is a negative or hostile attitude toward
a person or group formed without just or sufficient knowledge and
based on negative stereotypes. Prejudice is the result of
``prejudgment'' and can lead to discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   _ DISCRIMINATION: Discrimination is the restrictive treatment of
a person or group based on prejudiced assumptions of group
characteristics, rather than on individual judgment. It is the
denial of justice prompted by prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   _ RACISM: Racism is prejudice or discrimination based on the
belief that race is the primary factor determining human traits and
abilities. Racism holds that genetic or inherited differences
produce the inherent superiority or inferiority of one race to
another. Institutional racism is racial prejudice supported by
institutional power and authority used to the advantage of one race
over others.
</P>
<P>
   _ RELIGIOUS BIGOTRY: Religious bigotry is prejudice or
discrimination against one or all members of a particular religious
group based on negative perceptions of their religious beliefs and
practices or on negative stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANTI-SEMITISM: Anti-Semitism is prejudice or discrimination
against Jewish people, based on negative perceptions of their
religious beliefs and/or on negative group stereotypes.
Anti-Semitism can also be a form of racism, as when Nazis and
others consider Jews an inferior ``race.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SEXISM: Sexism is prejudice or discrimination based on gender.
Like the other isms, sexism can be both personal and institutional.
</P>
<P>
   _ HETEROSEXISM: Heterosexism is prejudice against people who are
gay, lesbian or bisexual. Homophobia (fear of such persons) can
lead to discrimination and violence against homosexuals or people
perceived to be gay, lesbian or bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
