<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIALITE-DIARY29-COX     01-28 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIALITE-DIARY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `This is sort of the art of being a woman'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lesley Friedman is a self-made woman.
She created a temporary-lawyer business in New York, sold it and
became a multimillionaire, then retired early and moved to Palm
Beach, Fla., four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then she took a look at herself.
</P>
<P>
   She never had the time before, she says. She and other women at
the law firm had purposely dressed conservatively, even matronly.
She got manicures when she remembered to, and she let her naturally
curly hair be. Makeup and styling really didn't make a difference,
she thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes on dates, I would wear my business suit,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She was too busy to bother. ``I had the attitude of, `This is
me, successful and smart. People are going to like me no matter how
I look.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She never married. When she retired, she realized that the
young, natural look starts to go in the mid-30s. And if she was
going to take the trouble to correct it, she figured, wouldn't it
be nice to have someone around to admire the work?
</P>
<P>
   So, a year and a half ago, she got started. She lost 25 pounds
on a variety of diets and hired a New York fashion consultant at
$100 an hour. She shipped her entire wardrobe by UPS to New York,
and the consultant threw almost everything out. Friedman, nervous,
learned to get used to low-cut necklines and tight pants. For the
first time in her life, she teetered on stiletto heels.
</P>
<P>
   As she changed she tackled dating, to a degree (73 blind dates
in one year) that the Wall Street Journal ran a front-page feature
story about her new ``job.'' She got hundreds of calls, some very
odd, but also a book deal. The topic: ``How I'm using my business
skills to find a mate.'' There's talk of a movie, and if that comes
about she wouldn't mind Meg Ryan in the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   She's finding, though, that her transformation is neither
complete nor permanent, and it certainly isn't cheap. It takes
hours of maintenance, and last week she was willing to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   With classical music playing softly and a vanilla aromatherapy
candle flickering, she lies back in a chair at Deborah Koepper's
Palm Beach salon and waits for her newest treatment, a light
electric current that is supposed to tone the facial muscles _ at
$75 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman is refreshingly open. The only thing she keeps quiet
about is where she gets waxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I didn't care about this s---,'' she says.
``But when things started happening to me, it got really
bothersome.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman lives alone in Palm Beach and travels often to New York
or California, where she grew up in a Los Angeles suburb and
skipped dating to study.
</P>
<P>
   When in town, she spends her days working out at Mar-a-Lago,
visiting the salon, dating, going to parties, working on her book
and wondering if she started all of this a little too late.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman won't quite reveal her age. ``That's like asking a man
about his net worth,'' she says. She only admits to 37 and told the
Wall Street Journal she only admits to 39.
</P>
<P>
   Size is easier. She is a 6 or 8 on top and a 8 to 10 on the
bottom, and she still wants to lose another 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   With the weight loss and the straightened and colored hair and
the dental work and the contact lenses, she looks nothing like her
driver's license photo anymore.
</P>
<P>
   She walks into the salon in slim black pants and a peach-colored
scarf around her neck one day, and the next she comes in wearing a
lime-colored tank minidress. ``I wouldn't have worn this dress
before,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her New York fashion consultant, Sheila Grant, remembers meeting
Friedman with her ``sacky'' dresses and her ``long, kind of bushy''
hair. ``She had no real sense of fashion or style, to be honest
about it,'' Grant says. ``As much as she was sort of reluctant, it
was a very exciting process.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant, a tall blonde who admits to having had a face lift at 47,
is used to seeing women like Friedman. ``Many, many women wake up
at age 40 and say, `My God, I don't have a life.' It's a panic
button. For Leslie, she had made all this money and was wonderful
and independent, but she wanted a personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   After dumping most of Friedman's clothes, Grant took her on a
three-day shopping spree for a 77-piece fall and winter wardrobe,
and even went with her to the hairdresser. In that first year,
Friedman spent into the six-figure range on clothes alone.
</P>
<P>
   Grant would dress her for her dates, and the two still talk
nearly every other day. Last week, Friedman needed to a buy a coat
for a romantic weekend in the Hamptons, and Grant described what
she needed over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Friedman thought the clothes were too young, too sexy.
``I want to be taken very seriously, for my brains,'' she says. But
she squeezed into the 3-inch stilettos and the strapless cocktail
dresses just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still fiddle,'' she says, ``but I try not to do it in
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Her seasonal wardrobes are bought to mix and match. For one
season, she says, they bought four pairs of tight pants, three
cashmere turtleneck sweaters and four blazers. The spring corner of
her walk-in closet is full of lime greens and peaches, which go
well with her skin tone, and the usual black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Grant taught her to wear long jackets (``You're hippy''), high
heels with pants and low-cut tops (``I have a good chest'').
Friedman used to buy what was trendy or cute. Now she gets what
flatters her body shape, and when it doesn't she has learned to use
a tailor.
</P>
<P>
   She shops at Luca Luca, Escada, Celine, and Armani, but she can
walk just as easily into Ann Taylor, Banana Republic and the Gap.
``You can find a copy of an Armani at Ann Taylor,'' Friedman says.
And she goes to Nine West for ``great knockoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   About accessories, she knew zip. ``I didn't understand you don't
take a purse like this out at night,'' she says, pointing to her
beige Charles Jourdan bag. She went to Books-A-Million and bought a
book on how to tie a scarf, and packs about 15 scarves when she
travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how the French women do it,'' she says, as she gets a
pedicure. ``They spend a fortune on accessories, and clothes-wise
they have just a few pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   She switches chairs, tissue paper stuffed between her toes, to
get her blow dry and manicure done simultaneously. At 11 a.m., two
hours after walking into the salon, the blow dry is over and the
base coat is on. ``I'm going to be here three hours today,'' she
says, marveling at the time. ``It's ridiculous. But I'm not gonna
cut back.''
</P>
<P>
   She grabs a phone. Usually she checks her messages, or chats, or
plans what clothes she will pack for an upcoming trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is flying to New York for a date? Wow, it must be
nice!'' Deborah Koepper says to Friedman, preparing her for makeup.
</P>
<P>
   She dabs on concealer _ ``She had the facial yesterday, so her
face is nice and plump and moisturized'' _ and peach-colored blush,
to show off Friedman's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   All Friedman will have to do the rest of the day, Koepper says,
is touch up her Glossy Maple lipstick (Koepper's own brand). And
she's right _ lipstick is usually the only makeup Friedman carries
in her purse.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items for her weekend getaway are already laid out
on the table in her living room. Among the jewelry is a copy of
``Chic Simple's What Should I Wear?'' She's more confident in her
judgment now, but a little help is nice.
</P>
<P>
   She is, of course, not finished with her changes. ``She's not
willing to accept any imperfections now,'' Grant says. They consult
about getting her ``undereyes'' done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel like this is my creative expression,'' Friedman
explains. ``Before, I was doing nothing, just being casual. But
this is sort of the art of being a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The facial
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $135 per session
</P>
<P>
   How often: Every two weeks
</P>
<P>
   (Another $75 buys a 15-minute session using electrical current
to tone up the face muscles)
</P>
<P>
   The pedicure
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $38 per session
</P>
<P>
   How often: Every two weeks
</P>
<P>
   (Toe polish color is Fine Red Wine)
</P>
<P>
   The manicure
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $18 per session
</P>
<P>
   How often: Every week
</P>
<P>
   (Nail color is Bashful Beige)
</P>
<P>
   The blow-dry
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $40-$45 per session
</P>
<P>
   How often: Twice a week
</P>
<P>
   (If she's careful, a blow dry can last a week)
</P>
<P>
   The makeup
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $50 per session
</P>
<P>
   How often: About twice a week
</P>
<P>
   (The finishing touch is the lip lacquer, to make her lips look
wet. ``Men don't like to kiss it, though, because it gets on
them,'' she says)
</P>
<P>
   The closet
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $100-an-hour fashion consultations; for clothes, budget is
not an issue
</P>
<P>
   How often: Spring, summer, fall and winter
</P>
<P>
   (When she started, Friedman shipped her entire wardrobe by UPS
to her fashion consultant in New York for a critique _ and almost
everything was thrown out)
</P>
<P>
   The workout
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $75,000-a-year membership
</P>
<P>
   How often: An hour, four or five times a week
</P>
<P>
   (40 minutes of bike or treadmill, 20 minutes of Nautilus or free
weights)
</P>
<P>
   The hair straightening
</P>
<P>
   Cost:
</P>
<P>
   How often: Every three or four months
</P>
<P>
   (Two weeks later, she gets her naturally brown hair colored)
</P>
<P>
   The waxing
</P>
<P>
   Cost: Unknown
</P>
<P>
   How often: Once a week
</P>
<P>
   (``Just say it's mysterious'')
</P>
<P>
   The rules
</P>
<P>
   _ Three weeks ago, she stopped drinking coffee
</P>
<P>
   _ She drinks three liters of water a day
</P>
<P>
   _ She is on a high-protein, low-carbohydrate diet _ three eggs
and toast for breakfast, meat and salads for lunch and dinner
</P>
<P>
   _ She snacks on fruit or sliced turkey
</P>
<P>
   _ She counts every calorie
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disciplined _ I have to be. It's the only way to keep
the weight off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
