<P>
   SOCIALITE-DIARY _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The diary of a socialite:
Reporter Cara Anna follows Palm Beach socialite Lesley Friedman as
she endures the the time-consuming process of being well
maintained. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). 30. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SENSITIVITY-TRAINING _ Think you're pretty sensitive? Not if you
commit linguism. Yes, linguism, yet another new, politically
correct buzz phrase: It means prejudice or discrimination against
people who speak another language. Remember that the next time
you're staring (or glaring) at an uncomprehending store clerk from
Pakistan or a cabdriver from Iran. One false grunt, and you could
be accused of being a ... linguist? It's not a capital offense, so
far, but it's enough to set off Ilene Allgood's diversity radar.
``People are pretty closed to foreigners,'' she says. ``Even if
they're trying to learn the language, we're impatient with them.''
You think Allgood should keep her lectures to herself? Not likely.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). 35. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DIXIE-CARTER _ `I've always been nice, but kind of bossy.' Dixie
Carter comes to Kravis Center in West Palm Beach with sultry tunes,
Southern tales and just a tad of attitude. Reporter Loretta
Grantham asks her what she misses about the South. (Grantham, Palm
Beach Post). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-BELLAGIO _ LAS VEGAS _ Every major hotel in Las Vegas has
a theme, whether it's Hollywood glitz at the MGM Grand or ancient
Egypt at the Luxor. At the Bellagio _ a 3,005-room
hotel/casino/entertainment complex that is Las Vegas' grandest
project to date _ the theme may be best described as ``high
class.'' Developer Steven Wynn clearly intends to outclass his
neighbors with such offerings as an art gallery filled with the
works of European masters, a permanent multimillion theater built
for Cirque de Soleil's underwater production ``O,'' and the most
dazzling line-up of restaurants this desert city has seen.
Near-replicas of the finest eateries of New York (Le Cirque and
Osteria del Circo), San Francisco (Aqua) and Boston (Olives) are
just the beginning. The jewel in the crown is Picasso, where $37
million of the Spanish's master's work hangs on the walls and San
Francisco's most celebrated chef cooks full time. You can spend a
glorious few days at Bellagio _ dining, gaming, viewing art _
without once stepping outdoors. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-BELLAGIO-EAT _ LAS VEGAS _ An in-depth look at the
restaurants of Bellagio, with capsule reviews of several different
options. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY, JAN. 31
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-BELLAGIO-GAMING _ LAS VEGAS _ When Bellagio was under
construction, word went around Las Vegas that this upper-end casino
would have $1 minimum slots and $10 minimum gaming tables. But the
truth is it has just as many nickel slots and dollar roulette
wheels as any casino in town. We'll take a look at the chioces for
gaming in Bellagio. And has it been a while since you last dropped
a quarter in a slot machine? Then you may be surprised by the
bells, whistles and high-tech video screens of today's slots.
(Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN.
31
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-OTHERHOTELS _ LAS VEGAS _ A listing of the major
construction projects recently completed and under way in Las
Vegas, with room numbers and convention capacity. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES _ Going Places (travel notes) column. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
