<P>
   MOVIES-CRAZY _ Review of ``Still Crazy.'' Twenty years after
their highly publicized breakup, a rock band is persuaded to get
back together for a reunion concert. (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _BOOKS 0122 -- The well is dry, the brain
atrophied. Iris Murdoch, the last of the great 20th-century British
writers, has Alzheimer's. And yet, in ``Elegy for Iris,'' a
beautifully rendered portrait by her husband, John Bayley, we are
allowed to glimpse the private sanctuary of the artist's once vital
mind. We get to peer through the opaque windows of a marriage that
wouldn't seem nearly so remarkable had it not spawned such a
monumental body of work _ 26 novels that have the Protean grandeur,
the intellectual richness, the lyrical luster of Shakespeare or
Proust. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW _ In ``American Beach,'' author Russ Rymer is too intent
on academically documenting the disintegration of African American
businesses to let his characters take charge. (Crowell, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW _ ``Angels Flight'' may be author Michael Connelly's
darkest novel yet. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE ON BOOKS _ The biographer, like any artist, must possess
the intuition and moral imagination to breathe life into his
subject. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
