<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _BOOKS 0122 -- The well is dry, the brain
atrophied. Iris Murdoch, the last of the great 20th-century British
writers, has Alzheimer's. And yet, in ``Elegy for Iris,'' a
beautifully rendered portrait by her husband, John Bayley, we are
allowed to glimpse the private sanctuary of the artist's once vital
mind. We get to peer through the opaque windows of a marriage that
wouldn't seem nearly so remarkable had it not spawned such a
monumental body of work _ 26 novels that have the Protean grandeur,
the intellectual richness, the lyrical luster of Shakespeare or
Proust. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
