<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEBUT-NOVEL29-COX     01-28 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBUT-NOVEL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book divulges scares of polio with accuracy while enteraining
audience
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like others who grew up in the 1950s, Decatur writer
Pat Cunningham Devoto remembers the Eisenhower years as a time of
innocence, when a gallon of gasoline cost 25 cents, every family
resembled television's Cleavers and role models never went into
drug rehab.
</P>
<P>
   The former history teacher at College Park High School also
remembers how much fear and prejudice bubbled beneath that veneer
of normalcy. AIDS was unknown then, but in the years before Jonas
Salk's vaccine, polio was a mysterious disease that struck terror
in the hearts of families every summer.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of fear, mingled with the magical innocence of a
1950s childhood, is the theme of Devoto's debut novel, ``My Last
Days as Roy Rogers'' (Warner, $20).
</P>
<P>
   Set in Alabama in 1954 _ the last ``polio summer'' _ the novel
chronicles the coming of age of Tab Rutland, a headstrong
10-year-old white girl who chooses the celluloid cowboy as her
ideal. With her black playmate, Maudie May, Tab uncovers a scandal
involving stolen money intended for polio victims and exposes a
racial injustice as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-publication review, Booklist magazine describes Devoto
as ``writing as if she were the literary love child of Harper Lee
and Mark Twain.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the book grew out of a long-ago conversation Devoto
had with her mother about the AIDS crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my mother what, if anything, in our lifetime had been
comparable to the fear of AIDS,'' Devoto recalls. ``She immediately
said, `The polio summers in the late '40s and early '50.'''
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Devoto went to the library the next day to research
the period. And, although she had never written more than a couple
of short stories, she began taking notes for a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing started right after I divorced about nine years
ago,'' says Devoto, 59. ``The more I read about polio, the more I
found that my mother had not been exaggerating. During a polio
summer, the movies might close, the pools always closed, and rumors
ran rampant. If someone came down with polio, parents wanted to
know what had they eaten the night before and who had they been
playing with? People lived in dread every summer that there was an
outbreak in their town.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman told her about being raised in Oklahoma, where her
father was a doctor. ``She said she would never forget the night
her father came home and had her mother burn all the clothes he had
on because one of his patients had died of polio that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Other families would use antiseptic throat spray and wear
surgical masks whenever they drove through a town where there had
been a polio outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Devoto's sister, Joanne Walker, 63, recalls how scared she and
her friends would get if they got a sore throat, since the early
symptoms of polio resembled those of a cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towns used to spray DDT to try to control the outbreaks,''
says Walker, a free-lance writer who lives near Auburn, Ala. ``We
had no idea DDT was harmful. All we knew was that it was yellow
dust, and we were warned that it might stain our clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker says her sister asked her what she remembered about those
summers, but she had no idea Devoto was writing a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she asked me to read it, I said to myself, `Oh, Lord, I
don't want to do this.' She had never shown an interest in writing
and I expected the worse. I was reading Lee Smith and a lot of
Southern writers at the time, but I put their books aside and read
Pat's. I was amazed. I told her, `This is it,' but since I was her
sister, she took my opinion with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   Devoto sold the manuscript to a small press in Alabama, but
financial problems forced them to reconsider. Then, last May, she
got a call from her agent telling her that Warner had bought the
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was thrilling,'' Devoto says, ``but I had no idea how much
more work there was to be done. I had written it in first person,
present tense, and they wanted me to do it in past tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Now on the road to promote the book, Devoto says she has been
surprised by the strong reaction to the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has memories about those summers,'' she says. ``The
stories aren't so much about polio as they are about the fear that
the disease caused. But then, that's really one of the main themes
of the book, how fear convolutes our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
