<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORD BLOOD COULD SAVE LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Feb. 4)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my daughter was born a few years ago, I had heard about a
new procedure that involved donating umbilical cord blood to help
cancer victims.
</P>
<P>
   Try as I might, I couldn't get any of my doctors interested in
it. I mentioned it to my ob/gyn, my pediatrician, and finally, the
hospital nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anybody collect umbilical cord blood around here?'' I
finally said during labor, as a last-ditch attempt. ``They can have
ours if they need it.'' Everyone looked at me with amusement, as if
women in labor were always blurting out odd questions like that.
</P>
<P>
   So, I figured the procedure was either too expensive, or there
were enough women having babies around that when and if these stem
cells are needed, doctors just pop into a delivery ward and talk
someone into making a spontaneous donation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than two years down the road, my daughter's only trace
of an umbilical cord is a very cute belly button that she likes to
have tickled while hanging upside down.
</P>
<P>
   But the procedure is getting a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few headlines I've clipped over the past month: ``Study:
Umbilical cord blood can save cancer victims.'' ``A Birthday Gift:
a new medial technology _ the use of umbilical cord blood,'' and
``Umbilical Cord is Link to Survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but several of the articles suggest banking your
own baby's blood, in case he or she needs it later.
</P>
<P>
   So, I started researching it, just so I could feel REALLY bad
about not banking Adam or Sarah's baby blood.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what I found.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of parents are doing this. In fact, it's becoming
positively trendy. Private banks are springing up all over,
charging $1,200 to $1,500 and then another $100 or so a year as a
storage fee. The families are looking up the frozen blood as
``biological insurance policies,'' in case siblings or other family
members need it for bone-marrow transplants to fight leukemia or
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Some states have public banks that will store donated umbilical
cord blood, which will be available to anyone in the world who
needs it.
</P>
<P>
   The first cord blood transplant was successfully performed in
Paris in 1988. Since then, more than 1,500 umbilical cord stem cell
transplants have taken place, according to the National Institutes
of Health. Cord blood is high in stem cells, the building blocks of
the blood and immune system. The blood is retrieved by inserting a
needle into the vein of the cord after delivery, and drawing out
about 2 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   So why doesn't everyone do it?
</P>
<P>
   Well, like most things that go with parenting, it isn't that
clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in cord-blood transplants say most parents shouldn't
spend the money to store their newborn's cord blood.
</P>
<P>
   The blood would be a last option for the child, should he or she
get sick later, because the relapse rate is much higher when a
person's own stem cells are used in transplants.
</P>
<P>
   And the chances that the blood will ever be needed by someone in
your own family are 1 in 10,000, says Dr. Paul Root Wolpe, or the
Center for Bioethics at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of money to be made in autologous blood storage
and quite a lot of overselling is occurring,'' said Wolpe, who
co-authored the article, ``Ethical Issues in Umbilical Cord Blood
Banking'' in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception, he says, would be families who already have
a child with leukemia or some other disease that may eventually
require a transplant. Siblings have a one in four chance of
matching their brother or sister's cord blood. For families with
ill siblings, most public banks will collect, process and store the
cord blood for free.
</P>
<P>
   Also, families who donate umbilical cord blood to public banks _
at no charge to the donor _ could use the blood later as needed _
as long as the cord blood wasn't matched to another family first.
</P>
<P>
   For information on family banking of cord blood with the Cord
Blood Registry, or for an application to donate to the Cord Blood
Donor Foundation (dedicated to banking a mixed ethnicity bank of
cord blood stem cells) call 888-CORDBLOOD, or find information on
the Web at www.cordblood.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
