<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLASS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Professor Martin Edelman welcomes
more than 100 students to ``Sex, Lies and Impeachment,'' a course
where the hallowed edicts of the Constitution mingle freely with
the murky realities of politics. The State University of New York
at Albany class examines current events, even the salacious ones,
as they're unfolding. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FAILING-STUDENTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ It sounds simple enough: If
you fail in school, you don't promote. But when President Clinton
raised the idea of a national policy to end so-called ``social
promotion,'' educators say he oversimplified an issue far more
complex than the either-or proposition of promoting or holding back
students. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   SF-LOBBYISTS (San Francisco) _ The lobbying business has
exploded under Mayor Willie Brown as corporate and other interests
doubled their spending _ to more than $3.3 million a year _ on
hired guns at City Hall, records show. The bulk of the money,
described alternately as a scourge on democracy or the welcome
by-product of robust times, has gone to a trio of lobbyists with
close ties to the local Democratic establishment. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-INTERVIEW-BALL (San Francisco) _ Promoting the paperback
edition of his book ``Slaves in the Family,'' a chronicle of his
family's legacy of slave ownership, Edward Ball says it's easier
this time around. ``The crowds are bigger,'' he says, ``and the
emotions are more developed, not as raw.'' By BERNADETTE FAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-BOWL-ADS (Undated) _ Long after the game, the advertising
that airs during the Super Bowl will be remembered. Take Apple
Computer's ``1984'' ad, which presented an Orwellian vision of an
IBM-dominated world that not only predicted the personal computer
boom, but also set the Super Bowl as the ultimate advertising
stage. By MARK McGUIRE. (For release Sunday, Jan. 31.)
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-BOWL-FOOD (Undated) _ The first commandment for hosting a
Super Bowl party is one worth memorizing: Keep it simple. Sunday is
not an occasion for spending hours in the kitchen putting together
tasty dishes that will wow your friends. It's a day for simple fare
_ like chip dip. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CRIME (San Francisco) _ To help the old-school
detectives on the critically acclaimed ``Homicide: Life on the
Street'' navigate through the intricacies of an on-line crime
investigation, ``Homicide'' writers turned to Alex Wellen and Luke
Reiter, two young lawyers who host the ``CyberCrime TV'' broadcast
and Web site in San Francisco. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROFILE-LYN (San Francisco) _ Good news for teenage girls
throughout the land! Actress Jodi Lyn O'Keefe, she of the perfect
hair, teeth and bod _ not to mention a face like Venus _ is a
klutz. By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STUGGLING-BOOKSHOP (Berkeley, Calif.) _ With its business
suffering under pressure from corporate-owned and on-line
booksellers, owners of the independent Gaia Bookstore have asked
its employees and customers to rescue the store from imminent
closure by investing $25 to $250 _ essentially becoming part owners
of what will become a nonprofit cultural institution. By VICTORIA
COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAVEUR-COOKS (Undated) _ Heaven on a bun is a bacon
cheeseburger. The way Saveur magazine editor Colman Andrews sees
it, the bacon cheeseburger is among the highest culinary
achievements of modern man. To illustrate how food permeates
people's lives, Andrews and his Saveur colleagues have crafted
``Saveur Cooks Authentic American'' (Chronicle Books, $40). By DAI
HUYNH.
</P>
<P>
   W/ SAVEUR-COOKS-RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-ANDERSON (Miami) _ Jamal Anderson of the Atlanta
Falcons is basking in the warmth and shine of joining the Denver
Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII. Two seasons ago, his first as a
starter in the National Football League, the Falcons went 3-13. ``I
enjoy the situation we're in right now,'' Anderson says. ``There
are no bad days for Jamal Anderson.'' By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-BUCHANAN (Miami) _ Ray Buchanan arrived at just the
right time, etching himself between the this-coach-hates-that-coach
angle and the actual kickoff of Super Bowl XXXIII. He's a shot of
inspiration, a compelling character in a week when just about
anything is considered interesting. He's fresh, and that counts for
plenty because the Super Bowl gets stale long before it ever
begins.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RANKINGS (San Francisco) _ David Duval's 59 made history
Sunday at the Bob Hope, and now it may even change history. It's
that 59, combined with the number ``2'', that has PGA Tour players
and fans conspiring to overthrow the World Golf Rankings, which
have Tiger Woods in the top spot this week and Duval at No. 2,
11.58 points to 11.38. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   HKO-HOCKEY-SLUMP (Philadelphia) _ Four years ago, hockey was
labled as the sport of the '90s and beyond. Yet television ratings
of hockey have fallen and a recent survey shows that golf may
overtake the puck as the nation's No. 4 sport. Until hockey is
accepted into the mainstream, it will be a hard climb. By PETE
DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ You want to exorcise someone? Try
Kenneth Starr. Starr isn't evil on a grand scale, unless you're
looking at him from the president's perspective. But he's foremost
among those I'd try to exorcise, just to see what fly-sized angels
of darkness flutter out. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For years now, pro-choice
advocates have tried to drive home a truth about the violence that
is inflicted on abortion providers and their clinics. Last week,
Hillary Rodham Clinton called it was it is _ terrorism. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
