<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Basra missile error exposes our imperfection
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 31, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep wondering about the AGM-130. That's the missile that went
astray last week and into a residential neighborhood in Basra,
Iraq, reportedly killing 11 civilians and giving Saddam Hussein a
soapbox for his rantings.
</P>
<P>
   That the Pentagon admits we may have made a mistake means that
we did make a mistake. A mea culpa does not bring back the dead,
heal the wounded or silence Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   My knowledge of missiles is limited to those I was involved with
on firing ranges in the New Mexico desert during and just after the
Korean War, where I was a radar operator. Nothing about the
missiles was accurate in those days and, apparently, they aren't
today, either.
</P>
<P>
   It was my later understanding that we had become so
sophisticated with our missile technology that we could thread a
needle on Mars with one of them.
</P>
<P>
   As we found out during Desert Storm and, more recently, Desert
Fox, we haven't totally mastered the field of ``pinpoint
accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the AGM-130, that rocket-propelled bomb that was
launched from an F-15 fighter. As soon as I heard of our possible
``error,'' I wanted to know if we could get our money back from the
Boeing Company, which manufactures them in Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we paid good money for those suckers _ and they ought
to work.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to hit something else, something without women
and children in it. Apparently, it went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release by Boeing as recently as Jan. 20 _ Basra was
hit Jan. 25 _ the manufacturer described the AGM-130 Standoff
Weapon System as a ``guidance, control and propulsion kit that
makes a 2,000 pound bomb `smart.' The weapon, operated by the U.S.
Air Force, uses a television or infrared seeker to enable an
aircraft's Weapon System Operator to guide the bomb to a specific
target aimpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   In reading other information gleaned from the Web, it became
quite apparent that the crew of the F-15 takes control of the
weapon, watches its course on TV and steers it to its target.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 30, 1997, Boeing news release reporting on the test of
an AGM-130 near Eglin AFB in Florida, the company said that as soon
as the weapon entered ``the terminal phase of its flight ... the
weapon system officer took control of the missile ... and manually
guided the weapon to impact on the target.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear then that while the missile might be
sophisticated, eventually a human gets his or her hands on it. And
it is that human who either can or cannot hit the side of a barn,
or in this case, perhaps did hit the side of the barn _ while
trying to go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It is an error and we are going to catch heat for it, from our
allies and, certainly, from our detractors and enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, we have been treated by high-ranking military
officers holding premature news conferences to tell us how we hit
all of our targets, only to find it had not been the case. I am not
astonished that we cannot thread a needle on Mars; I am astonished
that we have supposedly responsible people telling us that we are
doing just that but not using missiles in sensitive areas that
override potential human error.
</P>
<P>
   Put this in your memory bank: According to Boeing in June 1997,
the company has built or is on contract for more than 675 AGM-130
missiles for the U.S. Air Force inventory. I don't know how many
already have been expended over Iraq but I've got a problem with a
system, despite all its sophistication, that still relies on the
human element to guide it to a supposed pinpointed site.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
