<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELLING-BODY-PARTS-NY     01-28 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELLING-BODY-PARTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BODY BAZAAR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing a female with her body parts labeled --
the positions of her internal organs outlined in black marker on
her skin -- is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this
article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery, using
your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that you
want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By KAREN WRIGHT  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   There's a bank in central Boston that offers its customers a
unique investment opportunity. For an initial outlay of $2,500 and
yearly fees of $95, investors can realize returns of incalculable
value _ or, more often, no returns at all.
</P>
<P>
   The institution in question is Viacord, the nation's largest
commercial banker of blood from fetal umbilical cords. In recent
years cord blood has become something of a hot commodity, as
medical research has demonstrated its potential for treating
leukemia and certain immune disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Private bankers like Viacord can guarantee expectant parents
future access to their own baby's blood, thereby increasing the
likelihood of a match should the child or a relative someday need
to restore a crippled immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Viacord's 1,400-plus samples of frozen cord blood could
represent roughly $3.5 million in revenue for the company. But no
one knows what cord blood will be worth to the families who have
paid to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in medical technology have created a marketplace for
everything from organs and tissues to genes and sex cells. Prices
vary: $300 for a pint of plasma, $50 for a sample of sperm, $10,000
for a nine-month lease on a surrogate mother's womb.
</P>
<P>
   Blood was the first commodity on the market, and it is still the
most commonly sold body product. Paid blood donors typically earn
from $50 to $500 per pint; those with rare blood types or
components may get more.
</P>
<P>
   The League of Red Cross Societies and other international
organizations have expressed concern that the financial incentives
offered by the blood trade constitute a subtle form of coercion for
impoverished or otherwise disadvantaged groups.
</P>
<P>
   But concerns about donor exploitation have not succeeded in
halting blood buying and selling. Part of the reason may be that,
in legal terms as well as popular perception, blood is more a body
``product'' than a body ``part.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Organ Transplant Act (NOTA), which in 1984
banned interstate commerce in organs for transplant, specifically
excluded ``replenishable tissues such as blood or sperm'' from its
prohibitions.
</P>
<P>
   NOTA was passed in response to the transplant successes of the
late 1970s. Before the transplant act, there were cases of would-be
donors advertising for potential buyers, and of organ brokers
offering to match the two in exchange for a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   While NOTA has shut down organ brokers here, however,
unregulated _ and poorly documented _ markets for organs are
believed to flourish elsewhere, mostly in India and Brazil. And
while the act prohibits traffic in organs for transplantation, it
allows such commerce if the body parts in question are to be used
in research or product development and testing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 businessman John Moore sued his doctor, the University
of California and several pharmaceutical companies for using,
without his consent, tissue from his cancerous spleen to create a
commercial cell line now valued by some at $3 billion in potential
profits. Moore lost.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 the California Supreme Court ruled that patients do not
have property rights to their tissues, since granting such rights
would ``destroy the economic incentive to conduct important medical
research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next of kin have a lot more authority over your dead body
than you have over your live body,'' says George Annas, professor
of health law at the Boston University School of Public Health.
There are laws protecting the inviolability of cadavers but almost
none to protect what happens to tissues and organs removed from a
patient who's still alive.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most complicated issues in body-shop policy is the
traffic in fetal parts, which are gleaned almost exclusively from
fetuses that have been electively aborted. (Miscarried or stillborn
fetuses tend to have defects and are harder to harvest).
</P>
<P>
   Fetal tissue has been a prized medical resource ever since
research demonstrated its potential for treating Parkinson's
disease, diabetes and Alzheimer's, as well as spinal-cord injuries
and hemophilia. Combined markets for cures of these diseases have
been estimated at more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But when a company began in the mid-1980s to develop a treatment
involving transplanted fetal cells, right-to-life protests erupted,
and in 1988 Congress passed the only amendment to NOTA, extending
the act's restrictions to include fetal organs and tissues. Of
course, fetal body parts are still being collected for use in
research.
</P>
<P>
   Another segment of the body-parts market prices the goods and
services for assisted reproduction. At present, money can buy sperm
($50 to $100), eggs (starting at $2,000), embryos (market value
varies), and a place to put them (gestational surrogates start at
$10,000, not including brokers' fees).
</P>
<P>
   The story of cord-blood banking may present an object lesson in
commercialization, though the moral of the story is not quite
clear.
</P>
<P>
   At least one expert has predicted that the average person's
chance of ever needing to use the blood banked is 1 in 200,000.
Nevertheless, the idea of cord-blood banking seems to be taking
off. More than a dozen companies, in addition to Viacord, now offer
banking services.
</P>
<P>
   And people are buying. At first, Viacord's customers were mostly
families who had a present or foreseeable need for stem-cell
transplants. Now more than half of Viacord's families have no
apparent need for the blood at all.
</P>
<P>
   Champions of cord-blood banking maintain that they have turned a
medical waste product into a valuable resource. But critics of the
trafficking in human anatomy claim that no matter how many lives
are saved (or created), any such commerce inevitably violates the
sanctity of the human body.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, animals engineered with human genes and
tissues have already been patented. The Thirteenth Amendment to the
Constitution, which outlawed slavery, would seem to prohibit the
patenting of a human being.
</P>
<P>
   But when does a human part, or a part-human, become a
full-fledged person? The ever-expanding scope of biomedical
commerce is forcing answers to such improbable questions. As the
market races forward, issues that were once the province of the
very ill or the very thoughtful may soon become every body's
business.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Karen Wright is a free-lance writer and editor.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
 &UR; (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
