<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-SIXTIES-ART-NYTS     01-28 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-SIXTIES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIXTIES ARE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slide and black and white photo of actress Julia Stiles in a
scene from the NBC miniseries ``The Sixties.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The '60s are back.
 &HT;    But you can relax. It's only on TV.
 &HT;    It was probably inevitable: The baby boom generation are now
running the country. They're also producing its movies and
television, and the '60s for them was the best of times.
 &HT;    Says Lynda Obst, producer of ``The Sixties,'' the four-hour
miniseries airing Feb. 7 and 8 on NBC: ``The music that gave tempo
to that (decade), the community that was forged at that time, the
values that were stirred up at that time still live with us, and
inside of all of us.''
 &HT;    She's not alone. Two other '60s projects are already established
in the TV season or coming up.
 &HT;    On Lifetime the much praised ``Any Day Now'' goes into its
second season with Annie Potts and Lorraine Toussaint as childhood
friends from the segregated South of the '60s reunited in a much
different America of the '90s. Child actors Mae Middleton and Shari
Dyon Perry co-star as the childhood friends as the action veers
between the black-and-white past and the full color present.
 &HT;    On TNT, ``Passing Glory'' airs Feb. 21 starring Andre Braugher
as a Catholic priest in a Southern town trying to get his high
school basketball team a game against the town's all-white
champions.
 &HT;    Also taking up the issue of race, Obst follows two American
families, one black and one white, through the travails of the
Vietnam War the civil rights movement, and brings them out more or
less intact on the other side.
 &HT;    ``I loved making this miniseries more than I've loved doing
almost anything in my entire career, '' she confesses. ``I was
going to say, in my entire life, but I think living the '60s was
more fun than actually making them again.''
 &HT;    At the Paramount Ranch in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, she
re-created the pivotal moment of her favorite decade when she
presided over the new Woodstock. Obst attended the real thing back
in 1969 _ ``I remember driving my car in reverse for about 12 miles
to get out of the mud'' _ so she insisted that every detail be true
to life.
 &HT;    As an army of studio workers unleashed a rain storm, some 300
extras milled around with long bleached hair, tie dyed shirts,
headbands, bodies draped in U.S. flags _ and that was just the men!
 &HT;    The women with flowers in their hair were in ankle-length
dresses and bell bottoms. Psychedelically painted buses stood
nearby, the ``bummer tent'' lay open for kids having bad trips, and
incense burned throughout. The odor of pot was missing, of course,
to keep everything legal.
 &HT;    Defying the adage about the '60s _ ``If you can remember it, you
weren't there'' _ Obst can recall those years in obsessive detail.
 &HT;    ``In many ways I've wanted to find a way to tackle the '60s for
all of my career,'' she says. ``I did a book on it (`The Rolling
Stone History of the Sixties') but TV is the right medium because
we received the '60s through television, from the Kennedy-Nixon
debates, where we got to see what beauty and charisma meant on
television....to the pictures from Vietnam, and the kids we saw
getting beaten up by cops on TV. ''
 &HT;    Obst's working class white family, the Herlihys, lose their
daughter when she gets pregnant by a rock musician and ends up in a
commune in Haight Ashbury. One son goes off to Vietnam. The other
becomes a peace activist.
 &HT;    The other family is no less split. Rev. Willie Taylor is burned
out of his home in Greenwood, Miss. and moves to California where
his son is recruited by the Black Panthers. The son becomes a
bodyguard and narrowly avoids being killed at the 1968 Democratic
Convention in Chicago.
 &HT;    Real-life Black Panther David Hilliard was an adviser to the
production and the cast includes a mixture of new and familiar
faces: Charles Dutton, Cliff Gorman, (as Father Daniel Berrigan)
Julia Stiles and David Alan Grier.
 &HT;    While Obst says she tried not to romanticize the decade, she
insists there is an enduring positive legacy from the controversial
decade.
 &HT;    ``I think there's great beauty in trying to re-imagine what it
felt like to be engaged in the world without apathy, and I want
more than anything for this series to be an invitation from my
generation to my son's generation.... to see what it's like to be
involved in speaking up, and finding out that your voice does make
a difference.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or
by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL;
</P>
