   Cuba still has more doctors per capita -- one for every 185
citizens -- than any country in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba even exports some of its doctors, with 1,000 physicians now
working abroad, including more than 400 in South Africa's grossly
under-serviced rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most importantly for Cuba's esteem is that the state-run
biotechnology industry is still breaking new ground. Recently,
Cuban scientists expressed hope that this will find vaccines for
AIDS and some types of cancer within the next seven years or so.
Health Minister Carlos Dotres has been even more optimistic, saying
in December that an AIDS vaccine would be ready within two or three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biotechnology industry is still a very gung-ho industry,
and Cuba seems to have an army of engineers and scientists at work
in this area,'' said Florentino Chacon Puig, who works here for the
United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   He said scientists already have developed a vaccine for
meningitis C, one of the last childhood killers, and are working on
a vaccine to fight cholera.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, despite Cuba's shortages, doctors at the Ameijeiras
Brothers Hospital have performed 94 heart transplants over the last
10 years, as well as cornea, kidney, and bone marrow transplants,
advanced procedures unavailable in many other developing countries.
In the hospital's basement, doctors use four hyperbaric chambers --
that are worth $45,000 a piece -- to treat patients with all sorts
of common and acute conditions using concentrated levels of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every hospital room is equipped with a television and
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital still needs sutures, anesthetics, and drugs
such as the cancer-fighting Tamoxifin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get Tamoxifin from China, so you can imagine how
expensive it is,'' said pharmacist Robin Garcia, referring to high
transportation costs.
</P>
<P>
   The dire need for foreign exchange in recent years has led many
of Cuba's better hospitals to market some of their beds to foreign
patients, who now pay $20 million a year in hard currency for
various treatments, according to Cuban government estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuban government officials say no more than 5 percent of
hospital beds is set aside for foreigners so that there's still
plenty of space for Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1,000-bed Ameijeiras Brothers Hospital, only 50 beds are
reserved for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money that's collected is devoted entirely to keeping the
rest of the health-care system alive,'' said government spokesman
Roberto de Armas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anti-Castro critics blast Cuban hospitals for treating
foreigners with ample supplies of food and medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that foreigners are treated with the best care and
the best drugs when the average Cuban must suffer from extreme
shortages?'' asked an angry Frank Calzon, director of the
non-profit Center for a Free Cuba in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But Armas said hospitals must provide foreigners with good care
because their money is the glue that holds the entire health-care
system together.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our hospitals, the material conditions have deteriorated --
the beds are old and the paint is peeling,'' he said. ``But every
bed and every hospital is still open and the equipment still works,
and that's saying something.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
