<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY TIME I QUIT SMOKING, MEAN LITTLE JUNKIE BUTTS IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here she comes, I thought to myself yesterday as I
stood in line at Walgreen's.
</P>
<P>
   She started off slowly, sliding in a slight, almost unnoticeable
slither up my spine. She began calling me, louder and louder until
it was impossible to ignore her. I felt the touch of anxiety that
she shot my way, and then it hit me like a 50-foot wave.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, I was under, swimming in a craving that had
seeped into every cell of my body, clawing at me from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   I could only think about one thing: I WANT A CIGARETTE.
</P>
<P>
   NOW.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 10 days since I've had a cigarette, 10 days since I've
sucked that smoke into my lungs and held it there until the mean
little junkie in me was satisfied. Ten days, going colder than the
turkey my mother got on sale in November and put to sleep in the
deep freeze inside her garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``NOW!'' the mean little junkie screamed.
</P>
<P>
   This was not good. I was standing behind a woman so old that I
was sure she had dated Moses. After she had hoisted $15 worth of
laxatives and hard candy onto the counter, the mean little junkie
trembled with hate when I realized the old woman was paying for her
stuff in nothing but quarters. Bumping around in my hands was a box
of Nicorette gum that I just wanted to pay for, rip open and shove
so much of it into my mouth that it looked like I was sucking on a
softball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four twenty-five, four fifty, four seventy-five,'' I heard the
cashier count as he dragged each coin across the counter.
</P>
<P>
   That was when I completely lost control. I couldn't help it when
a tear slipped out the corner of my right eye and I began to cry. I
was still crying when the cashier swiped the box of Nicorette over
the scanner and told me that it cost $32 for (begin ital) gum. (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   Like almost every smoker, I've quit before, and battled the mean
little junkie head-on as she hissed, spit and snarled through the
first two weeks of withdrawal. Wound up in a tight ball of hate,
anger and irritation, I purged her in the hardest fight of my life
several years ago, when a portion of a puffy Cheeto got lodged in
my throat but I thought it was cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, our house was robbed, and before I had finished
dialing 911, there was a cigarette firmly planted and lit between
my lips. The mean little junkie was back, fiery and alive,
demanding that I feed her at least a pack a day. She laughed at me
as I looked at my yellow fingers, tasted my own rotten breath and
listened to my lungs scream like a rape whistle when I tried to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was there when you caught your ex-boyfriend trying to move
out of state without telling you?'' she demanded of me as I watched
another insipid anti-smoking commercial on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was there when your last boss said, `Don't look so scared.
You're not fired. Your position has just been eliminated.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was there last week when you walked around Trader Joe's
with your dress tucked into your panties? Me. Me! ME!!! And I don't
care if you just coughed so hard that you threw up! Find the
lighter and give the devil her due!''
</P>
<P>
   When the price of cigarettes zoomed up to nearly four bucks a
pack, it was just too much. Although I wasn't looking forward to
withdrawal and ending my affair with the mean little junkie, I
figured that if it cost me $3.75 a day to see my husband, I'd drop
him, too.
</P>
<P>
   I secured a prescription for Zyban, but became a little hesitant
after I discovered that it was quite similar to an antidepressant,
and that I would have to continue taking it for three months.
Frantically, I imagined that my next 12 columns would begin with
the words, ``Everyone is beautiful, in their own way'' . . .
``Today, I smelled a flower. . .,'' or ``Have you ever really seen
the colors of a rainbow?'' and quickly dumped the prescription in
the trash.
</P>
<P>
   When she suspected that I was thinking of quitting again, the
mean little junkie scoffed and declared, ``You put a patch on me
and I'll shove a Nutty Ho-Ho in your mouth with every breath you
take. You try that nicotine inhaler and I'll turn your bowels into
concrete. You undergo hypnosis and the first words that will come
out of your mouth will be about a particularly horrifying dream you
had about bearing Bob Saget's children in 1991. You just try it.
You just try to kill me, sister!''
</P>
<P>
   Then I coughed. And I sneezed. Before I knew it, I was down,
sweating more than a fat cop after chasing a perp for a block, my
lungs thick with congestion, my head pulsing with a fever. The flu,
it seemed, would be my method of least resistance in quitting.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three days, the mean little junkie stayed dormant
as I kept coughing up things that appeared to be vital organs and
possibly glands. But in a couple of days I got better, my lungs
cleared, the sneezing stopped, and she was ready to show herself.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the craving wave had just hit me when my husband lit
up not three feet from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you please not do that in front of me?'' I pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, taking a drag, ``withdrawal is completely
psychological. If you believe it hard enough, it won't bother you
that I'm smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor thing. My husband did not know the mean little junkie
like I did. Before I knew it, she had my husband in a chokehold and
had a utensil in her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychological, huh?'' the mean little junkie said, her mouth
frothing. ``Then I guess it won't bother you when I psychologically
stab you in the forehead with this fork the next time you wrap your
lips around that butt!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, this isn't so bad,'' I said as I later applied
ointment to the four round wounds on my husband's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen the mean little junkie this morning. It
could be worse. At this very moment, there's a little old lady
somewhere in Phoenix, sitting on her potty with six dollars in
change and a pound of Pep-O-Mints crashing together in her colon,
just screaming to get out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
