<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS ON THE TELEPHONE FOR AMERICAN CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you travel to London or Rome, Helsinki, or Hong Kong, the
first thing you notice is that everyone's on the mobile. Mobile
telephony is quickly becoming the personal communications tool of
choice in Europe and Asia. In the next 10 years, it should become
the European and Asian standard for telephony. People who live and
work there won't have a ``home phone number'' and ``an office phone
number.'' They'll just have a phone number.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for the hard-wired phone companies in Europe and
Asia and very good news for American consumers. Why? Because
success breeds imitation and the success of wireless telephony in
Europe and Asia is now breeding highly competitive product here in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in US wireless telephony actually occurred last
year when AT&AMP;T introduced its ``Digital One Rate'' plan. The plan
allows users 600 minutes a month of talk time for $90, with no fees
for so-called roaming charges (out of network calls) and no
long-distance charges. Pay $150 a month and you get 1,400 minutes.
AT&AMP;T is also offering unlimited ``local'' wireless service in test
markets for as little as $40 per month. Sprint PCS, Omnipoint,
Nextel, and others are scrambling to match the AT&AMP;T plans.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, service can be spotty, particularly here in the
Northeast. But in three to five years wireless service is expected
to be all but universal in the United States and the connections
are likely to be crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   Once that happens, and assuming stiff price competition
continues unabated, the choice between wireless and wired telephony
will quickly become a no-brainer. Do you want to pay Bell Atlantic
$75 for local phone calls and AT&AMP;T another $75 for long distance?
Or would you rather pay AT&AMP;T Wireless or Sprint PCS one flat fee of
$120 for all calls and pay no additional charge for paging, text
mail, voice mail, caller identification, and call waiting?
</P>
<P>
   Already, some corporations are beginning to convert. Many
companies that reside in cities with fully developed wireless
systems, such as San Diego and San Jose, are now wireless for
``voice communications.'' Employees wear ``holsters'' for their
cell phones and do all their phone work and personal business
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The savings for companies that have converted are not yet
substantial, but the productivity gains are enormous. The old dodge
game of ``he (or she) just stepped away for a moment'' no longer
applies. Employees, unless they have their phone shut off, are
always ``on call.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward wireless is causing regional Bell operating
companies (RBOCs), like Bell Atlantic, to sit up and take notice.
Bell Atlantic recently offered to buy AirTouch, a California
wireless company with over 8.4 million US customers. Vodafone, the
leading European wireless firm, promptly trumped Bell Atlantic's
bid with a staggering offer of $97 per share. Bell Atlantic's
defeat in the AirTouch bidding war was a jarring wake-up call for
the RBOCs, because the more ubiquitous wireless becomes, the more
competitive local telephony becomes.
</P>
<P>
   More competition in local telephony is devoutly to be wished.
Competition in telecommunications has been a boon for the US
economy. Since the break-up of Ma Bell, long-distance rates have
declined by 70 percent. Long distance rates are likely to fall even
more, as Internet technology incorporates telephony. The cost of
mail, thanks to the Internet and electronic mail, has also dropped
dramatically. Only two communications monopolies remain to be
smashed; the regional Bell operating companies and cable television
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Supreme Court ruled that the Telecommunications Act
of 1996 gives the federal government (specifically the FCC), and
not state regulatory authorities, jurisdiction over the RBOCs.
Traditionally (although not in all cases), state regulatory
authorities have been quite cozy with the Baby Bells and have
granted them the benefit of most every doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Clinton, the FCC has been adamant that local
telephony be deregulated. In granting the FCC jurisdiction, the
Supreme Court has increased the likelihood that the last great
telephone monopolists will finally have to join the real world and
compete.
</P>
<P>
   The RBOCs might begin by cutting prices. They might also push
ahead with their ADSL modem roll-out. ADSL modems offer lightning
fast Internet connections, which reminds consumers of the value of
hard-wired telephony. Wireless modems, which are scheduled for
roll-out this year, will not be competitive with ADSL any time
soon. The sooner Bell Atlantic rolls out ADSL modems and cuts
prices on local telephony, the more likely it is they'll be able to
beat back the wireless challenge.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't get with the program, they'll soon be looking out
the window at their customer base chatting it up on wireless
phones. Whatever happens, the cost of telephony can now only go in
one direction: downward, onward, for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
