<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2323 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BUSINESS-BOS &LR;      01-28 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS CROWD IMPATIENT WITH TRIAL'S COST, DURATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For the crowd lunching on slabs of meat and
salads laced with blue cheese dressing, the bottom line in the
year-old investigation into presidential sex and skulduggery is the
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   As waiters in white jackets refilled their bread baskets and
coffee cups, businessman after businesswoman at the Savoy Grill
expressed contempt for the millions of tax dollars spent to bring
Bill Clinton to trial in the US Senate. They bemoaned the money
wasted, not to mention the time. More than a few say they would be
embarrassed to run a business as inefficiently as the impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   That went for the entrepreneur in conservative suit and tie who
wants Clinton removed from office, as well as the advertising
account manager in shirt sleeves who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Their audit of Washington was both affable and angry, one
straight-shooting opinion after another, punctuated by jokes, such
as the one about the pope refusing to hear Clinton's confession in
St. Louis for lack of time.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the Savoy Grill, where the speciality of the
96-year-old house on the edge of downtown is seafood, was
ambivalent about what to do and when to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been punished. He has been humiliated, whether he
thinks he has or not,'' said Clinton supporter Robert Sullivan,
vice president for sales and marketing at a local brewery. ``Enough
is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Added his lunch companion, advertising executive Perry Beal:
``What he did was not right, but they should stop it right now.
It's costing us too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   A table over, however, office equipment manager David Lesher
said that so much money has already been spent _ more than $40
million by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr alone _ that the
Senate has little choice but to continue the trial unless Clinton
fesses up completely. ``At this point, we may as well see it
through,'' Lesher said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one was pleased about the closed-door sessions in
Congress, with one likening it to a public company holding private
annual meetings. That's just bad business, more than one said.
Whatever happens, whether the trial ends tomorrow or continues
indefinitely, the consensus was that the people paying for the
process have a right to know what compromises are being made and
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appalled that it has gone this far, but I'm not
surprised,'' said Matt Hicks, a private investor who dislikes
Clinton but opposes the Senate trial as ``just not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The table where the talk was harshest was filled by four older
men who meet for lunch every so often. Friends long enough to cut
each other off midsentence and to moan at each other's punch lines,
the four wanted Clinton impeached and now want him out of the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   As Les Wood, a retired airline vice president, put it to his
friends' guffaws: ``I thought he was a phony with a capital F when
he was running. I say we give him a fair trial and hang him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Les, why don't you just say what you really think?''
interjected Chuck Peterson, a retired airline pilot who described
himself as conservative but not ultraconservative. ``But this is
not a man who should be in office, no matter what his credentials
are, and I don't mind saying so either.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a corner table covered in white linen, beneath one of
the restaurant's themed murals, the men spoke of old-fashioned
morality and political muscle and gossiped about whether Hillary, a
``smart cookie,'' will leave Bill ``like a dirty shirt'' regardless
of how he exits Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Each said he thinks that D.C. Democrats got carried away with
their clout. Then again, they don't much like the behavior of
anyone on Capitol Hill. ``I have a difficult time with Congress,''
Peterson explained. ``They're politicians, not gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually their conversation wound its way back to the bottom
line. None of them said he expects Clinton to be ousted from
office, although none of them wants the Senate trial cut short,
either. Still, they said they are aghast at the money spent to hold
Clinton accountable, only for them the fault lies with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really puckers me up is when Democrats complain
about the cost of all of this,'' said Max Norman, a retired
executive with the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce. ``I
mean, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Wood: ``He had it in his power to nix the whole thing a
year ago. If he'd told the truth, we'd have said, `OK, Bill, don't
do it again.' At least we might have.''
</P>
<P>
   At the next table, Michael Boyce said he, too, had considered
forgiving Clinton. Initially, he even opposed impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had any guts, he'd resign, but he doesn't have any
guts,'' said Boyce. ``But no matter what happens, it's going to be
hard for there to be a winner in this whole thing, including the
American public. Either way, we're paying for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
