A2324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWAGGART-ENDURES2-BOS     01-28 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAGGART-ENDURES2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWAGGART CONTINUES HIS QUEST FOR CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ The sign on busy Interstate 10 giving
directions to Jimmy Swaggart's Bible College is gone, and the
Sunday throngs at his Family Worship Center have dissipated. But
the voice, rasped by overuse and kissed by the bayous, endures on
the radio, pleading, as ever, for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Won't you help us?'' Swaggart asked the other day during a
fund-raising ``radiothon'' on his flagship station, WJSM in Baton
Rouge. ``In November we had a $4,000 deficit. We're looking at a
$150,000 deficit for the year . . . We're not a money-making
operation. I wish we were. If we could get more money, we'd use it
for Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   A $25 pledge comes in from down the river in Donaldsonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless you! That's wonderful! Is this station a blessing to
you? I'm waiting to hear from you in Franklin and Houma and Lutcher
and Denham Springs,'' he says, reeling off the names of several
south Louisiana towns.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after his disgrace, the 63-year-old
evangelist continues to carry on his quest for money and lost
souls. But Jimmy Swaggart Ministries, once a far-flung empire that
collected about a half-million dollars a day during its heyday, has
been reduced to a regional mission that reaches out to a dwindling
following from its base in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of tragicomic episodes, with Swaggart lurching
from one crisis to another, the minister has settled into humbler
times. The prince of Pentacostalism is now mostly a merchant for
his business enterprises. Increasingly, he turns over his pulpit on
Sundays to his son, Donnie. His weekly television show, which once
commanded an audience of 2 million households across the nation,
relies on reruns and is thought to be limited to a few stations
with weak signals in Louisiana and Texas. The river of dollars has
dried up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy Swaggart has become a nonentity,'' says Ed Pratt,
religion editor for The Advocate, the daily newspaper in Baton
Rouge. ``At his peak, he had three to five thousand people at two
regular services every Sunday. But his son and his wife have shut
him up. There's virtually nothing at his Bible College, and it's
not accredited by the Assembly of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister who reveled in his fame in the 1980s rarely
ventures beyond his moated mansion behind walls along Highland Road
or his business complex on Bluebonnet Boulevard here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a blanket policy of giving no interviews. That policy
has been in place for a lot of years,'' says Linda Westbrook, an
officer for Jimmy Swaggart Ministries who dismissed a reporter's
request for information about the scope of the ministry and a
meeting with Swaggart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no access to the press,'' says Gus Weill, a Baton
Rouge publicist who once handled the Swaggart account. ``It's a
closed shop, impossible to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear contemporary Swaggart, one must tune to 88.5 on the FM
dial in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio commentary, Swaggart equates himself with a
Biblical apostle. ``I'm like Paul, fighting devils and demons,'' he
says, making it clear he believes reporters are the agents of the
devil. ``Every week,'' he says, ``there's another newspaper article
with ridiculous, ribald stories. It's all outlandish, ridiculous
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses to give his radio station's telephone number, to call
for more pledges. ``You can use your credit card,'' he says. ``I
hear the Holy Spirit. If you hear God pressing you, and you don't
have the full amount, you can still help.'' He advises that a $100
commitment can be paid off in $10 monthly installments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday, we raised $24,000. So far...we've raised $34,815. I
believe in the Lord's power to raise $100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he is counting on the faith of his listeners. Then the
voice drops an octave. ``Satan,'' he says, ``didn't want this
ministry to work.''
</P>
<P>
   At his height, Swaggart could raise $140 million a year. A child
of Ferriday, La., a working-class town across the river from
Natchez, Miss., he grew up to become a bigger phenomenon than his
two singing first cousins, Jerry Lee Lewis (``Great Balls of
Fire'') and Mickey Gilley (``Looking for Love, in All the Wrong
Places''). As Carol Flake wrote in ``Redemptorama,'' a 1984 book
about televangelists:
</P>
<P>
   ``For devotees of good-ol'-boy gospel, swaggering Jimmy
Swaggart, who topped the religious TV ratings in 1983, offered
brow-mopping, piano-banging Pentecostalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies helped red-jacketed Swaggart security forces
handle the crowds that flocked to his Sunday services at the
futuristic Family Worship Center on the eastern edge of Baton
Rouge. It was the epicenter of a worldwide ministry televised in
145 countries. He commanded more than 500 missionaries and a staff
of 2,000. His Bible College graduated hundreds of disciples a year.
</P>
<P>
   Swaggart's downfall began after he became embroiled in a strange
holy war involving the high priests of televangelism. He
characterized Jim Bakker, a North Carolina preacher who wound up in
prison, as ``a cancer on the body of Christ that needs to be
excised.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned his fire on another rival, an Assembly of God
minister in New Orleans named Marvin Gorman, whom Swaggart purged
from the denomination with accusations that Gorman seduced the wife
of a fellow preacher as well as other parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation, Gorman's son trapped Swaggart with a prostitute
at a seedy motel along Airline Highway in New Orleans in the fall
of 1987, flattening the tires on his car so Swaggart couldn't
escape until Gorman arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Swaggart, who had written that ``pornography titillates and
captivates the sickest of the sick,'' in his book ``Rape of a
Nation,'' was confronted with charges that he regularly paid $20 to
a prostitute with a tattooed cross on her arm to assume provocative
poses in front of him while he masturbated.
</P>
<P>
   In a tearful confession that was captured on film and came to
symbolize hypocrisy among television's prophets, Swaggart told his
congregation: ``I have sinned against you, my Lord, and I would ask
that your precious blood would wash and cleanse every stain until
it is in the seas of God's forgetfulness, never to be remembered
against me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   His prayer was not answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Assemblies of God defrocked Swaggart for refusing to abide
with a one-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Within the year, his consort, Debra Murphree, posed for raunchy
photos and sold her story to Penthouse magazine for $210,000 (her
agents, lawyers, and the IRS got all but $54,000). ``To me, he was
kind of perverted,'' she told the magazine. ``I wouldn't want him
around my children.''
</P>
<P>
   His tribulations persisted. Saying that he had been falsely
accused, Gorman won a $10 million judgment against Swaggart in a
highly publicized defamation trial in New Orleans in 1991. Gorman,
who acknowledged only one instance of adultery, said Swaggart
orchestrated a campaign to undermine Gorman's reputation by
charging him with scores of infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   After appeals prolonged the case another three years, court
records indicated that Swaggart's insurance company settled with
Gorman for $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swaggart's still worth $100 million,'' says Hunter Lundy, a
Lake Charles lawyer who represented Gorman and has written a new
book on the case, ``Let Us Prey.'' ``They try to hide as much
information as they can, but last year he bought five new black
Mercedes. And he's still buying TV time across the country, most of
it's c.o.d.. (cash on delivery).''
</P>
<P>
   With his collection plates gone fallow, Swaggart's wealth is
based on real estate holdings in Baton Rouge, where he owns about
100 acres of prime commercial property next to the giant Mall of
Louisiana. He also makes money from a ministry building leased to
the state Department of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years after he reigned over the Arbitron ratings, an aura
of Oz still lingers around Swaggart.
</P>
<P>
   His television programs are produced on the grounds of his
ministry, a complex of low-slung stone buildings with bunker-like
slits for windows.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who monitor Swaggart's work, many shows use
recycled tapes from the glory years when thousands came to
Swaggart's camp meetings. In later productions from the Family
Worship Center, Swaggart's cameramen focus on tight shots of the
congregation to avoid showing rows of empty pews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
