<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DENVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER HIGH ON CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Decades after miners emptied gold, copper, and silver
from the nearby Rockies, a frontier spirit burns brightly here once
again.
</P>
<P>
   This time it has fueled downtown makeovers, high-tech startups,
and a mayor who is not afraid to take a flier at landing the
ultimate media-op: the year 2000 Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   It has also inspired scenes unimaginable a decade ago, including
a gawky, former oil-hunting geologist swirling a glass of
chardonnay with young Turks at an art museum benefit.
</P>
<P>
   But in the same way Denver has taken a turn from mining mecca to
a Western hub of culture and tourism, that geologist _ a local
visionary named John Hickenlooper _ evolved into a beer baron and
pioneer of preservation after plummeting oil prices ended his first
career. He wound up launching the country's largest microbrewery,
and helping to turn skid row into LoDo, a lower downtown stretch
where the trendiest restaurants, galleries, and residential lofts
have sprouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have remade ourselves,'' says Hickenlooper, born a
12th-generation Philadelphian. ``We took a stodgy cowtown and
mostly through our own efforts _ not with big government grants _
recreated it.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention bid that started as a whim in 1996, when Mayor
Wellington Webb was looking for hometown headlines at the Chicago
convention, has grown into an earnest effort. As is the case with
Boston, few expected Denver to be a serious contender, much less
going head-to-head with Boston and Los Angeles as the final three
vying for the lucrative political bash.
</P>
<P>
   After cutting its teeth on such worldly events as the visit of
Pope John Paul II in 1993 and the Summit of the Eight (formerly
G-7) in 1997, Denver leaders say the viability of the city's bid
for the Democratic National Convention should not be too
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to take it to the next level,'' says Steven
Farber, a Denver lawyer and member of the city's convention site
committee. ``We have shown we can play with the big kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Denver boosters still see their bid as a longshot
behind Los Angeles and Boston, because Colorado remains a largely
GOP bastion. But the city's ace is Roy Romer, a former Colorado
governor who is the Democratic National Committee's general
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   As a ``new American city'' and gateway to the West, Denver is
cast by supporters as offering a launching pad for the Democratic
Party to expand its base. As Denver's convention point man Mike
Dino says: ``We are a battleground and our message is, `Don't give
up on the West like the Democrats once gave up on the South.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's bid for the convention caps a growth spurt that saw
home sales rise 81.5 percent in 1998, office vacancies plummet, and
jobs proliferate to a supply of 1.5 for every city resident, by
city calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism draw is only expected to increase as more
entertainment destinations are completed, including a Six Flags
amusement park and an aquarium to join a newly minted downtown
retail and entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   The building binge goes on with enough superlatives to make a
Texan blush. There is the new airport, said to be the largest in
the country, and the largest performing arts center under one roof,
not to mention the Pepsi Center, already being touted as the most
technologically advanced arena when it opens in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On the horizon is a light-rail spur for downtown, to stanch the
flow of cars to big events, and a $180 million football stadium for
the Super Bowl-bound Broncos. The stadium is slated to cost roughly
half the price of the Patriots' planned new home in Hartford, and
is funded by a sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Given a migration rate into Colorado that grew 18.2 percent from
1990 to 1997, much of it into the four fastest growing counties in
the nation, there should be no shortage of patrons for all the
attractions, according to the Center for the New West, a Denver
research group.
</P>
<P>
   Key to that growth is what Mayor Webb, a liberal Democrat
described by Ebony magazine as one of the 100 most influential
African-Americans in the country, calls the ``Denver attitude,''
which takes a decided disinterest in social pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The city's up-by-the-bootstraps ethic contrasts with convention
rivals Los Angeles, which leans on Hollywood moguls, and Boston,
still reliant on a blue-blood establishment. Denver stands tall on
Horatio Alger potential in a city that is not obsessed by image,
ancestry, or Ivy alma maters, its supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no limits here; people are very comfortable with who
they are,'' says Richard Higgins, 27, who, as head of a thriving
software company, is intent on hiring graduates from the business
schools back East that rejected him.
</P>
<P>
   Webb says his administration is equally broad-minded, whether a
developer is Republican, Democrat, or ``blue-eyed monster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to know, `Do you have the intellect and the work
ethic to make the deal work?' '' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   For all its growth and budding sophistication, however, nothing
drives home Denver's cowtown heritage like the annual National
Western Stock Show. Below the gleaming skyscrapers of US West and
Amoco last week, bronco-busters from the largest rodeo in the world
mingled with buttoned-down biomedical conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say the animal pungence that pervades the Rocky
Mountain air these days emanates from the stables at the Coliseum.
Others say it's just the persistent eau de Denver, an ambient cloud
that wafts between the tannery and the Purina Dog Chow factory.
</P>
<P>
   None of that should be confused with the brown cloud that slope
winds can trap in the Mile High valley and bring LA-level smog to
mind. But when a visitor raises either aerial subject, it is
quickly changed to the preferred topic of whether Denver has 300 or
310 sunny days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all its growth, Denver has struggled to assemble enough
hotel rooms within a short drive to meet the DNC's standards. The
city now says it well surpasses the required 20,000 rooms, tallying
30,000, including rooms in Boulder. The convention's site committee
even went on helicopter rides last summer to check on the hotel
sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   The other bid weakness, in a state where GOP congressmen
boycotted President Clinton's State of the Union speech last week,
is a financial commitment by the Republican state government.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the city is putting up $6 million and the rest of
its $33.9 million bid would come from private sources. Denver would
prefer to be in Boston's shoes, with $6 million pledged by the city
and another $6 million from the Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   Denver figures it has muscled the maximum in pledges without the
final decision, which after impeachment delays is expected by
mid-February. ``If Denver is awarded the convention, the money will
come,'' Webb says.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has taken an amicable attitude toward Boston in the
convention sweepstakes, a respite from its LA-bashing. Denver would
see an LA victory as a slap against the West, from which it
considers Los Angeles a world apart, while a Boston win could be
seen as a logical response to the GOP choice of Philadelphia for
its convention.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is ``perceived as too Democratic and we're seen as not
Democratic enough,'' says Webb, who is incoming president of the US
Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Webb sees Boston as a proper peer because its bid is also
mayoral-driven, unlike the private committee in LA that must
guarantee services from police and public works departments run by
a Republican mayor.
</P>
<P>
   To Webb's way of thinking, mayors are the key to any campaign.
``The only way you win the war is with ground troops,'' Webb says,
``and that's from the mayors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-28 1706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETEND PLAY ENRICHES DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In years gone by, children in Cheryl Silveira's family daycare
in Windham, N.H., would get very excited if she found a
refrigerator box. They could play for hours pretending it was a
boat or a house or maybe a space ship.
</P>
<P>
   This year, when she proudly plunked a refrigerator box into the
play area, the children's response was far different.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do anything,'' says Silveira. ``When I said, `Wow!
Isn't this a great box, we can pretend all kinds of things with
this!' they said, `But it's just a box.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Silveira crawled inside and pretended it was a school bus. The
six children, ages 1 1/2 to 5, were happy to crawl in and out with
her but, says a disappointed Silveira, ``They never got carried
away with it. It never was more than a box to them.''
</P>
<P>
   When a box is only a box, preschoolers may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to create make-believe worlds lays the foundation
for academic learning and healthy development, according to
researchers. ``Being able to pretend is not a luxury, it's a
necessity,'' says Yale University psychologist Jerome Singer. One
of the nation's leading authorities on children's play and coauthor
of a classic on the subject, ``House of Make Believe'' (Harvard
University Press), Singer is sad but not surprised to hear what's
happening in Silveira's Bugle Bear Day Care. Unfortunately, he
hears it from teachers all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Smith, who runs a three-day-a-week laboratory preschool
at Ipswich High School as part of the child development curriculum,
sees the lack of imagination most in children's artwork. ``It used
to be that kids would prefer a blank piece of paper for coloring
and they'd create elaborate stories to go with the drawing. Now,''
she says, ``they either want a coloring book or they want us to
tell them what to draw.'' Smith, who has worked with preschoolers
for seven years, laments, ``They look to the adults for how things
should be rather than pretend how they'd like them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no single, overarching reason why teachers are seeing
less pretend play. Silveira attributes it to too much TV and
computer time. Singer says it's that, plus too many programmed
activities at too young an age, and overworked parents with too
little time to play. Early childhood educator Mary Mindess of
Lesley College has another theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society in general doesn't value play as a learning process,''
she says. ``We want results, as in test results, so we push
academics too early, letters and words at age 3. The message kids
get is that pretending isn't valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best way for adults to understand pretend play is to
think of it as a filter that enables young children to view the
complicated pieces of their world up close and transform them into
pieces they can manage. Because it is every-day experiences that
loom largest, these are what children most need to examine and own.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how the preschooler watches several times a day as mom
stops what she's doing and gets very busy in the kitchen with her
noisy, shiny objects. What is she doing? Why can't she play
anymore? This must be very important.
</P>
<P>
   By playing kitchen herself, a preschooler not only imitates the
role of mom, she becomes mom, says early childhood educator Edgar
Klugman. ``First, she studies the person. Then she imitates the
actions, even the speech and movements. The more mom engages with
her _ `To scramble an egg, I crack it against a bowl' _ the more a
child learns rules of the role,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The more imagination a child brings to the play, the richer the
experience. Indeed, research shows that elaborate imaginary play
leads to increased language comprehension, vocabulary,
problem-solving skills, attention span, cooperation, empathy, and
social skills, according to Klugman, a professor at Wheelock
College who is known for his research on children's imaginary play.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the coin, research shows that children who
have little or poor experience with imaginary play are more
aggressive in later years, have less self-control and less success
with learning.
</P>
<P>
   The positive payoffs begin to accrue as early as kindergarten
and first grade and continue through adulthood, says Klugman.
``Without the rich experience of imaginary play as a child, an
adult is very limited. Leaders tend to have had very good play
experiences,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how make-believe play fosters development in three areas:
</P>
<P>
   --Emotionally. ``Because a child plays out feelings as well as
roles, it has a cathartic effect: The things he's worried about
will play out,'' says Mindess, who is coordinator and founder of
the New England Kindergarten Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was in a car accident with daddy. In his play, he'll
re-create the accident over and over, she says, until he has
control of the events and the feelings are less scary. Parents
typically don't even realize this is happening, partly because
we're too literal and don't recognize the play for what it is, says
Mindess, and partly because children don't need realistic props.
``They're very good at using objects as symbols, a block for a car,
for instance,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --Intellectually. As he observes something and acts it out, he
learns about it. Every week, the 4-year-old goes to the grocery
store. At first, he is intrigued by the cashier, then watchful of
him. One day in his imaginary play, he is the cashier. The next
trip to the store, he watches more carefully because his play has
made more aware of nuances. He sees something he didn't see before,
perhaps the numbers on the register. Next time in his play, he says
to the make-believe customer, ``You owe me 10-teen dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's a misunderstanding in the learning, it
doesn't matter, because it's a self-correcting process,'' says
Mindess. ``He'll learn correct numbers another time. What's more
important is that the pretending gives the brain the opportunity to
make more and more links.'' The more links there are, the more
information the brain can take in, and that makes a child more open
to more experiences. In other words, Mindess says, the concrete
provides the basis for pretend play, but the pretending helps a
child make it her own and learn.
</P>
<P>
   --Morally. Because children use play to work through their own
issues, pretending may start off as imitation but quickly branch
out to reflect a child's perceptions. It's in this way that values
get absorbed, says Mindess. She gives an example of a preschooler
with a new-born brother who is caring for her doll, much like mommy
cares for the baby, except that suddenly she hits the doll and
says, ``You're a bad baby!'' It's through that process, she says,
that a child's conscience develops: She's working out for herself
the moral value of knowing it's wrong to hit the baby at the same
time she's coping with feelings of jealousy. ``Without the
opportunity to hit the doll, the feelings are pent up and the child
won't be as free to incorporate the positive values,'' or to keep
from acting on the negative ones, says Mindess.
</P>
<P>
   The more parents or caregivers can engage in pretend play with a
child, the more likely it is a child will make believe on her own,
and the more learning will occur. ``Sometimes you just need to
provide objects and show an interest,'' says Klugman. Other times,
as with the children in Silveira's care, ``You have to literally
show them,'' says Singer.
</P>
<P>
   It takes energy, interest, and know-how and some parents are
either clueless or uncomfortable with pretending. It's so
important, though, that Singer has a new project in New Haven to
teach low-income parents how to encourage imaginary play. Most
popular is the restaurant game:
</P>
<P>
   ``You imagine you're in a restaurant and you sit at the table
and you take turns being the waiter and the customer: `Oh, I have
two friends with me, so I need three seats.' Suddenly your child's
not just having fun playing with you, he's learning numbers and
words, like appetizer, and he's learning social amenities,'' says
Singer. ``We pitch that it helps with school readiness, which it
does,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But it's even more basic than that. Pretend play is practice of
real-life skills. ``It's a rehearsal,'' says Mindess.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --As important as it is for parents to be encouraging and
involved in pretend play, it's also important to back off once her
imagination is ignited. There's no bigger damper to creativity than
a parent who takes over the play.
</P>
<P>
   --Children don't need store-bought toys for pretend play.
Improvising with whatever is around the house is often better.
</P>
<P>
   --Observing a child's pretend play can give you a window into
the issues she's working on, but even if you don't like what you
see, don't scold her for the content of her play. If it's
troublesome to you, talk to a professional about it.
</P>
<P>
   --There's nothing wrong with a 3-year-old who only piles blocks
up and knocks them down, but you can try to engage his imagination
with a story around his play: ``Once there was a big tall tower
that was the biggest building in the city, but one day there was a
giant who had such a powerful sneeze he could make buildings fall
down. One day he had a terrible cold. . .''
</P>
<P>
   --By age 4, children typically engage peers in elaborate pretend
play where they use props. Interacting with each other _ ``Don't
you know waiters don't say that?!'' _ they learn from each other
ways to interpret various roles.
</P>
<P>
   --Reading daily to your child or telling her stories is the best
way to encourage pretend play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading: ``Ritalin Nation, Rapid-Fire
Culture and the Transformation of Human Consciousness'' by Richard
DeGrandpre (Norton).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
