<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-ANTIQUES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEARTHING TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The upper east side of Manhattan in January is ground
zero for the American antique trade. It's here that trends are
spotted and auction records set in sweaty-palmed bidding wars. Top
dealers paraded their finest treasures here at the Winter Antiques
Show, which ended Sunday. ``The tremors in that room spread to all
corners of the antique world,'' said Clark Pearce of Essex, Mass.,
an antique furniture consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading auction houses, Sotheby's and Christie's, ``save
their best things that turn up during the year'' for American
decorative arts auctions held during the show's 10-day run, said
Dean Lahikainen, a curator at the Peabody Essex Museum in Salem,
Mass. Lesser shows and auctions surround these behemoths like
pleasure boats accompanying the QE2 into harbor. During this annual
gathering of the clan, the excited buzz of dealers, scholars, and
collectors builds to a consensus that elevates the finest
decorative objects to the status of art.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to an 18th-century Newport secretary which
sold at Sotheby's Jan. 17 for $8,250,500, 10 times the catalog
estimate and the second highest price paid for a piece of American
furniture. Like many a masterpiece, it has ``a provenance,'' which
means a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Stardom arrived partly because the stately mahogany secretary
was a new face on the auction stage. It had spent 200 years hidden
away in France, and it made a dramatic entrance when it reached
Sotheby's only days before the auction. Like many other previously
undiscovered treasures, it surfaced through unsolicited photographs
that owners sent Sotheby's for appraisal, said John B.A. Nye,
senior cataloger of the American Furniture and Decorative Arts
Department.
</P>
<P>
   It had been in the same family for eight generations, beginning
with the Rev. Nathaniel Appleton, who was minister of the First
Church in Cambridge, Mass. from 1717 to 1784 and a Harvard officer
for almost as long. His heirs took it with them when they went to
France on a diplomatic posting in 1800. They stayed there. So did
the Newport secretary.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the photographs, Sotheby's Leslie Keno and his
staff began their own six-year diplomatic initiative to coax the
family into sending the heirloom to auction, all under the greatest
secrecy. It was photographed in Paris and the catalog entry was
necessarily written without a thorough examination of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   When it arrived in New York, infrared revealed the rare penciled
signature ``Made by Christopher Townsend.'' He was a founder of the
premiere family of American cabinetmakers, and the signature
immensely increased the secretary's value. Then experts discovered
peg holes from missing rounded feet. Within 24 hours, Sotheby's had
replacement feet made that restored the piece to its full 9-foot
height. The Newport piece was looking better and better. The
last-minute drama of these discoveries riveted attention as the
auction approached.
</P>
<P>
   The shell-carved doors characteristic of great Newport furniture
and the slanted desk front both open to reveal valanced pigeonholes
and drawers for filing documents and writing instruments. Its
height, domed top, and construction entirely from very expensive
and dense ``plum pudding'' mahogany (usually used only on the front
of even fine furniture), further marked it as exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only early piece of American furniture with silver
hardware,'' said Keno. ``Any original handles this old are rare,
and never have we seen any so beautiful, delicate, and expensive.''
The lopers that support the deskfront writing surface are cast as
vigilant falcon-like birds with green stone-inset eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware bears the rare stamp of Samuel Casey, a Rhode
Island silversmith whose talent couldn't save him from ruin when
his goldsmith's forge set fire to his house and shop. Insolvent,
Casey was arrested for counterfeiting dollars in 1770 and sentenced
to be hanged. The night before his scheduled execution, ``a
considerable number of People . . . with Faces black'd'' broke into
the jail and freed him, reported the Nov. 10, 1770 Providence
Gazette. After nine years as a fugitive, Casey was pardoned and
able to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Townsend, as the patriarch of a large and
industrious Quaker dynasty, led a quieter and more prosperous life,
schooling his numerous progeny in the craft of making fine
furniture. The deeply lobed shell front carvings in this early
secretary became the family trademark and, eventually, an American
icon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The astronomical sum paid for this secretary by an anonymous
private collector, which follows an all-time $12.1 million record
three years ago at Christie's for another Newport secretary by the
same Quaker family, illustrates how the best decorative arts are
gaining the same respect accorded fine paintings, even if such
status was the last thing on the minds of their makers when they
were struggling to keep the wolf from the door.
</P>
<P>
   As with fine arts, the top folk art and decorative pieces often
nowadays go straight from owner to auction house to buyer, leaving
traditional antique dealers out of the loop. But the best dealers
are still savvy trendspotters who indicate where collecting is
heading and what kinds of objects will be considered tomorrow's
masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Multiculturalism was the greatest trend apparent at the 45th
Winter Antiques Show, which benefits the East Side Settlement
House. There was an intriguing focus on historic artifacts from the
collisions of cultures which eventually produced today's global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 opening of a new wing devoted to Asian export art at
the Peabody Essex Museum is evidence of swelling interest in Asian
art, particularly the portion that intersected with American and
European history to produce new hybrid visions.
</P>
<P>
   (So is the four-year-old International Asian Arts Fair, which
includes a dozen dealers who handle antique China Trade porcelain,
and which is scheduled for March 25-30 at the same Seventh Regiment
Armory where the Winter show was held.)
</P>
<P>
   Martyne Gregory's booth at the Winter show was devoted entirely
to early 19th-century portraits and harbor scenes painted in Canton
but commissioned by Europeans for export. They combined both
Western and Chinese visual styles.
</P>
<P>
   So did Marc J. Matz Antiques' furniture and objects made for
export in China, India, and Ceylon during the 18th- and early
19th-century colonial period.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Indies trade furniture and decorative arts, though
western in design, was reinterpreted by the artists in those
countries to create new forms, such as an English-style Indian pier
table with carved lotus flowers. Everything becomes new,'' said
Matz, who also maintains a shop in Cambridge. ``Museums, which have
neglected this area until recently, have bought all my most
important pieces in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
