r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TINSEL-REVIEW-LADN     01-28 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINSEL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY PERLMAN'S PERFORMANCE KEEPS `TINSELTOWN' ON THE MAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1 1/2 STARS  
 
  
BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
LOS ANGELES _ ``Tinseltown'' is a misfired comedy about talentless
show-biz wanna-bes trying to hustle their way into the Hollywood
movie game. Some jokes about the people responsible for making the
film could be made here, but it would not be fair to do so. Not too
far off the mark in some of their cases, but still unfair.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on the play ``Self Storage'' by director Tony Spiridakis
and Shem Bitterman, the no-budget movie indeed spends a lot of time
inside one of those high-rise, concrete structures where people
lock up their excess stuff. These warehouses make singularly ugly
movie locations.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, on Christmas Eve, homeless would-be screenwriters Tiger
and Max (Tom Wood and Arye Gross) break into one of the buildings
to spend the night. They're surprised to discover many other people
living in the cramped units.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it? The storehouse manager Cliff (Ron
Perlman) is a failed actor who reads one of the guys' awful scripts
and loves it. He also may be the serial killer who's terrorizing
Hollywood by dressing up his victims' corpses in silly costumes.
But, hey, Tiger and Max figure, that only makes their new friend a
great source of screenplay material.
</P>
<P>
   Assorted other lowlifes _ Kristy Swanson's amoral film-school
careerist, Joe Pantoliano's producer who sleeps in the park _ try
to horn in on the action. Like the bad writers, they're all fairly
well-acted, but they never transcend the show-biz cliches they're
built to represent.
</P>
<P>
   The black comic idea here, that these bums are so desperate
they'll let a killer run amok if it gets them a movie deal, isn't
exactly cutting edge, either.
</P>
<P>
   We all saw ``The Player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was crueler. And smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tinseltown's'' one saving grace _ and he is a substantial one
_ is Perlman. He puts his imposing, cro-magnon form to frightening
good use here, but he also exhibits the film's only compelling
emotions and genuinely cagey intelligence. While most of
``Tinseltown'' is lazy satire that seems to have come from a dusty
old trunk, Perlman's performance is like a treasure found at a yard
sale. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-ANTIQUES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     01-28 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-ANTIQUES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... recent years.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Matz's display was a luminous 1833 oil
portrait by the great Philadelphia painter Rembrandt Peale of the
Rajah Rammohun Roy, an early Indian reformer who the admiring
artist painted in London, where Roy was campaigning for Indian
rights shortly before he died. ``To me it brings together all the
threads of east and west,'' said Matz.
</P>
<P>
   Another collision of cultures was recorded in the 9-foot oil
``The Crows Attempting to Provoke an Attack From the Whites on the
Big Horn River, East of the Rocky Mountains.'' It was painted by
Alfred Jacob Miller in 1841 after he witnessed the event on a
western expedition with Sir William Drummond Stewart. Tucked away
ever since in the Stewart family castle in Scotland, it, too, was
new to the market. Dealer Peter Tillou gave it a $8.5 million price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Several exhibitors devoted themselves to Native American crafts,
such as a beautiful Acoma ceramic olla, priced at $16,500, offered
by Morning Star Gallery of Santa Fe. If colonial American
cabinetmakers struggled to survive, one can only wonder what
dispossessed Native Americans would make of such prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Antique dealing is an inherently peculiar trade which a few
decades ago had, with notable exceptions, a reputation for veracity
only slightly higher than used cars sales. Much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992 every item displayed at the Winter show has been
examined by teams of curators, scholars, and art restorers before
opening night and anything questionable removed, or ``vetted out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great increase in scholarship has helped the market,''
said Madison Avenue dealer Leigh Keno. It has also upgraded the
status of antiques. Now a piece can be described as an 1880 Acoma
ceramic olla instead of ``an Indian pot,'' or a 1745 Newport
secretary by Christopher Townsend instead of an ``old mahogany
desk.'' An eastern woodland Indian war club in the Guthman
Americana display can be carbon dated, and was, to prove its
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Like these treasures, the American antique trade itself has a
history. In this case, one that began in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Street was the national hub of the American antique
market for the first 60 years of its existence, beginning in 1876
when Americans began to prize original colonial furniture instead
of associating it with rural backwardness and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pickers'' would drive their wagons out to rural Concord and
Lexington, going door to door to ask if the inhabitants had any
``old furniture'' to sell. Early Boston and surrounding New England
towns were especially rich in antiques because their Puritan
culture and bustling Yankee trade fostered fine craftsmanship.
Cultural conservatism also inspired owners to hold onto family
pieces for many generations. While more style-conscious New Yorkers
regularly threw out the old to make way for the new, Bostonians
followed the once-popular adage: ``We don't buy hats. We have our
hats.'' They already had their furniture, too, and didn't care if
it was old.
</P>
<P>
   As antique American furniture gained wider appreciation, much of
it was sold by dealers to wealthy clients in Manhattan. During the
Depression, most of the top dealers migrated there, including
Israel Sack, whose family antique business became the country's
most successful.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston remains a player in the trade it once dominated. New
England antiques still command center stage, and many of the major
dealers and collectors have New England addresses. More antiques
still leave New England than arrive here, but the flow is hardly
one way, as it is with many provincial capitals.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH-TV's successful program, ``Antique Roadshow,'' invades
auditoriums around the country, inviting locals to bring their
treasures for on-air appraisals. National in scale, yet
Boston-produced and featuring many local experts, it's the latest
example of how Boston antiquarians manage to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But suppose you're not in the market for a masterpiece. What are
the new collectibles? Minor trends abounded at the Winter show,
including:
</P>
<P>
   --Cocktail broaches from the 1950s. Barbara Macklowe of Macklowe
Gallery in New York calls them ``mommy pins'' because Mom used to
wear them. Also re-emerging from their long hibernation in the rear
of family jewelry chests are Mom's classic pearls and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   --Ivory and scrimshaw are hot again. Hyland Granby Antiques of
Hyannis, Mass. had a tiny bone guillotine (with a female victim)
carved by French prisoners from their soapbones, and a remarkable
whale's-tooth scrimshaw carved by a Marine aboard the HMS Beagle
when Charles Darwin was aboard that sold for a record $65,000. Marc
Matz had a circa 1770 engraved Indian ivory jewel cabinet and
dressing mirror with English scenes that for $12,000 to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   --Garden statuary has really taken off. Barbara Israel Garden
Antiques of Katonah, N.Y., had a pair of 1880 cast iron lions for
$19,500. Or a pair of carved stone sphinxes for $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   --Young couples are buying antique Victorian engagement rings.
Just the thing for a Valentine's Day proposal.
</P>
<P>
   --The age of celebrity has sent document collectors scurrying
for big names, reported Kenneth W. Rendell, who offered a $3 check
signed by Marilyn Monroe for $5,750. ``But something with real
content by a person who's not famous, like a soldier's Civil War
diary, is a better value.''
</P>
<P>
   --``Really great painted furniture has gone through the roof,''
reported Winterthur Museum scholar Brock Jobe.
</P>
<P>
   --Art and artifacts related to western expansion. A first
edition report on the Lewis and Clark expedition commanded $65,000
at Bauman Rare Books. (Owner David Bauman picked first editions of
``Angela's Ashes'' and ``Cold Mountain'' as future collectibles.
But don't lose the dust jackets.)
</P>
<P>
   --Early 19th-century silk embroidered pictures. They kept young
finishing school ladies busy long after they finished all those
alphabet samplers.
</P>
<P>
   --Antique walking sticks. Highland Granby Antiques had canes
that contained watches, guns, telecopes, swords, and watercolor
paintboxes. Wayne Pratt of Woodbury, Conn., had a fantastic German
cane stand carved with writhing snakes and grotesque animal and
demon heads on consignment from the owner, who had brought it into
WGBH's ``Antique Roadshow.''
</P>
<P>
   --Anything related to hit movies. Letters by World War II
figures such as Winston Churchill and Dwight Eisenhower command
even greater cache and cash after Steven Spielberg's ``Saving
Private Ryan'' this year. Rendell quickly sold a $25,000 floor plan
of the first class sections of the Titanic which were sent to the
London parents of a prospective passenger. He decided not to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
