<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SOUTHERN-2TAKE     01-28 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SOUTHERN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVERSAL OF FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN _ The theory was simple. After putting my own garden
to bed for the winter, I'd flee to the Southern Hemisphere, where
the seasons are reversed. I'd enjoy other gardens while not
neglecting my own.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I didn't escape the guilt. Autumn offered no free
time to cut back, tidy up, or mulch, and my garden is filled with
brown stalks that stare at me accusingly every morning. But I
didn't give my own grounds a thought while I was in South Africa,
where I marveled at the glories of Kirstenbosch, one of the world's
greatest gardens, met an eccentric plantsman at the University of
Stellenbosch, and talked with a remarkable young woman whose
contribution to post-Apartheid society is teaching disadvantaged
people the florist's art.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town was founded as a garden. In 1652, a young merchant
named Jan van Riebeeck was sent to the Cape by the Dutch East India
Company. His mission: to plant a 43-acre vegetable patch in what is
now the center of town, to grow fresh produce for the crews of the
ships on the long voyage to the East Indies. You won't find any
veggies in the ``Company's Gardens'' nowadays, just a tranquil
oasis of fountains and flower beds, a place where Cape Town
residents feel free to lie on the lawns.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer variety of South Africa's flora is mind-boggling. More
than 8,500 species grow on the Cape, a relatively tiny area which
is the smallest by far of the world's six floral kingdoms, but has
the greatest variety of plant species. It is particularly rich in
``fynbos'' _ hardy plants that include the king protea, South
Africa's national flower. The protea is a sturdy, spikey,
sculptural bloom known for its ability to regrow quickly after a
fire _ an appropriate symbol of the new South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest of all South Africa's botanical gardens is
Kirstenbosch, which sprawls at the base of Cape Town's Table
Mountain, the city's symbol. The meandering, asymmetrical design
here is the opposite of the Euclidean borders of Cape Dutch manor
house gardens, although some of Kirstenbosch's ``natural'' rock
formations conceal elaborate drainage systems.
</P>
<P>
   Kirstenbosch was once the property of Cecil John Rhodes, prime
minister of the Cape in the 1890s, who planted a grand allee of
ficus, camphor, and other nonindigenous trees from the farthest
reaches of the British Empire. If you snap a camphor twig in two,
it becomes an instant inhaler to clear your sinuses. (You are not
allowed to break branches off trees, of course, and I didn't. But
my official Kirstenbosch guide did.)
</P>
<P>
   When Rhodes died in 1902, he left Kirstenbosch to the people of
South Africa. Rhodes had imported plants; ironically, his estate
was to become the world's first major botanical garden devoted to
local plants. Part of Kirstenbosch's purpose nowadays is to
convince South Africans who grew up thinking that the English
perennial border was the zenith of the gardener's art to choose
indigenous plants instead, plants able to survive disease and
drought. Heaven knows there are enough of them: Kirstenbosch grows
nearly 6,000 species of southern African plants, with another 900
growing wild.
</P>
<P>
   The garden also has an active program of reintroducing species
threatened by illegal collection in the wild. Cycad-snitchers use
that plant for medicinal purposes or in private gardens: You
actually need a permit to own a cycad in South Africa, and one in
Kirstenbosch has a cage around it, to prevent unscrupulous
collectors from hacking bits of it off.
</P>
<P>
   Kirstenbosch boasts a new state-of-the-art entrance where you
get your first glimpse of the garden's logo _ the fan-like profile
of the bird of paradise. A yellow bird of paradise has been
christened ``Mandela's Gold.'' Part of the entrance is the new
shop, with a world-class selection of garden ornaments and
accessories: palatial birdhouses, plant pedestals clad in rugged
bark, stone sculpture. The urns would be difficult to lug back to
America, but a big Zulu basket can become carry-on luggage, I've
found: You just put everything else inside it.
</P>
<P>
   A glorious new conservatory at Kirstenbosch houses one third of
the world's succulents. Collected from the drier areas of southern
Africa, they couldn't live outside in Cape Town's wet climate. The
conservatory's centerpiece is a century-old, 7-ton baobab tree,
accompanied by a display of ``Things You Can Do With a Baobab''_
including weaving its bark into hats or bags. Here you'll also read
legends including the one that accounts for the baobab's
upside-down appearance. It seems that God gave each animal a tree,
and the hyena, which got the last of them, a baobab, was so upset
he planted it upside down. The baobab is the world's largest
succulent, and hollowed out trunks have been used as stables, pubs,
and a 30-person bus shelter. At the other end of the succulent
spectrum are plants so tiny you might miss them, and plants that
camouflage themselves, blending right in with the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor gardens are divided into specialized sections
including a ``Braille Trail'' for the blind, with a rope to hold
onto and flowers chosen for their fragrance and feel. Another
section is devoted to the plants used by the Khoi people, who
inhabited South Africa long before white settlers arrived. The Khoi
ate some plants and used others as medicine, dyes, teas, and even
bedding. A ``Water Wise Garden,'' just a year old, features
agapanthus, freesias, pelargoniums, aloes, and other plants that
thrive on little water. A free pamphlet on this garden offers a
valuable how-to even for gardeners from northeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   And there's an ``Evolution Garden'' _ wire sculptures of plants
from 200 million years ago _ that gave me ideas about doing the
same in my suburban Boston yard, and the heck with all that unruly
stuff I keep killing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wim Tijmens had a tough time creating a botanical garden for the
Mountain Kingdom of Lesotho. The king's sheep have grazing rights
there, so they eat the plants. And Tijmens had to work around the
location where a sacred circumcision ritual is held.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
