<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPPING VS. STRIPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I plan to take off all the woodwork and doors in my house and
have them dipped, so I can have a natural finish rather than paint
as they are now. Is there anything as far as damage I should be
alerted to?
</P>
<P>
   DIERDRE MANNING, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's an ambitious project, but worth doing instead of
trying to strip them in their place; that is a nightmare. There are
two things you should be alerted to: Do not dip anything that is
glued, because the stripping material will dissolve it. Woodwork is
not glued, and doors are usually not glued, so that shouldn't be a
problem. Secondly, make sure that the dipping process does not turn
the wood gray. You should get that in writing from the dipper. Lyes
and other strippers may turn the wood gray, and while it might be
able to be sanded to reveal new wood, it is a tedious process. If
you varnished the gray wood, it would turn very dark.
</P>
<P>
   If the wood comes out nice and new looking, you can apply two
coats of a satin polyurethane varnish. Use a water-based
polyurethane, which will darken it less than oil-based
polyurethane, but you have to apply it very, very thinly; too thick
a coat of water-based polyurethane can stay cloudy. This is
especially critical for the second coat. If you have qualms about
this, use an oil-based polyurethane; it is less convenient to use
because it will smell longer as it cures, and cleanup is a pain.
</P>
<P>
   If you want the wood a little darker, use a penetrating oil
stain before varnishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My carbon monoxide detectors are showing elevated levels. The
higher levels occur between 9 and 11 a.m. The boiler is 31 years
old, but I don't know how old the oil burner is. The fire chief
suggested servicing the oil burner to make it burn cleaner. I did
that, and made sure the smoke pipe leading to the chimney is sealed
properly and is sound. The carbon monoxide levels are lower, but
still elevated. The oil man said the problem is not the burner but
the car in the attached garage. Could that be possible?
</P>
<P>
   STEVEN EINSTEIN, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sure could, to give a short answer to a long question. In
the morning, when you back the car out of the garage and close the
door, you may be trapping a cerain amount of carbon monoxide,
despite moving the car out quickly. When the burner comes on, it is
pulling air from the garage and anywhere else it can get air that
it needs to burn the oil, and some of that garage air containing
carbon monoxide gets into the house. In the afternoon, when you
drive the car into the garage and shut it off quickly, you may be
producing less carbon monoxide than in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is multifaceted. First, get in the habit of leaving
the garage door open for longer than you have in the past. Second,
open windows in the basement just a tad so the burner can use air
in the basement without pulling air from the garage. Third, since
open windows in the basement can cool it off excessively, provide
the burner with its own outside air. Extend a PVC pipe or any other
kind of duct from a basement window or other opening leading
directly to the burner.
</P>
<P>
   Then check your detectors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting coincidence, relating to Steven Einstein's
problem with carbon monoxide: Betsy Amsel of Melrose, Mass. said
her oil burner man told her that burning oil does not produce
carbon monoxide, and that she does not need a carbon monoxide
detector. ``How can that be?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   How can it be indeed, because it isn't. Any fuel _ solid,
liquid, and gaseous _ produces carbon monoxide when it burns. Some
produce more than others, but all produce some. So, go ahead and
put in one or more detectors, and you will rest easier for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am replacing the ceiling tiles in my bathroom. I found the
flat, smooth, painted tiles you mentioned that are washable (as
opposed to acoustical tiles with holes or fissures), but the people
at Home Depot said the tiles will not hold onto the ceiling in a
damp environment. I am concerned about that because part of the
ceiling is over a tub shower. Will the tiles work in that area, and
more important, will they hold?
</P>
<P>
   ED TAKACH, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing much of anything will stick well on a damp surface,
but you should be able to put up the tiles with adhesive if the
surfaces are dry, because most adhesives for ceiling tiles are
water resistant, and are generally unbothered by moisture. And, if
you are reluctant to use adhesive, you could install 1-by-3-inch
strapping to the ceiling, then staple the new tiles to that
strapping.
</P>
<P>
   And, while you are at it, consider putting in an exhaust fan.
Properly used, this fan will keep the bathroom as dry as it every
will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
