<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING WITHOUT TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago my husband, Jack, and I were looking for
something on TV that would interest us. I saw an ice skating show
and Jack caught sight of the Celtics. Immediately we abandoned our
lofty goal to compromise. We couldn't agree. We wouldn't back down.
``OK, let's just get rid of the TV,'' I exploded. ``Fine with me!''
he replied.
</P>
<P>
   So there we were, with no entertainment but each other.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, I settled down at home alone to watch TV in
secret. No matter which buttons I pushed, there was nothing but
snow on the screen. That's when I realized that without telling me,
Jack had disconnected the wire that led to our rooftop aerial. I
really couldn't blame him. TV used to hold me hostage. I'd choose
to watch one show and hours later, I'd still be compulsively
circling from one dreary channel to another. Jack would have to
break the spell by dragging me away from the set; I would
eventually thank him for rescuing me. It was not a scenario he
enjoyed repeating night after night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I missed TV, especially when Jack was out. Having finally
noticed that I was often home alone, I felt sorry for myself. I was
jealous that he had more places to go than I did. I was low on
energy. I didn't want to go out after dark. I moped a lot.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, however, I noticed how many interesting classes
and programs were offered in our town. I taught a course at our
church. I started sewing again. I finally had time to read for
pleasure. I founded the Marblehead Cancer Prevention Project and
used my time in the evening to make calls. Jack and I often went to
a movie at our local theater or rented videos. We lit a fire and
settled down on the couches in front of the wood stove to read or
play cards. We talked to each other.
</P>
<P>
   My life began to feel more spacious.
</P>
<P>
   And then, one day, I realized I was no longer tired after
dinner. I began to understand that the spell which TV casts begins
before you turn on the set, in that moment when you look inside
yourself and find that you have no energy for anything else. In the
meantime, like a cult, TV has weaned you away from anything else
that might nourish you. It's hard to give it up if you no longer
have faith in your ability to amuse yourself or have come to
believe that it's too much trouble to seek other people out.
Seduced into passivity, you're left with the feeling that TV is
your only true, dependable, and undemanding option.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Jack and I were watching TV in his hospital
room as he recovered from an illness last winter that we actually
experienced how alien sound bites, laugh tracks, constant
commercials, rapidly shifting images, gratuitous violence,
pointless discussions, and stupid jokes are to our nature. Not only
did the general flow of TV images fail to appeal. It actually felt
repellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of what you're missing,'' friends occasionally say to
us, as if with every choice we make, good or bad, we aren't always
ruling out a million alternatives. Our local video store has
Masterpiece Theatre tapes and HBO specials. Jack watches sports at
a friend's house. I listen to books on tape and catch all the news
I can handle on National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I think I'm catching more news than I can handle. I
don't want strangers' voices in my head anymore. Thoreau said,
reflecting on the media in 1845, ``If we read of one man robbed or
murdered, or killed by accident, or one house burned, or one vessel
wrecked, or one steamboat blown up, or one cow run over on the
Western Railroad . . . we need never read of another. One is
enough. If you are acquainted with the principle, what do you care
for a myriad instances?'' How many more opinons about impeachment
can I absorb before my head explodes?
</P>
<P>
   I want to lower my daily dose of global input, to replace my
second-hand opinions about far-flung events and concentrate on the
life around me. For too long I've treated my mind like an empty
container, filling it with expert opinions and lurid stories about
celebrities, as if keeping attuned to this flow of information was
to my benefit. Now I want to see why I feel so uneasy with silence.
</P>
<P>
   My father always said, ``Take one step and if it feels good,
you'll know you're heading in the right direction.'' I'll still
turn to NPR in the morning, but I've already started listening to
music while I'm making dinner in the afternoon. If the world comes
to an end, I'm sure someone will call and tell me. A lifelong media
junkie, I never expected to find myself walking away from the
myriad distractions this culture offers, but it's time to find out
what happens in my soul when I can hear myself think.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
