<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL ODDS GET EVEN ODDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year millions of fans bet on the Super Bowl. It's the
biggest betting day of the year in Las Vegas, where gambling on
football is legal. No one knows exactly how much is wagered
illegally on the game, but conservative estimates are in the
neighborhood of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There's so much ``action'' that the betting propositions have
gone far beyond a simple win or loss. This year bettors can wager
on dozens of propositions, some of them odd, to put it mildly. For
example: Will Denver Broncos wide receiver Rod Smith catch more
passes against the Falcons than Bruins' Ray Bourque scores goals
against Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   If there's money to be made, why not consider some additional
propositions?
</P>
<P>
   Number of times broadcasters will invoke the name of Vince
Lombardi during the first quarter: Over/under 5.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will be called in to mediate peace talks
between Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves and Denver Broncos coach
Mike Shanahan: 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   The referee will call the coin toss correctly: Even.
</P>
<P>
   Number of fans at Pro Player Stadium in Miami who will fill the
Durex Extra Sensitive condoms they find in their game gift packs
with beer and toss them on the field: Over/under 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart will appear on the pregame show to demonstrate
how to throw a perfect Super Bowl party: 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   Martha's perfect Super Bowl party will involve microwaved
enchiladas: 4,000-1.
</P>
<P>
   The winning quarterback will say he's going to Disneyland: 1-99.
</P>
<P>
   The losing quarterback will be going to the Foxy Lady: 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Bumpers will be summoned to give a halftime pep talk to the
Falcons: 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Number of fans at Pro Player Stadium injured while trying to do
a tsunami ``wave'': Over/under 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Which contains more cubic feet of hot air: The Goodyear Blimp,
2-1; Pat Summerall, 5-2; John Madden, 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan will announce at halftime that he quit basketball
in order to become an NFL quarterback: 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   A telemarketer from Viagra-is-Us will call your house during the
game: Even.
</P>
<P>
   The special Super Bowl version of the Falcons' Dirty Bird dance
will be so nasty they won't show it on TV: 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Total number of Cher's tattoos visible when she sings the
national anthem: Over/under 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will move to Hartford: 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will move to Atlanta: 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   Number of close-up shots of Fox network stars in the stands:
Over/under 35.
</P>
<P>
   Number of Fox network stars anybody will actually recognize:
Over/under 1.
</P>
<P>
   The winning quarterback will say that God is on his team's side:
1-5.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will say he feels the losing team's pain: 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   National consumption of tortilla chips during the game:
Over/under 10 million pounds. (Hint: Last year's total was 8.1
million.)
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of guests passed out by halftime at your Super Bowl
party: 40 percent, 5-2; 70 percent, 2-1; 90 percent, 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials will exceed playing time: 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky will testify at halftime: 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez will trounce Dolly Parton at halftime on MTV's
Celebrity Deathmatch Deathbowl '99: 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Jumbotron will explode: 99-1.
</P>
<P>
   A bad call will decide the outcome of the game: Even.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SOUTHERN-2ND &LR;  &UR;      01-28 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SOUTHERN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAPE TOWN, South Africa: ... is held.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the names of the rare species he cultivates at the
University of Stellenbosch, Tijmens's rather daunting title is in
Latin: He's Praefectus Horti, Hortus Botanicus. What this boils
down to is that he runs what he calls an ``outdoor laboratory''
filled with plants, including many extremely rare ones. While
Kirstenbosch cultivates South Africa's indigenous plants, Tijmens
brings plants from all over the world to South Africa. He also
lures gardeners from all over: They come to see a world's worth of
species in one place. And he leads tours, to the ``Impressionist''
gardens of France and the Silk Road in China, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   He's particularly proud of a Welwitschia mirabilis, his rarest
plant of all, from the Namibian desert. A stump of the plant has
been carbon dated to over a thousand years old. ``It grew in a
place where there is no rain,'' Tijmens says in an awed tone. He's
also pleased with his Pelargonium collections, which have lured
some visitors he doesn't want to attract: A perfume manufacturer
stole a cutting recently. He's working on breeding a yellow
geranium, and grumbles about the possibility of someone secretly
snipping off some of it.
</P>
<P>
   He's a zealot. ``We'll do anything to teach people about
plants,'' he says. ``We link students from all disciplines with
plants.'' He even organizes exhibitions of plant art _ a show of
Chinese paintings of flowers during my visit. He's so ardent about
plants that he trails after me as I leave his garden, talking all
the while, as we pass by yellow camellias from China, ginkgos from
Japan, and California redwoods. When he stops at the garden's edge,
though, he's surrounded by one of the most beautiful of South
African trees _ the blue jacaranda. When in bloom, it is the South
African equivalent of cherry blossoms in Japan _ an event. On the
day I talked to Tijmens, the jacarandas were shedding their
startlingly lovely lavendar blossoms onto the grass below, creating
an opulent tapestry of color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alison Soanes was an out-of-work personnel manager with a
fondness for flowers when she took a humble job at the least humble
hotel in South Africa _ Cape Town's legendary Mt. Nelson. She began
by washing out vases, but soon graduated to the post she's held the
last five years, that of head florist. Responsible for all the
flowers in a hotel that is an outpost of the British Empire,
stylistically speaking, she designs the kind of extremely full
arrangements you might encounter in a great British country house.
</P>
<P>
   She's also been innovative, incorporating vegetables, fabrics,
fruits, sheaves of wheat sparkling with silver stars, locally made
crafts, or even toys into the flower arrangements she creates for
the hotel and for private clients.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen of Denmark had one of Soanes's vast arrangements of
proteas wrapped up in brown paper, to take home on the plane.
Princess Michael of Kent had a bed of Mt. Nelson agapanthus dug up,
to take back to England.
</P>
<P>
   Soanes spends far more time with disadvantaged people than with
European royalty, though. A missionary preaching a gospel of flower
power, she's instituted an apprenticeship program for uneducated
hotel workers stuck in the most menial of jobs. She takes them to
restaurants, museums, and theaters where they couldn't have gone in
the Apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a florist, you have to understand music, architecture,
and poetry,'' she says. ``Floral design is about composition and
color.'' It's also about the designer's own life, so she starts by
having her students make flower arrangements that represent their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry about the `Rainbow Nation' is that it will all
blend,'' she says. She tries to get her students to cherish their
differences of style. The Cape Malay community, for instance, loves
vivid color, and paint their houses bright blue, yellow, and red.
``They even spray-paint their flowers,'' Soanes says approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   She's organized flower-arranging classes for children and made
her workshops a movable feast, taking them to impoverished areas. A
Soanes student has opened a florist's shop in a township, one of
the sprawling shanty towns that ring Cape Town. ``You have to have
beauty around you to keep your dignity,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She's also a champion of local plants. ``Plants we'd think
boring fascinate outsiders,'' she says. ``We've been very British
in our gardening. That's changing. We're now using indigenous bulbs
that people used to ignore or slight.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Mt. Nelson has lost its colonial ambience, indoors
or out. To celebrate its centennial this year, the grande dame is
introducing a new rose, imported three years ago from American
breeders Jackson and Perkins and nurtured by South Africa's biggest
commercial nursery, Malanseuns Pleasure Plants of Pretoria.
Initially identified only as BC 89 009934, it has been rechristened
``The Mount Nelson Rose,'' and, yes, the frilly bloom is pink with
white highlights, to match the colors of the hotel's famous facade.
Strolling through the hotel grounds, Soanes stops to sniff a Mt.
Nelson Rose _ and sneeze. ``I have the most terrible hay fever,''
she confesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(SIDEBAR) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Scholtz has been leading garden and wildflower tours
to her native South Africa for more than three decades _ not very
often at first, for political reasons. ``I was told I was
supporting a white supremacist regime,'' she says. ``But plants and
gardens don't have anything to do with politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholtz, director emeritus of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, has
increased the frequency of her tours in the post-Apartheid era.
She's going annually now, usually in September, which is autumn for
us but spring in South Africa _ and peak wildflower season. Her
tours visit Kirstenbosch and other botanical gardens, as well as
private gardens and wildflower fields. She includes a stay at one
of the luxurious private game reserves for which South Africa is
rightly famous, and she chooses first-rate hotels. The tours last
about 2 1/2 weeks and have cost around $6,000, including airfare.
</P>
<P>
   Dates for the tour are Sept. 12-27; the exact itinerary is still
in the works. For information, contact Elizabeth Scholtz at the
Brooklyn Botanic Garden, 1000 Washington Ave., Brooklyn, NY
11225-1099. Telephone 718-622-4433, extension 251; fax:
718-857-2430.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
