<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE SURE YOU UNFREEZE YOUR PIPES, AND KEEP THEM THAT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It ain't ever gonna freeze this winter, it seems, so I wonder if
the tulips will bloom nicely this spring. Those bulbs, you know,
need a period of freezing before they bloom.
</P>
<P>
   There's no sense worrying about that, though, because there is
nothing you can do about it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Well, then I guess I don't have to worry about freezing pipes
this winter because they won't freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   There is still plenty of winter left, and Mother Nature has a
habit of hitting with all she's got at us at unseasonal times of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   So it's time to worry about freezing pipes, and to do something
about them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thawing them out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, what to do when they do freeze? Sometimes, if water
freezes in a straight run of pipe, you won't get a leak or a burst,
so you can just wait for it to thaw out.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, a freeze will occur at a bend in the pipe,
increasing the chance of a burst or leak. You might not get a leak
as long as the water stays frozen, but once it thaws, watch out!
And, if water freezes in a heating pipe, you really have to do
something, and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   First locate where the freeze is, and turn on the faucet served
by the pipe. Second, apply heat to it. When thawing out a frozen
pipe, apply the heat nearest to the faucet, so that the melted
water can flow out the faucet. If the pipe is thawed out further
from the faucet, you could get serious pressure problems caused by
solid ice turning to steam.
</P>
<P>
   If the pipe is exposed, usually in the basement, where most
freezing occurs, wrap heavy towels around the pipe and pour hot
water on the towels. Move the process down a little and pour on
more hot water. Melted water will flow from the open faucet,
signaling success.
</P>
<P>
   Another heat source is a putty torch, a small electric coil
designed to soften window glazing putty. But don't put it directly
on the pipe. Intense heat turns the ice to steam, which has enough
pressure to burst the pipe. Hold it a few inches away from the
pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Hot air will help, but do not use a hot- air gun (too hot); a
hair dryer will do, but you also might burn it out with prolonged
use.
</P>
<P>
   Or, hang a 100-watt trouble light (an extension cord with a bulb
in a cage) on the pipe. Use the cage to keep the hot bulb from
direct contact with the pipe, or just hang it on the pipe. This is
a slow process, but it also is a good way to keep the pipe from
freezing in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If the pipe is not visible, hidden in a wall, set up a
floodlight with a good reflector, or any large-wattage bulb to aim
at the wall. This technique is slow but steady.
</P>
<P>
   If you thaw out a pipe that has burst or has a leak, be sure to
shut off the water after the thaw. Then make repairs, or call your
favorite plumber.
</P>
<P>
   OK, those are the things you can do in an amergency to get you
back in business. But you're not through yet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Insuring for the future &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now your priority is to make sure the same pipes, or any others,
don't freeze in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Most pipes are in the basement, and are unlikely to freeze
because even in an unheated house, the temperature in a closed
basement rarely gets below 40 degrees Fahrenheit in winter.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes pipes go perilously close to a concrete or stone
foundation. This masonry is a cold sink (the opposite of a heat
sink), getting as cold as it is outdoors. As a result, the nearby
pipes freeze.
</P>
<P>
   A quick solution is to provide those pipes with a permanent or
at least a winter-long heat source. A trouble light with a 100-watt
bulb hung on the pipe will keep it from freezing. Use one or more.
It's a rather expensive way to do it, but it is better _ and
cheaper _ than trying to heat the whole basement.
</P>
<P>
   A permanent solution is to relocate the pipes two feet or more
from any large amounts of masonry.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't move the pipes easily, insulate them. For water
pipes, use the foam- type tubes that wrap lengthwise around the
pipes. They can be cut to turn corners, too. Be sure to cover every
trace of pipe, and cover all joints with duct tape. Do vertical
joints, where the tubes butt each other end to end, and horizontal
joints, where the tube is slit lengthwise. Be sure to buy the
right-sized tube to fit the pipe snugly.
</P>
<P>
   Where pipes go through a very cold crawl space, it might be wise
to use a special compressed fiberglass insualtion tube, which gives
much more insulation. It is sold at plumbing supply shops.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your pipes are not subject to freezing, it's a good idea
to insulate them: The water in an insulated hot-water pipe will not
cool off as fast, saving you water- heating costs. And insulation
on all pipes will help prevent condensation on them in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the good old days, most water pipes were exposed. Most of us
over a certain delicate age can remember the water pipes _ and
steam and hot-water pipes _ going up the wall and exposed for all
to see. But they didnt freeze, did they?
</P>
<P>
   Then builders started putting the pipes in walls, not paying
attention to where they are located.
</P>
<P>
   When pipes tend to freeze in the wall cavity, keeping them from
doing so is difficult. If they are in an uninsulated cavity, blow
insulation in that cavity, and of course all others, which will
save you heating costs.
</P>
<P>
   If the pipe is nearer the outside wall than the inside wall,
then insulating the cavity might not work; if the pipe is near the
outside wall in an insulated cavity, this won't help much, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you will have to open up the cavity to see just what
is there. You can move the pipe to the inside wall and insulate the
cavity. This is a lot of work but it cannot be helped. At least you
will be virtually guaranteed that those particular pipes will not
freeze.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. Until you are able to take down the wall surface
covering a suspected freezing pipe, you can try this: Cut a hole in
the cavity at the top and bottom; put a decorative grille over
them. Warm air from the house will circulate in that cavity,
insulated or not. There will be some, but not a lot, of heat loss,
and your pipes will not freeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
