<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS LOOK AT SUPER BOWL AS A WINNING FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 31)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Super Bowl may be the only show on television where people
leave the room during the program, but make sure they are back by
the time commercials come on.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperbole? Not by much. Super Bowls can be blowouts, and the
plays and games quickly become clouded memories. But it is the ads,
which cost as much for 30 seconds as the average person will make
in 60 or so years, that linger long after we have forgotten the
names of the games' most valuable players.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the conversation at the office Monday: Will it be
more about Atlanta's run defense and Denver's ground game, or the
TV ads? Could you blow $1.6 million, which is what advertisers pay
for a half-minute Super Bowl spot, in 30 seconds? Tick ... 40 BMW
Roadsters ... tick ... 80,200 copies of any CD from K-tel (plus
postage and handling) ... tick ... 22,857 Juiceman juicers.
</P>
<P>
   If you got in on the ground floor in the first bowl (which
wasn't even called the Super Bowl) in 1967, a 30-second spot would
have cost $42,000. But no matter how you look at it, buying a Super
Bowl spot is a crapshoot for advertisers. Sometimes the money is a
waste, especially in the second half of a one-sided game, or if the
commercial is not good enough to rise above the pack. The ones that
stick out do earn their money. And are able to burn their way into
America's cultural conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Apple's ``1984'' ad in, appropriately, 1984. The
brilliantly stark spot presented an Orwellian vision of an
IBM-dominated world, and not only predicted the personal computer
boom but also set the Super Bowl as the ultimate advertising stage.
</P>
<P>
   As far as more recent commercials go, the front-runners include
the nation's foremost pitchman, Michael Jordan. Jordan scored
back-to-back hits in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Nike's ``Hare Jordan,'' a duet with screen legend Bugs
Bunny, not only helped sneaker sales but spawned the movie ``Space
Jam.'' The next year, Jordan teamed up with old court nemesis Larry
Bird in the funniest game of Horse ever seen in McDonald's
``Showdown.'' The spot added the phrase, ``Nothing but net'' to the
nation's vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the two most memorable commercials were Budweiser's
unveiling of the lizards vs. the frogs, and McIlhenny Tabasco's
Pepper Sauce mosquito ad (which actually debuted in 1997).
Tabasco's clever ad featured a mosquito that quickly vaporized
after biting a man who had just ingested Tabasco. It did wonders
for the small company.
</P>
<P>
   This year, that's what Hotjobs.com is counting on. The small
Internet company is going against its largest competitor,
Monster.com, in a high-stakes, first-of-its-kind shootout between
two on-line job-recruiting outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never would have expected the Super Bowl to turn into a
battle ground for Internet job sites,'' Hotjobs spokesman Robert
Liu said. ``For beer? For cola? Sure. We didn't want that to
happen. We tried to ask for exclusivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing doing. But the company expected to post $4 million in
sales this year is staking half that amount, including production
costs, on one 30-second blip in time. And the commercial to be
aired see Sunday wasn't even its first choice. An earlier version
was considered too risque by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Too risque by Fox? Funny, I don't think that phrase has ever
been used before in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   Liu hopes the Hotjobs' spot kicks the snot out of Monster, but
it doesn't matter. Since the little New York-based company
announced late last year it was buying a Super spot, the number of
resumes added to its system doubled. ``We caught a lucky star
there,'' Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what a lot of advertisers are hoping for on Super
Bowl Sunday, a little luck bought with a bucket of cash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a roster of many of the advertisers during the Super
Bowl, according to SuperBowlSpot.com:
</P>
<P>
   American Express Co.; American Honda Motor Co.; Anheuser-Busch;
Apple Computer; AT&AMP;T Corp.; Blockbuster Video; Dr. Pepper/Seven Up
Co.; Federal Express Corp.; First Union Corp.; and Frito-Lay.
</P>
<P>
   Also, General Motors Corp., Oldsmobile; General Motors Corp.,
Cadillac. Hartford Group; Hotjobs.com; Intel Corp.; Just for Feet;
Land Rover of North America; Mail Boxes Etc.; MasterCard
International; MGM; M&AMP;M/Mars; Monster.com; New Line Cinema;
Pepsi-Cola Co.; Pizza Hut; Progressive Insurance; WWF; Universal
Studios; Visa; Volvo Truck North America; Warner Bros.; and Yellow
Pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
