<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING A FATHER TO THE CULTURAL REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THIRTY YEARS IN A RED HOUSE 
A Memoir of Childhood and Youth in Communist China 
By Zhu Xiao Di 
University of Massachusetts Press, 255 pp., illustrated, $34.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A host of Chinese have written memoirs of growing up absurd
during the Cultural Revolution, the decade-long crusade against all
things traditional and material that preoccupied China from 1966 to
1976, and many of those efforts are splendid both for their
humanity and for their factual content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Swans,'' ``Born Red,'' ``Son of the Revolution,'' and
other volumes chronicle the experiences of people caught up in a
closed society in which truth, reality, and individual fates
changed radically, whimsically, from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Given the magnitude of this disastrous crusade, and the
importance to the rest of the world of having some grasp of how
China works, additions to the genre are still in order. But enough
has been written so that new offerings now should do more than
retell a gripping, but oft-told, tale of personal suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Xiao Di rises admirably to this challenge in his ``Thirty
Years in a Red House.'' The book starts out as a personal memoir,
but swiftly shifts to an affectionate biography of Zhu's father,
spanning not just the three decades of the author's life but most
of China's revolutionary and Communist history.
</P>
<P>
   This serves two important purposes: It places the Cultural
Revolution in solid historical context without requiring the reader
to digest a huge volume, and it opens a window on the thinking of
an important, little-heard-from generation of Chinese _ people who
matured in the years between the Cultural Revolution and the
Tiananmen Square massacre of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Qiluan, the author's father, was a deeply committed
communist from early on. He joined the Communist Youth League in
1932, recruited his brothers and sister, and helped organize the
historic December 9 Movement, the 1935 Beijing demonstration that
inspired generations of Chinese students. He worked underground
during the climactic years of the revolution, constantly putting
his life at risk, and when victory was won was rewarded with
responsible positions in the new order.
</P>
<P>
   Idealistic but also politically savvy and sure-footed, he
avoided the first waves of ideological excess. Then, in 1968, when
his son was 10 and the Cultural Revolution was two, he and his
wife, who was also committed and idealistic, were swept under.
Their mental and physical sufferings as suspected enemies of the
people were typical: They lost their jobs and their home, and were
confined in separate detention camps.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Zhus were cleared, and when Zhu Qiluan died, a
statue was erected in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ghastly, but not unusual, cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Similar woes, and much worse, befell uncounted people both below
the Zhus in rank and at the highest levels of Chinese Communist
society, before as well as during the Cultural Revolution. From the
courageous revolutionary General Peng Dehuai, who opposed Mao
Zedong's extremism early on, to the tenacious Deng Xiaoping, who
came back from all the purges to take supreme power and commit his
own awful excesses, almost everyone was eventually politically
rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   It is extraordinary to follow Zhu Xiao Di through his teen years
and his 20s as he watches his father cope. Without ever seeming to
try, his book convinces you that tens of thousands of other bright,
ambitious young boys saw similar things, and now are thinking
similar thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the narrative reaches the crackdowns of 1986 and
1989, the unavoidable conclusion is that the Communist Party, at
least in its incarnation as the sole wielder of power in the
Chinese state, is finished. Its problems are too big, its members
too corrupt, its constituents too cynical. Zhu's generation places
neither hope nor faith in it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no explicit advice here for Americans who have worried,
for good reason, as US policy toward China has fluctuated wildly
between appeasement and confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   But an implicit message seems clear when Zhu, as a newly minted
English professor at Nanjing Teachers' University, takes up
Hamlet's ``to be, or not to be'' soliloquy with his students. At
first, the students are tempted to say it is nobler ``to take arms
against a sea of troubles, and by opposing end them.'' That is the
answer their indoctrination dictates. But they quickly become
confused, and fall silent, when he presses on.
</P>
<P>
   What is nobler, he asks his students and himself: Open public
dissent that is sure to draw the slings and arrows of the
threatened Party, or remaining painfully silent on forbidden
subjects while encouraging freer thinking wherever possible?
</P>
<P>
   The students, and Zhu himself, cannot readily answer, for some
of the people they most admire fall into one group, and some into
the other. No matter. The orthodoxy that once would have dictated a
single, firm answer and forbidden all others is dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
