<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLOWS TAKES ON THE POWERS THAT GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the ``hardening-of-the-arteries'' theory of journalistic
malfeasance. Writing in the upcoming issue of the American Prospect
magazine, noted press critic Jim Fallows finds a unique way to lash
out at the media oligarchy he disdains. He reveals their ages.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his article examining journalistic sins in
``Monicagate,'' Fallows _ a former U.S. News &AMP; World Report editor
now toiling for Microsoft _ hits upon his controversial ``Geriatric
Punditariat'' theory. Basically, he claims that the ``people who
have set the media tone during the Monica era'' are too old, a
``complacent establishment . . . less fascinated by testing,
improving and expanding the possibilities of its craft than in . .
. exercising the power it enjoys.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a nasty little twist, he provides the ages _ as of the
end of 1999 _ of media stars ranging from Sam Donaldson (65) to
Cokie Roberts (56), from John McLaughlin (72) to Maureen Dowd (47).
(Under that formula, the average age of a Fallows bigfoot is a ripe
61.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of them are not particularly impressed by the geriatric
theory. When asked if Fallows's idea had merit, Washington Post
columnist David Broder (70) said simply: ``Not a lot.'' A spokesman
for Cokie Roberts declined comment, saying Fallows ``has a long
history of being overly, aggressively critical.'' Wall Street
Journal editor Robert Bartley (62) said, ``I guess Jim Fallows
still has his nose out of joint because we ridiculed his argument
that Japan was going to take over the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You desperately need someone who's a bomb thrower and who's
generally wrong to make things interesting,'' responded PBS talk
host Charlie Rose (57). Newsweek's Howard Fineman (51) was blunter.
``I don't need a Washington blowhard like Jim Fallows to lecture
me,'' he declared before tempering his language. ``He's like Cotton
Mather,'' he added. ``He provides a useful service.''
</P>
<P>
   The antipathy between Fallows and the press corps boiled over
with the 1996 publication of his assault on Washington journalism,
a book titled ``Breaking the News: How the Media Undermine American
Democracy.'' Thus, there was more than a little glee emanating from
some quarters when Fallows was fired as editor of U.S. News last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   And some sharp-eyed observers may detect a note of revenge in
the makeup of his list of aging pundits. Included are such Fallows
critics as Dowd, who has sarcastically called him ``the Rector of
American Journalism''; Times editorial page editor Howell Raines
(56), who called him a ``fount of dangerous nonsense''; and
Fineman, who attacked Fallows's book on CNN's ``The Capital Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not really my motive,'' insisted Fallows (50), when
asked if the ``Geriatric Punditariat'' was a way of getting even.
``The press establishment'' converging on this White House scandal,
he adds, consists ``largely of the same people in the big media
establishment'' who were around for Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Then an unrepentant Fallows twisted the knife a final time ``I'm
still younger than most members of the Punditariat,'' he says,
``but I'm older than everybody here at Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the old TV commercial explaining how we would all take
more pride in our work if we signed our name to it? Well, Colorado
Springs Gazette editor Steven Smith is testing that theory. Since
November, the Gazette (circulation 99,500) has been running stories
featuring not just the reporter's byline, but the names of the
headline writer and story editor as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tired and bored with things,'' says Smith, explaining
the impetus for the experiment. And the idea has already expanded
past its original parameters, with the Gazette now crediting some
page designers and considering giving a byline to photo
caption-writers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Smith admits there is no hard evidence that all this has
improved the quality of the paper. But ``what we've been able to do
is (create) more accountability internally. . . . Their sense of
ownership and pride in their work has been notably improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also reports that readers have begun calling story editors
to discuss published articles _ a development that could be
welcomed or dreaded, depending on your perspective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is Internet use dumbing down as a second wave of less affluent,
less educated citizens go on line? Yes, says a new Pew Research
Center poll indicating that as users grow more mainstream,
``Internet news interests are changing markedly.'' (Two years ago,
the most popular Internet news draw was technology stories. Now,
weather is the most popular category.)
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey of nearly 3,200 adults, veteran Internet
surfers are more likely to seek out news about technology,
business, international events, and politics than those who came on
line within the past year. The new users' favored categories are
entertainment (57 percent) and weather (56 percent). One reason
suggested by the Pew researchers is that the new cybersurfers are
decidedly less elite. Only 29 percent of those who started using
the Internet in the past year are college grads and a plurality has
household incomes of less than $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The question for Internet content providers is whether news
priorities will be permanently changed by the influx of
``ordinary'' citizens or whether their tastes will grow more
refined the longer they are on line. Pew Research director Kimberly
Parker opts for the latter, noting that new users ``from lower down
in the socioeconomic spectrum . . . don't bring the same news
interests as the sophisticated old users.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
