<HEADLINE>
LET THE DIPS WIN ON SUPER BOWL SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first commandment for hosting a Super Bowl party is one
worth memorizing: Keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is not an occasion for spending hours in the kitchen
putting together tasty dishes that will wow your friends. Quite the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   An event dominated by a football game on television cries out
for snacks and only snacks. And what is more appropriate than dips,
an hor d'oeuvre staple, for this truly American celebration?
</P>
<P>
   Quick and easy to prepare, dips are some of the most versatile
foods. Endless flavor combinations are possible. Be creative. Let
your imagination inspire you.
</P>
<P>
   The most common bases for dips are sour cream, yogurt, soft
cheese, mayonnaise, cream cheese or creme fraiche (thickened,
slightly soured cream). High fat content is not required, though.
Use reduced-fat versions for any dairy base to lower the fat
content of your dip, or make vegetable or bean-based dips instead.
</P>
<P>
   With a minimal amount of planning, you can offer a variety of
zesty dips to accompany an assortment of cut-up raw vegetables,
crackers, assorted breads, chips or cubes of cheese or meat.
</P>
<P>
   While the normal rule of thumb is one cup of dip serves four
people, for a Super Bowl shindig it's a good idea to double up.
Plan on one cup for every two people. Remember, the game lasts at
least three hours and folks will turn to the snacks time and again.
</P>
<P>
   A good tip for keeping cold dips chilled is to set them in bowls
of ice. Hot dips will stay warm in a crock pot. If you don't have a
slow cooker, be sure to serve them in a container you pop into the
microwave.
</P>
<P>
   If dips aren't fancy enough for your guests, it's easy to
present them in ways that would impress even Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Try hollowing out large round loaves of bread and serving the
dip in them, with the cut-up bread as an accompaniment. Another
attractive way to serve dips is in vegetable ``containers'' such as
bell peppers, pineapples or cabbage leaves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
