<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CRAZY-BOS &LR;      01-28 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CRAZY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFECTION IS AT THE HEART OF `CRAZY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you first spot the members of the fictional British band
Strange Fruit in the film ``Still Crazy,'' you may be thinking this
is not a particularly likable group of fellows: too much ego, maybe
not that much talent, long in the tooth. The movie's director,
Brian Gibson, cuts to the chase: ``They were decadent, decayed,
self-indulgent, and a miserable lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Is another ``This Is Spinal Tap'' about to be sprung?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no. ``Still Crazy,'' though a comedy and hardly
averse to pointing up the foibles and emotional fragility of its
``rock stars,'' isn't played at the satirical high pitch of
``Spinal Tap.'' The guys in the band _ singer Ray (Billy Nighy),
bassist Les (Jimmy Nail), keyboardist Tony (Stephen Rea), and
drummer Beano (Timothy Spall) _ turn out to be charming in spite of
their rough edges and ill-conceived notions. Hughie, their roadie,
played by Scottish comedian-actor Billy Connolly, is an even more
lovable rogue. The film opened to generally positive reviews last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are rock 'n' roll archetypes,'' says Gibson, ``but have
enough individuality to exist as characters. There's the
narcissistic lead singer, the self-destructive muse type, the
raucous drummer. . . . Hopefully, they're well enough written and
well enough played that there's flesh on the bone.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot is uncomplicated. The long-defunct band, having moved
on to dodgy real-life pursuits, is urged to re-form by a young
promoter. They track down one another and attempt the rickety
business of reconstructing both the friendships and the passions of
their youth. They also try to locate their missing or dead band
leader, the mysterious guitarist Brian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll tales are usually limited,'' says Gibson. ``In
really crude terms, it's like a Mickey Rooney movie: `We're gonna
get together and make some noise and some music. Are we gonna
succeed? Are we gonna fail?' Those are the parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   The story _ penned by ``The Commitments'' writers Dick Clement
and Ian La Frenais _ may be basic, but the satisfaction comes in
the knowing details. Nighy, as the frontman Ray, is recovering from
substance abuse, broke and jittery but still living in his mansion.
He projects both the arrogance of fame and sheer terror of going
about daily life. In one scene at a recording studio, a delivery
boy brings pizza and asks Ray to sign for it. Ray asks whom he
wants the autograph made out to. Uh . . . Ray, hello?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky with the script,'' says Nighy, ``because the
writers not only write some of the best gags in town, but they
support you completely in the way they develop the characters. We
all kind of helped each other along naturally. But it was not
improvised at all, which is a compliment, really, to the writing.''
(The film was nominated for a Golden Globe Award for best motion
picture comedy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``At my time of life,'' says Nighy, 49, ``it's an unlikely
prospect to be asked to do this,'' that is, sing. ``And for him,
for Ray, he had a period of intense celebrity a long time ago. To
persuade yourself that it still works, it was some jump for me.
With the help of his wife he's sustained the illusion that his
celebrity still continues. If he goes down to the shops, which I
don't suppose he does, he probably still wears shades for fear of
being mobbed. And the terrible truth is nobody remembers who he is,
which is obviously rich pickings for comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Role model as a singer: ex-Bad Company/Free singer Paul Rodgers.
Nighy says: ``I didn't believe I could sing like him. But I can
hold a mike stand like him.'' Nighy actually sings in the film _
the other actors had musicians play their parts _ though he says
his background is limited ``to singing around the house and I have
a daughter who has banned me from doing that because she finds it
so intensely embarrassing. Any more Van Morrison or Bob Dylan and
she'll leave home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' was made for $11 million _ ``by Hollywood
standards, a postage stamp,'' says Jimmy Nail. He adds that
everyone involved had ``a great awareness that we didn't want to go
near the `Spinal Tap' scenario, one of the reasons being that I
didn't think you could do that any better than what Rob Reiner did.
. . . What we all tried to do was create characters that an
audience could care about, their individual and collective journey.
I think you win a little battle. The hardest thing you can do is
introduce characters and get the audience to care for them in the
space of 90 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson knows his way around rock 'n' roll movies, having done
two of the better ones, the Tina Turner bio-pic ``What's Love Got
to Do With It,'' and the fictional ``Breaking Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of research,'' says Gibson. ``Either deliberately
or unconsciously in previous areas of our lives. The script is
beautifully written, but it does read like a comedy script and I
didn't want it to be `OK, here comes the gag.' I wanted it to have
an authentic edge, so the performance and the casting, the
lighting, the way the scenes are blocked are designed to make you
feel that you're watching reality first and a comedy second. The
camera will pan around, slightly out of focus, it does this and
that. But it is all contrived, very carefully cued and worded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' gets the music right too. It's semi-hooky hard
rock, but dated. Much of it is penned by Mick Jones (from
Foreigner) and Chris Difford (from Squeeze). ``The Flame Still
Burns,'' which earned a Golden Globe nomination for best sound,
does seem cut from Foreigner cloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask people to buy into the fact that this was a
big song, and just the very fact that they don't know this song
(makes that) immensely difficult to do,'' says Nail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely cliches built into some of the lyrics,
combined with some good lines,'' says Gibson. ``So you do feel,
yeah, they probably were top of the '70s B-list. They're not a
transcendent rock band. To begin with, the mandate with the writers
we were working with was to make them deliberately not very good,
and I said, `No, what we should do is aim to make them as good as
we possibly can and then pull back if they're too good.' `All Over
the World' and `The Flame Still Burns' are pretty good songs, but
there are certain words that are very '70s words. We used
`tapestry' a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly serves as the sometime narrator, framing the picture.
The decision to do that came late in the process, says Gibson. ``I
realized that in my view the film was a little bit soft at the end,
and at the beginning a bit earnest, so I felt having Billy frame
the movie would help pull the audience in to the right attitude, to
make you feel right from the beginning this was an impertinent,
silly group of people and here is a cautionary tale if you like.
It's a bunch of clowns who never quite learn from their
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Having staged a comeback, will Strange Fruit continue via a
sequel? ``If it does as well as we hope, there's always a threat,''
says Gibson, with a laugh. ``I don't think I'd direct it, you know,
having done it, but I'd love to go and see it because I'd be
curious about what they'd do next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
