<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BEER SEEKS BREW TO REVITALIZE COMPANY'S VALUE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Koch would throw a fit if his beer was as flat as his
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Beer Co., maker of the famous Sam Adams beers and
ales, is in a serious funk along with the rest of the upscale craft
brewing industry. Sales that boomed through most of the 1990s
suddenly hit a wall and haven't budged for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Beer shares, which went public at 20 in 1996, were worth
less than half that Wednesday, closing at 9 1/2. The only recent
excitement in the stock occurred two weeks ago when a rumor,
apparently started on an Internet site, speculated about a takeover
by beer giant Anheuser-Busch Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, Boston Beer's founder and chief executive, cringes if you
use the word flat to describe his business, but won't dispute the
need to rejuvenate the sagging public value of his company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As by far the largest shareholder who has almost all his net
worth tied up in the company, I probably have the biggest stake in
increasing the value of the company,'' said Koch, whose 5.6 million
Boston Beer shares are worth about $53 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston Beer has taken no disasterous wrong turns or missed
any great opportunities on the way to this predicament. It is stuck
in a consumer category that lost some of its cache and may be
fighting an uphill demographic battle.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Beer went public with a wave of other craft brewers in
late 1995 and 1996, at the time Wall Street's most popular
speciality stock offerings. They started off hot and then turned
out to be investment disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Redhook Ale Brewery Inc. went public in August 1995 at 17 and
shot up to 34 3/4. It traded at 5 3/4 Wednesday. Pete's Brewing Co.
launched an IPO at 18, three months after Redhook, and quickly
traded to 25. It was acquired last summer by Gambrinus Co. for 6
3/8 a share, just better than a third of its IPO price. Pyramid
Breweries Inc. was known as Hart Brewing Inc. when it went public
at 19 the summer of 1996. It finished Wednesday at 1 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? On the shelves, success spawned many more craft
brewers. Some of them tasted terrible. Eventually people lost
interest in craft brew experimentation and went on to something
else, often high-end imports with familiar names like Heineken and
Corona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imports stole their thunder,'' said Benj Steinman, editor of
Beer Marketer's Insights, an industry newsletter. ``The core user
base was never that large. So once they weren't expanding the
experimental customer base it was tough to grow. A lot of their
growth had come from trial customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Beer owns a commanding 21 percent market share of the
craft beer business, far ahead of number two Pete's. But Koch's
strategy has tried to extract Boston Beer's products out of that
category in the minds of his distributors and customers.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about a ``better beer'' segment that includes the best
of the craft beers and the popular imports, creating distance
between Sam Adams and the more obscure craft names. This is how the
customer really thinks, Koch contends, and it would align Sam Adams
with a growing beer segement again.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: it may be easy for Boston Beer to outmuscle craft
companies like Sierra Nevada or Anchor Brewing Co., but imports
like Heineken have big money and huge global organizations behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boston Beer is pushing hardest with its flagship Sam
Adams Boston Lager brands and not emphasizing its array of other
specialty beers that play into the no-win experimentation market.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Beer's overall sales fell about 8 percent to 943,000
barrels through the first nine months of its fiscal 1998. But the
company's leading brands actually gained modest ground while its
group of ``nonfocused'' special brews suffered sales declines, some
as steep as 20 percent, according to analyst Skip Carpenter of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Koch insists Boston Beer's best long-term strategy is to protect
the quality image of its Sam Adams products. Customers, he said,
will come as long as the product stands for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``People constantly suggest to me to lighten the beer up and
make it more accessible,'' he said. ``I could probably get more
sales by dumbing down the beer. But in the long run, that would be
inconsistent with everything Sam Adams stands for. There is no way
I'm ever going to consider that.''
</P>
<P>
   No-growth sales and weak stocks are usually the prime
ingredients for corporate mergers that squeeze costs and
consolidate market share. But big brewing companies have shown
scant interest in buying their way into the craft segment, which no
longer offers one of the industry's few growth opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch has bought minority interests in Redhook and
Widmer Brewing Co. Others have created their own labels,
particularly easy because contract brewers around the country have
so much excess capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Koch once scoffed at the idea of a sale of Boston Beer. Ask if
he would sell today and the answer is a bit softer, but only a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is yes, if I had complete confidence the quality,
integrity, and passion wouldn't suffer and we'd get better in other
ways. Anything less would be an acquisition that would destroy the
value of what was being acquired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
