<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REASON TO BE PARANOID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't watched a single episode of ``The X-Files'' this
season, and it's affecting me. I'm losing my paranoid edge. Things
just don't seem as bleak and menacing as they used to. I didn't
even freak out when I heard last week about Intel Corp.'s plan to
put an electronic ID number inside its Pentium computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've talked to Intel engineers, civil liberties
advocates, and security experts. And to my surprise, I'm still not
freaked out.
</P>
<P>
   I may be the only one who isn't. Intel's getting mail from
congressmen, an Arizona state legislator has announced a plan to
outlaw the production of the chips in his state, and privacy
advocates have called for a Pentium boycott. All in response to an
idea that strikes me as mostly harmless, and actually rather
clever.
</P>
<P>
   Intel plans to release a new line of chips this year called the
Pentium III. Each will include an electronic serial number, which
can be read with the help of a piece of software.
</P>
<P>
   Say you do your banking on line. When you open your account, the
bank sends a program that reads your chip's ID. This is filed away
with other personal information and your password. The next time
you sign on, the computer can check your chip ID as proof of your
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Tom Waldrop says the system will provide an
extra layer of security against data thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd not only have to steal your password'' to rip off your
bank account, Waldrop said. ``They'd also have to steal your
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The chip ID would also be a blessing for corporate users who
must manage hundreds or thousands of machines over a data network.
At a glance, the manager could identify every connected machine.
</P>
<P>
   Cryptography expert Bruce Schneier tells me it should be
possible to create a program to generate fake chip IDs, but the
Intel folks say this would be so difficult that few hackers would
waste time trying. Besides, you'd still need your victim's
password.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the Intel ID system was to be switched on when the
computer starts up. But the fury of civil libertarians and
lawmakers has led Intel to a sensible change of heart. The Pentium
III chips will be sold with the ID switched off, unless the
customer chooses to switch it on. This can't be done remotely by
some evil hacker, either. It requires a complete shutdown and
restart of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the ID is switched on, it isn't broadcast
automatically to every Web site you visit, as some early press
reports implied. Only sites that request the information will get
it. And all they get is an ID number _ not your name, address, or
shoe size.
</P>
<P>
   For a site to get any personal information, you must give it to
them, or some other Web site must sell it to them. But that's your
problem, not Intel's. If you want to keep something private, don't
publish it on the Net, or give it only to Web sites that promise
not to share.
</P>
<P>
   A number of privacy advocates dropped their opposition to the
Intel system once the company agreed to let users decide whether to
activate it. Not the Electronic Privacy Information Center, which
wants Intel to remove the technology altogether. As long as it's in
the chip, says EPIC, Web sites could require their customers to use
it. And software makers could require the chip ID as a way of
preventing piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but why drive away so many customers? There are hundreds
of millions of computers that don't have chip IDs. Meanwhile,
chipmakers Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and National Semiconductor
Corp. say they won't put IDs on their Pentium-compatible chips.
What Internet merchant or software firm will refuse all this
business, just so he can read a chip code that provides far less
information than the customer's credit card number?
</P>
<P>
   The Intel plan offers a slight improvement in computer security,
and will cause hardly any loss in privacy. A little paranoia has
its uses, and there are genuine privacy threats for computer users
to worry about. This just isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com_
</P>
</TEXT>
