<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HILO29-COX     01-28 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HILO29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A western simmering on the edge of wild
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone could breathe new life into the western, you'd figure
it would be Stephen Frears. The British director has invigorated so
many tread-worn genres: the costume drama (``Dangerous Liaisons''),
film noir (``The Grifters''), the biopic (``Prick Up Your Ears''),
social satire (``My Beautiful Laundrette'') and domestic comedy
(``The Snapper'').
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he couldn't reinvent the gothic romance with his muddy
``Mary Reilly,'' but he gave it a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hi-Lo Country'' isn't a blunder like that flick. It's
handsome and absorbing in a low-key, big-sky way. But like its
narrator, Pete (Billy Crudup), the movie never seems to find focus.
It's a tale of passion, greed and gunfire that seems to be playing
out at a slight, discreet distance.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is in the casting. Patricia Arquette plays
Mona, a married woman who becomes the object of desire for both
Pete and his pal Big Boy (Woody Harrelson). Arquette can be fine,
but she's more of a presence than an actor. Here, she swims through
the role as if she's heavily sedated.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the real love story has nothing to do with Mona. It's
the (nonsexual) crush Pete has on Big Boy, a powerhouse fellow who
represents the spirit of the Old West. He's out of step in
post-World War II New Mexico, where family farms are being
swallowed alive by ranchers like Jim Ed Love (Sam Elliott).
</P>
<P>
   Mona happens to be married to Love's foreman. So when Big Boy
starts sleeping with her (and barely bothers to hide it), it's
considered as much an affront to him as to her husband. The women
in ``Hi-Lo Country'' are tools the men use to express their anger
and frustration. That includes Pete's old girlfriend Josepha
(delectable Spanish actress Penelope Cruz), who becomes an
unwitting stand-in for the passion Pete actually feels for Mona.
</P>
<P>
   Frears is an expert at slowly building tension. We know from the
start that somebody is about to die; Pete alludes to it in his
opening voice-over. That's what holds ``Hi-Lo'' together when its
romantic plot line isn't clicking. There's a terrific scene at a
dance, with Big Boy and Pete keeping an eye on the crowd, waiting
for an inevitable eruption from Love's men. It's a masterful
sequence, encapsulating the whole movie's mood of violence always
waiting to explode from the dusty, scenic landscape. But the film
is too uneven and too long to grip us the way it should.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson does his usual rollicking, loudmouth-rooster routine;
take that as an endorsement _ or a warning. Personally, I'm getting
tired of the actor's limited loudness. Like Robin Williams, he
seems to think acting is all about the mouth and jaws; he's
perpetually chewing on something or rolling a cigar between his
teeth. He's like a hyper kid who'll do anything to grab your
attention and steal focus from everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup has the harder role. Pete is the quiet center of the
movie, an enigma. Though he's the narrator, we never get inside his
head. That's the fault of the script, not Crudup, who delivers a
performance much like the film: subdued, reactive, but with
something in his eye that warns you he could become dangerous when
you least expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hi-Lo Country''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Billy Crudup, Woody Harrelson and Patricia Arquette.
Rated R for sexuality, violence and profanity. 2 hours, 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A tale of passion in the fading West that never
quite catches fire.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
