<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CRAZY29-COX     01-28 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CRAZY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beat goes on for '70s band in rock-solid `Still Crazy'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the midst of Sunday's Golden Globe Awards madness, you might
have heard mention of a small British film called ``Still Crazy.''
A nominee for best comedy/musical, it lost, without anyone much
noticing, to ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Still Crazy'' is no loser. It's the richest, most
delightful surprise of a still-young year (it played Los Angeles
briefly in 1998 to qualify for award consideration).
</P>
<P>
   To say that it concerns the reunion of a fictional 1970s rock
band called Strange Fruit can't help but conjure up the hilarious
dino-rock classic ``This Is Spinal Tap.'' But while ``Spinal Tap''
is a dead-on, tongue-in-cheek, needle-sharp satire, ``Still Crazy''
strives for something more complex. That doesn't make it a better
movie, just a different one _ one with a special resonance for the
generation that traded the Yellow Brick Road for Abbey Road and
thought it could be young forever.
</P>
<P>
   Strange Fruit disbanded in 1977 after a disastrous gig at a
``legendary'' open-air festival named Wisbech (Isle of Wight,
anyone?). They were struck by lightning _ literally _ in midset,
prompting their dryly jovial roadie, Hughie (``Mrs. Brown's'' Billy
Connolly), to note that divine intervention was at work. ``I think
God got sick of all that '70s excess,'' he says. ``That's why he
invented the Sex Pistols.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's 20 years later and each Fruit has pursued his own
peculiar loop. Keyboardist Tony (Stephen Rea) stocks condom
dispensers. Bass guitarist Les (Jimmy Nail) is a roofer with a
family to support. Beano (Timothy Spall), the drummer, lives in a
trailer on his mum's farm. Lead singer Ray (Bill Nighy) has retired
to county squiredom, sharing a stately mansion with his domineering
Scandinavian wife (Helena Bergstrom).
</P>
<P>
   As for the band's star _ an impish lead guitarist named Brian
(Bruce Robinson) _ well, he's missing in action. When Tony and the
group's former manager/gofer decide to round up the lads for a
reunion tour, they line up a replacement named Luke (Hans
Matheson).
</P>
<P>
   Loaded up in a bus once used by the Psychedelic Furs, the Fruits
go back on the road, hitting the slummier clubs in Belgium and the
Netherlands. Lightning doesn't strike, but old tensions, feuds and
jealousies do. They are, indeed, still crazy after all these years.
Also still vain, needy, petty and all the other rock-life
afflictions.
</P>
<P>
   The film is both a celebration and an elegy, a sharp, knowing
tragicomedy for baby boomers. The music is a potpourri of
contributions from members of groups such as Spandau Ballet,
Foreigner and Squeeze. The script is full of shrewd jabs and
poignant touches. The director is Brian Gibson, who proved he knows
his way around movies and music with ``Breaking Glass'' and
``What's Love Got to Do With It.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire ensemble cast is terrific, from Spall's low-comedy
antics to Rea's low-key believer (he still wears Jimi Hendrix's
tooth on a chain around his neck). The standout, however, is Nighy.
As the tremulous has-been heartthrob, smearing on the makeup and
jacking himself up with ``You are the man!'' pep talks, he recalls
the tragic grandeur of Terence Stamp's diva-ish drag queen in ``The
Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the generation it both mocks and mourns, ``Still Crazy''
balances its smart-mouthed self-absorption with a sad-eyed
sweetness. And it honors the survivors of that long, strange trip
known as the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stephen Rea, Billy Connolly and Bill Nighy. Directed by
Brian Gibson. Rated R for sexuality, language and drug references.
1 hour, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Brilliant, poignant and sharply observed, this
comedy about a reunited '70s rock band doesn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
