<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-READERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You be the critic, readers review current movies
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Thin Red Line'
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Malick's ``Days of Heaven,'' quite possibly the most
visually beautiful film ever made, came out 20 years ago. ``The
Thin Red Line'' makes it clear that we are in the hands of one of
the greatest visual poets ever. Malick's extraordinary vision does
not come along often. Think Welles, Kurosawa and Truffaut _ pieces
of each live inside Malick's films. Let's hope we don't have to
wait another 20 years to see a genius at work.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Ivester, Rome (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   `Meet Joe Black'
</P>
<P>
   I saw ``Meet Joe Black'' three times. It was one of those movies
that surprise you with every turn it took. I observed that the
other members of the audience were enjoying it as much as I was _
especially the ending. Great group of actors in that movie.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Boyd, Smyrna (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   `A Bug's Life'
</P>
<P>
   Pixar's second animated film is a darling flick. (It's) the
story of ants living under the thumb of grasshoppers. The jokes
come left and right. (The) voices are funny, and the music is very
fitting. An enjoyable movie for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kazmierczak, Conyers (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   `In Dreams'
</P>
<P>
   What would you do if your dreams were not your own, but those of
a madman? Annette Bening demonstrates a wide range of talents,
portraying such a woman, whose life is devastated by a psychopath,
well-played by Robert Downey Jr. An intriguing story and
interesting characters.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Winstead, Conyers (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   We're looking for movie fans who want to add their opinions to
our film coverage. To qualify, send us a brief review, preferably
of no more than 50 words, about a recent movie. Send your review,
name, address and telephone number to:
</P>
<P>
   Reader Movie Response
</P>
<P>
   Features Department
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 4689
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, GA 30302
</P>
<P>
   Or: Send a fax to 404-526-5509
</P>
<P>
   Or: E-mail kjanich(at)ajc.com
