<HEADER>
A2357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-SHES29-COX     01-28 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SHES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen comedy ain't that much
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the problem with ``She's All That.'' She isn't. And
neither is he.
</P>
<P>
   In this teen rebake of ``Pygmalion,'' Rachael Leigh Cook plays
the Eliza Doolittle role _ only she's not a poor Cockney, but a
morose, arty student named Laney. Freddie Prinze Jr. plays the
Higgins part, now called Zack and reconceived as the most popular
guy in his Los Angeles high school.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly dumped by his girlfriend Taylor (Jodi Lyn O'Keefe), Zack
accepts a bet from his cool-clique colleague Dean (Paul Walker) to
swan-ify the ugliest duckling on campus. Dean's choice: Laney.
(That seems odd, because even with long hair and nerd glasses, Cook
is already a stunner.) Zack has to transform Laney into a prom
queen in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think the chances are that he'll fall in love with
her in the process? Get real. You know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   In our oversaturated world of movies and TV series built around
tart-tongued, hyper-articulate teens, ``She's All That'' has some
verbal zing that distinguishes it from the crowd. Wounded by his
breakup with Taylor, Zack describes her as ``a C-minus GPA with a
Wonderbra.'' And the movie has funny throwaway bits, like Laney's
dad (Kevin Pollak) watching ``Jeopardy!'' and getting every single
answer wrong. Or the sly cameo by TV's ``Buffy,'' Sarah Michelle
Gellar. And in its general sweetness, the movie is leagues beyond
the rude, crude (and hugely successful) ``Varsity Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   The flick's liveliest moments deal with Taylor's new boyfriend,
Brock Hudson, the ``dyslexic volleyball guy'' from ``The Real
World.'' Played by Matthew Lillard (``Scream''), the Puck-like
slacker is one of the movie's best inventions, an epitome of a
brain-dead West Coast clown who's famous for being famous. And for
his habit of passing gas and calling people names.
</P>
<P>
   The lively supporting cast (including Anna Paquin, Kimberly
``Lil Kim'' Jones and Usher Raymond in a minuscule part) makes the
movie's real weakness all the more obvious: Prinze and Cook are
easy on the eye, but they're stiffs. He's noble and sensitive but
never seems three-dimensional. And though she looks like the
younger Winona Ryder, Leigh's performance lacks the warmth and
vulnerability Laney needs.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't helped by a script that's thick with laughs but thin
on character development. We never believe these two are made for
each other, that their preordained clinch is right and inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the two young stars fall in love because the script
says they do. That's what makes ``She's All That'' not all that
different from the dozens of other teen comedies around.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's All That''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Freddie Prinze Jr., Rachael Leigh Cook. Directed by
Robert Iscove. Rated PG-13. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: This week's latest disposable teen comedy has some
laughs and charm, but it ain't all that.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
