<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-ARCHITECTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING ARCHITECT ON YOUR PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all started in December 1994, when my wife and I decided to
spend Christmas vacation at a quaint little inn on Martha's
Vineyard. We made the mistake of picking up one of those little
real estate guides. By the following May we'd bought a little house
in Vineyard Haven that was quite picturesque, but also in desperate
need of repair. Today, nearly four years later, the renovations
still aren't finished.
</P>
<P>
   Last month my attempts at finishing the ongoing work hit a snag.
I was thinking of turning a porch into a few extra bedrooms when
the housing inspector told me that he wanted to see some
architectural drawings before anything got serious. Meanwhile, my
electrician asked me for some plans for the older part of the
house, so that we could plan where to install a number of new
circuits, light switches, and outlets.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later I was shopping in Staples when I saw a whole
category of home software: three-dimensional architectural design
tools. I had never noticed these boxes before; suddenly they were
very interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything needed to plan a new home, remolding project, deck,
and visualize new exterior landscaping,'' screamed the
advertisement on one box. ``Now anyone can easily visualize
remolding and decorating ideas in no time! said another.'' Here was
a way that I could recreate the missing plans to my 150-year-old
house, design the new addition, and do it all without hiring an
architect! And all for $59.95! What a deal!
</P>
<P>
   Now mind you, I never believed this hype for one moment. But I
did think that I might be able to use one of these programs to
create a rough set of plans and save me a few hundred dollars in
architectural fees. And indeed, after spending nearly 40 hours with
Broderbund 3D Home Deluxe, Sierra's Home Architect 2.0, and Planix
3D Home Designer, I'm still convinced that these programs are
useful to the layman. But don't think that they will make you an
architect.
</P>
<P>
   All of these programs let you create a rough set of plans, then
build a three-dimensional model of your home, view it from any
perspective, and furnish it with objects. And all of them have
special calculators and other kinds of gimmicks, like tools for
calculating the number of tiles you will need for a bathroom, or
the optimal location for a home satellite TV dish.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I found Broderbund's 3D Home Deluxe far easier to
use than its competitors. 3D Home Deluxe is like a paint program,
except that instead of painting with a brush, you paint with a tool
that puts down 2x4 stud walls. Draw four walls in a rectangle, and
you've made a room. Click on the icon of a door, then click a wall,
and you've just installed a door. Windows go up the same way. My
only complaint had to do with making changes: the program requires
that you select and change each wall one-at-a-time, rather than
allowing you to make multiple selections and change them all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   The programs by Sierra and Planix take a different approach.
Instead of starting with walls, these programs start with rooms,
each represented by a rectangle or other suitable shape. By
dragging these rooms around your screen, you create the floor plan
of your fantasy house. When you are happy with the design, you draw
the exterior walls. Although you can create some pretty creative
plans this way, you're also likely to end up was some structures
that are fairly difficult, if not impossible, to build.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra and Planix are stronger in the interior decorating
department. They have many different wall textures, interior
fixtures, pieces of furniture, and so on. The Sierra program is
heavily oriented toward three-dimensional design, with
photo-realistic rendering of furniture and walls. You can then
create your own 3-D walk-through and mini-movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra does its three-D rendering in the background, a help on
even fast machines, since rendering takes a lot of time. The
program also has cute little instructional videos that play every
time you switch into a different module. Unfortunately Sierra keeps
all of these videos, plus the modules themselves, on the CD-ROM,
which must be inserted in the drive in order for the program to
run. This may be a clever form of copy protection; unfortunately,
it also makes the program run very slowly.
</P>
<P>
   My least favorite program was Planix. Created by Autodesk, the
program is similar to the company's high-end AutoCAD program for
the kind computer aided design done by the pros. This makes the
Planix pretty alien to the users of most desktop software. Planix
menus, icons, and toolbars don't work like other PC programs that
you might be familiar with. And unlike Broderbund's program, which
tries understands that connected walls should stay connected,
Planix is very manual: if you want to resize a room, you'll need to
move several walls, one after another.
</P>
<P>
   None of the programs that I tried had any sort of architectural
smarts _ not even simple concepts, like the fact that it's a good
idea to put your second floor bathrooms over your first floor
bathrooms, or the importance of building central walls that can
support the weight of the upper floors. Nor did the programs
understand plumbing or heating systems, although they do offer
limited electrical planning capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem that I found with these programs is that they
really don't understand the way we build houses in New England.
Many of the sample plans included on the CD-ROMs put the heater on
the first floor, rather than in a full basement, where it belongs.
I think that this is because these programs were all designed in
either Northern California or Seattle, and they show their regional
biases.
</P>
<P>
   But my biggest complaint about these programs isn't their lack
of architectural intelligence, but their limitations as Windows
applications. All the programs I reviewed were created for the
older Windows 3.1. None of the programs worked properly when I
installed them in the Program Files directory; the space in the
directory name caused them to malfunction. Planix doesn't even
support long file names.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these problems, I was able to use the Broderbund's 3D
Home Deluxe to make a relatively complicated set of plans for my
house on the Vineyard. Now I finally understand why I don't have
any closet space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at
plugged-in(at)simson.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
