<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NALEN OWNS UP TO UNSPEAKABLE OFFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ A week from today &UR;  &LR; (Thursday), Tom Nalen
will be on a beach in Hawaii, preparing the way NFL players do for
the annual league all-star game, the Pro Bowl. He's happier this
week in dark meeting rooms shielded from the Florida sun at the
Hyatt Pier 66, preparing the way NFL players do for the annual
league Big Game, the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't tan,'' the Wrentham, Mass., native said jokingly of
his preferences for Super Bowls over Pro Bowls. ``I get red. Then I
peel.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Nalen will try mightily to peel away the layers of
the aggressive Atlanta Falcons' gap defenses to open holes for
running back Terrell Davis. It is something he has done well enough
the past two years to be elected to the Pro Bowl and it is
something he has done well enough this season for Davis to become
only the fourth player in NFL history to gain more than 2,000 yards
(2,008). Yet none of his success or Davis's has brought as much
notoriety to Nalen and his fellow offensive linemen as has the
simple act of not talking about either or much of anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the arrival of offensive line coach Alex Gibbs in
1995, the Broncos' offensive linemen have been mum by inclination
and enforcement. Each year, they have voted to accept Gibbs's
suggestion of a no-talk policy, a refusal to speak with the media
until the Super Bowl, the one week when the league fines the silent
rather than rewarding them.
</P>
<P>
   That policy was amended this year by fiat from head coach Mike
Shanahan, who agreed with a Pro Football Writers Association
protest that someone needed to speak for the linemen each week and
named a different one spokesman each week. Other than that, the
linemen remain silent or get fined by a kangaroo court that
collects the money and uses it for a year-end celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've been doing for a number of years,'' Nalen
said. ``We think it brings us closer as a group, and it's a way to
make fun of each other. Plus, the fines go to a good cause _
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has worked to our advantage. Now people
actually want to talk to us really bad. It's like we're geniuses _
which we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   The fine system began simply as $50 charges for any quote
appearing in a newspaper or on radio or TV. But over time, Nalen
says, the system took on a life of its own, with penalties being
levied for an assortment of other transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a prima donna fine; that's about 50 bucks,'' Nalen
said. ``There's a whole list of them, but if I told them all to
you, I'd get fined. There's a $1,000 fine for being quoted on
`Monday Night Football,' though.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I was stuck in traffic on a Tuesday, which is our
day off. I had the radio on, and there's one of our guys as a
co-host on a show for two hours. He figured because it was our day
off, nobody would be listening and he could get away with it. I
charged him the next day and he had to confess.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even fines for not having enough fines, which seems to
fly in the face of the spirit of the no-talk policy but which Nalen
said has been enforced more than a few times against those trying
to limit their contributions to the year-end party pot.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nalen, he gets few fines for violating the no-talking
rule and none for being a prima donna despite his status as one of
the best centers in the NFL after just five seasons. But he has
been penalized more than once by the sensitivity police for another
violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cause a lot of my own fines,'' Nalen said, laughing as he
talked. ``I've had a couple of big ones for reacting to criticism
in the wrong way. Harry Swayne and Tony Jones are the sensitivity
judges. If both their hands go up, you're guilty. I don't know how
they got that job. They're more sensitive than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That last comment will probably cost Nalen another 50 bucks, but
these days he can afford it. Or he soon should be able to. After
coming to Denver as a seventh-round draft choice out of Boston
College in 1994 (the 218th player taken), he needed only two
seasons to become a full-time starter and four to become a Pro Bowl
regular.
</P>
<P>
   He has remained the former since breaking into the regular
lineup in 1995, and each year he played just a little bit better
than the year before until his breakout season last year, when he
made the AFC Pro Bowl team for the first time. Yet even with
success, Nalen has changed little from his days playing in a far
different Super Bowl, the one his Foxboro High team twice won
before he moved on to BC to earn a bachelor's degree in accounting
and a master's in football.
</P>
<P>
   He has used the latter so successfully that one day soon, he may
have to put the former to use either as a free agent or in
negotiations with a team for whom he has started 64 of the last 70
regular-season games. Until then, Tom Nalen will just try to keep
his account with the sensitivity police balanced, his accounting of
Terrell Davis's rushing yards on the profit side, and his comments
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not talking to the media didn't bring us a lot of attention
until we got close to the Super Bowl last year,'' Nalen said. ``I
voted for it because I don't really like talking and I don't want
to stick my foot in my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once we got to the Super Bowl last year, we decided to
talk because we didn't want to get fined. When that started, it
became pretty obvious the media didn't really want to talk to us,
anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the questions were about why we weren't talking. Once they
found out we were, that was the end of the conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is nothing to get sensitive about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
