<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GEM FROM SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If soccer leagues are seeking diamonds in
the rough, they could do worse than to follow the trail of mineral
prospectors to the war-torn West African republic of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   That is the home of the latest Revolution recruit, Unisa Conteh,
a solidly built, 22-year-old, 6-foot striker with skills advanced
enough for the Major League Soccer team to have invited him to camp
after a one-hour workout last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution might not have room for Conteh, who would have
foreign status this season. But Conteh seems committed to staying
in the United States, or whichever country offers the best
opportunity, even to the point of adopting another nationality.
This is understandable, considering the ferocity and
unpredictability of Sierra Leone's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared to go back,'' Conteh said. ``When I left, I was 17
and the fighting was in the provinces. Now I am scared. Nobody in
my immediate family has been hurt, but friends and relatives have
been. I've got to try to get my family out, and that is on my mind
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighting doesn't give you a chance to do anything. They
start the league each season, and then there is fighting and the
league stops playing. When I left, I was not a national team
player, and I want to be a recognized player, with a good club and
a good coach. If I get a chance in another country, I would take
it. I want a chance to play in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in form, I have speed and power. I am from the Timne
tribe, and we are strong from childhood. This is what I have going
for me, and I want to now adopt the white man's skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Conteh's agent, Steve Weymouth, has helped with visa issues and
is trying to arrange safe passage for Conteh's family. He also
provides Conteh's primary form of transportation, since Conteh does
not have a driver's license valid in the US.
</P>
<P>
   Conteh seems confident beyond his years and is worldly enough to
respect the uncertainties of life. West Africa has been exploited
for many decades, first for its so-called ``human resources'' and,
after slavery was abolished and Sierra Leone was created as a haven
for ex-slaves in the late 18th century, for its natural resources,
especially bauxite, diamonds, and rutile.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently have European clubs scouted Sierra Leone for
soccer players. Kewullay Conteh, a cousin of Unisa, and Mohammed
Kallon are playing in Italy, and Mohammed Conteh is in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the war, everyone is kind of scared to go to Sierra
Leone,'' Conteh said. ``They can't really go to countries with
wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``With African players, it's luck. A lot depends on what you
want to do, what your goals are. And with God's grace, I am here to
learn something every day. I am not perfect and I still have a lot
to learn about this game. But I want to learn. I am confident, but
all I want to do is work hard and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Conteh was discovered as a teenager playing for Freetown United
in Sierra Leone's capital. He joined Al Ansar in Lebanon and
experienced his first taste of the exploitative policies of some
leagues. Former Revolution midfielder David Nakhid led Conteh and
others in an attempt to gain basic rights, such as preventing clubs
from releasing injured players without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Conteh's next stop was Trinidad, where he joined a club called
Joe Public. The team played in the CONCACAF Champions Cup against
D.C. United at Washington's RFK Stadium, Conteh's first encounter
with cold weather. He had been slowed by an injury, then developed
cold and flu symptoms and left the game at halftime of an 8-0
defeat. Conteh decided to stay in Washington, then moved to Boston,
where his club's photographer resides.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Conteh will seek his fortune far from his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the whole of Sierra Leone is made of diamonds,'' he
said. ``Sometimes people are planting and they will find diamonds
in their garden. You don't have to dig that deep. So I don't know
why they are fighting. As long as everyone has some money, that
should be enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
