<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_DRUG COMBINATION SAID TO EASE ARTHRITIS  
 _YALE STUDY PRAISES TEACHING HOSPITALS  
 _MIT SCIENTISTS INVENT `PHARMACY ON A CHIP'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 Drug combination said to ease arthritis
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis researchers announced encouraging news for hundreds of
thousands of rheumatoid arthritis sufferers whose tender and
swollen joints are not relieved by current drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a new ``designer'' drug to standard methotrexate therapy
improves symptoms for the many patients who have active arthritis
on methotrexate alone, according to a study in the current New
England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a 75 percent improvement in the number of
tender joints'' on the two-drug combination, vs. 39 percent
improvement on methotrexate alone, said Dr. Michael E. Weinblatt of
Brigham and Women's Hospital, who conducted the study with
researchers at six US medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced joint pain was not the only effect. Swelling was
similarly reduced in comparison to methotrexate alone, Weinblatt
said. ``That's pretty remarkable,'' he said. ``To make someone's
`joint count' almost 80 percent better is really pretty dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination, tested in 89 patients with severe, unresponsive
rheumatoid arthritis, contains a drug called etanercept, which has
won federal approval for use in arthritis by itself. The
genetically engineered drug sponges up a natural substance called
tumor necrosis factor that plays a pivotal role in the chronic
inflammation of arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   However, the price of relief will be high. A year's worth of
etanercept, made by Immunex Corporation in Seattle, costs about
$12,000. Methotrexate adds another $1,000 for the drug alone.
</P>
<P>
   Etanercept isn't the only new item on the arthritis treatment
menu. Specialists expect federal approval too for infliximab, an
artificial antibody that disables tumor necrosis factor. Taken
together, the two drugs will usher in ``a new era in the treatment
of rheumatoid arthritis,'' Dr. James R. O'Dell of the University of
Nebraska wrote in an editorial accompanying the current article.
</P>
<P>
   Rheumatoid arthritis afflicts about 2.1 million Americans,
usually beginning between the ages of 20 and 40. It strikes about
three times as many women as men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Yale study praises teaching hospitals
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do teaching hospitals provide better care? For treatment of
heart attacks, yes, according to a Yale University study published
Thursday. But not because of their high-tech capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the current New England Journal of
Medicine, found that heart attack patients were more likely to be
alive 30 days after admission if they went to the 60 US hospitals
that ranked highest on the well-known (but controversial) ``best
hospitals'' ranking published by US News and World Report. All but
one of the 60 were teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   However, the researchers ascribed the mortality advantage
largely to the fact that patients at the ``best'' hospitals were
more likely to receive aspirin and standard drugs called
beta-blockers _ simple, low-tech treatments known to cut the risk
of a subsequent fatal heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   A second study in the same journal found that older patients
with hip fractures, stroke, heart disease, and congestive heart
failure had substantially lower mortality rates if they were
treated at major teaching hospitals compared to other types. The
survival edge was most pronounced for hip fracture patients.
</P>
<P>
   But mortality comparisons are not the only measure of a ``best''
hospital. Dr. Jerome Kassirer, the journal's editor, noted in an
editorial that major teaching hospitals scored lower on a 1998
Massachusetts hospital survey of patient satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teaching hospitals and nonteaching hospitals still have
much to learn about providing high-quality care,'' Kassirer
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIT scientists invent `pharmacy on a chip'
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Institute of Technology scientists have invented
what they call a ``pharmacy on a chip'' _ a tiny drug-dispensing
device that could be implanted in the body and programmed to
release drugs successively from its reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the British journal Nature, Robert Langer and his
colleagues say the novel drug-delivery system could be made as
small as two millimeters square _ about eight hundredths of an
inch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
