<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-BUSY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING GIG IS LATEST ADVENTURE FOR EX-MAYOR KOCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ ``Do you want me to tell you all the things I
do?'' asks Ed Koch. And then the former mayor of New York leans
back in his chair and ticks them off on the fingers of his large
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's Koch as television actor playing the judge in
``The People's Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's Koch as political commentator, three times a week
on Bloomberg Television and once a week for the (N.Y.) Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Koch the movie critic, writing reviews every week
for a chain of 24 small papers around the Big Apple. And Koch the
advertising guy; he is currently doing commercials for Jammin'
105.1, an oldies radio station in New York, and last year he
shilled for Dunkin' Donuts, among other companies. Not to mention
Koch on the speaking circuit, Koch the author (now writing his 11th
book), and Koch the teacher at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Whew. And now, the peripatetic 74-year-old lawyer has taken on
yet another ``challenge:'' teaching at Brandeis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not finished remaining relevant,'' he says, with a modest
grin, during an interview at Brandeis shortly before his first
class Monday. ``I will never retire.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Koch's obsession with remaining relevant after an
extraordinary three terms as mayor of the world's greatest city is
the operative principle of his life, and it is central to
everything he says and does, even now, after more than 40 years of
public service.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident, for instance, in the way he spins his current
Brandeis gig _ teaching a semester-long course in government to 150
undergrads. He is the second celebrity-politician (former Texas
governor Ann Richards was the first) to assume the university's
mantle of the ``Fred and Rita Richman Distinguished Visiting
Professor'' in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was presented to me as a course (to be taught) by people
who had been in government,'' he says, adding, ``and had left with
their reputations intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch's never-say-die relevance is also apparent in the way he
makes light of his unsuccessful attempt to win an unprecedented
fourth mayoral term: ``I'm probably the most successful political
reject in the history of New York City. The people threw me out in
1989, but they still feel warmly about me and I to them.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is there in the clever sound bites he delivers in a phone
call with a Washington Post reporter, who is writing on deadline
about the impeachment trial: ``It's not as exciting as a case I had
on the People's Court about the python who ate the Chihuahua.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is no more obvious than when he takes the bully pulpit in
front of a lecture hall filled with students, many of them from New
York City, and spins the story of his mayoral years, as only
Hizzoner can.
</P>
<P>
   When he became mayor in 1978, Koch tells the students, he had
two major objectives: balance the budget and make New Yorkers, who
had come within a hair's breath of bankruptcy, ``feel better about
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am by personality and temperament a restrained, shy,
reticent human being,'' says Koch, whose shoot-from-the-hip style
in his third term earned him the epithet ``Mayatollah'' from the
local media. ``But I knew that if I didn't become bigger than life
. . . people wouldn't follow me.''
</P>
<P>
   So unlike his predecessor, Abraham Beame, he became a mayor who
was accessible to the press and above all, ``quotable,'' Koch says.
He also became a boss who didn't take no from his underlings.
</P>
<P>
   In his effort to change New York's reputation as a city that
never paid its bills, Koch says, he threatened to tell the press
which of his commissioners weren't paying their departments' bills
on time. When he did just that, the parks commissioner, who had
placed last on the list, paid a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was so humiliated and he was never going to be 10th
on that list again,'' Koch recalls. ``He told me that he went back
to his comptroller and said, `If I'm in 10th place again, it's your
ass.' And guess what? He was never number 10 again.''
</P>
<P>
   The students laugh appreciatively. And later when Koch
criticizes Mayor Rudy Giuliani for his mean streak, his tendency to
``go for the jugular,'' the students nod their heads in agreement.
They don't seem to see, or perhaps have chosen to overlook, the
contradiction between how Koch sees himself _ a righteous leader
who was tough for the sake of the city _ and how he views the
mayors who came after him:
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani will never be a great mayor because he doesn't enjoy
and like people. Dinkins was a very nice guy and a terrible mayor.
Giuliani is a good mayor and a terrible person.''
</P>
<P>
   Class over, Koch, his trademark bald head leading the way,
strides purposively down the stairs of the Golding Judaica Center,
flanked by his handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Without pausing to speak to the students who cluster nearby,
Koch hops into a car parked on the sidewalk, waiting to take him to
the 6:30 p.m. shuttle back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it, Ed Koch is still a man on the move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
