A2367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-28 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEPARATION BASED ON STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was developing a bad attitude about this winter. Could last
weekend have been any worse? Was last Sunday _ 50 degrees and
torrential rain in January _ just God's way of letting non-drinkers
see what a hangover is like?
</P>
<P>
   From New Year's Day to Martin Luther King weekend, a combination
of natural and manmade snow gave us quite good conditions,
especially considering how boney Christmas week was, not to mention
the weeks before it.
</P>
<P>
   Those stingy weeks before the holidays kept the ground bare and
brown, the trees and rocks dangerously close to the surface. Then,
the snow came, but now this spring stuff really has ski country
feeling a bit schizophrenic. If last Sunday was ugly, Saturday at
Sugarbush, where I happened to be skiing, the dawn broke a foggy
wet gray.
</P>
<P>
   It was not particularly inviting as we trudged toward the lift
after breakfast, feeling almost like we were going to work. Up, up
into the fog we rode, looking down for some sign of how conditions
were below. Then, sliding off, the first 6 feet down the ramp gave
an indication: fast and fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   We started on a familiar cruiser, Jester, so that we could sort
of remember where the turns were in the thickest pockets of fog,
and with about 15 yards visability, following the swichbacks became
fairly easy.
</P>
<P>
   The lower we descended, the thinner the fog, and we skied faster
on snow that was soft and fast, a nearly perfect ride with almost
no one else on the trail.
</P>
<P>
   This may not have been the day for back-country slashing through
the woods, and it was certainly not a day for the 75-m.p.h.
downhill racers I was there to cover. But cruising at half that
speed made this one terrific ski day, even with the light a bit,
uh, flat and a few raindrops falling here and there. It even gave
me a chance to deliver my lecture 27A to companions on the quad
chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason the Swiss and Austrians become such great skiers,''
I pontificated, ``is their feel for the snow. When they're just
kids in camp, they do some training exercises where they ski with
tape over their goggles. No, really. A coach skis behind them
yelling out when to turn right and left. They have to learn to
react to feel instead of sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I think I remember a European coach telling me this once,
but the point was valid. At least that was my story, and I was
sticking to it. Watching downhill racers free-ski _ part of my
life's work, you understand _ it becomes quickly obvious what the
difference is between a decent recreational skier and a great one.
For starters, that difference is never apparent until conditions
throw a curve.
</P>
<P>
   Two Austrian racers, Leonhard Stock and Peter Wirnsberger, went
down one run ahead of us as we worked our skis to adjust to unseen
variances of terrain and pillows of loose, soft snow on the trail.
</P>
<P>
   And as we tried to shift gears properly, reacting to change,
those great skiers (any racer who makes the Austrian National Team
is by definition a great skier) did not appear to make the least
movements at all, particularly in the upper body. Their skis were
smooth, thighs absorbing bumps like shock absorbers, their body
flow just seamless as they shot away from us down the trail.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me that the vast majority of middle-ability
skiers are terminally intermediate and will not improve without
instruction, or without pushing themselves into uncomfortable
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   So who wants to be uncomfortable?
</P>
<P>
   Take Average Blue Cruiser. Ten years ago, ABC might have gone
down the Starr trail or headed for Castle Rock or the Snowfields
just for the satisfaction of making it to the bottom in one piece _
not a particularly lofty goal.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a decade ago, and now maybe he doesn't have a
yapping adolsecent around to goad him into risks. Or maybe he just
likes to relax a bit more now, and hasn't really wanted a tough
challenge for years.
</P>
<P>
   Skiing 10 or 12 times a year (the US average) ABC isn't
progressing, and he's probably going backwards, like a guy who
doesn't get to the putting green enough. These days, when ABC hits
an icy day or bumped up terrain, or tough weather conditions, he
bails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life's too short,'' he says. ``I'm here to relax, not to prove
anything to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   So here is a definite crossroad, and ABC has a point. There will
be enough good days on the slopes for him to enjoy corduroy
cruising to the end of his days.
</P>
<P>
   The other route is to push off the plateau, to take a bump class
or some ice training. Practice skiing through trees, in and out of
crud, over the fearsome death cookies of a frozen granular track.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is not to survive varied terrain and conditions (an
intermediate skier can survive anything). The goal is to learn to
shift gears so imperceptibly as conditions underfoot change, that
you can ski anything as smoothly and confidently as ABC skis those
groomed white boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   It can even begin by trying to follow a couple of Austrian
downhillers through the fog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
