<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-MOE-BOS &LR;      01-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-MOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIP TO MOE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON HOLE, WYO. _ As can happen occasionally on chairlifts,
conversation hit a lull. So the guy seated to the far right
recalled his thoughts the moment before he launched from the
starting gate to win downhill gold in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands forward, outside ski,'' Tommy Moe recalled the other
day, reflecting on what went through his mind during the countdown
at the Lillehammer Winter Olympic Games. Then he added one of those
nuggets that buffs to a shine when it comes unsolicited from a
superstar just passing the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same thing here, same thing in any terrain. Keep the hands
forward and over the (downhill) ski,'' said Moe.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the inaugural Tommy Moe All-Mountain Ski Camp,
conducted where, when the skiing gets tough, the not-yet-tough get
scared and squirrely _ and ultimately better.
</P>
<P>
   Moe, 28, has just joined the elder Pepi Stiegler of 1964 Winter
Olympic fame to become the newest ``skiing ambassador'' to Jackson
Hole. Moe's four-day camp is one of five specialty ski and
snowboard workshops geared predominantly to improving the skills of
intermediate and advanced snow riders.
</P>
<P>
   The camps range in cost from $400 to $600, and include lift
tickets and other incidentals. For example, an ``incidental'' at
the Moe camp (the next one is slated for March 11-14) includes an
evening lesson at a nearby swimming pool learning how to snap roll
a kayak. The relevance of kayak proficiency on a 10,450-foot
mountain remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's fun!'' proclaimed Moe.
</P>
<P>
   A fitting epitaph for a man destined to play fast for a living.
In addition to winning gold in the downhill, Moe won silver in the
super-G, retiring from the US Ski Team last year to ski for Jackson
Hole and join the professional circuit. He currently leads the pack
in the Ford Downhill Series, placing last weekend at Sugarbush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not that difficult to have fun and ski for a
living,'' said a lad who thinks nothing of dropping 20 vertical
feet into Corbett's Couloir, which would be the graduation exercise
(not compulsory) for his January camp.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduling windfall two weeks ago allowed me to join Moe for
the first day, our ranks including two mothers, a teen-ager, and a
73-year-old retired electical engineer from the flats of Michigan
who had been skiing for only six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you've got to factor in that they have been full years,''
said John Davies, who lives in Teton Village at the base of the ski
area's tramway.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1 began in steep bumps in Cheyanne Bowl where, one by one,
campers were asked to strut their stuff in front of coaches who
then divided us by skill level. John Grant, a local landscaper,
became my partner. When Grant is not skiing narrow chutes or
tickling the levers of earth-moving machines, he competes in
national swing dance competitions. The point is, one part of his
body tends to know precisely what the other part is doing. I tend
to leave body parts behind.
</P>
<P>
   So I followed him. He followed Moe, and when Moe was instructing
other groups, he followed Bruce Keller, a member of the Jackson
Hole Ski School who, despite his Kansas roots, has a specialty in
skiing extreme terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is confidence building. Confidence is transferable,
from one environment to another,'' Keller explained as our trio set
off to explore such double-black diamond delights as Toilet Bowl,
Alta 1, Dick's Ditch, and Tower. The names say it all. No cruisers
here. And now a note about the local jargon.
</P>
<P>
   If the start of a run requires ``hopping in,'' don't think Hokey
Pokey, think free fall. ``Chocolate chips'' are not nibbles; they
are scatter shot of limestone shards in the snow that stop skis
like the barbed ends of fish hooks. You do not want to ``biff'' on
a chocolate chip. To ``point it'' means to take a deep breath and
plummet in the company of your angel. With skill, you'll ``huck''
it, which means your angel persevered. If you hucked it with
``aggro'' (aggression), your angel's taking Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a summary of some of the lessons learned from a
day of hucking the steeps with Tommy Moe and friends:
</P>
<P>
   --About half the ski boots worn by recreational skiiers are too
big, leading the wearer to over tighten the buckles and warp the
shell to the point it creates sores. Big boots are quick sales in
some equipment shops. Test: Remove an inner boot, place your foot
in the shell with toes snug to the front. You should have enough
room behind your heel to insert a little more than one finger.
</P>
<P>
   --When the going gets steep, the body should lead the skis
downhill. To the inexperienced, the alternative is preferable _
skis first, then the torso safely snuggling the hill above. This
puts the weight back and will end in a biff (see above).
</P>
<P>
   --The steeper the terrain and/or the faster the speed, the less
input is needed to accomplish a turn. And of course, hands forward
and over the outside (downhill) ski to maximize edging on the
downhill ski and stabilize the platform _ your stance.
</P>
<P>
   How does Tommy Moe feel about seeing a lifetime of ski training
condensed into three bulleted paragraphs gleaned from one day in
his ski camp?
</P>
<P>
   This is not known. He wasn't asked. But a safe bet might be
following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrific! Have fun!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-28 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING HIS 23RD OPERATION, SCHLERETH GOING STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A strong case can be made that they're all crazy, every
single one of them. Professional football is, after all, a barbaric
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   But among these gladiators, there are degrees of madness. There
are tough guys and there are really tough guys. There are stories
and there are epics. There are medical risks and there is Mark
Schlereth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doctor in his right mind would ever pass me for a physical
if his job were on the line,'' Schlereth reports. ``But this is the
NFL. If they want you to pass the physical, you will pass the
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Denver this season, he went wading into the
free agent waters. He flunked physicals in Chicago, Indianapolis,
and _ you'll love this _ Atlanta. Back in Denver, however, no
problem. The Broncos quite obviously wanted this 33-year-old,
287-pound guard to pass his latest physical. He has started every
game this season. On Sunday, he will start at left guard in Super
Bowl XXXIII _ against the Falcons. A week later, he will undergo
his 23d career surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things floating around inside my left elbow,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   He has had his knees invaded 17 times. The upcoming procedure
will be the fourth on his elbows. He has had back surgery. And he
has had kidney stones removed. They came out at 9 on a Sunday
morning. The next evening, he played a half in a Monday night game
before feeling too ill to continue. ``We were up, 21-0, at the
half, so I didn't feel too badly about missing the second half,''
he explains.
</P>
<P>
   If playing can be painful, not playing can be even worse. When
surgery for two herniated disks forced him to watch another Monday
night game on television, Schlereth couldn't handle it. ``I was
physically ill watching the game and knowing that I should be out
there with my teammates,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Matter-of-fact doesn't quite describe this fourth-generation
Alaskan's attitude toward his medical situation. Fatalistic doesn't
quite do it, either. Is it possible for a man to accept one's
physical fate with serene defiance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Get your pens ready,'' he commands. ``I'll explain myself to
you. I am nine parts stupidity and one part complete lunacy. If
something is important to you, then do it. Football is important to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that if someone had told this guy on the occasion of
his first operation 16 years ago that it would be the first of 23,
it would not have remotely fazed him. He might even have thought it
would be pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   When you've battled through dyslexia, you feel confident you can
overcome life's obstacles. You go through the dyslexia, the 22
surgeries, and a bout with a debilitating disease known as
Guillain-Barre syndrome _ which rendered him pathetically weak and
took away the feeling in his hands and feet for three months back
in '92 _ and it makes you amazingly resilient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe you learn from adversity,'' Schlereth maintains. ``I
am stubborn and rockheaded. I have never learned anything about
myself in good times. Adversity is good for me. Because of it, I
know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He is surely a Bill Parcells kind of guy. ``During football
season,'' The Tuna loves to say, ``football players play
football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schlereth corollary: ``When I've been a free agent, I've
told people, `Don't even fly me in if you want me to pass the
physical. But if you want someone who is going to line up and play,
I can do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He is a legend in the Denver locker room. ``Mark Schlereth is a
guy who has had 22 surgeries,'' says coach Mike Shanahan. ``When we
signed him, a lot of people thought his career was through.
Football is very important to him. When guys come into the locker
room and they're a little hurt, they look at him and say, `I'm not
hurt.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He's not just tough; he's good. He's been to Pro Bowls and he
has won championship rings with both Washington ('92) and last
year's Broncos. But he has become so identified with the surgeries
and what they represent in the larger picture that there is a
danger he will eventually pass through the game without being
properly appreciated for his skill.
</P>
<P>
   As if he cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I walk off the playing field,'' he roars, ``none of
you will remember me. Ten years down the road, I will be forgotten.
I'm not playing to establish any legacy. But I will know that no
one ever got more out of his body in the history of the game than I
have. I'm saying that in all humility. I can't say I'm proud of
that. But that's the way it is. I just want to be remembered by my
teammates as someone who put out the effort in every practice and
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a stupid man. He has made a rational choice to play
football as hard, and as long, as he can. As a current consequence,
he reports, he cannot bend over to putt a golf ball or crawl on the
floor to play with his kids. He will almost undoubtedly require as
many artificial body parts as they manufacture, but that is of no
concern to him right now. ``I don't spend a minute of wasted time
worrying about what the future holds,'' he says. ``I have no idea
what's going to happen. The damage to my body has been done. I'll
just press on and cross that road when it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   His daily motivations? ``Fear and paranoia,'' he says. ``There
is the fear of failure and the fear of getting beaten up and the
fear of being embarrassed. It's all part of being an offensive
lineman. A defensive lineman can play a poor game and then make one
sack late and get in the highlights. An offensive lineman can play
57 or 58 great minutes with no one paying attention and then give
up one sack late, and what will be in the highlights?''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, therefore, that offensive linemen are so
notoriously clannish? ``I am a Christian, and I truly believe I am
here to serve others,'' says Schlereth. ``Offensive linemen must
always be ready to help each other on the field, and if I needed
help at 3 in the morning, I would feel comfortable calling any one
of those guys, and they all know they could call me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are the bad knees, the bad elbows, and the bad
back, and it goes without saying there are the hopelessly mangled
fingers and the toes that have been stepped on countless times and
probably a half-dozen other things Mark Schlereth thinks are too
irrelevant to talk about. In his own strange way, they are his
comfort, his reminder of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are so much a part of my life,'' he says, ``that
I wouldn't know what to do if I felt good. I've just adjusted to it
all and gotten used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   You tell him he's crazy. I'll pass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
