<HEADLINE>
ANDERSEN HAS MADE THE RIGHT EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Florida's Turnpike can bring you to Sunday's Super Bowl.
Interstate 95 also can deliver you close to the big game. Many
other lesser-known routes lead to Pro Player Stadium as well.
</P>
<P>
   Morten Andersen's path to Super Bowl XXXIII, though, is one of
the most intriguing, even if it cannot be found on any map.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen arrived in the United States as an exchange student on
his 17th birthday. He had arrived from the little town of Struer,
Denmark, where his mother was a librarian, his father a
psychologist and supervisor of educational programs for handicapped
children. Andersen truly was bound for the heart of America on his
birthday, to the home of the Baker family in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The following day after I arrived with the Bakers, they told
me there was something called a `jamboree,' '' recalled Andersen,
whose English is perfect now but who could not understand back then
what this ``jamboree'' word meant. ``The Bakers asked me if I
wanted to go to the jamboree.''
</P>
<P>
   All lives, in retrospect, have such moments at which they turn.
Andersen was an athlete in his little town of 9,000, and when he
came to America, he wanted to play soccer. But the high school he
would be attending had no soccer team. Yet there was this
``football,'' this ``jamboree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bakers told me this was sort of a preseason game, and Dale
Baker asked me if I wanted to go and watch this jamboree,''
Andersen said of his conversation with the head of the Baker
family. ``I said . . . what could I say? . . . I didn't know what
he was talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   So Andersen went to the game, watched all these boys in strange
helmets and padded shoulders, ``and I had no clue what was going on
out there.'' But word had passed through the local grapevine that
this boy had arrived from Denmark, and of course, all Europeans
play soccer, and perhaps Andersen could kick the football. ``They
told me the high school team had no kicker and they asked me if I
wanted to try out,'' he recalled. ``I told them I'd give it a
try.''
</P>
<P>
   The school ``threw together some equipment for me, and I put it
on and I think my number was 42 _ a pretty high number for a
kicker, huh? _ and the team and the coaches lined up on the side
and watched me kick,'' Andersen said. ``We started on extra points,
and I hit the extra points, and then we moved back 30 yards and the
ball was still going through. I could could tell the other guys
were pretty excited and the coach was, too. So that was my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is a bit more to the story.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time for his first actual game of the season, a
season that would wind up an 11-1 success, Andersen was given some
unusual instructions for his kickoffs by his coach, Bob Wilbur.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that when I kicked the ball, I should just run for
the sidelines the moment I kicked it,'' said Andersen. ``So I would
kick the ball and I would just haul for the sidelines. So
basically, we had just 10 guys covering the kick all year long.
Every time, I'd kick and then I would just run for the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   A vivid image of an interesting starting point on that Andersen
road to the Super Bowl. Kick the ball and run like mad to the
sideline. The first step of this kicker can be copied by little
boys and girls, but not the first step of this journey. Never.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until much later in the season that Andersen had a
clue about what was going on between the teams on the field. ``I
was not close-minded when I came to America,'' he said. ``The
reason I came here was because I wanted to expose myself to a
different culture, the language and the people. But I really had to
open my mind up to football.''
</P>
<P>
   But Andersen could kick, and soon recruiters noticed him and he
went to Michigan State, where he was very good, and then to the
NFL, where he has been very, very good for 17 years. In fact, it
was his overtime field goal at Minnesota in the NFC Championship
Game that enabled the Atlanta Falcons to complete their improbable
trip to the Super Bowl, where they'll meet the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, Andersen would return to Denmark to visit
family and friends. And from time to time on those trips, he would
go to a nearby soccer field and practice his kicking. Little Danish
boys and girls and older Danes would gather to see this famous son
of Streur who had made so much money kicking. ``I'd be kicking at a
soccer net, and of course, I'd be trying to kick it over the net
and not into it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm, the Danes surmised, money must be easy to come by in
America, since this Andersen can't even kick the ball into the net,
even without a goalie there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd happen all the time,'' he recalled, laughing at the
memory. ``They'd be watching me kick and they're saying, `This
guy's really, really bad,' and `He's terrible; he kicks them all
over the crossbar.' Several times, boys would come up to me and
say, `No, hit it into the net. Don't keep hitting it over the net.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark may still be confused about why America considers Morten
Andersen so good when he can't even do what any Danish boy or girl
does so easily _ kick a ball into a net. But Danish television has
a videocam and a reporter with ``Sporten2'' on his microphone
recording Andersen's every move and word this week, and three
sportswriters from Danish newspapers are scribbling down every
vignette.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has a custom-made kicking shoe, and every detail of
that $5,000 shoe is public fodder. Andersen has been to Nepal to
find harmony and peace up in the Himalayas, and it slipped out that
``I've seen Tibetan monks levitating,'' and media skeptics have
grilled him about that.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Andersen reviews his list of Super Bowl ticket
requests, the names of people for whom he absolutely has to find
tickets. His parents, of course, Hanne and Erik; brother Jakob;
Janice Appelgreen of Big Rapids, Mich., who was his surrogate mom
when he was at Michigan State; wife Jennifer and her family from
Maine; his old neighbors from New Orleans; and yes, Lois and Dale
Baker of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to take care of the people,'' he said, ``all of
them who took care of me.'' Or even, like the Bakers, who asked the
question which changed Andersen's life: ``Do you want to go and
watch the jamboree?''
</P>
</TEXT>
