<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
THEQUE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) After nearly two decades, the American
Cinematheque has found a permanent home at the Egyptian Theatre on
Hollywood Blvd. It begins continuous programming there next week
with a spectacular James Cameron retrospective, and over the next
few months will present an eclectic range of series. 
. 
STREEP-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ With her uncanny ability to disappear
into a character, Meryl Streep established herself in the '70s as a
leading dramatic lady with a chameleonlike quality. She's played
rich and poor, mother and daughter, jilted wife and cheating
spouse, lover and friend, criminal and whistle-blower. By Bob
McCarthy. 
. 
TINSEL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Tinseltown'' is a misfired comedy
about talentless show-biz wanna-bes trying to hustle their way into
the Hollywood movie game. Some jokes about the people responsible
for making the film could be made here, but it would not be fair to
do so. Not too far off the mark in some of their cases, but still
unfair. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
SHES-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``She's All That'' isn't much. One of
the approximately 150 high school comedies coming out this year,
it's as bland and generic as ``Varsity Blues'' was calculated and
pandering. Frightening as the prospect may be, at least we might
remember ``Varsity Blues'' by the time the millennium gets here. No
chance of that happening with this one. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
TITANIC-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The Switchblade Kittens' punky
girl-centric version of ``My Heart Will Go On'' is the the funniest
song parody you may never hear. ``I heard Celine Dion's version on
the radio so many times it was driving me nuts, so I decided we had
to make a joke out of it,'' says Switchblade Kittens' leader,
bassist and singer Drama Mahaffey-Arthur. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
SHARPS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ I'm not one of those who believes
there's little interesting or challenging pop music being produced
anymore. I just don't think the labels are bound by law to sign 35
versions of the same hit sound. What's needed is more creativity in
the executive suite. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
TRIO-VIDEO (LoS Angeles) _ Three films that feature
independent-minded women hit video stores Tuesday: the outrageously
funny ``There's Something About Mary'' and Disney's animated
``Mulan.'' But you may have missed the third one _ an enjoyable bit
of comic fluff called ``Shooting Fish.'' By Rob Lowman. 
. 

