<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT29-COX     01-28 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Jan. 29, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ Senators are struggling to reach a bipartisan
timetable for the remainder of President Clinton's impeachment
trial as the White House signals it may forgo defense witnesses if
there's no new damaging testimony. Senate Republican leader Trent
Lott and Democratic leader Tom Daschle expressed hope they could
present a proposal today to conclude the trial by Feb. 12 or
sooner. Any agreement approved in party meetings would be presented
for approval in today's impeachment trial session.
(Foskett/Carr/Sherman, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BARR _ ATLANTA _ House impeachment prosecutor Bob Barr was back
in Atlanta Thursday, a day after the potentially forshadowing
Senate votes of Wednesday. Hanging with Barr to get his take on
where the process goes from here and what constituents think.
(Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-LEPTO _ WASHINGTON - Leptospirosis, a bacterial disease
that infects humans and numerous animals, apparently is becoming
increasingly common in dogs, according to some veterinary schools.
At times the shock to a canine's kidneys is so severe the animal
must have hemodialysis to survive. Only four veterinary hospitals
in the country are equipped to administer the treatment. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   PANDA _ Zoo Atlanta is getting two pandas from China and will
build a new exhibit in which to house them. Besides the two pandas
coming to Atlanta this summer, there are only three others in the
U.S. _ two in San Diego, and one in Washington, D.C. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON _ DAYTON _ Rev. Jesse Jackson comes to Dayton this
afternoon to announce his latest initiative, calling for 1,000
churches to begin investment clubs and mentoring programs for
troubled youths in their churches. This is, in part, a continuation
of his effort to encourage investment in Appalachia. (Franklin,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Developing from 4 p.m. EST press conference and 7 p.m. EST
address.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKMEN-MENTORS _ The 100 Black Men of America have launched a
$35 million Miracles of Mentoring campaign with a goal of building
a national youth leadership institute in
</P>
<P>
   metro Atlanta. (PScott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TEENDRIVE-GRADES _ ASHEVILLE, N.C._Wanda Coates, the registrar
at the 1,225-student high school in this western N.C. mountain
community, has one tough duty ahead of her next week. She must sort
through the grades of all ninth and tenth graders, siphoning off
those who failed two or more courses, to send letters telling them
they've lost their driver's license. Last year, the N.C.
Legislature tied driving privileges to school performance. The
first grading period since then has just ended, with some 30,000
students expected to lose their license this month, according to
Artie Kamiya, who is overseeing the project for the N.C. Department
of Instruction. In all, 17 states tie school attendance to driving
privileges, but only a few add the extra provision of maintaining
good grades. In Georgia, the state can yank a license if students
are suspended from school for violence, drug or alcohol use on
school grounds or for having a weapon at school. It does not punish
dropouts or those with poor grades. (Riddle, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TRACK COUGH _ More on the strange `kennel cough' afflicting
greyhound tracks around Florida. Need to talk to experts to find
out: is it a bacteria or virus, what is it exactly, symptoms, how
you treat it, are track owners reluctant to treat dogs because they
can't raise while being medicated, how often do you get this kind
of outbreak, what are the rules about shifting dog from track to
track, where are the Palm Beach kennel dogs bred, do they have an
outbreak, etc? (Donald, Palm Beach Post)..
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-WAY _ AUSTIN _ Austin set a national record for
increasing its contributions to the United Way in 1998, the second
year in a row that Austin has seen among the highest increases in
the nation. The big increase in contributions from Dell and the
other high-tech companies, and the increase in people giving over
$1,000, fueled the growth. (Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-BUDGET _ AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush unveils his
budget plan on Thursday. We are looking for details on his proposed
$2 billion school property tax cut and how he plans to make sure
local school districts don't simply raise local taxes (like they
did in 1997) to fill the gap. How much money will Bush put into his
plan for remedial programs to stop kids from being socially
promoted? (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ South Carolina legislature
takes the first step toward approving a lottery. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-LOBBY _ ATLANTA _ Doors to the House and Senate were
flung open for them but now a badge bars them from the chambers
where they once helped write laws. Once legislators they are now
lobbyists _ among the more than 1,000 who work the Capitol halls;
among the ones targeted by Gov. Roy Barnes in his ``eel-skinned
briefcases and aligator shoes'' comments. (Cook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN _ AMMAN, Jordan _ King Hussein appears closer to
death now than at any time. In recent days, he has thrown the royal
palace -- and an adoring public -- into a frenzy with a 14-page
letter written to his brother, Prince Hassan, essentially naming
his son, Abdullah, as his successor to the thrown, then suddenly
jetting back to the United States in an apparent relapse of his
cancer. What's really going on here? Who are the key players? Why
are all eyes in Israel and the Arab world focused on this tiny
country of nomads? Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
