<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORISM AT ABORTION CLINICS ISN'T FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For years now, pro-choice advocates have tried
to drive home a truth about the violence that is inflicted on
abortion providers and their medical facilities. Last week, Hillary
Rodham Clinton became perhaps the most prominent mainstream figure
to join this effort. She identified clinic violence for what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not free expression,'' she said. ``This is domestic
terrorism and it must stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In an address to the National Abortion Rights Action League on
the 26th anniversary of the Roe vs. Wade Supreme Court decision
that affirmed a woman's right to an abortion, the first lady cited
some familiar statistics:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years there have been seven murders (of clinic
doctors or staff), 38 bombings, 146 cases of arson and 733 cases of
vandalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, as did Nation magazine writer Katha Pollitt, such a
siege against any other business or organization. In a column last
autumn, Pollitt wondered what the national response would be ``if
zealots like the ones who burn down abortion clinics and kill
doctors and stalk their children were committing the same crime
against, say, dermatology clinics or convents or the Marines.''
</P>
<P>
   How many folks would term these overt criminal acts ``free
expression'' or defend them as a natural result of deep-seated
religious convictions? How many would ignore the fact that the
activities of the dermatologists, nuns or Marines are _ like those
of abortion providers _ still legal?
</P>
<P>
   The day before Hillary Clinton's speech, the Feminist Majority
Foundation reported findings from its most recent survey of the
nation's abortion providers. From January through July 1998, more
than 20 percent of clinics experienced at least one incident of
violence. The incidents included blockades and death threats,
invasions, stalking, bombings, fires and chemical attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a noted abortion provider _ the obstetrician and
gynecologist Dr. Barnett Slepian _ was shot to death through a
window of his home outside Buffalo, N.Y. The prime suspect, a
longtime anti-abortion zealot named James C. Kopp, has eluded the
police and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the shooting of Slepian, Attorney General Janet
Reno finally delivered an appropriate federal response. She created
a task force to prosecute and prevent violence against abortion
providers. Besides establishing a national database on clinic
violence, the task force will train the police and clinic staffs in
response and prevention tactics.
</P>
<P>
   In her abortion rights address, Hillary Clinton told her
audience that the president's forthcoming budget will ask Congress
for $4.5 million for an array of protective devices for abortion
providers. They would include closed-circuit cameras, motion
detectors and bulletproof windows.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the president would not be handicapped by the residue
from his impeachment (and he will), the likelihood of this Congress
allocating such a sum to protect abortion providers is probably
small. Most of the women who use highly visible family planning
clinics are among one of the least powerful influence groups _ the
young and the financially strapped. Middle-class and wealthy women
receive birth control or abortions in their doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, too many members of the male-dominated Senate and
House fear the voting and funding clout of the anti-abortion
movement. They may not be willing to target legal abortion for
extinction, but they don't like to appear to support the procedure
in any active way.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that could include not allocating the funds to protect
providers from being murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke the obvious truth when she said, ``Violence,
harassment and intimidation have no place in our health care system
or in this debate.'' But until our nation's lawmakers admit that
such tactics are indeed domestic terrorism, their place in the
debate and the health care system will be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
