<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREEP-FILMS-LADN     01-28 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREEP-FILMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREEP WRAPS HERSELF IN MYSTIQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With her uncanny ability to disappear into a
character, Meryl Streep established herself in the '70s as a
leading dramatic lady with a chameleonlike quality.
</P>
<P>
   She's played rich and poor, mother and daughter, jilted wife and
cheating spouse, lover and friend, criminal and whistle-blower.
With so many outstanding performances to her credit, it's sometimes
hard to remember Streep as much as the characters she has embodied.
</P>
<P>
   Bing Theater at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art is hosting
a retrospective of her work starting Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' (1979, for which she won her first Oscar,
co-starring Dustin Hoffman) and ``A Cry in the Dark'' (1988,
co-starring Sam Neill) will screen Feb. 5, ``Out of Africa'' (1985,
co-starring Robert Redford) on Feb. 6. Streep, a graduate of Yale
Drama School, has compiled a string of memorable performances since
first gaining notice in ``The Deer Hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   Other films to be shown in the February series are ``Silkwood,''
``The River Wild,'' ``Sophie's Choice,'' ``Postcards From the
Edge,'' ``Death Becomes Her,'' ``The French Lieutenant's Woman,''
``The Bridges of Madison County'' and two current films, ``One True
Thing'' and ``Dancing at Lughnasa.''
</P>
<P>
   This series is made possible with the support of Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   LACMA's Bing Theater is at 5905 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles.
Tickets cost $7 general admission, $5 for museum and AFI members
and students with ID. Purchase of a ticket includes admission to
the museum. Call (323) 857-6010 or Ticketmaster for ticket
information.
</P>
<P>
   PRIDE AND JOY: With the theme of ``Infinite Imagination, the
sixth Pan African Film &AMP; Art Festival opens Thursday at the Magic
Johnson Theatres and the Baldwin Hills Crenshaw Plaza. The festival
runs through Feb. 15 with actor Malcolm Jamal Warner acting as
celebrity host.
</P>
<P>
   Executive director Ayuko Babu explains that the theme
encompasses the sheer number of exhibitions planned _ 70 features,
shorts and documentaries along with works from prominent and
emerging artists and craftsmen. ``The entire scope of our event
mandates one's infinite imagination,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan African Film Festival is the largest festival of black
films in the United States, according to organizers. Along with
cinema, it offers poetry, fashion and music. Last year's event drew
100,000 spectators and celebrities Sidney Poitier, Tim Reid and
Blair Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   Awards for best narrative feature, best documentary, best short
and best student film will be handed out.
</P>
<P>
   Screenings are $7.50 for adults ($4.75 after 6 p.m.) and $4.75
for seniors and children. The opening-night gala is $45. Forums,
children's events, art and photographic exhibits are free. Call
(213) 896-8221 or (323) 295-1706 for information.
</P>
<P>
   `DETROIT 9000' BACK: Director Quentin Tarantino apparently liked
``Detroit 9000'' enough to re-release this 1973 action-packed
standout from the blaxploitation era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit 9000'' is playing today through Sunday only at the
Nuart Theatre, 11272 Santa Monica Blvd., Los Angeles. Call (310)
478-6379 for show times.
</P>
<P>
   Two cops _ one black, the other white _ set out to discover the
truth about the robbery of a politician in a racially charged
atmosphere. Arthur Marks (``Friday Foster'' and ``Bucktown'')
directed this tame and humor-laced production that features a soul
soundtrack and ultra-hip characters. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
