<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIO-VIDEO-LADN     01-28 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIO-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ECLECTIC TRIO WORTH CLOSE LOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are three films hitting the video stores
next Tuesday that feature independent-minded women. Two of them are
box-office hits _ the outrageously funny ``There's Something About
Mary'' and Disney's animated ``Mulan'' _ but you may have missed
the third one _ an enjoyable bit of comic fluff called ``Shooting
Fish.'' With ``Mary,'' the Farrelly brothers, who were behind the
summer blockbuster, have managed to mix the gross-out, even
tasteless, humor they are known for into a romantic comedy and make
it work.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the credit goes to the performance of Cameron Diaz
(Mary), as well it should. But the writing-directing brothers
(``Dumb and Dumber,'' ``Kingpin'') have gone beyond their usual
cardboard cutouts and given us characters we can care about in Mary
and Ted (Ben Stiller).
</P>
<P>
   The running joke in ``Mary'' is that this wholesome, intelligent
woman attracts nothing but a collection of losers. But because of
her good heart and determination and the fact that she takes care
of her mentally retarded brother, Mary takes the bizarreness of her
life in stride. The closest thing to a normal guy in her life was
Ted, who disappeared after a humiliating accident (which we are
sure already has been described to you) the night of their prom.
After 13 years of dreaming about her, Ted hires a private
investigator (Matt Dillon) to find her.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to recount the whole plot. ``Mary'' isn't a
perfect mesh. The Farrellys at times still seem caught between the
worlds of gags and storytelling. But it works most of the time, and
most of the time it's hilarious. The cast deserves credit for
throwing themselves into this lunacy. One delightful touch is the
use of singer-songwriter Jonathan Richman as drummer Tommylark in a
twisted Greek chorus.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem much point in hoping that a Disney animation
feature will do well. Like a well-oiled machine, it spits out one
hit after another. But with ``Mulan'' there is a reason. Disney
often has feisty females at the heart of its stories _ ``The Little
Mermaid,'' ``Pocahontas,'' Belle in ``Beauty and the Beast.'' In
``Mulan,'' it has been taken one step farther. The title character
is a young girl on the brink of womanhood. Her family wants her to
marry. But when her infirm father is called back into the army to
fight against invading Huns, she cuts her hair and dons her
father's suit of armor and takes his place in the ranks, calling
herself Ping.
</P>
<P>
   In the army, her former concerns of womanhood are transformed
into concerns with being a man among the other recruits. She must
show her strength and be one of the boys while still being a woman
inside. For most women trying to make it in the business world, it
must seem like a familiar story.
</P>
<P>
   There is love, of course, but for Mulan it is honor, not
romance, that drives her. By the end, she has learned about her
masculine side and become a self-assured woman.
</P>
<P>
   The music is witty, if not memorable. And, as is expected, the
animation is quite wonderful. Smartly, Mulan hasn't been drawn as a
Barbie doll.
</P>
<P>
   `Shooting Fish'' is a light confection that reminds you of those
swinging '60s British comedies, such as ``The Knack, and How to get
It.'' ``Fish'' even has a couple of Burt Bacharach songs in it just
to remind you. It stars Kate Beckinsale as Georgie, a med student
who moonlights as a stenographer. She is hired by a couple of con
men, Jez (Stuart Townsend) and Dylan (Dan Futterman), for one of
their schemes. After she figures out the con, she turns the tables
on the pair, who both grew up as orphans and were raising the money
to fulfill their dreams to have some kind of a family. Georgie
enlists them to raise money to save a medical facility. Love, high
jinks and laughs ensue. ``Shooting Fish'' is one of those little
gems that shouldn't be overlooked. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
