<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEVIL WITHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Vatican issued a new handbook for exorcism,
and the rites haven't changed much since 1614. The Vatican still
believes in the devil and possession. What's new is that the
Vatican now believes in psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   Next we'll find out they believe in Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The handbook warns that exorcists must ``not think possessed by
a demon someone who is suffering from some illness, above all
psychic'' or ``the victim of one's own imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good that the Vatican has recognized the importance of
treatment for mental illness. After all, our HMOs are trying very
hard to dodge the issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's also good that the Church still recognizes that the devil
is among us, or in us. Psychiatry has explored the vastness of the
Id and the depths of depression, but it's never been very good at
explaining evil.
</P>
<P>
   Every psychoanalytic study of Hitler or Manson falls into
cliches about anger at parents or feelings of sexual inadequacy.
The shrinks can't even explain the little evils of life, like what
possesses people to use sports utility vehicles as 3,000-pound
phone booths moving at 75 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, known
as ``the bible'' of the American Psychiatric Association, contains
descriptions of disorders from schizophrenia all the way down to
compulsive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no listing for Possession by the Devil Syndrome, or
PDS, as it would be known in syndrome-happy America.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrists have debated whether to include caffeine
withdrawal in their manual, but they've left evil, the toughest
problem of all, to religion.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I know. If he doesn't literally exist, he's made in
our image, as a Dostoyevsky character once put it. And the devil is
in the details, as a character named Ross Perot put it.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, does the devil like details.
</P>
<P>
   You want to exorcise someone? Try Kenneth Starr. The man is
obsessed with details only the devil and Paula Jones could love. To
prove the president had a few pathetic sexual encounters, he
produced a 445-page X-rated report with 2,600 pages of
detail-filled appendices.
</P>
<P>
   Starr isn't crazy. Something has gotten into that boy. Could it
be Satan? No, Starr isn't evil on a grand scale, unless you're
looking at him from the president's perspective. But he's foremost
among those I'd try to exorcise, just to see what fly-sized angels
of darkness flutter out.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for his benighted army of the night, Reps. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., Bob Barr, R-Ga., and the rest of the gang of 13. They may
not be tools of the devil, but if they are, they're very small
tools, like the little thingamabobs on a Swiss Army knife you have
no use for.
</P>
<P>
   If I were chief exorcist, high on my list would be the creative
geniuses at MSNBC who aired split screens of the pope arriving in
St. Louis with President Clinton's lawyers talking about Monica and
the fact that it's all about sex. At least it wasn't about
contraception, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, he's been possessed quite often in his life. The
exorcism of his recurring serpent spirits, however, has been
performed by thousands of journalists.
</P>
<P>
   What comes out if you exorcise David Hasselhof, Rupert Murdoch,
Jerry Springer, Linda Tripp, Courtney Love, Calista Flockhart,
Geraldo Rivera, any supermodel or all of those young people on
``Party of Five''? If it's Satan, at least we know they weren't
entirely empty.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Rolling Stones is they just can't convince
anyone they're possessed by the devil anymore. Now they're simply
the Grateful Dead Brits.
</P>
<P>
   You can't tell me the devil wasn't at work down at Intel when
they invented a chip that automatically identifies individual
computers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet itself is possessed by evil spirits. Intel was
about to give the flamers and hackers a powerful technology to
sneak into our private lives.
</P>
<P>
   The devil wouldn't have to waste a lot of time taking human form
and walking the Earth. He could virtually possess people.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the puniest of evils. What's got into Dan Quayle and
conservative activist Gary Bauer that makes them think they can be
president? Could it be Satan?
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's power lies in Mammon and his rich Family Research
Council. He even offered to pay the $90 registration fee of anyone
who would attend a conservative conference last week and vote for
him in a straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is running on name recognition, and yes, his name does
have an E on the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at my exorcism manual, I believe those guys aren't
possessed by even tiny devils perching on their shoulders. I think
each qualifies as a ``victim of one's own imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Call in the shrinks, and look up ``delusions of being somebody''
in the psychiatric manual.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
