<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRUGGLING-BOOKSHOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKSELLER STRUGGLES IN ERA OF INTERNET, MEGASTORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ When the Gaia Bookstore hit hard times, the
spiritually oriented, independent Berkeley shop turned to an
unlikely source of inspiration: the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, the only nonprofit, publicly held professional
sports team in the nation, turned to its fans when it needed cash
to finance stadium improvements in 1997, selling so-called shares
at $200 apiece and making the Wisconsin town its owners.
</P>
<P>
   With its business suffering under pressure from corporate-owned
and on-line booksellers, Gaia's owners have asked its employees and
customers to do the same: rescue the store from imminent closure by
investing $25 to $250, essentially becoming part owners of the
store.
</P>
<P>
   Gaia wants to use the cash to bridge its transformation from a
for-profit bookstore to a nonprofit cultural institution, a move
the founder said would keep the store alive.
</P>
<P>
   The bookstore may be the first in the country to try this
financial model. Gaia's co-owner and founder, Patrice Wynne, calls
it ``shared capitalism'' or ``venture capital of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole other investment model _ it's a community line
of credit,'' Wynne explained. ``If we want enterprises that are
quirky, original, entrepreneurial and reflective of the values of
the community, we have to make choices to give them economic
viability.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaia's story resembles the plot of the movie ``You've Got
Mail,'' which highlights the plight of the independent bookseller.
In the film, the opening of a book superstore forces actress Meg
Ryan's character to close her children's bookshop.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, Gaia, named after the Greek goddess of Earth,
was a thriving bookstore whose owners never dreamed of turning to
readers with their hand out.
</P>
<P>
   Annual sales grew steadily until 1997, when they hit a peak of
$1.4 million. Then, in 1998, sales began dropping 10 percent to 20
percent per month. In November, they plunged 39 percent from the
year-earlier period. Overall holiday sales dropped 25 percent at
the 12-year-old store.
</P>
<P>
   Wynne said the decrease is the result of increasing pressure
from on-line and chain booksellers.
</P>
<P>
   Gaia is not alone in hurting. In the past five or six years,
independent booksellers have gone from selling a third of all books
in the country to about 18 percent, according to the Northern
California Independent Booksellers Association.
</P>
<P>
   During that same time, more than 25 million square feet of
retail space dedicated to selling books was added nationwide, the
association said. And that space excludes on-line sellers and
general merchandise stores like Target and Safeway, which are
devoting an increasing amount of space to books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have economic conditions in this country where we have an
explosion of retail book space without the indicators that we're
cultivating new readers and that millions more books are selling in
this country,'' Wynne said.
</P>
<P>
   She surveyed her customers when sales began to drop, and they
told her they have less time than ever to read.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the handwriting on the wall, Wynne and her co-owner hit
on another novel idea: transform the bookstore, which holds about
250 readings a year, into a nonprofit cultural institution. The
store already had plans to move in the summer of 2000 into a larger
location in downtown Berkeley. But last month Wynne determined it
would be impossible to stay open for the next year and a half. She
told her customers Gaia would close in February.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, a longtime customer offered to donate $200,000 on
the condition that Gaia employees, customers and other supporters
match that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Wynne said that would be enough to cover $300,000 in debt to
publishers, distributors and banks as well as operating expenses
until the move. The nonprofit status offers tax reductions as well
as increased fund-raising opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In the Green Bay Packers model, investors get a certificate and
voting rights at the annual meeting. Wynne said Gaia's
``shareholders'' would have the satisfaction of supporting a
neighborhood institution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amy Thomas, president of the Northern California Independent
Booksellers Association, said other independents would be closely
watching Wynne's efforts. While Gaia has a devoted following,
Thomas said, Wynne's plan is still risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of running a retail operation under nonprofit
guidelines is tricky,'' she said, explaining that the nonprofit
structure of making decisions by committee tended to go against the
entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas said Wynne's focus on creating a cultural center
around a bookstore was different. ``She's very interested in ways
of making Gaia more than just a bookstore,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thomas could not predict whether Wynne would be
successful. Thomas, owner of bookstores in Berkeley and Oakland,
said customers had admitted buying books she had suggested on-line,
and seemingly loyal customers are still lured by the volume and
discounts at the mega-chains.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley author Melody Ermachild Chavis has been both a customer
of Gaia and an author at Gaia readings. Chavis said her first book,
``Altars in the Streets,'' published in 1997, would not have
survived without the promotion and support it had received from
Gaia and other independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berkeley should be able to save its bookstores the way other
towns save lighthouses and train stations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynne said she had been encouraged by the initial response. One
author wrote a check for $1,000. Smaller donations have been
trickling in for a total of about $3,000. If the store fails to
raise $200,000 by March, Gaia will be closed, with plans to reopen
as a community center.
</P>
</TEXT>
