<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS28-CO     01-28 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Live witnesses `unlikely,' top Republicans say
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First the House prosecutors were told to limit the
number of witnesses to three. Now they face the prospect that they
will not be allowed to call witnesses at all in the impeachment
trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Much to their dismay, Republican prosecutors say they have been
told by top Republican senators that it is ``unlikely'' that they
will be allowed to call live witnesses at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they have been told that videotaped depositions from
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, presidential friend
Vernon Jordan and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal will do just
fine. Senators seem more interested in pursuing a quick exit
strategy from the trial than pursuing the truth, several
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they were not at the Alamo or Valley Forge,'' said
Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), chairman of the House Judiciary Committee
and lead prosecutor of the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's frustrating is all these steps constantly intended to
limit us,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a member of the prosecution
team. For example, Barr said, the prosecution was not allowed to
rebut the arguments made by the White House legal counsel in
defense of the president.
</P>
<P>
   And it does not help that the road blocks to calling witnesses
are controlled by the Republican-dominated Senate, Barr said.
``This whole thing is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that the witnesses won't be allowed to
testify in person,'' said Barr, who added that he is so frustrated
by the Senate that he has decided to fly home to Georgia for a
slice of the ``real world.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say whether live witnesses will be called,
said John Czwartacki, press spokesperson for Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott. He said he knew of no conversations where members of
the Republican Senate leadership spoke with House proseuctors or
investigators about the prospects of calling live witnesses. ``You
cannot make a prediction until those depositions are taken,''
Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   Another House prosecutor stopped short of saying that the trial
is all but over, suggesting that the focus should now turn to to
the question of how to improve the impeachment process for future
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more like a man on the verge of retiring than
prosecuting, Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) said he wants to fix the
law allowing independent counsels to conduct the impeachment
investigation as well as the rules governing the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he would like to see a bipartisan task force tackle
the process so that ``the law will be left better than the way we
received it.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he said that he wanted to make sure that future
impeachment prosecutors are given the authority to do much of what
independent counsel Kenneth Starr did in his investigation, such as
the right to interview and obtain testimony from witnesses under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to change the law,'' Graham said. ``The
House impeachment process should not be limited, nor should it
hamstring the prosecutors' team to make its case.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he is ``frustrated'' by the push in the Senate to
end the trial. He said the House prosecutors have not been given
the chance to put on their entire case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a big record here and a political mood here for
closure,'' said Graham, about the chances of calling witnesses. ``I
don't think you have to be a rocket scientist to know you have to
cross great hurdles to have live witnesses,'' Graham said. But as
Rep. Christopher Cannon (R-Utah) put it, ``it does not take a genie
with a crystal ball to see the votes aren't there (to convict
Clinton).''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Cannon said, the public would judge the Senate's
decision on whether to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public will be unsatisfied,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the Democratic senators, save one, and some
Republican senators say they do not think witnesses are needed. The
record is extensive and the Republican prosecutors are unlikely to
garner the 67 votes they need to remove the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case has not been made for witnesses,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy (D-Mass.), who is upset that the Republican prosecutors
were even given permission to depose witnesses. ``The House
managers are calling the shots for the Senate Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from his private ``hideaway'' office overlooking the
Lincoln Monument, Kennedy said the House prosecutors had disrupted
government long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House managers are in danger of demeaning the Senate,''
Kennendy said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the president's staunchest foes say they do not
think live witnesses will be presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm a betting man, I say it tilts against live witnesses,''
said Sen. Robert Bennett (R-Utah).
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.), one of the
prosecutors responsible for deposing the witnesses. Hutchinson said
that it was important to remember that just last week, it appeared
doubtful that the House prosecution would be allowed to depose
witnesses at all. Now they have that permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an openness for our case to call witnesses,''
Hutchinson said. ``I can see the hurdles, but I'm hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchinson is one of the few that has such hopes on the
prosecution team. With others abandoning hope of live witnesses,
the question is prompted: Is this over?
</P>
<P>
   ``As Yogi Berra said: it's not over until it's over,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
