</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-ELEMENT (Undated) _ In a brief news story, the journal
Science reports a claim by Russia's main nuclear physics lab at
Dubna to have created Element 114 _ a long-sought target of
scientists hoping to reach the ``island of stability.'' Beyond the
element plutonium, the dozen or so additional elements created in
laboratories are all so unstable they survive for only tiny
fractions of a second. But theorists have predicted that if someone
could make Element 114 and higher numbers, the mix of protons and
neutrons in their nuclei might be stable enough for these elements
to survive for a while. The Russians claim to have reached this
goal, and that Element 114 seems to survive for about 30 seconds.
``Superheavy'' elements as stable as 114 may have very interesting
properties, and in any case, if the Russian claim holds up, a Nobel
Prize could be in the offing. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ The American Geophysical Union, the
nation's foremost organization of earth scientists, issues its
first-ever statement on climate change. It says there is a
``compelling basis for legitimate public concern'' about climate
change resulting from increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases
in the atmosphere. The present level of scientific uncertainty, the
paper says, does not justify inaction in the mitigation of
human-induced climate change and/or the adaptation to it. By
William K. Stevens. (500 words)
</P>
