<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-ETHICS-$ADV31-C     01-28 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ETHICS-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW HOUSE ETHICS CHAIRMAN ALREADY HAS FULL AGENDA
 &HT;    900&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the new chairman of the House ethics committee,
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, will barely have time to say howdy to
his posse before saddling up for two tough cases involving powerful
members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   The committee must complete an ongoing investigation of Rep. Bud
Shuster, R-Pa., the chairman of the House Transportation and
Infrastructure Committee, who is accused of improper dealings with
a developer in his district. And it will have to decide whether to
investigate accusations in the online magazine Salon that Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the Government Reform and Oversight
Committee, misused his office payroll and campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Smith said House rules prohibit him
from discussing any case being considered by the ethics panel,
officially titled the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct.
However, he expressed the hope he would be able to stress the
``advice and education'' aspect of committee responsibility rather
its investigatory duties.
</P>
<P>
   Providing more guidance on ethics ``could result in fewer
investigations,'' he said. ``An ounce of prevention is worth a
pound of anxiety and bad publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-generation Texas rancher from near San Antonio, Smith is
replacing Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, in what is perhaps the most
thankless job in Congress. ``It's an honor and a privilege to be
asked to serve'' as chairman, Smith said. ``But it is not always a
pleasure'' to carry out the tasks.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, demands for House ethics investigations have
sometimes been seen as tactics in partisan struggles. Some Capitol
Hill observers viewed the 1997 ethics case against then-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., as retaliation for the ethics case
that Gingrich led a decade earlier against then-House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after joining the committee as a member, Smith cast the
only vote against the reprimand and $300,000 fine that were levied
against Gingrich. At the time, Smith said the penalty was excessive
in relation to the violations.
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of years, Smith said, the ethics committee
has avoided the partisan rancor that has divided the House on
issues such as the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider the ethics committee not to be bipartisan, but to
be nonpartisan. We have checked party labels at the door,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some continuity,'' with eight of the 10 members having
served for a number of years, he said. The new members are
Republicans Rob Portman of Ohio and Dave Camp of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Few members lobby for this committee assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job that you can't brag about, but it is necessary,''
Smith said. ``We take our responsibility seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Those responsibilities will require quick consideration of
several complaints filed by the Congressional Accountability
Project, a private, non-partisan watchdog organization affiliated
with Ralph Nader, the longtime consumer activist.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, the Congressional Accountability Project
called for an investigation into the relationship between Shuster,
who has considerable influence over spending billions of federal
dollars on transportation projects such as highways and airports,
and Maurice Lawruk, a Shuster friend and a real estate developer in
Altoona, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, who was unopposed in winning his 14th term in November,
has denied any wrongdoing. ``I look forward to being fully
exonerated, as I have complied with all House and Federal Election
Commission rules,'' he told Congressional Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Accountability Project questioned Shuster's
links to Lawruk, who has financially supported the congressman's
grown sons in business ventures and whose own businesses have
profited from federal contracts. The group has also questioned
Shuster's ties to Ann Eppard, a transportation lobbyist who was
formerly Shuster's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ruskin, director of the Congressional Accountability
Project, charged that the long delay in finishing the Shuster
investigation shows that ``the ethics committee is well designed as
a shield to protect members from investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Smith as chairman, Ruskin said that the Texan's
record on ethics is so limited that it is premature to predict how
he will do on the job. As a subcommittee chairman, Smith led a
``very thorough'' ethics investigation of former Rep. Jay Kim,
R-Calif., he said, but then the full committee ``didn't recommend
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruskin said he didn't know how much Smith was involved in that
final decision. However, in addition to the Shuster probe, he said
his group has several requests for investigations pending before
the ethics committee:
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Burton kept ``ghost employees'' _ two women who who
did little or no work on the payroll of his congressional office
and campaign staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Rep. Corrine Brown, D-Fla., received illegal
gratuities, bribes or gifts _ including a $50,000 Lexus car _ from
a West African millionaire and a $10,000 payment from Rev. Henry
Lyons, a Florida minister.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Rep. Jerry Costello, D-Ill., accepted an illegal
gratuity and tried to obstruct a federal gambling investigation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
violated the House gift rule by accepting the personal services of
a private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   First elected to Congress in 1986, the 51-year-old Smith is a
graduate of Yale and the Southern Methodist University law school.
With the turmoil in the House leadership since Gingrich stepped
down following the November elections, Smith jokingly said he
thought he might get a ``reprieve'' in serving as ethics committee
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was called about the job around Thanksgiving by
Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., then the speaker-designate. But
Livingston abruptly resigned after revelations that he had had
extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what was going to happen then,'' said Smith. But
then the new speaker-designate, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., called
Smith in Texas over the Christmas recess and asked him to serve.
</P>
<P>
   He again said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
