<HEADER>
A2489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN29-CO     01-28 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DREAMSVILLE: History kept under concrete
 &HT;    (''Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    By Willard N. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was born in the farm community of Dunwoody, Ga., in the year
1928.
</P>
<P>
   My dad was a poor, hard-working farm laborer whose pay was not
more than $1 a day.
</P>
<P>
   We moved from one shabby shack to another during all my growing
years, and each time we had to battle a hungry horde of bedbugs
left by the former residents.
</P>
<P>
   We never knew the luxury of electricity, running water or any of
the comforts folks now take for granted. (Of course, the outhouses
were fully ``air-conditioned.'')
</P>
<P>
   We had meat almost every Sunday, and only on Sunday. We kids
always thought that eating end-cut ham was really living high on
the hog.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 6 years old we moved to nearby Sandy Springs, which
was big enough to have two grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The town center included nine or 10 stores and service shops on
three corners of the road crossing, and a baseball field on the
other corner. This was one of my favorite places.
</P>
<P>
   Our town had some mighty good players. We also had a huge umpire
with a booming voice that could be heard for a mile when he called
a third strike.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite memories is fishing in the Chattahoochee
River, either by myself or with my dad.
</P>
<P>
   A Prince Albert tobacco can of worms, a few rolled fishing lines
and a walk of several miles always made for the start of a perfect
day.
</P>
<P>
   Usually we could fish for a whole day and never see another
person. Nowadays the river is used by thousands.
</P>
<P>
   During my teen years, my best friend lived a couple miles away.
His family owned a radio, and we spent many happy hours listening
to ``The Lone Ranger'' and the other great radio shows of that day,
especially the mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that long, scary walk home late at night. I
always had a fear of rabid dogs, of which we had a good supply, but
those lonely walks are among my favorite memories.
</P>
<P>
   My most vivid memories are of the many small farms planted
mostly with cotton. In between grew miles and miles of woods,
mostly pine forests.
</P>
<P>
   It was this land that I loved and thought would last forever,
and I never dreamed of any other life.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1949 I joined the Air Force, and my little world was no
longer to be.
</P>
<P>
   It was my fortune to be transferred quite often, and my world
soon extended to half of the American continent and to the lands of
Japan, Okinawa and a war in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, my little town began to grow, and today it is a city
surrounded by cities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 we arranged a reunion of our 1941 graduating class of
Hammond Elementary School, and we now meet each year.
</P>
<P>
   This is all we have to remind us of our little town. Everything
we loved is now buried under buildings and roads, and, of course,
many of us have been buried as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Willard N. Smith lives in Riverdale, Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dreamsville,'' c/o
Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915. A
photo of the writer is optional. If your article is used, you will
receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
