</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION-DATA-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPULATION CONTROL IN CHINA
 &HT;    With CHINA-ONECHILD-$ADV31.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 31 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOE ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINESE DESPERATION FOR MALE OFFSPRING -- HOW IT CHANGES WITH
EACH CHILD
</P>
<P>
   Chart shows sex ratios of new infants born in China in 1990,
broken down by their number of older brothers and older sisters.
</P>
<P>
   With  &QL;  &QR; ............With  &QL;  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   older..................older..........Sex ratio at birth
</P>
<P>
   brothers...........sisters......( boys per every 100 girls)
</P>
<P>
   0 0 106
</P>
<P>
   0 1 149
</P>
<P>
   0 2+ 224
</P>
<P>
   1 1 116
</P>
<P>
   1 0 101
</P>
<P>
   2+ 0 73
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Throughout the world, a ratio of 106 boys to 100 girls is
the normal biological average of infant births. This slight excess
of infant male population typically declines to zero by age 20 due
to higher male mortality in infancy and childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Source: These are the latest published breakdowns, taken from
the 1990 Chinese Census. Figures adapted from ``Causes and
Implications of the Recent Increase in the Reported Sex Ratio at
Birth in China, ``Population and Development Review (Beijing, June
1993).
</P>
<P>
   THE RISE OF SEX SELECTION IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Chart shows sex ratio at birth in China. (Worldwide, the normal
biological average of infant births is 106 males for 100 females.)
</P>
<P>
   TIME PERIOD..................SEX RATIO AT BIRTH
</P>
<P>
   ....................................( boys for every 100 girls)
</P>
<P>
   1970- 1974 106
</P>
<P>
   1975- 1979 106 (1979 - start of ``One Child'' policy)
</P>
<P>
   1980-1984 108 (Mid-1980s - ultrasound machines become common)
</P>
<P>
   1985-1989 112
</P>
<P>
   1990-1994 115
</P>
<P>
   mid-1990s 118
</P>
<P>
   late 90s (unofficial) 120
</P>
<P>
   Sources: 1997 Beijing Symposium on Demography of China; China
Population Today (Aug. 1995 issue); Statistics of 1992 Fertility
Sampling Survey in China; Shanghai Express, cited in Associated
Press Jan. 1999 Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
   MILESTONES OF POPULATION CONTROL IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Early 1950s - Chairman Mao Tse-tung, fearing nuclear war,
encourages rapid population growth. China's population explodes
from 540 million in 1950 to 850 million in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   1958-1960 - Famine kills millions, shocking the ruling
communists to worry whether their crowded land could feed an
ever-expanding population.
</P>
<P>
   1973 - China adopts limited population control, calling on
citizens to have ``late-spaced-few'' children.
</P>
<P>
   1970 - China's fertility rate drops rapidly. Chinese women bore
an average of 5.8 children each in 1970, but by the end of the
decade this was down to 2.2 children each.
</P>
<P>
   1979 - China intensifies population policy, introducing
mandatory ``One Child, One Family'' policy that led in the early
1980s to compulsory sterilizations and abortions after unplanned
second pregnancies. The fertility rate drops further.
</P>
<P>
   1984 - China loosens ``One Child'' policy, allowing some rural
families to have a second child, especially if the first was a
daughter. Forced abortions and sterilizations are officially
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   1989 - Realizing that ultrasound machines are being used for
sex-selection abortions, the Chinese Health Ministry issues an
urgent notice ``strictly forbidding'' use of medical technology to
determine sex of fetuses. However, this and follow-up rules
throughout the 1990s are evaded or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   1990 - China exceeds 1.1 billion population.
</P>
<P>
   1995 - Fertility rate continues dropping. Now, Chinese women
have only 1.8 children each -- comparable to the rate in Western
Europe, and lower than the rate in the United States. ``One Child''
policy is still in effect in the cities, two-child families in farm
areas is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   2000 - China's population is expected to reach 1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: These bits of history could be super-imposed on Chart 2.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
