<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2495 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     01-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, QUAYLE AND THE QUESTION OF COMPASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give that man from Indiana credit. He knows political balderdash
when he hears it, although he might not be able to spell it.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle's denunciation of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' theme as a ``silly
and insulting term'' fused together by ``liberal Republicans''
suggests that his bovine-excrement detector is in pretty good
working order.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's easy to understand why Quayle would be offended by
this term. In using the adjective ``compassionate'' to modify
``conservatism,'' Bush appears to be suggesting that conservatives
have been hard-hearted and that some of them still are.
</P>
<P>
   True conservatism, a Dan Quayle might argue, is compassionate by
its very nature. It is a philosophy that stresses individual
opportunity, responsibility and accountability. And there is true
compassion in removing the fetters of excessive governmental
control and reducing taxes to allow individuals to make the best
use of their own resources.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, a real Quayleyan conservative is
committed to certain core moral and religious values that they
perceive to be the bedrock on which society rests. Those values
cannot be compromised just for political expediency, in Quayle's
view.
</P>
<P>
   So it is reasonable, from the Quayleyan perspective, to assume
that either Bush is not a true conservative or that he is flying
false colors with his accentuation of the compassionate in a effort
to win over independents, liberals and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle chooses not to dissemble, but rather to be what he is and
not to describe himself in a way that suggests otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not alone in that. It is noteworthy that some of
Bush's other rivals for the 2000 Republican nomination view Bush's
characterization of his new political philosophy with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who served as former
President George Bush's education secretary, has taken pointed
exception to the compassion thing, accusing Bush the younger of
using ``weasel words'' that in his view are ``cleverly and
deliberately put together to confuse people by meaning ...
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander hearkened back to the days when Bush the elder
admonished his fellow party members to be ``kinder'' and
``gentler,'' and he raised the poignant question: ``Is Mr. Bush
(the younger) trying to tell us that he's not like the rest of us
conservatives?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there came magazine publisher Steve Forbes, whose eyes are
again on the prize of the White House, also castigating Bush's
catch phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mealy-mouthed rhetoric and poll-tested cliches are no
substitute for a muscular, substantive agenda,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   The flat-tax advocate asserted that conservatives were
``betrayed'' after Ronald Reagan's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan's brand of pro-growth, pro-freedom conservatism wasn't
enough, we were told. What was needed was a `kinder and gentler'
approach. Promises were made, but had to be broken, we were told,''
Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Bush the elder's having reneged on his
``read-my-lips'' pledge to allow no new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the 2000 campaign is nearing, and we're hearing the
familiar chorus. Even a few of the names sound familiar,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm. Does anyone hear the opening chords of a cacophonous
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bush says he has not made up his mind yet about
running. And you have to take him at his word on that, even if,
like Quayle, one perceives a tad of duplicity in his compassionate
conservatism advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the 2000 election is likely to be the Texas
governor's only shot at the White House. He must either do it now
or limit himself to heading only a compassionately conservative
state government, which he appears to be trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   It is noteworthy, for example, that Bush is calling for an end
to social promotion in the public schools of Texas. Retaining
students who do not master basics or who fail the TAAS exams at
prescribed grade levels is a solidly conservative idea.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush would give them three chances to pass the test and
provide millions in state funds for summer school, tutorials and
extended day programs to help them pass, so that very few would
have to repeat a grade.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds ... well ... pretty compassionate. But Quayle would
probably spell it l-i-b-r-e-l-l.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
