<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2510 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-POPULARITY-NYTSF     01-28 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-POPULARITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT ACCOUNTS FOR THE POPE'S APPEAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Why would hundreds of thousands of Mexicans camp out overnight
at a chilly racetrack to gain a glimpse of Pope John Paul II? Why
would 20,000 St. Louis teen-agers chant ''We love you'' at a youth
rally, or 100,000 people attend a Mass at the city's Trans World
Dome?
 &HT;    As the head of a church with a billion members, any man would
attract crowds. But not with the fervency and love that this man
sparks. Though he is now very frail, with a visibly trembling hand,
when he speaks he moves crowds deeply. Why?
 &HT;    First, all know this may be his last visit. Second, he speaks in
the language of whatever people he has visited in his 85 trips
abroad. We admire a man whose native tongue is Polish, who took the
time to learn our language whether English, Spanish, French,
Italian, etc.
 &HT;    Third, he has keen insight on each culture and senses the
deepest feelings of those he is visiting. In his fourth visit to
Mexico, he mentioned the Virgin of Guadalupe six times in his brief
arrival statement. She appeared to an Indian peasant named Juan
Diego in 1531, a decade after the brutal Spanish conquest of the
Aztec empire. She asked him to tell the bishop to build a church on
the hill where she appeared.
 &HT;    But the bishop did not believe Juan Diego. On Dec. 12, 1531, she
appeared again and told him to pick flowers from the hillside,
gather them in his cloak and take them to the bishop. When Juan
Diego later opened his cloak, it bore her image, that of a
dark-faced woman.
 &HT;    The garment has hung ever since in a series of churches built on
the site. The newest basilica, a cylindrical building built in
1976, is the most visited shrine in the world, after St. Peter's in
Rome. ''For us, she is the mother of Mexico, and she is my mother.
She is dark like us. We adore her every day,'' Clara Frias Tapia,
55, told a reporter.
 &HT;    In St. Louis, the pope insightfully recalled the 1857 Dred Scott
decision, a Missouri case in which the Supreme Court declared ''an
entire class of human beings, people of African descent, outside
... the Constitution's protection. America faces a similar time of
trial today.'' He added, ''Today the conflict is between a culture
that affirms, cherishes and celebrates life and a culture that
seeks to declare entire groups of human beings -- the unborn, the
terminally ill, the handicapped and others considered `unuseful,'
-- to be outside the boundaries of legal protection.''
 &HT;    John Paul is also inspirational in what he says. He challenged
Catholics to ''stir up a new springtime of holiness'' across the
Americas, linking North and South America against the ''social
sins'' of violence and injustice. In the Basilica of Our Lady of
Guadalupe, he called for ''No more violence, terrorism and drug
trafficking. No more torture or other forms of abuse.'' Applause
erupted after each sentence.
 &HT;    In St. Louis he thanked ''the American people for the countless
works of human goodness'' which ''have been such a part of the
history of your country. I know that you will hear my plea to open
wide your hearts to the ever-increasing plight and urgent needs of
our less fortunate brothers and sisters throughout the world.''
 &HT;    In his first major message to the Americas as a whole, a
135-page exhortation, ''Ecclesia in America,'' he acknowledges that
many of the hemisphere's 500 million Catholics are only nominally
Catholic, but called on them to engage in intense prayer and to
seek ''a personal encounter with Christ.'' He said the church needs
''new order, methods and expression'' for a ''new evangelization of
America.''
 &HT;    He noted the Americas are tied together by immigration and Latin
America's $697 billion debt. ''The decision to speak of `America'
in the singular,'' John Paul explains in the document, ''was an
attempt to express not only the unity which in some way already
exists, but also to point to that closer bond which the peoples of
the continent seek and which the church wishes to foster.
 &HT;    ''In America as elsewhere in the world, a model of society
appears to be emerging in which the powerful predominate, setting
aside and even eliminating the powerless.'' While he called for a
''preferential love for the poor,'' he added, ''If evangelization
of the leadership sector is neglected, it should not come as a
surprise that many who are a part of it will be guided by criteria
alien to the Gospel and at times openly contrary to it.''
 &HT;    This pope speaks to all of us, inspiring any who listen. That is
his appeal.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
