   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Still struggling to find a
bipartisan roadmap for the rest of President Clinton's impeachment
trial, Senate Republicans and Democrats are jockeying over rules to
govern the deposition of witnesses and guidelines for proposals for
punishment short of removing him from office. By STEWART M. POWELL,
JUDY HOLLAND And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan warns that taxes will have to be raised or benefits cut
to maintain the long-term viability of the Social Security system.
By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ Attorneys for a gay rights legal
defense fund meet with Air Force officials to voice their concerns
about the record number of homosexuals released from the service
last year. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BASE-CLOSINGS (Washington) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen
proposes closing more military bases to save $20 billion that he
says could be better spent for military preparedness, salaries and
weapons. But some lawmakers say the proposal will be dead on
arrival in Congress. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTING (Undated) _ The Pentagon has made it tougher to
use of ground troops for anti-drug missions along the border, a
policy that stems from the shooting death of a young Texas man
nearly two years ago. Now troops can be deployed only with special
permission from the secretary of defense or his deputy. By THADDEUS
HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ John William King, a suspect in
the gruesome death of a black man, reportedly told three prison
inmates in the past that he planned to carry out such a murder. The
prosecutor in the Jasper case, however, says he doesn't believe the
inmates' story about King hatching the plot in prison. By RICHARD
STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BUDGET (Austin, Texas) _ Yielding to budgetary restraints,
Gov. George W. Bush unveils a slightly thinner package of tax cuts
than the one he proposed during his re-election campaign. But he
insists he isn't backing down on his tax-relief pledge. Bush also
proposes spending $96.4 billion over the 2000-2001 budget period,
an increase of $8 billion over current spending. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-EARTHQUAKE (Armenia, Colombia) _ Gougers drive up the
prices of everything from milk to coffins in this quake-devastated
Colombian city, where 200,000 homeless people await desperately
needed food, water and shelter. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-NETWORK (New York) _ Women.com Networks and Hearst New
Media &AMP; Technology, a wholly owned unit of The Hearst Corporation,
announce that they are forming a joint venture that will own and
operate the largest online network for women. By The Hearst
Newspapers. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When Senate Republicans, searching
for a face-saving exit from President Clinton's impeachment trial,
tried to get him to answer provocative questions in writing or in
person, they claimed they just wanted to be fair to him. But he
viewed it as a partisan trap. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-COLLINS (Miami) _ The Atlanta Falcons' largely
unheralded offensive line has been a big part of the team's
success, opening holes for Jamal Anderson and protecting the
always-vulnerable Chris Chandler. One of the keys to the
improvement of that line has been the emergence of Calvin Collins,
a second-year player from Texas A&AMP;M and Beaumont, Texas. By JODY
GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-TEXANS (Miami) _ The Atlanta Falcons are loaded with Texas
connections, from Dan Reeves with the Dallas Cowboys to Billy White
Shoes Johnson, Tommy Nobis, Harold Richardson. A look at the Texas
connection for both teams. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-NEIL (Miami) _ The Denver Broncos' offensive line has
quietly emerged as one of the best in pro football, thanks in part
to former University of Texas standout Dan Neil, a second-year
player. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
