<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-NETWORK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST AND WOMEN.COM ANNOUNCE NEW ONLINE VENTURE FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates with fresh quotes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Women.com Networks and Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology,
a wholly owned unit of The Hearst Corporation, announced Thursday
that they are forming a joint venture that will own and operate the
largest online network for women.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Women.com Networks will each own approximately 50
percent of the new enterprise, which will include the Women.com
network and the HomeArts.com network.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture will be called Women.com Networks and will
enjoy the highest reach among women's sites, with 6 percent of the
Internet audience as measured by Media Metrix, and well over 4
million women each month.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from both companies said the joint venture will focus
on increasing market share rather making money. Women.com has yet
to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we started, growth has been more important than profits
and that will continue,'' said Maureen McDaniel, president and
chief executive officer of Women.com Networks. McDaniel will be
chief executive, president and chair of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and chief executive officer of
The Hearst Corporation, added that Hearst's Lifetime cable
television network operated in the red for years before becoming
television's largest network for women. ``I've been hearing this
same question for years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel said that while the majority of the company's revenue
comes from advertising, she expects the firm's online shopping
service to eventually be its main source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack said Hearst wanted the merger with Women.com because the
two companies' audiences were ``perfect complements.'' Most of
Hearst's women's magazines and its online company HomeArts.com
focus on home and family issues, while Women.com specializes in
women and careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, we give women the whole range of information on work
and home,'' Bennack said.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of taking the company public, McDaniel and Bennack
did not rule out the possibility but declined to say if and when
the decision would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Women.com) was an attractive company before and that has only
increased with the merger,'' McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture will have distribution rights for the Hearst
women's magazine sites; promotion in Hearst's leading women's
magazines; on-air promotion from Hearst's television properties and
interests (which include Lifetime, A&AMP;E, The History Channel, and
the Hearst-Argyle group of network-affiliated television stations);
capital; and Astronet, the world's leading online astrology site
which was recently acquired by Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 Hearst magazine sites to be distributed by Women.com
Networks are Cosmopolitan, Country Living, Country Living Gardener,
Country Living's Healthy Living, Good Housekeeping, Harper's
BAZAAR, House Beautiful, Redbook, Town &AMP; Country and Victoria.
Hearst magazines reach 48 million women each month.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Creech, general manager of HomeArts, will assume the
role of senior vice president and general manager of the HomeArts
division in Women.com Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Women.com will each have four members on the
Women.com board of directors. The company's headquarters will
remain in San Mateo, Calif., the home base for Women.Com, with
significant operations in New York City, the headquarters for
Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Women.com and HomeArts ``will deliver
increased value to our audience, as well as to the advertisers who
want to reach women _ the most important market on the Web,''
McDaniel said. ``The cross media synergies that Hearst brings to
the venture add an exciting new dimension to the new Women.com
Networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Sikes, president of Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology, predicted
that the joint venture ``will create a new standard for destination
sites on the Internet, securing leadership in serving both
consumers and advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1995 launch of flagship site Women's Wire, Women.Com
Networks has grown into a network of women's oriented communities,
now featuring Women.com, HomeArts.com and Astronet. To the over 4
million women visiting each month, the Women.com Networks delivers
interactive content and services, supportive communities and online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The Women.com Networks can be found at www.women.com,
www.homearts.com and www.astronet.com and through AOL Keywords
``Women.com,'' ``HomeArts'' and ``Astronet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
