<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLASS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS TAKES IN-DEPTH LOOK AT IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Founding Fathers probably would never have
imagined the Constitution being mentioned in the same breath as the
Kinsey Institute sex survey _ even if it had been published 200
years ahead of schedule. But such is the strange world of
impeachment, '90s style.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Edelman, a professor of political science at the State
University of New York at Albany, welcomed more than 100 students
to ``Sex, Lies and Impeachment,'' a course where the hallowed
edicts of the Constitution mingle freely with the murky realities
of politics and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the tone for the first day of class on Wednesday,
Edelman informed his students that a recently published Kinsey
survey showed that 60 percent of students at a midwestern
university would not consider oral sex as sex _ apparently
supporting the view President Clinton asserted in grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Then Edelman went ahead and quoted from the Constitution, which
says that a president may be removed for conviction of ``treason,
bribery, or high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not gods and they're not infallible,'' he said of the
framers of the Constitution. ``But they're pretty damn smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The course, which examines current events in federal politics
even as they're unfolding, meets three times a week and includes
readings in four required texts. ``Wag the Dog'' and ``Primary
Colors'' _ both films that critics say parallel the Clinton
presidency _ are part of the syllabus.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman said he wants to look at the issue through the prism of
a ``culture war'' that has divided the nation on issues like
homosexuality and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   If student reaction on the first day of class was any
indication, some of that war may be fought in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very devoted Democrat,'' said freshman Allison Biller, a
political science major from Long Island. Biller, who served as a
page for House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt last summer,
believes that Clinton did what most Americans _ and most members of
Congress _ would have done under similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's right,'' she said. ``He did commit
perjury. But if you asked the whole Congress, many of them have had
affairs. I think the majority of Americans would lie about that
sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a view is abhorrent to junior Gil Woodard, a history major
from North Creek and a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the sex, it's using the resources of the White House
to cover it up,'' he said. ``The man who's in charge of the highest
office of the land should have more responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelman said he planned to look at the history of the special
prosecutor law as well as precedents for Clinton's debacle, from
the Senate trial of Andrew Johnson to efforts to impeach Richard
Nixon during Watergate.
</P>
</TEXT>
