<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-TCU-TEX (Fort Worth) _ Southern Baptist conservative
leaders in recent years have enforced a strict conservatism on
professors in the six Southern Baptist-supported seminaries. The
Baptist Studies Program at Texas Christian University, established
in 1995, is a moderate alternative. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Another high-profile
evangelical, this time the Rev. Jerry Falwell, has stuck his foot
in his mouth. Falwell would like to take back his remarks made
recently stating that the evil Antichrist probably is alive today
and, of course, will be a Jewish man. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-Y2K-COX (Undated) _ Shaunti Christine Feldhahn, a
former federal reserve financial analyst who lives in Atlanta, has
started a project and written a book to help churches get ready for
Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SACRED HARP-TEX (Undated) _ Sacred Harp, or shape-note
singing, is one of America's oldest musical heritages and survives
to this day little changed from the 1800s, when it flourished in
rural communities in states such as Kentucky, Tennessee and
Alabama. Next Saturday, the Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Fort Worth will have its 15th annual ``singing,'' a
free event designed more for participation than listening. By Dave
Ferman.
</P>
<P>
   SWAGGART-ENDURES-HNS (Baton Rouge, La.) _ The sign with
directions to Jimmy Swaggart's Bible College is gone as are the
throngs at his Family Worship Center, but the voice endures on the
radio, pleading, as ever, for money. By Curtis Wilkie.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ The nation's seminaries and
theology schools need to start preparing a new breed of preachers.
By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-J-NYT (Undated) _ In the traditional interpretation of the
Bible, the Five Books of Moses are exactly that: Genesis, Exodus,
Leviticus, Numbers and Deuteronomy, written by Moses at God's
command. What may not be as well known is that during the last two
centuries, many biblical scholars have offered a different type of
analysis, concluding that those biblical books, also known as the
Pentateuch, are a compilation of four separate narratives, woven
together by ancient editors, or redactors, to create a single text.
By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
