<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS SOUND OFF ON TV CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Creider doesn't just dislike arts critics. He despises
them. Won't read them. Won't talk to anyone who reads them. Won't
read anyone who's writing about them.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the new NBC drama ``Providence,'' airing its fourth
episode at 7 p.m. CST Friday. He considers it a laid-back,
entertaining series about real people and not contrived characters
living ``where no one would want to anyway.'' (''NYPD Blue'' is
mentioned specifically, so I suppose he dislikes New York and New
Yorkers, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Critics hammered ``Providence'' mercilessly. Mike's relationship
with critics didn't crumble there, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I didn't read a word of what the critics had to say
about `Providence,''' Mike says in a tersely worded e-mail, a
response to a story he did read, about the wide gap between
critics' and viewers' tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he put any stock in what any critic has to say about
anything: TV shows, movies, music, ``or the price of tea in
Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I view most critics, if not all, as frustrated people who are
not talented enough to produce a film, TV show, or record,'' he
continues. ``So to keep their noses in the business, they get a job
as a critic.''
</P>
<P>
   For credibility, Mike mentions a journalism degree ``from a
reputable college,'' one that doesn't give him license to be a
critic about anything having to do with the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you guys wonder why people like me don't pay attention to
the critics,'' he says near the end of his e-mail. ``Who needs
to?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, those who don't want to be led by the publicity machine of
the networks, for one. Taking critics out of the equation means
networks are your only source of information. True, far too many
critics write for themselves and other critics. Even more think
that bulldog writing tactics entertain readers. But a critic's job
is to give programming a social and historical context, and to
produce some sort of judgment, one that should be used as a
guidepost rather than as the final word.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Providence,'' many readers wrote about their love for
the series, but others actually agreed with critics. One was Liz
Valente, who finds the show ``sappy.''
</P>
<P>
   She also felt that the episode about the autistic child insulted
her intelligence. Her theory of its success? ``There's nothing
decent on in that time slot other than `Legacy,' which I thoroughly
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz thinks the networks ``should realize that for years they
have ignored Friday nights for good programming. I hate to tell
them, but not everyone goes out on Friday nights, and many people
who are out there working hard look forward to a quiet evening at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks also finally seem to be realizing, after years of
success from series like ``The Simpsons,'' that animation works.
It's a genre in which writers can get away with more than they can
in live-action series. But the creators of ``The PJs,'' airing
Tuesdays on Fox, found out quickly enough that race is still a
sensitive area.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an essay about the Fox series and the protests it
created, Curvie Hawkins, who grew up in an urban, inner-city
setting, writes that seeing characters tossing down 40-ounce malt
liquors was ``an objectionable moment.'' But overall, he saw
nothing that he hadn't witnessed on comedies like ``Married ...
With Children,'' ``Roseanne,'' ``South Park'' and ``Martin.'' ``No
more,'' he writes, ``no less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the current protesting group will find a more
salient purpose for displaying their anger, hopefully toward a
cause that will have a positive effect on conditions of people who
live in the projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin, who lists his age as 37 and his TV entertainment
during the '70s as ``Good Times'' and ``Sanford and Son,'' offers a
different take. ``The main problem with `The PJs,' at least in the
episode that I've seen so far, is that it isn't funny,'' he writes.
``The only interesting thing about it is the animation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Curvie sees a red flag in a series that is threatened by
protests. ``I recall that protesters created the cancellation of
one of my favorite shows in the '90s, which was `South Central.' I
still have a few episodes that ran on videotape. I hope that
doesn't happen with `The PJs.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. ``The PJs,'' despite the protests (and lukewarm
response from critics, Mike) is doing quite well in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
