<HEADER>
A2545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKE     01-28 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TIME STANDS STILL, NOT PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palm Beach, Fla., is beloved for its Spanish-style shopping
arcades and 1930s Mediterranean Revival mansions designed by
society architects like Addison Mizner and Maurice Fatio. The
Historic Preservation Society of Palm Beach has strict guidelines
to protect these old buildings as well as the town's charming
wooden bungalows. Very few houses are modern or contemporary. It's
not Miami Beach, you know.
</P>
<P>
   So it's striking that at least eight of the 84 dealers
participating in the Palm Beach International Art and Antique Fair,
which opens Friday in West Palm Beach and runs through Feb. 7, are
showing Art Deco and 20th-century furniture and objets d'art.
</P>
<P>
   They are not well known to the public in the United States, but
are favorites among European collectors and New York interior
designers. Jean-Claude Ciancimino, who specializes in Art Deco
furniture, is from London. Jacques De Vos and Robert Vallois are
from Paris, Philippe Denys from Brussels, and Galerie Beyrie from
New York and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Even French companies that concentrate on antiques of other
periods, like the wallpaper dealer Carolle Thibaut-Pomerantz and
the 18th-century furniture dealer Ariane Dandois, have some
20th-century works.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of 18th-century French and English furniture
and shabby chic,'' said Ciancimino, a dealer for 40 years who once
concentrated on English Regency and Neoclassical antiques. ``They
want to live in cleaner surroundings. The public is now realizing
how important this period is.'' He has focused for 10 years on Art
Deco, the fashionable style from between the wars.
</P>
<P>
   He is selling a pair of ebony-veneered screens designed about
1930 by Jean-Michel Frank, the French decorator and furniture
designer. Each screen has six handsome, unadorned panels that are
eight feet tall; they are simple and architectural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank stripped the rigid late-18th-century forms of their
ormolu and applied sumptuous veneers,'' Ciancimino said. ``He
reduced furniture to its simplest expression, limiting its
decoration to flat surface areas.''
</P>
<P>
   John Saladino, the New York interior designer, called Frank ``a
follower of simple geometric forms,'' adding: ``That's why his work
is so timeless. Frank let the wood or shagreen or cracked eggshell
be the decoration. He held back on ornament.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, the great-uncle of Anne Frank, was born in Paris in 1895.
His two brothers were killed in World War I, his father committed
suicide and his mother was placed in a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris Frank studied law. Then in 1927, he commissioned a new
decor for his apartment from Adolphe Chanaux, a Paris designer who
had worked with Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann, the 1920s designer who was
part of the 1925 Paris exposition that gave Art Deco its name.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Frank and Chanaux went into business together, catering to
clients like the couturier Elsa Schiaparelli in Paris, Count Cecil
Pecci-Blunt in Rome and Nelson A. Rockefeller in New York. Frank
also worked on the Riviera villa and Paris apartment of the
Viscount and Viscountesse Charles de Noailles, a society couple
known for their daring taste.
</P>
<P>
   Their Paris residence on the Place des Etats-Unis is still
considered one of the most important modern interiors of the
century. When Jean Cocteau saw the sparseness of Frank's decoration
there, he is said to have quipped, ``Pity the burglars got
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank did projects with other artists and designers, including
Emilio Terry, Christian Berard, Diego and Alberto Giacometti and
Dali. ``You have to remember these people were all working
together,'' Ciancimino said. ``They all copied each other. Unless a
piece is signed, it's hard to tell who did what.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallois Gallery is showing a glamorous sofa in Macassar ebony
designed by Ruhlmann, who was known for his sumptuous wood veneers.
The sofa, with slim, rectangular silvered bronze feet, is in the
form of a sleigh bed, with a silver mattresslike seat cushion and
round silver bolsters. The dark ebony is inlaid with fillets of
ivory. It costs $340,000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vallois is also selling a dressing table fit for a movie star.
It has an oval mirror flanked on both sides with black lacquered
wooden drawers. The top is covered in shagreen. It was designed
about 1925 by Pierre Legrain, a modernist who revolutionized the
art of bookbinding.
</P>
<P>
   Vallois has an exceptional black lacquer and gold leaf screen
created in 1931 by a Japanese lacquerist named Hamanaka, who worked
in Paris. He is not well known, but Barbara Deisroth, Sotheby's Art
Deco specialist, said it was Hamanaka who taught lacquering
technique to Eileen Gray and Jean Dunand. The dramatic screen, with
a Zorro-like zigzag in black, is $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Denys, the Brussels dealer, is showing a Dunand collector's
cabinet in blond tortoise-shell lacquer from about 1935. Dunand,
who was Swiss, moved to Paris and, beginning in 1919, began
producing lacquered panels and tables for Pierre Legrain, Eugene
Printz and Ruhlmann to incorporate into their works.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thibaut-Pomerantz, a private dealer who divides her time
between Paris and New York, is selling a pair of Art Deco wallpaper
panels manufactured in 1928 by Stephanie of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   She said she will display them with a group of period crystal
lamps, a lemonwood console by the Parisian decorator Jean-Charles
Moreux ($20,000) and an Austrian chest in pearwood and mahogany
attributed to Dagobert Peche, the Austrian architect who served as
co-director of the Weiner Werkstatte in Vienna from 1917 to 1923.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Deco furniture is strong. ``There has been a big
change in demand in the last two years,'' said Peter Loughrey, an
owner of L.A. Modern Auctions. ``Things that weren't moving at all
are now selling for double the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rogin, a dealer in 20th-century design at 21 Mercer
Street, in Manhattan, who is not at the fair, said: ``The auction
houses are getting unbelievable prices for the big names, like
Rateau, Frank, Gray and Chareau. Prices for signature pieces are
going up 20 to 40 percent per year.'' Rogin sells cheaper examples,
like a Jacques Adnet club chair from 1928 ($6,000) and a pair of
1925 mahogany and seagrass chairs by Francis Jourdain ($12,000 for
the pair).
</P>
<P>
   The prices don't surprise Ms. Deisroth of Sotheby's. ``Deco
furniture always does well; it's the most popular furniture of this
century,'' she said. ``The quality is unchanged from the 18th
century and it easily fits in with any kind of furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy McClelland of Christie's tried to explain why a cast
bronze armchair by Armand Albert Rateau sold at auction on Dec. 10
for $640,500, a world auction record for any 20th-century chair.
``The chair is quintessential in form and very rare,'' she said.
``But then, we've gotten record prices in every 20th-century
decorative arts sale this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did the dealers clamor to go to Palm Beach? David Lester,
the organizer of the fair, said, ``They regard this as a second New
York market. Their best customers are American, and they know their
clients are in Palm Beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
