<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SHESALLTHAT-TEX     01-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SHESALLTHAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT QUITE ALL THAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, the Baltimore Sun ran a story about millennials,
today's Internet-savvy, parent-friendly generation of teens and
young adults. We probably shouldn't begrudge filmmakers who want to
give millennials movies like ``She's All That,'' even though it
isn't very well-executed.
</P>
<P>
   This high-school ``Pygmalion'' tries hard but misfires
frustratingly on many levels. It's sensitive to its teen
characters' emotional confusion and respects their intelligence,
but it struggles _ and usually fails _ to represent those
qualities. Ultimately, though, its near-miss failure falls squarely
on the shoulders of its leads, whose performances don't do justice
to their appealing characters; and its director, Robert Iscove, who
can't bring his actors to the levels needed for the film to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Prinze Jr., cursed with that Judd Nelson/Patrick Swayze
look _ you know the one, in which the actor registers pain, anger
and confusion by knotting his brow as if trying to decipher a
complicated physics text _ plays Zack, a big man on campus who has
just been dumped by his narcissistic girlfriend. Belatedly noticing
his ex's superficiality, he bets a friendly rival ``(Varsity
Blues''' Paul Taylor) that he can turn any girl at the school into
a prom queen by giving her the right look _ and putting the right
guy on her arm. Their test case is Laney (Rachael Leigh Cook), a
noncomformist art student who's a reverse snob: She thinks she's
better than everyone else because she doesn't think she's better
than everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   How can this scenario go wrong? Let us count the ways: 1) Laney
is already by far the most interesting person at the school,
despite her geeky klutziness; 2) With her glasses and free-flowing
long hair, she's prettier before her ``makeover,'' which turns her
into a babe but conventionalizes her; 3) She hardly seems the type
to get caught in the prom-queen thing, even reluctantly; 4) Zack is
revealed from the outset as such a decent guy, it's hard to believe
that he'd make such a sexist bet.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a peripheral plot line in which Zack's ex (Jodi Lyn
O'Keefe) takes up with a guy from MTV's ``The Real World''
``(Scream's'' Matthew Lillard, in an incredibly irritating
performance), who's so self-absorbed that he'd rather watch himself
on TV than have his hottie girlfriend kiss his bare chest (maybe
``self-absorbed'' isn't the word; ``nuts'' is probably better). The
movie somehow fails in its attempts to lampoon ``The Real World'' _
the pop-culture equivalent of missing the broad side of a barn with
a rolling tank.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all its deep flaws, the movie is hard to dislike,
especially after you get past the indifferently written,
haphazardly directed opening scenes. The turning point comes during
a face-off between Laney and Zack's ex, as the movie finally
decides that it's going to find a tone and take itself a bit more
seriously. Still, Cook's performance is flatter than her character
deserves; she suffers seemingly eternal agonies by looking like
she's suffering indigestion _ heartburn instead of heartache.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the movie's best scene _ which has nothing to do with
the rest of the story and looks as if it was filmed by a guest
director _ illustrates what's wrong with it. During the prom, a
bunch of teens kick it in a production number set to Fatboy Slim's
irresistible techno-funk anthem ``The Rockafeller Skank.'' It's
completely unbelievable, yet it's great fun to watch, because it
teems with life and youthful vigor. If the rest of the movie had
this much energy, we might have had something.
</P>
<P>
   After the screening, local Miramax representatives were
collecting audience surveys, with most 18- to 24-year-olds rating
the movie good to excellent. So it's succeeding at reaching its
target audience, but there's a laziness in that, as if it were
trying just hard enough and not going the extra mile. Teen-oriented
movies don't have to be the province of teens; the best of them,
from ``Saturday Night Fever'' to ``The Breakfast Club'' to ``Say
Anything,'' cross generational lines because they find depths that
``She's All That'' doesn't try to reach.
</P>
<P>
   That Baltimore Sun story about millennials also stated that they
hate being lumped into groups. So here's a movie that, despite
apparently good intentions, argues that it's OK to be
individualistic, as long as you have contact lenses, the right hair
and the right clothes. Perhaps the filmmakers don't even see the
hypocrisy in that. Perhaps we can begrudge them films like this,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``She's All That''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Robert Iscove
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Rachael Leigh Cook, Freddie Prinze Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ language and adult situations, and for one
gratuitously gross food gag
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
