<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STILLCRAZY-TEX     01-28 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STILLCRAZY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAZED AND CONFUSED: AGING ROCK BAND STRANGE FRUIT IS RIPE FOR THE
PLUCKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the new comedy ``Still Crazy,'' the broken-up and reunited
(though broken down) '70s rock band Strange Fruit are more like
middle-aged crazy than ``still crazy.'' These 50-ish has-beens,
having disbanded 20 years ago, decide to get together for a tour.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1978, they were probably already on their way to
becoming the Jurassic Park Orchestra _ punk was raising its spiky
head for the first time, putting an end to the whiny bloat of a
band like the Fruit. Anyone who's read a favorable review of Mick
Jagger's alleged dancing will start to tear up with laughter when
the lead singer of the Fruit, Bill Nighy, hauls his ravaged
scarecrow frame onstage and contorts what's left of him into
rock-star poses. He's like Gumby without elasticity.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rea is the band's keyboardist, who manages a musty
dignity, even though he's been reduced to restocking condom
machines for a living. He wants to bring his mates back together,
even if it means losing the collectible that he's been saving for
an emergency: one of Jimi Hendrix's teeth, salvaged from a barroom
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Fruit are a salvage job themselves. The band's painful,
caterwauling brand of excess hasn't aged well. (They're the last
ignored artifact of the '70s for a reason.) The majestically
indifferent trophy wife of the Fruit's lead singer (Helena
Bergstrom) wants nothing to do with them. She's too busy tromping
around in their arena-sized castle, trying to lure buyers with
enticements like, ``The Queen slept here. So did Steve Winwood.''
But soon enough _ probably too soon, given what they sound like _
the Fruit are rotting and rolling again, thanks to their ace road
manager (the irrepressible Billy Connolly) who knows where every
body is buried ... even that of their leader, whose disappearance
finished off the band.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Still Crazy'' writers Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais
(contributors to Tracey Ullman's HBO series) also wrote ``The
Commitments,'' there they had a great novel as source material, and
a director (Alan Parker) who knew how to lovingly serve the script.
Still Crazy director Brian Gibson stumbles like an aged pop figure
who hasn't quite figured out less is more; you can almost hear his
arches fall as he trolls the stage.
</P>
<P>
   As written by Clement and La Frenais, ``Still Crazy'' slams its
jokes home into the broad side of a barn. It may not be adroit, but
a lot of it is very funny. It helps too that the Fruit's song
catalog _ anthemic roof-raisers _ were written by Squeeze's Chris
Difford (with production by Jeff Lynne and Foreigner's Mick Jones).
These lovingly re-created plow horses have a wheezing authenticity
_ it's as if Difford and company listened to the worst of Yes and
T. Rex, completely absorbed it and toiled until they crafted
hilarious sound-alike gems. Maybe ``Crazy'' doesn't have the
vicious vigor of ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' but unlike ``Tap'' it
carries affection for its protagonists and their game idiocy. If
you still chuckle when you hear the first crunching chords of
``Smoke on the Water,'' then bogard your way into ``Still Crazy,''
my friend.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Still Crazy''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brian Gibson
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Stephen Rea, Billy Connolly
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language, sexuality and drug use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
