<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING LIFE'S LESSONS ON THE FOOTBALL FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VARSITY BLUES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Van Der Beek, Jon Voight, Amy Smart, Paul Walker, Ron
Lester, Scott Caan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian Robbins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 106 minutes
</P>
<P>
   At a beery party, a deputy sheriff tells a high school boy
called Tweeter (Caan) that it's time to go home. Tweeter agrees and
takes off in the deputy's squad car, siren screaming, which he
later loads up with friends, all of them stark naked.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily that would get a guy in Dutch, but this is Texas
football country and Tweeter is the West Canaan Coyote's ace wide
receiver. With the team's 23rd district championship there for the
clinching, nobody wants to rile Coach Bud Kilmer (Voight), a nasty
piece of work even in the off-season, by disciplining his players
(especially those at the skill positions).
</P>
<P>
   Every West Canaan male Kilmer ever coached for the last 30 years
is not only still stuck in town, but slavishly worships him and the
great god football. A racist tyrant, the coach is the kind of man
who reacts to substandard performance by promising to ruin his
players' lives.
</P>
<P>
   He also isn't above locking the trainer's door and injecting
enough pain killer into a badly blown knee to get a star back in
the game regardless of the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of drugs or intimidation can revive the injured
quarterback Lance Harbor (Walker), so Kilmer inserts his backup,
Jon Moxon (Van Der Beek, the ``Dawson's Creek'' star).
</P>
<P>
   Mox is a West Canaan original: a sensitive, intelligent
teen-ager who doesn't regard football, or Kilmer, as the fount of
existence. He's also a pretty fair quarterback, which keeps the
West Canaan juggernaut on track. Even so, a revolt against Kilmer
is building, and with the inevitable big game inevitably in the
balance Mox mounts the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE They can dish it out on a west Texas football field,
and an aura of physical combat hangs over West Canaan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Plenty. Decked out in a whipped-cream bikini, a cheerleader
lures quarterbacks, having sex with one on top of a washing
machine. Later, the high school's sex education teacher gives a
torrid demonstration as a topless dancer at a local strip joint.
And don't forget Tweeter in the buff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Thoroughly laced throughout.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 Parents should be aware of the sex, but on an
entirely different plane the film has an estimable character in
Mox. Having applied to Brown, he has a lot to lose by defying
Kilmer, who threatens to taint his transcript, but he sticks to his
values and acts on his convictions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP The sex may still raise objections, but on
balance there shouldn't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC GLORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A two-dimensional Imax film (no headsets required) at the Sony
Theaters Lincoln Square &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kieth Merrill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No rating 42 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With elaborate corporate sponsorship and the official imprimatur
of the International Olympic Committee, Merrill's documentary about
the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, makes a grand if antiseptic
splash across the gigantic Imax screen.
</P>
<P>
   Events from Alpine and Nordic skiing to figure and speed skating
are presented one by one, exalted by high-blown and sometimes
ponderous narration that could never be accused of not taking
itself seriously. At one point, for instance, we are told
dramatically that ice hockey, a sport most people have at least a
passing familiarity with, is played with a rubber object called a
puck.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many engaging scenes. The film is at its best with
big vistas in events like the downhill, which gives a good feeling
of the immensity of the course and what it's like to be on skis at
80 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   For the roller-coaster effect, which is de rigueur in all Imax
films, there are rocket rides down the bobsled and luge runs. And
there may never be a better secondhand look at ski jumpers soaring
almost forever down a 90-meter hill.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that considers only victory and lofty ideals, losing
hockey players don't trash hotel rooms as they really did in Nagano
nor do figure skaters go sprawling. Nor, of course, is there any
hint of the current allegations of corruption over the selection of
Salt Lake City as the site of the 2002 games.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more genuine moments is the last-place finish in
cross-country skiing by a competitor from Kenya, a land with no
snow. An accomplished marathoner, he had trained for skiing in
Finland. ``It was great,'' his Finnish instructor says. The Kenyan
smiles broadly. ``It was terrible,'' he says. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY In the heat of competition, some may be mouthed, but
none is audible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-11 The littlest ones may not fathom every detail, but the
film is a wonderful spectacle for young children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP By this age, more sophisticated viewers may roll
their eyes ceilingward at some of the more flowery narration.
Still, they'll be enthralled at the sights on screen. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOU'VE GOT MAIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meg Ryan, Tom Hanks, Parker Posey, Greg Kinnear, Jean Stapleton,
Dave Chappelle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nora Ephron &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 110 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Ephron's film, based on Ernst Lubitsch's ``Shop Around
the Corner'' (1940), Kathleen Kelly (Ms. Ryan) runs a sweet little
children's bookstore, a fixture on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan, and exchanges wistful e-mail messages about bagels and
life with Joe Fox (Hanks), scion of the Fox superstore book chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the over-30 room and there he was,'' Kathleen
tells a friend. She means chat room. Maintaining strict Internet
anonymity, she and Joe don't know each other's identity but
gradually come to acknowledge a strong attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, their flesh-and-blood selves live in the same
neighborhood and regularly and unwittingly cross paths. Eventually
they meet, never realizing that they're e-mail correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   His new superstore is about to put her shop out of business. He
doesn't seem too sorry, but he has a golden retriever and is not
that bad a fellow. She is determined to be civil and carry on.
</P>
<P>
   She loses her shop. Now they run into each other everywhere,
still unaware of the Internet connection. They both get rid of
inappropriate live-in partners (Ms. Posey and Kinnear). The stage
is set for the big revelation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-11 The film is harmless, but it is too slow-moving and
ruminative to hold the attention of younger children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP More romantically inclined viewers will enjoy
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1626EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
