<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2576 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEW-TEX     01-28 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR MOTLEY FOOL'S INVESTMENT GUIDE HAS YET ANOTHER SEQUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fools are back, but the Ladies are conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about some distorted board game, but rather of
popular investment books and their continual sequels.
</P>
<P>
   The Motley Fools, aka Tom and David Gardner, are among the
leaders of the pack in investment book sales. They have produced a
book e year for three years running, with a workbook published in
that time frame, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardners say their latest book ``closes out a trilogy of
investment works.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait for 2000, to see if a fourth book emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Beardstown Ladies, that affable group of senior
citizens from Beardstown, Ill., who rose to talk show fame after
their investment books came out, are MIAs in the annual surge of
investment books for January.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that the Ladies have taken to hiding after a
journalist ran their numbers last year and found that they
significantly inflated their portfolio's percentage of total gains.
The ladies said it was an error on their part. If so, it's one that
their publisher should have found long before their first book hit
print. It's little wonder that they are still under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   That said, let's see what the Fools have to say this year.
</P>
<P>
   Their book is ``The Motley Fool's Rule Breakers, Rule Makers:
The Foolish Guide to Picking Stocks'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 340 pages,
$25).
</P>
<P>
   The Gardners have used their feature on America Online and their
Web site to propel themselves into investment guru status in the
past few years. By showing investors how to act Foolishly, meaning
to do their own investing rather than relying on brokers or mutual
funds, the Gardners have created quite a following. Their
interactive investment advice, as well as the posting of their
portfolio's performance with daily updates, attracted millions to
their Internet sites. Their previous books, outlining their basic
investment strategy, have all been bestsellers.
</P>
<P>
   This book discusses exceptions to their typical strategy that
have shown up in their portfolio. Or, as they write, ``an attempt
to answer one of the more frequently asked questions on
www.fool.com: `Why did you guys buy America Online and Amazon.com?
They don't seem to fit any of your parameters!'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, those stocks and others the Gardners list, including
Starbucks, Microsoft, Whole Foods Market and Wal-Mart, are examples
of another genre of investments that the brothers call ``Rule
Breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The business world is full of rules made by industry leaders,
they say. ``In order for a new business to come into existence and
gain significance, it must consciously break those rules. ...
Entrepreneurs therefore invent new rules or change the game
altogether.... All great businesses begin by being Rule Breakers,''
they write.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardners identify six traits investors can look for to find
rule-breaking companies. For example, the companies must be the
market leader and first mover in an important, emerging industry,
the Gardners write. They go on to detail those traits and provide
numerous examples of companies that do and do not fit those
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rule Makers,'' the other investment strategy found in their
book, deals with less volatile and less risky companies for
investment. The rule makers are actually the rule breakers that
have grown up and become stable, rock-solid industry leaders. They
are the kings, or legalized monopolies of the business world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They maintain high valuations, wield outlandish power in their
industries, and exert great influence over the business world at
large,'' the Gardners write.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies make great long-term investments and are of
tremendous benefit to society in that they provides good and
services at unparalleled combinations of high quality and low
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Among that group are Dell Computers, the Gap, Cisco Systems,
Intel and Microsoft (again).
</P>
<P>
   The latest Fools book is as well-written as the others and
certainly offers more food for thought. It will be interesting to
see what variation on the variation they come up with, however, to
continue the flow of book sales.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cover Blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels in the Workplace: Stories and Inspirations for Creating
a New World of Work''
</P>
<P>
   By Melissa Giovagnoli
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $22
</P>
<P>
   Whether starting a program to teach underprivileged teen-agers
how to run their own businesses, or running a work program for
homeless men or fighting against a major polluter, some people in
the workplace inspire like angels, Melissa Giovagnoli says. She
discusses the traits the ``angels'' have in common and provides
hundreds of anecdotes about what they are doing. Her book is
inspiring and informative.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Landlord's Legal Guide''
</P>
<P>
   By Marcia Stewart, Ralph Warner and Janet Portman
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press, $34.95
</P>
<P>
   From advertising rental property to evicting unruly tenants,
this book covers
</P>
<P>
   legal issues for landlords. Now in its third edition, it has
been hailed as a bible by real estate trade publications. All three
authors are with Nolo Press, a major publisher of self-help legal
guides. The guide includes a computer disk with 25 legal forms
pertaining to rental property.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Dictionary of Economics''
</P>
<P>
   By Graham Bannock, R.E. Baxter and Evan Davis
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   From accelerator coefficient to zero-sum game, this book
provides clear, quick definitions of the easiest and most
complicated economic terms. It took the authors 439 pages to
complete the task, in quite small print. But this fourth edition
should define any business term you need.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
