<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAILING-STUDENTS-HNS &LR;      01-28 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAILING-STUDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS SAY CLINTON PLAN DOESN'T PASS MUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Illinois, New York.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It sounds simple enough: If you fail in school,
you don't graduate to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   But when President Clinton raised the idea in his State of the
Union address of a national policy to end so-called social
promotion, educators say he oversimplified an issue far more
complex than the either-or proposition of promoting or holding back
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how good that sounds to people ... it's not a sound
educational practice,'' said Warren Gemmill, assistant
superintendent of the Saratoga Springs City School District, which
he said holds back few students.
</P>
<P>
   Social promotion is the practice of promoting students
performing below grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Schenectady school district in upstate New
York ended the practice of social promotion _ a move, said
Superintendent Raymond Colucciello, based on the idea that ``if we
socially promote, we're doing an injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   The district increased support along with the policy, he noted,
instituting summer school and tutorial programs and alerting
parents early on to problems. The district did not immediately
provide statistics on how many children have since been held back.
</P>
<P>
   But some educators are skeptical of plans to eliminate social
promotion. The president failed to acknowledge research suggesting
that holding students back can increase the likelihood of them
dropping out of school altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Education said that Clinton was not
advocating holding children back, but wants to encourage schools to
pay closer attention to struggling students. Schools that fail to
end social promotion practices would risk their federal aid, which
accounts for about 7 percent of school funding nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we mean and what the president means is putting in place
programs that help all children succeed,'' said Department of
Education spokeswoman Julie Green. ``This is really an effort to
get standards into the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address on Jan. 19, Clinton said he would send Congress a
five-point Education Accountability Act that would require every
district receiving federal aid to take certain steps, including
ending social promotion.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal was hailed by the New York State United Teachers
union, which in a 1996 survey of 1,000 members found that 61
percent felt pressured to promote students regardless of their
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This union has always believed that social promotion is really
a harmful practice, that it's really the Achilles' heel,'' said
union spokeswoman Linda Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting an unready student and forcing them to struggle with
new material when they haven't mastered the old is ``far more
damaging to self-esteem,'' Rosenblatt said. And, she said, ``It
makes a high school diploma meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   But educators, including the New York State United Teachers, say
such a change must be backed up with special programs to give
at-risk students the best possible chance of success. That means
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just as easy as saying, `OK, we're not going to
just promote children,''' Rosenblatt said. ``That's were the rub
is. Some people say, we don't have the money to do that. Our
position is, we can't afford not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton alluded to the complexity of the issue, saying, ``We
can't just hold students back when the system fails them.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposed tripling the $200 million the government now
provides for summer and after school programs, to help districts
prepare students to advance a grade.
</P>
<P>
   That grant program, however, already is fiercely competitive;
out of 2,000 applications last year, only about one-third were
funded. ``Obviously, that still is only a drop in the bucket,''
Green said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited the Chicago school district as an example of how
eliminating social promotion can work. Under Chicago's 3-year-old
program, children in grades three, six, eight and nine must pass
their classes, score well on standardized tests or successfully
complete a summer school program.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago last summer graduated the most eighth graders to high
school ever _ 28,160 _ including more than 4,700 who underwent the
summer program. About 3,000 children were either held back or moved
into a special transition program.
</P>
<P>
   But one educator said the short-term results Clinton praised in
Chicago ignore 70 years of studies that for the most part show a
long-term downside to retention.
</P>
<P>
   Gemmill said one study showed that students who were held back
were three times more likely to drop out of school as children of
even lesser achievement who were promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it sounds great to get tougher, it's not borne out by
hundreds and hundreds of studies,'' he said, adding that holding a
student back leaves the child, along with classmates, siblings and
even parents, with a perception of failure. ``It follows them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
