<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH-COX     01-28 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    A YEAR LATER, FBI STILL BELIEVES RUDOLPH IN N.C. MOUNTAINS
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ This seems such an unlikely place to find a
domestic terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Serious crime is rare and people in this town of 2,600 don't
hestiate to speak to strangers. The streets are adorned with
rambling old Victorian homes and stately churches. A few families
still keep chickens in backyard pens. From anywhere in town is a
breathtaking view of 5,000-foot high peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet federal authorities remain convinced that accused bomber
Eric Robert Rudolph still is somewhere in these mountains into
which he disappeared a year ago. Led by the FBI and the U.S. Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, about 200 federal and state
agents continue the 12-month search on foot and in the air.
</P>
<P>
   They remain convinced that Rudolph is here because they have no
proof he is anywhere else. He knows the mountains, they point out,
and the dense forests where he learned survival skills as a
teenager near his remote home in the Nantahala community. The
country is so rough that it can conceal an airplane crash with no
trace to be found.
</P>
<P>
   And some residents think he still is here because he is getting
support from local sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   An old sewing machine factory along the railroad tracks is now a
heavily guarded command center for the Southeast Bomb Task Force.
Helicopters rumble over the town day and night. Each morning,
squads of law officers, often with tracking dogs, fan out over the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, 32, a carpenter and former soldier, is charged with a
series of bomb attacks that began at Centennial Olympic Park, where
one person was killed and 111 others injured, during the 1996
Summer Games and ended with the Jan. 29, 1998, explosion at a
Birmingham abortion clinic that killed an off-duty police officer
working as a security guard and seriously injured a nurse. He also
is accused of setting bombs in 1997 at a Sandy Springs abortion
clinic and at an Atlanta lesbian nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say he was motivated by extreme anti-government and
anti-abortion views. He is on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list and
carries a $1 million reward on his head.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become one of the most intense manhunts in American
history, the pursuit of Rudolph also has resulted in painful media
scrutiny of this town and surrounding villages. Community leaders
contend the area has been linked unfairly to anti-government
extremists who have settled in the mountains the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of people here support what (the agents) are
doing,'' Mayor Jim Dailey said. ``We may have some militants around
here, but no more than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is difficult to find Rudolph sympathizers in Andrews,
it is not so difficult in the rural community of Nantahala north of
here. In a high and remote mountain valley, Nantahala is where the
Rudolph family moved from Florida when Eric Rudolph was 14 in 1981
and where he lived off and on until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here I'd say it's 50-50 as far as the people who would
turn him in and those who wouldn't,'' said John Wagner, as he
sipped coffee in Nantahala's only restaurant, The Lake's End Grill.
``A lot of people say he killed people who were killing babies.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Wagner's wife, Joy, who writes a regular column for the
weekly Andrews Journal, disagrees. ``I think those who support him
are just a few.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the town of Andrews has tried to make the outside
law enforcement agents feel welcome. Over the Christmas holidays, a
number of agents were invited into local homes for dinner, while
residents delivered food to the command center.
</P>
<P>
   Agents have presented programs to Scout groups and attended
local churches. FBI and ATF officials have maintained for months
that most citizens have cooperated fully, offering information
about Rudolph's background and tips about his possible whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the mayor and others are at a loss to explain why on a
chilly night in November several rifle rounds were fired at the
federal compound. One bullet grazed an agent inside the building
and narrowly missed another.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged in the shooting and federal agents
declined to discuss a possible motive for the attack. A few days
after the shooting, leaflets were distributed in town calling the
investigators ``jack-booted thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the community, theories about who fired the shots range from
Rudolph sympathizers to drunken teens or maybe a jealous husband.
Some residents say they feel agents overreacted by continuing to
press misdemeanor charges of impeding the investigation against a
local mechanic arrested the night of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Rogers, 45, admits to shining his son's toy laser on a
surveillance helicopter as it flew over his house. Agents said they
thought it was a laser-targeting device used on sharpshooting
rifles. Rogers was quickly swarmed by at least 10 agents who threw
him to the ground and handcuffed him, recalls Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit it was a dumb thing to do,'' says Rogers, a life-long
resident of Andrews, who says he was not aware of the shooting at
the time. ``But I was just playing with my little boy's toy laser
he got for his birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were led the day after the Birmingham blast to
this rugged area where Cherokee and Macon counties. The
registration for a gray Nissan pickup truck seen near the clinic
was traced to Rudolph, who rented a mobile home in neighboring
Murphy. He was charged Feb. 14 in the Birmingham attack. In
October, federal agents declared they had enough evidence to also
charge Rudolph in the three metro Atlanta bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The last verified sighting of Rudolph immediately after the
Birmingham explosion was Jan. 30, 1998, when he rented a video,
Kull the Conqueror, in Murphy. He resurfaced briefly in July and
obtained food from a friend living in the Nantahala community.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, George Nordmann, a noted local herbalist who owns a
health food store in Andrews, waited four days before alerting
authorities. By then, Rudolph again had slipped into the forest.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, authorities said Rudolph had obtained six months'
worth of food. They think he now may be hiding in a bunker, cave or
old mine and may be running short of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel he is still here,'' Woody Enderson, the FBI agent in
charge of the task force, said at a recent media briefing. ``There
is no evidence that he has left, and, as we told you before, he has
to have food, and may make a significant move to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   That move may come soon, Enderson added.
</P>
<P>
   It would be virtually impossible for the fugitive to live off
the land, especially in winter, and not be conspicuous about it,
says Burt Kornegay, a guide who has led numerous hiking and camping
trips into the mountains where Rudolph is thought to be hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's either dead and been eaten by a bear or someone is
helping him.''says Kornegay, owner of Slickrock Expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   With food, the hiding places are nearly unlimited. The 30-mile
prime search area is mostly within the Nantahala National Forest.
The remote peaks are thick with stands of hardwoods, which shade
jungle-like tangles of laurel and rhododendron. Water is readily
available from a myriad of springs and creeks.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, a private plane piloted by the father of an
agent flying to visit his son crashed into the remote ridges. The
plane has yet to be found, despite an intense air search.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't find something as big as an airplane that is
fixed in one place, what makes people think it would be so easy to
find a person who can move around?'' asks former Cherokee County
Sheriff Jack Thompson. Part of the search has concentrated on
trying to locate abandoned mines and caves in the area. Darren
Free, a Hendersonville, N.C., spelunker is assisting agents in
their search for old mines.
</P>
<P>
   Free says there are about 300 mines in the area, most of them
abandoned pits for digging mica, gold, corundum and other minerals.
Some are narrow tunnels dug back into the mountain, he adds, and
would provide excellent hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be very stressful on the agents,'' says Lee
Colwell, former associate director of the FBI and now director of
the University of Arkansas Criminal Justice Institute. ``They know
they are very vulnerable to him. In many ways he has the upper
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rudolph is receiving aid from an area resident, it does not
surprise Mark Potok, who helps track hate groups for the Southern
Poverty Law Center. Intelligence gathered by the Montgomery civil
rights organization indicates that western North Carolina is a
``center of anti-government activity,'' along with the Ozark
Mountains in Arkansas and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Potok contends that most of these people moved into the area
because ``there are few minorities there, it's very white. It's
rural. There's a lot of privacy. And it's the Bible belt and they
feel comfortable there.'' But Andrews Police Chief Clay Hardin, who
is also a minister for Mountain View Baptist Church, says just
because many residents are traditional Christian conservatives does
not mean they support the tactics of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that most people in this area are conservative and
are against abortion,'' he says. ``I don't think they would cover
up for him, though. In fact, many people have been helpful (to
investigators).''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rudolph may have escaped long ago from this area.
That is the opinion of Gary Perlstein of Portland State University,
a criminologist who has studied the militant anti-abortion
movement. He thinks Rudolph may have tapped into a sort of
``underground railroad'' for militants fighting abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who may not murder a doctor, who may not blow
up a clinic, but they understand why the person did it and deep
down have some empathy with them,'' Perlstein said. ``They are the
kind of people who would help move him across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
