<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-570(2TA     01-28 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-570(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIUMPHAL HOMECOMING  
 BACK FROM THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ Tony Bui was only 2 when his family fled
Vietnam in 1975 shortly before the fall of Saigon. He grew up in
Sunnyvale, Calif., and studied film at Loyola Marymount University
in Los Angeles. When he was 19, he returned to Vietnam for two
weeks to visit ailing relatives. ``I hated it,'' he recalled. ``I
hated the dust, the heat, the humidity. I hated the fact that my
grandfather didn't have a real toilet. I was very ignorant.''
</P>
<P>
   On his return to California, driving from San Francisco to
Sunnyvale in Silicon Valley, Bui found he couldn't get Vietnam out
of his head. ``I kept smelling Vietnam; I could hear the traffic,''
he said. ``It sounds strange, I know, but something happened. I
knew I had to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bui returned to Vietnam several times, staying with his
relatives, learning Vietnamese and eventually making a 30-minute
film, ``Yellow Lotus,'' based on a journal he kept. The movie,
about a poor fisherman who comes to Ho Chi Minh City, won awards at
several film festivals. That success led Bui, 26, to create a a
more ambitious drama, ``Three Seasons,'' the first full-length
American film shot in Vietnam since the war there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons,'' which was shown at the Sundance Film Festival
here, is to be released by October Films in April. Costing less
than $2 million, the English-language movie includes a mostly
Vietnamese cast but also features Harvey Keitel, whose involvement
was vital in getting it made. Keitel plays a returning Vietnam
veteran searching for a daughter he has never seen.
</P>
<P>
   The film, loosely based on characters Bui had seen or met, is
essentially about today's Vietnam in the midst of transition and
focuses on several disparate people. These include a cyclo driver
obsessed with a prostitute, a boy hustling watches and cheap
lighters, a girl hired to assist a reclusive spiritual master, and
Keitel's character.
</P>
<P>
   Bui, whose father was an officer in the Vietnamese air force
during the war, said filming was arduous. The 60 crew members _
half Vietnamese, half American _ were distrustful and hostile to
one another at first but eventually became friends. More
problematic, he said, was the Vietnamese government, which 4ept an
official, who often clashed with the director, on the film set at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many arguments and many threats of being shut
down,'' Bui said. ``You can't shoot a single frame of film without
a censor being with you.'' The government objected, of course, to
some material depicting poverty and prostitution, but some of the
concerns seemed odd.
</P>
<P>
   When the color red appeared in a scene, officials often
objected, saying it was a negative comment on communism. When a
character with a deformed face talked of being a poet at 21, the
officials strenuously objected because they felt it was a negative
comment on Ho Chi Minh, who took up his life's work at 21. Bui
changed the reference to 23.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally showed the full film as a courtesy to the
Vietnamese authorities several months ago, he was nervous. ``I was
freaked out,'' he said. ``If they didn't like it, they could ban me
from coming back. But they were so moved. They stood up and
congratulated me. They said it rang true.''
</P>
<P>
   Bui said he would keep returning to Vietnam. ``My sensibilities
are American, but what I am is Vietnamese,'' he said. ``I think a
lot of my life will be trying to determine what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Back From the Brink
</P>
<P>
   About 10 days before flying to Salt Lake City to drive to the
Sundance Film Festival, where she is appearing in two films, Ally
Sheedy was honored by the Los Angeles Film Critics Association for
her performance last year in Lisa Cholodenko's drama ``High Art.''
Ms. Sheedy shared the top women's acting prize with Fernanda
Montenegro of ``Central Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy, a one-time member of the Brat Pack of the 1980s and
a star of movies like ``The Breakfast Club'' and ``St. Elmo's
Fire,'' was stunned at the award. Before ``High Art,'' the career
of the 36-year-old actress had gone into such a downward spiral
that she thought of giving up acting, because she was barely
earning a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blindsided by the award; there were people in the
audience like Joan Allen and Bill Murray and Steven Spielberg,''
said Ms. Sheedy, seated in a Park City hotel room. ``To have come
from this place where I couldn't even get on a bad television
sitcom two years ago, where my agents at William Morris fired me
because I wasn't earning enough, where I felt just two years ago
like a washed-up, down-and-out, can't-get-arrested, teeny-bopper
actress _ it was mind-boggling for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy's intense performance in ``High Art'' as a
middle-aged, drug-addicted lesbian photographer has advanced her
career and certainly buoyed her confidence. But the scripts are
still not rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know; I think parts will come from strange places,''
said Ms. Sheedy, a likable and friendly woman who lives in New
York. She said the one positive turn in her personal life in recent
years was meeting David Lansbury, an actor whom she married, and
having a daughter, Rebecca, who is 5.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy plays disparate roles in her two films at Sundance.
In Allison Anders' ``Sugar City,'' a comedy-drama about the music
business, she portrays, as she put it, ``a very neurotic, very
successful production designer who can't find a good man in
Hollywood.'' In Steven Maler's ``Autumn Heart,'' she plays a
daughter of Tyne Daly in a family drama set across the class divide
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy is also set to start production next month for an NBC
drama, ``Our Guys,'' based on the true story of the sexual assault
of a retarded girl by members of a high school football team in
Glen Ridge, N.J. Ms. Sheedy plays a police detective. She said the
role, a good one, was probably the direct result of ``High Art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't know why they offered this part to me,'' she
said. ``They usually give these parts to television stars, and I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy spoke candidly about the near-collapse of her career.
``I was no longer commercially viable,'' she said. ``The movies I
was making weren't making money. And there's a certain point in the
road if you're an actress in Hollywood who becomes well known in
your early 20s that you have to really sell yourself. You should
become very glamorous and sell the sex appeal thing and start doing
fashion spreads in magazines and wearing certain clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was advised to do it,'' she said. ``It seems so trivial
talking about it now, but it was a huge obstacle for me. I really
felt there was nothing about me that could carry all that off. And
I was told I was either too fat or too thin and not beautiful
enough. I felt there was something really wrong with me. It was so
hard to keep some perspective. And from the way I was raised as a
kid _ my mother is a militant feminist _ there was no way I could
do any of this.'' (Ms. Sheedy's mother, Charlotte Sheedy, is a
literary agent in New York.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy worked in theater for a while and earned a living
working on television shows that were mostly forgettable. The fact
that she had played in all those adolescent films dogged her. ``I
was typecast in a dismissive way,'' she said. ``Who knew if I had
any talent?''
</P>
<P>
   Her banishment by the William Morris Agency after she failed to
get a job in a television pilot left Ms. Sheedy devastated. ``I
can't tell you how horrific it was,'' she said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, she heard about the part in ``High Art'' from
Rachel Wein, her sister-in-law, who had just been promoted as an
agent at the Don Buchwald agency, which now represents Ms. Sheedy.
She phoned Ms. Cholodenko at her New York apartment and left a
message pleading for an audition. Ms. Cholodenko, a film editor of
art movies turned director, had never heard of Ms. Sheedy, who was
given the part after an audition.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Sheedy's performance was acclaimed by critics,
``High Art'' has been seen by a relatively small audience. This
makes it uncertain whether Ms. Sheedy will be nominated next month
for an Academy Award, although she said with a laugh that her
neighbors in New York insisted she would be.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy said she still thought with fear of how her
professional life would have evolved had she not been cast in
``High Art.'' She said slowly: ``I don't know what else I could do
but act. I was in my 30s. I was untrained to do anything else. It
was the part of a lifetime for me. I owe so much to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
