<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta _ ScotsFest '99, a celebration of Scottish culture,
brings a taste of Scotland to Barnes &AMP; Noble, 2952 Cobb Parkway, at
noon Tuesday. Learn about Scotch whisky from master distiller and
expert Evan Cattanach, watch Highland dancing, listen to MacUmba (a
Scottish band that plays salsa music on Celtic instruments) and
hear the history of the Highland Games. 770-953-0966.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Southern Highland Craft Guild's Folk Art
Center presents ``Decorative Textiles: A Survey From the Guild's
Permanent Collection'' through March 21. The exhibition features
textiles from the Civil War era through the 1970s. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Waynesville, N.C. _ The Haywood County Arts Council presents
its second annual January Jazz concert featuring the Jack Coker
Trio at 7:30 p.m. Saturday at the Performing Arts Center downtown.
828-452-0593.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eatonville, Fla. _ The Zora Neale Hurston Festival of the Arts
and Humanities today through Sunday highlights the life and works
of America's most celebrated collectors and interpreters of
Southern rural African-American culture through theatrical
performances, educational programs and art exhibitions.
407-647-3307 or http://www.cs.ucf.edu/-zora
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola, Fla. _ The Pensacola Museum of Art presents ``World
Exploration: The Mary Ewing Textile Collection,'' which showcases
exotic lands such as Thailand and Peru through an extensive
assortment of garments and accessories. Through Feb. 20.
850-432-6247.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cypress Gardens, Fla. _ Cypress Gardens presents a series of
weekend concerts including Guy Lombardo's Royal Canadians with Al
Pierson (Saturday and Sunday); Glenn Miller Orchestra (Feb. 6-7);
Tommy Dorsey Orchestra (Feb. 13-14); Four Aces (Feb. 20-21); and
Four Lads (Feb. 27-28). Additional concerts are scheduled through
May 2. 1-800-282-2123.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biloxi, Miss. _ Mississippi Gulf Coast Mardi Gras Saturday
through Feb. 16 celebrates three centuries of revelry since the
first parade in 1699. Parades every weekend in Gulf towns including
Waveland, Bay St. Louis, Gautier, Pascagoula, Ocean Springs,
Biloxi, Gulfport, Pass Christian and Iberville. 228-896-6699 Ext.
210.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, GA. _ The Thomasville Cultural Center presents
two exhibits, ``Who'd of Thought It: Improvisation in
African-American Quiltmaking'' and ``Visions . . . the
African-American Ceramics of Yvonne Edwards Tucker'' through Feb.
28. 912-226-0588.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Hunter Museum of American Art presents
``Seeing Jazz,'' a traveling exhibition organized by the
Smithsonian Institution. Includes a variety of artistic responses
to jazz through paintings, sculpture, photographs, collage,
drawings and literature. Through April 4. 423-267-0968.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts opens four new
exhibitions on Saturday: ``The Lamps of Tiffany: Highlights From
the Egon and Hildegard Neustadt Collection,'' ``Akari Light
Sculptures of Isamu Noguchi,'' ``Cam Langley Glass'' and
African-American works from the collection of Drs. Albert and Gail
Holloway. Through March 28. 334-244-5700.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbia, S.C. _ The Columbia Museum of Art presents ``From
Van Os to Van Gogh,'' featuring 80 watercolors and drawings
produced in Holland between 1800 and 1900. Through March 21.
803-799-2810.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
