<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGAS-BELLAGIO31-COX     01-28 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-BELLAGIO31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The marquee at Las Vegas' hot new gambling palace Bellagio
flashes: ``Vincent Van Gogh! Henri Matisse!'' Whatever happened to
Wayne Newton?
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Colleen Newblom admitted that she had drunk too many
Lemon Drops. But that didn't stop the Reno, Nev., native and her
husband, Norman, from ordering another round of the sticky-sweet
libations as soon as they sat down for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in sequined black velvet, Mrs. Newblom, 69, sank into a
glove-soft ivory leather banquette, cracked open a supersized menu
and gave it a perplexed once-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a French restaurant?'' she asked her husband, who
shrugged. She turned to a neighboring diner, her blue eyes
twinkling brightly if not exactly focused. ``This is supposed to be
a French restaurant, isn't it? Better be at these prices.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was one of the world's most celebrated French
restaurants: Le Cirque. Or, more precisely, a near-replica that's
even swankier and more intimate than the New York original.
Fashioned from the richest mahogany and the plushest fabrics,
containing a mere 80 seats, Le Cirque is a fantasy of fine dining.
</P>
<P>
   Little would you expect that just past the intricately etched
glass and mahogany front door lie row after row of nickel slot
machines, clang-clanging in a bright, smoky and vast casino.
</P>
<P>
   Worlds collide at Bellagio, the grandest and most ambitious
resort that Las Vegas has witnessed. Developer Steve Wynn, whose
Mirage and Treasure Island casinos are nearby on the Strip, has
loaded Bellagio with so many options for fine dining, entertainment
and cultural enrichment that he has effectively upped the ante on
what this tackier-than-thou gambling kingdom expects from its
glittery citadels.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn famously shifts the focus of his casino resorts away from
nuts-and-bolts gambling to sybaritic delights of luxury travel.
(His latest pleasure palace, Beau Rivage, is slated to open in
March in Biloxi, Miss.) At Bellagio, he has gone all out.
</P>
<P>
   Named for an Italian vacation town on Lake Como, this 3,005-room
hotel conjures European glamour with mosaic-tiled floors, expanses
of rosy marble and a palatial conservatory filled with exotic
plants. In the lobby, a 2,000-square-foot canopy of free-form blown
glass by Dale Chihuly bathes new arrivals in the serene light of
expensive taste.
</P>
<P>
   Everything here boasts highbrow marque value. Along the vaulted
marble Via Bellagio are boutiques for Chanel, Prada, Giorgio
Armani, Tiffany &AMP; Co. and Gucci. Cirque du Soleil's underwater
spectacle, ``O,'' has a permanent stage here through 2010. In front
of the building, arching fountains erupt every hour, timing their
jets to a Luciano Pavarotti performance of ``Rondine al Nido.''
</P>
<P>
   The top names in American dining have set up shop as well,
effectively doubling the number of fine-dining rooms in the city.
Sirio Maccioni of Le Cirque also brought a branch of his Italian
concept, Osteria del Circo. There are clones of Boston's favorite
Mediterranean restaurant, Olives, and San Francisco's stunning
new-age seafood place, Aqua. Superchef Jean-Georges Vongerichten
contributes a cutting-edge steakhouse, Prime, to the mix. Bellagio
even lured one of the country's top chefs, Julian Serrano of Masa's
in San Francisco, to run the show at Picasso, a restaurant where
seven of the Spanish master's canvases hang on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   How does Serrano feel about leaving Babylon by the Bay for
Gomorrah in the Desert? ``I miss San Francisco, but I like it
here,'' he says, pointing firmly at the funky geometric carpet
designed by Claude Picasso, the painter's son. ``The Bellagio. It's
a safe house.'' And the city? No comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio's restaurant program is only matched in audacity by its
fine art museum, a feature that Wynn financed when his investors
balked. Throughout the day, visitors queue up for an hour or more
to take the $14 tour of the approximately two dozen prominent
artworks by European masters, among them Cezanne, Modigliani, Miro,
Degas and Renoir. If you're lucky at the tables _ really, really
lucky _ most of the paintings are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In Wynn's world, these artists are the real headliners. Their
names even flash on Bellagio's marquee: ``Vincent van Gogh! Henri
Matisse!'' Whatever happened to Wayne Newton?
</P>
<P>
   With such touches, you'll never mistake Bellagio for a Venetian
palazzo. Despite the $1.8 billion spent on the property, there
remains a degree of Vegas cheesiness. Marble walls are topped with
fake wallpaper cornices; plastic bathroom tissue boxes are gilded
with gold spray paint. And you can never get to your room without
trudging through the maw of the casino, because at heart that's
Bellagio's raison d'etre: the double down.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn understands that Bellagio's appeal has to cut across income
levels for this new-style resort to thrive. Yes, there are villas
with private lap pools and personal butlers as well as magnificent
suites with soaring ceilings. There are also perfectly nice rooms
that go for as low as $99 during the winter holidays. And though
Bellagio courts high-stakes gamblers, there are just as many nickel
slots here as anywhere in Vegas, and just as many little old ladies
parked in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn also knows that any Las Vegas resort has to have a theme.
If New York, New York has a faux Coney Island and the Luxor a
sphinx, Bellagio offers a vision of Euroclass. Some high spenders
come to indulge and some penny-ante folk to gawk. Both are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are these two sides of the experience more apparent than
at Le Cirque. Inside, a trio of well-heeled young men wash down 6
ounces of Russian caviar with a 1970 Chateau Lafite Rothschild.
While out front, Colleen Deralto, a schoolteacher from Mesa, Ariz.,
pumps a lucky nickel into a slot machine lit up with the name
Filthy Rich.
</P>
<P>
   Deralto hits the jackpot. Bells clang, the cherry-top light
flashes, and an attendant arrives with a master key to lock the
machine and cash out the winnings: $63.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Colleen and husband Andrew will spend their jackpot at
Le Cirque?
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' she laughs, ``We couldn't afford that.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. An ounce of caviar at Le Cirque, a mere nibble,
costs $65.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Delta's lowest fare for nonstop flights to Las
Vegas is $295 round trip (off-peak hours only), with a seven-day
advance purchase and a minimum two-night stay. Seven other airlines
match that fare but include connecting flights.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bellagio rates and reservations: Rooms $159-$499 ($99 room
rates available during the Christmas season). Call 1-888-987-6667.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Las Vegas Visitors Center, 702-892-7576.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE VEGAS HORIZON
</P>
<P>
   You can always find a place to stay in Las Vegas. This year,
nearly 12,000 additional hotel rooms will open, increasing the
total to more than 120,000. Here are the major developments:
</P>
<P>
   1999
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mandalay Bay, 3,276 rooms. Construction cost: $950 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Venetian (Phase 1), 3,036 rooms. $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paris Hotel and Casino, 2,914 rooms. $760 million.
</P>
<P>
   2000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marriott Marquis at MGM, 1,500 rooms. Budget not available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The New Aladdin, 2,600 rooms. $826 million.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
