<HEADER>
A2620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGAS-BELLAGIO-GAMING     01-28 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-BELLAGIO-GAMING31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For neophyte, a windfall leads to monkey business
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 31
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ During my first hour in Sin City, I was eating
Chinese noodles at a casino restaurant when I glanced down at the
floor and saw a fat, green wad.
</P>
<P>
   Omigod. One, two, three, four, five, six! $20 bills. Some old,
some new. All legal tender.
</P>
<P>
   A woman at the next table took an immediate interest in this Las
Vegas moment. After trying to bargain for a cut, she dissuaded me
from handing it over to the waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kid, you're in Vegas,'' she chuckled. ``You give that to the
waiter, it's a tip. And if there's someone who can lose that kind
of money, they won't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutching my ill-gotten wad, I realized what it was: gambling
cash. Free gambling cash.
</P>
<P>
   I slurped down lunch and wandered into the casino. What, where
and how would I wager this windfall? Craps? Blackjack? Poker? I
hadn't considered any of these games since my last ninth-grade
sleepover.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw Banana-Rama.
</P>
<P>
   A slot machine disguised as a video game, Banana-Rama features a
little cartoon monkey and an orangutan staring imploringly from
under a coconut tree. I touched the orangutan; it giggled. I
touched the little monkey and a coconut fell on its head. I was
hooked.
</P>
<P>
   The machine accepts ones, fives, tens, twenties and hundreds for
$1 wagers. I slipped a twenty into the slot and pressed the
touch-screen button. Bananas spun across the screen. I kept
pressing, and the fruit kept spinning until something remarkable
happened: triple bananas landed on the pay line. A bongo fanfare
erupted, and the monkeys went berserk _ screeching, flipping over,
climbing the tree and leaping down. They were in banana heaven, and
I had won $100. I cashed out and traded my heavy cup of tokens for
one crisp Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   The first moral of this story (there are two) is that today's
Las Vegas has more temptation than ever for the gaming neophyte.
</P>
<P>
   Modern slot machines are, in essence, high-tech video games
powered by microprocessors. If you get bored with the monkeys, you
access a menu and switch to an Arabian Nights motif, or let a pair
of eerie, detached hands deal blackjack.
</P>
<P>
   If one game of video poker bores you, you can draw five hands at
once. And nearly all the games have surprise bonus rounds that
unleash a new video landscape. If you play Fort Knox long enough,
you will eventually get the combination to the safe and be led into
the inner recesses of the compound to choose a cash prize.
</P>
<P>
   Even the traditional one-armed bandits are now driven by
computer chips rather than spring-coiled reels. All feed
information into central mainframe computers, some into citywide
networked jackpots. One such network of slots, called Megabucks, is
the talk of the town since a local woman won $27 million and change
with a lucky pull.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to move past slots into the hard stuff, casinos are
all too happy to oblige; they place gaming instruction booklets in
the hotel rooms. During my four days in Las Vegas, I never did try
one of the card tables or the roulette wheel, figuring that was a
place I didn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I was spending too much time getting to know the slots.
One evening at the MGM Grand, I pumped quarters for nearly two
hours into Fort Knox waiting to unlock the safe. My big payoff was
a measly $6.25.
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, is the second moral of this story: Win
early, and you're hooked. I forced myself to quit after squandering
$70 on Arabian Nights, Double Diamond, Monopoly, Wheel of Fortune
and every game in between.
</P>
<P>
   I left Vegas with about $150 of combined findings and winnings.
But I still think I should've given that money to the waiter in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
