<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-MANUSCRIPTS-2T     01-28 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-MANUSCRIPTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY TREASURES, BOUND FOR ETERNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When is a book more than a book? Anytime it does its
job, you might well answer. That is, when its contents awaken the
mind with some combination of guidance, insight, knowledge and
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But there are concrete ways that books can be more than books:
when they combine aspects of painting, sculpture and architecture
to become works of visual art.
</P>
<P>
   Books of this sort are the subject of a sumptuous exhibition at
the Morgan Library that ranges through more than nine centuries,
from medieval and Renaissance manuscripts and early printed books,
through an extraordinary array of fine bindings from different
countries, periods and styles, to modern, mostly English
private-press books and livres d'artistes. They all come from the
collection of Sir Paul Getty, a son of J. Paul Getty and a lifelong
bibliophile.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 30 years Sir Paul has built a collection that is
considered one of the world's best, especially for being top-heavy
with important volumes in unusually fine condition. It reflects
what can happen when money is no object, and taste, expertise and
focus are similarly abundant.
</P>
<P>
   His collection is housed at Wormsley, Sir Paul's estate in
Chiltern, outside London, in a mongrel structure that seems the
outcome of several centuries of expansion and remodeling: Doric
columns here, crennelation there, a round tower elsewhere. The new
building (the show includes an architect's model) and the
collection it holds are known as the Wormsley Library.
</P>
<P>
   The 110 or so books at the Morgan are a small percentage of the
collection, but they include many of its high points; they form by
far the largest group of books to leave Wormsley at one time since
Sir Paul began assembling his treasures.
</P>
<P>
   He selected this sampler, working with the library's curators,
Bryan Maggs and Robert J.D. Harding, and with L. George Fletcher,
who until September was the curator of printed books and bindings
at the Morgan and is now director for special collections at the
New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all these items are sure to delight or enlighten, and
quite a few may inspire speechless awe. Here, for example, is a
fragment of what is considered the oldest manuscript in England, a
30-line page from a history of the Christian church written in the
middle of the seventh century.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a pristine copy of the 1462 Mainz Latin Bible,
published seven years after Gutenberg's, with an improved version
of Gothica Textura (or Black Letter) type that remains crisply
legible today. And there is a copy of the first printed edition of
Chaucer, compiled and published by William Caxton in 1476; Sir Paul
acquired it in July.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes arcane material is made more accessible by
informative labels whose headings can have an emphatic,
journalistic sound. ``The Only Bookbinding Designed by Robert
Adam'' reads one. ``A Binding by Jean Grolier's Last Binder'' says
another, referring to the 16th-century bibliophile.
</P>
<P>
   A third identifies a five-volume Bible bound in 1906 for the
Doves Press by Katharine Adams as ``One of the Very Best Specimens
of Tooled Binding.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time this display is reached, attentive viewers will have
seen enough in the way of leather bindings _ tooled, gilded and
stamped; inlaid, onlaid or painted; overdone, clumsy or refined _
to understand that Adams' elegant arrangement of dotted and solid
interlocking circles and arcs is indeed sublime.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning the word was God's, and all books were rare.
Before Gutenberg, and even after, books were painstakingly made by
hand, usually in a king's or abbot's scriptorium, and most of them
pertained to religion, whether they were works of philosophy or the
Bibles, psalters, graduals and books of hours for daily worship.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition beautifully captures the various minglings of
printed texts and images, with hand coloring, illumination and even
calligraphy that persisted in the two centuries after Gutenberg. In
addition to its crisp new type, for example, the 1462 Mainz Bible
includes exquisite illuminated initials whose long tendrils trail
gently down the page.
</P>
<P>
   The show is laid out in roughly chronological order. In the
first several vitrines, images predominate: books are shown
primarily as repositories for mostly religious images. They glow
with gold, color and devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Seven rare leaves from a lost manuscript known as the
Burckhardt-Wildt Apocalypse (circa 1290) show a soul being saved: a
woman first seen as beset by demons and snakes and covered by sores
(as well as a brilliant orange blanket) becomes a bride of Christ,
dressed in white, and is then depicted with her arms raised in
ecstatic devotion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the collection's high points, the Ottobeuren Gradual
(circa 1164), is open to an image of Jesus on an aqua cross flanked
by Mary and St. Paul, shown on a perfect plane of shining gold. On
the opposite page is an illuminated initial T (of ``Te igitur,'' or
``Thou therefore'') festooned with decorative vines, the cruciform
of the alphabet as stylized tree.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few signs of the revival of antiquity that would
eventually lead to the Renaissance. One of the largest, most
gorgeous books here is the Ulm Pytolemy of 1482, the third European
edition of the Egyptian astronomer's atlas ``Cosmographia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   It was the first edition of this work published north of the
Alps, as well as the first to use woodblock printing instead of
engraving. Printed on vellum and hand colored, it is confident and
tentative in equal portions. Its oceans are lapis, its rivers gold
leaf, but the Indian Ocean is shown with a southern shore labeled
``terra incognita.''
</P>
<P>
   The beginnings of the bookbinders' art are touched on here in
12th- and 13th-century books that have bindings of crudely cut
leather or tawed deerskin or sheepskin that is still on the fuzzy
side. These set the stage for the show's center section, dominated
by the book as object, a six-surface opportunity for decoration. It
is here that the lay person's knowledge of bookbinding and its
development in terms of craft and style can expand exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   One gains a working knowledge of the variety of gilding tools by
studying the repeating patterns and details of these surfaces: the
undergrowth of stylized plant life, the gently molecular fields of
stipling and the penchant for architectural motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Some covers look like elaborate ceiling designs, others like
whole rooms, among them, the grand scheme of John Whittaker's 1816
binding for the Magna Carta, presented to the Prince Regent on the
600th anniversary of its signing. The deep borders surrounding the
royal coat of arms run from rococo scrolls to Gothic arches, the
latter looking like nothing less than walls full of windows.
</P>
<P>
   Common words take on new meanings. ``Cottage roof'' refers to
the gablelike diagonals that cap some binding designs, and ``drawer
pull'' to the ubiquitous eyebrow or downturned-mouth motif. (It is
deployed most effectively on a Bible bound in the English
Restoration style, ``picked out'' in black stain on red goatskin
gilt and with silver paint.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Strapwork'' denotes the designs of interlocking, usually black
bands that wind through many binding designs; ``gauffering,'' the
patterns and images sometimes found on the edges of a book's closed
pages (including the Restoration Bible).
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, where the 19th and 20th centuries dominate, the
books' interiors and exteriors are equally prominent. And the show
in some ways comes full circle, as the intricate illuminations and
beautiful calligraphy of the Middle Ages are restored to some of
their former glory during the English Gothic Revival and the Arts
and Crafts movement, continuing into Art Nouveau, Art Deco and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent works is Paul Bonet's 1957 design for
Alphonse Daudet's 1937 ``Aventures Prodigieuses de Tartarin de
Tarascon,'' with 34 decorated initials by Raoul Dufy. It features a
flamelike lion's head depicted in fiery leathers, not unlike the
``Lion King'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   This section is full of show stoppers. Francis Bedford's binding
for Henry Shaw's 1860 ``Dresses and Decorations of the Middle
Ages'' is appropriately medieval, replete with clasps, gauffering
and imitation jewels in ormolu mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it fades in comparison with Sangorski and Sutcliffe's
extravagant 1913 binding for a volume of Keats, a carefully
orchestrated riot of gems, pearls, contrasting leathers and gilt.
</P>
<P>
   For chasteness there's the green goatskin gilt binding that
Thomas James Cobden-Sanderson, founder of the Doves Press, designed
for William Morris' copy of the first French translation of Marx's
``Capital.'' A pattern of stylized leaves and clouds of stipling
form a cover that is consistent with its author's critique of
industrialization, at least in principle.
</P>
<P>
   Even more restrained is the gilded white pigskin binding that
Cobden-Sanderson designed for the great Chaucer edition brought out
by Morris' Kelmscott Press in 1896. It is paired with a second
Kelmscott Chaucer in the Getty collection whose open title page
shows Morris' roiling foliate patterns at their most dense.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no going back. The books at the beginning of this
exhibition represented the prevailing states of knowledge, book
technology and religious faith of their time. They pushed history
before them, and they have its urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The books at the end are expressions of increasingly marginal
passions and obsessions. Reviving once-essential crafts, they are
undeniably beautiful but also anachronistic, drifting at the edges
of the great stream of books that Gutenberg unleashed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
