<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-LAMOTT31-COX     01-28 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LAMOTT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bit by bit, Lamott has forged a vision of humane spirituality
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Lamott, author of the quirky new ``Traveling Mercies: Some
Thoughts on Faith,'' is reverent in a free-spirit, leftist-liberal,
recovering-addict, single-mom kind of way. She doesn't walk gently
toward a state of grace; she ``staggers.'' She doesn't have a leap
of faith; she has a ``lurch.'' And if religion and humor are not
traditionally interwoven, well, they should be, says the
44-year-old California author and online essayist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think being religious means that you can't also be
funny,'' Lamott says. ``And if God's not funny, then I'm not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamott wrote four novels before her first book of nonfiction _
``Operating Instructions,'' a journal of her son's first year _
sold 100,000 copies in 1993. A year later, her second book of
nonfiction, ``Bird by Bird,'' sold 200,000 copies. Subtitled ``Some
Instructions on Writing and Life,'' that book made her something of
a cult figure among writers and readers _ ``a rock idol of the
literary world,'' one bookseller put it _ and made it possible for
her to quit teaching weekly writing classes, cleaning houses,
teaching tennis, waitressing and writing restaurant reviews. In
1997, she began writing biweekly essays for the hip online magazine
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Through those essays and her nonfiction books, readers have
followed Lamott through the death of her father, the birth of her
son, Sam (now 9 1/2), the death of her best friend, her eating
disorder, drug and alcohol addictions, loves lost quickly or en-
</P>
<P>
   dured too long, rampant neuroses, bad thigh days and religious
epiphanies. Clean and sober since 1986, the writer has learned to
bow her dreadlocked head and prey on the insecurities that once
threatened to destroy her. From her home near San Francisco _ which
she shares with her son, a dog, a cat, an iguana and a goldfish _
she took a few minutes to talk about her ``very ordinary'' life,
her inspiration and her ``Traveling Mercies,'' a uniquely Lamottian
mix of painful insight and laugh-out-loud confessional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a single interesting theological thought in my
head,'' Lamott says. ``I don't understand very much, and I don't
have a position I want to get people to. All I can do is tell
people my own truth and my own version of things, and that tends to
come out kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does it help or hurt a writer to actually have some financial
success?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it makes life a lot easier. It's a relief not to always
be sweating where the rent's coming from.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your daily writing routine?
</P>
<P>
   A: I try to sit down at the same time every morning _ 9 o'clock
_ and work until about 11:30. Then I stop and take a break until
about 1. I'll walk my dog, eat, catch up and hang out, check in on
the impeachment proceedings. . . . Then I work until a quarter to
3, when I leave to pick up my son from school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has motherhood changed your writing?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's certainly a lot more efficient before you have children,
when you're only responsible for yourself. But it so profoundly
changed me as a person, in terms of changing the whole geography of
my heart and my spirituality . . . it gave me a depth that I was
lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the idea for ``Traveling Mercies'' come about?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been on a book tour every year since 1993, and
everywhere I went people were really glad to talk about writing,
but I noticed that they also really wanted to ask me about faith,
to tell me about their own faith or to express appreciation that
somebody on the left was a person of faith, that somebody who was
not conservative or Moral Majority was talking out loud about God
and faith and religion. I just started to feel there was a real
hunger in the world _ even in the reading world _ for somebody like
me to talk about these things.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of things do you read?
</P>
<P>
   A: I used to read really wonderful, esoteric, fresh new voices .
. . and then I had a kid. . . . I'm secretly looking forward to the
new John Grisham _ none of my friends would ever cop to reading
John Grisham. I just finished reading ``King of the Gypsies,'' a
25-year-old book by Peter Maas, and I'm reading ``The Orchid
Thief'' by Susan Orlean. . . . And I read The New Yorker and the
New York Observer religiously.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concept of family _ in the broadest possible sense _ has
always seemed important to you. Have there always been people
around you to serve that function?
</P>
<P>
   A: I always understood that the secret of life is friendship.
Everything else can come and go, but if you have a strong community
of support around you, your fortunes can change and you'll still be
OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The chapter on your aging mother in ``Traveling Mercies''
surely will touch a chord with a lot of readers. That had to be
difficult to write.
</P>
<P>
   A: It was difficult to write, and it was difficult for her to
read. Our relationship is imperfect and it always was. . . . I'm
not like my mother much at all, but I'm very devoted to her and
have put a lot of time into this relationship. It's just what it
is. . . . I think she was really grateful for a daughter who could
tell the truth and love her and be loved by her for what is rather
than for the great fantasies we had all those years _ what it
should be like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're obviously very close to your son, whom you write so
much about. Does he have any problem with people knowing so many
details of his life?
</P>
<P>
   A: I always check with him before I write something. I make sure
he doesn't mind, to cover myself in any future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, what inspires you as a writer?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's wonderful when writers tell the truth and help
me understand life a little more. I try to do that myself. . . .
When a writer makes me laugh or catches me by surprise, that always
inspires me to do it myself.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Weaver is an editor for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
