<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS31-COX     01-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crittenden's credo: Only unhappy victors in battle of the sexes
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  What Our Mothers Didn't Tell Us. By Danielle Crittenden. Simon
&AMP; Schuster. $23. 224 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls are taken every day, and not infrequently the
findings of yesterday's poll contradict the findings of today's.
People are fickle. And sometimes they just change their minds. But
for some odd reason a poll from the '70s sticks in my mind. It set
out to determine who was happiest: married men, married women,
unmarried men or unmarried women.
</P>
<P>
   This one, I thought, was loaded: sex and marital status lined up
like coordinates on a graph, with happiness the elusive variable.
You knew, whether by intuition or from experience, how it was going
to come out. Happiest were the single women. Next happiest were
married men. Then came married women, and the burden of the
findings _ their details now forgotten _ was that they were not all
that happy. Finally, a sad group of puppies if ever there was one,
the single men.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway knew that men without women reverted to animal
instincts. So did James Dickey and James Jones.
</P>
<P>
   You don't read much about women without men. Maybe there's a
reason. On both sides of the equation, the notion of need is
implicit: A man is lost on his own; a woman on her own gets along
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Generalizations go only so far, and there are many exceptions to
this one. But most people would recognize in it a certain truth.
Some might even recognize themselves, past or present.
</P>
<P>
   How is it, then, that so much is written about women's
happiness, so little about men's?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, progress
</P>
<P>
   The subtitle of Danielle Crittenden's book ``What Our Mothers
Didn't Tell Us'' is ``Why Happiness Eludes the Modern Woman.''
Well, why does it? They marry and have children at a later age than
their mothers and grandmothers did. They're studying subjects other
than education and nursing (almost half the students in medical
school are women). At the office, they're managers and get to go to
the meetings just like men. What's not to be happy about?
</P>
<P>
   They're not happy, Crittenden says, because they got sold a bill
of goods. All you have to lose is your chains, feminists told them,
but they instead lost their moorings:
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the ripping down of barriers that has taken place over
a generation, we may have inadvertently also smashed the
foundations necessary for our happiness. Pretending that we are the
same as men _ with similar needs and desires _ has only led many of
us to find out, brutally, how different we really are.''
</P>
<P>
   This is neither a revelation nor, in its essentials, a new
argument. ``The truth,'' Sally Quinn wrote more than 10 years ago,
``is that many women have come to see the feminist movement as
anti-male, anti-child, anti-family, anti-feminine. And therefore it
has nothing to do with us.''
</P>
<P>
   A man is wise to leave this issue alone, but opinion surveys
have documented that most women do not identify themselves as
feminists (in 1980, more women voted for Ronald Reagan than for
Jimmy Carter). The label is self-limiting and they don't like it.
They like professional feminists even less. But if radical feminism
is passe, it's because all of us _ or nearly all of us _ are
members of the faith. We believe in equal pay for equal work, in
equal opportunity under the law, in marriage as partnership and not
property management. The war's over, and the right side won.
</P>
<P>
   Yet poll after poll also confirms the feeling among women that
they are the junior partners in the marriage, and that they
submerge a part of themselves in their husband's life and career.
Pulled one way by work, pulled the other by family, they cannot
give themselves fully to either.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Men don't either. Hence the conundrum of happiness.
Why is it that women's happiness should matter more than men's?
</P>
<P>
   Happiness as privilege
</P>
<P>
   Crittenden _ a journalist and founder of The Women's Quarterly,
a wife and mother _ has no answer. She is a shrewd, often witty
analyst of our contemporary social arrangements and a lucid writer
in a field populated by preachers and charlatans. If she is a
kinder, gentler Dr. Laura, she's also a more intellectually
grounded one. Women would be happier if they had their children
earlier, she tells us, and began a career outside the home in
midlife.
</P>
<P>
   What is of greater interest is the assumption that happiness is
the right of one sex and the privilege of the other, the fulcrum on
which the two find their balance. Only Americans could think this
way. The pursuit of happiness is not only written into their
national charter but encoded in their psyche.
</P>
<P>
   And yet happiness _ however we construe it _ or marital status
might have nothing to do with any of this. Relations between the
sexes have changed drastically in the 35 years since Crittenden was
born, mostly for the better. Human nature changes more slowly. If
the fruits of feminism have not been as sweet as advertised, it is
not only women who had expected something more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube' writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
