<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THAT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-28 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHE'S ALL RIHT': WHEN `PYGMALION' METS MTV, THE BOOKWORM TURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how much the world changes, the caste system of a
typical American high school seems inviolable. The jocks,
cheerleaders and pretty people rule, while the nerds, bookworms and
arty types remain the untouchables.
</P>
<P>
   But in Hollywood, at least, there's always the outside chance
that an outcast Cinderella will remove her glasses, put on a chic
party dress and be discovered by Prince Charming. That's sort of
what happens to Laney (Rachael Leigh Cook), a bespectacled,
extremely earnest art student at an upscale Los Angeles high
school, in Robert Iscove's wispy romantic comedy ``She's All
That.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly out of the blue one day, Laney finds herself avidly
pursued by Zack (Freddie Prinze Jr.), the school's handsome senior
class president and star soccer player. Because she's smart, she
senses something fishy.
</P>
<P>
   Zack's sudden interest in Laney isn't exactly altruistic. Having
been unceremoniously dumped by his snooty girlfriend Taylor (Jodi
Lyn O'Keefe) for a self-centered clown named Brock (Matthew
Lillard), who is featured on the MTV series ``The Real World,''
Zack finds himself dateless for the senior prom.
</P>
<P>
   When Zack's pal Dean (Paul Walker) bets him he can't turn the
gawkiest, geekiest girl in his class into a prom queen in just two
weeks, Zack takes up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's All That'' is essentially a formulaic comedy, but it has
enough glimmerings of originality and wit to make you wish it were
much bolder and funnier than it turns out to be. Among other
targets, the movie takes pointed aim at the MTV mystique as it is
embodied by the evil Taylor, who flounces about spitting outrageous
venom, and the goofily narcissistic Brock, who would rather watch
himself on a movie-size television screen than succumb to Taylor's
slavering advances.
</P>
<P>
   The film has short fantasy sequences that parody MTV's ``Real
World'' and ``Spring Break.'' And come the prom, this movie, which
has never really had its feet on the ground, takes leave of reality
altogether and lets its senior class members break into an
elaborate choreographed line dance enhanced by a psychedelic light
show. It also employs a student disk jockey (Usher Raymond) as a
part-time commentator who disseminates gossip on the school's
public-address system in a modified rap style.
</P>
<P>
   If ``She's All That'' has the trappings of a Cinderella story
(Laney undergoes a spectacular makeover supervised by Zack's
sister), its heroine is no abject ugly duckling transformed into a
radiantly passive swan.
</P>
<P>
   Very early in their courtship, Laney puts Prince Charming
through his paces at a performance art event in which she is
participating. Coaxed into doing an impromptu solo, in which he
tosses around a beanbag and improvises a soliloquy, Zack joyfully
discovers his inner nerd. It is all thanks to Laney.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the charm of ``She's All That'' emanates from Ms. Cook,
a star of ``Dawson's Creek'' who looks and sounds like a baby
Winona Ryder. Unlike so many actors playing smart young people, she
actually projects some intelligence along with a sly sense of
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's All That'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned).
It has some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   SHE'S ALL THAT
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Iscove; written by R. Lee Fleming Jr.;
director of photography, Francis Kenny; edited by Casey O. Rohrs;
music by Stewart Copeland; production designer, Charles Breen;
produced by Peter Abrams, Robert L. Levy and Richard N. Gladstein;
released by Miramax Films. Running time: 86 minutes. This film is
rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Freddie Prinze Jr. (Zack Siler), Rachael Leigh Cook (Laney
Boggs), Matthew Lillard (Brock Hudson), Paul Walker (Dean Sampson),
Jodi Lyn O'Keefe (Taylor Vaughan) and Usher Raymond (Campus D.J.).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
