<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-ANDERSON-HN     01-28 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-ANDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA'S ANDERSON DISCOVERS HIS OWN FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Friend-of-the-family Muhammad Ali was in the hospital
waiting room when Jamal Anderson arrived in the world. So of
course, Anderson grew to understand the importance of outer beauty.
Anderson works hard at it. A man can count on natural good looks to
go only so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Europeans have shown us the way,'' Anderson said, a
running back who carried the Atlanta Falcons to their first Super
Bowl since, well, the beginning of time. ``You get facials. You
wash your face nightly.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Anderson is basking in the warmth and shine of joining
the Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII. Two seasons ago, his first
as a starter in the National Football League, the Falcons went
3-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the situation we're in right now,'' Anderson said.
``There are no bad days for Jamal Anderson. We're here, and we're
the only two teams playing for the world championship. It's the
greatest athletic stage there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes arrive on center stage better prepared than
Anderson. His father, James, is a former New Jersey policeman who
has handled security for the likes of Ali, Sugar Ray Leonard, Mike
Tyson and assorted entertainers. ``Uncle'' Muhammad, the prettiest
boxer the world ever laid eyes on, used to perform magic tricks for
Jamal and his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Summer has read Anderson bedtime stories. Anderson has
skated at Richard Pryor's place. Leonard sang once at the birthday
party of Anderson's father. Under the circumstances, the Super Bowl
_ with its worldwide audience of 800 million _ seems like a natural
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous in this setting,'' Anderson said. ``Everything
is (treated) like a chore. Why not have fun doing our jobs? People
say, `He's a ham.' It's not being a ham. It's just being relaxed
and natural. Doing my thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has always pointed out that the people who changed
always had a sudden and hard fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Hang around the stars enough, and it's only natural to want to
reach for them. ``You say, `I'm going to be like Muhammad,'''
Anderson said. ``Right. Every time I thought about boxing, one of
those guys either lost or got beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   One episode with Tyson reinforced Anderson's suspicion that he
wasn't cut out to be a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of mock slap-boxing,'' Anderson said. ``You know
how you get with your buddies? You duck, thinking you're a boxer.
Mike swung _ I kind of think he had a flashback. The wind took me
back. I was like, `Twenty-second timeout. This game is over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Football seemed safer. Saner. As a boy, Anderson was an NFL
Films junkie. The trademark stiff-arm that helped Anderson to the
ninth-highest season rushing total (1,846 yards) in NFL history? He
unveiled it at age 9, inspired by old clips of Jim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the stiff-arm wasn't enough of a weapon to attract more
than passing interest from the NFL. Anderson lasted until the 201st
pick of the 1994 draft. Twenty-three running backs went before
Anderson, who rushed for 1,275 yards at Utah. In his career. A year
later, Terrell Davis went to the Broncos on the 196th pick. Davis
has made an illogical progression from 1,117 yards to 1,538 to
1,750 to 2,008.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of carries the flag for the unwanted,'' Anderson said.
``I'm part of Terrell's Army.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Anderson wasn't even a foot soldier with the Falcons.
Anderson carried the ball 41 times his first two seasons. He has
rushed for 3,903 yards and 26 touchdowns in the three seasons
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no way you can prepare for him,'' Broncos
safety Steve Atwater said. ``He's a unique athlete. Come Sunday,
we're going to have to go after him like a pack of wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-feet-11-inches and 234 pounds, Anderson is a tailback in a
fullback's body. He squats 670 pounds. He bench presses 465. When
necessary, he handles like a Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up watching Earl Campbell ... that's who he reminds me
of most,'' Broncos safety Tyrone Braxton said. ``He's strong, he's
short, he's thick, he's quick and he's fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL-record 410 carries this season only hint at how much
Anderson softens up a defense. Anderson produced 1,133 of his
rushing yards and nine of his 14 touchdowns in the second half of
games. He'll have plenty of time later to get tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always talk about the residual effect, the wear and
tear on your body,'' Anderson said. ``But that's over 10 or 20
years. I'm only in my fifth year, and realistically, I didn't even
play my first two years, so this is really my third year. So I've
got seven or eight more years of ... dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson laughed. Everything is beautiful. He's in the Super
Bowl. Besides, Anderson figures he has something else in his favor,
something that allows him to be a beast of burden without being any
worse for the wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genetics,'' Anderson said. ``Genetics. But you also have to
take good care of yourself. This is really the first season that I
started getting massages and getting in the cold tub and
incorporating a lot of the things that my trainers were telling me
I should do. And it kind of all fell into place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
