<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-BOSTON-ART-5TA     01-28 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-BOSTON-ART-5TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOSTON, A BOOM AND NEW HURRAHS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston is the most historical city in America, a
repository of the national past, yet it has an extraordinary
capacity to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilgrims landed nearby. Boston became the cradle of liberty,
but later it became a byword for bluenosed narrow-mindedness.
(``Banned in Boston!'' they used to say when they wanted to tout a
naughty book or a risque play.)
</P>
<P>
   It has traded and manufactured. Nowadays it manages money, and
capitalizes on the science and technology developed in its
laboratories. It has boomed and busted and it is a boom town again,
uncouth as that sounds. The one constant has been ideas: Boston
ideas have washed across the nation and the world for two
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is a second constant: the accent, as distinctive
as those of Brooklyn and Tidewater, Va. Hear a man say ``farm'' _
``fahm'' _ in that distinctive nasal way, and you know just where
he came from. It is the sound of ``a brick-throated bullfrog,''
Ford Madox Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   There can be very few cities in the country with as much to
offer the visitor. Historical sites abound, of course, enough to
exhaust the most avid dwellers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Dockside at the Charlestown Navy Yard, you can visit ``Old
Ironsides,'' the Constitution, commissioned in 1797 and never
decommissioned. You can visit the Old South Meeting House, a
Colonial gem with a sounding board hung above the pulpit, where
Samuel Adams roused the rabble against the tyrant in London, and
see Faneuil Hall, with its grasshopper weather vane, still used
occasionally for political meetings, and stand beside the Old State
House, where five protesters, including a black man, Crispus
Attucks, were killed by the redcoats in the Boston Massacre of
1770.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, Boston ranks among the nation's leaders. The Museum
of Fine Arts has no peer in the Western Hemisphere for its
collection of Asian art. The Boston Symphony Orchestra, under the
baton of Seiji Ozawa, born in China to Japanese parents, is one of
the top five in the United States, and the inimitable Boston Pops
flourishes as it did in the days of Arthur Fiedler and John
Williams. The whole panoply of American architecture, from Bulfinch
to I.M. Pei, is on show here.
</P>
<P>
   Boston loves sports; in fact, it has often been said that only
three things count here: sports, politics and revenge. The
basketball Celtics, who have never recovered from the loss of the
formidable Larry Bird, and the baseball Red Sox, jinxed since they
traded Babe Ruth to the Yankees 79 years ago, are nevertheless
beloved. The Sox play in Fenway Park, a wonderful old band box, as
idiosyncratically shaped as the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Beantown
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Boston is a superb walking town. Compact and
convenient, a mosaic of distinctive neighborhoods, it is a baby
London.
</P>
<P>
   Right at its heart lie the Boston Common and the Public Garden,
twin parks that are perfect for strolling. Swan boats, propelled by
boatmen whose pedaling turns paddles, cruise the garden's pond,
familiar to all as the setting for the children's classic ``Make
Way for Ducklings.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Boston's aristocrats, the fearsome Brahmins, ran
everything. The Cabots spoke only to Lowells, as the doggerel had
it, and the Lowells spoke only to God. Then the Irish fought their
way to power.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the two worlds _ the world of John P. Marquand's
``Late George Apley'' and the world of Boss Martin Lomasney,
celebrated in Edwin O'Connor's ``Last Hurrah'' _ came to terms with
each other. They learned to co-exist. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
carries the flag of his brothers and Tip O'Neill and James Michael
Curley. William Weld, recently the governor of Massachusetts, walks
in the footsteps of two presidential Adamses from nearby Quincy and
two senatorial Henry Cabot Lodges. And now, mirabile dictu, the
mayor and the governor are both Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   William Lloyd Garrison, foremost of the abolitionists, made his
first anti-slavery speech in Park Street Church in 1829, and Robert
Gould Shaw raised a black regiment here to fight in the Civil War.
But tolerance is a latecomer to 20th-century Boston. The
controversy over court-ordered busing of students in the interest
of racial balance left deep scars, with the city's intellectuals,
many of whose children attended private schools, pitted against the
clannish, less affluent Irish-Americans of South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, though no longer, Brahmin hostility to other tribes
was obvious, with the haughty Somerset Club a pre-eminent symbol of
that. During the Civil War, it had been a stronghold of the
Southern sympathizers known as Copperheads, and it is enshrined in
Boston lore that they closed the club's windows when Robert Gould
Shaw walked past. Benjamin C. Bradlee, the scion of an old Boston
family, once tried to take Sen. John F. Kennedy to lunch there but
was turned away. He may as well have arrived in blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bostonians developed a reputation for
self-satisfaction. Once, a guest at a White House reception told
Franklin D. Roosevelt, ``I'm from Boston.'' He replied, ``You'll
never get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1857, Oliver Wendell Holmes wrote that Boston, or more
precisely the State House atop Beacon Hill, was ``the hub of the
solar system.'' People still call it the Hub today, but they use
the term self-mockingly. They also call their city Beantown, after
their beloved Boston baked beans, which gives them something in
common with the proud inhabitants of Florence, another historic
city, who call themselves bean eaters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tea and Insurrection
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries ago Boston bred insurrection. Its patriots led the
way to independence, dumping chests of English tea into the waters
of the colonies' most important harbor to protest royal taxes. Paul
Revere, silversmith and midnight rider, and John Hancock, president
of the Continental Congress, were Bostonians. Lexington and Concord
lie just over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   American legal tradition owes much to Boston. The Supreme
Judicial Court of Massachusetts predates the U.S. Supreme Court. It
has sat without interruption longer than any other court in the
Western world.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, the city lived by the sea. Its trade was
built upon cod. That humble fish, now often called scrod
hereabouts, is still a favorite on local dinner tables, and a
wooden replica, the Sacred Cod, hangs in the State House in the
chamber where the House of Representatives meets. (Just as the lord
chancellor in Britain sits on the wool sack as a reminder of the
source of England's early wealth.)
</P>
<P>
   When the British market dried up, Boston opened trade routes to
the East, bringing porcelain, spices and silks to the young United
States in its snazzy clipper ships. And when steel-hulled ships
made the clippers obsolete, it turned to manufacturing; Boston
money and management built the mills in the smaller cities around
it, from Salem to Lawrence to Brockton.
</P>
<P>
   The profits built Boston's great educational and cultural
institutions. Henry Lee Higginson came home from the Civil War and
helped establish both the Boston Museum of Fine Arts, which still
accords the van der Weyden he gave it a place of honor, and the
Boston Symphony Orchestra. Harvard University, across the Charles
River in Cambridge, flourished anew. Boston became the nation's
intellectual locomotive.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century Boston and its suburbs were filled with
writers whose names resound today: Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David
Thoreau, Margaret Fuller and the other Transcendentalists, the poet
Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, the historian Francis Parkman, the
psychologist William James, the educational reformer Horace Mann,
the philosopher George Santayana, and the novelist William Dean
Howells, editor of The Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   They have their successors in this century in scholars and
writers like David Reisman, John K. Galbraith and Henry Louis Gates
Jr. Houghton Mifflin and Little, Brown &AMP; Co. carry on the city's
publishing tradition, and WGBH, Boston's public television station,
produces much of the best fare on PBS, including the Julia Child
programs and ``The American Experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston and its suburbs are home to countless colleges and
universities: peerless Harvard, the oldest institution of higher
education in the country, whose business, law and medical schools
educate the nation's leaders-to-be; the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, one of the world's great science and engineering
schools; Wellesley, Hillary Rodham Clinton's alma mater; Tufts and
Brandeis, Boston College and Boston University and Northeastern.
Its eminent hospitals, like Massachusetts General and Brigham and
Women's, draw patients from everywhere, and high-technology
businesses cluster around the exits on Route 128, the semicircular
highway skirting the city.
</P>
<P>
   A Renaissance
</P>
<P>
   For almost half a century, from the 1920s to the 1960s, Boston
was a backwater of sorts, subsisting largely, it seemed, on
memories. But the Kennedy presidency brought new attention to the
city. (Kennedy's presidential library is housed in a Pei building
in Dorchester, south of the center.)
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, a mayor named John Collins and a
redevelopment genius named Edward Logue began reshaping the place.
They cleared out the malodorous neighborhood known as Scollay
Square, installing a new government center there. In two decades,
the nearby Quincy Market was turned into a chic shopping precinct
by the architect Benjamin Thompson, incorporating the raucous old
eating house called Durgin-Park. In and near Copley Square, new
towers were built for the Prudential and John Hancock insurance
companies, reviving that neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   After a nasty slump in the 1980s, yet another renaissance is
under way. Average rents exceed those in Manhattan and San
Francisco, and hotel rooms are as scarce as downtown parking
meters. An $11 billion project is at last burying the city's
unsightly main north-south highway deep beneath the ground, and a
new 1,000-acre seaport district is abuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Boston is a money town along with everything else. The
Fidelity group, the country's biggest mutual fund enterprise, is
headquartered here, along with several competitors. Peter Lynch,
its smooth-talking stock picker, shows up on commercials
nationwide. Fleet Financial, headed by Terrence Murray, is a
banking powerhouse in and beyond New England.
</P>
<P>
   The Arts
</P>
<P>
   Boston has a downtown commercial theater district, where many an
aspiring Broadway show has had its kinks ironed out (or not). The
city's theatrical life is centered, however, across the river, in
Cambridge, where the gifted, turbulent Robert Brustein directs the
American Repertory Theater, an unfailing source of new dramatic
ideas. Cherry Jones, a joy of the New York Theater, developed her
craft in a decade of classic roles under Brustein's aegis.
</P>
<P>
   Opera is a less happy story. For decades Sarah Caldwell kept the
Boston Opera going, innovative if unstable, with bailing wire and
duct tape. She also championed the music of Russian modernists like
Rodion Shchedrin and Alfred Schnittke. But the Caldwell era
collapsed in a heap of recriminations over questionable financial
practices in 1990, and the Boston Lyric Opera, now headed by Leon
Major, a Canadian, is a more modest proposition, with only three
productions a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Symphony Orchestra has always been Boston's
performing arts favorite. In winter it plays in Symphony Hall,
which need not take a back seat, esthetically or acoustically, even
to the Musikverein in Vienna, and in summer it plays in the Music
Shed at Tanglewood, in the Berkshire Hills of western
Massachusetts. Maestro Ozawa, lithe and balletic, a charismatic,
controversial conductor whose musicianship is praised by many and
doubted by a few, has led it for 25 years, matching the tenure of
the Russian Serge Koussevitzky and exceeding that of the Frenchman
Charles Munch.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting the Boston area:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON HARBOR HOTEL, 70 Rowes Wharf, (617) 439-7000. On the
waterfront, a few steps from the city's financial district, this
place offers arresting harbor views, especially wonderful from your
(very comfortable) room at sunrise. It has a water taxi to Logan
Airport, which lets you bypass snarls in the tunnels. Rowes Wharf,
its restaurant, specializes in modern New England cooking, with the
best brunch in town on Sundays. Double room: $305 to $450 on
weekends; $365 to $550 on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES HOTEL IN HARVARD SQUARE, 1 Bennett St., Cambridge, (617)
864-1200. Great for old grads, visiting lecturers and proud
parents. (Is there any other kind, when the young-un's get into
Harvard or MIT?) The 296 bedrooms, mostly on the snug side, have a
lean, Quakery feel, with quilts and Colonial-style furniture.
Chilly reception. Jody Adams' Rialto restaurant can disappoint, but
on most nights the Mediterranean fare scores. Double room: $239 to
$389.
</P>
<P>
   THE ELIOT, 370 Commonwealth Ave., (617) 267-1607. This is a
find, a neo-Georgian hotel built in 1925 and discerningly renovated
a few years ago. Tucked into patrician Back Bay, convenient for
shopping along nearby Newbury Street. The 92 suites all have
kitchens; if cooking palls, Clio awaits downstairs, a supper club
with a leopard skin rug and the gutsy French cuisine of Ken
Oringer, who used to cook at Silks in San Francisco. Winter rate:
$195 a suite.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SEASONS, 200 Boylston St., (617) 338-4400. Overlooking the
Common and the Public Garden, with the golden State House dome just
beyond, this one gets an A for location and for everything else:
attentive service, with jolly, efficient doormen; large, handsome
bedrooms (including one, to which I was once upgraded, with a grand
piano); one of Boston's very best restaurants (see below), lush
lobby flowers and a 50-foot indoor pool. Double room: $475 to $665.
</P>
<P>
   RITZ-CARLTON, 15 Arlington St., (617) 536-5700. Kansas City and
even Naples, Fla., have their Ritzes now, but this is THE Ritz, a
link to Boston's days of glory, a hallowed institution where the
elevator operators still wear white gloves. I can remember when
they did your bill in pen and ink and made you wear a tie to
breakfast (the blueberry muffins are famous). It's formal, even a
bit stuffy, but it lives and breathes Old World elegance. Double
room: $245 to $600.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   AUJOURD'HUI, Four Seasons (see above). The first time I took
Julia Child out to eat, I asked her where she wanted to go; this is
her town. She chose Aujourd'hui. Like her, it lives and breathes
style. The kitchen produces Americanized haute cuisine that lets
the quality of the ingredients shine through, and many think it the
city's premier restaurant. ``Tres chic, tres cher,'' says Boston
Magazine, which pretty well sums it up.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE GINGER, 583 Washington St., Wellesley, (781) 283-5790. So
much fusion cooking is so bad that it's a joy to taste that of Ming
Tsai, 34, who grew up in his family's Chinese restaurant, then went
to Yale. Try his crab cake with kafir lime, and you'll think
Baltimore and Bangkok at the same time, or shu mai dumplings
stuffed with foie gras and shiitakes in caramelized onion broth, or
miso-marinated sea bass, with a slug of wasabi oil. No one in the
country can match Tsai's virtuosity in this idiom.
</P>
<P>
   EAST COAST GRILL, 1271 Cambridge St., Cambridge, (617) 491-6568.
Author, grillmeister and hot-sauce maven, Chris Schlesinger serves
barbecue in several regional styles, plus other lively specialties.
Good raw bar, terrific drinks, reasonable prices, good sides but no
side.
</P>
<P>
   HAMERSLEY'S, 553 Tremont St., (617) 423-2700. That's Gordon
Hamersley in the Red Sox cap at the range, and his winter menu
delivers genuine cold-weather cheer. Things like seared foie gras
with prunes and armagnac, choucroute with smoked bacon, sausage and
quail, and slow-cooked Vermont pig with endives, along with Mrs.
Hamersley's sagely chosen wines.
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL SEAFOODS, 35 Columbus Ave., (617) 426-4444; and other
locations. Don't go to Legal's for fancy cooking; go because Roger
Berkowitz, the owner, buys the best fish and shellfish and tests it
for freshness and purity. The oysters and clams on the half shell
are nonpareil; the clam chowder is the city's best, rich but not
thick, and oh, the fried clams . . .
</P>
<P>
   OLIVES, 10 City Square, Charlestown, (617) 242-1999. Todd
English carries the flag nationally for Boston cooking, and no
wonder. He has turned a storefront in the middle of nowhere into
the city's top address with his lustily flavored, eclectically
inspired food. A typical uptown, downtown example: brisket with
parmesan risotto. No reservations for parties under six.
</P>
<P>
   LES ZYGOMATES, 129 South St., (617) 542-5108. The kind of wine
bar every town needs, a meeting place for young and old, rich and
just getting by. Ian Just, the chef, learned his craft at the Paris
mother house of Les Zyg, and his plats du jour warm the heart (and
other parts). The name, fittingly, refers to the muscles that make
your face and mine smile.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   CHARLESTOWN NAVY YARD, USS Constitution Museum, Building 22 in
the Charlestown Navy Yard, off Chelsea Street. Hours: 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. daily, Nov. 1 through April; 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., May 1 through
October. Admission: $3 donation. Everything in the museum is
related to the Constitution, docked at Pier 1 in the Navy Yard.
Hours for guided tours (required) of the ship: 9:30 a.m. to 3:30
p.m. year-round. You can board the top deck only from 3:30 p.m. to
sunset. Free.
</P>
<P>
   OLD SOUTH MEETING HOUSE, 310 Washington St., (617) 482-6439.
Built in 1729 as a Puritan meeting house, this is where the Boston
Tea Party started, with a meeting to debate the British tax on the
tea. Hours: 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily, Nov. 1 through March; 9:30
a.m. to 5 p.m. daily, April 1 through October. Admission: $3; $1
children 6 to 18, $1; under 6, free; $2.50 for college students and
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   FANEUIL HALL, Congress Street, (617) 242-5642. The market is
downstairs. The upstairs is Town Hall, open to the public when not
used for meetings. Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Talks on the 1742
building's history every half hour on request. Free.
</P>
<P>
   OLD STATE HOUSE, corner of State and Washington Streets, on the
Freedom Trail, (617) 720-3290. A museum of Boston history operated
by the Bostonian Society. Self-guided tours of the 1713 building: 9
a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. Admission: $3; $2, students and the elderly;
$1, children 6 to 18; free for under 6.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL REVERE HOUSE, 19 North Square, (617) 523-2338. Hours: 9:30
a.m. to 4:15 p.m. daily, Nov. 1 through April 14 (but closed
Mondays in January, February and March); 9:30 a.m. to 5:15 p.m.
daily, April 15 through October. Admission: $2.50; $2, students and
the elderly; $1, children 5 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   STATE HOUSE, corner of Beacon and Park Streets, (617) 727-3676.
Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., year-round;
tours leave between 10 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. Free. Advance notice of
visits, especially for groups, is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA, Symphony Hall, 301 Massachusetts
Avenue, (888) 266-1200. The orchestra, conducted by Robert Spano,
music director of the Brooklyn Philharmonic, will perform Sibelius'
Symphony No. 3 and ``The Swan of Tuonela''; Beethoven's Piano
Concerto No. 2 and the U.S. premiere of Magnus Lindberg's ``Arena''
Friday night, Saturday and Feb. 2 at 8 p.m. Tickets: $26 to $74.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON LYRIC OPERA, Shubert Theater, 265 Tremont St., (800)
447-7400.6772). ``Romeo et Juliette,'' through Feb. 7. Friday night
at 7:30 p.m. and Sunday at 3 p.m. Tickets: $25 to $98.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS, BOSTON, 465 Huntington Ave., (617)
267-9300. ``French Photography: Le Gray to Atget,'' through May 23.
Opening Feb. 14: ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman,'' through May 9.
Hours: Mondays and Tuesdays, 10 a.m. to 4:45 p.m.; Wednesdays
through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 9:45 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 10
a.m. to 5:45 p.m. Tickets: $10; $8, students and the elderly;
children under 18 free.
</P>
<P>
   ISABELLA STEWART GARDNER MUSEUM, 280 the Fenway, (617) 566-1401.
``Josiah Henry McElheny: The Story of Glass,'' a display of recent
glass pieces, through April 25. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 11
A.M to 5 p.m. Admission: $11 on weekends; $10 on weekdays; $7, the
elderly; $5, college students; children under 18 free.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS AT HARVARD UNIVERSITY IN CAMBRIDGE. Fogg Art Museum, 32
Quincy St.: ``Building Representation: Photography and
Architecture, Contemporary Interaction,'' through April 11. Sackler
Museum, 485 Broadway: ``Mastery and Elegance: Two Centuries of
French Drawings From the Collection of Jeffrey E. Horvitz,''
through Sunday; ``Divinely Inspired: Images of Mystics and
Mendicants,'' through March 28. Busch-Reisinger Museum, 32 Quincy
St.: Permanent collection of Expressionist, Bauhaus and Northern
and Central European art on view now; ``Wols Photographs,'' a
display of 1930's photographs, opens Feb. 13 and runs through April
25. Hours for all three museums: Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m. One admission covers all three
