<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIET-RUDOLPH-COX     01-28 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIET-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ECHOES OF VIETNAM RESONATE IN RUDOLPH SEARCH
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
 &HT;    WITH ILLUSTRATION
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a year since Atlanta and Birmingham bombing suspect
Eric Robert Rudolph slipped into the heavily wooded mountains
around Andrews, N.C., with federal law enforcement agents only a
few hours behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Heat-detecting infrared sensors have failed to spot the
anti-government recluse and former airborne soldier in the thick
woods and mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Listening devices planted in the woods have failed to pick up
any sound of him.
</P>
<P>
   Specially trained hunting dogs have failed to sniff him out.
</P>
<P>
   And heavily armed searchers, at times as many as 200, have
failed to run him to ground or dig him out of a cave despite
focusing their search on a 30-square-mile area in the Nantahala
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph's hunters appear no closer now to their quarry than they
were when they first showed up in Andrews in the wake of the
bombing of an abortion clinic in Birmingham on Jan. 29, 1998. If
anything, the feds have gotten bogged down in a mission that has
developed eerie similarities to the U.S. military involvement in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Like the U.S. military in Vietnam, the feds in North Carolina
are facing something of a no-win situation. If they catch Rudolph,
they look foolish for taking so long. If they don't, they look even
more foolish for being outwitted by one rugged individualist.
Either way, they risk losing the confidence and respect of the
American people, just as the U.S. military did after the Vietnam
War.
</P>
<P>
   When the first wave of regular combat troops was sent to Vietnam
in early 1965, it was with high expectations that the widely
disparaged Viet Cong insurgency would be quickly taken care of. The
Viet Cong were considered little more than illiterate peasants who
were poorly armed, had virtually no military training and could be
quickly overwhelmed by America's superior firepower and manpower.
Overlooked and ignored were their commitment to the cause and the
backing they received from North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The feds have not underestimated Rudolph's commitment to his
cause, whatever that might be, but they too were overconfident
about how they would be able to hunt down one man with their
superior technology and firepower. Just as the resourcefulness of
the Viet Cong initially befuddled America's military, which until
then had been training to fight a set-piece battle with the Soviets
in Central Europe, so too has Rudolph's elusiveness baffled those
searching for him in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam the U.S. military found a population that often only
grudgingly accepted its presence. The people there feared the
Americans almost as much as they feared the Viet Cong and North
Vietnamese. In Andrews and the surrounding areas, the feds have met
with the same sort of grudging acceptance from many residents who
are independent and who harbor strong anti-government feelings.
Federal officials are close-mouthed about how much, if any, outside
help Rudolph might be getting, but it seems highly unlikely that he
would be able to survive this long without assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The feds have developed something of a bunker mentality in
Andrews, hunkering down in a old sewing-machine factory that is
enclosed by a fence, its access road closed to public traffic. It
is somewhat reminiscent of Vietnam-era base camps and fire support
bases. But that did not keep someone from firing off eight shots at
the building in November, one of the rounds grazing the head of an
agent and another round narrowly missing a second agent.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent search for the gunman did nothing to endear the
feds to the local populace. Phillip Rogers, a local mechanic
unaware of the shooting at the task-force headquarters, was
arrested by federal agents after he tracked a search helicopter
with a laser pointer. According to Andrews attorney Tim Rasmussen,
Rogers was charged with ``forcibly assaulting, resisting, opposing,
impeding, intimidating and interfering with a federal officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen says the whole thing is overkill and symptomatic of
the growing friction between the feds and the locals. ``It's like
too many people in an elevator for too long. After a while you get
uncomfortable with the people around you,'' Rasmussen said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the troops fighting in Vietnam grew more discouraged the
longer America's involvement went on, so too do some of the troops
hunting for Rudolph. Living conditions for federal agents are less
than ideal: They're sleeping in motels far from friends and
families and eating restaurant food for weeks at a time. Progress,
if any, is difficult to measure. And Rudolph's emergence in some
quarters as a mythic hero for his ability to outwit the feds has
added to the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in Vietnam, leaders from Washington occasionally drop in
to visit the troops in the field to tell them what a great job they
are doing. FBI Director Louis Freeh made two morale-boosting trips
to Andrews over the past year, telling agents, ``We will maintain
the investigation and search for as long as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasional briefings for the news media in Andrews have
taken on aspects of the media briefings in Vietnam, once derisively
referred to as the ``Five O'Clock Follies.'' Those Vietnam
briefings were long on statistics, body counts and rosy outlooks
and extremely short on realistic assessments. In Andrews the
briefings seldom offer anything of substance and agents rarely
answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   The feds searching for Rudolph are not likely to declare victory
and go home. That would entail telling the public they believe he
is dead, either through natural causes in a cave somewhere or by
his own hand. But doing that could be extremely dangerous because
it leads to the possibility of Rudolph passing into legend in the
style of D.B. Cooper, who disappeared into the Pacific Northwest
before Thanksgiving in 1971, with $200,000 in Northwest Airlines'
money, after parachuting from one of its Mexico-bound jets.
</P>
<P>
   If Rudolph is not caught or his body is not found, the same
could be in store for him. Sightings of Rudolph, some real but most
imagined, would probably go on for decades in the Nantahala
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Without the capture of Rudolph and a trial, or without his body,
there will be no satisfactory end to this mission, just as in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
