<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: MADAME DE POMPADOUR PORTRAIT; SOTHEBY'S IN FRANCE;
MUSEUM GETS A COPLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Regular visitors to the Frick Collection will notice
some changes to the grand interiors of the limestone mansion at 1
East 70th St. Several paintings in its collection that had been out
of sight for years were rehung this week in prominent places. Some
of the Frick's fine porcelains, too, have found temporary new
niches.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the reinstallation is to create a mini-exhibition
that revolves around a single loan: Drouais' full-length portrait
of Madame de Pompadour from the National Gallery in London. It is
the first time the Drouais has been seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait, painted in 1764, one month before Madame de
Pompadour's death, depicts her in a voluminous gown of painted
Chinese silk edged with yards of fine lace. The work hangs in the
Frick's East Gallery, where it will remain through April 25.
</P>
<P>
   It is flanked by two works by Chardin from the Frick's
collection: ``Still Life With Plums'' (circa 1730) and ``Lady With
a Bird-Organ'' (1751). ``Elizabeth, Countess of Warwick,'' a
portrait by Jean-Marc Nattier that had been in the director's
dining room on the second floor and had not been exhibited since
1980, is on the same wall.
</P>
<P>
   Madame de Pompadour loved Sevres porcelain, so three vases
dating from around 1762 from the royal factory at Sevres can now be
seen at close range on a commode placed in front of the portrait.
They are usually displayed in the museum's Boucher Room on a mantel
out of the public's reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``These paintings and objects all relate to Madame de
Pompadour,'' said Samuel Sachs II, the Frick's director. ``It's a
revisitation to the 18th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's own Drouais, ``The Compte and Chevalier de Choiseul
as Savoyards'' (1758), which usually hangs behind stanchions to the
left of the grand staircase leading to the Frick's private
quarters, has been rehung, too. It is now on the north wall of the
East Gallery, directly across from Madame de Pompadour's portrait.
</P>
<P>
   The Frick curators have hung a Van Dyck in the Drouais'
customary place: ``Ottaviano Canevari'' (circa 1627), which had
been at the top stair landing and had not been publicly displayed
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The loan of the Drouais portrait from the National Gallery was a
result of discussions in which the Frick agreed to lend the London
museum its Ingres portrait of the Vicomtesse d'Haussonville (1845).
An exhibition of Ingres portraits opened on Wednesday at the
National Gallery and will travel to the Metropolitan Museum of Art
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Henry Clay Frick's will, the Frick is not
allowed to lend works acquired by its founder, which make up
two-thirds of its collection. But it can lend art that has been
bought since Frick's death in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   In the spot where the Ingres had hung, a long, narrow room
called the North Hall, there is now a painting by the only female
artist in the collection, Cesarine-Henriette-Flore Davin-Mirvault.
It is a portrait of Antonio Bartolomeo Bruni that had been hanging
in a curator's office and has not been on public view since the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's in France
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated delays in opening the French auction system to
non-French auctioners, Sotheby's has figured out a way to hold one
of the most eagerly anticipated house sales of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This week it announced that it would join with two French
auctioners _ Remi Le Fur and Herve Poulain, vice president of
Drouot _ to sell the contents of the Chateau de Groussay, the home
of Charles de Beistegui, an interior designer who died in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, a series of sales from June 2 to 6, will take place
at the chateau in Montfort l'Amaury, an hour southwest of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great step forward for making the French auction
system more international,'' said Laure de Beauvau Craon, deputy
chairman of Sotheby's in Europe and president of Sotheby's France.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the French Senate would debate the issue of
opening the system to companies like Sotheby's and Christie's in
April and that the National Assembly would do so in June.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Sotheby's first involvement in an auction in France
since it opened its grand quarters in the Galerie Charpentier on
Rue du Faubourg-St. Honore early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Beauvau Craon said that Poulain and Le Fur, not
Sotheby's, signed the contract to conduct the sale with Juan de
Beistegui, Charles de Beistegui's nephew, who inherited the 21-room
chateau. Sotheby's will be paid only for its services, which
include organizing the event. That approach meets the French
requirement that French auctioners conduct sales in France.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which is estimated to bring $20 million, includes an
array of furniture, art and objects: magnificent Russian and French
furniture, porcelains, clocks, marble busts and 18th- and
19th-century paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Gets a Copley
</P>
<P>
   A double portrait of Pennsylvania's first governor, Thomas
Mifflin, and his wife, Sarah Morris Mifflin, by John Singleton
Copley is being sold by the Historical Society of Pennsylvania to
the Philadelphia Museum of Art, where it has been on loan since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 1773 portrait, which was bequeathed to the Historical
Society in 1900, has been the jewel in its collection of more than
10,000 paintings and objects. But the Historical Society decided to
become a research library two years ago and to dispose of much of
its art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to stay in Philadelphia,'' said Anne d'Harnoncourt,
director of the Philadelphia Museum. ``This is where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Fitz Eugene Dixon Jr., longtime trustees of the
museum, have given the lead gift toward buying the Copley. The $4
million price will be met with additional money from the museum's
endowment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
