<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     01-28 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JOURNEY BACK TO JUDAISM, THANKS TO THE DALAI LAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Jew in the Lotus'' is a documentary that suggests that
film may be far from the ideal medium for portraying a spiritual
journey that takes a man back to his religion.
</P>
<P>
   Made by Laurel Chiten, whose previous work includes ``Twitch and
Shout,'' about Tourette's syndrome, ``The Jew in the Lotus'' is
introduced as a work about a group of rabbis who traveled in 1990
to Dharamsala, in northern India, to meet with the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Driven from Tibet by invading Chinese bent on obliterating
Buddhism, the Dalai Lama sought to know the secret of the spiritual
survival of Jews in the millennia of the Diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   A fascinating question, but it is rapidly subsumed and abandoned
without meaningful answer beneath the story of Rodger Kamenetz, a
writer asked by a friend to accompany the rabbis to India and
chronicle their encounter with the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens Friday and is part of the New York Jewish Film
Festival at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   For Kamenetz, agonizing over the death of an infant child and
the blunt rejection of a book into which he had poured himself, the
journey to Tibet proved an experience that reawakened and deepened
his Judaism. The experience also led him to relate his story in
``The Jew in the Lotus,'' a best-selling book that not only
restored his faith in himself as a writer but also made him a
popular figure on the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his gifts as a writer and public speaker may be,
Kamenetz generates little interest and radiates no charisma in this
documentary. One can sympathize with his torment over the death of
a child, but for the most part the film makes him appear to be a
self-absorbed neurotic surrounded by mostly unidentified talking
heads striving hard to imbue him with a significance that his words
and acts on film fail to justify.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the meetings of the rabbis and the Dalai Lama
seem slighted, and the travelogue elements of ``The Jew in the
Lotus'' appear unexceptional.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, when Kamenetz returns to Dharamsala and presents the
Dalai Lama with a copy of his book, Ms. Chiten's documentary bears
an unfortunate resemblance to a 60-minute infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   THE JEW IN THE LOTUS
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Laurel Chiten; based on the book ``The
Jew in the Lotus: A Poet's Rediscovery of Jewish Identity in
Buddhist India'' by Rodger Kamenetz; director of photography, Peter
Wiehl; edited by William Anderson; released by Blind Dog Films. At
the Cinema Village, 22 East 12th Street, Greenwich Village. Running
time: 60 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
