<SLUG> BC-SAVEUR-COOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVEUR COOKS: BOOK REFLECTS AMERICAN HERITAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See SAVEUR-COOKS-RECIPES) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heaven on a bun is a bacon cheeseburger.
</P>
<P>
   At least Colman Andrews thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   The way the editor of Saveur magazine sees it, the bacon
cheeseburger is among the highest culinary achievements of modern
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good food is good food,'' he said. ``The fact that it's called
foie gras or lobster doesn't mean that it's better than something
that is called hamburger or green beans. If it's honest, fresh and
well-made, it's good food.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles native's philosophy on food goes even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food connects with virtually every area of life. Food is a way
of anchoring ourselves, reconnecting with our roots and also with
the world,'' said Andrews, who lives with his wife and two
daughters in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how food permeates people's lives, Andrews and his
Saveur colleagues have crafted ``Saveur Cooks Authentic American''
(Chronicle Books, $40).
</P>
<P>
   The 320-page volume offers a glossy, lush look at the foods and
traditions of Americans through 175 recipes from all corners of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   From out west, Rose Pistola shares her recipe for calamari
cakes. Back east, Susan Blew talks about Swedish coffee bread. Up
north, there's food writer R.W. Apple Jr.'s family recipe for
Pennsylvania Dutch creamed corn. And in Texas, Houstonian Carter
Rochelle's Real Texas Chili consists of plenty of meat but no
beans, podnuh.
</P>
<P>
   The accessible text is supplemented with compelling photographs.
It's hard not to feel some kind of connection with the land when
viewing photographs of swollen vine-ripened tomatoes being peeled
or the sweeping wild-rice paddies of Minnesota being harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Providing even more texture and soul to the culinary
anthropology are the essays on the people, places, ingredients,
rituals and dishes that define authentic American cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors to the book tell readers how they got their hands
on a ``dead man's recipe'' for fried chicken from Gus Vanderbilt or
the secret to perfectly cooked glazed ham from Monte Mathews. Many
recipes include stories that describe their origins, such as
Tutu-Man's chicken with teriyaki sauce, Mrs. Garrett's chicken
pies, Georgene's fluffy rolls, Sam's apple pie and Francis Vitale's
lamb's-neck stew with polenta.
</P>
<P>
   The book is peppered with uniquely American fare, such as
iceberg lettuce with blue cheese and barbecued ribs. Many, however,
are transplants, reinvented or adapted from other parts of the
world. This has prompted many to question whether foods such
asgnocchi and pesto, flour tortillas and chow mein can be labeled
as authentic American food.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the foods we eat,'' replied Andrews. ``We're all
immigrants. Our ancestors brought over these recipes and adapted
them to the ingredients we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking more like a football coach than a gastronomical guru,
Andrews didn't start his career as a food authority. Critiquing the
music scene was his meal ticket until the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music world was getting less hospitable, more bottom-line
oriented,'' he recalled. ``Food, at about the same time, was
becoming, for the first time, a major preoccupation in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch from music critic to restaurant critic wasn't too
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of my parents came out of a food tradition, and a lot
of what we ate at home came from a can,'' he said. ``But my parents
took me out to restaurants from the time I was a little babe in
arms. I became very comfortable in their surroundings, learning
everything I could about food by observing what was on other
people's plates.''
</P>
<P>
   After establishing a name in food journalism, Andrews got
together with Dorothy Kalins, editor in chief, and Christopher
Hirsheimer, executive editor, to launch Saveur (pronounced sa-VER).
</P>
<P>
   The threesome, however, wanted to go beyond publishing just
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to share and discover with our readers where food
comes from, why it was made a certain way and who made it,''
Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   The concept clicked with readers and catapulted the magazine
into the culinary limelight in the summer of 1994. Today,
circulation has swelled to more than 375,000.
</P>
<P>
   In less than five years, Saveur has garnered many notable
awards, including six James Beard Awards (the Oscars of the
culinary world) and two National Magazine Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like most about it is the nice marrying of the
geography with the cuisine of the region,'' said Len Pickell, an
avid reader and president of the James Beard Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You not only get the recipes but you get the source.''
</P>
<P>
   For Andrews, the source is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is one of the most direct links we have with the earth _
stuff that comes out of the earth and comes into us and literally
makes us what we are. How people don't find that fascinating I
don't understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although a connoisseur of food, he rejects the distinction
between haute cuisine and simple cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good food is good food,'' he repeated. ``It's not a serious,
pretentious kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
