<HEADER>
A2669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVEUR-COOKS-RECIPES-     01-28 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVEUR-COOKS-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. APPLE'S CREAMED CORN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Recipes are from ``Saveur Cooks Authentic American'' (Chronicle
Books, $40) 
 
4 cups dried corn (See Note) 
4 cups milk 
3 cups whipping cream 
3 teaspoons each: sugar and salt 
4 tablespoons butter 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Place corn in a large bowl; cover with milk and cream. Cover
with plastic wrap and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer corn mixture to a large saucepan. Add sugar, salt and
butter. Bring to a boil, stirring frequently, over medium-high
heat. Reduce heat to low and simmer, stirring occasionally, about
30 minutes. Adjust seasoning to taste with salt and pepper just
before serving. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Pennsylvania Dutch-style dried sweet corn is available in
many markets in Lancaster County, Pa., and through specialty
mail-order sources.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAM'S APPLE PIE &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pastry &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
2/3 cup solid all-vegetable shortening, chilled &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sift flour and salt together in a large bowl. Cut in shortening
with a pastry cutter or 2 knives, until mixture resembles coarse
meal. Make small depressions in the mixture with your finger and
drizzle in up to 5 tablespoons ice water, 1 tablespoon at a time,
mixing until dough holds together. Form into a ball, wrap in
plastic wrap and refrigerate 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Filling &QL; 
 &QL; 
3 pounds baking apples, peeled and cored &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
Pinch of nutmeg &QL; 
2/3 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
4 tablespoons butter, cut into small pieces &QL; 
1 egg, lightly beaten &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut apples into wedges, 1/2 inch thick at the widest point. Mix
sugar, nutmeg, cinnamon and salt in a large bowl. Add apples and
mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Divide dough into 2 balls. Roll out
1 dough ball into a 12-inch round on a floured surface, then ease
into a 9-inch pie pan. Fill the pastry with apples and all their
juices, and dot with butter. Roll out remaining dough into a
12-inch round, place on top of apples, then fold edge under and
crimp or flute. Poke 4 or 5 holes in top crust with your finger to
allow steam to escape during baking. Beat 1 tablespoon water into
egg, then brush top of pie with egg wash. Bake until crust is
golden brown, about 45 minutes. Allow to cool slightly before
serving. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PANFRIED FLANK STEAK WITH GARLIC BUTTER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (1 1/2-pound) piece flank steak, about 3/4 inch thick &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil &QL; 
2 tablespoons Garlic Butter (recipe follows) &QL; 
1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh parsley &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat steak dry with paper towels; season liberally on both sides
with salt and pepper. Heat a large cast-iron skillet over high
heat. When pan begins to smoke, coat with oil, then add steak (be
careful; oil will spatter) and sear until almost black, about 4
minutes on each side (for rare). Don't move meat until ready to
turn, or crust will break.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer steak to a platter and top with Garlic Butter. Cover
loosely with foil to keep warm. Allow steak to rest 10 minutes,
then cut across the grain into 1/4-inch slices. Spoon juices over
steak and top with parsley. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Garlic butter &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 tablespoons butter &QL; 
3 garlic cloves, crushed &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heat butter and garlic in a small saucepan over medium-low heat.
Cook until garlic is fragrant, about 5 minutes. Remove and discard
garlic. Keep butter warm. Makes enough to top 4 servings of steak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herb Butter: Beat 4 tablespoons softened butter with a fork in a
medium bowl until creamy. Add 1 1/2 teaspoons minced fresh
tarragon, 1 1/2 teaspoons minced fresh chives, and 3/4 teaspoon
each, minced, fresh: chervil and parsley. Mix thoroughly; season to
taste with salt and pepper. Mound butter on a piece of plastic
wrap, roll to form a cylinder, twist ends of wrap, and refrigerate
until firm, at least 1 hour. Slice into rounds to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Roquefort Butter: Substitute 1 tablespoon crumbled Roquefort,
1/2 teaspoon cognac and 1 teaspoon Dijon mustard for the herbs,
then proceed as in Herb Butter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STUFFED PEPPERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
8 fresh poblano peppers or 4 green bell peppers &QL; 
1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil, divided &QL; 
1 small yellow onion, peeled and diced &QL; 
1 garlic clove, peeled and minced &QL; 
1/4 pound each, ground: beef and pork &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
1 large tomato, peeled, seeded and chopped &QL; 
Pinch of ground nutmeg &QL; 
1 1/4 cups cooked long-grain white rice &QL; 
1 tablespoon each, chopped, fresh: marjoram leaves, thyme and
parsley &QL; 
1/4 cup fresh bread crumbs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Char peppers over a gas flame or under a hot broiler, turning to
blacken all over. Place in a paper bag, close tightly, and steam 15
minutes. When cool enough to handle, rub off and remove blackened
skin, taking care not to tear flesh. Cut a slit down the length of
each, stopping about 1/2 inch from the tip. (If using bell peppers,
simply cut off the top.) Scrape out ribs and seeds. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons oil in a skillet over medium heat. Add onion
and garlic and cook until soft and golden, about 20 minutes.
Increase heat to medium-high, add beef and pork, breaking meat up
with the back of a spoon, and brown 7 to 10 minutes. Reduce heat to
medium, season to taste with salt and pepper, and stir in tomato
and nutmeg. Cook 5 minutes, then remove from heat. Stir in rice,
marjoram, thyme, parsley and 1 tablespoon oil. Adjust seasonings.
Preheat broiler. Spoon about 1/4 cup filling into each pepper and
place on a cookie sheet. Sprinkle with bread crumbs, drizzle with
remaining oil and broil until golden. Serve hot or at room
temperature. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
