<HEADLINE>
`SHE'S ALL THAT' RECYCLES TIRED TEEN THEMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She's All That'' may seem to borrow from the latest in
cinematic high-school social studies, but it outright steals from
the genre's master, John Hughes, especially his ``Some Kind of
Wonderful'' and ``16 Candles.''
</P>
<P>
   The character equation is shuffled a bit but it's essentially
the old familiar story: wealthy, handsome and smart Zack Siler
(Freddie Prinze Jr.) has just been dumped by his longtime
girlfriend, Taylor Vaughan (Jodi Lyn O'Keefe). She's the icon
``every girl wants to be, and every guy wants to nail.'' Zack
learns Taylor met a new guy over spring break and now it's only
eight weeks till the prom, and Zack needs a date.
</P>
<P>
   He takes a dare from his competitive, not-so-best friend, Dean
(Paul Walker), and agrees to transform the nerdiest, most
politically-conscious girl in the class into queen of the prom.
Laney Boggs (Rachael Leigh Cook) lives on the wrong side of the
tracks, is working hard for an art scholarship, wears glasses and
is more concerned about what the king of Zimbabwe is doing to the
mountain gorillas than who will be crowned king of the senior
class.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Zack comes to his senses because after a little
makeover by his savvy little sister, Mack (Anna Paquin), Laney
transforms from an ugly duckling into the swan. Too, he finds he
likes performance art better than being class president. But when
Taylor's new guy, Brock Hudson (Matthew Lillard), an egomaniacal
actor from the TV show, ``The Real World,'' dumps her, she has to
win Zack back and grab the regal title from new threat Laney.
</P>
<P>
   Director Robert Iscove, whose credits include TV fare such as
``Rodgers and Hammerstein's Cinderella,'' makes his feature film
debut. He has a strong choreographic eye and his work in musicals
lends a ``Rocky Horror Picture Show'' meets ``West Side Story''
pulse to the dance sequences at the prom. And in that, ``She's All
That'' is kind of fun.
</P>
<P>
   But the high school milieu is limited as far as new ideas. Every
teen movie that comes along recycles the same themes.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is very little that's fresh in ``She's All That,''
at least the presentation keeps the ho-hum material from feeling
stale. Still, it's hard to feel sorry for a guy who drives a Range
Rover to high school and who has been accepted at every prestigious
college from Dartmouth to Harvard and still feels like he's a
victim.
</P>
<P>
   She's All That. Directed by Robert Iscove. Written by R. Lee
Fleming Jr. Cast: Freddie Prinze Jr., Rachael Leigh Cook, Matthew
Lillard, Paul Walker. Miramax Films. 97 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
