<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY BOOSTERS HOPE TO BOOST AMERICANS' APPETITE FOR THE SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ All-star festivities bring out the best a league
has to offer. Certainly the National Hockey League put on its best
face last weekend for its midseason extravaganza in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   The American Hockey League is trying to do the same here for its
All-Star Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of cocktail parties, autograph sessions and
virtual-reality exhibits get those around hockey feeling good about
the sport. But is it a false sense of security?
</P>
<P>
   About the time Fox network returned the NHL to national
television four years ago, hockey was labeled the sport of the '90s
and beyond. Michael Jordan was playing baseball, putting the NBA in
a slump. Baseball canceled its World Series because of labor
problems. Even the NFL was fretting over its lack of compelling
Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   So where is hockey's imprint? Fox's television ratings last
season fell 42 percent. ESPN's cable number dropped 13 percent. A
recent Sports Illustrated essay determined that golf is poised to
overtake hockey as America's fourth major sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad year last year,'' said John Davidson, a Fox
analyst and former New York Rangers goaltender. ``Let's face facts.
We had a real short Stanley Cup final. We had a mess at the
Olympics. There's a lot of different people who bear responsibility
for this. Everything that could have gone wrong went wrong last
year regarding the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth straight year, the best-of-7 Stanley Cup final
ended with the losing team failing to win even one game. A U.S.
Olympic team went to Japan in February as a co-favorite but
finished 1-3, after which several players trashed their rooms in
the athletes' village.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic incident notwithstanding, hockey players are among
the most media- and fan-friendly professional athletes anywhere,
but America's public perception that they compete in an obscure
sport is hard to shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madison Avenue has put some hockey players in commercials, but
those commercials only run during hockey broadcasts, where you're
preaching to the choir,'' said Ed Goren, executive producer of Fox
Sports. ``You'll know that there's some success and they've
developed personalities when you see an NHL player in a commercial
that runs during a football game, a basketball game, a baseball
game. You see it with other sports crossing over.''
</P>
<P>
   Until hockey is accepted into the mainstream of American sports,
it will be a hard climb.
</P>
<P>
   Most hockey players say they are avid fans of all sports. Yet
take a collection of people who claim to be serious sports fans,
and only a limited percentage follow hockey closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch ESPN `SportsCenter,''' said Robert Esche, a
goaltender for the AHL's Springfield Falcons. ``The thing that
ticks us off all the time is that there's so many football and
college basketball and baseball highlights, and they'll show like
two or three frigging hockey highlights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has a lot more people participating because you can play
no matter what your skill level,'' said Ken Gernander, a Minnesota
native who has played nearly 500 AHL games. ``In a lot of areas of
the country, playing hockey isn't even an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a northern pocket extending from Maine and ending in
Minnesota, there are few hockey hotbeds in this country. Supporters
of the sport say the NHL's expansion into new territories such as
Nashville, Atlanta and Florida will increase the interest base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a growing process,'' said Steve Guolla, a Canadian now
doing his AHL playing in the basketball hotbed of Lexington, Ky.
``They've never seen hockey before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't happen overnight,'' said Jon Coleman, a
Boston-born member of the Adirondack Red Wings. ``Kids have to get
interested and youth hockey programs have to be built up. It's
going to take a little more time to become a national sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen new arenas in a lot of cities around the country,''
Davidson said. ``The next generation of kids is starting to learn
the game at a young age and they have an understanding of it.
There's going to be a void between the time those kids grow up and
the kids who are adults now who watch. Through time, the next few
years we're going to have more people involved at all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the top level, hockey has more concerns than just
indoctrinating an American audience.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the perception that it is not a made-for-TV
sport. Fox, although it will relinquish network rights to ABC after
this season, invested millions to develop a glowing puck that's
easier to see on television screens. The network also was
progressive trying to find camera angles that show the game's
speed, which only on-site fans can appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what Park Avenue may feel, there are people who
are involved with these teams whose only concern is their in-house,
live, ticket-paying audience,'' Fox's Goren said. ``In today's
world, you're maxed out on attendance. The only way to pay for the
escalating player salaries is to make it a better television
product, which translates into bigger rights fees and maybe greater
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is the development of stars. The NHL has had
several, headed by Wayne Gretzky, who may be in his final season,
and Mario Lemieux, who already retired.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has players with Hall of Fame talent but not necessarily
Gretzky-like personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next couple of years we are going to lose Wayne
Gretzky, Ray Bourque, Mark Messier,'' Davidson said. ``I hope the
young players coming up who are going to be the future stars, like
Paul Kariya, Eric Lindros, that they know and understand what
Messier, Gretzky and Bourque meant to the game. They're going to
have to share the responsibility of being there for the media, for
the public, to be part of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of the players in this league are still from
Canada,'' Coleman said. ``It's just going to take a little bit of
time for hockey to keep growing. It grew a lot after the '80
Olympic Games. You see all these new college programs, the
different junior teams cropping up. With the East Coast league
getting bigger and bigger, kids are getting into hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey right now is on a great path,'' Esche contended. ``I
could be wrong, but to me it keeps getting bigger. Now that there
are teams all over, you're going to find songs written about
hockey. Hank Williams always sings about football, someday he's
going to be singing about hockey. It's something that's starting to
come out of the closet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
