<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH-FUGITIVE-COX     01-28 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-FUGITIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SOME OF FBI'S MOST FAMOUS SEARCHES HAVE TAKEN YEARS
 &HT;    WITH RUDOLPH AND RUDOLPH-VIET
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 31
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the recent annals of fugitives on the lam from the law, the
year-long manhunt for Eric Robert Rudolph is considered still in
its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   What sets the search for accused Atlanta and Birmingham bomber
Rudolph apart from most other manhunts is its focus. Federal posses
often cover the entire country, and sometimes the world, in their
pursuit of bad guys. The hunt for Rudolph is concentrated in about
30 square miles of rugged Nantahala Forest wilderness in western
North Carolina. But the difficulty of the terrain, and possibly
because Rudolph is receiving help from some local citizens, has
frustrated efforts of law enforcement to run him to ground.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the FBI or the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms or the Georgia Bureau of Investigation are
likely to give up any time soon. In fact, FBI Director Louis Freeh
has stated repeatedly that the task force hunting for Rudolph will
stay in the mountains as long as it takes to find him. If nothing
else, federal agents can be incredibly persistent. Among their most
noteable searches, many of which dwarf the longevity of the hunt
for Rudolph:
</P>
<P>
   -- It took a 40-agent task force18 years to track down and
arrest the ``Unabomber,'' who turned out to be an eccentric Harvard
graduate and former University of California mathematics professor
named Theodore ``Ted'' Kaczynski.
</P>
<P>
   -- This Thanksgiving eve, it will be 28 years since fabled
hijacker D.B. Cooper plummeted into the night sky over the Pacific
Northwest with $200,000 in cash. He was never seen again, and may
be dead, but the file on him is still open.
</P>
<P>
   -- Leo Fredrick Burt also is approaching his 28th year on the
run. Burt is wanted in connection with the May 1971 bombing of a
building at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   -- Donald Eugene Webb, like Rudolph, is one of the FBI's 10 Most
Wanted. He has been on the run since December 1980, when he
allegedly shot and murdered a small-town police chief in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another long-time runner and FBI Most Wanted is Victor
Manueal Gerena. He is approaching 16 years on the loose after he
allegedly participated in a $7 million robbery in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the FBI's more notorious manhunts in the more distant
past were of relatively short duration.
</P>
<P>
   It took the feds little more than 18 months to track down and
kill Bonnie and Clyde and ``Pretty Boy'' Floyd in separate
incidents. And John Dillinger's crime spree lasted a mere nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
