<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-INTERVIEW-BALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SON OF SLAVE OWNERS LOOKS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BERNADETTE FAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Promoting the paperback edition of his book
``Slaves in the Family,'' a chronicle of his family's legacy of
slave ownership, Edward Ball says it's easier this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds are bigger,'' he says, ``and the emotions are more
developed, not as raw.''
</P>
<P>
   Part archival research, part oral history, ``Slaves in the
Family'' is an examination of the Ball clan's past as a prominent
plantation family in Charleston, S.C. The book peels back the
family lore of benevolent masters to reveal the brutality of forced
labor that became the family business when the first Ball _ young
Elias ``Red Cap'' Ball _ arrived in Charleston from England in 1698
to inherit half a farm.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly 170 years, Edward Ball estimates, his family owned
about 4,000 slaves on 25 rice plantations, and their descendants in
America numbered 75,000 to 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of this chronicle belongs to those black people bought
and sold by the Ball family, or, in some cases, spun into the
lineage through sex. Again, patriarch Elias Ball seems to have led
the family by fathering five white children, and, apparently, two
children by his housekeeper, a slave named Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most often, by today's measurement, we would have to describe
it as rape,'' says Ball, 40, in a telephone interview from San
Diego. ``And yet there were relationships between black women and
white men that survived over time and produced a number of
children, and it would be disrespectful, to the women especially,
to describe those relationships exclusively as relationships of
exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball chooses his words carefully, treading cautiously in a
geography of race, sex, power and privilege. He has been criticized
for being too easy on slave owners; he has been criticized for
being too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book has stung some members of my family in a way that
cannot be healed,'' he says, ``and I regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every door that has closed, another has opened. For the
magic of ``Slaves in the Family'' is that it tells the stories long
missing from most African-American families. It allows these
descendants of diaspora the rare chance to look at their family
tree and put a name to each branch _ in one case all the way back
to 1756 and a girl herded off a slave galleon onto the docks of
Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Her Ball owners named her Priscilla. She would be one of five
children bought by the Balls that day. More than 200 years later,
Edward Ball would track down and meet her descendants.
</P>
<P>
   What was it like, meeting these strangers with a common past, if
slave owner and slave can be said to have anything in common?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared when I started contacting people, and I continued
to be scared for a long time,'' Ball says. ``It still does make me
nervous to think about it. It seemed like a connection that had to
be made. It seemed it was worth the risk of being rejected, being
denounced, being accused of exploitation and all other kinds of
social risk. But the rewards of actually contacting people could be
important enough to make everything else moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the power of the encounters that I had with the African
Americans,'' Ball says. ``It felt like something larger than we
were. It felt like we were two electrical poles, pulsing, creating
a current or a charge of some kind. It was a jolt every time I had
another encounter with a family, an enormous cathartic jolt.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball was invariably met with suspicion by these families, some
still living hard by the plantations where their ancestors worked
and died, some as far away as Los Angeles and Philadelphia. But
after the suspicion, says Ball, was relief. Indeed, Ball's next
project is a collaboration with his Harleston cousins, prosperous
blacks who can trace their Ball kinship to the union of an
unmarried white rice planter and his black slave that produced
eight children. The Harlestons are an artistic bunch, something the
Balls decidedly are not. That appealed to Edward Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are artists and musicians who had a direct influence on
American popular culture,'' he says. ``It's not a continuation of
the book I just finished. It's the story of a prosperous Southern
black family over a period of five generations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Ball comes back to the words ``story'' and
``storytelling'' to describe the three-year research project that
took him from his columnist's job at the Village Voice back to his
childhood haunts in South Carolina and then to Sierra Leone to try
and make sense of the inhuman flesh trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unusually rich and long story,'' Ball says of his
genealogy, and he hoped he wouldn't ``botch'' the telling of it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. The book won a string of awards, including the
National Book Award for Nonfiction in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's one more look back, along with recent movies ``Amistad''
and ``Beloved'' and the buzz over Thomas Jefferson's relationship
with his slave Sally Hemmings, at the long and winding path through
the thicket of American slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Ball calls this surge of interest part of the vast ``unfinished
business'' of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, he says, are ``very happy to tell the Germans how to
make sense of their Nazi past ... and we're very happy to lecture
the South Africans about their history of exclusion and
disenfranchisement of African people, and yet we're not able to
incorporate the memory of slavery into our sense of who we are. It
deeply marks who we are as Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, we have never had an honest reckoning
with the legacy of the plantations.''
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter of the earnings from sales of the book go to
restitution projects Ball and family members are designing with
descendants of Ball slaves.
</P>
</TEXT>
