<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-MUSIC-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
A GLOBAL HEARTBEAT ON CDs 
(bl) 
By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   World music thrives on misunderstandings. As a marketing
category, it's a grand hodgepodge. The world-music bins of any
well-stocked store are likely to hold field recordings from remote
villages as well as pop songs concocted in 64-track digital
studios, and practitioners of traditional styles end up next to
hybrids of, say, didgeridoo and Brazilian percussion and
synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion may baffle new fans, but it's true to the history
of music, where no category stays intact very long.
</P>
<P>
   Music carries the traces of cultures as they meet, dance
together, struggle for pre-eminence or get together on the sly;
musicians steal each other's licks only to recast them in the mold
of their own traditions. The ever-evolving material might be a
deity's rhythm that travels back and forth across the Atlantic,
changing with each journey; it might be the way an electric guitar
is made to sound like a zither in one place, a thumb piano in
another, or bagpipes somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   World music can make a listener appreciate (and worry about the
survival of) isolated cultures. Yet it can also make listeners
marvel at the surprising things that happen when isolation ends and
musicians start to pick up foreign accents, bending what they
borrow into something new. American popular music is downright
provincial in its mass media, rejecting nearly everything with
lyrics that aren't in English.
</P>
<P>
   But while world music is ignored by commercial radio and
television, many listeners who discover it get hooked. Importers
and licensers and packagers of world music have created a small
world with a huge number of possibilities: sonic excursions as
close as a CD player. There's music for purists and
assimilationists, traditionalists and rock fans, and every few
years, another bit of the globe claims some shelf space: Pakistan,
Cape Verde, Ireland, Cuba and the musical cornucopia of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   One central source for international music is the World Music
Institute's new catalog of albums and videos, with thousands of
releases documenting mostly traditional music from Albania to
Zimbabwe; the institute's Web site is www.heartheworld.org.
</P>
<P>
   Major record-store chains, like Virgin, Tower and HMV, also
offer plenty of world music. Stern's (71 Warren St. in Manhattan's
Tribeca) is a reliable source of African music; Bate Records (140
Delancey St. on Manhattan's Lower East Side) and the mail order
house Descarga (718-693-2966, 800-377-2647 or www.descarga.com)
have a broad selection of Caribbean music, particularly from the
Spanish-speaking Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a selection of some of the best world-music releases of
the past year (and one from 1997): just a handful of destinations
for the ears. (CDs range in price from $15 to $19 for a single
domestic disk to $20 to $25 for an imported CD.)
</P>
<P>
   Algeria
</P>
<P>
   RACHID TAHA: ``Diwan'' (Island). Rachid Taha is one of the most
important voices of rai, Algerian rock with a confrontational
streak. He has lived in France for 30 years, beyond reach of
Algerian censors, and he has sung about the intolerance facing his
fellow immigrants and the loneliness of exiles. ``Diwan'' asserts
his cultural pride, reviving older songs from Algeria, Egypt and
Morocco and celebrating the history of rai. Meanwhile, the music
considers tradition with 1990's ears. Most of the time, hand drums
drive the music's terse but unfolding melodies, and Taha's rough,
ardent voice is answered by oud, flute or Arabic-style strings. And
every so often, a programmed drumbeat or a wah-wah guitar slips
into the mix, only making the songs sound more biting and fervent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamas
</P>
<P>
   ``THE REAL BAHAMAS, VOLS. 1 AND 2'' (Nonesuch). Musicians were
immediately smitten with these recordings when Volume I appeared in
1966. It was a collection of gospel songs and hymns, radically
adapted to Afro-Caribbean timing and delivery, with raw, ebullient
voices building call-and-response harmonies full of rhythmic moxie.
Guitarists like Ry Cooder and Taj Mahal studied the hide-and-seek
syncopations of Joseph Spence, who always placed a chord where it
was least expected; the Grateful Dead and the Incredible String
Band both learned the Pinder Family's version of ``I Bid You Good
Night.'' But none of the imitators could match the verve of the
original recordings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brazil
</P>
<P>
   CAETANO VELOSO: ``Livro'' (Polygram, Brazilian import). Caetano
Veloso is one of the greatest songwriters of the century: a master
melodist, a lyricist who merges surreal imagery with a sense of
history and a sense of humor, a singer whose voice radiates
tenderness and supple swing and a musician who connects to
traditional music, pop and jazz from all over. ``Livro''
(``Book''), which was released in 1998 along with Veloso's
autobiography, floats endearing melodies over a subtly remarkable
array of backups: sambas and 12-tone lines, Bahian drum choirs and
electric-guitar funk. Looking inward, Veloso contemplates a world
of musical ideas.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELO VELLOSO: ``Um Segundo'' (Velas, Brazilian import). This
young Brazilian singer brings a warm, guileless voice to
immaculately graceful pop. The album's dozen pop songs touch on
Brazilian styles like bossa nova, forro and pagode samba, and bring
a Brazilian subtlety to borrowings from reggae, salsa, funk and
nuevo flamenco. The arrangements maintain a light touch while Ms.
Velloso caresses the melodies, making the songs seem to come
straight from the heart.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOM ZE: ``Fabrication Defect'' (Luaka Bop). Tom Ze may be
Brazil's most impish songwriter. Like his fellow members of
Brazil's tropicalia movement, he thinks about semiotics and
multinational capitalism as well as the imperatives of romance and
carnival. He puts together ingenious vamps and engaging tunes, then
knocks them off-center with a shifty beat or an unexpected noise,
finding beauty in the disruption. He has often been compared to
Frank Zappa, but he's more melodic and far more concise, coming up
with sweet-and-sour songs that tease before they spring their
surprises. An album of remixes of his songs by fans including John
McEntire of Tortoise, Sean Lennon, the High Llamas and Amon Tobin
is due this spring.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon
</P>
<P>
   ANTHOLOGY OF WORLD MUSIC: ``Africa: The Ba-Benzele Pygmies''
(Rounder). Rounder Records has been reissuing CD versions of albums
from the remarkable series of ethnomusicological recordings that
were released by Unesco from 1968 to 1987, and academics aren't the
only ones who should hear them. The Ba-Benzele Pygmies, nomadic
hunters who live in the rain forest where the Central African
Republic meets Cameroon, are rhythm wizards whose hunting songs,
stories and even lullabies sound like a perpetual party. They
create astonishing lattices of rhythm: vocal parts that yodel and
leap, quick call-and-response choral singing, layer upon layer of
polyrhythm, all using nothing more high-tech than voices,
percussion and whistles. It's beautifully cooperative music, with
soloists and choruses and percussionists interlocking in grand
designs. The individual voices are strong and vivid, the ensemble
singing would challenge even a gospel choir, and the drumming
builds unstoppable grooves. The only shortcoming of this recording
is that it's monophonic; stereo would have made heads spin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Congo
</P>
<P>
   SAMBA NGO: ``Metamorphosis'' (Compass). Congo gave the world
some of the most exuberant guitar music anywhere: soukous, built on
reclaimed rumba rhythms and twinkling intertwined guitar lines.
Samba Ngo, a Congolese guitarist and singer who now lives in the
San Francisco Bay Area, has been pushing soukous in pan-African
directions, incorporating Nigerian Afro-Beat, reggae, Zimbabwean
thumb-piano music, and some dance-music electronics. In his genial
voice, he sings serious lyrics about the strife in his homeland,
but the music stays buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba
</P>
<P>
   ``PINARENO: FROM THE TOBACCO ROAD OF CUBA'' (Alula). Cuba fields
some of the world's slickest and most startling dance bands, among
them the highly recommended Los Van Van, David Calzado and Charanga
Habanera, Manolito y Su Trabuco, NG La Banda and Paulito y Su
Elite. But far outside Havana, near the plantations where tobacco
is grown for cigars, bands also stay in practice playing for the
farm workers. This collection, recorded in the tobacco country of
Pinar del Rio, features local bands who make up in exuberance what
they lack in polish; they conserve slightly older styles than urban
bands do, and their voices sound approachable rather than
superhuman, though the rhythms still jump. Don't miss Grupo el
Organo Pinareno, whose wooden-piped organ sounds like a salsa
calliope.
</P>
<P>
   Finland
</P>
<P>
   LOITUMA: ``Things of Beauty'' (Northside). These
conservatory-trained Finnish musicians probably sound more polished
than the original performers of their folk songs; in exchange, they
bring the music an angelic purity. Four women harmonize in ethereal
voices, accompanied by the chiming tones of a five-string harp and
an occasional fiddle. The melodies are kin to Celtic and medieval
music, ranging from jaunty waltzes to sustained, otherworldly
chorales that seem to float between centuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greece
</P>
<P>
   ``MOURMOURIKA: SONGS OF THE GREEK UNDERWORLD 1930-1955''
(Rounder). Criminal types have patronized musical innovations from
tango to jazz to reggae. In Greece, too, outlaws had music they
could call their own: the rembetika, a story-song accompanied by
string instruments like bouzouki, guitar or the smaller lute called
the baglamas. The songs on this collection have a hard-bitten,
clandestine tone, sung in voices that have seen their share of
trouble. And the translations of the lyrics spin scenarios that
gangsta rappers would recognize: gambling, smoking dope, shootouts
with cops, woman trouble. The recording quality varies, from a few
worn 78-RPM. disks to fairly high fidelity, and despite the
bare-bones arrangements, the music suggests that Norman Mailer was
wrong: tough guys do dance.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti
</P>
<P>
   BOUKMAN EKSPERYANS: ``Revolution'' (Tuff Gong International).
Boukman Eksperyans builds its songs on traditional Haitian and
African drumbeats, many of them from rural styles of voodoo. Above
that foundation, anything can show up: guitar power chords, reggae
backbeats or age-old call-and-response vocals. The songs' lyrics,
sung in Haitian Creole (or Kreyol) with occasional bits of English,
insist war must end, urge Haitians to resist ``industrialism,
imperialism and monopolism'' and, in a song that dominated Haiti's
last carnival, mock corrupt politicians. There are a few too many
pompous synthesizers, but the ancient rhythms and the singers' raw,
troubled voices make the songs ring with passionate commitment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia
</P>
<P>
   ``KALIMANTAN: DAYAK RITUAL AND FESTIVAL MUSIC'' (Smithsonian
Folkways). Smithsonian Folkways has been releasing a monumental
series of carefully recorded music from all over Indonesia, with
extensive notes and plenty of selections that non-specialists can
enjoy. Scattered across an archipelago of 13,000 islands,
Indonesian villagers maintain a huge array of traditional styles,
many of them previously unrecorded. The 17th volume presents music
from central and southern Borneo: somber choral songs; peppy,
syncopated ensembles of gongs and bamboo tubes, and the utilitarian
drumming and singing of a shaman ritual, including the sound of the
shaman singing with a spirit's voice.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iran
</P>
<P>
   KAYHAN KALHOR: ``Scattering Stars Like Dust'' (Traditional
Crossroads). Kayhan Kalhor gives the kemancheh, a Persian fiddle
played upright, an extraordinary workout in the three long
improvisations on this album. Playing alone, or accompanied by
Pejman Hadadi on the tombak (hand drum), Kalhor turns little riffs
and lines into dizzying extrapolations, full of suspense, insistent
rhythms and breakneck virtuosity. He plucks shifting, percussive
accents; he plays somber melodies; he lingers over buzzing tremolos
and then races to the far reaches of his range. With no more than
two musicians, the music is stark but riveting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ireland
</P>
<P>
   SOLAS: ``Words That Remain'' (Shanachie). Solas, a
fleet-fingered Irish traditional band that features Seamus Egan on
stringed instruments and whistles, brings out the kinship of Irish
and American tunes on its latest album. With Woody Guthrie's
``Pastures of Plenty'' and a guest vocal by Iris DeMent, Solas
provides some reminders of the Celtic-Appalachian connection. But
its jigs and reels retain the combination of assertiveness and
delicacy that marks the best Irish traditional music.
</P>
<P>
   Israel-New York
</P>
<P>
   THE KLEZMATICS AND CHAVA ALBERSTEIN: ``The Well''
(Xenophile/Green Linnet). Chava Alberstein is an Israeli singer
whose hits follow the conventions of pop anthems everywhere. But on
``The Well,'' she moves away from pop and collaborates with the
Klezmatics, a New York band that extends klezmer tradition with
touches of jazz and funk. Ms. Alberstein smooths the band's more
raucous tendencies, while the Klezmatics pull her away from pop
orchestrations to sing alongside accordion and clarinet and fiddle,
letting her reveal all the subtleties of her pensive, compassionate
voice. Together, they unveil new songs based on texts by leading
Yiddish poets: tales of longing, loss and a search for identity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
