<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-MUSIC-3RDTAKE-N     01-28 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-MUSIC-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: for identity. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Italy
</P>
<P>
   PAOLO CONTE: ``The Best of Paolo Conte'' (Nonesuch). A gruff
smoker's voice, a piano style that wanders from honky-tonk to tango
palace to tony cabaret, and a weathered romantic's world view have
made Paolo Conte a well-known songwriter in Italy. This survey of
his songs, re-recorded with cannily arranged small bands featuring
fisarmonica (Italian accordion), guitar or saxophone, introduces a
wily European character to an American audience. The translated
lyrics capture his incorrigible mixture of seduction and nostalgia.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madagascar
</P>
<P>
   TARIKA: ``D'' (Xenophile/Green Linnet). Madagascar, the island
in the Indian Ocean known for its unique flora and fauna, has
home-grown instruments that are just as unusual: the valiha, the
marovany and the kabosy, bright-toned zithers and lutes that are
plucked in transparent, marvelously intricate patterns. Tarika has
made itself Madagascar's pop ambassador to the Western world,
adding electric guitar and other Western touches to Malagasy music,
but it holds on to the music's charm and its breezy momentum. The
title of Tarika's new album, ``D,'' stands for dance. On it, the
band remakes some Malagasy dance hits alongside its own tunes, and
the music's perpetual-motion rhythms could make anyone want to
learn how to dance the salegy or the tsapika.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico
</P>
<P>
   JUAN GABRIEL: ``Con Banda . . . El Recodo'' (BMG U.S. Latin).
Juan Gabriel, one of Mexico's most popular singers, periodically
hooks up with old-fashioned ensembles like mariachi groups and, on
this album, a banda: one of the brass bands that parades through
town squares, oom-pahing and tootling with grand disregard for the
niceties of being perfectly in tune. He went to the heartland of
banda music, Sinaloa, to hook up with Banda El Recodo. Singing
about love going wrong, Gabriel emotes emphatically, with a sob and
a smile in his voice. Most of the songs use the classic banda
style, waltzing and strutting, while a few try brassy versions of
doo-wop and calypso. Even as Gabriel suffers the pains of love, the
clarinets are laughing his troubles away. It's a short album _ only
33 minutes long _ but a lot of fun.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morocco and Beyond
</P>
<P>
   ``HAMDULILLAH: FEZ FESTIVAL OF WORLD SACRED MUSIC, VOL. 2''
(Sounds True). The recorded memento of the ecumenical Festival of
World Sacred Music held in Fez, Morocco, wisely concentrates on
performers in Arabic and Middle Eastern traditions. One after
another, men and women raise their extraordinary voices in devout
song: meditative music from Turkish whirling dervishes and Indian
dhrupad singers, gracious melodies from Andalusia and gutsy,
impassioned, lavishly ornamented improvisations from Iraq,
Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan and Morocco. Although the music was recorded
live at outdoor shows, the sound is detailed and remarkably
intimate.
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar
</P>
<P>
   KYAW KYAW NAING: ``Pat Waing: The Magic Drum Circle of Burma''
(Shanachie). Music from Myanmar, formerly Burma, can baffle
Western-trained ears. The melodies hop around, scamper ahead,
circle through a repeating line, speed up and ease off, or pause
before leaping off in a brand-new direction; asymmetry rules.
Burmese music, like such other Southeast Asian music as Indonesian
gamelan music, uses all sorts of tuned percussion instruments.
Among them is the pat waing, a circle of 21 tuned drums played by
one musician, with tones so pure they sound almost electronic. The
pat waing, played by Kyaw Kyaw Naing, is at the center of the music
on this album. It's used for speedy, bubbly solo pieces, alongside
other percussion instruments, or in tandem with the Western piano
(played in a purely Burmese way, with its own skittering lines).
Duets for pat waing and the oboelike hne have the flexibility and
friskiness of Ornette Coleman's jazz. The tunes are exhilarating,
footloose and impossible to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   KING SUNNY ADE: ``Odu'' (Atlantic/Mesa). King Sunny Ade was one
of world music's revelations when his albums appeared
internationally in the 1980's, and he has released countless albums
since then. But he's not to be taken for granted. He and his
African Beats _ his big band of guitars, drums, keyboards, singers
and dancers _ remain one of the world's most satisfying ensembles,
intertwining rhythm and riff in music that bubbles and kicks behind
his sweetly understated voice. ``Odu'' captures the group in all
its clockwork genius, letting listeners hear all the internal
colloquy of hand drums and stick drums, high and low guitars and
plush choral vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and Beyond
</P>
<P>
   ``HOMMAGE A NUSRAT FATEH ALI KHAN'' (Network, German import).
Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, who died in 1997, introduced the world
outside Pakistan to the driving, spiraling, hand-clapping
improvisations of qawwali: ecstatic songs devoted to the saints of
Sufism, a mystical branch of Islam. Related forms exist across the
Islamic world, and this double album brings together some of the
leading performers from Syria and Senegal, Iran and Kurdistan, as
well as Pakistan, offering tributes and memorials to Khan. The
songs are prayers, elegies and joyous incantations. As they pay
homage to qawwali's towering figure, Mehr and Sher Ali _ brothers
who, like Khan, are in qawwali's Punjabi school _ and some of
Khan's cousins show that the style will endure.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippines
</P>
<P>
   ``UTOM: SUMMONING THE SPIRIT'' (Rykodisc). The T'boli, a tribe
in southwest Mindanao in the Philippines, are Minimalists without
the college degrees. Playing lute, tuned gongs, fiddle, zither or
wooden flute, they cast natural sounds _ birdcalls, rushing winds _
into short musical cells, then build them into pieces that use the
repetition of just a few notes to propel and hypnotize. These
skillful field recordings place the listener close to the
instruments, capturing precise nuances of tone; now and then, a
tropical bird chirps along with the austerely compelling music.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-MUSIC-4THTAKE-N     01-28 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-MUSIC-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
UNDATED: compelling music. 
  &HT;    Portugal and Beyond &HT;    ``ONDA SONORA: RED HOT AND LISBON'' (Sonovis, Portuguese import;
an American release is likely this year). Five centuries ago,
Portugal built a colonial empire that stretched from Brazil to
Angola to Macao, and music traveled along with slaves and goods.
The empire left behind an esthetic that prized saudade, the wistful
sadness that permeates bossa nova, Portuguese fado and Cape Verdean
morna.
 &HT;    This album, part of a series of benefit albums for AIDS
education and relief, brings together some of the far-flung results
of that empire, with musicians from Portugal, Brazil, Africa and a
few ringers from the United States (K.D. Lang, David Byrne) and
England (Durutti Column).
 &HT;    The musicians mix and match, with plenty of African-Brazilian
collaborations and styles from an ethereal version of fado to
driving carnival drumming to lilting African pop to dance-hall rap
in Portuguese over a samba beat: world music that dances across
national boundaries.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Zimbabwe
 &HT;    
 &HT;    STELLA CHIWESHE: ``The Healing Tree: The Best of Stella
Chiweshe'' (Shanachie). Stella Chiweshe was the first woman to make
a career of playing the mbira, the thumb piano that's at the center
of Zimbabwe's traditional and rock music. She sings in an earthy
voice, like a gospel singer who can also ululate, and she meshes
the intricate, plinking patterns of her mbira with marimbas and
guitars.
 &HT;    As she sings about spirits and social responsibilities, the
patterns pile up with so much kinetic intensity that in songs like
``Vana Vangu,'' the music simply levitates.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WORLD MUSIC LIVE
 &HT;    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A cornucopia of live world music can be found
throughout New York City. Here is a sampling of concerts through
April, most of them sponsored by the World Music Institute.
Manhattan performance spaces for the concerts are Symphony Space,
Broadway and 95th Street, (212) 864-5400; Beacon Theater, Broadway
at 74th Street, (212) 307-7171, and Town Hall, 123 W. 43rd St.,
(212) 840-2824. Information: call the hall or World Music
Institute, (212) 545-7536.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``MUSIC OF ARMENIA, THE NEAR EAST AND SPAIN,'' with George
Mgrdichian and Dennis Koster, Symphony Space, 8 p.m. Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 12
</P>
<P>
   ``HAWAIIAN SLACK KEY GUITAR FESTIVAL,'' with George Kahumoku
Jr., Cyril Pahinui, Dennis Kamakahi and dancers, Symphony Space, 8
p.m. Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 13
</P>
<P>
   ``THROAT SINGERS OF TUVA, HUUN-HUUR-TU,'' Town Hall, 8 p.m.
Tickets, $25.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 19
</P>
<P>
   ``BAHIA AND BEYOND: MUSIC AND DANCE OF NORTHEAST BRAZIL,''
Symphony Space, 8 p.m. Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 20
</P>
<P>
   ``DRUMMING AND DANCES OF GHANA: ODADAA!,'' Symphony Space, 8
p.m. Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 21
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GOLDEN VOICE OF MALI: SALIF KEITA,'' Beacon Theater, 8
p.m. Tickets, $20 to $40.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 26
</P>
<P>
   ``ALI AKBAR MORADI WITH PEJMAN HADADI AND KAYHAN KALHOR,''
Symphony Space, 8 p.m. Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 27
</P>
<P>
   ``SOUNDS OF NUBIA: HAMZA EL DIN,'' Symphony Space, 8 p.m.
Tickets, $21.
</P>
<P>
   March 5-6
</P>
<P>
