<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMAN-FILM-REVIEW-790     01-28 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-FILM-REVIEW-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE 24-HOUR WOMAN': WORKING 9 TO 5 IN DAYDREAMS ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk shows and women's magazines are full of the
matters raised by Nancy Savoca in her new film, ``The 24-Hour
Woman,'' in which a woman with a high-powered job tries to cope
with the high-powered hassles of balancing career and family. But
somebody on the other side of the camera has clearly been here and
done this, and boy, does it show on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicating the film to her own mother, Ms. Savoca describes the
joy and frustration of new motherhood in workaday detail, right
down to the last unmade bed. ``Nobody threw food around!'' one
woman marvels about office life, returning to the work force after
having stayed home bringing up children for a long spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 24-Hour Woman,'' which had its world premiere at the
Sundance Film Festival last Friday, is also the opening feature for
``The Feminine Eye: Twenty Years of Women's Cinema,'' the
ambitious, far-reaching series that began Thursday at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music Rose Cinemas. It's nothing if not a topical,
well-intentioned way to begin this program, presented by both the
academy and New York Women in Film and Television.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Savoca's film joins Sally Potter's ``Orlando,'' Julie Dash's
``Daughters of the Dust,'' Euzhan Palcy's ``Sugar Cane Alley,''
Jane Campion's ``Sweetie,'' Claire Denis' ``Chocolat,'' Agnieszka
Holland's ``Angry Harvest'' and Barbara Kopple's ``American
Dream,'' among others, as films so alert to the experiences and
sensibilities of women that they could never be mistaken for the
work of men. Even in Ms. Kopple's anatomy of a strike at a
meat-packing plant, there is a particular awareness of hardship for
the strikers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   These are films that aren't likely to gloss over serious
concerns with brutish, escapist fantasy. It's also unlikely that
any man would humorously incorporate a breast-pump scene, as Ms.
Savoca does here.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to report that Ms. Savoca, whose ``True Love''
belongs high on any list of films rich in womanly wisdom and whose
``Household Saints'' and ``Dogfight'' were no less fearless, had
made the most of such a golden opportunity to hit a nerve. But
``The 24-Hour Woman'' is an unexpectedly strained farce, and not
often a very credible one at that.
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of a long, classic comedy-of-errors
sequence about a working mother racing to her child's first
birthday party, the film is otherwise a homey compendium of
feminist talking points laced with awkward satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is deal with the little everyday stuff,''
says the film's heroine, Grace Santos (Rosie Perez), echoing the
filmmaker's outlook. ``The little everyday stuff that drives us
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The world in which Grace means to do this is that of daytime
television, where she has had a hyperactive career directing a zany
women's show. The handsome host happens to be Grace's husband,
Eddie Diaz (Diego Serrano), so it is seen as a huge ratings boon
when Grace becomes pregnant and the blessed event becomes
television fodder. On a show that runs stories like an expose about
pantyhose, Grace's pregnancy is big news.
</P>
<P>
   In a screenplay written with her longtime collaborator, Richard
Guay, Ms. Savoca describes the different stages of ambivalence that
herald the birth.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that Grace's boss (Patti LuPone) is hard-driving
and unhelpful, that Grace's mother-in-law is discreetly meddlesome,
or that Eddie remains an on-the-air dreamboat while Grace flails
and loses confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it help that despite the huge metamorphosis of
impending motherhood, Grace does her best to resist change. She
clings to work yet feels the thrill of maternity, and to the film's
credit it has no easy answers about such mixed feeling.
</P>
<P>
   What's best about ``The 24-Hour Woman'' is its refusal, most of
the time, to buy into Hollywood's usual happily-ever-after
solutions to this very contemporary dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Far less successful are the film's feeble efforts to send up an
already self-satirizing species of television show. (``You know
what? We gotta do a segment: `Baby Fever!' Who gets it, and why?'')
</P>
<P>
   And its use of supporting characters as straw men and women also
robs the story of life. Eddie is vain and preoccupied, leaving
Grace to pick up the slack. Grace's new assistant, Madeline
(Marianne Jean-Baptiste), is too conveniently her opposite, as a
woman who has stayed home with children and now wants to resume her
career. And Madeline's husband, played with amusing exasperation by
Wendell Pierce, is the obligatory househusband the screenplay
requires for balance.
</P>
<P>
   For all the film's rumpled realism, these characters too often
operate like chess pieces rather than flesh and blood.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The 24-Hour Woman'' goes on ruefully to watch Grace at home
with the new baby, stuck in a home that looks as if a tornado had
hit it, while Eddie's perky television partner (Karen Duffy) laughs
and frolics on the air. Then it sends her back to work, confronts
her with the problem of nanny envy, and arrives at a pinnacle of
domestic disaster with that aforementioned birthday-party sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Motherhood and workaholism collide spectacularly as Grace works
later than she should have, races to get a present just in time to
see the last flavor-of-the-month toy being sold to someone else,
can't find a taxi and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's final desperate measure _ having the nanny videotape
counterfeit party scenes so that it will look for posterity as if
Grace made it home on time _ makes for an emblematic image of
late-1990s motherhood that will not soon be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Perez is vigorous, though never entirely convincing in the
film's workplace scenes. But by the last half-hour, nobody could be
persuasive in this role. The story contrives such a heavy-handed
on-the-air crisis for Grace and Eddie that it would be hard to
think of anything less credible, unless it's the Band-Aid
resolution pasted on afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The ending is encouraging, but it also betrays the film's
overall message. In leaping from the real world to an idealized
one, ``The 24-Hour Woman'' loses track of its most important
thought about mixing work and parenthood. It's not this easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 24-Hour Woman'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes brief sexual situations and
much more profanity than the material warrants.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE 24-HOUR WOMAN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nancy Savoca; written by Ms. Savoca and Richard
Guay; director of photography, Teresa Medina; edited by Camilla
Toniolo; music by Little Louie Vega and Kenny Gonzalez; production
designer, Bob Shaw; produced by Guay, Larry Meistrich and Peter
Newman; released by the Shooting Gallery. Running time: 95 minutes.
This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Rosie Perez (Grace Santos), Marianne Jean-Baptiste
(Madeline Labelle), Patti LuPone (Joan Marshall), Karen Duffy
(Margo Lynn), Diego Serrano (Eddie Diaz) and Wendell Pierce (Roy
Labelle).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1723EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
