</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN ON SOCIAL SECURITY FIX: HIGHER TAXES, LOWER BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
Thursday that taxes will have to be raised or benefits cut to fix
the nation's Social Security system permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also urged Congress to consider raising the retirement
age and lowering annual cost-of-living increases as part of any
plan aimed at expanding the life of the Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Unless changes are made, Social Security will not be able to pay
out the full amount of benefits beginning in 2032 when there will
likely fewer workers paying into the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all likelihood, (Social Security) taxes will have to be
raised or benefits cut, given that the system as a whole is still
significantly underfunded,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said later that ``we
could not agree with him more on the fact that we need to do more.
The president has made clear that he needs to work with Congress in
order to reform. In addition to reserving the surplus and paying
down the debt, we need to do more to reform the system. And we look
forward to having that debate with Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman praised President Clinton's plan to put aside
62 percent of the projected federal budget surplus over the next 15
years to bolster the system, saying it ``represents a major step in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But he reiterated his opposition to Clinton's plan for the
government to invest 25 percent of the Social Security surplus in
the stock market. Greenspan said there would be no way to insulate
investment decisions from political pressures and that investing
trillions of government money in the stock market could crowd out
private money, which could damage the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large surpluses over the next 15 years, if they actually
materialize, can significantly reduce the fiscal pressures created
by our changing demographics,'' Greenspan said. But he cautioned
lawmakers on fashioning a Social Security fix largely or wholly on
projected budget surpluses because, he said, they may not
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-as-you-go Social Security system is funded by payroll
taxes that are taken from current workers' paychecks and given to
current retirees. The system is also supported by a trust fund
invested in government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   As the large baby boom generation begins retiring over the next
decades, the trust fund is projected to run out of money in 2032.
At that point, unless something is done, the system would not be
able to make full payments to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton outlined his plan to shore up the system in his
State of the Union speech last week, Social Security reform has
become a major topic on Capitol Hill. Several lawmakers, including
Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., and Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, are working on their own plans aimed at
keeping Social Security fully funded beyond 2032.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan, $2.7 trillion of the projected $4.4
trillion federal surplus, would be used to bolster Social Security
over the next 15 years. He also proposed investing $700 billion of
the $2.7 trillion in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Social Security, he proposed setting aside $500
billion from the surplus to allow low- and middle-income people to
set up their own individual retirement accounts by investing in
stocks and bonds. The general idea of allowing individuals to
invest some of the money they pay in Social Security taxes in
securities has been endorsed by many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who headed a commission that succeeded in boosting
the viability of Social Security in 1983, warned lawmakers that
raising payroll taxes could be ``burdensome'' and said they also
need to look at increasing the retirement age. The current Social
Security retirement age is 65, but beginning next year it will
gradually increase to age 67 by 2022. Last year legislation that
would have gradually raised the retirement age to 70 failed in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also said lawmakers could adjust the consumer price
index that is used to determine annual cost-of-living increases in
Social Security and government programs. He and several other
economists have said that the index, which was adjusted slightly
last year, still overstates annual price increases by about 1
percentage point.
</P>
</TEXT>
