<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEELCITY-DANCE-REVIE     01-28 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEELCITY-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STEEL CITY': ALL IN A DAY'S WORK FOR HARD-TAPPING HARD HATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Canada)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dein Perry has upped the ante exponentially in
``Steel City,'' which opened its 40-city American and Canadian tour
on Tuesday night at Radio City Music Hall. Perry, the creator of
the smaller and more intimate ``Tap Dogs,'' crams the Music Hall
stage with steel stairways, huge steel grids that get flipped every
which way, and trucks and cars of all descriptions. A steel-mesh
front curtain rises and descends, and an immense reflecting disk
opens to frame the show's culminating rock-club scene. Colored
lights and smoke are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   To match this scale, the Australian tap choreographer, dancer
and director has assembled a company of 21 dancers who are
accompanied by a four-man rock band perched high above the action.
Their music and the dancers' taps are heavily miked. What emerges,
along with the big production values, is 90 minutes of sounds: taps
hitting steel stairs, grids and the sides of the various trucks and
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Also in scale are the long lines of synchronized tappers that
sometimes split, excitingly, into smaller ranks like skaters'
whirling group combinations. Dancers slide down a very steep
incline formed by the tipping floor of a truck. They leap from one
steel cage to another as forklifts move the cages up and down. They
bounce against and dangle from high up on the front curtain.
</P>
<P>
   There is a scenario of sorts, with the men playing workers at a
large factory or high-tech garage. They punch in at a clock, put on
their work clothes and construction helmets and dance through the
day, sneaking visits with their girlfriends before reassembling for
more hard dancing at the rock club that night. One waits, however,
for the whole thing to turn into a lavish television ad for upscale
jeans or bargain car tires.
</P>
<P>
   Perry does attempt humanizing moments with a few smaller,
quieter routines, though not very strenuously or with much
confidence. Best of all is his own rough-edged, buoyant tapping as
the factory supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The score is by Tim Finn, with set design by Brian Thomson,
lighting by Trudy Dalgleish and costumes by Michael Wilkinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
