<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-BUCHANAN-HN     01-28 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BUCHANAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN BRINGS FRESH AIR TO STALE SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Ray Buchanan arrived at just the right time, etching
himself between the this-coach-hates-that-coach angle and the
actual kickoff of Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   He's a shot of inspiration, a compelling character in a week
when just about anything is considered interesting. He's fresh, and
that counts for plenty because the Super Bowl gets stale long
before it ever begins.
</P>
<P>
   What Buchanan, the Atlanta Falcons' left cornerback, has done is
steal the show.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has taken the spotlight away from the everlasting feud
between Mike Shanahan, John Elway and Dan Reeves and we thank him
for that. That issue is just about dead. Terrell Davis is the
league's most valuable player and Jamal Anderson is Atlanta's star
runner, but neither can compete with Buchanan right now because
they don't wear studded dog collars at interview sessions. Elway,
even leading up to what's supposed to be his last game, is just
Elway. Even he seems bored with himself.
</P>
<P>
   So we are left with Denver Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe as
the only legitimate contender to Buchanan's title, and even Sharpe
admitted that his opponent has top billing at this point. All
Sharpe had to do was ask a group of reporters one question:
``Anybody ever heard of Ray Buchanan before he got to Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   This whole thing started with a prediction. Call it a joke,
because that's how Buchanan and his Falcons view it. Buchanan was
doing a televised interview for HBO's ``Inside the NFL'' last week
when Cris Collinsworth asked him if he thought the Falcons would
win. Buchanan said yes. He did it in a roundabout way, but enough
people who saw it figured this was Broadway Joe and the Jets in
this city all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guarantee is full of confidence,'' Buchanan said. ``We're
a football team that is coming in here believing in ourselves.
There's a lot of buildup to actually giving a guarantee for a win.
But the guarantee is about the fact that we believe in ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he hasn't backed down, Buchanan embodies what these
Falcons are all about. They aren't cocky _ you can't be that when
you have this team's horrendous history. They're ebullient,
enjoyable, and one of their few drawbacks is that more of them
can't be as interesting as Buchanan has been this week.
</P>
<P>
   For now, we'll take Buchanan because lately he's talking as well
as he's playing. That's the thing about this guy who no one ever
heard of before this season. The man can play.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was easily the Falcons' most important acquisition
after quarterback Chris Chandler prior to last season. In four
seasons with Indianapolis, he had proven himself an adept coverage
corner and the Falcons hadn't had one of those since Deion Sanders
left town.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan made Jerry Rice irrelevant in a divisional playoff win.
Randy Moss roasted secondaries throughout the season, then faced
Buchanan and caught just one pass for 4 yards in the second half of
Atlanta's upset victory over Minnesota in the NFC Championship
Game. He earned his first Pro Bowl and he's earned the right to
chirp a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand where I'm living on the football
field anyway,'' Buchanan said. ``I'm playing on an island out there
and I'm feeling like Gilligan so I can go out there and hold my
own. I believe you can say what you want and then hopefully, you
can back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan can back it up. So can the Falcons, even if people
aren't as excited about them as they would be about the Vikings.
And now that Buchanan has garnered his fair share of the media's
attention, here's hoping he has a few more tricks left to unveil.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it would be one thing if Buchanan just arrived in
Miami and started spouting off blather to prove the Falcons weren't
scared. Instead, what he's done is make people notice his resume
and realize this man was a star before he stepped onto this stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
