<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `A Brief History' To `Zebrahead' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every January independent film celebrates its high season at the
Sundance Film Festival, now in its 15th annual session, in Park
City, Utah. This year, in need of an independent infusion itself,
home video checked in, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-way collaboration, the Sundance Channel, New Video
and Critics Choice Video have gathered 99 Sundance films and are
offering them as a special package on the Internet at the Sundance
Filmstore (www.sundancefilmstore.com).
</P>
<P>
   The list begins with Francois Girard's ``Thirty-Two Short Films
About Glenn Gould'' (1993) and proceeds alphabetically from ``A
Brief History of Time'' (1991), Errol Morris' documentary about
Stephen Hawking, to Anthony Drazan's ``Zebrahead'' (1992), about
the tribulations of a racially mixed group of students.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way are a mix of documentaries and dramas, many of
them of the small, intense variety one expects to find along the
festival circuit. Tom DiCillo's ``Box of Moonlight'' (1996), with
John Turturro as a man on a journey to find himself, and ``Big
Night'' (1995), with Stanley Tucci, are included, as are Adam
Egoyan's ``Exotica'' (1994), Joel Coen's ``Blood Simple'' (1984),
Mira Nair's ``Mississippi Masala'' (1991) and Todd Solondz's
``Welcome to the Dollhouse'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $9.99 to $24.95 each. If you're feeling
especially expansive, the entire collection is $1,360.77. Or one
can choose groups of five films according to category. Sundance
Audience Awards make up two groups: documentary and drama.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are five grand jury prize winners: ``Blood Simple,''
Nancy Savoca's ``True Love,'' Edward Burns' ``Brothers McMullen,''
Victor Nunez's wonderful ``Ruby in Paradise,'' about a young woman
who deserts Tennessee for a new life in Panama City, Fla., and Kayo
Hatta's ``Picture Bride,'' the story of a Japanese woman renovating
her life through an arranged marriage in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Other categories include black directors, Australian movies,
first feature films shown at Sundance (for example, Quentin
Tarantino's ``Reservoir Dogs'').
</P>
<P>
   Some groupings go outside the festival: Hong Kong action, for
instance, five films by Akira Kurosawa and ``docs that rock'': five
music documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the collections of five range from $52.77 to
$123.77. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Indies &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While it has no connection to Sundance, a new Web site put up by
the video chain West Coast Entertainment (www.moviebuff.com) also
features independent films (albeit not to the exclusion of big
studio titles), with panel discussions and comments.
</P>
<P>
   In a column called Off Hollywood by Michael Sauter, it is
suggested that the 1999 Academy Awards might resemble those of
1996, when independent films won so many Oscar nominations. Then it
was ``Fargo'' and company. Now it's ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``Gods
and Monsters,'' ``Elizabeth,'' ``Central Station,'' ``Life Is
Beautiful'' and ``Affliction,'' to name a few. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's Something About Mary &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the dweeb Ted Stroehmann (Ben Stiller) asks the very
attractive Mary Jensen (Cameron Diaz) to go to the prom with him,
she amazingly says yes. That makes Mary both gorgeous and nice, but
while picking her up at her house Ted zippers himself up too
hastily in the bathroom and winds up in the hospital instead of on
the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Still smitten with Mary years later, he hires a private eye
named Healy (Matt Dillon) to track her down in Florida, where
everybody, including Healy, has fallen in love with her or is about
to. As in any film by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (``Dumb and
Dumber''), bedlam ensues with, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times, ``a crazy audacity that's worth admiring.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $108.97. 118 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Feb. 2. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mulan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sign me up for the next war!'' cries the grandmother in a
Chinese fable that elevates the level of violence in children's
animation. When her ailing father is unable to serve in the army,
Mulan dresses like a man and takes his place, accompanied by a tiny
dragon (the voice of Eddie Murphy) perched on her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of her father, the Emperor and the son of a
general, the males she encounters are buffoons. They and the often
wooden scenes don't help ``the most inert and formulaic of recent
Disney animated films'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Disney. $26.99. 88 minutes. Closed captioned. Release
date: Feb. 2. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marie Baie des Anges &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocks jut like the fins of ``angel sharks'' in the sea near
Nice, where a 15-year-old girl named Marie (Vahina Giocante) runs
wild one summer. First she takes up with a group of sailors and
then with a pug-faced petty thief (Frederic Malgras).
</P>
<P>
   In a paganistic ode to Eros, the camera never stops as youths
prowl looking for danger and excitement. Visually beautiful, the
film views its characters as untamed forces of nature, but gets
into problems when its ``story line isn't always clear'' (Stephen
Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 90 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Alarmist &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heinrich Gregoris (Stanley Tucci) markets his home-security
systems by breaking into one house, thereby opening checkbooks of
neighbors terrified that the same thing will happen to them. Such
behavior scandalizes Gregoris' earnest young protege, Tommy Hudler
(David Arquette), who later has an affair with an attractive 40-ish
divorcee (Kate Capshaw) and becomes the central character in a kind
of no-fault late 90s variation of ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the halfway point, Evan Dunsky's film suddenly decides to
be a murder mystery, turning a light, loopy satire into something
that is ``unable to decide where to go or what tone to adopt''
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 92 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Feb. 2. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROJECT GRIZZLY. &UR;  &LR; Having survived a close encounter with a
grizzly bear in his youth, a Canadian researcher named Troy
Hurtubise decides to go face to face with another one and this time
do it right. So he designs a ``Robocop''-style armored suit, which
turns out to be bulletproof. But bearproof? 1998. First Run
Features. $19.95. 84 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAKED CITY (1948), BRUTE FORCE (1947) and THE BLUE GARDENIA
(1953). In the first film (96 minutes), precursor to the television
series, Jules Dassin directed Barry Fitzgerald as Detective
Muldoon, on the trail of a killer in New York City. Inmates revolt
against a sadistic guard (Hume Cronyn) in ``Brute Force'' (95
minutes), Dassin's dark prison drama, which also stars Burt
Lancaster and Yvonne De Carlo. (Both films were produced by the New
York newspaper columnist Mark Hellinger.) In Fritz Lang's ``Blue
Gardenia'' (90 minutes), the panicky Norah Larkin (Anne Baxter)
kills an amorous fellow (Raymond Burr) with a fire poker, or so she
supposes. Kino. $24.95 each. Information: (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING FROM THE HEART. &UR;  &LR; A play performed by the Polka
Children's Theater of Wimbledon, England, and filmed by the BBC
tells the real-life story of the solo percussionist Evelyn Glennie,
who has had a worldwide concert career despite being ``profoundly
deaf'' since the age of 12. 1998. Global Stage. $27. 98 minutes.
Information: (888) 324-5623. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
