<HEADER>
A2773 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERBOWL-ALTERNATIVE     01-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-ALTERNATIVES-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST RIVAL TV CHANNELS WILL PUNT, BUT SOME ARE LINING UP REAL
COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a programmer for a network or cable channel that's not
airing the Super Bowl, you have a choice of two strategies on the
night of the big game: fight or give up.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, of course, has the game this year. But only a handful of
outlets appear to be fighting it directly, with marathons designed
to pull away the nonfootball demographic, which is largely, but not
exclusively, female.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl is scheduled to air from 5 to 9 p.m. CST Sunday _
not that it ever finishes on time, or that it's always interesting
throughout. But there's even more time to watch _ or avoid _ the
big event: The official pregame show begins at 1 p.m. CST, and Fox
will begin football-related programming as early as 10 a.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know that this year's game pits Atlanta vs. Denver,
or you aren't even aware that those cities have NFL teams, or you
don't even know what the NFL is, check out this guide to what else
is on.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST
</P>
<P>
   ABC: Apparently throwing in the towel completely, ABC is airing
``Muppet Treasure Island'' _ sure to cause strife among young kids
and their football-loving elders _ at 6 p.m. CST. Following that is
something called ``Don't Get Taken,'' a consumer-oriented show
about avoiding ripoffs, and a rerun of ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS: Adding an installment of ``48 Hours'' (6 p.m. CST) before
the venerable ``60 Minutes'' (7 p.m. CST), CBS is also aiming
directly at the non-jock-obsessed audience with a repeat of ``The
Spirit of Liberty Moon,'' a two-hour ``Touched by an Angel''
``movie'' (8 p.m. CST).
</P>
<P>
   NBC: Falling in the Not Quite Giving Up category, NBC is airing
a double-feature of movies directed at young, primarily female
audiences. ``Clueless,'' starring Alicia Silverstone in a
surprisingly well-done high-school version of Jane Austen's
``Emma,'' airs at 6 p.m. CST. ``Miami Rhapsody,'' starring Sarah
Jessica Parker in the most Woody Allen-esque romantic comedy not
directed by Woody Allen, is more of a misfire and airs at 8 p.m.
CST. By the way, the Super Bowl is in Miami this year. Coincidence?
We think not.
</P>
<P>
   PBS: Pledge dollars, not ratings, are PBS' concern, and
KERA/Channel 13 in Dallas-Fort Worth is not taking the Super Bowl
lightly. Beginning at 1 p.m. CST, the public-broadcasting station
will air ``Souper Bowl'' _ six hours of cooking shows, including
the ever-popular ``Two Fat Ladies.'' Afterward, Channel 13 will air
a crooners' double bill against the big game. ``Engelbert
Humperdinck: Love Unchained'' airs at 7 p.m. CST; ``Harry Connick
Jr.: Romance in Paris'' airs at 8 p.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   UPN: The little network that's suffering is airing one of the
best non-Bowl options: 1995's ``A Little Princess,'' a marvelous,
too-little-seen film that's one of the best family movies of the
'90s. Our recommendation: skip the Muppets and ``Clueless,'' and
watch this at 6 p.m. CST. UPN needs your help more than ABC and
NBC. (Rival netlet the WB is apparently staying out of the fray
with a standard run of sitcoms.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CABLE
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MOVIE CLASSICS: AMC is pulling out the big guns _ or
rather, the big hankies, with a ``Superbawl Sunday'' tear-jerker
marathon, and the cable channel isn't just going after the Super
Bowl time slot; it wants the whole day. It starts at 5 a.m. CST
with ``Sayonara,'' starring Marlon Brando. In direct competition
with the Super Bowl will be ``Never Say Goodbye,'' with Rock Hudson
(5 p.m. CST); ``Love Is a Many-Splendored Thing,'' with William
Holden and Jennifer Jones (7:05 p.m. CST); and for some well-earned
comedy relief, Billy Wilder's ``Love in the Afternoon,'' with Gary
Cooper and Audrey Hepburn (9 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E: Also taking direct aim is A&AMP;E, with a ``Murder, She Wrote''
marathon that begins at 11 a.m. CST and runs straight through the
Super Bowl slot before concluding with the final credits at 3 a.m.
CST. Anyone who watches all the episodes can claim to have more
stamina than John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   CARTOON NETWORK: The hippest 'toon station on TV
(Nickel-what-deon?) does a pretty good job of parodying real-life
sportscast bombast with the ``Sylvester vs. Tweety Marathon'' (noon
to 4 p.m.). The ``pre-game'' show features a look back at last
year's big match-up (Tom vs. Jerry), expert analysis from HBO's
stable of football announcers, great voice-over narration by NFL
Films' Harry Kalas and, of course, cheesy 3-D graphics. (You don't
think this Ted Turner-owned station purposefully mocked the
overblown sportscast style of Rupert Murdoch-owned Fox? Nah,
'course not.) The ``game'' is a series of cartoon moments between
the bad ol' puddy-tat and Tweety, with play-by-play provided by Fox
Sports' Pat Summerall and John Madden. It's all very cute, but the
pre-game is too long, and the cartoons are funnier than the
commentary. The best moments are the on-the-scene reports, in which
rabid fans tailgate and dine according to their allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY CENTRAL: In a late-breaking program change, what Craig
Kilborn used to call ``your channel of fun'' is airing ``Absolutely
Not the Big Game'' _ a six-hour marathon of the witchy Britcom
``Absolutely Fabulous'' (beginning at 1 p.m. CST). Because over
there, they don't play football with their hands, sweetie darling.
``AbFab'' fans can even vote for the episodes they want to see at
www.comedycentral.com.
</P>
<P>
   FOX FAMILY: We're not sure if this counts as counterprogramming,
especially because this is a sister channel of the Super Bowl
network, but we find it intriguing: ``High School U.S.A.,'' a 1983
movie starring Michael J. Fox, Nancy McKeon _ and a pre-''ER''
Anthony Edwards. That's at 7 p.m. CST. Before it is a solid triple
bill of animated features: ``Charlotte's Web'' (2 p.m. CST);
``Snoopy, Come Home'' (4 p.m. CST); and ``A Boy Named Charlie
Brown'' (5 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   FX: Is this counterproductivity, or is it trying to monopolize
the audience? Fox's cable channel is airing ``The Princess Bride,''
Rob Reiner's delicious fractured fairy tale, at 7 p.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   LIFETIME: You can bet that ``The Network for Women'' will put up
a fight, and it is, airing ALL of the 1995 miniseries ``A Woman of
Independent Means,'' from 3 to 9 p.m. CST Sally Field stars.
</P>
<P>
   TBS: Although network owner Ted Turner has more than a passing
interest in Atlanta, his cable ``superstation'' is airing a 24-hour
``Andy Griffith Show'' marathon, beginning at 5 a.m. CST Sunday.
Included: the series' first episode.
</P>
<P>
   TNT: One of Turner's ``other'' networks is taking an interesting
tack: Rather than air female- or kid-friendly stuff, it's airing a
series of made-for-TV westerns, including 1996's ``Riders of the
Purple Sage'' (5 p.m. CST) and 1997's ``Last Stand at Saber River''
(7 p.m. CST).
</P>
<P>
   THE TV FOOD NETWORK: Naturally, this network knows which side
its bread is buttered on, and is mostly staying out of the way
during the Super Bowl. In anticipation of the game, however, it's
airing two specials featuring its biggest star, Emeril Lagasse:
``Tailgating,'' at 11 a.m. Saturday, and ``Emeril Live! Superbowl
Cocktail Special'' at noon Sunday. Before you go thinking that
Emeril's gone provincial on you, his tailgate-party menu includes
grilled quail and andouille sausage ragout.
</P>
<P>
   USA: Getting to have it both ways, the USA Network is airing one
of its macho standards, ``WWF Sunday Night Heat,'' at 6 p.m. CST,
then following it with the female- (and Sensitive New Age Guy-)
friendly ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' at 7 p.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   VH1: Beginning at 1 p.m. CST, the pop-culture cable channel will
run seven installments of its ``Behind the Music'' series. Gloria
Estefan, who perhaps not coincidentally is one of the headliners of
the Super Bowl's halftime extravaganza, goes head to head with the
Super Bowl at 5 p.m. CST; Madonna's segment is at 7:30 p.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
