<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETS-LEPTO29-COX     01-28 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-LEPTO29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VETS SEEING MORE CASES OF POTENTIALLY FATAL DISEASE OF DOGS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although dogs often receive annual vaccinations for
leptospirosis, veterinarians say they have started seeing an
increase in cases of the potentially fatal disease _ possibly
because suburban pets are catching it from raccoons and other wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine approved for use in dogs does not protect them from
wild animal strains, college veterinarians say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until a few years ago, we saw a few sporadic cases,'' said
Larry Cowgill, a professor at the University of California at Davis
veterinary school. ``In the last three years, we have seen 37 or 38
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most dogs can easily tolerate the strain of
leptospirosis that has traditionally been a canine disease, strains
that ``jump'' from wild animals such as rats, mice and raccoons can
be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   A dog with the disease may have symptoms that are common to many
canine ailments _ vomiting, lethargy and a difficulty standing up
because muscle pain. In some cases, the disease causes kidney and
liver failure and death.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians can treat most cases with antibiotics, but Cowgill
said a number of animals with kidney failure have been given
hemodialysis at the Davis school.
</P>
<P>
   Animal doctors in Pennsylvania, Tennessee and New York also have
reported increases in leptospirosis. The disease is known as a
zoonosis because it can spread from animals to human beings.
</P>
<P>
   It often is spread in water contaminated by the urine of an
infected animal, and aid workers say large numbers of human cases
have appeared in the aftermath of flooding brought to Honduras and
Nicaragua by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard from colleagues in Boston, the New York City area
and in Knoxville, Tenn., that they are seeing an increase in cases
among dogs,'' Cowgill said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, University of Florida small animal
specialists said through a spokeswoman their clinic had ``not seen
a case of lepto in several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Green, a professor at the University of Georgia veterinary
school and author of a widely used textbook on small animal
infections, said part of the perceived increase may lie in the fact
that vets are better able to detect leptospirosis than they were a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been there all along and we're just now
recognizing it,'' Green said. ``People were doing blood tests that
did not detect the strains many dogs were getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said the wild animal strains are likely to be more severe
to dogs than disease caused by the organism to which canines have
adjusted over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines approved by the Food and Drug Administration are based
on the canine strain and therefore don't prevent infection by the
wild animal disease. Although zoo lions and tigers get
leptospirosis, it does not occur in housecats.
</P>
<P>
   University of Pennsylvania veterinarians say the increase among
dogs may be the result of ``urban sprawl'' with more and more pets
being exposed to puddles and streams that have been contaminated
with wild animal urine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners of dogs that run in areas with a lot of wildlife should
be on the lookout for symptoms and take the animal promptly to a
veterinarian if illness is suspected,'' the Pennsylvania vet school
said in a recent newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
