<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXBUDGET-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Thursday, Jan. 28, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Lou Hudson, Paul Wagner, Tom Uhler, Carmelita Bevill or
Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's National/Foreign Desk at (817)
390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUPER BOWL-ALTERNATIVES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ If you're a programmer for a network or cable channel
that's not airing the Super Bowl, you have a choice of two
strategies on the night of the big game: fight or give up. Fox, of
course, has the game this year. But only a handful of outlets
appear to be fighting it directly, with marathons designed to pull
away the nonfootball demographic, which is largely, but not
exclusively, female. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Why ``Providence'' succeeds, a few thoughts on ``The
PJs'' and a viewer's view of critics, as readers sound off to TV
Critic Ken Parish Perkins. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STILL CRAZY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In the new comedy ``Still Crazy,'' the broken-up and
reunited (though broken down) '70s rock band Strange Fruit are more
like middle-aged crazy than ``still crazy.'' These 50-ish
has-beens, having disbanded 20 years ago, decide to get together
for a tour. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SHES ALL THAT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ We probably shouldn't begrudge filmmakers who want to
give millennials movies like ``She's All That,'' even though it
isn't very well-executed. This high-school ``Pygmalion'' tries hard
but misfires frustratingly on many counts. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story
has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Give that man from Indiana credit. He knows political
balderdash when he hears it, although he might not be able to spell
it. Former Vice President Dan Quayle's denunciation of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' theme as a ``silly
and insulting term'' fused together by ``liberal Republicans''
suggests that his bovine-excrement detector is in pretty good
working order. By CECIL JOHNSON. Story has moved in ``k''
commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ BOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The Fools are back, but the Ladies are conspicuously
absent. I'm not talking about some distorted board game, but rather
of popular investment books and their continual sequels. By TERESA
MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
