A2779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT29-COXUPDATE     01-28 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    1STLEDE
 &HT;    Adds: IOC-GANGA-0129, WACO-CARJACK, GA-COMMUTES, HIV-SUIT,
IMPEACH-MANAGERS, DOG-COUGH
 &HT;    Updates: JORDAN-HUSSEIN-0129, IMPEACH-BARR
 &HT;    Deletes: TEENDRIVE-GRADES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Jan. 29, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ Senators are struggling to reach a bipartisan
timetable for the remainder of President Clinton's impeachment
trial as the White House signals it may forgo defense witnesses if
there's no new damaging testimony. (Foskett/Carr/Sherman, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   w/IMPEACH-BARR _ ATLANTA _ House impeachment prosecutor Bob Barr
was back in Atlanta Thursday, a day after the potentially
forshadowing Senate votes of Wednesday. Hanging with Barr to get
his take on where the process goes from here and what constituents
think. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MANAGERS _ WASHINGTON _ House managers are drawing up
the questions they will ask in the depositions, whenever they
occur. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PETS-LEPTO _ WASHINGTON - Leptospirosis, a bacterial disease
that infects humans and numerous animals, apparently is becoming
increasingly common in dogs, according to some veterinary schools.
At times the shock to a canine's kidneys is so severe the animal
must have hemodialysis to survive. Only four veterinary hospitals
in the country are equipped to administer the treatment. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   PANDA _ Zoo Atlanta is getting two pandas from China and will
build a new exhibit in which to house them. Besides the two pandas
coming to Atlanta this summer, there are only three others in the
U.S. _ two in San Diego, and one in Washington, D.C. (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON _ DAYTON _ Rev. Jesse Jackson comes to Dayton this
afternoon to announce his latest initiative, calling for 1,000
churches to begin investment clubs and mentoring programs for
troubled youths in their churches. This is, in part, a continuation
of his effort to encourage investment in Appalachia. (Franklin,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Developing from 4 p.m. EST press conference and 7 p.m. EST
address.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKMEN-MENTORS _ The 100 Black Men of America have launched a
$35 million Miracles of Mentoring campaign with a goal of building
a national youth leadership institute in
</P>
<P>
   metro Atlanta. (PScott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WACO-CARJACK _ WACO, Texas _ Bystanders thwart carjacking,
detain suspect for police. (Gaar, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   TRACK COUGH _ More on the strange `kennel cough' afflicting
greyhound tracks around Florida. Need to talk to experts to find
out: is it a bacteria or virus, what is it exactly, symptoms, how
you treat it, are track owners reluctant to treat dogs because they
can't raise while being medicated, how often do you get this kind
of outbreak, what are the rules about shifting dog from track to
track, where are the Palm Beach kennel dogs bred, do they have an
outbreak, etc? (Donald, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   DOG-COUGH _ An outbreak of kennel cough has shut down dog racing
tracks in Birmingham, Mobile and Palm Beach. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-COMMUTES _ ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes said Thursday that it'll
probably take two multi-modal stations to link the metro Atlanta
bus, rapidrail/commuter rail, auto transportation systems as
invisioned _ one station downtown and another somewhere on the
northside for east-west rail. Wouldn't say where the northside
station would be located or how much both stations would cost.
That's part of the studies to be done, he said, and that the train
from Atlanta to Macon to Albany would be almost self-sustaining _
probably operational in about five years. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UNITED-WAY _ AUSTIN _ Austin set a national record for
increasing its contributions to the United Way in 1998, the second
year in a row that Austin has seen among the highest increases in
the nation. The big increase in contributions from Dell and the
other high-tech companies, and the increase in people giving over
$1,000, fueled the growth. (Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-BUDGET _ AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush unveils his
budget plan on Thursday. We are looking for details on his proposed
$2 billion school property tax cut and how he plans to make sure
local school districts don't simply raise local taxes (like they
did in 1997) to fill the gap. How much money will Bush put into his
plan for remedial programs to stop kids from being socially
promoted? (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ South Carolina legislature
takes the first step toward approving a lottery. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-LOBBY _ ATLANTA _ Doors to the House and Senate were
flung open for them but now a badge bars them from the chambers
where they once helped write laws. Once legislators they are now
lobbyists _ among the more than 1,000 who work the Capitol halls;
among the ones targeted by Gov. Roy Barnes in his ``eel-skinned
briefcases and aligator shoes'' comments. (Cook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN-0129 _ AMMAN, Jordan _ When it came time to
choose the successor that would ensure his kingdom's future, time
finally caught up with Jordan's King Hussein. Faced with his
deteriorating health, Hussein apparently changed his mind about
which son will take his place and on his last night in Jordan
handwrote the 14-page explanation of why he would dump his loyal
brother from the job: He described ``parasites'' and ``climbers''
sowing discord in the palace. Observers in Jordan have hope in the
new crown Prince Abdullah, the king's surprise choice over his
favorite but much younger son, Hamzeh. But, they believe the king
was not healthy enough to face the resistance that would have
occurred had he made the 18-year-old Hamzeh his successor. The
king's frantic last week involved the ambitions of a queen and
would-be queen, and tragic misunderstandings between brothers.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   IOC-GANGA-0129 _ LONDON _ Signaling a bitter fight ahead,
Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo on Thursday said he intends to oppose
the move to expel him from the International Olympic Committee over
allegations that he accepted improper payments from the Salt Lake
City bidding committee. ``Never in my life will I resign,'' Ganga
said in an interview published in a French newspaper. ``I will
fight tooth and nail before my peers.'' Ganga, the powerful
president of the Association of National Olympic Committees of
Africa, also struck out at IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch,
whom Ganga accused of sacrificing his friends to save himself.
Ganga has been an IOC member since 1964, two years longer than
Samaranch, who has been president since 1980. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 4:30 p.m. EST in both the International and
Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HIV-SUIT _ ATLANTA _ In what is believed to be the first lawsuit
of its kind in Georgia, a dental hygenist who is HIV-positive will
file suit Thursday in federal court against his former employer,
who fired him because he disclosed he was HIV-positive. The lawsuit
is unusual because it involves a health-care provider. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
