<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARING COMPANIES THRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Teller turnover at NationsBank is 46 percent,
which means nearly half the faces at the windows change in a year's
time. Customers may or may not care, but the bank does.
</P>
<P>
   It costs between $2,000 and $3,000 to replace each teller _ a
hefty sum for a notoriously low-paying job. But trying to cut
turnover is not just about money, said Bill Nelson, president of
the Kansas City region of NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about keeping happy workers. That's why, for example,
the bank offers a subsidized child-care program. The subsidy is
only $25 a week, but among tellers who participate, turnover
plummets to a paltry 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto among the bank company's check processors. Turnover among
processors not receiving day-care subsidies is 44 percent; among
those in the program it's 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not every worker needs day care, of course. That's why the
subsidy is just one of the work/life balance programs available to
all bank associates.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson deliberately says associates _ not employees. He wants
the language to mirror an evolving corporate culture. The shift,
Nelson said, involves less reacting to workplace problems and more
proactive programs to make associates' lives better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solutions to workplace pressures begin and end with
corporate culture,'' Nelson said at a ``Best Practices'' seminar
sponsored by the Johnson County Community College's Business and
Industry Institute. ``Those are values that begin at the top and
permeate every aspect of a company.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson arrived in Kansas City in 1988, he joined Boatmen's
First National Bank, which later became a part of NationsBank. He
found an organization still in emotional turmoil from a 3-year-old
merger.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank now is merging with BankAmerica. Change _ and the
pain of smashing two corporate cultures together _ roils on. It
isn't easy to convince associates that the organization believes in
giving its people freedom to make choices and share responsibility
and rewards when change continues to pour down.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a tight labor market, when employers claw to get and
keep good workers, an organization in merger turmoil has to work
even harder. To compete, it must offer the best practices of other
preferred employers. Among them: parental leave, flextime, the
option of reduced hours, job sharing, child-care assistance,
employee assistance programs for mental health counseling and legal
assistance referral programs.
</P>
<P>
   Such benefits are the tools a company has to tell its people it
cares about their personal well-being. No company can promise
paternal, lifetime care. But Nelson is trying to encourage a
workplace partnership that gets commitment and responsibility from
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, for example, associates get two hours of paid time
off to spend with their children. Those with no children of their
own are encouraged to use the time for youth-oriented community
service.
</P>
<P>
   These may look like little things. But they're bigger things
than many employers do. They make a place feel like somewhere good
people want to work.
</P>
<P>
   Now if they would just do something about tellers' pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
