<SLUG> BC-FARM-POLICY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT, HARKIN SAY FARM GOODS SHOULDN'T BE TOOLS OF FOREIGN
POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sens. John Ashcroft of Missouri and Tom Harkin of
Iowa, who are on opposite ends of the presidential impeachment
fight, came together Wednesday to co-sponsor a bill that would give
Congress more control over food embargoes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would establish rules for congressional approval or
disapproval of embargoes used as leverage in foreign policy
matters. Sometimes, for example, the United States punishes a
country by halting farm exports.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft issued a news release about the bill shortly before the
Senate resumed the impeachment trial Wednesday. Ashcroft, a
Republican, voted against dismissing the case and for the calling
of witnesses. Harkin, a Democrat, voted just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But the two senators from neighboring states see eye-to-eye on
the embargo issue. The bill's other sponsors include Republican Kit
Bond of Missouri and two Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``An embargo that singles out foodstuffs is destined to fail,
harming family farmers without achieving meaningful foreign policy
objectives,'' Ashcroft said. About 40 percent of all food and fiber
farm sales are exported, according to Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would amend the Agricultural Trade Act of 1978,
would give Congress 100 days to approve or reject a food embargo.
If Congress approved, the embargo would be in effect for one year,
or less if the president desired. If Congress disapproved, the
embargo would end in 100 days unless vetoed by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said the legislation would send two messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it tells customers overseas that U.S. farmers and
ranchers are reliable suppliers,'' he said. ``Second, it increases
the security of American agriculture that the farm sector won't be
singled out as a tool of foreign policy without full consideration
by the president and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said about 80 farming organizations support the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
