<P>
   CARMAKERS-SALES-NYT (Tulsa, Okla.) _ The carmakers are out to
overhaul how they sell cars, and how Americans buy them. Ford is
going farthest, buying up dealerships in mid-size cities, entering
into joint ventures with leading dealers and thereby gaining
control over the car-buying experience. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO-NYT (Undated) _ In recent weeks, Volvo has
again appeared on the corporate dinner table; Fiat S.p.A., the Ford
Motor Company and possibly others have been weighing a purchase of
the Swedish company's automotive division. The buzz has sent
Volvo's stock spiraling first up, then down. Enjoy the S80 while
you can. It may be one of the last products an independent Volvo
produces. By Dan Neil.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-BELTS-NYT (Undated) _ In Sweden more than 40 years
ago, automaker Volvo conducted its first test of a two-point safety
belt. It hired Nils Ivar Bohlin, now 75, a Swedish-born aircraft
engineer as the company's first safety engineer. He immediately
went to work on inventing a three-point safety belt, which was
installed as standard equipment in the 1959 Volvo. Since then,
Bohlin's invention has been used by automakers worldwide and is
credited with saving millions of lives. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ The Mazda Protege: What you see is
not all you get. By Bill Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-DESIGN-NYT (Detroit) _ Auto shows were once time machines
that propelled visitors into a utopian future where cars might fly
_ or at least they looked as if they could. But at today's big
shows, the clock runs backward. A stroll through manufacturers'
glitzy displays, like those at the North American auto show that
ended here this week, is often a trip down memory lane. By Michelle
Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ The California Air Resources Board
has wrought a lot of misery in the name of clean air. Now the
Specialty Equipment Market Association, an industry group
representing after-market equipment manufacturers and suppliers to
the auto industry, is suggesting that CARB is ignoring California
law in its zeal to destroy old cars in the name of environmental
correctness. By John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
