A2822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-28 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Jan. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Protracted heavy rain will result in areas of flooding in parts
of the southern Plains and Mississippi Valley during the next few
days. A slow-moving low-pressure area will drift east from western
Texas, drawing copious amounts of moisture from over the Gulf of
Mexico. The heaviest rain will occur later Friday and Friday night
from eastern Oklahoma to northern Arkansas where a series of
thunderstorm clusters will pass over the region. Later Friday night
and Saturday, the rain will gradually spread into the Tennessee and
central Mississippi River Valleys. Farther west, locally heavy snow
will fall from eastern New Mexico to the panhandles of Texas and
Oklahoma. Some areas will have more than a foot of snow by Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will spread south from New England to the Middle
Atlantic states as high pressure burgeons over eastern Canada.
Gusty breezes from the north and scattered snow showers will add to
the chill of the day along the New England Coast. Otherwise, partly
to mostly sunny skies will prevail across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably mild air will spread from the interior Northwest to
the northern Plains on gusty breezes from the west. However, chilly
air will remained trapped in some of the deeper valleys of the
northern and central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of fronts will bring windswept rain to
the Washington and Oregon coasts. Locally heavy snow will fall in
the Cascades. Farther south, ample sunshine will cover most of the
Southwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Cut-off Low
</P>
<P>
   Like puddles of standing water that are left behind after a
flooded stream recedes into its banks, high-altitude pools of
stagnant, cold air can be left behind after the jet stream dives
south and then recedes north. These cold pools, having been
separated or ``cut-off'' from the steering winds of the jet stream,
can stall over a region for days. Since cold air at high altitudes
is associated with low pressure aloft, cut-off cold pools can cause
protracted precipitation. During the next few days, a cut-off low
will drift east from the southern Plains, bringing flooding rain to
the lower Mississippi Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
