<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-SCANDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMING COMMISSION AGREES TO LET HILTON OFF THE HOOK IN BRIBERY
SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Gaming Commission agreed
Wednesday to let Hilton Hotels Corp. walk away from a Kansas City
casino bribery scandal unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms recommended by Mel Fisher, executive director of the
commission, the Beverly Hills, Calif., company would voluntarily
surrender its state gaming license at the same time the riverboat
is sold to Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That $15 million transaction, contingent on state licensing of
the Atlantic City, N.J.-based Trump group, was announced earlier
this month and could be completed by late April.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton attorney Jerry Riffel said after the meeting that his
client would not resist the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hilton is not admitting anything,'' he said. ``We've done
nothing in Missouri that would affect our suitability to do
business in Missouri. We will surrender our license pursuant to
Missouri regulations because we no longer intend to do business in
Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Fisher said he had been prepared to recommend
harsh disciplinary action against Hilton when the sale to Trump was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter,'' he said Wednesday, ``Hilton has a
right to appeal any action we might take, and we could conceivably
be tied up in court for months or years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our time and our resources can be better spent to
keep 800 jobs open for employees and the facility open for an
orderly transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Hilton been fined, suspended or stripped of its Missouri
license, other jurisdictions with Hilton casinos probably would
have taken their own disciplinary actions against the company.
</P>
<P>
   When New York real estate tycoon Donald Trump offered to buy the
casino for roughly 15 percent of its original $100 million cost,
Hilton accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Trump general counsel Robert M. Pickus on Wednesday introduced
several top company officers to commissioners and urged a quick
investigation and licensing approval for the Trump organization.
``The sooner the better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Hilton agreed to pay the federal government more
than $500,000 to avoid a criminal trial on charges that it provided
financial rewards to former Kansas City Port Authority Chairman
Elbert Anderson in exchange for his political support for the
casino.
</P>
<P>
   Under Anderson's leadership in 1993, the Port Authority selected
Hilton over two other applicants for city lease rights to the site
at the foot of the Paseo Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Markland Rousseau, a former Hilton senior vice
president, was indicted in Jackson County on three counts of felony
perjury related to the Anderson affair.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau, now an Atlanta businessman, has pleaded not guilty and
is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   The two cases culminated years of state and federal
investigations into a $250,000 grant Hilton awarded in 1993 to K.C.
Perspectives, a private group controlled by Anderson and Michelle
Lathan, a close associate.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Wednesday in Kansas City, the Gaming Commission also
levied a $5,000 fine against Station Casino Kansas City for its
failure to prevent a 16-year-old boy from entering the casino Nov.
22 and gambling on slot machines with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father learned of the incident involving his ex-wife
and reported it to state gaming authorities the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Harrisonville woman has been charged in Clay
County District Court and faces up to six months in jail for
allowing a minor to gamble. The case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Station Casino said the company had not decided
whether to appeal the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Station's St. Charles, Mo., casino did not contest a $250,000
fine in 1997 after a 12-year-old girl was caught there playing slot
machines while accompanied by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The two cases are the only ones on record in which minors have
been caught gambling in Missouri casinos, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Riverboat Gaming Association said that in 1997, the
latest year for which statistics are available, 29,800 minors were
identified by casino employees and refused admittance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
