<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-GANGA-0129-1STLD-     01-28 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-GANGA-0129-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: clarifies lede to say 'was quoted in a French daily on
Thursday . . . '; trims final three grafs
 &HT;    CONGO'S GANGA VOWS TO FIGHT EXPULSION FROM IOC
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Signaling a bitter fight ahead, Jean-Claude Ganga of
the Republic of Congo was quoted in a French daily on Thursday as
saying that he intends to oppose the move to expel him from the
International Olympic Committee over allegations that he accepted
improper payments from the Salt Lake City bidding committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my life will I resign,'' Ganga said in an interview
published in the French newspaper Liberation. ``I will fight tooth
and nail before my peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, the powerful president of the Association of National
Olympic Committees of Africa, also struck out at IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch, whom Ganga accused of sacrificing his friends to
save himself. Ganga has been an IOC member since 1964, two years
longer than Samaranch, who has been president since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   One of six IOC members targeted for expulsion last Sunday by the
IOC executive board, Ganga, who lives in Paris, made the statements
in the daily's Thursday edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Samaranch) defends his skin by throwing opprobrium on the
others,'' Ganga told the newspaper. ``We had friendly relations but
if he's trying to get rid of his friends it will be dangerous for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga said 40 IOC members would oppose his expulsion when a
special IOC session assembles in mid-March to consider the fate of
the accused members. A two-thirds majority -- or 75 members -- must
approve the motion to expel. If Ganga survives the March vote, it
would be a stinging defeat for Samaranch who has vowed to rid the
IOC of members accused of unethical behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The members are accused of accepting nearly $800,000 worth of
goods and services from Salt Lake before the city won a vote in
1995. Under IOC rules members are not allowed to receive gifts
worth more than $150.
</P>
<P>
   One of the accused IOC members, Kenya's Charles Mukora, resigned
Wednesday, bringing the total members to leave the organization
over the scandal to four. Accusations against three other members
are still being investigated by a special IOC commission formed to
look into allegations of vote buying related to Salt Lake's
successful campaign for the 2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga said none of the benefits he derived from his visits to
Salt Lake City during the bidding process, including large medical
bills, travel assistance and help in a huge real estate investment,
were bribes.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Organizing Committee records show that Ganga, 64,
received more than $200,000 from the bid committee, including
direct payments of $70,010, more than $17,000 for medical expenses
for his family, $115,000 in travel expenses and gifts and
entertainment expenses totaling more than $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
