<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-THEATER-NYT &LR;      01-28 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FARE: IS THAT A DOLL IN MY LASAGNA?; A TASTE OF DANCE; A
FRIEND IN NEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAUREL GRAEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a few minutes on Klickitat Street, you're bound
to think you're in ``Leave It to Beaver'' territory: The characters
include a full-time mother who's always baking cookies, a beaming
paterfamilias who dotes on his wife, and their two daughters, who
have a loving if often argumentative relationship. The only working
women are schoolteachers.
</P>
<P>
   But if this doesn't sound much like 1990s America, don't worry:
Fans of Beverly Cleary's children's books will recognize the street
as the home of Ramona Quimby, a feisty tomboy with enough spirit
and will to start a feminist movement of her own.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Ramona Quimby,'' Theaterworks USA's stage adaptation of
Ms. Cleary's books, does justice to its spunky namesake: When she
takes a beaten-up doll named Chevrolet to show and tell and later
plunges it into her teen-age sister's baking lasagna (Ramona says
she was only playing ``Hansel and Gretel''), you know this heroine
is no ordinary girl.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is ``Ramona Quimby'' ordinary children's theater. The
staging is refreshingly inventive, from the lively narration
provided by Ramona's sister, Beatrice (known by her nickname,
Beezus), to John Farrell's set, whose backdrop is an enormous green
felt board on which the actors place symbols of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Len Jenkins, who adapted the material, has included Ramona's
many challenges that go beyond show and tell. Her dad (John Ferry)
loses his job and takes up smoking again. Mrs. Quimby (Lisa Levy)
trades in her cookie batter for work in a doctor's office. Ramona's
adored aunt (Alexa Harris) falls in love with an old school chum
(Nicholas Little) and plans to move to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   And while divorce and destitution don't exactly loom, life on
Klickitat Street starts to look a lot more like 1990s America.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Barron, the production, for ages 5 and up, moves
as quickly as Ramona's imagination. And with talented guides like
Jane Mendez and Harley Abrevaya (Ramona and Beezus, respectively),
even adults won't mind returning to third grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramona Quimby,'' Saturday and Sunday at 10:30 a.m. and 12:30
p.m. at the Promenade Theater, 2162 Broadway, at 76th Street, (212)
627-7373. Tickets: $18.50.
</P>
<P>
   A Taste of Dance
</P>
<P>
   If Doug Elkins hadn't become a dancer, you have a feeling that
he might have ended up a chef. He describes one of his pieces,
``More Wine for Polyphemus,'' as ``the chicken pot pie of
classicism.'' Another, an excerpt from ``Narcoleptic Lovers,'' ``is
the equivalent of a tango and a taffy pull,'' he said. ``It kind of
pretzels around itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The pie, the taffy, the pretzels and other delights are all on
the menu at the New Victory Theater, where the Doug Elkins Dance
Company is the latest to take part in the ``Step Lively'' family
series.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins, known for his energized, highly athletic choreography,
has combined music by Led Zeppelin, James Brown, the hip-hop group
Urban Species, John Adams (composer of ``Nixon in China'') and
Handel, as well as forms like ballet, voguing and martial arts.
Call it a highly spiced stew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to make movement the way a DJ at a house party layers
different sounds,'' Elkins said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite examples is a duo from ``The Testosterone
Diversions,'' a work that pokes fun at machismo. Elkins describes
it variously as ``Robert Bly meets Buster Keaton'' and ``Roland
Barthes meets Jackie Chan.'' As for the a capella score, ``It's the
same music you get when you take your kids to a department store
and try to get them to come along,'' he said. ``The kids will
relate very much.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, no doubt, will the parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Doug Elkins Dance Company, at the New Victory Theater, 209
West 42nd St., (212) 239-6200. Performances: Friday night at 7;
Saturday at 2 and 7 p.m.; Sunday at noon and 5 p.m. Tickets, $10.
</P>
<P>
   A Friend in Need
</P>
<P>
   Usually, being a good neighbor doesn't involve anything more
demanding than mutual respect. But during World War II the Danes
discovered that it meant something closer to loving one's neighbor
as oneself. In September 1943, as the Nazis were about to arrest
all the nation's Jews, other Danes risked their lives by helping
more than 5,000 Jews to hide or escape.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue has been dramatized in ``Number the Stars,'' a
Newberry Award-winning novel by Lois Lowry that is required reading
in many New York City schools. Now it has been brought to the stage
by Sean Hartley, whose musical adaptation will open Saturday in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine is Anne-Marie Johansen, a 10-year-old whose best
friend, Ellen Rosen, is Jewish. Although Anne-Marie's parents do
their best to shield her from danger, she ultimately plays a small
but critical role in the Rosens' salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you read about people who do heroic things, you often
think, `Great, but I could never do something like that,''' Hartley
said. ``This novel leads you to think, `That much I could do.'''
</P>
<P>
   The production, by the Elaine Kaufman Cultural Center's Poppy
Seed Players, features two 11-year-olds, Chloe Levenson
(Anne-Marie) and Sofia Abassi (Ellen). Older actors, Hartley said,
would not capture the same vulnerability, or perhaps the same joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Holocaust horror story,'' he said. ``All the things
that kids do were still going on, even during the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Number the Stars,'' Saturday at 7 p.m. (sold out; call about
cancellations) and Sunday at 11 a.m. at Merkin Concert Hall, 129
West 67th St., (212) 501-3330. Tickets, $10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
