<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KATIELEE-BOOK-AZR &LR;      01-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR AWAITS RESURRECTION OF GLEN CANYON  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 LEE-BOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE NEWBERG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Katie Lee was one of the few who knew Glen Canyon
before it was filled with the waters of Lake Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``All My Rivers Are Gone: A Journey of Discovery Through Glen
Canyon'' chronicles her sojourns on the river and her own voyage of
self-discovery that evolved during her trips.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was introduced to the life of a river runner in 1953 when
she traveled the Colorado on the second commercial power boat run
through the Grand Canyon. Rivers ran in her blood after that first
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so awe-inspiring that I found it very difficult to
express my feelings,'' she said. ``You are one little grain of sand
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding the rough rapids of the Colorado in a 21-foot power boat
wasn't any picnic. One scientist on the trip stored dead specimens
in one of the boat's cabins, providing a stinking encounter for any
person unlucky enough to have to go in there.
</P>
<P>
   Floating through the relatively still waters of Glen Canyon for
the first time the next year was peaceful compared to the rough
chop of the same river in the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Glen was so soothing, such a laid-back, heavenly, heavenly
place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee would take about 20 trips through her beloved Glen Canyon
before it was flooded. A folk singer and actress, she was hired by
Mexican Hat Expeditions to sing for paying customers during her
early floating years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I just got so that I found out that this canyon had
something to say to me about my life and my career and how I
handled myself,'' she said. ``It taught me about intimacy and the
value of observation.''
</P>
<P>
   Whispers in the river told her that pursuing the life of an
actress and folk singer who performed for thousands wasn't the best
course. Lee decided to focus on intimacy _ singing for people in
coffeehouses and small venues where the experience was personal.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Canyon also possessed the power to kill, and Lee respected
that might, especially after almost drowning in a pool in a side
canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in Glen Canyon in a tremendous thunderstorm. It just
feels like the Earth is coming to pieces,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Danger was secondary when exploring beautiful side canyons with
fluted walls. There she could swim, wonder at waterfalls and admire
maidenhair ferns and wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just drags you in. You see the mouth of this canyon and
think, `God, what's in there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some slots had dimensions as drastic as 2 feet wide and 600 feet
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light in the place was enough to drive you crazy,'' she
said. ``It would just glow around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite trips were those that she took with companions Tad
Nichols and Frank Wright, river men who loved Glen Canyon as much
as Lee. Together, they named about 25 side canyons.
</P>
<P>
   When news filtered down to the river runners that plans called
for a dam to generate hydroelectric power and provide water for
growing cities of the day, no one thought it was true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said nobody would do a thing like that. None of us really
believed it because there was a law that said that no water could
encroach on a national monument,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and her fellow river mates eventually learned how wrong they
were. Glen Canyon Dam was completed in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   That was 34 years ago. Lee finally got to the point where she
could sit down and write the book about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My anger and my hatred seethed and seethed long enough to get
this book done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Lee wanted to do the book as a novel, but a friend
and fellow lover of Glen Canyon, Ed Abbey, talked her out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that the canyon itself was so powerful and so
wonderful that all I needed to do was to find a way to describe
it,'' she said. ``I just held out for years. Five years ago, I
finally picked it up and said, `OK Ed, I'll do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lee believes that Lake Powell will one day be drained to reveal
Glen Canyon again. That idea has been proposed by the Sierra Club.
Even the late Sen. Barry Goldwater of Arizona, who was instrumental
in the creation of the dam, stated later in life that he wouldn't
vote for it if given a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be drained one way or another. I want Mother Nature to
drain it like, tomorrow,'' Lee said. ``I just hope it happens in my
lifetime.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
