<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Jan. 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, warned Congress not to count on projected
government budget surpluses to solve Social Security's problems,
and he suggested that the two parties would still have to take
politically painful steps, like cutting benefits or raising taxes,
to insure the retirement system's future. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ A day after near party-line votes to
continue the trial of President Clinton, Senate leaders fractured
over the terms for deposing witnesses and put off a critical
dispute over how to conduct the final vote. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   D.C.-RACISM (Washington) _ The racial politics of Washington,
D.C. continue to boil after an aide to the new mayor, Anthony A.
Williams, resigns after using the word ``niggardly.'' By Melinda
Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-VOLVO (Undated) _ Ford announced an agreement to buy the
car operations of AB Volvo for $6.45 billion and immediately said
that the research, design, management and most of the manufacturing
of Volvo cars would remain in Sweden. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-DEATHPENALTY (St. Louis) _ After an extraordinary personal
appeal from Pope John Paul II, Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri
commuted a convicted murder's death sentence to a sentence of life
in prison without parole. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO warned that it was now fully ready
to drop bombs and even deploy troops to stop further violence in
Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
