<HEADER>
A2850 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAMIN-A-$ADV30-COX     01-28 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMIN-A-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILLIONS ARE DENIED THE WORLD'S CHEAPEST MIRACLE DRUG
 &HT;    With VITAMIN-LIST. For release Saturday, Jan. 30.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By failing to invest a few million dollars to add
vitamin A to food supplies in developing countries, the world is
missing the opportunity to prevent deaths of at least a million
children a year, health experts say.
</P>
<P>
   All children in the world were supposed to be free of vitamin A
deficiency by next year under a plan of action adopted in 1992 by
the World Health Organization and UNICEF, the United Nations
Children's Fund. But the year will come and go without the goal
being met.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts say an estimated 1 million to 3 million children
will continue to die annually for lack of doses of the vitamin that
would cost about 20 cents for each of them. Others will become
blind.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists speculate that the vitamin works in several ways,
including helping the immune system fight such diseases as
diarrhea, pneumonia, malaria, measles and other killers of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Dietary vitamin A is most easily derived from meat, fish, eggs
and dairy products, foods which poverty denies to many children in
developing countries. In addition, milk is routinely supplemented
with vitamin A in the United States and most other developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Although vitamin A is found in many vegetables in the form of
beta carotene, the body's ability to produce the nutrient from
vegetables is inefficient, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the U.S. Agency for International Development
recently launched a campaign to get Third World producers of foods
such as sugar and flour to add the vitamin to their products.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will cost the U.S. government about $25 million,
AID officials say, and will take at least four years to reach 60
percent of vitamin-deficient children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sluggish response by health agencies around
the world, the story of vitamin A is one of serendipitous discovery
and scientific skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Alfred Sommer, then an epidemiologist and
ophthalmologist at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, reported
in the Lancet, a noted British medical journal, on a survey he had
conducted of more than 29,000 children living in 450 villages on
the Indonesian island of Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
   The children in roughly half of the villages were given two oral
doses of vitamin A twice over a period of one year, and children in
the other villages were not.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the year, Sommer said, there were 34 percent fewer
deaths from all causes among children given the vitamin than among
those who were not.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1986, the reaction to Sommer's paper among other
scientists consisted of a flood of skeptical and even angry letters
the journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind regards new ideas the way the body regards a foreign
body,'' said William Foege, professor of international health at
Emory University and former director of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta. ``Al's finding is one of
those very crucial discoveries in public health. It was sitting
there for people to discover, but they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Following several years of scientific skepticism, Sommer has
been honored for his work. Now dean of the Johns Hopkins School of
Hygiene and Public Health, he received the coveted Albert Lasker
Award for clinical medical research in 1997. Some scientists regard
him as a serious candidate for the Nobel Prize for medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews this week, Sommer recalled that his initial
interest in the diets of children in Indonesia centered around eye
problems already known to be associated with lack of vitamin A.
</P>
<P>
   One condition, night blindness, occurs because vitamin A is a
necessary to the body's synthesis of rhodopsin, which the retina
needs to detect dim light. More serious conditions involve eye
damage and permanent blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer, a former member of CDC's Epidemic Intelligence Service
``disease detectives,'' organized a large survey at the request of
the Indonesian government to relate eye problems to diet, recent
bouts of infectious disease and the amount of vitamin A in a
child's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing data from this survey, he stumbled onto the fact that
not only were children with vitamin A deficiency more likely to
have vision problems, they were more likely to die. He estimated
that adequate vitamin A prevented 16 percent of childhood deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Despite contrary recommendations from its scientific advisers,
AID then agreed to fund a second study to see if Sommer's first
observation was correct.
</P>
<P>
   The second study produced results that surprised even Sommer. It
found that deaths could be reduced by more than twice that what he
had suspected. This was the study for which he was criticized by
other scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``To call the reaction skepticism would be too mild,'' said Nils
Daulaire, a former AID worker who now heads the Global Health
Council, an association of nongovernmental organizations such as
Save the Children and CARE. ``He was subjected to broad
pooh-poohing. Very few people believed it could be possible to do
something as inexpensive with the dramatic results he was
claiming.''
</P>
<P>
   Daulaire said he was among the skeptics. At the time, he said,
he was working for a AID contractor in Nepal, so he designed his
own vitamin A trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treated several thousand children with vitamin A and
compared death rate with an untreated group,'' Daulaire said. ``In
a period of five months we observed 26 percent more deaths in the
untreated group and stopped the trial. The effect was so great we
felt we had to dose all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Little by little _ and sometimes reluctantly _ other Third World
countries have repeated the experiment and found the same results.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer said even children who do not have eye problems may have
``sub-clinical'' deficiencies that make them more vulnerable to
disease. He said raising the level of the vitamin in a child's
blood to normal is all that is needed, and there is no need to go
above normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know precisely how improving vitamin A status has
its effect, but most evidence points to a more effective immune
response,'' he added. ``While adequate vitamin A doesn't prevent
infection, it seems to cause the infections to be less severe and
life-threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Research has also shown that giving vitamin A when a child has
measles can make the disease less severe.
</P>
<P>
   And Sommer said he recently found an article published in the
British Medical Journal in 1932 in which a scientist reported that
the death rate from childhood measles dropped 50 percent when
patients were given cod liver oil. Scientists now know cod liver
oil is rich in vitamin A.
</P>
<P>
   Daulaire compared the effectiveness of vitamin A supplementation
to oral rehydration therapy, the system of giving small packets
containing water-soluble minerals lost during diarrhea. The therapy
has been credited with saving millions of lives, mostly among
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Al Sommer deserves the Nobel Prize for medicine for
what he did with vitamin A,'' Daulaire said, ``and a lot of other
people agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
