<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2858 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      01-28 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Jan. 29. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHINO-CORRUPTION (Chino Valley, Ariz.) - The town manager stole
nearly half a million dollars from a trust fund for the blind. The
Town Council concealed his past. A Parks and Recreation employee
who runs the town motocross track is a convicted killer. The town
conducted no background check. Needless to say, Chino Valley is in
an uproar. Especially since the former prisoner town manager was
very instrumental in the firing of the popular town police chief:
Arizona's first woman police chief and an instructor at the FBI
national academy. A recall election for the mayor and four council
members will be held in March. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DRINK-ARIZONA (Phoenix) - It turns out that you CAN drink and drive
in Arizona _ as long as you drink just before you jump in your car,
then drive real fast so you get home before the alcohol kicks in. A
loophole in the state's DUI law is allowing people to beat drunken
driving charges by claiming they drank heavily just before driving,
and that their blood alcohol level had yet to reach the legal limit
at the time they were stopped. The level only exceeded the limit
during the time it took for the officer to conduct an alcohol test,
they claim. The defense is so successful that the Legislature is
considering a bill to eliminate the loophole _ the only one of its
kind in the nation. By HAL MATTERN. Story will move in the `'A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANYON-UPGRADES (Undated) - The Grand Canyon Foundation announces a
major corporate donation to kick off a campaign to bring light
rail, a new museum, bike paths and other improvements to the Grand
Canyon. This is part of a burst of activity that could drastically
improve _ or in some cases threaten _ the land around the canyon.
By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KATIE LEE-BOOK (Phoenix) - Katie Lee was one of the few who knew
Glen Canyon before it was filled with the waters of Lake Powell.
``All My Rivers Are Gone: A Journey of Discovery Through Glen
Canyon'' chronicles her sojourns on the river and her own voyage of
self-discovery that evolved during her trips. Lee was introduced to
the life of a river runner in 1953 when she traveled the Colorado
on the second commercial power boat run through the Grand Canyon.
Rivers ran in her blood after that first trip. With PHOTOS. By
JULIE NEWBERG. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Here she comes, I thought to myself as I
stood in line at Walgreen's. She started off slowly, sliding in a
slight, almost unnoticeable slither up my spine. She began calling
me, louder and louder until it was impossible to ignore her. I felt
the touch of anxiety that she shot my way, and then it hit me like
a 50-foot wave. I could only think about one thing: I WANT A
CIGARETTE. NOW. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) Chevrolet Lumina is headed toward the end of
its road, destined to be replaced for 2000 as Chevy's
bread-and-butter family sedan by a more interesting craft bearing
an old name, Impala. The Lumina's styling is attractive, though
generic. Performance is competent, though bland. The overall theme
is mainstream to a fault, offending no one but not enticing anyone,
either. The big plus during its 10 years of existence has been its
affordability. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category.
Embargoed for Saturday, Jan. 30. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
