<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     01-28 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   February may be the shortest month, but it might be plenty long
for a few Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Side Man,'' at the John Golden Theater, have
been trying to cut costs for the remainder of the winter. Jay
Harris, one of the producers, said this week that the production
was working out a four-to-six-week royalty pool, wherein the
playwright, producer, director and major designers would receive
reduced royalty payments, or none at all, if the show begins to
lose money in any week.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the show's box-office gross was $166,829, or about
$15,000 above breaking even. But Harris said advance sales for
coming weeks were slow, despite a special $35 ticket offer. ``So
far we've run at a profit,'' he said. ``But suddenly we're facing
some tough weeks and facing some tough decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The production has also asked for and received a rent reduction
from the Shubert Organization, which owns the Golden. The show's
star, Christian Slater, has also agreed to stay through Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   None of that, however, is going to prevent another daunting
element of February: new competition. The month's openings include
``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' on Thursday, and three
straight plays: ``Death of a Salesman'' (Feb. 10), ``Night Must
Fall'' (Feb. 21) and ``Not About Nightingales'' (Feb. 25). And
don't even mention what a blizzard could do to sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade,'' at Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theater, also
saw its box-office numbers slide last week. Bernard Gersten, the
theater's executive producer, said he was evaluating the show's
status, week to week. ``We have not veered in any significant way''
from the show's budget, he said. ``We haven't had any calamitous
surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center Theater, of course, is a nonprofit institution
with a large subscriber base, guaranteeing an audience each week.
Still, the theater produced ``Parade'' with Livent, which is now
bankrupt, and is currently swallowing the running cost and any
losses by itself. Last week, for example, the show grossed only
$245,023, meaning a net loss for Lincoln Center of about $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade'' and ``Side Man'' are not alone; many Broadway shows
have endured sales slumps recently and have austerity measures in
place, from discount ticket deals to long-term royalty pools. And
both Harris and Gersten said their shows would be active contenders
for the Tony Awards. Tonys, of course, mean ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   But Tony time is June, and that is a lo-o-o-ong way off. In the
meantime Gersten said he hoped the figures would bloom around St.
Patrick's Day. ``We're working as hard as we can to keep the show
going until the weather improves,'' he said. ``And enjoy the
madness of spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Load Up The Vans
</P>
<P>
   As the hunt for available theaters intensified, one piece of the
puzzle shifted this week with news that ``Peter Pan,'' which had
been booked for a return engagement in April at the Neil Simon
Theater, would play instead at the Gershwin Theater, just vacated
by ``On the Town.'' (All tickets already bought for the Simon will
simply transfer to the Gershwin.) Both theaters are owned by the
Nederlander Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The move opens up the Neil Simon, a smaller, more intimate
space, which is good news for a number of shows currently sniffing
around for Broadway houses. They include two revues, ``The
Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm'' and ``Putting It Together,'' a
Steven Sondheim sampler.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fervor to install musicals, several producers said,
was fueled by the perception of a weak field of potential Tony
nominees, especially in the new-musical category.
</P>
<P>
   One contender for the Neil Simon, however, is a familiar face:
``The Scarlet Pimpernel.'' The show will likely have to vacate its
current home at the Minskoff Theater in the fall to make way for
the musical ``Saturday Night Fever.'' Instead of closing, however,
the producers are looking to transfer. And for good reason: The
show's advance sale, now at $3 million, continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Ta-ta, Mum
</P>
<P>
   One certainty for the spring is ``Ring Round the Moon,'' Jean
Anouilh's fantasy play about a pair of twins _ one good, one evil _
and a Cinderella-like ballerina. It opens on April 28 at the
Belasco Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The play's cast is set and includes Irene Worth as a rich aunt
and Francie Swift as the ballerina. The central role (or roles) of
the twins will be played by the British actor Toby Stephens, who
just returned to London after finishing a run in Racine's
``Phedre'' and ``Brittanicus'' at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
Rehearsals start in three weeks for what will be his Broadway
debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing's not bad because I just lost my flat and had to
move back in my mum's place,'' said Stephens, from London. (His
mother is Maggie Smith, the actress.) ``She'd begun to look at me
like, `How long you staying here?'''
</P>
<P>
   An Offer Refused
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like a near-perfect match of character and actor.
Last May, Alexander H. Cohen said that he would produce
``Othello,'' with Iago, that treacherous schemer, played by Al
Pacino, who has portrayed a few bad guys in his day.
</P>
<P>
   But after several delays the deal seems to be off. Cohen said
this week that he'd never been able to settle on so much as a
rehearsal schedule with Pacino. ``From my vantage point, it has
been a giant waste of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Buxbaum, a spokeswoman for Pacino, confirmed the project
had ``fallen by the wayside.'' But she left open the possibility
that it could be revived. ``Al's a big fan of the material,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Along The Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Victor Borge, only 90, is looking for a theater for a
three-to-five-week Broadway run in late April or early May, said
his manager, James Murtha. ``It's not a farewell performance,''
said Murtha. ``He's planning on performing to 106.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Playwright Edward Albee and actor Tim Robbins will give
readings at 7 p.m. on Thursday to benefit the Theater for the New
City, in the East Village. Tickets are $100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
