<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECT-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CORRECT ME IF I'M RIGHT!'': MOSTLY TERRIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kate Clinton thinks reaction to Ellen DeGeneres'
sitcom was pretty funny. Even some gay men and lesbians, she points
out, thought the show was ``too gay.'' Maybe, she suggests, ``it
should have been gay every other week.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clinton's imperfect but ultimately terrific one-woman show
at Westbeth, on the other hand, should be gay from beginning to
end. Luckily, much of it is. &UR;  &LR;  ``Correct Me If I'm Right!'' falters
in the beginning, though. Maybe it's time for Ms. Clinton, now an
established urban sophisticate and lesbian humorist, to retire the
jokes about her old days as a high school English teacher in
upstate New York. She's probably right that being a teacher was
great preparation for knowing ``how to work a room,'' but it's
doubtful that many in her audience come to hear about the student
who thought the plural of leaf was tree. The first act of Ms.
Clinton's show also relies on a lot of Manhattan-recognition humor;
she gets appreciative laughs at one point just by mentioning
Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   The first act does have its moments, though. Ms. Clinton is
often asked if Janet Reno is a lesbian, she says. Her answer: ``I
don't know, but her hair is.'' She observes how happy Hillary
Rodham Clinton always looks when she's photographed in another
country these days. She's noticed that there's ``too much skating
on television.'' And she's a little fed up with well-intentioned
but overzealous Manhattan parents who consider every moment a
teaching opportunity, even introductions to Mommy and Daddy's
friends (``This is Kate. What other words begin with K?'').
</P>
<P>
   But things really pick up after intermission, when Ms. Clinton
begins commenting on the state of being gay at the turn of the
millennium, when a ``freedom-to-marry kit'' is for sale. ``We used
to be a movement,'' she says. ``Now we're a market.'' She's a
little perplexed that people think there aren't already gay people
in the military (two words: Gomer Pyle). And although toward the
end she veers back into general political territory, about the
likes of Kenneth Starr and William Rehnquist (when they did drug
testing on him, it turned up traces of formaldehyde), who can argue
with the observation that Marilyn Quayle seems suspiciously like a
new Lily Tomlin character?
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to be gay to appreciate Ms. Clinton's gay
humor, especially observations like ``I'm worried about straight
people; I don't think things are going well for them'' (thank you
for noticing) and ``Gay people are getting more like straight
people, and vice versa'' (there is no question that this is a
compliment to heterosexuals). It's not that Ms. Clinton is off-base
when she's dealing with other subjects; it's just that sexual
identity is such a deeply felt issue and there are still too few
outlets in which to laugh about it, even in 1999. Fairway jokes we
can get from Nora Ephron movies.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CORRECT ME IF I'M RIGHT!'
</P>
<P>
   Written and performed by Kate Clinton; sets by Kristen Costa;
lighting by Josh Monroe; sound operator, Gregory Kostroff; stage
manager, Monroe; associate producer, Donna DuCarme. Presented by
Westbeth Theater Center, Arnold Engelman, producing director.
</P>
</TEXT>
