<SLUG> BC-FORD-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, FORD BETS ON THE CUTE LITTLE KA 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(See also FORD-VOLVO, FORD-EUROPE) (ATTN: Mich., Japan)   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The steering wheel is on the right-hand side and the
air-conditioning system was specially designed to stand up to
Japan's sticky summers, but the Ford Ka, the most visible plank of
Ford Motor Co.'s efforts to resuscitate its gasping business here,
may have a tough road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The car that Ford is counting on to burnish its image in Japan,
where its market share is one-half of 1 percent, went on sale
Thursday for delivery in late March. Eiji Iwakuni, a former Honda
executive, has been hired to turn Ford around here.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japanese, ``ka'' means mosquito, and the cars are only
available with manual transmissions, which are about as popular in
Japan as diesel engines are in the United States. Only 13 percent
of the Japanese-made cars sold here last year had manual
transmissions, according to the Japan Automobile Dealers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been better if there were an automatic
transmission,'' Iwakuni acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The Ka was originally developed for the European market, where
consumers tend to like small, cheap, functional cars. Thus, Ford
never developed an automatic transmission for the car, which was
introduced in the fall of 1996 and is built in Spain. Ford has sold
roughly 500,000 units to date.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker had toyed with the idea of developing an automatic
transmission for the model sold in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But, Iwakuni said, development costs and the prospect of a later
introduction here, where Ford is eager to improve its business,
persuaded the company to put a car up for sale that features an
obvious, built-in barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Ford acknowledges the hurdle, with company officials saying Ka's
lack of an automatic transmission forced them to scale back their
sales projections. The company now plans to sell 5,000 of the cars
here this year. Last year, the company sold 21,995 cars, 6,677 of
which were imports. The rest were assembled here by Mazda Motor
Corp., in which Ford holds a 33.4 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   James Treece, the Asia editor for Automotive News, said that
while Ford would have a harder time selling a manual transmission,
it was not overestimating its ability to sell the car. ``Five
thousand cars is not shooting for the moon,'' he said. ``And unlike
in the U.S., where you'd have a really difficult time selling a
manual because almost no one knows how to drive them, in Japan you
still have a majority of people who learn how to drive a manual.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiroo Tanabe, a spokesman for Ford Japan, said that adding an
automatic transmission would have raised the price of the Ka, now
at 1.5 million yen, or about $13,000, to 1.8 million yen, or more
than $15,000, which would have made it less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The Ka will compete here with the Opel Vita, the Volkswagen Golf
and Toyota's new small car model, the Vitz. The most popular
three-door Vitz sells for 928,000 yen, or about $8,070, a Toyota
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ka, with its bulbous figure, has a strong ``kawaii,'' or
cute, factor, which is important to the young consumers who may
help Ford overcome the unpopularity of the manual transmission.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Ford will bring four models to Japan this year _ the Ka,
the Lincoln LS and two cars that will be made for Ford by Mazda.
</P>
<P>
   It is also overhauling its dealer network, closing some small
storefront showrooms and paring down its outlets. It has hired a
pop music star, Tetsuya Komuro, a songwriter and music producer
behind several popular bands here, to promote the Ka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
