<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOKE-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVI     01-28 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOKE-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW WORLD LANDSCAPES': MAKING THE FAMILIAR SEEM STRANGE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Thailand, N.J., Pa.)   By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a visitor from another planet who has landed on
Earth, the color photographs of Jan Staller mirror an urban
landscape that is eerily, often spectacularly alien. Again and
again he shows that the trappings and detritus of 20th-century life
can be as mysterious as the glyphs of giant creatures and geometric
patterns left on the desert floor in southern Peru by an obscure
pre-Incan culture.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, his book of photographs last year, showing work
made over 15 years, is called ``On Planet Earth: Travels in an
Unfamiliar Land'' (Aperture). Staller's ability to turn the
terrestrial into the extraterrestrial, the ordinary into the
extraordinary, is on display at the Julie Saul Gallery in SoHo.
This exhibition of 14 large prints includes two images from the
book _ ``Workshop, Ruins of State Penitentiary, Philadelphia, Pa.''
and ``Tapioca Plants, Thailand'' _ that serve as a kind of bridge
to the mostly newer work. The show runs through Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Through the meticulous framing of his subject and in many
instances the use of harsh stadium lights, Staller can portray an
outdoor scene at dusk as if he has just landed in an unidentified
flying object, the space craft's lights casting a ghostly glow on
everything close by but leaving everything in the distance _ a city
skyline or low mountains and open sky _ looking normal. Even when
he photographs inside a building, he uses existing light (and long
exposures) as if it were lent by an alien spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Workshop, Ruins of State Penitentiary,'' for example, the
white glow from a barred skylight is strong enough to show an
interior that is grim but esthetically striking. Ranged along one
wall are three big blocks: one is full of cubbyholes, another
consists of wood planks bearing old nail marks and strips of wood
with nails in them, and the third, painted red, is a metal door
with odd cutouts in it. To complete the somber decor, wood planks
are laid across the floor, the mostly vertical lines paralleling
the bars in the skylight and offsetting the horizontal lines on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   In Staller's daytime pictures, like the delightfully surreal
``Tapioca Plants, Thailand,'' blue sky and brown earth are
frequently the dominant motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Here a big cluster of stalks sitting in splendid isolation on
parched land is crowned with luxuriant green leaves, wisps of
clouds in the blue sky almost forming a halo around the green
crown. Is this, a viewer might ask, the Thai version of the golden
sheaf of wheat?
</P>
<P>
   Although the indoor and outdoor images differ in feel and tone,
they are all part of Staller's vision of a world whose inhabitants
leave puzzling markings that are sometimes darkly, sculpturally
beautiful or dreamily enigmatic.
</P>
<P>
   That the dark and the light are all of a piece is marvelously
illustrated in the exhibition's first four photographs, hung on one
gallery wall.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Spray Booth, Brooklyn,'' Staller uses the site's existing
spotlights to transform a grungy industrial paint shop into a place
of exquisitely detailed Old Master beauty. The walls near two of
the spotlights have the texture of black-on-black oil paintings;
the spotlight on the ceiling trains a beam of amber light on the
brownish objects on a rusty brown shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Lending energy to the picture are strips of old wire hanging
from the shelf and rubber hose trailing on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond a low stand encrusted with black paint in the middle
of the image are four rows of brilliant turquoise squares (air
filters), with one or several in each row turned pitch black.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the turquoise-square theme are two pictures taken in
a restaurant overlooking the water in East Ocean, South Korea. The
image next to ``Spray Booth'' is a close-up of metal frames
overlooking the restaurant's expansive outdoor balcony with its red
overhead framework and its wall of glass in white metal frames.
What is near and what is far are initially baffling, since Staller
places his camera at a spot where the outside glass wall panels
seem to be part of the metal framing in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   The image's main point of interest is another visual trick. On
two center glass panels, which are of a darker shade of turquoise
blue than the sea and sky beyond, are broad jagged bands (actually
tape holding together the broken glass) that effectively break the
monotony of the metal framing and overhead grids.
</P>
<P>
   In the next picture of the restaurant's balcony, the camera
moves farther back. In the image's foreground are glass sliding
doors, their small red squares echoing the square blue glass panels
but overlapping tidily with one sliding door halfway open.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling even further away, to the great outdoors, Staller in
``DMZ, Korea'' shows coils of barbed wire on an otherwise empty
beach. Instead of looking vicious, the barbed wire with even
notches is arranged in a circular, gently sculptural formation, as
if it were a Christo-like attempt to impose an outlandish note on a
pristine setting. Staller adds his own touch by aligning the tops
of the barbed wire with the edge of the horizon, where the darker
blue of the sea meets the light blue of a peaceful sky. Not all
Staller's images are successful. His ``Rice Paddy, Korea'' is
indistinguishable from many other pictures of bucolic green fields,
despite slightly dissonant metal guard rails in the foreground. His
``Root Ball, Korea'' brings to mind certain of Toshio Shibata's
photographs in which he shows the Japanese tendency to wrap outdoor
objects with infinite care.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Root Ball'' is a striking image, it lacks that
distinctive Staller edge, since it doesn't go much further than
show a huge root ball _ crisscrossed with rope, thick wire and blue
bands _ perched on a ledge of reddish brown earth.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, two photographs he took on New Year's Day
this year are astonishing in their powerful and menacing bleakness.
Both are titled ``Elizabeth, N.J.'' In one the entire image is dark
brown mud _ the kind so thick it resembles sea waves and so
malleable someone tracking through it leaves clear, fresh shoe
prints behind. Inexplicably, near the trail of shoe marks is a
large green blotch resembling spilled paint.
</P>
<P>
   In the other, starker ``Elizabeth, N.J.,'' a desolate moonscape
greets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Taking center stage and lying on its side is a section of black
metal tubing with circular ridges. This foreboding land is
featureless all the way to the horizon, where a sliver of white sky
quickly gives way to lowering clouds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
