<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     01-28 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAURESMO MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ St. Tropez was a snoozy fishing village on the
French Riviera until a sultry young unknown called Brigitte Bardot
showed up to inject herself, the town, and a director named Roger
Vadim into the world's consciousness. Their 1956 movie: ``And God
Created Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Today St. Tropeziens, and everybody else in France, are
wondering hopefully if God has created a woman tennis champion in
the form of a similarly undiscovered kid with a St. Tropez address,
19-year-old Amelie Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the quick, supple Mauresmo was a nonentity. She, like
Bardot, had been on favorable view before, as the Wimbledon junior
champ of 1996. But in nervelessly knocking planetary No. 1 Lindsay
Davenport out of the Australian Open Thursday, 4-6, 7-5, 7-5,
coming from 28 lengths behind in the rankings _ and twice a service
break down in the decisive set _ to do it, Amelie has established
herself as the prime outsider in a tournament ravaged by such.
</P>
<P>
   No Riviera fisherwoman herself, Mauresmo nevertheless landed the
most formidable catch of the fortnight, hooking US Open champ
Davenport with a line-drive backhand well out of Long Lindsay's
very long reach on a second match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amelie just threw everything into that last shot,'' whewed
Lindsay. ``Where she surprised me, at the end of the match _ when I
was up a break at 2-1 and again, 4-2 _ she just stepped up and hit
great shots. And I didn't. She beat me in Berlin _ but that was
clay. I didn't think she could play that well on hard courts. Her
serve (nine aces, 12 winners) was tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Every tennis loyalist in France, from First Hacker Jacques
Chirac in the presidential palace on down, must have hummed the
``Marsellaise'' when that match-point replay was shown again and
again. Could it be that the country's first major champion since
Yannick Noah 16 years ago will be crowned at Melbourne Park
Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis may have something negative to say about that in
their callow title bout. Thirty-eight years have passed since the
most recent bracketing of teenagers here. Australia's last, 1962,
was homegrown 18-year-old Margaret Court, over 19-year-old Jan
Lehane, first female to flap a both-handed backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Champ the last two years, 18-year-old Hingis wrecked Monica
Seles's perfect record at the Open, 6-2, 6-4, in the other semi.
Seles, the victor in 1991-92-93 and 1996, was riding a 33-match
streak. Now Martina's is 20.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis already had said something else negative during her press
conference in German: ``Amelie's here with her girlfriend _ she's
half a man.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it will take more than catty sniping to beat the
cheerful, engaging Mauresmo, who has been straightforwardly casual
about that aspect of her life. ``I moved to St. Tropez from Paris
to be with my girlfriend, Silvie Bourdon,'' she has told French
journalists, and feels that traveling together has kept her happy
and ``relache'' (relaxed).
</P>
<P>
   It's evident that her tennis has been happy and relaxed, too,
punctuated by smiles and air-punching elation as she darted across
the court, playing to win. Presenting Davenport with a puzzle of
mixed spins and speeds, power when needed, no shyness about dashing
to the net, she was deceptively deadly with that rarity, a
single-handed backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's strong, big shoulders,'' said Davenport. ``I know she
goes to the gym a lot. Wearing that tank top, there was no question
about her strong physique.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times a week to the gym,'' smiled dark-eyed Mauresmo,
her streaked auburn hair pulled back. Gone is her mysterious court
presence behind huge shades. ``Now I have contact lenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Since, as she says, contact with Noah behind the glass of a TV
screen propelled Amelie to this height, maybe her story line goes
all the way back to Arthur Ashe in 1971. That year, on an African
tour, Ashe encountered Noah, a young Cameroonian, batting tennis
balls with a plank. Ashe liked what he saw, gave the kid a racket,
urged the French federation to give him a tennis education. Fair
enough, since Noah's mother is French. Voila _ 12 years later,
Yannick had the French title, becming the first citizen to seize a
major since Francoise Durr won in Paris in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched Yannick win on TV when I was 4 and made up my mind I
would be a player,'' Mauresmo said.
</P>
<P>
   Another flashback: to opening day of the Open. Out in the wilds,
Court 14. Few witnesses besides Bourdon and the coach, Christophe
Fournerie. Amelie is virtually out of action before the tournament
has even begun. Floridian Corina Morariu has her embalmed, 6-2,
5-2, with two match points and serving. ``Nothing to lose'' _
Mauresmo swats a forehand winner and is resuscitated on her way to
the penthouse, the stadium, where 14,942 watched her ambush
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that first round,'' she said, ``I am loose and think I
can beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that for Mauresmo-mentum?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
