<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      01-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN INTEREST? DON'T BELIEVE THE POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you were looking for a quiet place to take a midday
nap last week, chances are you were not at the Celtics' Merrimac
Street offices. Unless, of course, the sounds of constantly ringing
telephones put you to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   If you were looking for a safe place to enter a basketball arena
earlier this week, chances are you were not outside Gate 1 at
SkyDome. Unless, of course, thousands of people rushing turnstiles
and taking down doors is your idea of a safe entrance.
</P>
<P>
   And if you were looking for a local place where the polls would
come to life _ a place where large percentages of fans say they
don't care about the Celtics and the NBA _ chances are you don't
have time to read this; it is difficult to read and look for
indifference at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Polls by ESPN/Chilton and the New York Times/CBS Sportsline
indicated that the NBA would have major problems when it returned
from its 204-day lockout. The ESPN poll, taken in November, stated
that 63 percent of fans said they would not care if the season were
wiped out. In a November editorial, USA Today announced that the
``NBA has more than labor problems to worry about. It is suffering
from fan ennui.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason for anyone to doubt the polls. But a strong
case can be made that the pollsters interviewed some of the leading
indecisive minds in America. The NBA season opener is a week away,
and already, the polls are looking obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night the Celtics were in Worcester for an open
practice at the Centrum. The practice was free. It was also packed.
Friday night the Celtics and their very familiar neighbors, the
Raptors, play an exhibition game at the FleetCenter. The game is
free. It also will be packed. Long before the 18,624 tickets were
taken, the Celtics were receiving calls from curious fans looking
for a place to pick up their tickets. And long after the tickets
were gone, the phones in the team's offices continued to ring.
</P>
<P>
   A cynic could attribute all this to American indulgence. But
that would not explain the Tuesday night scene in Toronto, when
fans tore down two doors so they could quickly get to obstructed
view seats in a nonbasketball facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Kenny Anderson said Thursday. ``What is it? Paul
Pierce? Rick Pitino? What is it, man? We're putting people in the
seats. I don't know what it is. I just think people are interested
in basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds after saying that, Anderson noticed Pitino walking
a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe everyone is interested in seeing Rick Pitino on the
sideline wearin' one of those nice suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men got a laugh out of that. And at different times, both
would say that the free tickets certainly aren't hurting the
attendance figures. Still, the interest level appears to be deeper
than freebies and handouts. Anderson should know. His summer and
winter were full of public relations disasters. He was held up as
the symbol of what's wrong with NBA players. But the team's point
guard spent part of last Sunday at a ticket window talking with
fans and listening to their remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were cool,'' he said. ``It was nice. It wasn't real
difficult or nothing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson may not have said the right thing during the lockout
when he joked that he would have to sell one of his luxury cars to
generate income. But he seemed to capture the essence of fan
interest with his words Thursday. Very simply: Basketball fans are
basketball fans. It takes a lot to turn them off to the point where
you won't see them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the season starts, people love basketball,'' Dwayne
Schintzius said. ``The Super Bowl will be over and then you'll have
college ball and the pros. People can watch volleyball, soccer, and
stuff like that, but I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson may have been joking about fans wanting to see Pitino
in his Armani suits, but there is some truth to that statement.
People do want to see Pitino simply because they also want to see
Pitino's team. It does not appear that the lockout has changed
expectations. Celtic fans were excited about Pierce before the
lockout and they are even more so after his 14-point, 7-rebound
debut Tuesday. Clippers fans, however, are most likely at the same
level now as they were in June. That means chances are you will be
able to find an empty seat at the Los Angeles Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thing is: If you know who is going to win the race,
there's really not much excitement,'' Pitino said. ``But when you
don't know who is going to win the race, fanfare becomes bigger
than ever. Right now no one knows who is going to win the race and
everybody is smelling a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   An abbreviated 50-game season has given all hope. It has given
hope to young teams who begin strong and then fade because of
youth. It has given hope to older teams who begin strong and then
fade because of age. It has given hope to fans, who have 32 fewer
games to watch and can now see the importance of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was about to finish speaking when he thought of another
example of fan interest. ``Madison Square Garden,'' he said of his
hometown arena, ``was packed (Wednesday night).''
</P>
<P>
   And you know what happened there, right? Latrell Sprewell, a
Knicks guard, was on the floor. He is the same player who once
choked his coach, the same player who saw his name mentioned
unfavorably in headlines, the same player whom fans promised never
to root for again. Before Wednesday night was over, Garden fans
were on their feet, giving Sprewell a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just New York,'' Anderson said. ``People are excited
everywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
