A2882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-TEACHNG-BOS &LR;      01-28 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-TEACHNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO PUMP UP FUNDING FOR SCIENCE PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard University, as part of a long-term plan to fundamentally
alter the way it educates students and conducts research, announced
Thursday it will spend hundreds of millions of dollars during the
next five years for new science programs.
</P>
<P>
   The $150 million to $200 million investment, which officials
described as ``seed money'' that would draw far more in private and
government funds, is intended to keep Harvard at the cutting edge
of research and teaching in genetics, neuroscience, computer
technology, and other young or emerging fields.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the spending on science is part of a strategic
effort by president Neil Rudenstine and his dean for the faculty of
arts and sciences, Jeremy R. Knowles, to accomplish two goals: add
significant resources in relatively new areas of inquiry, and move
the university away from traditional educational formats. The idea
is to restructure the university so that more teaching cuts across
or even combines traditionally separate subjects, while research
increasingly is conducted in a similar inderdisciplinary manner
rather than by individuals who win grants for relatively narrow
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ensure that in your next century, and mine, that
the best things and the most exciting things are done here,''
Knowles said Thursday. ``The idea, simply, is to make Harvard a
place where one can do one's best work, surrounded by colleagues
and students and resources that make it irresistible.''
</P>
<P>
   The programs announced Thursday involve the creation of two new
facilities, to be started with $70 million in funding that already
has been allocated. They are the Center for Genomics and
Proteomics, for the study of genes and their proteins;and the
Center for Imaging and Mesoscale Materials, for examining and
developing minuscule machines composed of patterns of atoms.
</P>
<P>
   Planning has also begun for a third facility, to study
neuroscience. Officials said the $150 million to $200 million total
in the next five years could finance construction, equipment, and
staff for additional centers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton, Stanford, the California Institute of Technology, and
other universities already have allotted tens of millions of
dollars for the study of genetics, one of the hottest scientific
fields today. Harvard officials acknowledged they have some
catching up to do to remain academically competitive; the amount of
money they plan to spend, however, makes it appear that their
intent is to get ahead of the pack and not just join it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a combination of playing catch-up in some cases
and, in others, forging out on our own,'' said David Nelson,
chairman of Harvard's physics department. He noted, for instance,
that other schools are plunging deeply into gene research, but that
no other comparable facilites have been started for mesoscale or
neurosciece research.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is able to aggressively pursue its ambitions because its
$13 billion endowment is the largest of any educational institution
in the world, and its current $2.1 billion fund-raising drive is a
success. The university has been sharply criticized in the past for
not using enough of that largess to offset student costs and
institute educational improvements, but that began to change last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Harvard announced the most sweeping restructuring
of its undergraduate financial aid program in three decades _ with
a 20 percent increase in assistance, an additional $2,000 per
student annually, and an easing of work-study requirements. In
December, the school said it would tap its endowment for an extra
$95 million annually to help decrease class sizes, hire more
professors, and make other broad changes.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of science programs is another major way in which
the new infusion of capital will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles said that, since he and Rudenstine arrived at Harvard in
the early 1990s, they have planned to institute a series of reforms
``to secure and strengthen us for the coming century.''
</P>
<P>
   The first was to increase financial aid to lessen financial
pressures and improve students' academic prospects. The second was
to decrease nonseminar class sizes, which fell this year from a
maximum of 20 to 18, and increase the number of faculty; 12 were
added this year, for a total of 650, and Knowles said he will
continue the trend for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The final goal, he said, was to start dismantling the boundaries
among traditionally distinct areas of study.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, various subjects in the humanities were brought
together _ both by housing them in the same buildings for the first
time and by promoting cross-disciplinary teaching. Social sciences
received similar treatment a few years later, and now the physical
sciences are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for such changes, at colleges around the
country, is the belief that students learn to think more creatively
when teaching isn't segmented or linear. Last year, for instance,
an English professor and a psychology professor at Harvard offered
a class on memory and imagination, with reading material that
ranged from American literature to biology.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the impetus also is rooted in financial and operational
realism.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of the equipment needed to conduct scientific
research, especially in genetics and other emerging fields, is
extraordinarily expensive. The work itself is frequently so complex
that it requires biologists, chemists, computer specialists, and
sometimes experts in additional fields.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, research and development in the private sector doesn't
function the way it traditionally has in academic settings, where
individuals with specific ideas might apply for grants and then
guide their research from start to finish. In business, diverse
teams are assembled from the start to expedite the completion of a
project so it can get to market.
</P>
<P>
   So, as with so many aspects of higher education today, operating
in a cross-disciplinary manner is partly intended to prepare
students for the jobs they eventually will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``To maintain and strengthen Harvard's preeminence in higher
education . . . means you cannot do things the same way in the
future as you did in the past,'' said the university's provost,
Harvey Fineberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing how to change is no easy trick,'' he added, ``but
knowing you must change is essential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
