<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCOMPANY-CHINA29-COX     01-28 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCOMPANY-CHINA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern to purchase stake in China power plant operator
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co. is expected to purchase a 10 percent
stake in a Chinese provincial electric power plant operator when
the state-owned enterprise sells shares to private investors early
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Electric Power Asia, Southern's Hong Kong-based
electric power subsidiary, is seen as the ``strategic investor'' in
an initial public offering by Shandong International Power
Development Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   According to press reports from Hong Kong, Southern has agreed
to purchase 40 percent of the share offer, which is intended to
raise up to $285 million. The price will be set next week, and
dealing in shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange is to begin Feb.
9.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Shandong province would retain majority
control of the power company, but Southern/CEPA would hold 10
percent through an indirectly owned subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are closley watching the deal following recent
decisions by two other state-owned Chinese enterprises to cancel
their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is one of the largest growth markets for private power
projects and presents tremendous long-term potential for IPP
(independent power plant) investment,'' said Southern spokesman
David Mould.
</P>
<P>
   China's growth potential for electricity is clearly evident in
Shandong province, 300 miles north of Shanghai on the Yellow Sea
coast. There are about 17,000 megawatts of generating capacity for
a population of 87 million _ about the same generating capacity
Southern's Georgia Power Co. subsidiary operates for 7 million
Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   Shandong International Power Development owns 13 power plants in
the province with combined capacity of 3,600 megawatts but is
expected to build more to meet growing demand in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has asked the Securities and Exchange Commission for
authority to more than double _ to almost $8 billion _ its
investments in unregulated businesses outside its prime Southeast
service territory. But the company said most of the anticipated new
investments would be inside the United States. Southern last year
announced participation in plans to build and operate a
600-megawatt coal-fired plant in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's CEPA unit is also currently building a $1.4 billion
power plant in the Philippines and has taken a 28 percent stake in
a prospective power plant project in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dow Jones News Service contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
