</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLIN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLAYING THE DAYS OF BLACK VAUDEVILLE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Ga., Mo., Md., Ill. Washington) `ROLLIN' ON THE T.O.B.A.': (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Song, dance, comedy, eloquent prose and fine music
are mingled with nostalgia, bitterness and sadness in ``Rollin' on
the T.O.B.A.,'' the potent and instructive entertainment that
opened Thursday night at the 47th Street Theater here.
</P>
<P>
   This tribute to the last days of black vaudeville transports its
audience back to 1931 for a ride along the circuit that carried
black performers to black audiences in shabby, underequipped
theaters in places like Atlanta, St. Louis, Baltimore, Chicago and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Exploited by the T.O.B.A. _ the Theater Owners' Booking
Association _ some of the finest entertainers in America did as
many as 10 shows a day, had to pay their own travel expenses and
were subjected to Jim-Crow laws that barred them from white-only
hotels, restaurants and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The performers bore names like Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson,
Pigmeat Markham and Moms Mabley, and this production provides an
affectionate homage.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived and written by Ronald ``Smokey'' Stevens and Jaye
Stewart, and directed by Stevens and Leslie Dockery, this show
stars Stevens as half of the comedy act of Stevens and Stewart
(Rudy Roberson) as they travel the circuit and occasionally hook up
with one of its queens of song, the formidable Bertha Mae Little
(Sandra Reaves-Phillips).
</P>
<P>
   Basically a revue, with enough connective narrative to evoke the
loneliness and hardship of the road and of black life in segregated
America, ``Rollin' on the T.O.B.A.'' treats its audience to
routines accompanied sometimes by recorded music and often by the
gifted David Alan Bunn, the musical director, who brings not only
flying fingers but also nimble heel and flexed elbow to the music
bubbling out of his piano.
</P>
<P>
   The composers in question range from Duke Ellington and Charles
Gounod to Fats Waller and Eubie Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Given its age and its quantity, the material is sometimes
uneven. But the multitalented Stevens and Roberson and Ms.
Reaves-Phillips go at it with zest and panache and deliver a fair
share of treats.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens brings down the house with his account of an encounter
with a terrifying hulk. He and Roberson cleverly mime a game of
chess that involves slow-motion combat with guns, swords and
various body parts. They even put over an old joke about the young
Jesse James. Roberson brings the audience to laughter when he sings
``Huggin' and Chalkin','' about a man with a very large girlfriend.
Ms. Reaves-Phillips, often swathed in feathered boas and gowns
glittering with rhinestones and sequins and dripping with fringes,
growls and sashays her way through numbers like ``St. Louis
Blues,'' ``Take Me as I Am'' and the lusty ``One Hour Mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, there are caustic, proud, perceptive words from
the writings of Langston Hughes on blackness and the need for black
support for black artists.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, the audience has a chance to join the singing and,
at the evening's end, be grateful for many reasons that the days of
black vaudeville have rolled around once more.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ROLLIN' ON THE T.O.B.A.'
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald ``Smokey'' Stevens and Jaye Stewart, with additional
material by Irvin S. Bauer and excerpts from Langston Hughes;
directed by Stevens and Leslie Dockery; sets by Larry W. Brown;
lighting by Jon Kusner; costumes by Michele Reisch; choreography by
Ms. Dockery; musical direction by David Alan Bunn. Presented by
Frenchmen Productions, John Grimaldi and Ashton Springer. At 47th
Street Theater.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sandra Reaves-Phillips, Rudy Roberson and Ronald
``Smokey'' Stevens.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
