<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SEES INTERNET STOCKS AS FASCINATING LONG SHOT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He has made a habit of worrying in public that
stock prices are getting out of hand, but when Alan Greenspan, the
Federal Reserve Board chairman, was asked Thursday about the
highest-flying investments of all, Internet companies, his answer
was tinged as much with fascination and even enthusiasm as with
caution.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan hardly suggested that he had become a day trader, one
of a new breed of investors who go online to trade technology
stocks on rumor and whim. He left no doubt, though, that he sees
more good than bad in a phenomenon that has driven the market value
of America Online higher than that of General Motors and pushed the
share price of an upstart company like Ebay from $18 to over $300
in just four months.
</P>
<P>
   The upward march of Internet stocks continued again Thursday.
Reaction to better-than-expected earnings from America Online, the
dominant Internet access provider, and an announced acquisition by
Yahoo, the largest World Wide Web search engine, of Geocities, the
biggest provider of personal Web pages, pushed technology indexes
and many company shares to new highs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during a Senate Budget Committee hearing by Ron Wyden,
D-Ore., about the attention surrounding Internet stocks, Greenspan
cited not irrational exuberance but the very real prospect of
success for at least some companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you wouldn't get hype working if there weren't
something fundamentally sound under it,'' Greenspan said. ``The
issue really gets to the increasing evidence that a significant
part of the distribution of goods and services in this country is
going to move from conventional channels into some form of Internet
system _ whether it's retail goods or services or a variety of
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential market is so big, Greenspan said, that there are
``pie in the sky'' growth opportunities for many companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And undoubtedly some of these small companies, which have
stock prices going through the roof, will succeed and they very
well may justify even higher prices,'' Greenspan said. ``The vast
majority are almost sure to fail. That's the way the markets work
in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest he come across like an analyst promoting a hot sector,
Greenspan quickly added that he viewed the entire Internet-stock
phenomenon as another example of human willingness to bet on a long
shot.
</P>
<P>
   He compared buying Internet stocks to playing the lottery. For
centuries, he said, people have been willing to pay more for a
lottery ticket than their chances of winning would justify, because
they are captivated by the possibility, however remote, of a big
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that means is that when you are dealing with stocks _ the
possibilities of which are it's going to be valued at zero or some
huge number _ you get a premium in that stock price which is
exactly the same sort of price-evaluation process that goes on in
the lottery,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   There always has been a certain dissonance between Greenspan's
libertarian faith in the market and his fretfulness about the
ability of investors to gauge risk. There has been a disconnect of
late between Greenspan's concerns that Wall Street could be in for
a downturn and the policy of interest-rate cuts he pursued last
fall, probably the single biggest factor in the market's latest
rise.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday Greenspan sounded downright sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there's some hype,'' he said, but the securities
markets seemed to be doing a good job of funneling capital to
promising ideas even if they had not yet proved profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good for our system,'' Greenspan said. ``With all of
this hype and craziness, that is something that at the end of the
day probably is more plus than minus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
