<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY RIGHTS GROUP TO INVESTIGATE LACKLAND AFB GAY DISCHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Air Force agreed Thursday to allow a gay rights
organization to investigate the high rate of homosexual discharges
at Lackland Air Force Base in San Antonio, which accounted for more
than half of the Air Force's homosexual discharges last year.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came during the first-ever meeting between senior
Air Force officials and leaders of the Servicemembers Legal Defense
Network, which represents military personnel discharged from the
armed forces because they are gay or lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director for the group, said Air
Force representatives agreed to allow the gay rights organization
to visit Lackland and interview service members, including military
training instructors, recruits and military attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Air Force's 414 homosexual discharges last year _ a
record high number _ 271 were at Lackland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know what the command climate is like and whether
the level of anti-gay harassment there is pervasive,'' said Osburn.
``We want to understand the entire training process, and to
understand where in the process gays are being kicked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also agreed to provide the group with information
comparing Lackland's homosexual discharges with those at other Air
Force training centers, according to Osburn. In addition, the Air
Force will provide discharge data for the last 10 years to enable
Osburn's organization to compare discharges at Lackland before and
after President Clinton's ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue''
policy went into effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force spokeswoman T'jae Gibson, confirming the outlines of
the plan, said the gay rights organization's representatives while
at Lackland will be allowed ``to talk to personnel, talk with
people who work there and look at the training site.''
</P>
<P>
   Osburn said the gay rights organization's representatives will
visit Lackland in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Osburn said of the first-ever encounter between the group and
top Air Force officials: ``It was a very open and welcome
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Osburn and Michelle Benecke, also a co-executive director at the
group, met with three Air Force officials: James Wolffe, a special
assistant to F. Whitten Peters, the acting Air Force secretary;
Col. James Swanson, a staff judge advocate for Lackland, and Col.
Jack Rives, a military lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The gay rights organization has complained that the Air Force
and other military branches actively root out homosexuals, even
though a controversial policy implemented by the Clinton
administration allows them to serve under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, the Air Force officials ``explained the current
procedures for implementing federal law and Defense Department
policy on discharges for homosexual conduct,'' said Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   The officials maintained that Air Force commanders are not
violating the homosexual policy, as the gay rights group alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said a majority of the Air Force's homosexual discharges
last year _ 391 cases _ were because the service member voluntarily
came forward and revealed his or her homosexuality to a commander.
That is a violation of the ``don't tell'' policy and is basis for
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   She said an internal Air Force report conducted at Lackland
found that most of those at the facility who said they were
homosexual did so ``solely for the purpose of self-eliminating from
basic training and the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The number of homosexual discharges in 1998 _ 1,145 personnel in
all four branches of the military _ compares with a total of 997 in
1997 and was the highest level since 1987 when 1,380 men and women
were released, according to a report by Rudy de Leon,
undersecretary of defense for personnel and readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The Army also discharged record numbers of homosexuals in 1998,
according to Pentagon figures, with 310 personnel dismissed. The
Navy released 345 sailors in 1998, while the Marine Corps, the
smallest military branch, released 76 homosexual troops in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   The current Pentagon policy of ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' _ the result of a bruising battle among the White House,
the Joint Chiefs of Staff and Congress in 1993 _ means that
homosexual activity is banned in the military, but that gays and
lesbians may serve as long as they keep quiet about their sexual
orientation and aren't caught engaged in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that commanders may not inquire of a service
member's sexual orientation, according to the rules. However, they
may do so if they have ``credible information'' that a service
member engages in homosexual conduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
