<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASE-CLOSINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN SEEKS TO SHUTTER MORE MILITARY BASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen called Thursday for
two additional rounds of base closings to save $20 billion that he
said would be better spent on military pay raises, benefits and
weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should offend every one of us that serious needs for our
troops remain unmet while we squander money on facilities that we
no longer need,'' Cohen told the Illinois House of Representatives
in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is expected to meet stiff opposition in Congress,
where lawmakers, in the past two years, have rejected similar
proposals to close more bases.
</P>
<P>
   Under previous rounds of closings prompted by the end of the
Cold War, 97 installations were ordered shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people out there who believe we have done
enough closing,'' said Rep. Ciro D. Rodriguez, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes are not there,'' said Rodriguez, a member of the
House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen used his speech in Illinois to outline President Clinton's
military spending proposals for the next fiscal year, which begins
Oct. 1. The Pentagon's budget requests are expected to be released
Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is seeking a $112 billion increase in defense spending
over the next six years. The increase includes a 4.4-percent pay
raise for service personnel, improved benefits and purchases of
more state-of-the-art weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is speaking to audiences outside Washington to drum up
support for the administration's spending plan and for closing more
bases in 2001 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon analysts said reducing the number of bases would save
$20 billion, plus $3 billion annually after 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preserving our security tomorrow means we have to make some
prudent investments today,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers from states with large numbers of military
installations are opposed to the politically unpopular procedure of
shutting bases, a key source of federal spending and jobs for many
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The city of San Antonio is working with the Air Force and Army
to stop the potential closure of Brooks Air Force Base and Fort Sam
Houston. An aircraft repair base in San Antonio, Kelly Air Force
Base, is expected to close in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 97 installations ordered closed in the 1988, 1991, 1993
and 1995, 82 have been shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, a member of the Senate
Appropriations subcommittees on defense and military construction,
has called any future base closings ``premature.''
</P>
<P>
   But support for base closures has grown in the Senate. And
Clinton administration officials said this non-election year could
provide a climate to reduce the number of military outposts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has been an ardent supporter of
eliminating unneeded bases and is sponsoring _ with the support of
Republicans and Democrats _ a bill seeking new rounds of closings
in 2001 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   To gain the support of more lawmakers, McCain's bill would
prohibit the administration from privatizing workloads at
facilities scheduled for closing. In 1995, Clinton tried to
privatize military work at Kelly and McClellan Air Force Base in
Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers accused Clinton of meddling in the process
to secure support in the vote-rich states of Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, signalled his support for legislation to close more
bases, but warned that any bill must include language making the
process immune from political meddling.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, R-Va., said no support for base closures would be
forthcoming until the process is ``absolutely bulletproof to
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
