<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-28 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A WAY OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the tortured last-minute maneuvers of Senate
Republicans searching for an exit from President Clinton's
impeachment trial were efforts to drag him personally back on to
center stage, as if constantly befouling his name were not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Since the president successfully stared down his legislative
tormentors during his State of the Union address, he has kept his
distance from the heated Capitol Hill debate over his moral
failings and possible criminal behavior. After all, what is there
left to say? We already know more than we need to conclude that he
has done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it is clear that the Senate cannot muster a
two-thirds majority to impose the ultimate penalty of removing him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing more that Clinton can responsibly do in public
for his own defense beyond maintaining his policy of carrying on
with the nation's business. It is in the hands now of his lawyers
and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate GOP leaders wanted one last crack at him, sending 10
provocative questions seeking detailed answers in writing to the
White House and ``inviting'' him to grovel before the them in the
well of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise! Both times he politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   Did they really think he would fall for a transparent strategy
that could prolong his public humiliation and potentially trap him
into self-incrimination?
</P>
<P>
   This latest move was supposed to provide a patina of
``fairness'' to soften a continuing sense, heightened by the
calling of witnesses, that Congress has not given the president a
fair shake in the partisan rush for a sacrifice on the altar of the
GOP right wing.
</P>
<P>
   The senators tried to create the inference that they were
generously giving the president another chance to clarify details
that are now murky. If he would just titillate us with more
details, it would settle everything and we would feel more kindly
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the only reason they have insufficient evidence
to hang Clinton from the nearest tree is that he has stonewalled
them. If only he had offered minimal cooperation their
investigative efforts, so sincere and high-minded, the trial would
have been satisfactorily concluded by now.
</P>
<P>
   This argument did in fact meet with some public applause. A USA
Today/CNN Gallup Poll published Thursday indicates that while 43
percent of those surveyed approved of his decision not to answer
the questions, 52 percent disapproved. The pollsters do not tell us
whether those surveyed actually knew what the questions contained.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the numbers were reversed when it came to the
issue of continuing the trial rather than wrapping it up promptly.
The survey said 57 percent disapproved of the Senate vote not to
dismiss the trial and only 41 percent approved. Calling witnesses
didn't bother a majority, but the inevitable consequences in terms
of stretching out the trial did.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators could not press their ``invitation'' to the
president to appear before them because they have no constitutional
authority to compel such a breach of the separation of powers. Once
the White House said thanks but no thanks, that was that.
</P>
<P>
   When Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and nine other GOP
senators tried the 10-question tack, they must have thought the
presdent had a short memory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fabled skills as a political genius have not been up
to snuff throughout this scandal, but he still knows how to learn
from his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   He was burned badly by answering 81 questions submitted by the
House Judiciary Committee during its impeachment debate. Repeating
that miscalculation would be stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee's GOP majority didn't like his
answers to their prying quiz. Their questions often had the
patronizing tone of a school teacher grilling an inattentive
student, and the White House responded in the same vein.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP committee members were so incensed that they even
proposed the answers become the basis for a fourth article of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, was too much for many responsible GOP House
members to swallow. The committee made no attempt to prove the
president was lying in his answers rather than simply reverting to
evasive legalese.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed article, contending the president ``misused and
abused his office by making false and misleading statements to
Congress,'' was properly defeated with 81 Republican votes as well
as 204 Democratic ones.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 questions submitted by Lott and his allies were similarly
dopey and insulting. Clinton has little dignity left, but even he
should be allowed some limits. There's no point in answering
questions that can be harmful but cannot be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Clinton's major mistake throughout this sorry
saga was in not invoking his Fifth Amendment right to remain silent
during his grand jury performance. No testimony, no videotape
dumped by the GOP for world-wide viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The political lesson left by Richard Nixon, who resigned in 1974
to avoid impeachment, is: Burn any tapes or official records that
can reveal what you did in your own words. The political lesson for
Clinton is similar, though less draconian: Don't let your enemies
get you under oath unless you really, truly know you don't have
anything to hide.
</P>
<P>
   This does not make for noble politics. But where is it written
that politics is noble?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
