<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-28 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: QUITE A PAIR  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bibi and Bill, two politicians running for their lives. One the
prime minister of Israel. The other president of the United States.
So different, yet so much alike.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: Bibi tells the truth about his sex life (sort
of), but lies about his politics. Bill lies about his sex life, but
tells the truth about his politics (sort of). What does this tell
us about them and their respective countries? Actually a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Prime Minister Netanyahu. In January 1993, two
years into his third marriage, Bibi was faced with a whisper
campaign that he was cheating on his wife, Sara. In a pre-emptive
strike, Netanyahu went on Israeli TV and boldly disclosed the
affair himself. Israelis tittered about it for a week, his wife
throttled him, but Bibi's tele-confession ended the matter as a
political threat. Unlike Americans, Israelis have more immediate
dangers to worry about than where their prime minister slept last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Where Netanyahu has had a harder time telling the truth _
judging from the number of his former ministers who have called him
a liar _ is when it comes to his own policies. Here Bibi has a
certain structural problem. His core right-wing constituency hates
the Oslo peace process, but he can't get elected without attracting
part of the Israeli center, which favors Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of building an ideological synthesis to bridge the
center-right and center-left, which might capture the 75 percent of
Israel in the middle, Bibi has opted for a strategy of division.
His campaign is based on arousing, energizing and holding his core
right-wing base by dividing Israel between his supporters _ whom he
calls the true guardians of the national interest _ and ``the
leftists.'' Bibi uses the term ``leftist'' the way U.S.
conservatives use ``liberals'' _ as a way to smear anyone who does
not agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two ways,'' Netanyahu told his followers last
week, ``our way or the left.'' No sooner did his tough,
Kurdish-born defense minister, Yitzhak Mordechai, announce that he
would not run with Bibi anymore than Bibi denounced him as a
``closet leftist.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, Bibi probably knows that no one believes anything he
says about politics anymore. He's cheated on his core supporters,
without any explanation, too many times. So his strategy is to
insure that even if his supporters don't fully trust him they will
hate the other side even more.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, politics is about building a broad coalition of the
center that can protect him from the radical extremes. For
Netanyahu, politics is about building deep divisions through the
center so that the extremes will keep him in office, even if he
satisfies them one day and cheats on them the next.
</P>
<P>
   Many Bibi supporters will always overlook his lying about
policies. Many of them enjoy the idea of him lying to all these
pretty-boy, upper-class Israeli WASP politicians, and they love
even more that in a neighborhood with lots of lying Arab leaders,
Bibi can lie with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, lives in a different neighborhood, one where
sexcapades can get you in a lot of trouble. He's had to do a great
deal of lying to cover up these antics. In politics, though,
Clinton finds it easier to tell the truth, because he is telling a
majority of Americans what they want to hear. And what they want to
hear is that he has stolen all the best programs from the
Republicans _ welfare reform, balanced budgeting, missile defense,
100,000 more police on the streets, free trade _ given them a
humanizing patina and made them the core of a 21st-century
Democratic politics and a new American center.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton developed so much personal trust and even affection with
his core Democratic constituencies that he was able to build a
bridge between them and centrist Republicans, thereby consolidating
the American middle. He got NAFTA through because labor trusted
him, welfare reform through because blacks and Hispanics trusted
him, and the balanced budget through because many liberals trusted
him.
</P>
<P>
   America will survive Clinton's lies about sex because there is a
huge middle that still identifies with his politics. But Israel is
another matter. This is the first Israeli election that is
primarily going to be about Israel _ not Israeli-Arab relations.
Bibi has already made clear he is going to run a campaign of
demonization. If his opponents do the same, Israel might have a
hard time surviving the first election about Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
