<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE REPORTS SUCCESSFUL FOURTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gillette Co. announced Thursday its fourth-quarter
profit rose 4.1 percent, after a disappointing third quarter,
largely on sales of its Mach3 shaving products.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest maker of razors and blades said net income
rose to $435 million, or 39 cents per share, from $418 million, or
36 cents, for the same quarter last year _ a performance that
matched the average forecast of analysts surveyed by First Call
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mach3 is definitely a success,'' Robert Thornburg, an analyst
with D.A. Davidson &AMP; Co., told Bloomberg News. ``It's exceeding
everyone's expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred M. Zeien, Gillette chairman and chief executive, said six
months after the launch in the United States and three months after
the launch in Europe, the Mach3 razor ``is number one in every
country in which it has been introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Mach3 blade cartridges _ which eventually will drive sales in
the category once consumers have purchased the razor _ already
account for 14.6 percent of blades sold in the United States. Zeien
said Gillette's previous blade technology, Sensor, achieved that
market share 18 months after its introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current share of the total blade market in the US,
considering all of our products, is 70.7 percent,'' he said.
``That's the highest share the company has achieved since 1972.''
</P>
<P>
   The razor _ the handle portion of the shaving product _ is
already the top seller in all six European markets where it has
been introduced, after four months, he said. According to company
figures, the Mach3 razor has garnered an 83 percent market share in
Spain and 77 percent in England. In Italy, only three weeks after
its introduction, the market share is 88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company also produces Duracell batteries, Papermate pens,
Braun appliances, and other consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous quarter, Gillette's profit fell for the first
time in eight years, with company officials and analysts blaming
economic problems in Asia, Latin America, and Russia. One-third of
Gillette's revenues come from outside the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Mach3 technology cost $1 billion to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the company's experience with the introduction of
its Sensor line of razors and blades in the early 1990s, Zeien said
healthy sales of razors led to a boom in sales of the products
after about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward to the third quarter of 1999, Zeien said, ``A
tidal wave is about to hit the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect international sales growth to return to double
digits in the third quarter of '99, bringing growth rates up to the
traditional 15 percent to 20 percent that the company has
experienced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stock closed up 3 9/16 Thursday, at 57.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
