u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKB-SNOWDEN-BOS &LR;      01-28 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKB-SNOWDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOWDEN TO HEAD BANKBOSTON RETAIL BANKING UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp. has appointed Gail Snowden as head of
New England retail banking, replacing R. Nelson ``Oz'' Griebel, who
resigned to join a chemicals company.
</P>
<P>
   The changes shifted one of BankBoston's mergers and acquisitions
specialists, 37-year-old William Parent, to Connecticut to oversee
retail banking there, a duty Griebel, 48, had fulfilled. Parent was
one of three staffers reporting to mergers and acquisitions
director Peter Manning, and his reassignment was viewed as a sign
BankBoston was not in any major deal discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change would suggest to me that BankBoston pretty much has
its franchise in place,'' said Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony
Inc. ``There may be some isolated deals, but things have been quiet
for BankBoston, and some talented people in the organization are
going to use their skills elsewhere in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent's old position has not yet been filled.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, New England's second largest bank after Fleet
Financial Group Inc., has struggled to expand its niche in
Connecticut, where it competes against Fleet and two smaller banks,
Webster Financial Corp. and People's Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Parent said BankBoston was not in combination talks with the
latter two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Snowden, 53, among the most prominent black women in US banking,
was also appointed to BankBoston's executive management group,
which sets overall policy and strategy. Five executives covering
retail banking in Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, and New
Hampshire report to Snowden, who continues to oversee BankBoston's
community banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Griebel, a 22-year BankBoston veteran who was promoted to
oversee New England regional banking only five months ago, is now
president and chief operating officer of MacDermid Inc., a
chemicals company in Waterbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Snowden reports to Brad Warner, vice chairman in charge of
global consumer banking. BankBoston has yet to replace its former
New England consumer banking head, Thomas Hollister, who left in
September to head up Citizens Bank of Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
