<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARENA-NAME29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philips Electronics expected to nab naming rights for Atlanta
arena
 &HT;    By Henry Unger and Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting System is expected to announce
soon that Philips Electronics has purchased the naming and major
sponsorship rights to the new Downtown arena, according to people
familiar with the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, although similar deals in
other cities have recently topped out at more than $100 million
over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would give Philips, a Netherlands-based
conglomerate that has its North American consumer electronics
division based in suburban Atlanta, a broad promotional platform to
market its products.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the arena, Turner Broadcasting and its parent, Time
Warner, control many media outlets Philips could tap into.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hawks nor Thrashers officials would confirm any aspect
of the deal. ``When the naming rights is done and we're ready to
announce it, we'll let you know,'' said Hawks Executive Vice
President Lee Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Gordon, a spokesman for Philps Electronics, said, ``We are
not able to make a statement or an announcement at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Several companies said Turner Broadcasting's initial asking
price for the arena's naming rights totaled about $180 million over
20 years. But they also said the promotional benefits were
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Philips has about 300 employees near Perimeter Mall, where it
moved from Knoxville, Tenn., in 1997. The company's presence is
expected to grow in the metro area.
</P>
<P>
   Philips is active in about 100 businesses, including consumer
electronics, domestic appliances, security systems and
semiconductors. It reported $39.2 billion in sales in 1997, the
last year annual figures were available.
</P>
<P>
   The $213 million arena, now under construction on the site of
the demolished Omni, is scheduled to open this fall for the Hawks
basketball team and Thrashers hockey team's inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   This would not be the first time a foreign-based company bought
naming rights to a U.S. sports facility. The Swedish
telecommunications company LM Ericsson, for example, paid $25
million to have its moniker on Ericsson Stadium in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
