<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-LAYOFFS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed Martin to lay off 280
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ About 280 workers at Lockheed Martin Corp.'s
Marietta plant face layoffs this winter as the company copes with
slow sales and high costs in the C-130J cargo plane program.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs will trim the work force at Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems by 3 percent from the current level of 9,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must get overall costs down. There's no way around it,''
Bill Bullock, president of the division, and Chief Operating
Officer Terry Graham said in an employee newsletter article
disclosing the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs come from various areas and take effect by the end
of February. In addition, ``non-critical'' hiring will be frozen.
</P>
<P>
   More layoffs can't be ruled out, Graham said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens the rest of the year depends in large part on
what business we are able to generate and how efficient we are,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long term does look brighter,'' Graham added.
</P>
<P>
   The plant last week won a $450 million contract to update
cockpit systems on older C-5 airlifters, but it won't offset the
need for immediate job cuts, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs come amid contract negotiations between plant
management and the Machinists union Local 709, which represents
nearly half the Marietta workers. Their three-year contract expires
March 1.
</P>
<P>
   A union official declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin developed the C-130J as an updated version of
the venerable airlifter, older models of which are used around the
world. The program fell behind schedule and development costs
soared, inflating the price of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 90 orders so far, including 35 from the U.S. Air
Force, enough to keep workers busy into 2001. Six planes were
delivered to the Air Force just this week. But sales stalled in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``While many customers acknowledge their need for the C-130J,
they simply can't _ and won't _ buy the aircraft at its current
price'' of $50 million to $60 million, Bullock and Graham wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has indicated it needs 150 more of the planes
starting in 2004 but wants the price cut 10 percent. Complicating
the situation, Lockheed Martin is lobbying the Air Force to begin
those purchases by 2001 to avoid a break in production.
</P>
<P>
   The plant also faces pressure in the fledgling F-22 fighter
program, whose costs are capped by Congress. Final assembly will be
done in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the pressure on Marietta management, Bethesda,
Md.-based Lockheed Martin on Thursday said fourth-quarter profit
fell 15 percent to $308 million, not counting write-offs from a
subsidiary shutdown. Operating profit in its aeronautics group,
which includes the Marietta plant, fell 17 percent to $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin shares fell $1.25 to $35.93 3/4 in heavy trading
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
