A2942 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-BLUECROSS-BOS &LR;      01-28 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-BLUECROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCBS-NH ACCEPTS PURCHASE OFFER FROM ANTHEM UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Blue Cross-Blue Shield of New Hampshire has
agreed to accept a $120 million offer that will make the
57-year-old non-profit a wholly-owned subsidiary of Anthem Inc., a
$4.4 billion Indiana-based mutual insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover, should it win regulatory approval, would mark
Anthem's second acquisition of a New England Blue Cross plan and
would leave the region with four remaining non-profit Blue Cross
organizations. Anthem merged with Connecticut's Blue Cross Plan in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary method of operation and our primary approach to
growth will be as a Blue Cross Blue Shield licensee,'' Anthem
president L. Ben Lytle said Thursday at a press conference held at
New Hampshire Blue Cross headquarters in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem, which has made no secret of its intentions to become a
major player in the Northeast, recently divided its
Indianapolis-based company into midwestern and eastern divisions.
It opened its own managed care company, Anthem Health, in New York
last year and now insures some 4 million people. The cash
acquisition of New Hampshire Blue Cross will add another 350,000
people to that total.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal in New England is to hopefully merge or acquire other
Blue Cross Blue Shield operations, but if we are never successful
beyond New Hampshire we would be thrilled,'' Lytle said.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Blue Cross has had a roller-coaster financial
history, losing $20 million last year on revenues of $600 million.
By contrast, Anthem, which also operates Blue Cross plans in
Indiana, Kentucky, and Ohio, had earnings of $172 million last year
on revenues of $5.9 billion, according to unaudited figures
provided by the company.
</P>
<P>
   As a mutual company, Anthem may legally pay dividends to its
three million policy holders, though it has never done so, Lytle
said. ``Any money we collect in excess of claims and operating
costs goes into reserves. If reserves get to the point where we
feel we have excess reserves, we lower our premiums.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of New Hampshire Blue Cross was set at $120 million by
investment banking firm Wassterstein Perella, according to New
Hampshire Blue Cross chief executive David Jensen. Out of that, $30
million will go to repay loans by Blue Cross plans in South
Carolina, Chicago, and Michigan that helped New Hampshire Blue
Cross fund its 1997 purchase of the Matthew Thornton Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remaining money _ between $70 million and $80
million _ would be used to set up a health care foundation to
compensate the state of New Hampshire for the charitable value Blue
Cross accrued over its years as a non-profit.
</P>
<P>
   Though the regulatory review process is the same whether the
takeover applicant is a for-profit or non-profit, any decision will
have to await an independent analysis of Blue Cross' charitable
value, said Monica Ciolfi, New Hampshire's Assistant Insurance
Commissioner. Jensen said he expected approval could come within
six months.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by New Hampshire Blue Cross dashed the hopes of
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts, which also had a bid
on the table. That offer, sources said, called for Massachusetts
Blue Cross to pay off New Hampshire Blue Cross' $30 million in
loans and arrange details of a merger or affiliation later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This region may soon face the question of whether or not
not-for-profit health care is worth fighting to preserve,'' said
Susan Leahy, spokeswoman for Massachusetts Blue Cross. ``We've said
for those interested in preserving the not-for-profit heritage of
Blue Cross plans in New England, a regional solution accomplishes
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy declined to discuss whether Massachusetts Blue Cross was
engaged in talks with any other Blue Cross plan in the region.
Aided by the sale of its Summer Street headquarters, the plan had
an after-tax gain of $64 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance of Anthem bodes ill for Blue Cross of
Massachusetts, said Stephen Caulfield, chairman of the Chickering
Group, a Cambridge-based student health-care insurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when they appear to be turning things around and
looking, if not robust, at least viable, the opportunity to grow
their market share has been frustrated,'' Chickering said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Blue Cross plans have not been immune to the rapid
consolidation taking place in the health-care industry, shrinking
from 100 plans in 1989 to 54 today. ``To survive you have to become
bigger,'' Lytle said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Sager, a Boston University School of Public Health
professor, however, called news of the sale ``another sad day'' for
health care. Such acquisitions are part of a health industry arms
race that is leading to bigger hospitals, doctors groups, and HMOs,
Sager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Britain and Germany before World War II with
everyone building bigger battleships and bigger guns,'' said Sager.
``There is a great risk that patients will be trampled in all of
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
