<SLUG> BC-MA-UNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION MEMBERSHIP RISES 7.1 PERCENT IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the push to gain new union members, Massachusetts
labor leaders added 30,000 workers to their rolls last year,
increasing rank-and-file membership by 7.1 percent, the federal
Bureau of Labor Statistics said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's findings came two days after it reported a
nationwide net gain of 101,000 union members as well as a drop in
the overall proportion of union employees in the work force to 13.9
percent in 1998, down from 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But while the national news was bittersweet, Massachusetts labor
leaders had much to celebrate. According to federal statistics, not
only did they add union members but the proportion of people in the
state's work force who are unionized also increased in 1998, to
15.9 percent from 15.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indicates that Massachusetts was organizing union members
faster than the rate at which the work force was growing,'' said
Lane Windham, a spokesman for the AFL-CIO in Washington, D.C.
``This is definitely a sign of good organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several Massachusetts unions have increased recruiting
efforts over the last two years. Between the spring of 1997 and the
fall of 1998, for example, the New England Council of Carpenters
added 1,100 new members, increasing overall membership to 22,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Nurses Association in Canton, which serves as
both professional organization and union, has organized 1,735
nurses since 1997, according to Julie Pinkham, director of the
association's labor program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wild out there right now,'' said Pinkham. ``Nurses are
concerned about managed care. They are fed up. So, we are telling
them, `Organize! Get a voice, or you'll never have a say in the
workplace and you and your patients will ultimately suffer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkham said the association has added three new organizers to
keep up with calls from registered nurses at hospitals and health
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Local 285 of the Service Employees International
Union in Roxbury signed up 811 health workers during the first
seven months of 1998 alone, up from 707 for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts was the not the only state where unions received
good news. California's labor movement added 87,000 new union
members last year, posting an increase of 4.2 percent. And the
proportion of unionized employees in California's overall work
force increased to 16.1 percent, from 16 percent in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
