<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKAM-EARNINGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BankAmerica's shares up on earnings outlook
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of BankAmerica (ticker symbol BAC) rose $2.75
to $64.87 1/2 Thursday after Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
Hugh L. McColl Jr. told analysts in New York the company would
produce earnings gains of 25 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, BankAmerica's operating income was $6.49 billion, or
$3.64 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The news from the nation's largest banking company contrasted
sharply with that from First Union (FTU), the sixth-largest bank,
which said Tuesday its earnings will rise less than 10 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   First Union, also based in Charlotte, saw its stock slip again,
by 43 3/4 cents to $51.75. It fell $4.87 1/2 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica also said it will buy Fleetwood Credit from
Associates First Capital. The price was not disclosed. Fleetwood
Credit lends money to buyers of recreational vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading:
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer (PFE) jumped $5.62 1/2 to $127.56 1/4 after it joined a
growing list of companies announcing stock split news. Pfizer said
its board will vote on a 3-for-1 stock split at its annual meeting
on April 22. Shareholders would need to approve an increase in the
number of authorized Pfizer shares.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications provider GTE (GTE) added $1.75 to $67.93 3/4
after its fourth-quarter results proved stronger than analysts
anticipated. The company also said it was preparing to introduce a
series of new wireless service plans to compete with the rate
schedules of rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg (K) rose $2.87 1/2 to $42.06 1/4 ahead of fourth-quarter
earnings results, which the company is expected to release this
morning. At least one analyst, Patrick Schumann of Edward Jones,
however, attributed the rise more to interest in the entire food
sector.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dow Jones News Service contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
