A2959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIV-SUIT29-COX     01-28 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-SUIT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Gay group backs HIV-positive dental hygienist's
suit over lost job
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Atlanta dental hygienist who contends he was fired
solely because he is HIV-positive filed an employee discrimination
lawsuit Thursday in what gay rights groups say is the first case of
its kind in Georgia involving a health care provider.
</P>
<P>
   Lamba Legal Defense and Education Fund Inc. also said the case
is expected to test a U.S. Supreme Court decision issued last June
recognizing that the Americans with Disabilities Act protects
people with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Spencer Waddell, 35, said that shortly after he
told his employer, Valley Forge Dental Associates Inc., in
September 1997 that he was HIV-positive, the company immediately
placed him on leave of absence. Four days later, Valley Forge
offered Waddell a lower-paying position that did not allow him to
treat patients.
</P>
<P>
   When Waddell declined, the company deemed him to have
``resigned'' and then fired him, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating, on a personal level, to be betrayed by
people who should not discriminate against someone because of his
HIV status,'' said Waddell, a hygienist since 1992 who now works
with patients at the Grady Health System Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a simple answer to concerns about HIV in the health
care setting _ gloves, masks, sterilized instruments,'' said
Stephen Scarborough, a Lambda attorney who represents Waddell.
``Instead the dental clinic in our case chose to defer to stigma
and fired our client.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Valley Forge, headquartered in King of Prussia,
Pa., could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
