<HEADER>
A2966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-28 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES VIDEOTAPE DEPOSITIONS OF THE THREE WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday approved the videotaping of
testimony by former White House intern Monica Lewinsky after
rejecting a hurry-up vote on impeachment charges against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to videotape her deposition opens up the
possibility that the public could see Lewinsky's testimony on
television, if the Senate decides later to use the videotape in the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, voting along party lines, rejected a proposal by
Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., to end the 12-day
impeachment trial with an immediate up-or-down vote on the perjury
and obstruction of justice charges pending against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans also rejected Daschle's proposal to limit the
admission of testimony from sworn depositions from Lewinsky,
Clinton confidante Vernon Jordan or White House staffer Sidney
Blumenthal to printed transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP majority then adopted rules for the remainder of the
first presidential impeachment trial in 131 years _ with sworn
depositions beginning Monday, deliberations on various options next
Thursday and a target date for ending the trial on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   All three votes were along strict party lines, with 54
Republicans and 44 Democrats voting as blocs. Those votes, coupled
with a pair of equally partisan votes on Wednesday to admit three
witnesses to the trial and to reject dismissal of the case,
appeared to spell an end to bipartisan cooperation in the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The votes also underscored that Republican advocates of
convicting and removing Clinton from office do not currently have
the two-thirds majority of 67 votes they need to meet the
constitutional requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called the roadmap
for the trial ``a good plan'' that was ``fair'' to the White House
and House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the trial timetable aimed for a final vote by noon on
Friday, Feb. 12, but he cautioned that deadline could slip if new
information comes out during the rest of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really still trying to be fair to all sides,'' said
Lott. ``That's a real challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle sounded a conciliatory note even though he had failed to
win Senate action to speed the trial to a conclusion or to set a
Feb. 12 deadline for completion of the trial, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply couldn't bring this matter to a successful
bipartisan conclusion,'' Daschle lamented, adding that Republicans
and Democrats had worked ``diligently'' to find agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Blumenthal will give sworn testimony Monday; Lewinsky
on Tuesday; and Jordan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors won Senate permission to summon testimony from
the trio to clarify questions that have come up during the
impeachment trial about Clinton's alleged efforts to cover up his
sexual dalliance with Lewinsky by misleading special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr and lawyers for Paula Jones, who filed a civil suit
against Clinton alleging sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown on the Senate floor followed negotiations over a
24-hour period _ negotiations that failed to bridge the partisan
divide.
</P>
<P>
   Lott twice came to the floor of the Senate to update colleagues
on the fitful progress before recalling the Senate shortly after 5
p.m. to allow votes on the conflicting approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan calls for the depositions to be videotaped. It puts
off a decision on whether portions of the tapes will be played on
the Senate floor where they could become available to national
television networks. Democrats had been fighting to limit the use
of the videotape to senators and senior staff only.
</P>
<P>
   The White House vigorously opposes the videotaping of the
witnesses or the potential release of the material.
</P>
<P>
   The outline also allows lawmakers to vote later on whether to
call the three witnesses to the Senate floor and allows lawmakers
to vote on whether to call additional witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Democratic plan would have only allowed the
possible release of a written transcript of the three depositions
and restricted videotapes of the depositions to senators and senior
staff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said Republican senators want to
permit the possible showing of videotaped testimony to the Senate
because ``there's a fair amount of sentiment against bringing live
witnesses to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said Republican senators merely
wanted to reserve the right to decide later whether to show the
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no one who is going to be jumping up and down to use
a videotape on the Senate floor, unless there is a good reason to
do so,'' Thompson said. ``We're in agreement to have videotapes.
It's whether or not to agree on the front end what you will do with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats expressed opposition to permitting
videotaped testimony to be used in the trial. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., said ``you don't need to take the videotapes
onto the Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats remain at odds, as well, on what will
be permitted in the final stages of the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insist that the Senate has the option of condemning
Clinton's conduct with a ``finding of fact'' without removing him
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans advocates said the ``finding of fact'' within the
Senate impeachment trial itself would be a stronger form of
condemnation for Clinton's conduct and would assure that Clinton
could not claim vindication.
</P>
<P>
   The ``finding of fact'' would allay some Republicans' concerns
than an acquittal of Clinton would imply exoneration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, one of seven GOP senators looking
at a finding of fact resolution, said the measure ``would not use
legal terms like `perjury and obstruction of justice''' in order to
give Democratic senators ``a basis to acknowledge the president has
committed wrongdoing but not impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said senators could ``feel good'' about voting for the
measure, adding: ``It doesn't give the president a right to claim
acquittal or to claim vindication or to claim exoneration, which he
should not have under these circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said the ``finding of fact''
option should be viewed merely as an ``expression of sentiment'' in
the Senate and ``should not be a step toward criminal action''
against Clinton for perjury and obstruction of justice after he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats challenged the approach.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the proponents of
such an approach were trying to ``construct a procedure where they
can convict the president but not remove him. They want to have it
both ways. They can't. The Constitution doesn't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., challenged the effort to open the
door to a ``finding of fact'' approach because it could expose
Clinton to legal prosecution after he leaves office on Jan. 20,
2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
