<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DENVER-FEATURE29-     01-28 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-FEATURE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legacy of Elway remains the cause
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It is happening to John Elway again and there is nothing
he can do to stop it. The longer Super Bowl week lasts, the less he
becomes ``The Quarterback'' and the more he becomes ``The Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Denver Broncos were harangued to please allow
Elway to win a Super Bowl before he retires, which they gloriously
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weren't you here last year?'' safety Steve Atwater said. ``For
everybody, that was the million-dollar question.''
</P>
<P>
   But Denver's return engagement this year has not reduced that
price tag. With the consensus that Sunday will be Elway's final
game, the Broncos now are being pushed to send out their great
quarterback as a winner. As if this game isn't hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's got that in the back of their minds.
Everybody understands that,'' coach Mike Shanahan said. ``This
isn't a game where you need a lot of motivation. But everyone
respects the job he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The young guys on this team, it might be their only
opportunity (to reach the Super Bowl),'' wide receiver Ed McCaffrey
said. ``For the older guys, they may not ever get another chance.
This is what it all boils down to. No one will take this game for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   For a game that can go decades without a genuine emotional
angle, this Super Bowl has two of them: Elway at the end of the
line and Dan Reeves' refurbished heart. With Elway getting a title
last January, the Reeves campaign has an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get that feeling,'' tailback Terrell Davis said. ``But
people who feel that way, they're not playing the game. The game is
between the Falcons and the Broncos and the players who are on the
field. But that's fine. We recognize that. The shoe was on the
other foot last year. We had a chance to feel it, and we know what
to expect from a team that's been put in that role.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win rings for everybody who's here,'' Sharpe
said. ``Yeah, we'd love to have one for John, especially if this is
his last game. It's not something we're rattling around. We didn't
have T-shirts printed up, and we don't have things on the bulletin
board saying, `Win one for John.'''
</P>
<P>
   But a legion of fans are thinking exactly that. Elway, for one,
seems to be enjoying this trip more than his first four. Sunday, he
becomes the first quarterback to start five Super Bowls. By the end
of the evening, he hopes he won't have joined Jim Kelly as the only
quarterback to lose four of them. The game is hard enough without
playing ``The Cause,'' too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I gone and said, `This is going to be my last practice?'
No, I haven't,'' Elway said. ``After last year, though, it's a lot
easier to get excited and enjoy what's going on, having won a Super
Bowl. The atmosphere is so much more positive, not having to answer
the questions of never having won a Super Bowl or why the AFC can't
beat the NFC. Those are negative questions that I answered for 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
