<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY29-COLUMN-     01-28 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY29-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ABy Mark Bradleyc. 1999 Cox News ServiceMIAMI _Paul Tagliabue
gives his State of the NFL address today. Here's what Art Shell
wants to hear from the commissioner about minority hiring: ``That
there's progress being made, that we'll continue to work through
dialogue.'' But hearing won't necessarily mean believing.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has 31 franchises, three black head coaches. More than
two-thirds of the league's players are African-American. Nine
head-coaching jobs were open this postseason. Only one was filled
by a black man _ Green Bay hired Ray Rhodes, who'd just been fired
by Philadelphia. Art Shell, who coaches the Falcons offensive line
and who won 58.6 percent of his games as the Raiders' head coach
before being dismissed in 1994, still awaits a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Unprovens galore were chosen to do what they've never done,
which is run an NFL team. Shell has already proved he can run one
and win. ``I'd like to think (not being hired is) not because of my
color,'' he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shell has moved heaven and Earth to make the Falcons offensive
line a punishing unit. Why not entrust him with a whole team? ``I'm
trying to find out, too,'' Shell said. ``Ask the owners. Ask the
general managers. ... `Why wouldn't you consider a guy like Art
Shell? Why wouldn't you hire (Green Bay offensive coordinator)
Sherman Lewis, who has an impeccable record as an assistant?' We
don't have the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   As an expansion team, Cleveland was given license to interview
assistants on teams still playing. Shell met with team president
Carmen Policy and thought the interview went well. ``It was
legit,'' he said. The Browns hired Jacksonville offensive
coordinator Chris Palmer instead. Kansas City asked if Shell would
be interested in talking after the Super Bowl. He said yes. This
week the Chiefs promoted Gunther Cunningham, their defensive
coordinator. No other club expressed a willingness to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I aspire to be a head coach,'' Shell said. ``Every assistant
in this league does. Anybody who says otherwise is telling a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   That Shell isn't technically a coordinator is thought to have
hurt his resume. ``You can put any spin you want on it,'' he said.
``It's not so much X's and O's. All coaches know those. You have to
be able to deal with men. If players don't respond to you, you
might as well be talking to that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   How has the Falcons' O-line responded? Splendidly. Considered a
liability in preseason, Shell's men opened enough holes to make
Jamal Anderson the NFC's leading rusher. And who are these guys? A
rookie tackle, a second-year guard, a transplanted center, a career
journeyman and Bob Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   This line could claim a championship ring Sunday. Its coach has
three _ two as a player, one as a Raider assistant. In 1977 Shell
had the greatest Super Bowl any blocker has had, essentially
erasing Jim Marshall. The Minnesota man had no tackles and no
assists.
</P>
<P>
   That no black head coach has yet won a Super Bowl means nothing,
Shell said. ``The Super Bowl should not be a criterion to enhance
black hiring.'' He looked pointedly at his visitor. ``I coached a
team to the AFC championship game (in 1991), but I'm still an
assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
