<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now that he knows what he can do, Terrell Davis sets some lofty
goals
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As a visionary, Terrell Davis failed. Said so himself
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be a back to get 50, 60 yards a game,'' said
Davis, the feature back of the Denver Broncos. ``Maybe catch a pass
or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you know whom not to consult on betting advice. Davis
couldn't see that his speed, strength, determination and instincts
were qualities of a star NFL running back. No one is more surprised
than Davis that he amassed 2,008 rushing yards this season, that he
has a chance to win consecutive Super Bowl MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any award that I receive at this point, on this level, is
something that words can't ever explain,'' he said. ``Everything
that I'm achieving is pretty much something I never, ever would
have imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has, however, his vision has cleared, to the point
where he sees himself leaving the game someday as the most prolific
back in history. That's a quantum leap from anticipating a career
as an average contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple'' Davis said. ``I love to play the game.... After
you win the championship, you want more.... But I think my cast
makes me look better than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Davis' small but athletic and technically sound
offensive line and punishing blocking back Howard Griffith have
produced running lanes for the 5-foot-11, 211-pound former Georgia
runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Terrell is the one who hits the holes,'' Griffith said.
``We expect him to do what he does. But it's hard to not get
spoiled. To put up the numbers he has, he's raising the bar of
excellence. It's tough to stay there. But we'll keep trying to keep
him there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Davis wants to go is into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I leave this game, I want to leave my signature on it,''
he said. ``By doing that, I can come back each year and be the best
I can be. That's just the way I think right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The next order of business for Davis and the Broncos is the
Falcons in Sunday's Super Bowl. The Falcons were the second-best
team in the league against the run, a fact not lost on Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Atlanta, with (Jessie) Tuggle and (Cornelius) Bennett,''
he said, ``they seem to be very patient with what they do and they
just hold the back sides off the front side. It's kind of like they
just play gap control very well, and it's the type of team that I
hate to see. I like to see people a little bit more undisciplined
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he didn't seem too worried: ``I know what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
