</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-NOTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spies? Birds circling at Broncos' practice
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Broncos practiced in helmets and shorts for nearly
two hours Thursday, and coach Mike Shanahan agreed that his players
are getting eager for game day to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day. Nobody went down. Nobody got hurt,'' Shanahan
said. ``I'm sure the players are looking forward to playing the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through the practice, some birds circled the field
and swooped down near Shanahan. ``Was it a falcon?'' Shanahan said.
Man in demand
</P>
<P>
   Wide receivers coach Mike Heimerdinger figures to be a popular
guy after Sunday. Four teams _ Kansas City, Cleveland, Jacksonville
and Chicago _ are interested in him for offensive coordinator.
Heimerdinger, 46, was offered the coordinator's job in Dallas last
year by Cowboys coach Chan Gailey but elected to stay with the
Broncos. He likely would have been promoted to coordinator by
Shanahan had Gary Kubiak accepted the head coach job at the
University of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy returns
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff-return specialist Vaughn Hebron and punt returner
Darrien Gordon both have noted how difficult it is to get solid
runbacks against Atlanta kickers Morten Andersen and Dan
Stryzinski. The key, said Gordon, is patience. ``You're not going
to get a lot of chances against Stryzinski, because he forces so
many fair catches,'' Gordon said. ``He wants you to make a bad
decision out of frustration. You have to fair-catch four or five
balls in a row, and the normal reaction is to try to make something
happen even if it's not there. He can punt the ball 10 times, and
you're still not going to get more than one or two returns. So I'm
looking to make maybe one play that helps us win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Put me in, coach
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Willie Green of Athens has been bugging Kubiak all
week to get him more involved in the game plan, and the eight-year
veteran has good reason to be seeking a shot at the Atlanta
secondary. During Green's two seasons in Carolina, he played four
games against the Falcons and had 24 catches for 431 yards and two
touchdowns. ``I've been in his ear like a bee,'' Green said.
``You've got to look at the past history, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Days numbered
</P>
<P>
   After talking for days about retiring after Sunday's game, free
safety Steve Atwater now seems set to return for 1999. ``My body
feels good, and I'm pretty certain now that I'll be back,'' said
Atwater, who probably will be asked by Broncos' salary-cap
specialist Dave Blando to restructure a contract with a '99 cap
value of $2.6 million. Not so sure is the return of strong safety
Tyrone Braxton. The 12-year veteran conceded again on Thursday that
Sunday probably is his swan song with the Broncos. Braxton lost his
starting job this year to second-round draft pick Eric Brown and
then regained it late in the season after the rookie suffered a
groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   The son shines
</P>
<P>
   Third-string quarterback Brian Griese, the son of Hall of Fame
passer Bob Griese, was not even born when his father led the Miami
Dolphins to consecutive Super Bowl victories. The youngster doesn't
have any of his father's Super Bowl rings and hopes to get one of
his own. ``To be here as a rookie is an incredible experience,''
said Griese, who played in only one regular-season game this year.
If John Elway retires, Griese will battle Jeff Lewis for the backup
job behind Bubby Brister next season.
</P>
<P>
   Kickers of a sort
</P>
<P>
   Punter Tom Rouen and Olympic swimming gold medalist Amy Van
Dyken, a hot item for about six months, have been seen in several
Miami restaurants this week. One Denver columnist said, ``Wonder
who has the more powerful kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the day
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Terrell Davis had a league-best 15 rushes for 20 or
more yards during the '98 regular season. The Atlanta defense
surrendered an NFL-low three.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Elway listed his three favorite quarterbacks as Dan Marino,
Johnny Unitas and Roger Staubach.... Offensive line coach Alex
Gibbs thinks defensive end Chuck Smith is the key to the Falcons
front four. Because Davis prefers to run left, the Broncos must
stop the quick penetration of Smith.... Middle linebacker Glenn
Cadrez on stopping Jamal Anderson: ``Low is the only way to go. If
you're up high on him, he'll just rip right through you.''
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Tony Jones when asked if the Broncos'
seal-blocking schemes are revolutionary: ``The only thing I know is
we had a running back go for 2,008 yards, so if we're doing
something wrong, everyone will be doing it next year. I don't think
Terrell Davis getting all those yards is just luck, you know? I
guess we've got to be doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
