A2973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DIRTY-BIRD-COX     01-28 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DIRTY-BIRD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flocking to the Dirty Bird
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about getting swept up in Super Bowl hype.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Larry Peterson walked into a local mall to get some
film. He walked out as a Dirty Bird dance contest winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the people up there having fun, so went for it,'' said
Peterson, 31, of Cobb County. ``I just got up there and did
something. I didn't have anything to lose. The Dirty Bird just gets
you.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Kids do it. Adults do it. Even Dan Reeves has tried to do it.
There are several Dirty Bird songs out on the streets, and it seems
that a Dirty Bird dance contest is happening on every raised
platform or stage in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has galvanized the whole town, moreso than the Braves ever
did,'' said Gerard Ingraham of Marietta, who watched the contest
with his 10-month old daughter, Demi. ``Everybody is having fun.
Everyone can get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen King, her husband and two sons drove from Cartersville
to Cumberland Mall in Marietta to watch the contest. King was
trying to convince her husband to participate for a chance to win a
big-screen television and a recliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is fun. It gets the people excited about the team,
especially if they can't go to the Super Bowl'' said King. ``We
came down here today because we wanted to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatched in the minds of a couple of Atlanta Falcons players, the
Dirty Bird has become Atlanta's defining dance craze for the close
of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is pretty cool,'' said Falcon linebacker Jesse
Tuggle. ``I never thought it would be that big. But it just lets
you know how much fun we are having. We have been having fun and
winning all year. The Dirty Bird has been good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Bird innovator O.J. Santiago revels in the madness he
helped create.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has got to be up there with the great dances,'' said
Santiago, the Falcons' starting tight end. ``Everybody is trying to
do it and copy it. If other teams are doing it, it has gotta rank
up there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Santiago is quick to point out that he did not invent the
Dirty Bird. That distinction goes to running back Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before the (Nov. 8) New England game, we said we gotta
come up with something,'' said Santiago. Anderson devised the
framework of the dance, but Santiago, who scored a touchdown after
Anderson in the 41-10 blowout of the Patriots, was the first player
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has called Santiago the Jermaine to his Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be mad when you play football. You have to be in
the right frame of mind to make plays and make blocks,'' said
Santiago. ``So when you get into the end zone, it is time to
release and let loose _ to do the Dirty Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Dirty Birds'' actually came from Alan Weiss, a
12-year season-ticket holder. Weiss, who managed Nicky's Seafood,
which is near the Dome, had been hanging a Dirty Birds banner in
the lower southwest corner of the Georgia Dome for three seasons
before the name caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Like any great dance _ the Charleston, the Hustle, the Electric
Slide _ the Dirty Bird comes in many varieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you raise the roof, then bring your arms across
your body,'' said Santiago, who may be the only person who clucks
while doing the dance. ``From there you can do whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Dirty Bird so unique is that everybody does it
differently. At the Cumberland Mall contest, Peterson borrowed
heavily from the classic Funky Chicken. Co-winner Betty Daniel, on
the other hand, mixed several genres of dance to get the same
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they are doing now, I've done,'' said Daniel, a
47-year-old nurse's assistant from Atlanta. ``When I do the Dirty
Bird, I incorporate the Bird, the Dirty Bird and the Funky
Chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   John Welker, a professional dancer with the Atlanta Ballet, said
the Dirty Bird is one of the ugliest dances he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to say it is bad, but it is ugly. Usually, I wouldn't be
caught dead doing it, but everybody is doing it, so I have to,''
said Welker, 22. ``Aesthetically, it is not too pleasing. Maybe
they should add some Swan Lake to it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the clear exception of Swan Lake, the Dirty Bird does owe a
lot to its fowl-inspired predecessors. The Bird, popularized in
1985 by the funk legends The Time, involves spreading your arms and
flapping them while hopping from one foot to the other.
</P>
<P>
   With the older Funky Chicken, dancers tuck their hands beneath
their armpits and flap, while their legs flail in and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing the Funky Chicken. We used our legs a little bit
more, but it is similar,'' said the Falcons' Coordinator of Player
Programs Billy ``White Shoes'' Johnson, the Godfather of end-zone
dancing during his playing years. ``This adds to the excitement of
the ball game, from here on out. I look forward to people doing the
Dirty Bird. We have found something that the fans enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tore Bowman, promotions manager for Flava 2000, a local dance
club, said versions of the Dirty Bird have made it to the dance
floor there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, if the DJ says something about the Falcons, people
will start doing it,'' said Bowman. ``But it is not a strict Dirty
Bird. It is the Dirty Bird with a little Bankhead Bounce and Jiggy
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, who has seen dances come and go, gives the Dirty Bird
until March before it peters out. The key to the Dirty Bird's
staying power may be how well the Falcons do next year. Because
they go to the playoffs annually, the Braves have managed to make
an institution of the Tomahawk Chop. Conversely, the Ickey Shuffle
came and went as fast as its inventor, former Cincinnati Bengals
running back Ickey Woods. A lame leap frog routine tried by the New
Orleans Saints this year lasted until the next loss.
</P>
<P>
   While they're pleased with the response of the Dirty Bird, you
won't see every Falcon stepping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do that thing, man,'' said the Falcons' gregarious,
310-pound offensive tackle, Bob Whitfield. ``I'm not going to run
45 yards after Jamal to do it. Tell them to pan the camera around
to the line of scrimmage if they want to see me doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Star receiver Tony Martin, who has caught six touchdown passes,
said he has never done the Dirty Bird, but has no problem with
dancing. He even claims to have something up his sleeve for the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my own routine that I have been practicing and I will
unveil it when I score a touchdown in the Super Bowl,'' said
Martin. ``You heard it here first.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
