<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FEATURE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ephraim Salaam : A ready rookie
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _Ephraim Salaam has gotten used to the target that seems
to be tattooed on the middle of his chest, but it doesn't mean he
has adjusted completely to life in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, 22, is the Falcons' right tackle and the youngest player
on either team in Sunday's Super Bowl. With his start at that
position comes pressure that he says he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie, you always have a bull's-eye,'' said Salaam, a
6-foot-7, 290-pounder. ``I've been reading all year how teams are
going to move their best pass rusher over me, but you can't worry
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   All this fuss at the Super Bowl is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I catch myself just looking, and I can't believe
it. I really can't believe it,'' he said. ``There's millions and
millions of kids all over the world dreaming about playing in the
NFL, and I was one of those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But he almost wasn't one of those players.
</P>
<P>
   After building a reputation for indifference at San Diego State,
six rounds of the draft came and went before the Falcons selected
him in the seventh and final round, with the 199th overall pick. He
showed up in Suwanee looking out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a kid who was a basketball player, was quick, had good
feet, long arms ... needed strength,'' offensive line coach Art
Shell said. ``I said to him, `Do you know why you were drafted
where you were? Because there's a rap on you that you don't work
hard.' But I haven't seen any of that. He struggled early. As time
went on, he got better and better. Our last game, he had the
highest grade of any of our linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam has played much better late in the season, not allowing a
sack or pressure in the Falcons' two playoff victories.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would have made that prediction during the summer.
Atlanta signed free agent Corey Louchiey in the offseason with the
intention of plugging him in at right tackle, but he got hurt and
played inconsistently in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   He was released, and Salaam won the starting spot over fellow
rookie Jose Portilla.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam's NFL debut came on Sept. 6 at Carolina, when Kevin
Greene roasted him for two sacks and pressured Chris Chandler
several other times in the Falcons' 19-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of hard work, once thought unlikely for Salaam, has helped
him improve dramatically his habit of squaring his shoulders toward
the sideline. That makes it easier for defensive ends to get to his
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened up a lot, opened the gates, as they call it, and
shortened my corner,'' said Salaam, whose draft stock had been
weakened further when he didn't work out at the NFL combine because
he had a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art worked with me, (left tackle) Bob Whitfield worked with
me, and I have a much more physical approach now. Instead of
waiting for the defender to come to me, it's more of an attacking
style.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday against the Broncos, Salaam will play against Maa
Tanuvasa (6-2, 270) and Alfred Williams (6-6, 265), who combined
for 11 1/2 sacks in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   If recent results are any indication, he has the right mindset,
no matter whom he faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start your first game against ... Kevin Greene and give up
a couple of sacks and you don't get rattled the rest of the year?''
Whitfield said. ``That's a hell of an accomplishment. He bounces
back so quick. He's got the right attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam wants to improve on his power during the offseason, to
let his strength catch up to his height. But he's not thinking
about that now. ``There's a lot of guys who got drafted in rounds
one through six who haven't played a snap in the NFL,'' he said.
''I'd much rather be in the situation I am in right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Winklejohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
