<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ALLIES SAY THEY ARE WILLING TO TAKE MILITARY ACTION IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO allies warned on Thursday that they
were fully ready to take military action to stop further violence
by both sides in Serbia's ravaged Kosovo province, and Britain and
France said they were willing to send in ground forces if needed to
reinforce a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The allies acted after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told
them on Thursday that the threat of force was essential to enable
diplomacy to bring peace to Kosovo, where Serbian security forces
and armed rebels from the province's ethnic Albanian majority have
been battling with varying degrees of intensity for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Allied governments expect an international political ultimatum
to be issued on Friday in London by foreign ministers of the United
States, Russia, Germany, Italy, Great Britain and France, urging
both the Kosovo Albanians and President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia to begin negotiations swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration's top national
security officials will meet on Friday morning to decide whether
the United States will commit troops to Kosovo after a settlement.
With the public commitment of France and Britain on Thursday, the
administration is feeling strong pressure to agree to be part of a
NATO peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its European allies have all agreed that
the two warring parties must be forced to accept a political
solution.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Albanian rebels and Milosevic accept a solution
peacefully or after force is used, the Europeans are adamant that
American and European ground troops go together into Kosovo to
monitor the settlement. Administration officials say they
understand that the situation is moving quickly and hope a decision
can be reached on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   No country has said exactly how many troops might be needed to
enforce an eventual agreement in Kosovo, but both European and
American diplomats said that the allies were willing to contemplate
sending tens of thousands of troops into Kosovo as peacekeepers.
Allied and associated soldiers, including Russians, have been
keeping the peace in Bosnia since the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that the six countries meeting on Friday
in London, members of the ``contact group'' coordinating
international policy in the Balkans, would give both the leaders of
Yugoslavia and the ethnic Albanian rebels fighting for Kosovo's
independence a short deadline to negotiate ways to restore autonomy
to the southern province and stop the violence and a longer
deadline to reach a permanent political solution.
</P>
<P>
   The allies warned, ``The appropriate authorities in Belgrade and
representatives of the Kosovo Albanian leadership must agree to the
proposals to be issued by the Contact Group for completing an
interim political settlement within the time frame to be
established.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday evening, after President Jacques Chirac of France
and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain had met in London,
Chirac's office in Paris issued a statement saying that France and
Britain were ``ready to consider any military action, with their
partners and in the framework of the Atlantic Alliance, including
sending ground troops required to accompany a negotiated
settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, said in
Bonn that negotiations would be held in France within a week, but
French diplomats here said the talks could take place in Vienna or
in Italy. The parties would be given two weeks, Fischer said, to
agree on a transitional solution.
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats said that the allies would meet again this
weekend to back up that ultimatum with a credible threat to use
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are at a very important turning point,'' the
alliance's secretary-general, Javier Solana, said after reading out
a 10 point warning he said he had also sent personally to Milosevic
and to the ethnic Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova. In 1989, when he
was the Serbian president, Milosevic rescinded autonomy in Kosovo,
which is 90 percent populated by Albanians, although it is part of
Serbia and formed the heart of the Serbs' medieval empire.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's statement was part of a complex international
choreography insisted on by France and other European allies to
give diplomacy a chance to enlist the support of Russia in putting
pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In their warning, the allies demanded that Milosevic live up to
promises he made last fall to withdraw Serbian special police and
military units and heavy weapons used in attacks against Albanian
villages in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Those promises, which diplomats said had never been kept, were
made after NATO authorized wide bombing unless Yugoslavia agreed to
negotiate peace with the rebels. The Albania rebels, too, kept
fighting and thus talks never got off the ground _ despite a
framework negotiated by the American envoy, Richard C. Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre of 45 civilians in the village of Racak two weeks
ago, French diplomats said, made the allies realize they had to
make a fresh attempt to halt the violence or risk seeing more
massacres weaken their own credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, visiting NATO allies at their headquarters here on
Thursday, noted that the bloodshed in the former Yugoslavia carried
some lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bloody wars of the last decade have left us with no
illusions about the difficulty of halting internal conflicts _ by
reason or by force _ particularly against the wishes of the
government of a sovereign state,'' Annan said. ``Nor have they left
us with any illusions about the need to use force, when all other
means have failed. We may be reaching that limit, once again, in
the former Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance warned, ``NATO stands ready to act and rules out no
option to insure full respect by both sides of the demands of the
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana, NATO's secretary-general, said later, ``The next few
days will be decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   If the United States had had its way, according to some
diplomats, NATO could have issued an ultimatum of its own on
Thursday, authorizing the alliance's military commander, Gen.
Wesley K. Clark of the United States, or Solana to initiate
military action if the Serbs or the Albanians refused to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats said the French prevailed with the view that with
Russia opposed to the use of military force against fellow Orthodox
Serbs, it was better to wait until after Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and other foreign ministers had met on Friday
with Russia in London.
</P>
<P>
   None of the allies, diplomats said, were now insisting on
getting explicit authority for military action from the U.N.
Security Council, as France urged last year before the United
States and Britain bombed Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   French diplomats noted that the major question is how to
exercise military pressure on both the Serbian and the Albanian
side. While NATO has had plans for attacking Serbian military
targets in Kosovo and elsewhere in Serbia since last fall, it has
had more trouble coming up with ways to use force to get the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that NATO could impose naval blockades
around Albania, which the rebels use as a staging area, and deploy
forces along Albania's border with Kosovo to stop rebel
infiltration.
</P>
</TEXT>
