<HEADER>
A2978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN29-C     01-28 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Atlanta Broncos?
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It almost came about
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It comes to my attention that I have been withholding
information of intrigue from you. That the Denver Broncos almost
became the Atlanta Broncos, or whatever Leonard Reinsch would have
named them. Before that, however, the Broncos played a preseason
game in Atlanta _ or almost Atlanta _ in a ``stadium'' that
disappeared almost as fast as it was built. Like a traveling
roadshow, here today, gone tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   It was one puff of a pipe dream out of the mind of a man named
Bill McCain, one of several who had visions of bringing
major-league football to Atlanta. He was overoptimistic and
underfinanced. With plywood and bleachers borrowed through the
courtesy of Bud Adams and the Houston Oilers, McCain created
America Field _ I think that was the name _ on a chicken farm on
what is now Panola Road. With the help of Adams, McCain matched the
Oilers against Denver on an August night in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver media guide records that 11,500 came, on the one road
that led to the chicken farm, owned by a man named Roy Jones. There
were locker rooms, so to speak, but no running water. It was a
disaster. The bleachers went back to Houston, America Field
disappeared, and it all went up like, ``poof!'' As did Bill
McCain's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1965, with the new Atlanta Stadium rising on Capitol
Avenue and the Braves already pledged to the city, Mayor Ivan Allen
Jr. wanted a football team to be a sharing tenant. He went to his
friend Reinsch, president of Cox Broadcasting, and asked him to go
find one. Reinsch accepted the challenge and took aim on the
neophyte American Football League and its commissioner, Joe Foss,
who had been a fighter pilot ace in the Great War. Atlanta would
have been a plum to the AFL, and Foss apparently pointed Reinsch in
the direction of the Broncos, then gasping for life in Denver,
operating as Empire Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsch took a flight to Denver, had a meeting with the men who
ran Empire Sports, Cal Kunz and Gerald Phipps. Here it becomes a
bit muddled, but Reinsch came home with the assurance that he had
an AFL franchise _ if not Denver, then one that Foss would award
him under Cox Broadcasting ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsch reported to Mayor Allen, ``Here is the franchise you
asked for,'' then left for New Zealand, where his wife was
scheduled for delicate heart surgery that was only available there.
Wheels were turning in Denver, where Phipps and his brother Allan
bought control of the Broncos. Until then, the most season tickets
the Broncos had been able to sell was 8,000. The Phipps brothers
set off a drive that netted an amazing 22,905 season tickets, and
the Broncos were saved for Denver.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Reinsch returned from New Zealand, Pete Rozelle had
swung into action and cut in on the AFL. It was a war of leagues,
and commissioner Rozelle didn't want Atlanta to slip away. He met
with Mayor Allen and Arthur Mongomery, chairman of the Atlanta
Stadium Authority, and Gov. Carl Sanders made the scene. Suddenly,
Atlanta had an NFL franchise, but it needed an owner. There were
two major bidders, Lindsay Hopkins Jr., a sportsman of note with a
huge bankroll, and Rankin Smith, of the insurance firm of Life of
Georgia and a close friend of Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   With such connections and $8.5 million, Smith landed the
franchise, the AFL was left hat in hand, the Atlanta team became
the Falcons and 33 years later plays the Broncos, who almost came
to Atlanta, in the Super Bowl. (That the NFL revived America's
interest in Roman numerals might seem strange, since nobody ever
refers to World Series XCVII, or whatever, but the Super Bowl, in
this case, is XXXIII.)
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Reinsch, who has since passed away, was a bit miffed
with his friend, Mayor Allen, but it was between the two of them.
To speculate that the Broncos might have become the powerful force
they are today in Atlanta is just that, speculation. While the
civic-minded Phipps brothers saved the franchise for Denver, they
were getting nothing more than a dismal football team. The Broncos
had a stretch of futility longer than the Falcons'. They hadn't had
a winning season at the changing of hands, and wouldn't until 1973,
with John Ralston coaching.
</P>
<P>
   So, no matter how it all comes to pass Sunday at the stadium Joe
Robbie built, Atlanta can say it had a hand in it, preferably with
both hands on the trophy named for Vince Lombardi, who might have
become the coach of the Falcons. But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Bisher writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
