<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURANCE DISCOUNTS SLASHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' largest auto insurance companies have
slashed the discounts they offer good drivers to around 5 percent,
but a handful of tiny firms bucked the trend and offered rate cuts
two to three times higher.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent rate filings mean customers and companies are now
faced with some tough choices. Customers will have to choose
whether to stick with a large, well-known company or go with a
smaller, unknown firm and save $20 to $70 on a typical $800
premium.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which company they select, good drivers will pay more
this year than last because the discounts available from every
company are smaller. At Commerce Insurance, the state's largest
insurer with over a fifth of the market, drivers with clean records
will pay about $80 more this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now that companies have announced their discounts, the larger
companies have to decide whether to stick with their 5 percent
filings, and run the risk of losing customers to the smaller firms,
or amend their filings to match what the smaller companies are
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should switch carriers,'' said Josh Kratka, spokesman
for the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group. ``I say
reward the small companies and change the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Kratka said a mass exodus of customers to the smaller firms
could force the larger companies to raise their discounts. But
officials contacted at several of the larger firms said that was
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be wrong, but I don't think you'll see the market
respond to these smaller companies,'' said Ed Rinehimer, president
of Premier Insurance Co. in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Commerce Insurance, the state's largest carrier,
said he did not think the company would amend its filings as long
as the other major companies in the state were offering similar
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Even a spokesman for Horace Mann, the Springfield, Ill., insurer
that is offering a 14 percent discount to good drivers this year,
the highest of any company, seemed wary of a major influx of
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we'd like to say `come one, come all,' we're not
really able to handle an all-out blitz,'' said John Hoffmann.
Horace Mann, which caters primarily to teachers, insures fewer than
1 percent of Massachusetts drivers and has only 22 agents in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the only state in the nation where regulators
set all aspects of auto rates. Three years ago insurers, flush with
profits, started offering discounts off of the state-set premiums
to increase market share.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of discounts: those offered to good drivers
and those offered to members of specific groups. Consumers trying
to get the best rates generally seek out the best combination of
the two.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting was particularly aggressive in 1996 and 1997, but it
began to slow last year and this year has been scaled back
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce, for example, cut its discount for drivers in the best
Step 9 classification from 15 percent to 5 percent. It reduced its
discount for Step 10 drivers to 3 percent and held the discount
offered to members of the American Automobile Association steady at
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's filings with the Division of Insurance indicate most
other major insurers are bunched up around Commerce. Arbella,
Safety, Liberty Mutual, Metropolitan and Plymouth Rock all filed
good-driver discounts matching Commerce. Most other major insurers
were within a couple of points, including Premier (8 percent for
Step 9s), Hanover (7 percent), CNA and Commercial Union (6
percent), and Trust (4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In all, companies with 88 percent of the state's drivers as
customers are offering discounts to Step 9 drivers in the 5 percent
to 8 percent range. Nearly 57 percent of the state's drivers are in
the Step 9 classification. Another 14 percent are in the Step 10
category.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the larger companies have claimed they cannot afford
to offer larger discounts because state regulators have set base
rates unrealistically low. Rates have been cut the last four years
and were increased just 0.7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But six companies with a combined market share of less than 4
percent offered large discounts to good drivers. Horace Mann said
it would offer Step 9 drivers a 14 percent discount, give Step 10
drivers an 11 percent discount and award Step 11 drivers a 2
percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies offering double-digit discounts included Amica
(10 percent), newcomer Clarendon National (12 percent), Casco
Indemnity (12 percent), Masswest and Electric Insurance (10
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Step 9 drivers, who account for nearly two-thirds of the state's
drivers, have the most options. A Step 9 driver with a state-set
premium of $800 would pay $688 with Horace Mann's 14 percent
discount. The same driver would pay $752 with one of the major
insurers' 5 percent discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the major insurers, however, offer group discounts in
addition to the good-driver discounts. Commerce, for example, would
charge a Step 9 driver who belongs to AAA $714. That same Commerce
driver last year paid $640 with the company's higher 15 percent
Step 9 discount.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
