<SLUG> BC-CANCER-ADVANCES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMOTHERAPY BEFORE SURGERY AIDS BREAST CANCER PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giving breast cancer patients chemotherapy before surgery _ a
reversal of the usual order _ shrinks many large breast tumors
enough to qualify women for lumpectomy instead of more radical
surgery, researchers report.
</P>
<P>
   The chemo-first approach sometimes leads to a more dramatic
result: dissolving even microscopic traces of malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   One in eight women with large breast tumors or malignancy that
had spread to nearby lymph nodes had such ``complete remissions''
from presurgical chemotherapy. Nearly 90 percent of these lucky
women were alive and cancer-free five years after treatment, a rate
that parallels survival of women diagnosed at the earliest stages
of disease.
</P>
<P>
   The largest impact of putting chemotherapy first, the Texas
researchers said, would be to spare many more women from breast
amputation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. S. Eva Singletary of M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston
said the chemo-first approach can safely provide many thousands of
breast cancer patients an alternative to mastectomy now offered
only to women with the smallest malignancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually surgeons consider lumpectomy only for small breast
tumors,'' said Singletary, herself a surgeon. ``We're saying: Wait
a minute, you can give chemo, shrink that large tumor to a small
one, and do a lumpectomy safely.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of all women with newly diagnosed breast cancer
currently undergo mastectomy, in which the breast is removed along
with nearby lymph nodes in an attempt to excise malignant cells
that can lead to recurrence of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach, which so far is being done only in some
academic cancer centers, may apply to about 45 percent of newly
diagnosed breast cancer cases. That translates to about 81,000
American women annually, out of 179,000 new diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if US surgeons adopted the chemo-first approach,
the nation's mastectomy rate would plummet _ apparently without
raising the risk of breast cancer recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there appears to be no disadvantage with going with
preoperative chemo first,'' Singletary said in an interview.
``There's nothing wrong with doing surgery first, but going with
chemo first is safe, it's effective, and it may make the surgery
less radical. So you haven't lost anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence comes from an analysis of two separate studies of
breast cancer patients who got varying combinations of chemotherapy
drugs before and after surgery, with or without supplemental
radiation to the affected breast and regional lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   The 372 women in the two studies had ``locally advanced'' breast
cancer, classified as Stage II or Stage III. That means their tumor
was larger than 1 centimeter in diameter at diagnosis or that
cancer cells were found in nearby lymph nodes. In fact, the average
tumor among women in the studies measured six centimeters across, a
size that would rule out lumpectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients also had skin puckering from the underlying tumor
or positive lymph nodes above the collarbone, giving them a
less-favorable prognosis. But none in the Texas studies had
evidence of malignancy in the liver, bones, or brain.
</P>
<P>
   Giving these women chemotherapy first shrank the breast tumors
by more than half in 80 percent of the study subjects. Sixteen
percent had their breast tumors disappear entirely, and 12 percent
had no microscopic evidence of malignancy in either breast or lymph
node tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, women with such ``complete responses'' were more
likely to have more aggressive tumors. Because malignant cells in
such tumors are dividing faster, they give anticancer drugs more
opportunities to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers cannot yet claim an overall survival advantage from
the chemo-first approach, partly because they have not studied
enough cases. In ongoing studies, they are adding taxol to other
drugs to see if they can demonstrate a long-term survival advantage
among women who do not achieve a complete remission from
chemotherapy alone.
</P>
<P>
   The new analysis, published in the current issue of the Journal
of Clinical Oncology, may not convince many doctors to try
chemotherapy first because it is not based on random assignment of
women to this approach versus the traditional one, in which
patients receive anticancer drugs only after surgical removal of
the breast tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary said ongoing studies, and some on the drawing board,
will provide more data. For instance, the Houston researchers are
conducting a trial in which all chemotherapy is done ``up front,''
or before surgery. Prior studies have split drug treatments into
pre- and post-surgical components.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, studies have shown that chemotherapy
substantially improves survival in women who have breast lumps
measuring more than 1 centimeter at the time of diagnosis. Thus,
many women receive chemotherapy already, and the Texas researchers
say the issue now is one of timing.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston specialist advised women facing breast cancer
surgery and subsequent chemotherapy to ask her doctor whether he or
she would consider giving chemotherapy first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a woman is told, `You need a mastectomy because your tumor
is too large,' she should ask, `What about the option of using
chemo to downstage this tumor to see if I could be a candidate for
lumpectomy?' '' Singletary advised.
</P>
<P>
   In another cancer study in the British journal The Lancet, Dutch
doctors claimed partial success in using a vaccine against colon
cancer made from patients' own cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental vaccine reportedly reduced the risk of
recurrence among colon cancer patients with Stage II disease, which
means malignancy that has penetrated the bowel wall but has not
spread to area lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Robert Mayer of Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, a
colon cancer authority, called the results ``pretty inconclusive''
because of the study's small number of subjects and what he called
``marginal benefits'' in only a subgroup of patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
