<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Family Guy': A wonderfully bent little show
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's hoping that none of us in Atlanta will be
paying a bit of attention when ``The Family Guy'' debuts after the
Super Bowl Sunday on Fox, at around 10 p.m. We'll all be too busy
mobbing the streets, blowing our horns, behaving like
elbow-wiggling glorious fools, celebrating our victory.
</P>
<P>
   But those still sprawled and glazed in the front of the tube
will see Fox give its most visible platform to yet another animated
series, the third new one in three weeks, following ``The PJs'' and
``Dilbert.'' ``The Family Guy'' is better than either of them, a
wonderfully bent little show that blends some of the nasty
sensibility of ``South Park'' with some of the basics of ``The
Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   The work of 25-year-old newcomer Seth McFarlane, the guy in
``Family Guy'' is Peter Griffin, whom you'll recognize instantly as
a Homer Simpson knock-off (beer-guzzling incompetent loser). Mom
Lois stands in for Marge, but in this household there are two teens
(Meg and Chris).
</P>
<P>
   And then there's baby Stewie, the one you'll remember. Stewie
plots to kill his family from his highchair, and sounds like a bad
James Bond villian in his cultured British accent. ``Damn you, vile
woman!'' he curses his mother. ``You've impeded my work since the
day I escaped from your wretched womb!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy'' is one of those shows that throws everything out there
and hopes that some of it works. And some of it does, even as a lot
of it doesn't. There are scads of throwaway jokes, like the ``G.I.
Jew'' doll, a porno spoof of ``Casablanca,'' old sitcom send-ups,
and even Michaelangelo's David, which has a crucial bit broken off.
</P>
<P>
   The big risk for Fox is that it still hasn't decided on a slot
for ``Family Guy.'' The post-game premiere is a one-shot, and the
show will then not come on until sometime in March, at a time to be
announced. In today's programming logjam, some viewers may have
forgotten about it by the time it comes back.
</P>
<P>
   As a programming strategy, a cross between ``South Park'' (with
more staying power, perhaps) and ``The Simpsons'' (they should be
so lucky in the long run) is just what Fox needs. Whether this is
what television really needs will depend on your taste for bodily
appendage jokes, but these days, this is the level you get.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
