</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS WARN AGAINST IGNORING CLIMATE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Geophysical Union, the United States' most broadly
based professional organization in earth and space science, said in
an official policy statement Thursday that there was a ``compelling
basis for legitimate public concern'' about human-induced climatic
change.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific uncertainty about the problem, the statement said,
``does not justify inaction'' in coping with it.
</P>
<P>
   The statement dealt with the burning of fossil fuels like coal,
oil and natural gas. The burning produces carbon dioxide, a gas
that traps heat in Earth's atmosphere as in a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The geophysical union said ``there is no known geologic
precedent'' for the conversion of carbon from Earth's crust into
atmospheric carbon dioxide, in the amounts being burned as fossil
fuels, without changing the climate.
</P>
<P>
   The statement is the eighth the union has issued on some aspect
of science-related public policy, and the latest in a long list of
statements on global warming over the last two decades by
prestigious scientific groups that have reached similar
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer always comes back: `Global warming is a serious
problem, and policy-makers have got to figure out what to do about
it,''' said Dr. Michael Oppenheimer, a senior scientist at the
Environmental Defense Fund, an environmental research and advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   But the Competitive Enterprise Institute, a public policy group
that promotes free enterprise and limited government, said the
geophysical union, by making a judgment favorable to the Clinton
administration's policy of action on global warming, had ``crossed
the line separating science from advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The average surface temperature of Earth has risen by about 1
degree Fahrenheit over the last century, compared with a difference
of 5 to 9 degrees between now and the depths of the last ice age,
some 20,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An international panel of scientists convened by the United
Nations has projected that if emissions of the heat-trapping gases
are not reduced, the surface temperature will rise by another 2 to
6 degrees by the end of the 21st century, producing widespread
climatic disruptions. The world's industrialized countries in late
1997 bound themselves to reduce their emissions of these gases by
about 5 percent over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of mandatory action to reduce such emissions have
cited the uncertainties surrounding predictions about climate
change, and Thursday's statement dealt prominently with those
uncertainties. It noted, for instance, that while the observed
global temperature rise ``appears to be unusual in the context of
the last few centuries,'' it is ``not clearly outside the range of
climate variability of the last few thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it said, the complexity of the climate system ensures
that uncertainty ``will never be completely eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it said, present understanding of the system ``provides a
compelling basis for legitimate public concern over future global-
and regional-scale changes resulting from increased concentrations
of greenhouse gases.''
</P>
<P>
   While the statement recommended the development of strategies
for dealing with global warming, it did not propose any specific
solutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY29-CO     01-28 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia `Bubba' is winning votes for S.C. lottery
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ As the South Carolina Senate prepares for its
final vote next week on a statewide lottery that would compete with
Georgia's, Republicans opposed to the legislation already appear
defeated by a Georgia hayseed named ``Bubba.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters met Bubba last fall when the bearded character in a
Georgia Bulldog cap and T-shirt appeared in state Democratic Party
television ads ridiculing Gov. David Beasley, a Republican who had
denounced lotteries as immoral gambling, even if proceeds would
benefit public education.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley lost to Democrat Jim Hodges, whose main campaign pledge
was to use millions of dollars in lottery proceeds to improve South
Carolina's bottom-scraping public schools. Recent Democratic
polling indicated nearly seven out of every 10 voters favored a
lottery referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bubba is a folk hero,'' said Sen. Ernie Passailaigue, the
Charleston Democrat who sponsored legislation that would allow
South Carolinians to vote on erasing the state's 104-year-old
constitutional ban on lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Passailaigue contends the Republican-controlled House will be
risking a voter backlash in the Nov. 2, 2000, general election if
it derails the lottery vote when the legislation moves there. ``If
they sit around and hem and haw with it, and bog this down, they
are going to be turned out in droves,'' he said. ``Bubba is going
to be back in 2000 big time.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker David Wilkins, a Greenville Republican who opposes
the lottery, conceded Thursday that ``it is a foregone conclusion''
that legislators will schedule a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The Bubba character, played by actor Kerry Maher of Rock Hill,
S.C., was used by Hodges' supporters to point out that South
Carolinians were crossing into Georgia and spending millions a year
in that state's lottery. South Carolina Democrats estimate that
amount at $80 million or more a year, although Georgia lottery
officials don't keep exact tabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Georgia, we just luuuvvv David Beasley,'' Bubba
hee-hawed in the commercial, which Democrats insist galvanized
strong but unspoken sentiment among South Carolinians who hated the
idea of their money paying for HOPE scholarships for Georgia
college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in South Carolina has a relative in Georgia who is
going to school for free,'' Passailaigue said Thursday, shortly
before the state Senate resumed debate on the lottery and scheduled
a third and final vote for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate voted 37-8 in favor of a bill that
would schedule a lottery referendum for the Nov. 2, 2000, general
election. The legislation, which requires three votes, also would
set up a referendum on whether the state should ban the $2.3
billion-a-year video poker industry. Republican senators later
expressed regret about scheduling both votes on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's top priority is establishing a lottery as early
as 2001 in hopes that it would generate $90 million for public
education and $150 million in subsequent years. He favors holding
both referendums at the same time. ``I think the people ought to
decide thumbs up or thumbs down whether or not we have the lottery
or ... video poker in the year 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
