<HEADLINE>
FAA ORDERS WIRING INSPECTION ON MD-11 JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Federal Aviation Administration Thursday ordered
inspections of wiring and insulation in the cockpit and cabin of
all of The Boeing Co.'s MD-11 jets in the U.S. fleet.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest FAA-ordered inspection of the widebody planes
following the crash last year of a Swissair MD-11 near Halifax,
Nova Scotia. The jet plunged into coastal waters 16 minutes after
the crew reported smoke in the cockpit. All 229 people aboard the
plane were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The new order affects 65 U.S.-registered MD-11s, which were
built by McDonnell Douglas. The company was acquired by Boeing in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing issued a service bulletin earlier this week suggesting
airlines inspect wiring and insulation on their MD-11s, said Boeing
spokesman Russ Young. The FAA directive makes those inspections
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. operators, which include Delta and American airlines, have
60 days to perform the inspections, make repairs and report their
findings to the FAA. The inspections will cost about $720 per
aircraft, or $46,800 total for the U.S. fleet, according to the
FAA.
</P>
<P>
   There are 174 of the jets operated worldwide. While the FAA's
orders do not apply to foreign-registered planes, their operators
frequently follow U.S. safety suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign carriers operating MD-11 aircraft include Swissair,
Varig, Japan Airlines, KLM-Royal Dutch Airlines and EVA Airways
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the cause of the Swissair accident is still unknown,
the FAA will continue to use information from the (Canadian
Transportation Safety Board's) investigation to push forward with
preventive measures that improve safety for the flying public,''
FAA Administrator Jane F. Garvey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   She indicated there may be additional MD-11 inspections as the
investigation into the Swissair crash unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an interim action until we can determine the full
extent of any potential wiring problems on the MD-11,'' Garvey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is assisting Canadian
investigators in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, the NTSB recommended that airlines inspect wiring and
insulation in the cabin and cockpit of all all MD-11s. The FAA said
it was planning to order such inspections before the NTSB's
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the FAA ordered airlines to inspect two lighting
dimmer switches in the cockpits of MD-11 aircraft because they may
overheat and smoke, distracting the pilots. McDonnell Douglas had
issued a service bulletin suggesting the changes in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA found that when brighter cockpit lighting was needed,
and thus a higher voltage required, the part sometimes overheated
and emitted a burning odor and smoke. It was ruled out as cause of
the accident, however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
