A3002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAN-PSYCHOLOGY-COX     01-28 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAN-PSYCHOLOGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game helps meet our primal needs
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mix together a little sex, tribalism and religion, and you have
the makings of a great sports fan.
</P>
<P>
   Fans act the way they do because sports _ especially the Super
Bowl _ tap into a host of ancient human rites and beliefs,
psychologists say. The result is a temporary swell of emotional
solidarity. Families and communities suddenly find common bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl has become the national Bacchanalia,'' said
Dennis Perrin, author of the book, ``American Fan,'' scheduled for
release this year. ``It's a national holiday that allows everyone
to jump on the bandwagon and get carried away.''
</P>
<P>
   For most fans, the biggest hook in sports is that they get to
vicariously square off against an outside enemy, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbolic war after all, and wartime is notorious for
solidarity,'' said Dr. Neil Smelser, director of the Center for
Advanced Study of the Behavioral Sciences at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the whole point of rooting for the home team,'' said
Dr. Paul Ramirez, a psychology professor at Long Island University
specializing in crowd and sports psychology. ``It gives you a
chance to identify with your city and your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans are territorial creatures,'' said Smelser. ``But when
there's a clear outside threat, it's very easy for those closest
together to put aside their differences and unite against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Connection with a home team is only part of why a fan is a fan.
Many who attend or watch will have no geographical stake.
Psychologists say those fans are hooked because of a complex tangle
of sexual energy, ego and emotional attachment.
</P>
<P>
   Or simply put, some fans get worked up about sports because it
reminds them subconsciously of _ ahem _ another type of
extracurricular activity.
</P>
<P>
   For men, football feeds into a basic male need _ political
correctness aside _ for conflict and conquest, experts say. Unlike
women, who psychologists say tend to admire individual players, men
tend to concentrate on the team and a sense of oneness.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard fans add the element of emotional commitment. For them,
psychologists say, the team's fate is more than a game, it's part
of an ongoing relationship. And in this case, it makes no
difference whether the fan is a man or a woman, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember listening to a sportscaster talk about how his
holidays were ruined because his team lost,'' said Ramirez, who's
pulling for the Falcons. ``I think when people get depressed over a
sports event it speaks to the emotional investment they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Powder Springs resident Deniz Zoeller, 30, said she has been
going to Falcons games since she was 6 months old. And despite some
frustrating and difficult times, she said she has enjoyed being
able to express loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sitting in the stands, with 10 rows free on each
side of me,'' said Zoeller, who now takes her 4-month-old, Alex,
and 8-year-old stepson, Scotty, to games. ``But now, I can be proud
I stuck it out with them.''
</P>
<P>
   There's anther emotional element that draws fans to this year's
Super Bowl: The Falcons, kicked around for years, are the underdogs
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love underdogs,'' said Ramirez. ``Everyone enjoys
someone who wasn't supposed to make it, work this hard, and get so
far. And it's clear that if they're going to go down, they're going
to go down with a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
