<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons bring the noise to practice
 &HT;    By Matt Winklejohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro Player Stadium doesn't create near the noise problems that
the Metrodome in Minnesota does, and the Falcons will be surrounded
by a less hostile crowd than viewed their NFC title game against
the Vikings. But they're not taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons practiced in Coral Gables with three speakers on the
field blaring loud crowd noise. Atlanta coach Dan Reeves said he
didn't know what to expect Sunday, but he added, ``Certainly, this
is an AFC city, certainly, if you get into one end zone. . . . At
least we want to have some practice in case there is some noise.
You go in anticipating you won't have a problem, but I certainly
don't want to go in without practicing. We'll hit a couple of
drills (Friday) the same way, just the way we've done when we've
been on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' two-hour practice included work on the nickel
defense and the two-minute offense. Reeves was pleased that the
team had a chance to work in slightly windy conditions, in case
there are strong breezes Sunday at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concentration was good,'' Reeves said. ``You know, you're in
the Super Bowl. You ought to be that way. Now it's the distraction
of the families coming in, and, hopefully, we'll handle that
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Punt returner/wide receiver Tim Dwight practiced despite a
stomach virus. Dwight said he thinks the problems resulted from
something he ate for lunch. Reeves said, ``He didn't miss anything
but he didn't practice with his usual spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau (ankle) and tight end/fullback
Brian Kozlowski (foot) both practiced Thursday and reported no
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell -- not!
</P>
<P>
   Falcons backup running back Ken Oxendine is playing Denver
running back Terrell Davis on the scout team in practice this week
and is taking his role seriously. Oxendine even is wearing one of
Davis's actual game jerseys. The Bronco sent it to his friend, the
Falcons' Jamal Anderson, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Ken is getting his head knocked off in practice,'' tight
end O.J. Santiago said. ``Guys are zeroing in on that Broncos
jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine, who attended Virginia Tech, said Davis was his
designated ``host'' when he visited the Georgia campus in 1994.
Davis was a senior at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make some cuts like Terrell,'' said Oxendine,
who has played the opposing running back in practice all season.
``We have the same style, so it's not too hard. The (Falcons'
defense) is definitely adjusting. Some holes that were there last
week aren't there this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Winklejohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
