<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Booker hoping to get the corner spot
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - Falcons cornerback Ronnie Bradford continued Thursday to
get more practice time than Michael Booker, but there still are no
guarantees who will start in Sunday's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Rich Brooks said last week that Bradford
was likely to re-take the starting role he surrendered when he
suffered a slightly separated shoulder Dec. 27 against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   His shoulder, though, is still not exactly rock solid, which
could impact not only one of the starting cornerback spots, but
also the nickel safety spot on passing downs.
</P>
<P>
   Booker, the team's first-round draft choice, replaced Bradford
in the lineup in the Jan. 9 playoff game against San Francisco,
when Bradford dressed but didn't play at all.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the cornerback Jan. 17 against Miami, when Bradford
replaced Devin Bush as the nickel safety in passing situations.
Bush strained a hamstring a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm still not 100 percent, but nobody is at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Booker, who is 6-foot-2, 203 pounds, started six games in the
regular season after Bradford (5-10, 188 pounds) strained the
medial collateral ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   There was noticeable improvement in Booker over his rookie
season, but he was erratic against both the 49ers and the Vikings.
He does, however, matchup better size-wise against Denver's Ed
McCaffrey (6-5, 215) than any other Atlanta defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, returned to practice last week and was under
the impression he was going to re-take the nickel safety job that
he held during the final 13 regular season games, and against San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But in practices Monday and Wednesday this week, his role was
limited as Bradford got most of the work in that spot while being
replaced at corner by Booker.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Fuller has been getting most of the work at nickel
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, Bush got a little more action at the nickel
safety, as it is not yet clear if Bradford's shoulder is going to
be able to withstand a game's worth of pounding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Practice went smooth, like it usually does back at (team
headquarters) in Suwanee,'' said Pro Bowl cornerback Ray Buchanan,
who will play a lot of man-to-man coverage Sunday. ''We were really
crisp even though sometimes I was getting confused by all the
different combinations we had going.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a theme Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The Broncos) really do a lot of different things,'' he said.
''They move around a lot. They've got so many offensive sets, they
can confuse you.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
