<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-LOBBY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-lawmakers may face delay in becoming lobbyists through
`cooling-off' proposal
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a time, doors were opened for them to breeze
freely into the House and Senate chambers, but now a 2-by-3-inch
badge limits them to the hallways.
</P>
<P>
   They are legislators turned lobbyists; no longer writing
Georgia's laws but still trying to shape them.
</P>
<P>
   And in some cases, they now wield more influence from outside
the chambers than they once did inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cashing in on public service,'' said Ed Davis of the
Washington office for Common Cause, a nonprofit government watchdog
group. ``It's using your experience in public service and your
knowledge and contacts ... for the benefit of private interests and
for your own interests. There's nothing wrong with lobbying. But we
think that the public's interest is better served by having a
cooling off period.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress and 16 states have passed laws requiring waiting
periods before one-time lawmakers and top government officials can
begin lobbying their colleagues. Georgia has no such cooling-off
period, but one has been proposed. A bill drafted by State Sen.
Sonny Perdue (R-Bonaire) would require former legislators and state
officials wait at least a year before lobbying for a private
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a revolving door,'' Perdue said of legislators who retire
and immediately begin lobbying the Georgia Legislature. ``The
relationships one develops while you serve in this body or as a
department head, those relationships can be unfairly used.''
</P>
<P>
   In office less than three weeks, Gov. Roy Barnes has twice
turned a sharp tongue on lobbyists. The governor said members of
his staff and executive branch employees cannot accept gifts from
lobbyists, and on Wednesday took a pointed swipe at lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch those eel-skinned briefcases and alligator shoes. It's
their job to put a wedge between us and what the people want and
demand and deserve,'' Barnes said in his State of the State speech.
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth of the way through the 1999 session, 1,000 lobbyists
have registered, just 15 shy of the number that signed up by the
end of the 1998 General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 of those registered lobbyists were once legislators or
high-ranking state officials themselves _some of them as recently
as a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some come to the hallways for the money, while others just
weren't ready to leave the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Corrections, for example, hired former Rep.
Grace Davis, who is friends with the new chairs of the House and
Senate committees that oversee the state prison system. She was not
re-elected to represent her southwest Atlanta district.
</P>
<P>
   For two sessions, the State Board of Pardons and Paroles has
used former Rep. Carlton Colwell, who chaired the State
Institutions and Property Committee, which handles legislation
affecting the clemency panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I'm back. But it's tough to phase out of
here,'' said Bill Lee, who did not run for re-election last
November, retiring from the House where he had served 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lee says he is an ``consultant,'' not a lobbyist, representing
Zoo Atlanta. He signed on with Joe Tanner, who was in charge of
former Gov. Zell Miller's privatization effort and a state employee
for 28 years. Tanner's list of clients is long and includes KSL
Lake Lanier, the company that won the state contract to manage the
resort.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senate Republican Leader Arthur ``Skin'' Edge joined
another former legislator, Boyd Pettit, working the 1997
Legislature, the first session he was not a member. They have a
long list of clients like Egleston Children's Health Care System,
Equifax and Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Edge, leaning on a wall just outside the member's entrance to
the Senate, said he quit the Legislature after serving a decade
without any ``intention to lobby. But I enjoy the process up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Edge said he can participate, see old friends, and still focus
on his Newnan law practice during the nine months that the
Legislature does not meet without ``the political demands'' of
elected office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
