u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY29-CO     01-28 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-LEGIS-LOTTERY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia `Bubba' is winning votes for S.C. lottery
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ As the South Carolina Senate prepares for its
final vote next week on a statewide lottery that would compete with
Georgia's, Republicans opposed to the legislation already appear
defeated by a Georgia hayseed named ``Bubba.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters met Bubba last fall when the bearded character in a
Georgia Bulldog cap and T-shirt appeared in state Democratic Party
television ads ridiculing Gov. David Beasley, a Republican who had
denounced lotteries as immoral gambling, even if proceeds would
benefit public education.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley lost to Democrat Jim Hodges, whose main campaign pledge
was to use millions of dollars in lottery proceeds to improve South
Carolina's bottom-scraping public schools. Recent Democratic
polling indicated nearly seven out of every 10 voters favored a
lottery referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bubba is a folk hero,'' said Sen. Ernie Passailaigue, the
Charleston Democrat who sponsored legislation that would allow
South Carolinians to vote on erasing the state's 104-year-old
constitutional ban on lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Passailaigue contends the Republican-controlled House will be
risking a voter backlash in the Nov. 2, 2000, general election if
it derails the lottery vote when the legislation moves there. ``If
they sit around and hem and haw with it, and bog this down, they
are going to be turned out in droves,'' he said. ``Bubba is going
to be back in 2000 big time.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker David Wilkins, a Greenville Republican who opposes
the lottery, conceded Thursday that ``it is a foregone conclusion''
that legislators will schedule a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The Bubba character, played by actor Kerry Maher of Rock Hill,
S.C., was used by Hodges' supporters to point out that South
Carolinians were crossing into Georgia and spending millions a year
in that state's lottery. South Carolina Democrats estimate that
amount at $80 million or more a year, although Georgia lottery
officials don't keep exact tabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Georgia, we just luuuvvv David Beasley,'' Bubba
hee-hawed in the commercial, which Democrats insist galvanized
strong but unspoken sentiment among South Carolinians who hated the
idea of their money paying for HOPE scholarships for Georgia
college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in South Carolina has a relative in Georgia who is
going to school for free,'' Passailaigue said Thursday, shortly
before the state Senate resumed debate on the lottery and scheduled
a third and final vote for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Senate voted 37-8 in favor of a bill that
would schedule a lottery referendum for the Nov. 2, 2000, general
election. The legislation, which requires three votes, also would
set up a referendum on whether the state should ban the $2.3
billion-a-year video poker industry. Republican senators later
expressed regret about scheduling both votes on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's top priority is establishing a lottery as early
as 2001 in hopes that it would generate $90 million for public
education and $150 million in subsequent years. He favors holding
both referendums at the same time. ``I think the people ought to
decide thumbs up or thumbs down whether or not we have the lottery
or ... video poker in the year 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
