s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-WINDSTAR-MO     01-28 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-WINDSTAR-MOMS-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A MINIVAN CAN USE SOME MOTHERING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JULIE EDELSON HALPERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While serving as vehicle line director, supervising the
development of the 1999 Ford Windstar, Mary Ellen Heyde was struck
by the unusually large number of women with young children who were
working on the redesign. She thought it made sense to tap the
maternal expertise of these 30 ``Windstar Moms,'' most of them
engineers, and she consulted them routinely as the design
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   With the aim of making the minivan more family-friendly, the
mothers offered suggestions for innovations and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Martha McMahon, a lead electrical systems
engineer, noted that her sleeping baby often awoke at night when a
door was opened, switching on bright overhead lights. So she
developed lighting that can be turned to ``sleeping baby mode,'' in
which the opening doors activate only footlights. These dimmer,
lower lights provide some illumination, but are less likely to
disturb sleeping infants.
</P>
<P>
   Another convenience feature is a storage bin for a diaper and
wipes in the front seat area for easy access.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the mothers suggested cup holders that pull down from
the edge of the rear seats, where children can easily reach them
without stretching, as they must when cup holders are farther away
on the doors. That should cut down on spills.
</P>
<P>
   The door handles are designed for women's smaller hands, yet
provide ample room for jewelry and long fingernails. The manually
operated sliding doors glide smoothly in their tracks so that women
and children can open and close them better.
</P>
<P>
   The new Windstar will also be the first minivan to include a
reverse parking aid that warns drivers, with a beeping sound, if
they are close to hitting an object.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Zobel, a Windstar engineer, said that the emphasis on
comfort and convenience was bound to win over women, who account
for 75 percent of the Windstar's regular drivers. And the company,
recognizing the public appeal of mothers as designers, is featuring
some of the Windstar moms in corporate advertising that began this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
