<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S PROPOSED BUDGET TARGETS $2.6 BILLION IN TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Yielding to budgetary restraints, Gov. George W.
Bush on Thursday unveiled $2.6 billion in proposed tax cuts, a
slightly thinner package than he promoted during his re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed spending $96.4 billion on state government
during the next two years, an $8 billion increase over the current
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said his proposed budget ``meets the basic needs of
the state, makes the schools the No. 1 funding priority and sends
money back to the taxpayers of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tax reduction plan is close to the $2.7 billion he
promised last year. It includes a $2 billion cut in local school
property taxes; a $330 million cut in sales taxes on diapers, other
health aids, over-the-counter medicine and Internet access; and
$307 million worth of business tax credits and exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush deleted a proposal to temporarily suspend the sales tax
on children's clothing for two weeks before school starts. It would
have saved Texas consumers an estimated $97 million during the next
two years, but the governor said that so-called ``sales tax
holiday'' had ``faded'' because of a lower-than-expected budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've (still) got the largest tax cut in the state's history _
$2.6 billion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander has told legislators
they will have an additional $5.6 billion in general revenue to
spend during the two-year budget period that begins Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposed spending increase of $8 billion includes a
projected increase in federal funds as well. Almost $28 billion of
the governor's proposed budget is federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he is prepared to negotiate with lawmakers
but, ``We're giving no tax cuts away. The people of Texas don't
want any tax cuts given away.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic senators said the governor should give a
higher priority to health care and other state needs before he
tries to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we have taken care of our responsibilities to the
citizens of Texas, then we should return the surplus to the
taxpayers,'' said state Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, chairman
of the Senate Democratic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to increase state funds to the public schools by $1.6
billion during the next two years _ on top of the $2 billion that
he wants the state to reimburse districts for lower property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget director, Albert Hawkins, said changes in
state law, which are still being drafted, will be necessary in
addition to the budgetary provisions to carry out the governor's
plan to force school districts to cut their property tax rates by
an average of 13 cents for every $100 valuation.
</P>
<P>
   That would be $130 a year on a home valued at $100,000. The
reductions also would apply to business property.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said school districts would be reimbursed for their
lower tax rates with $1.55 billion in new state aid. The remaining
$450 million would be money that some districts will owe the state
because of higher-than-expected property values during the current
budget period. That money also would be distributed among school
districts to provide property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed that school districts use $1 billion of their
increased aid to raises teachers' salaries or hire more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   His budget also includes money to hire 380 new caseworkers to
investigate child abuse, expand juvenile detention facilities and
provide pay raises for prison guards, youth correctional officers,
parole officers and Department of Public Safety officers.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins also responded to criticism from state Sen. John
Whitmire, D-Houston, that the governor's proposals didn't include
enough money to tackle transportation problems, particularly in
cities like Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said Bush's budget calls for a ``substantial increase''
in transportation funding, including a $700 million increase in
federal highway funds alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
