<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-PROBE-BOS &LR;      01-28 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC BOARD THREATENS TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee's executive board will quit
if its colleagues do not expel five members implicated in the Salt
Lake City payoff scandal, vice president Richard Pound of Canada
warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Though four members have already stepped down amid the worst
scandal in modern Olympic history, three others _ Jean-Claude Ganga
of the Republic of Congo, Lamine Keita of Mali and Agustin Arroyo
of Ecuador _ have vowed to contest their expulsion before the full
115-member body in Lausanne, Switzerland in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these people show up and fight and can persuade two-thirds
of the membership not to expel them, you'll have the entire
executive board resign,'' said Pound, who chaired the IOC's special
inquiry into the bidding process for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-member board recommended unanimously Sunday that six of
the 13 members involved be expelled. A seventh member, Charles
Mukora of Kenya, quit on Monday, and IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch has urged the others to follow suit. Three additional
members _ Vitaly Smirnov of Russia, Kim Un-Yong of South Korea and
Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye of Ivory Coast _ are still under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said others could be implicated as the IOC broadens its
probe to other bid cities from other years. Samaranch has written
to the national Olympic committees from every candidate city for
the Games from 1996 to 2006, asking for evidence of further
wrongdoing by IOC members before the March special session.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that requires a major exhumation,''
Pound said. ``Either these things happened or they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pound said that four or five new names could surface from
other cities, he expects that an expanded list would largely
duplicate Salt Lake's. ``I suspect a lot of the same fish were
bottom-feeding in all of the ponds,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-GATECH-PREVIEW29-     01-28 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-GATECH-PREVIEW29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets rated a preseason favorite
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Expectations for Georgia Tech baseball are the highest
this year since 1994, when the Yellow Jackets lost in the finals of
the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The top three college baseball magazines ranked Tech No. 2, No.
7 and No. 9 nationally, and league coaches chose the Jackets first
in the ACC, ahead of Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Danny Hall doesn't back away from his team's potential.
``From a talent standpoint, this is the best team we've had since
1994,'' Hall said. ``We've got better (pitching) arms and more of
them than we've had in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech, which has been to 14 NCAA tournaments in a row, finished
last season 41-22 and advanced to the title game of the NCAA
Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets open their 1999 season today against 12th-ranked
Auburn in the Disney Baseball Blast in Lake Buena Vista, Fla. Also
in the field are Oklahoma and Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets, returning eight position players who started 34 or
more games, are led by senior catcher Eric McQueen, second baseman
Matthew Boggs, catcher-first baseman Bryan Prince, first baseman
Stephen Donaghey and outfielders Jason Basil and Derik Goffena.
</P>
<P>
   All-America pitcher Chuck Crowder, a senior from Mantua, Ohio,
who posted a 12-4 record and ranked third in the ACC in ERA (3.03),
leads an experienced group of starters. All-American lefty Cory
Vance and Simon Young join Crowder in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, Tech also boasts the consensus top
recruiting class in the nation, including six players drafted in
the first nine rounds of the 1998 major league draft.
</P>
<P>
   Hall will start two new position players _ freshmen Mark
Teixeira at third base and Victor Menocal at shortstop. ``I love
their attitude,'' Hall said. ``They're very competitive and want to
be in the middle of the action.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Tech looks on paper, Hall realizes that he's still
going to have to rely on youth to succeed. ``The key to our team
early is our freshman pitchers,'' he said. ``We've got some
upper-classmen to lead the way, but our new pitchers are going to
have to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall also is counting on Goffena, Basil, Prince and Teixeira to
carry an offensive load that they weren't expected to carry last
season. ``They're going to have to knock in some runs,'' Hall said.
``We're a very good defensive team, but I'm waiting to see about
our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's schedule is tougher than in years past. It includes
Auburn, Oklahoma, UCLA, West Virginia and Georgia, along with
Florida State, Clemson, Wake Forest and the rest of the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   In the ACC regular season, Hall has finished no worse than
third, and he won the regular-season title in 1997. With all of
that success in his five years, including an overall 215-100
record, the affable coach has had little success in the ACC
tournament. Tech's last ACC tourney title came in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bothers me big time,'' Hall said. ``We have not been a
good ACC tournament team, and I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
