<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-CHRISTIANS-NYT &LR;      01-28 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CHRISTIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA ORDERS INQUIRY INTO MISSIONARY'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The Indian Cabinet on Thursday ordered a
judicial inquiry into the killings of an Australian Christian
missionary and his two young sons _ who were burned to death in
their van on Saturday in a tribal village _ after a team of
government ministers who visited the village said they had found no
local people with a motive.
</P>
<P>
   The police in the eastern state of Orissa, where the killings
took place, had blamed a mob they said was led by a local activist
from the Bajrang Dal, a militant Hindu youth group that is part of
the same family of Hindu nationalist organizations as the Bharatiya
Janata Party, which heads the national coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Minister George Fernandes, a Christian who led the
team of ministers from the national government, said at a news
conference that they had found no evidence that any particular
group had committed the crime, but also cited a possible political
motive. Relations between the 100 Christians and the 700 tribal
residents of Manoharpur village had been ``generally cordial,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes suggested that the killings and the outcry they
engendered might be part of a larger design by ``forces'' in the
nation and abroad to bring down the government led by Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who heads the BJP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to see that beginning from Atal Behari Vajpayee down to
the last man in the government be crucified over the issue,''
Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes, who met with residents and officials in the village
for about an hour on Wednesday, declined to identify the forces
that he said might have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the ministers' findings, Fernandes did say he had
heard complaints that the state government, which is ruled by the
opposition Congress Party, had failed to arrest the accused
ringleader of the mob, Ravinder Kumar Pal, before the crime,
despite numerous criminal complaints against him. Pal is still at
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see not just a political party but I see a whole lot of
forces in this country which would like to see the government go,''
Fernandes said. ``There are forces abroad which are not prepared to
tolerate this government.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Bajrang Dal have denied any role in the deaths of
the missionary, Graham Staines, 58, and his sons, Philip, 10, and
Timothy, 6. They say that Pal is not a member of their group and
that they have no chapter in the district where the killings took
place.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government has come under pressure in recent months
from Western diplomats and some members of its own coalition to
stop the growing number of attacks on Christians and their places
of worship. Last year, there were 86 such cases reported to the
police, more than half of them in the western state of Gujarat.
</P>
<P>
   Christian groups say Hindu nationalist militants have been
emboldened to attack them because of the presence of a Hindu
nationalist-led government. The Hindu militants, while denying any
role in the attacks, have recently been harshly critical of what
they call Christian efforts to convert Hindus through bribes and
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes said the attacks on Christians, while serious, had
been blown out of proportion by Western reporters. ``I was in
France about 10 days before Staines' murder, and the only question
on everybody's lips was `What is happening to Christians in
India?''' he said. ``It had taken the place of the old questions on
snakes and cobras and elephants.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee has announced that he will fast this Saturday, on the
anniversary of the assassination of Gandhi, to promote harmony
among religious groups. His critics have called the fast a stunt to
draw attention away from his government's failure to stop the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   India's home minister, L.K. Advani, said the government had
decided to establish a judicial inquiry, led by a Supreme Court
judge, to look into the killings in part because the incident has
tarnished India's image abroad as a tolerant, secular nation. The
judge, yet to be named, will be required to report back within two
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Staines killings have drawn the world's attention because
``he was a foreign national working in this country for a worthy
cause,'' Advani said. Staines, who was with the Evangelical
Missionary Society, had devoted himself to the care of lepers and
ran a hospital and clinics for them in Orissa.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since his death, national television news programs
have carried images of weeping Indians, rubbing their eyes with
hands reduced to stumps by leprosy, grieving for their lost
champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
