<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASHINGTON-MAYOR-BOS &LR;      01-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-MAYOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. MAYOR CRITICIZED IN AIDE'S RESIGNATION OVER OFFENSIVE TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rap from some quarters on Anthony A. Williams,
Washington's new mayor, is that he isn't black enough. Others say
he isn't political enough. This week, Williams, a bow-tied
bureaucrat, tried to prove he is both, and now he's in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Julian Bond, the chairman of the NAACP, accused
Williams of having ``niggardly'' judgment for accepting the
resignation of David Howard, one of Williams's top aides, after
Howard used the word ``niggardly'' in a conversation about the
tight budget and offended some co-workers who thought it was a
racist remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole episode speaks loudly to where we are on the issue
of race,'' Bond said in a statement. ``Both real and imagined
slights are catapulted to the front burner. Seems to me the mayor
has been niggardly in his judgment on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Merriam Webster's ``Collegiate Dictionary, 10th edition,''
defines niggardly as ``grudgingly mean about spending or granting;
stingy.'' Niggardly is unrelated in its etymology and meaning to
the similar-sounding word that is an inflammatory racial slur.
Some, including Bond and gay leaders, believe Williams extended
political correctness too far in punishing his aide, a white man,
for saying it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, stung by the criticism, has opened an inquiry into the
incident and says he might reassign Howard, who was his director of
constituent services, to another job in his young administration.
Williams insists Howard did the right thing in resigning because
his insensitive choice of words was akin to being ``caught smoking
in a refinery that resulted in an explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   But some observers think the flap says less about Howard than it
does about Williams, a soft-spoken Ivy Leaguer who was the chief
financial officer for the powerful control board set up by Congress
to manage the collapsing city during former Mayor Marion Barry's
last term. Williams won the Democratic primary for mayor by
trouncing his opponents in Washington's white wards and picking up
the votes of the city's black professional class. He breezed to
victory in November with the blessing of the business community,
and he quickly brought in an administration heavy with young, white
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Williams has an image problem,'' said Mark Plotkin, a
political analyst with WAMU, the local public radio station. ``From
the day he got here, he was viewed by some as not black enough. He
was an outsider in a black city; he was the bureaucrat who had to
fire black people from government jobs; and he won the election
because wealthy white people supported him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This made him skittish, even defensive, about the racial
issue,'' Plotkin said. ``So when faced with the Howard issue, he
took the easy way out and acted like a conventional politician.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, a senior analyst at the Joint Center for
Political and Economic Studies, a black think tank, said Williams
should not have accepted Howard's resignation. Williams's success
as mayor in a multicultural city under Congress's watchful eye
depends on proving he is in charge and not carrying on Barry's
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's no political Arnold Schwarzenegger, he needs to
establish himself quickly,'' Bositis said. ``He is responsible and
going to be judged for getting rid of 500,000 rats, controlling the
trigger-happy cops, mending broken schools, and fixing thousands of
potholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Washingtonians were abuzz Thursday with the
``niggardly'' story. Joe Madison, host of Newstalk Network on local
WOL radio, said it was all his listeners wanted to talk about. He
said 98 percent of them are black, and almost all were offended by
Howard's remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different cultures have different reactions to language as it
relates to race,'' Madison said. ``Black people have heard the word
`niggardly' used in a derogatory way by people who have misdefined
it. They think David Howard used poor judgment in saying the word
and he should have been a little more conscious of the impact its
sound would have on people hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Language has social consequences, said Colleen Cotter, an
assistant professor of linguistics at Georgetown University, and
the fact that ``niggardly'' sounds like a racial slur may explain
why this Middle English word of Chaucer and Shakespeare has fallen
out of common usage.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Walters, a professor of government and politics at the
University of Maryland, said Williams should not be identifying
himself with the erudite elite _ including Bond and some national
leaders _ who offer brainy dictionary definitions in the place of
common sense and political wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor better not change his tune on Howard,'' Walters
said. ``He can't pretend that Washington isn't a city that is 67
percent black where mistakes like this don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, a white elementary school teacher in Brooklyn was
threatened by a group of angry black parents, and eventually
reassigned to another school, after she read the children's book
``Nappy Hair'' to her students. The parents accused the teacher,
Ruth Sherman, of being racially insensitive. Carolivia Herron, the
black author of the book, defended the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Herron, a professor of English at Cal State-Chico,
said the reaction to Howard's remark was sad but not surprising.
Herron recently gave her mother, who lives in Washington, an
audiotape of Charles Dickens's ``David Copperfield.'' When one of
the characters spoke the word ``niggardly,'' her mother reacted
with shock and disgust, Herron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoid the word _ I never use the word _ because it causes
those kinds of problems,'' Herron said. ``It's a sad commentary,
isn't it, because the language is poorer for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
