</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENNETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bennett reborn as Bird
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The world has been swirling around Cornelius Bennett
this week, racing by at a breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons linebacker, who will play Sunday in his fifth
Super Bowl of the 1990s, is in some ways moving as slowly as ever.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, he was nearly as fast as ever, leading the team
with 121 tackles, second-most in his 12-year career.
</P>
<P>
   But when a man becomes a reborn Christian, as he did in August
1997, and swears off his hedonistic ways, change is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 33, spent 36 days in the Erie County Correctional
Facility last spring after pleading guilty to sexual misconduct
charges from May 1997 in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he takes his time when he talks, almost always
measuring his words, calculating much of what he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because my life has changed, this (Super Bowl) is more special
than anything (in football),'' he said. ``I wouldn't trade anything
for those four that I played with Buffalo, don't get me wrong. But
just on a personal level, I'm seeing everything clearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been given another opportunity at a career most can
only dream about. I didn't think I was going to be around because
of the offseason trouble I had. Who wants that kind of thing on the
team? Coach (Dan) Reeves could have blackballed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has said several times that Bennett has paid his debt to
society.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has never gone into detail about the May 1997 incident,
which took place after a roast for retired Bills quarterback Jim
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never once ran off and hid anywhere. I did what I had to do
as a man,'' he said. ``I asked for forgiveness where needed, and I
took it to where any human being should take their troubles. I took
it to God.''
</P>
<P>
   While in jail, he also took it to his mates in misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of fans in there,'' he said. ``I was in
Buffalo, basically, and there were a lot of people who know who I
was. They were all just excited by the idea of me being around
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent most of my time in the Bible, or in chapel. There was
a lot of time to share, and a lot of guys in there were trying to
get their lives together at that particular time, just like I
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has corresponded with a few of his former
``colleagues,'' but not this week. ``I've written to a couple guys,
but it's not something I want to keep going back on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the man has gone from jailbird to Dirty Bird, swearing off
alcohol, a lousy diet and other vices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him play when he was at Alabama,'' said linebacker
Henri Crockett, a second-year pro. ``Other guys all wanted to be
Walter Payton. I wanted to be Cornelius Bennett, a big guy who can
run like that and make all those plays. I just love watching him
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has been one of the most obliging players on the team.
But when he was asked at one point this season if his tackles were
decreasing because he was wearing down, he flared. ``Don't start
talking to me about ... getting old,'' he said. Earlier this week,
Bennett was preaching that the worst thing his teammates could do
would be to party too much this week, which is what the Bills did
before their Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, he got tired of seeing it all blown out of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, he was the anti-Ray Buchanan, speaking in a
clipped voice, sipping coffee and reading between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you going with these questions?'' he asked a
reporter who just arrived. ``I don't want all of what I said
misinterpreted. (Former Buffalo coach) Marv Levy was a very good
coach and a fine man. We had rules; we broke them. All this makes
him look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bennett cares now in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons beat the Broncos on Sunday, he said it will be,
in a way, for former Buffalo teammates Kelly, Thurman Thomas, Bruce
Smith and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what about (current teammate) Jessie Tuggle? He wasn't
even drafted, but he has become one of the greatest middle
linebackers to play the game,'' Bennett said. ``And (kicker) Morten
Andersen took 17 years to get here. This game is not just about me;
it's about a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Rich Brooks said the Falcons' chances are
a lot better with Bennett, who at Buffalo played inside and outside
linebacker, defensive end and nose tackle while going to the Pro
Bowl five times.
</P>
<P>
   He can't forget a play Bennett made in Atlanta's 20-18 victory
against San Francisco in a Jan. 9 playoff game _ a play that might
have kept the Falcons' season alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using him a lot more in (pass) coverage this year, ...
and (running back) Terry Kirby was behind him, and Steve Young was
scrambling,'' Brooks said. ``He turned around and ran downfield and
knocked that pass down _ coming from 20 yards away. He turned on
the jets. He's still got the wheels to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his own admission, he's in better shape at this stage of
the season than he would have been because he has taken care of his
body. Maybe in his old lifestyle, those wheels would have had a
blowout.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Kirby would have scored, sending the Falcons home
instead of to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
