<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For talkin' trash, Sharpe has no match
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _We could take you deep inside the Super Bowl, dear
reader. To the game within the game, where X meets O in a clash of
complex schematics.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what the week before is all about. It's about
such truly weighty questions as: Does Ray Buchanan wear a
Wonderbra?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying (Buchanan's) a cross-dresser.'' Pause. Snickers
and nudging comments from others at the back of the class. ``That's
what I heard,'' said Shannon Sharpe, the loose-lipped tight end.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's final meeting with the massed media, Denver's
Sharpe let go one of the great verbal carpet-bombings in Super Bowl
history. Hollywood Henderson once suggested Pittsburgh quarterback
Terry Bradshaw couldn't spell ``cat'' if you spotted him the ``c''
and the ``a.'' That was during the primitive days of smack. It now
has been raised to the level of performance art.
</P>
<P>
   Catching the worst of it was Falcons cornerback Buchanan, a
noted vocalist himself from whom an interviewer had extracted a
victory prediction early in the going.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Buchanan) goes to the Pro Bowl for the first time, and now
all of a sudden he's great,'' Sharpe vented. ``I remember last year
when the guy from the Rams had that big game. What did Isaac Bruce
do to him?'' 233 yards receiving in one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he should have done with all that money he got to sign,
he should have given half of it back, because he stole last year's
salary. He backed up to the window with a mask on and a hood and
said, `Give me my check.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, Ray only started talking this year. When he was
in Indianapolis, he didn't say anything. He never guaranteed
anything there, except that the other team was going to win, and
that he'd aid the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The material is not highbrow, nor particularly instructive. It
basically is a variation of the ``your mama's so fat'' jokes. But
such mouth-to-mouth combat has become a charming part of the Super
Bowl ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan really has no one to blame but himself. He fired the
opening salvo during the Falcons' interview session first thing
Thursday morning. He began the war he couldn't win by questioning
Sharpe's looks. Like I said, this isn't exactly a Harvard debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon looks like a horse. I tell you, that's one ugly dude.
... You can't tell me he doesn't look like Mr. Ed,'' Big Say Ray
opined.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad opening gambit. But no one can run long with Sharpe.
He's going to get in the last, and most, words. His mouth is an
army.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were dutifully shuttled to Sharpe by a devious
media. The response was even better than expected. Some exerpts
from Def Comedy Football follow:
</P>
<P>
   ``He said what? Now I know he couldn't be talking, with the big
teeth in his mouth. Those teeth look like dominoes in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he my friend? No. Did I ever view him as a friend? No. Did
I ever view him as an acquaintance? No. Do I like him?
</P>
<P>
   Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
