<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sights and sounds from Miami
 &HT;    By Lenm Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Denver Broncos officials are fretting that commissioner Paul
Tagliabue might favor the Falcons in the Super Bowl, just to keep
peace on the homefront, they can quit worrying. Yes, the NFL's
first lady, Chan Tagliabue is a Milledgeville native. But Mrs.
Tagliabue pointed out Thursday that her brother, Charles Minter,
resides in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thrilled to see the Falcons in the Super Bowl, not because
they're from Atlanta, but because I like to see different teams in
the spotlight,'' Mrs. Tagliabue said. ''I want both teams to play
well so that we have a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tagliabue will today lead a contingent that will include
the commissioner, Jack Kemp, Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga and Hall
of Fame cornerback Mel Blount in ''Kickoff to Rebuild '99.'' The
program is part of the ''Christmas in April'' endeavor and the
group will extensively rehabilitate three low-income homes in the
West Little River section of Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tagliabue's mother, Elizabeth Minter, still lives in
Milledgeville.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION, FALCONS
</P>
<P>
   New Baltimore Ravens coach Brian Billick, here for a press
conference on Thursday, didn't exactly seem sold on backup
quarterback and former Georgia star Eric Zeier. ''It would be
difficult to live with a 6-foot quarterback,'' Billick said. ''He
makes plays, but . . .'' Billick didn't even try to camouflage his
ardor for Vikings backup Brad Johnson and predicted he will be with
another team in 1999. The Falcons signed Zeier to an offer sheet
last spring, but the Ravens retained his rights by matching it.
</P>
<P>
   SO LONG, TIM
</P>
<P>
   Former NFL cornerback Tim McKyer, who played two seasons in
Atlanta (1991-92), visited the media center this week and announced
that he has officially retired. ''Or to be more accurate, the NFL
retired me,'' McKyer said. The longtime veteran is less than
thrilled that no team signed him for the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   THE ZEBRAS
</P>
<P>
   The NFL on Thursday announced the game officials for Super Bowl
XXXIII. But poll of the learned group of scribes in the media
center, it's believed that none of the zebras were involved in any
of the horrid calls that marked NFL games in 1998. The crew: Bernie
Kukar (referee), Jim Daopoulos (umpire), Sanford Rivers (head
linesman), Ron Baynes (line judge), Tim Millis (field judge), Gary
Lane (side judge), Don Hakes (back judge).
</P>
<P>
   DAN THE MAN
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback Dan Marino was named as the Sprint/NFL ''Man
of the Year'' for the '98 season. The annual honor is awarded to a
player for his charitable indeavors and community service. The
Dolphins star established the Dan Marino Foundation, which was
created to benefit children's charites in South Florida. He hosts
several events each year to raise money for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER SHORTS
</P>
<P>
   Gene Upshaw, executive director of the NFL Players Association,
noted Thursday that the league in the future will look at moving
back the date for the free agency signing period. Upshaw predicted
the '99 salary cap limit will be $57.5 million, but NFLPA estimates
typically are a bit low. . . . The league's finance committee met
with the trustees of the estate of late Washington owner John Kent
Cooke to determine if the sale of the team to Howard Milstein was
handled appropriately. . . . Former Chicago Bears offensive
coordinator Matt Cavanaugh will join the Ravens in the same
capacity
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
