<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-GREENSPAN-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN WARNS THAT SOCIAL SECURITY'S FUTURE MAY STILL BE
JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman,
warned Congress on Thursday not to count on projected government
budget surpluses to solve Social Security's problems, and he
suggested that Republicans and Democrats would still have to cut
benefits or raise taxes to insure the retirement system's future.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the Senate Budget Committee, Greenspan was
clearly trying to interject a dose of hard reality into the debate
over Social Security, which for the last week has centered on
President Clinton's proposal to shore up the system with $2.7
trillion out of the $4.4 trillion in surpluses the White House
anticipates in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on the surplus reduces the sacrifices that would be
necessary from today's workers and tomorrow's retirees, and for
that reason Republicans too have generally endorsed allocating a
big portion of the surplus to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has alluded in general terms to the need for measures in
addition to using the surplus but has avoided specifics, while
Republicans have been silent or called for solutions that require
neither tax increases nor benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's message on Thursday was that budget forecasts have
been notoriously unreliable in the past and are likely to remain so
in the future, making 15-year surplus projections a rickety
structure on which to base a solution to Social Security's
long-term financial gap.
</P>
<P>
   The country should be wary of assuming ``extraordinarily large
projected surpluses as far as the eye can see,'' Greenspan said.
``I use that term advisedly, because it was originally used on the
deficit side, and it was obvious that as far as the eye could see
wasn't all that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted that the Congressional Budget Office had
predicted in February 1997 that the government would run a deficit
in 1998 of $121 billion. The actual outcome was a surplus of $70
billion, an error of $191 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, though, how receptive Congress will be to
Greenspan's message. Just hours after Greenspan spoke, the
Congressional Budget Office distributed a new budget forecast to
congressional leaders showing a total surplus over the next 11
years of nearly $2.7 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office's projections, which appeared to be roughly in
line with the $4.4 trillion, 15-year surplus projected by the White
House, show the overall surpluses mounting rapidly, from $107
billion in the current fiscal year to $381 billion in 2009.
</P>
<P>
   They also include $794 billion in surpluses over the eight years
starting in 2001 that would not rely on excess payroll taxes that
are nominally earmarked for Social Security _ in other words a true
surplus derived from annual spending being lower than annual
revenues from general tax collections. Republicans have been
counting on the emergence of a true surplus to finance their plans
for an across-the-board reduction in income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the overall surpluses materialize and are not used
for new spending programs, Greenspan said, Clinton's strategy of
using the surplus to bolster Social Security by paying down the
national debt is the soundest policy option available.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the debt held by the public would be the best way to
strengthen the economy in the long run, Greenspan said, and would
make it easier for the country to cope with the financial strains
that will be created by its aging population.
</P>
<P>
   But given the risk that a downturn in the economy or the stock
market could cause the surpluses to evaporate, Greenspan said,
Congress and the administration need to keep looking for ways to
increase the amount of money available for Social Security or to
decrease benefit payments. Greenspan led a commission in the early
1980s that pushed through both tax increases and benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Raising taxes now or altering the Social Security system to
require increased savings and investment through private accounts
might prove too politically ``burdensome,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he added, the country would have to examine a long
menu of potential benefit cuts. These might take the form of
increasing the age for retirement, reducing cost-of-living
increases or making less generous the formula used to calculate
lifetime earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considerations such as these should not be taken off the
table,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address last week, Clinton said his
plan, which also called for the government to invest a portion of
Social Security's reserves in the stock market, would keep the
system afloat until 2055, compared with 2032 if no changes are
made.
</P>
<P>
   But the benchmark for financial health in Social Security is
solvency for 75 years, and Clinton acknowledged that the two
parties would have to ``to make hard-headed but sensible and
achievable choices'' to meet that goal.
</P>
<P>
   He did not lay out the possibilities, much less endorse any of
them, and most Republicans have avoided the subject altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Greenspan's comments, Joe Lockhart, the White House
press secretary, said the administration ``could not agree with him
more'' about the need for further bipartisan steps to insure the
system's solvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to reserving the surplus and paying down the debt,
we need to do more to reform the system,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior House Republican aide said the issue was a ``crucial
question'' facing both parties and was part of a broader debate
over whether Congress and the administration should settle for a
partial solution on Social Security and defer the hard choices for
another day.
</P>
<P>
   Before it became apparent that the budget surplus could ease
much of the pain of addressing Social Security's woes, the two
parties had been circling warily around a variety of options.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had ruled out increasing the 12.4 percent payroll tax
rate _ split equally between workers and their employers _ that
finances Social Security. But liberal Democrats were advocating
other ways of increasing revenues, including an increase in the
wage level subject to the payroll tax, currently $72,000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, have been adamant that they will not
accept any kind of tax increase. They have been more open to other
options, including an increase in the retirement age, which is
already scheduled to rise gradually to 67 over the next several
decades. But organized labor has promised a ferocious effort to
block any further increase in the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony on Thursday came as Republicans continued
to question whether Clinton's plan to use the surplus for Social
Security was anything more than an accounting gimmick. And it came
as members of both parties are increasingly pessimistic that there
will be enough bipartisan trust in the aftermath of the impeachment
trial for Congress and the administration to reach a deal on Social
Security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
