<SLUG> BC-MA-RAPE-SETTLEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY SETTLES CASE OF SEXUALLY ABUSED BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A private agency that placed a troubled girl in a
foster home where she allegedly sexually abused the family's
11-year-old son, Thursday settled with the family for what sources
said was roughly $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys involved in the negotiations said the sum was
confidential. But sources familiar with the case said the agency _
Mentor, Inc., with which the state contracts to find foster homes _
agreed to the cash payment and issued an apology.
</P>
<P>
   The apology was for any negligence Mentor, Inc. showed when
seven years ago when it placed a 15-year-old girl in a home where
she repeatedly forced or coerced an 11-year-old boy into sex. The
girl became pregnant with the boy's child.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe is witholding the name of the girl because she was a
teen when the alleged offenses took place.
</P>
<P>
   The case, full of finger-pointing and contradictions,
highlighted the lingering effects of sexual abuse, the complicated
bureaucracy of social service agencies that struggle to place
foster children and the rights of foster parents to be forewarned
about potential trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a success,'' said Traver Clinton Smith, an attorney for
the foster family, who lived in Duxbury at the time. ``Our job was
to show, not that these incidents took place, but that she never
should have been placed in that home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Social Services was also named in the lawsuit,
but the agency was able to show that Mentor, Inc. had agreed to
take full responsibilty for the girl, whose case file specified she
should be placed, ``where there are no young males residing.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl had a long history both as a victim of sexual abuse and
as a perpetrator of sexual abuse on younger children, both sides
agreed. Thursday's settlement was reached after a little more than
four days of testimony in front a Suffolk County Superior Court
jury.
</P>
<P>
   The boy is now a 20-year-old college student who hopes to become
a Massachusetts State police officer. Broad-shouldered and
clean-cut, he bowed his head and cried during testimony this week
from his sister that he was transformed from a happy-go-lucky kid
to a withdrawn, forlorn boy.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was 11 when the incidents of sexual abuse allegedly
occurred, the Globe has agreed to withhold his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was young at the time,'' he said, talking to reporters
outside the courtroom Thursday. ``It would happen frequently.'' He
said he did not tell his mother about the sex until the day she
caught the pair kissing atop a stairwell, and ordered the girl out
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled teenage girl, now a mother of a 6 year-old,
testified Thursday that she would frequently visit the 11-year-old
boy's room in the early morning hours, or invite him to hers. She
said she considered it a romantic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The defense had attempted to show that foster mother was
neglectful for having occasionally left the pair alone.
</P>
<P>
   A former Mentor Inc. case worker, Frank Fitzgerald, testified
that he warned the foster mother that the girl had a traumatic past
and might be sexually aggressive. The foster mother says she was
denied crucial information.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was unclear who in the agency was responsible for
knowing that a staffer at St. Vincent's Home for Children had
recommended she should not be in a home with boys. Fitzgerald said
upon cross-examination that he would not have gone along with the
placement had he been aware of the warning.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand Thursday, the former foster teen told the court
that she believed her foster parents were aware that the two young
people shared a sexual relationship. But the plaintiffs scoff at
the notion.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the foster mother and her son have visited with
the baby girl and her mother several times, although they say it is
painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often wondered about the child,'' said the foster mother,
who has a long history of taking in troubled children. ``But I had
mixed feelings'' about whether to visit, ``because of how she came
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The family says they waited seven years to file a lawsuit
detailing their pain and suffering because they were worried about
their son's privacy and warned by prosecutors that criminal charges
would result in a public trial. The foster mother also said she did
not expect much sympathy from the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt that if he had been a girl (who was raped)
rather than a boy,'' the courts and a public would be more
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor Inc. continues to be a service provider to the state. The
foster mother acknowledged in interviews that she had received
dozens of successful placements from them prior to November 1990.
Attempts to reach agency officials Thursday were unsucessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
