<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A COMPLICATED QUARTER, RJR EARNINGS SIMPLY DECLINE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.C., Russia, Japan, Brazil, Argentina)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buoyed by the improving fortunes of its cookie and cracker
business but battered by the cost of tobacco-related litigation,
RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. posted fourth-quarter earnings Thursday
of 58 cents a share, 9 percent lower than a year ago, excluding
unusual charges.
</P>
<P>
   With the charges, however, the company reported a net loss of
$1.83 a share, mostly stemming from $780 million in
tobacco-settlement payments and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought the Hubble Telescope was complicated, you
should take a look at RJR's fourth quarter,'' said Emanuel Goldman,
an analyst for Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter, RJR lost $585 million, compared with a loss of
$197 million, or 64 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue for the
quarter fell 2.5 percent, to $4.47 billion from $4.58 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, the company's earnings declined 23 percent,
to $2.10 vs. $2.72 a year ago, without the unusual charges.
Including the one-time charges, the company had a net loss of $1.91
a share, up from $1.03 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of RJR's stock were unchanged Thursday at $27.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst for Salomon Brothers, called
the quarter ``reasonably good for the company.'' Most noteworthy,
he said, was that without spending much on promotions, RJR's share
of the cigarette market eroded just 0.2 percent, from 25.4 percent
to 25.2 percent. ``RJR's advertising and promotional expenditure
had been less than Philip Morris','' he said, ``yet it essentially
managed to stabilize its market share.''
</P>
<P>
   Income from the company's U.S. tobacco business rose 25 percent
in the fourth quarter, largely because of a 20 percent, or 45 cents
a pack, price increase that RJR and other cigarette companies
imposed in November, shortly after the $206 billion tobacco
settlement was approved by 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales of brands like Winston and Camel increased 15 percent,
to $1.5 billion, despite the price increase, although volume
declined 9 percent. For the full year, tobacco profits rose 7
percent, to $1.62 billion, the company said. Volumes for major
brands were down slightly, although the company said inventories
had been unusually high in anticipation of the tobacco settlement,
resulting in less demand in the fourth quarter from wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   International tobacco was disappointing for the company. While
sales in Western Europe and Japan were steady, sales in Russia and
other emerging markets fell. In Russia, sales volume grew 7
percent, but income fell because consumers traded down to cheaper
brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a global shrinkage of 5 percent in the high margin
brands,'' Feldman said. Net sales of tobacco overseas fell 10
percent, to $3.07 billion, the company said, and earnings from
international tobacco fell 30 percent, to $468 million.
</P>
<P>
   Profits on RJR's food business _ brands like Ritz crackers, Oreo
and Mallomar cookies and Grey Poupon mustard _ fell significantly,
largely because of reorganization costs and increased marketing
expenses to drive sales. Earnings from the cookie-and-cracker
division were down 29 percent, the company said, at $143 million
compared with $202 million in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, market shares rose, for the first time since late 1996,
the company said. Sales of cookies and crackers were up 4 percent,
and sales of the company's food products altogether were up 3
percent for the year, at $2.05 billion.
</P>
<P>
   International food sales fell 4 percent, to $677 million in the
quarter vs. $707 million a year ago. But earnings in the
international division rose 5 percent, mostly because of lower
costs in Brazil and Argentina, the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
