<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANDA29-COX     01-28 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panda pairings? Zoo officials hoping so
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that they've pulled off a major zoo coup, the main
concern for folks at Zoo Atlanta is whether they can teach
Yang-Yang and Lun-Lun to make love love.
</P>
<P>
   In a festive ceremony Thursday at the 40-acre animal park, zoo
officials announced they'd signed a deal to bring two rare giant
pandas from China for a 10-year study aimed at finding out why the
black-and-white creatures have such a hard time mating in
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   As employees passed out Chinese fortune cookies and panda plush
toys, zoo director Terry Maple, wearing a panda necktie, enthused
about plans for Yang-Yang, the male, and Lun-Lun, the female. He
thinks bringing the 2-year-old animals to Atlanta might help save
the species, one of the planet's most endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo executives elsewhere _ and Maple, too _ likened the
agreement to the deal two decades ago that brought the ``Treasures
of Tutankhamen'' exhibit to the United States for a tour.
</P>
<P>
   As bulldozers flattened land to build a $10 million panda
habitat, Maple said his other big concern is how to handle the huge
crowds expected when the public is allowed to see the pandas up
close, probably in October. ``That's really going to be a zoo,'' he
joked.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo's hopes of breeding the pandas are critical, he told a
large crowd of patrons and a delegation of scientists from China.
There are three other pandas in the United States, two at the San
Diego Zoo and another at the National Zoo in Washington. Only about
1,000 are believed alive, including about 100 in captivity. China
is their only native habitat. Other zoos have tried to breed
pandas, but with limited success.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo expects more than 1 million patrons to visit the exhibit
in the first year, a significant increase over normal attendance.
In fiscal year 1997-98, 823,984 people visited Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There's good reason for optimism. When pandas were lent to the
Toledo Zoo in 1988, attendance zoomed to 1.3 million, from 800,000
in most years, said Nancy Foley, a spokeswoman for the Ohio
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lines. We had people waiting to see them. It wasn't
just the community. It drew from Chicago and all over.
Attendance-wise, there's nothing better in a zoo than pandas,''
Foley said. ``I definitely plan to come see them myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoo will send at least $1 million a year to China to help
scientists there with panda conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Maple and fellow scientists Rebecca Snyder and Megan Reinertsen,
like him psychologists at Georgia Tech, suspect pandas don't mate
in captivity because they're taken away from their mothers far too
soon _ as early as 4 months old. Chinese researchers are reluctant
to adopt this theory. In the wild, it's normal for pandas to live
with their mothers for two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that young pandas learn mating skills by watching their
parents' lovemaking _ they don't, Maple said.
</P>
<P>
   But by yanking them away from other of their species, Snyder
said, they become depressed, even sullen, and apparently too shy to
form close relationships with other pandas when they reach mating
age at 4 to 7. Maple said he hopes Yang Yang and Lun Lun will learn
to like each other. Really like each other, enough, eventually, to
make some itty-bitty giant pandas. ``They will grow up here to be
breeding pandas in the same way as Willie B., so that they'll
become prime breeders when they go back to China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Willie B., a 40-year-old gorilla, didn't sire his first
offspring until he was 36, but apparently learned to like the
process. He's the father of three females and one male and is one
of the biggest hits at Zoo Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   By living together, Maple hopes the pandas will gain the
confidence required to do what should come naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what's going on in their minds,'' Snyder
said. ``Hopefully Lun-Lun's association with Yang-Yang will help
socialize them.''
</P>
<P>
   Their habitat will feature indoor and outdoor amenities designed
to simulate their native land. Outside, there will be rocks, pools
and places to climb and get some shade. The 1,674-square-foot
indoor quarters will include holding areas out of public view as
well as two climate-controlled indoor exhibits and storage space
for lots of bamboo, the pandas' preferred food. It will contain
three porches and a private ``cubbing'' den where Maple hopes the
pandas will make whoopee, or at least entertain such thoughts. The
pandas will have plenty of time to become good friends before
they'll be expected to go all the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two of the most lively pandas that you will ever
know,'' Maple said like a proud pop as a video played on a nearby
screen, showing the two cubs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said the deal represents ``probably the most
important project that Zoo Atlanta has ever undertaken. ``We're
really excited,'' Maple said. ``We're thrilled. We like running the
zoo for the public. But what really gets us excited as animal
people is when we can save an animal, when we can teach the world
about animals, and when we can study them and observe them. And
this project has all those features.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Atlanta has been sending researchers for two years to
China's Chengdu Zoo and the Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda
Breeding. Maple said Chinese researchers will be coming to Atlanta,
and he and his colleagues returning there, on a regular basis. The
pandas are on loan, and part of a research project involving Zoo
Atlanta scientists and researchers in China and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, the zoo will raise $4 million for the China-based
panda research program, $2 million for Zoo Atlanta's International
Giant Panda Scientific Breeding Center in Chengdu and $5 million
for conservation and education programs in Georgia. That phase
won't be completed until December 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
