<HEADLINE>
YAHOO TO PAY $5 BILLION FOR GEOCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The red-hot market for Internet companies has just gotten even
hotter, as the leading search service Yahoo Inc. agreed to plunk
down $5 billion of its stock to acquire GeoCities, whose technology
lets people publish pages on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the GeoCities community of 3.2 million members to Yahoo's
vast audience could create the single most popular destination on
the Internet, surpassing the current industry leader, America
Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, what you get is a superbrand,'' said Bruce Zanca,
a spokesman for California-based GeoCities.
</P>
<P>
   A spate of Internet mergers, many of them worth billions of
dollars, have been announced in recent months as companies jockey
for audience and market position in the new media industry. The
merger wave has been fueled by the sky high values of Internet
stocks, which are used as currency in many of the deals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the investors basking in the afterglow of the
Yahoo-GeoCities deal is CMGI Inc., an Andover, Mass. company that
owns about 27 percent of GeoCities. CMGI bought its stake less than
$6 million in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Yahoo stock closed up $31 7/8 at $367 1/4 on the
Nasdaq exchange, making CMGI's investment worth $948 million. ``Now
we're the proud owner of just under 3 percent of Yahoo,'' said Bill
White, president of CMGI's Internet business group. White added
that CMGI has every intention of hanging on to its Yahoo shares.
</P>
<P>
   Ullas Naik , an Internet analyst for First Albany Corp. in
Boston, called the Yahoo-GeoCities deal ``another validation of
CMG's strategy.'' The company has made strategic investments in a
wide range of Internet companies, including a 23 percent stake in
the Internet service Lycos Inc., a Waltham, Mass. company that
gained $11 5/8 on Thursday's news, closing at $123 1/8 on the
Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   As its competitors have rushed to merge, speculation has
increased that Lycos will have to find a merger or investment
partner. The company says it intends to stay independent, but is
searching for strategic partners.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' vice president of network strategies, Bo Peabody, in an
interview with the Reuters news service, said the Yahoo deal
demonstrates the value of Lycos strategy. Over the past year, Lycos
has leaped into the first rank of Internet firms by purchasing a
number of popular Web sites and weaving them into a network.
Peabody said that Yahoo's purchase of GeoCities is an attempt to
emulate the Lycos approach. ``One of our goals was to make Yahoo
sweat,'' he said, ``and we've clearly accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa Bane, an analyst for the Yankee Group in Boston,
said that Yahoo isn't interested in Lycos' network model, in which
each Lycos Web site has a different look and feel. Instead, Bane
said Yahoo would integrate GeoCities into its existing services, in
an effort to drive an ever greater number of visitors to the main
Yahoo site.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Internet sector benefited Thursday from the deal. The
Nasdaq stock index soared to a record close of 2,477.34, with help
from a host of on-line stocks. GeoCities' own shares skyrocketed to
$117 1/4, a gain of $42 1/4. Infoseek Corp., another Web portal,
gained $12 1/2 to close at $83 15/16. Meanwhile, on the New York
Stock Exchange, AOL closed up $8 15/16 at $174 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, based in Santa Clara, Calif., will swap about one-third
of a share of its stock for each outstanding GeoCities share or
stock option. GeoCities has about 40.3 million outstanding shares
and options; these will be exchanged for about 13.6 million Yahoo
shares and options, valuing GeoCities at about $5 billion, based on
Thursday's closing price for Yahoo. The deal is expected to close
in three or four months.
</P>
<P>
   A major goal of most Internet companies is to attract the
maximum number of viewers, so that companies will pay handsomely to
advertise at the site. According to the market research firm Media
Metrix Inc., Yahoo was in third place in December, with 48.2
percent of the entire Internet audience visiting Yahoo during the
month. Sites run by Microsoft Corp. did slightly better at 48.4
percent, while AOL sites held a solid lead at 54.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo officials said that GeoCities would deliver 10
percentage points of additional audience share, putting Yahoo at 58
percent. That could be enough to make Yahoo the Internet's No. 1
site. It could also help to stave off the fierce challenge from
Lycos, which has gone from below 20 percent reach a year ago to
46.5 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo chief operating officer Jeff Mallett admitted that the
GeoCities move was partly inspired by the aggressive expansion of
Lycos. ``They shocked people,'' he said. But he still believes that
Lycos will remain ``a mid-tier player'' among the major Web
services, with Yahoo, Microsoft and AOL vying for dominance.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo's Mallett downplayed his firm's chances of passing
AOL. He noted that AOL would complete its acquisition of Netscape
Communications Corp. this year. The audience from Netscape's
Netcenter service should once again give AOL the biggest Web
audience, Mallet noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
