<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BLOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SAYS CANADA IMPORTED TAINTED BLOOD FROM U.S. INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ark.)  (bl) 
By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A group of Canadians who claim they were infected by
tainted blood products collected from prisoners in the United
States filed a $660 million lawsuit Thursday against the Canadian
government and several private companies for failing to adequately
safeguard the blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suit charges Ottawa with neglect for failing to
keep out blood plasma collected in Arkansas prisons in the early
1980s after health officials in the United States had already
determined that using such products was ``imprudent'' because there
was a high risk of infection. At the time there was no test to
indicate the presence of hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Red Cross had stopped collecting plasma from
inmates in Canadian prisons in the early 1970s, because of
hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged in the suit filed in the Ontario Court of Justice
in Toronto on Thursday is a commercial blood broker in Montreal
that imported the prison plasma, its U.S. associates and the
Toronto laboratory that used the plasma to manufacture a medication
called clotting factor that hemophiliacs need to control their
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read about it in the papers, I was just appalled,''
said Michael McCarthy, 39, a hemophiliac from Sebringville,
Ontario, who used clotting factor in the early 1980s that contained
tainted plasma from Arkansas. McCarthy is lead plaintiff in the
suit, which seeks compensation for about 1,000 hemophiliacs who
contracted hepatitis C from 1980 to 1985. ``There has to be some
questions asked about the role of some people who allowed this
activity to continue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's lawsuit is the latest development in a long and
painful episode involving the deaths or infections of thousands of
Canadians who received tainted blood from a number of sources in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian government established a panel to investigate the
scandal. In its report in December 1997, the panel laid out a long
list of mistakes, oversights and careless procedures that allowed
the infections to spread though the population.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Canadian Red Cross has been forced to declare
bankruptcy and has been removed from the direct collection of
blood. Thousands of Canadians who contracted AIDS from tainted
blood between 1986 and 1990 and their families have already been
compensated by the government. Thousands more who have hepatitis C
or who were infected before 1986 are demanding government
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The prisons were not the only suspected source of tainted blood
but the disclosure that suspect blood from American inmates had
infiltrated Canada has stirred outrage here since it was first
revealed during hearings by the blood panel in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   According to the panel's final report, blood plasma that never
should have been collected from certain inmates at the Cummins
prison at Grady, Ark., was shipped to Canada in 1983 even though
all American blood processors by then refused to accept prison
blood products.
</P>
<P>
   John Byus, administrator of medical services for the Arkansas
prison for 21 years, said there is no question the plasma should
never have been collected from the inmates who had tested positive
for hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he does not think that Arkansas is responsible for
what happened in Canada. ``No I don't think that we have any
involvement,'' he said. ``But do I feel like we did anything wrong?
Yes, there were errors.'' Arkansas had one of the largest plasma
collection programs of any prison system in the United States,
producing 300 to 500 units of plasma every weekend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting plasma is more complicated than collecting whole
blood. A unit of blood drawn from a donor is put into a centrifuge.
The plasma then is spun off, leaving the rest to be returned to the
donor. The plasma is used to manufacture various products,
including the clotting factor that hemophiliacs need because of a
deficiency caused by their disease.
</P>
<P>
   Byus said the Arkansas plasma collection program, which
continued until 1994, was a way for inmates to earn from $7 to $10
for each donation. But Food and Drug Administration inspectors
regularly recorded problems with the way the program was handled.
And despite controls, inmates who should have been prevented from
taking part were accepted, probably because they bribed or offered
favors to other inmates who administered the program, Byus said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, before a definitive test to detect the AIDS
virus was available, the presence of hepatitis B was considered a
strong indicator of AIDS. The prison regularly sold plasma to
Continental Pharma Cryosan Inc., a blood broker in Montreal that
sold blood products around the world. At least 72 units of
questionable plasma collected from five Arkansas inmates in 1982
and 1983 were sold to the Montreal company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
