<HEADLINE>
MATHIS USES SPOTLIGHT TO REVEAL PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Terance Mathis used the
Super Bowl stage to reveal his past problems with alcohol. Mathis
said he feels better after speaking openly about his drinking for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to open up that closet door and let that demon run
out,'' Mathis said. ``I was not a alcoholic. I had a drinking
problem. Only three or four people knew about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, who surprised his teammates with the admission, said he
decided to get help and come clean because of his obligation as a
role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want some kid to see me drinking and he starts to do
it and something bad happens,'' Mathis said. Last stop for Reeves
Atlanta coach Dan Reeves says he isn't sure how much longer he will
coach but says the Falcons are his last team.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do I want to coach? It really hasn't crossed my
mind,'' said Reeves, 55, who was an assistant with the Cowboys
before head coaching stops in Denver and New York before Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved one time in 28 years \RDallas to Denver\S. And I've
moved twice in the last six years \RDenver to New York and New York
to Atlanta\S. I'm not moving again. So how many more years... I
don't know. But my wife won't go with me if we move again. So I'm
not planning on leaving her. This will be the last place I go.''
INJURY UPDATE Falcons defensive end Lester Archambeau (ankle) and
fullback/tight end Brian Kozlowski (ankle) practiced Wednesday and
Thursday for the first time since the NFC Championship Game and are
expected to play Sunday in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Archambeau led the Falcons with 10 sacks, and Kozlowski has been
running back Jamal Anderson's lead blocker since starting fullback
Bob Christian injured his knee with two games left in the regular
season. HAPPY WITH CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges Reeves faced when he came to
Atlanta two seasons ago was revamping the Falcons' offense after
seven years of using versions of the run and shoot under the
direction of offensive coordinator-turned-head coach June Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons players say they welcomed the change. Some offensive
players said the run and shoot wasn't physical enough, and
defensive players said it was useless to practice against because
they weren't going to face it on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could probably play 475 years in the run and shoot,''
offensive tackle Bob Whitfield said. ``I never had to hit anybody.
Now, we are pounding every play. Everything is real aggressive, a
more powerful game.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chuck Smith, who was suspended for the final game
of the 1996 season because he said the Falcons needed a coach that
kept the defense in mind, is happy as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that I played all those years in the
run and shoot, and we never practiced against a tight end,'' Smith
said. ``That's why you finish last in run defense. No one else puts
five receivers out there every down.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
