<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MOSS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK BUYING, SELLING SAID HEALTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ America Online bought Netscape. Exxon merged
with Mobil. And the horse racing industry is getting in on the
feeding frenzy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs just paid $86 million to acquire Calder Race
Course in Miami. Six days earlier, an unlikely partnership of
gambling interests that included Keeneland Race Course paid about
$45 million for Turfway Park. In November, Frank Stronach's Magna
International Corp. bought Santa Anita for $126 million. Also last
year, Call Now Inc., which operates Retama Park, signed an
agreement to purchase Louisiana Downs, Remington Park and
Thistledown from the DeBartolo Corporation, then apparently
couldn't come up with the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Considered poison as recently as two years ago, racetracks
suddenly seem almost as popular as Internet stock.
</P>
<P>
   Or are they?
</P>
<P>
   The buyers mentioned above were already heavily involved in the
horse business, so it isn't as if AT&AMP;T or Microsoft suddenly
decided racetracks are a blue-chip investment. Also, remember that
wherever there is a buyer, there often is a seller who believes the
time is right to get out.
</P>
<P>
   The opinionated Stronach owns more racehorses than perhaps
anyone in the world, other than a couple of sheiks, and he
desperately wants to show the industry how a track should be run.
But when he bought Santa Anita, the stock price of his Magna
International faltered at the news.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs is a publicly traded corporation, thus is under
continual pressure from stockholders to show growth. Also last
year, the Louisville, Ky., track, which is the home of the Kentucky
Derby, bought Ellis Park in Henderson, Ky. Many in the racing
industry believe that in its haste to expand, Churchill paid too
much for Calder.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one impartial observer believes the recent flurry
of track sales is a sign that the beleaguered sport has turned the
corner: outspoken Jerry Carroll, the real estate entrepreneur who
bought run-down Turfway Park (then called Latonia) in 1986 and sold
it this month for a huge profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime tracks like that are selling, the industry is good,''
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though things may be for sale, if those things are bad,
nobody wants to buy them. These are not foreclosure sales. Every
one of these racetracks is making a profit. In that kind of
climate, selling is good, not bad. That's called business.''
</P>
<P>
   The bartering of racetracks probably isn't over with, either.
Churchill Downs, which used up most of its $100 million credit line
to buy Calder and has also been rumored to be interested in
Gulfstream Park and Fair Grounds, has indicated it is planning to
go back to the bank for more money to buy other tracks.
Stockholders love that kind of talk. Last week, news surfaced that
Stronach is considering buying Bay Meadows racetrack near San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Much more of this, and we'll need a program to identify not just
the owners of the horses, but the owners of the tracks they are
running at. SPOTLIGHT Gone are the times when Oaklawn Park housed
the stables of trainers such as D. Wayne Lukas, Shug McGaughey,
Bill Mott, Frank Brothers and Bobby Barnett. And Pat Day is riding
at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   The day-to-day racing quality continues to erode, but although
Oaklawn is no longer booming, it hasn't gone bust, either.
</P>
<P>
   As the Hot Springs, Ark., track opens today for a 52-day season,
enough of its faithful horsemen have remained to ensure some
interesting races.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lynn Whiting, who saddled Lil E. Tee to win the
1992 Kentucky Derby, is still based at Oaklawn. So is owner John Ed
Anthony, an Arkansan formerly of Loblolly Stable fame, who has
rebuilt a 13-horse string with trainer Don Von Hemel.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers Kenny Smith, Donnie Von Hemel, Pete Vestal, Joe
Petalino and Cole Norman win races wherever they go. Jim Gaston
tied for Lone Star Park's training championship last summer. Jack
Van Berg returns after an absence, and Bob Holthus has collected
more Oaklawn titles than any active trainer. Leading jockeys at
Oaklawn are again expected to be Tim Doocy, Calvin Borel, Don
Pettinger, Jon Court, James Lopez and Carlos Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Albarado is now based at Fair Grounds, but will ride at
Oaklawn today for the mount on The Happy Hopper, favored in the
Dixie Belle Stakes for 3-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Racing at Oaklawn will be conducted on a Wednesday-Sunday
schedule, with a post time of 1:30 p.m. on weekdays and Sundays,
and 1 p.m. on Saturdays. This Sunday, the track has a special Super
Bowl post time of 1 p.m.
SERIES PILOT Silver Charm helps kick off the new NTRA Champions on
Fox series tomorrow when he runs in the $500,000 Donn Handicap in
his first visit to Miami-area Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old will be a heavy favorite in the 11-8-mile race.
But even before the gates open, he has received a test. The Donn
attracted 12 entrants _ a surprise to officials who expected fewer
_ and Silver Charm drew the far outside post position.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys already got me here ... I can't go back now,''
quipped trainer Bob Baffert when informed of Silver Charm's post.
``Gary \RStevens\S is a great rider. He'll figure something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible upsetters are Puerto Madero, Frisk Me Now,
Behrens and Texas Mile winner Littlebitlively, who nearly defeated
Silver Charm at Churchill Downs in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Donn will be televised live on Fox Network from 3 to 4
p.m.The national series for older horses consists of 11 races.
ANSWERING THE BELL Answer Lively returns to action in tomorrow's
$100,000 Lecomte Handicap at Fair Grounds, his first start since
winning the Nov. 7 Breeders' Cup Juvenile. The prospect of running
against the likely 2-year-old champion of 1998 didn't scare away
competition: 14 horses were entered in the 1-mile stakes. The
3-year-old colt, owned by John Franks of Shreveport, drew post No.
11 and will be ridden by Robbie Albarado, because Jerry Bailey is
staying in Florida to ride Sir Bear in the Donn. THE ACID TEST
Undefeated 3-year-old speedball Bet Me Best will finally be tested
against top-class competition Sunday in Gulfstream's seven-furlong
Hutcheson Stakes. Also expected to run are Texas Glitter and Cat
Thief. Bet Me Best was purchased privately last month by a
partnership headed by Houston-owned Prestonwood Farm. INAUSPICIOUS
START Texas apprentice jockey sensation Jeremy Beasley shifted his
tack last week to New York's wintry Aqueduct, picked up a winner in
his fifth mount, and now is sitting out a seven-day suspension for
careless riding. He is scheduled to resume riding Monday. ANOTHER
COMEBACK Jockey Mike Smith, 33, who hasn't ridden since suffering
fractured vertebrae in an Aug. 31 spill at Saratoga, is scheduled
to make his comeback aboard Truluck in the Donn. Actually, his
first mount will be one race earlier, when he is scheduled to ride
Close Up in an allowance sprint. TEXAS CELEBRATION Michael
Dickinson, who saddled Da Hoss to win last year's Breeders' Cup
Mile in one of the finest training accomplishments in racing
history, is scheduled to be a featured speaker tomorrow night at
the Texas Thoroughbred Association's annual meeting and awards
banquet in Austin.
</P>
</TEXT>
