<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOUTH THAT MADE MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Thirty-three years later, and one thing never changes
about Super Bowl week. A national media army, which grows larger
and less-organized each January, descends upon the host city,
everyone clutching the same set of marching orders.
</P>
<P>
   Find a theme.
</P>
<P>
   And if that fails, which it usually does, then invent a theme.
Even if you have to make it all up.
</P>
<P>
   But just a week ago, this particular edition of the Super Bowl
had the makings of a journalistic dunk. That whole ``Denver Thing''
involving Elway-Shanahan-Reeves was the media equivalent of a fat
batting-practice pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the dunk died, as if it was slammed too hard off
the back-iron. And our batting practice was rained out.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves stopped talking about his nasty Denver memories. John
Elway and Mike Shanahan never wanted to start in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   So then, what's the theme?
</P>
<P>
   Even though bad-blood talk can be muzzled by the characters,
it's obviously still there. One Denver newspaper columnist is
openly predicting a 50-something-to-nine victory for the Broncos,
apparently because Shanahan has a burning-hunk-of-dislike for
Reeves and won't hesitate to run it up on the former boss who fired
him for being disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   But without verbal fire-feeding, this much-anticipated theme has
basically vanished this week.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves us with the game itself, and frankly, it's a nice
consolation prize, at least in this opinion. The game itself will
be a good one, well-worth all the action stoppage for commercial
messages.
</P>
<P>
   But no Super Bowl game _ even the rare competitive, exciting and
well-played affair _ has ever saved Super Bowl week, which is
totally apart from the actual football. At least in the media
pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I hereby bestow upon Denver's Shannon Sharpe the
highest honor this country's sports media can offer: The Medal of
Mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Super Bowl weeks, this one has been lowered
to a last resort: listening to the players talk.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe arrived here with a reputation for being one of the best
talkers in the game, but to his credit, the man has outdone
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy from small-town Georgia and small-college Georgia
(Savannah State) who _ again, personal opinion _ has the best
combination of mouth and game ever seen in one of these Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him. Sharpe will tell you he's Hall-of-Fame bound because of
what he does at tight end, being both a big-yardage receiver and a
blocker. Even more important, however, is how he saved this Super
Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe was verbally sharp a year ago in San Diego _ his first
Super Bowl _ but the Broncos were considered so outclassed, no one
paid much attention to him. Until after the game, that is, when
Denver had sprung the large upset on the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   In a role reversal here, with Denver being the favorite over
Atlanta, Sharpe's mouth was under much more intense pressure. He
knew he would be on the media's Most Wanted list. He knew he was
expected to deliver. Tongue, don't fail me now.
</P>
<P>
   Like a true champion, Sharpe has become the Sultan of Sound
Bite. He has, in this one week, established himself as a talking
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   But how did it all begin?
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe warms to the question quickly. Elementary school, he
says. Glennville, Ga. A speech class.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy named Johnny was reading, and the teacher said, ``No,
student, don't you help him. Let me help him.'' She wanted him to
sound the words out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnny began stumbling badly over a word he couldn't
pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, it sounds like?'' Sharpe said the teacher told Johnny.
``Sounds like?'' she asked again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said, ``it sounds like Johnny can't read,'' Sharpe
recalled, proudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the teacher said, ``Shannon Sharpe, you get out of the
class. Get out of class.''
</P>
<P>
   But right then, on his way to the principal's office, a legend
was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a good talker... I'm a great talker,'' Sharpe noted,
``because I do it so often. I think if you do something well enough
and often enough, you become great at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the great ones always worked hard on their
``game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I'd get in front of the mirror for 20
minutes every night,'' he said. ``I'd talk to myself. I'd ask
questions, answer questions and just talk in general. I've kind of
perfected it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not kind of. The Medal of Mouth stands for ultimate perfection.
The best here. The best ever. And no matter if Denver makes another
Super Bowl, the NFL should bring back Shannon Sharpe every January.
He can always be the man who saved Super Bowl week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
