<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS' TALK ABOUT KILLINGS INTERCEPTED, U.S. SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American officials said on Thursday that
conversations among senior Serbian officials about a massacre of 45
civilians in Kosovo were intercepted and that this underscored the
need for an international war crimes investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The killings of those ethnic Albanians in the village of Racak
two weeks ago sparked international outrage and galvanized efforts
to try to impose an agreement on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The intercepted conversations are confirmation that Serb
officials ordered an attack on Racak, the officials said. The
attack was presumed to be in revenge for the killing of four men
from Serbian forces. But the conversations are not conclusive on
the question of whether senior Serbian political and military
officials ordered the killings of the civilians, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a smoking gun,'' one senior American official
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Serbs ordered an attack on Racak,'' he said. ``We
still don't know about the massacre. We need to have a full
independent investigation into the massacre'' by a U.N. war crimes
tribunal, which could determine the role of senior officials in
Belgrade in the killings, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military and intelligence agencies have seen transcripts of
the telephone conversations among senior Serb officials, which were
intercepted by Western military intelligence services during and
after the military operation in Racak. They show Serb leaders,
including the deputy prime minister, Nikola Sainovic, and a senior
Interior Ministry official, Sreten Lukic, discussing the political
implications of the killings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the intercepted conversations was first
reported by The Los Angeles Times and The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   While the intercepted conversations suggest plans for a
political cover-up of a military massacre, there is still some
disagreement among American officials as to whether ``rogue
elements'' killed the civilians without orders from above, one
American official said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief U.N. war crimes investigator, Louise Arbour, has been
blocked by Serb officials in her attempts to reach Racak. In
Strasbourg, France, on Thursday, she said that she would keep
trying to ``find out the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
