<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYMNAST-MOCEANU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GYMNAST MOVES FROM TEXAS TO FLORIDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Hoping to put family turmoil behind her and focus on
the 2000 Olympics, gymnast Dominique Moceanu has moved from Houston
to Orlando, Fla., to resume intensive training.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's happy there,'' her attorney, Ellen Yarrell said
Thursday. ``Her No. 1 priority is training for the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said Dominique moved Sunday to be reunited with her
former coach, Luminita Miscenco, 26, whom Dominique credited with
reviving her career last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Olympics will be in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Miscenco left Houston after police told Dominique on Nov. 13
they were investigating allegations that Dominique's father
negotiated with a hit man to kill Miscenco and another friend of
Dominique's.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu has denied involvement in such a plot, but he
took the Fifth Amendment to avoid self-incrimination when asked
about it in court in December. Police say the investigation is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Miscenco and the other friend, Brian Huggins, 32, helped
Dominique run away from her parents' Houston-area home Oct. 17.
Dumitru has said Miscenco and Huggins ``brainwashed'' his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 9, Harris County Family Law Judge John Montgomery
granted a protective order to keep her father away from her for a
year. Yarrell said she will ask a Florida court to issue the same
order there.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said Dominique will train for free at an Orlando gym
owned by Rita Brown, who also owns a gym in Katy, Texas, where
Dominique resumed training earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said Dumitru Moceanu plans to close in early February
the 70,000-square-foot Moceanu gym in Houston that was built with
money from Dominique's trust fund. The gym has floundered
financially without Dominique's presence, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hopes ``common sense will prevail'' and Dumitru
Moceanu ``will not attempt to disrupt Dominique's training.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone Thursday, Dominique's mother, Camelia, said
``no comment.'' She said her husband also did not want to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Moceanus' attorney Katherine Scardino confirmed that the
gym, which she has said cost $2 million, cannot survive without its
star attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main draw was Dominique, and she knew that,'' Scardino
said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney said she is unsure what will happen to the gym and
said there is a chance the parents will declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said if the gym closes, it could create some legal
issues over Dominique's trust fund because it is liable to repay a
bank loan for the property and building.
</P>
<P>
   She said the bank has been cooperating with Dominique, but it
might be in her interest to try to hire someone to keep the gym
running.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu owns 100 percent of the company that runs the
gym, Moceanu Gymnastics Inc., so he is within his rights to shut it
down, Yarrell said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said he has been selling expensive gym equipment
and that would be a violation of the loan agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said she ``keeps hearing'' that Dumitru Moceanu is
selling off gym equipment, but there is no evidence of it.
</P>
<P>
   She said the parents plan to stay in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique has said she believes her parents bought their home
and other personal items with her money. Yarrell said under Texas
law, the parents had a right to do whatever they wanted with
Dominique's money before the trust fund was set up in 1996. After
that, all her money was supposed to go to the trust fund, which she
does not have access to until she turns 35.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu has said all of Dominique's money went into the
gym, which she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrell said Dumitru Moceanu still has not provided the
financial records she has requested and a hearing will be held
Monday to try to depose him on those records. No lawsuit has been
filed on the financial matters, but Texas law permits depositions
before lawsuits are filed.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique's parents were gymnasts on the Romanian national team
before defecting to the United States. Dominique was born in
Hollywood, Calif., in 1981 and started gymnastics training at age
3. The family moved to the Houston area in 1990 so Dominique could
train with famed coach Bela Karolyi, also a Romanian immigrant, who
had trained Nadia Comaneci and Mary Lou Retton.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique, 17, sued her parents Oct. 19 to be declared a legal
adult. She said her parents had squandered her money and ruined her
childhood, and she needed to be declared an adult to get an
accounting of her money and live her own life.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, then 14, was the youngest member of the gold-winning
U.S. women's gymnastics team in the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After a growth spurt that saw her go from about 4-foot-4 to
5-foot-2, Dominique did not fare well in competitions after the
Olympics until she hired Miscenco as coach. In August, Dominique
was the first non-Russian to win the all-around competition in the
Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
