<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON GANG EXPERTS AND MEMBERS ON WITNESS LIST IN JASPER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Prison gang experts and members are among the
witnesses subpoenaed for the capital murder trial of a white man
accused in the brutal dragging death of a black man last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys said the newest subpoenas in the trial of John
William ``Bill'' King, 24, may indicate prosecutors intend to try
to prove that King planned to commit a racially motivated crime
while he was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to testify to helpful things,''
said court-appointed defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs.
</P>
<P>
   King, his prison cellmate, Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, and
former home-town buddy Shawn Allen Berry, 23, are accused of
chaining James Byrd Jr., 49, to the back of a pickup and dragging
him almost three miles along back country roads early June 7.
Brewer and Berry will be tried later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Bill King has had an idea of racial violence for a
long time,'' Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said
Thursday. ``As for if he planned this will be for a jury to
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gray said he doesn't plan to call prisoners Roy Lee Birnbaum
and Michael Lee Mahan to the witness stand because their prison
records may make their testimony suspect. He wouldn't say if Texas
prison system gang expert Sammy Buentello or William Knox, a
nationally-known expert on gangs, will testify.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum, 30, is an Aryan Brotherhood member serving a prison
term for burglary. Gray said Birnbaum, who has the prison nickname
``Dirtball,'' is a prison tattoo artist who drew some of the racist
tattoos on King's body while he was in prison between 1995 and
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan, 36, is serving a term for escape and aggravated assault
of a police officer. Identified as a member of the Aryan Circle, he
listed King and Brewer as prison enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the witness list are two other men who apparently knew
King in prison. The list also includes numerous law enforcement
agents, acquaintances of King, his girlfriend, Byrd's sister, the
wrecker drivers who towed Berry's truck after he was arrested and
the man who said he saw Byrd riding in the back of the pickup on
the night of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in the trial is expected to begin Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers continued Thursday to talk to potential jurors in an
attempt to find 46 qualified jurors from a pool of 122. The tally
rose Thursday to 20, including five blacks. Each side will be able
to strike 16 names from the shorter list. The first dozen jurors
not struck will be on King's jury and the next two will serve as
alternates.
</P>
<P>
   Among the jurors qualified for the pool Thursday was a former
private prison guard who said her first husband was a member of the
Aryan Brotherhood who was imprisoned for kidnapping her. Officials
said she and her children were being held in a rural area next to
an open grave when lawmen rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is currently married to another prison inmate she
met while working at a private prison in Newton. She said her
husband is serving a term for murder from Hawaii. ``It was
self-defense,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 10 potential jurors excused from service Thursday was
a middle-aged woman who said she couldn't impose the death penalty
for King because she knows and respects King's father, Ronald, too
much. ``Mr. King has done a lot for my family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King, sitting in a wheelchair and breathing bottled
oxygen, attended the opening day of the trial Monday, but hasn't
returned. The woman said his son's incarceration has hurt the elder
King's fragile medical condition. ``It's really broken his heart,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she sat on the witness stand, King, who has been taking notes
throughout the jury selection process, stared intently down at the
table in front of him. He never looked at the woman.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of individual questioning of jurors was so fast
Thursday that Cribbs quipped that he plans to tell judges in the
courts of Beaumont, his home town, that they work too slow. It is
common there, he said, to question about eight jurors a day in
capital cases. Lawyers in King's trial questioned 17 jurors
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that they might not be able to get enough jurors out of
the original pool of 122, state District Judge Joe Bob Golden had
earlier said he might also use jurors subpoenaed for Feb. 1. Jurors
in that group were notified Thursday that they won't be needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
