<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval ends day with 65 strokes
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was no 59 for David Duval on Thursday in the
first round of the Phoenix Open.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he used 65 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 holes.
</P>
<P>
   With early morning temperatures of 35 degrees causing a one-hour
frost delay Thursday at the TPC at Scottsdale, 45 players were
unable to finish before darkness. Among them: Duval, who is 2 over
par through 16 holes; and Tiger Woods, who is 2 over through 14
holes.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 birdies and an eagle last week in his stunning 59 to
win the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, Duval actually made a few
mistakes Thursday. In windy conditions that were knocking down
shots with regularity and quickening the greens, Duval bogeyed his
final two holes, the 15th and 16th, before darkness in the desert
suspended play.
</P>
<P>
   Weather permitting, 15 threesomes will attempt to finish first
rounds Friday morning, then begin the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard is the first-day leader with a 4-under 67 and
stands one shot ahead of Paul Azinger, who had a 68. Former Georgia
player Franklin Langham shot a 1-under 70 and trails by three.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, 27, the former four-time All-American from Georgia Tech,
has won his first two events of the PGA Tour season and already
passed $1 million in earnings. Through his first eight rounds of
the season he stood 52-under par.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
