<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bystanders derail carjacking
 &HT;    By Brian Gaar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Bystanders Thursday slashed the tires of a
suspected
</P>
<P>
   robber's getaway car outside a Subway restaurant, chased down
the
</P>
<P>
   escaping man and held him until Waco police arrived, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, a 41-year-old Woodway man was arrested by Waco
police in
</P>
<P>
   connection with the robbery of the restaurant at 1020 S. Fifth
St.,
</P>
<P>
   where Subway shares the building with an Exxon service station.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Exxon employees and other bystanders foiled the
escaping
</P>
<P>
   man's efforts to carjack another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A man entered the store at around 11:40 a.m. and, indicating
that he
</P>
<P>
   had a weapon, demanded money from an employee, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Dryden, the employee confronted by the man, said she
handed him
</P>
<P>
   money, then hit the panic button behind the counter after he
fled.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden said she then shouted a warning to employees working in
the
</P>
<P>
   garage of the Exxon station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a big family,'' Dryden said. ``When somebody yells
help,
</P>
<P>
   everybody runs.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the store, the man's getaway attempt was tripped
up when
</P>
<P>
   he discovered his tires had been slashed, witnesses said, adding
that
</P>
<P>
   employees of the Exxon station had cut the car's tires.
</P>
<P>
   In searching for another car, police said, the man allegedly
went to a
</P>
<P>
   neighboring car and tried to pull a woman out of the driver's
seat. He
</P>
<P>
   allegedly struck her in the face but couldn't remove the woman
because
</P>
<P>
   she was wearing her seatbelt, police said.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, employees of the Exxon station had spotted the man
and
</P>
<P>
   gave chase, along with other bystanders, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The onlookers chased the man away from the car and over to the
</P>
<P>
   intersection of Fourth Street and Dutton Avenue, where they
caught him,
</P>
<P>
   police said.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuers restrained the man until police arrived at 11:43
a.m.,
</P>
<P>
   minutes after receiving the intial call from Subway employees.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was taken to the McLennan County Jail on robbery
charges,
</P>
<P>
   said Larry Murphy, a Waco Police Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy praised the actions of the citizens who helped stop the
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under the circumstances, it was pretty heroic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Waco police believe the same person may be responsible for the
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday robbery of a Diamond Shamrock store in Waco, said Sgt.
Dennis
</P>
<P>
   Kidwell, a Waco police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police are also investigating the possibility that the Thursday
</P>
<P>
   incident may be related to the shooting of an elderly Corsicana
man by
</P>
<P>
   a carjacker on Monday, Kidwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the Subway store were visibly upset after the
robbery, but
</P>
<P>
   happy at the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did get money, but he didn't get much,'' said Dryden. ``He
didn't get
</P>
<P>
   any of us, and that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaar writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
