<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPINOFF-MARKETPLACE-2     01-28 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPINOFF-MARKETPLACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS LOOKING AT SPINNING OFF OF RESEARCH SUBSIDIARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors in Peoplesoft, the large California software company,
opened their mail boxes this month to find a bonus: shares of stock
in Momentum Business Applications, the technology firm's new
subsidiary. True to its name, Momentum's stock almost doubled in
its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   But the new company, which shares office space with Peoplesoft,
has little more than a former Peoplesoft executive and $250 million
of Peoplesoft's cash. And anyone reading deep into the company's
documents will learn that Momentum expects significant losses as it
pays for the research that Peoplesoft wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   The basic concept, of creating a new company for research and
then spinning much of it off to shareholders but retaining some
control, has been used in many industries in an attempt to improve
the bottom line. Biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies,
including Allergan Inc. and the Alza Corp. began setting up such
research companies several years ago. Expanding on their success,
investment bankers are now promoting the idea in other industries.
</P>
<P>
   Now the growing popularity of the approach has caught the
attention of federal securities regulators. Jane B. Adams, deputy
chief accountant at the Securities and Exchange Commission, said
that she could not comment on transactions at any specific company
but added that regulators feared that some of the deals could
mislead investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is likely that there are some abusive transactions out
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deals allow companies to transfer research costs to new
affiliates, while bolstering the parents' bottom lines. At times,
the parent companies record large, one-time charges for payments to
the subsidiaries, payments that Wall Street analysts often play
down, saying they mean little to the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adams said that the commission had referred the matter to a
task force at the Financial Accounting Standards Board. That group,
the Emerging Issues Task Force, has authority from federal
regulators to write opinions that force public companies to change
the way they account for certain transactions. For example, the
task force could require companies to disclose many more details of
the research transactions in their financial statements, something
that could diminish the attractiveness of these deals.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board, which is the main body
that sets the nation's accounting rules, has already agreed on a
proposal that would eliminate the loophole in the accounting rules
that the companies have been squeezing through. But that plan still
needs final approval, a process that could take more than a year.
The task force, however, could issue an opinion within months.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what moves, if any, regulators might take
against companies that have already completed these spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Paul A. Brooke, a stock analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, wrote a report about Alza Corp., a
pharmaceutical company based in Palo Alto, Calif. Brooke said that
Alza's stock price was weak on Jan. 7 because of speculation that
regulators were raising questions about the company's accounting
for its research subsidiary, Crescendo Pharmaceuticals. Federal
regulators are reviewing Alza's financial statements as they decide
whether to approve its proposed accounting for a merger with Sequus
Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke said last week that regulators might ask Alza to disclose
more information about its transactions with Crescendo but he did
not expect the two companies to be forced to consolidate their
financial statements or to recombine their operations. Alza's stock
closed Thursday at $45.6875, well off its 52-week high of $54 on
Nov. 23. Crescendo's shares have risen 4.6 percent this year to
close Thursday at $14.25.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Alza said Thursday that company officials were
not immediately available to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft says Momentum allows it to separate the risk of the
research from its core operations and allows shareholders to decide
whether to increase or decrease their own risk.
</P>
<P>
   At Peoplesoft Thursday , Kip Meintzer, who is in charge of
investor relations for Momentum, said that the relationship between
the two companies was clearly described to shareholders in
documents filed with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum is a separate entity,'' Meintzer said. ``Decisions
will be made by Momentum. It just happens that their main business
is from Peoplesoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft, whose earnings have sagged, said in documents filed
with the SEC that it created Momentum so it could spend more on
developing software.
</P>
<P>
   While Peoplesoft employees will create the programs, Momentum
will dip into its $250 million cash fund to pay for the work, and
even chip in an extra 5 percent or more to cover Peoplesoft's
administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum has two classes of shares. Peoplesoft owns all of
Momentum's B shares, which prohibits Momentum from merging,
liquidating or transferring assets without Peoplesoft's consent;
the A shares were distributed to Peoplesoft shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors in Momentum who have read the agreements between
Momentum and Peoplesoft see a payday if the research is fruitful.
Momentum will own any new software that is developed, and
Peoplesoft has an option to buy licenses for the products or to buy
back the portion of Momentum's stock it does not now own.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing requires Peoplesoft to buy back the shares or to pay
Momentum any more money, meaning the stock could become worthless
when Momentum's cash runs out. Peoplesoft has said that the $250
million should cover research for three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Under accounting rules, companies must consolidate their
financial statements with those of any subsidiaries they control.
That requirement is intended to prevent parent companies from
simply shipping more goods to these units or entering into other
transactions simply to make their businesses look stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft and other companies say they are now allowed to keep
separate financial statements because they own less than 50 percent
of their subsidiaries. The Financial Accounting Standards Board,
which sets the nation's accounting rules, has said it plans to
eliminate the 50 percent threshold and look more at the
relationships between the companies to determine the issue of
control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In documents sent to shareholders, Peoplesoft said that Merrill
Lynch, the Wall Street investment firm, had advised the company's
board last year on how to modify transactions done by
pharmaceutical companies to fit its needs. Merrill Lynch is to
receive $2.5 million for its financial advice and for its written
opinion that the deal was fair to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   About two months before the Momentum stock was issued,
Christopher C. Shilakes, a stock analyst at Merrill Lynch, issued a
report that said the Momentum spinoff was ``a positive long-term
move'' for Peoplesoft. Shilakes said that Peoplesoft and Momentum
shareholders would benefit from separate financial statements since
they would be aware of ``the degree of separation of these efforts
and the relative cleanliness of earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Shilakes noted in his report that Merrill Lynch would earn a fee
from the transaction and that a significant portion of the fee was
contingent on the deal's completion.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Momentum's A shares began trading on Jan. 19,
investors _ who may have been attracted by the company's plans to
develop software for use on the Internet _ quickly bid the price up
as high as $25.50. Thursday, the price closed at $11.25, down 25
cents. Stock in Peoplesoft has fallen 60 percent over the last
year, to $22.4375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
