u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-DAMAGE-BOS &LR;      01-28 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-DAMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIAN LEADER TAKES OVER QUAKE RECOVERY EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMENIA, Colombia _ Facing the most urgent test of his five-
month-old administration, President Andres Pastrana personally
intervened Thursday, dispatching thousands of military troops to
restore order to this heavily damaged city and establishing a
dusk-to-dawn curfew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of this earthquake is beyond what we could
imagine,'' Pastrana said during a &UR;  &LR; press conference after walking
through parts of downtown. ``Whoever wants to break the law will be
met with the fullest force of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As people and machinery continued to claw through dusty mounds
of brick and rubble Thursday, the official death toll rose to 881.
Authorities say more than 3,500 are injured. Some 200,000 were left
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to this city of roughly 300,000 people, where
bands of desperate and hungry residents looted stores on Wednesday,
Pastrana ordered 4,000 troops and national police to patrol
streets, and set up roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   A government spokeswoman in Bogata said the president's decision
to visit Armenia with his top emergency and military officials was
heavily influenced by news reports he saw on Wednesday showing
angry mobs tearing down storefront doors and shattering windows.
</P>
<P>
   Without running water or toilets, public health was also
becoming a serious concern.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the curfew, Pastrana banned liquor sales and said
he would announce an economic emergency and could impose a tax to
finance reconstruction in this hard-working heart of Colombia's
coffee country.
</P>
<P>
   To help rescue crews, Pastrana also ordered a moratorium on
traffic throughout the city, except for essential vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers from Miami-Dade County, Fla. recovered six bodies
Thursday from the remnants of a collapsed apartment building in the
south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens, if not hundreds, were still missing and efforts by Red
Cross and other relief workers to take inventory of families and
damaged homes was proceeding slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said 290 tons of humanitarian aid had been sent to the
region, which needs 150 tons of food daily. The military said it
was distributing 120,000 military rations to the hungry, but
officials clearly couldn't cope with the need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food we've gotten is minuscule,'' said John Mairo Cohecha,
mayor of the neighboring town of Calarca.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana called on the world to help, especially with tents and
medicine, but significant international aid was still wanting.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, the United Nations announced pledges of $2.7 million
Thursday, while the US Agency for International Development has
pledged $2 million in initial aid.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Colombians themselves had donated some $1.4 million
for quake relief, and Pastrana's aid organization, the Solidarity
Network, said 10,000 people had donated goods and shipped 190 tons
of supplies to Armenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up to our necks in bureaucracy, and that's what slowing
this up,'' a relief worker, too harried to identify himself, said
at Armenia's Eden Airport, which was bustling with incoming supply
flights Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The aid _ everything from sacks of potatoes to boxes of shampoo
_ was trucked five miles to a warehouse, where it piled up because
there were too few workers and vehicles to get it to stricken
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake is the largest and most serious challege yet to
Pastrana's young presidency. A former television journalist, he was
elected last summer largely on his pledge to reopen peace talks
between the government and leftist rebels. Those talks stalled
earlier this month when rebels demanded the government put an end
to right wing paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's response _ relocating the seat of government to the
disaster area and taking charge of the operation _ is a gambit to
distract attention from the faltering peace talks with the FARC,
says Alfredo Rangel, a Colombian political analyst. ``He's trying
to reduce a little the effect of the problems of the suspension of
the peace dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its densely populated business and residential
districts, Armenia suffered the most extensive damage. More than
half the casualties from the temblor, 544, were from here,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of corpses Thursday remained unidentifed. They have been
collected at a basketball gymnasium on the grounds of the state
university where a temporary morgue has been set up.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of bloated and bruised faces were displayed along a
wall to help relatives identify the unclaimed bodies. Three white
refrigerated trucks held most of the corpses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how much longer we can keep the bodies here.''
said Juan Guillermo Gouzy, 35, a forensic doctor on the scene.
``Maybe we can wait until the weekend, but beyond that something
will have to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Alina Castro, arrived at the gym around midmorning and found the
body of her nephew, Carlos Martinez. She and her adult children
placed the body into a wooden casket _ a gift from the morgue _ and
strapped it to the top of their car.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later the Castro family brought the coffin to Jardinez
Armenia, the local cemetary.
</P>
<P>
   There in a common prayer service a priest sprinkled holy water
on Martinez's and six other caskets. Afterward they quietly carried
the casket to a fresh plot, where he was buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to find him, and give him a respectful goodbye,''
Castro said, while holding her daughter's hand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Kirk Semple contributed to this report from
Bogota. Wire service material was also used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
