u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-BOMB-NYT &LR;      01-28 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB EXPLODES NEAR CAPE TOWN'S MAIN POLICE STATION, WOUNDING 11  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A bomb, the third in five months,
went off in central Cape Town on Thursday, wounding 11 people at
the doors of the city's main police station.
</P>
<P>
   No one took responsibility for the bomb, which the police
tentatively said was a pipe bomb left in a garbage can outside the
Caledon Square station. They said they were questioning two people,
whom they did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the wounded, none of whom were police officers, had
serious burns or shrapnel injuries. Shards from the garbage can
littered the street next to a khaki VW Beetle with holes blown in
it and police cars with their windows shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which took place just after 1 p.m., came one day
after the official announcement of a police plan to return peace to
the Cape Town area, where a three-way conflict pits the police,
criminal gangs and conservative Muslim vigilantes against one
another. The gangs, which are rich with drug money, and the
vigilantes are both based in the huge mixed-race Cape Flats
neighborhoods along the airport highway.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed-race South Africans are of many religions, but hundreds of
thousands are descendants of Malaysian slaves brought here by the
Dutch in the 18th century, and are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The vigilantes, most prominently a Muslim group calling itself
People Against Gangsterism and Drugs, are suspected of setting off
as many as 80 bombs in the last year in an attempt to kill drug
dealers, police officers and moderate Muslim leaders and to damage
synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   They began operations about two years ago and came to wide
public attention when a gang leader was shot dead and set on fire
as he tried to force his way through a crowd demonstrating outside
his house against drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the group has been taken over by hard-liners from an
organization called Qibla, and is thought to have spun off less
secretive groups calling themselves Muslims Against Global
Oppression and Muslims Against Illegitimate Leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They are suspected of two recent blasts on the Victoria &AMP; Alfred
Waterfront, a popular tourist spot. The first exploded in a packed
Planet Hollywood restaurant on Aug. 25, killing two people and
wounding 25.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of those hurt were Britons and South Africans, it
was thought to be aimed at a symbol of the United States, which had
just fired cruise missiles into Afghanistan and Sudan in
retaliation for the bombings of the American embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The second, on Jan. 1, blew up cars outside a theater that was
to show ``The Siege,'' an American film in which the villains are
Muslim terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged in any of the blasts, but the police
said the two bombs and those used against drug dealers and police
substations all had design similarities.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been trying to infiltrate the vigilante group,
with little apparent success. On Jan. 14, Capt. Bennie Lategan, one
of the chief investigators, was shot dead in his car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH29-COX     01-28 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witnesses to appear before Senate, against complaints of
extending impeachment trial
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans muscled through a plan Thursday
that opens the door for Monica Lewinsky to appear before the Senate
in person or in videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Under the GOP framework, President Clinton's impeachment trial
could end by Feb. 12 _ provided the Senate doesn't grant any more
requests for witnesses from either Clinton's defense lawyers or
House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The party line vote, taken just a day after a party line vote to
extend the trial with deposition testimony from three witnesses,
represented a setback for Senate Democrats who pushed an alternate
plan to explicitly exclude videotape testimony or live witnesses on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   On a party line vote, the Senate also defeated a Democratic
amendment that would have dispensed with taking depositions
altogether and moved to closing arguments Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that their plan could lead to a fair and
relatively quick end to the trial, but Democrats said it could lead
to delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their resolution calls for a date certain, but with all sorts
of provision for delay,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), the
Democratic minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Ore.), an architect of the GOP plan, said
he gave the Senate better than even odds of finishing on or before
Feb. 12, the start of the President's Day recess.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors will begin deposing Lewinsky on Monday,
Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan on Tuesday and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal on Wednesday, according to White House spokesman
Jim Kennedy. The agreement calls for the depositions to be
supervised by two senators appointed by Lott and Daschle and
concluded Wednesday. Each deposition will last eight hours, with
four hours for prosecutors and four hours for White House defense
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was not directly involved in any of the back and
forth that led to the trial plan, but communicated some of their
concerns to Daschle throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy condemned the GOP plan for leaving what he called ``trap
doors'' for extending the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans do not have the votes to end this presidency,
but they do have the votes to extend this trial indefinitely,''
said Kennedy. ``The spirit of bipartisanship that has characterized
these proceedings has evaporated, leaving a Republican impeachment
trial in its place.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has not decided whether it will exercise its
right to call witnesses, thereby extending the trial even further,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will not meet again as a court of impeachment until
Feb. 4 while the depositions are taken and senators have an
opportunity to watch the videotapes of the three depositions. White
House lawyers and House prosecutors will also have an opportunity
to resolve objections raised in the depositions during the week
that the court is in recess.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan requires a vote of the Senate to allow any of the
deposition transcripts and videotapes into the impeachment record,
a vote that would in effect make the materials public.
</P>
<P>
   Separate votes would also be required to allow for live
testimony from any of the three witnesses deposed.
</P>
<P>
   The trial plan leaves open the question of whether or not the
Senate will vote to depose additional witnesses. White House
lawyers will have 24 hours after Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal
are deposed to submit a request for their own witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If the House prosecutors want to call additional witnesses, they
will have to submit their request to Lott and Daschle. Daschle said
the agreement as worded required he and Lott to agree on the
witness request, but Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) said
he believed Lott could make a witness request on his own.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the agreement makes it more difficult for the
managers to call more witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to make the case for more witnesses, it's
going to have to be a pretty important need,'' Hatch said. ``I
don't expect any additional witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were clearly upset at the prospect that Lewinsky might
ultimately make her way into the trial, either in person or in
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about live witnesses,'' Daschle said.
``We don't want the spectacle of Monica Lewinsky or any one else''
on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle also argued that Republicans had left open the
possibility that ``salacious material'' would find its way to the
floor of the Senate, despite a pledged by prosecutors to avoid
questioning Lewinsky about the details of her sexual relationship
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy (R-Vt.) said, ``In depositions, lawyers often
go far afield.''
</P>
<P>
   Some moderate Republican senators said videotaping the
depositions might actually reduce the likelihood that Lewinsky or
other witnesses would be called to testify in person.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could vote to play the videotape of the depositions,
rather than call the witnesses themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we want witnesses yet,'' said Sen. Pete
Domenici (R-N.M.). But as for videotaped depositions, he said,
``What's the fear? Let's hear what they have to say, maybe it's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were also upset that the Republican plan did not
explicitly rule out the chance for senators to introduce a
so-called finding of fact motion. Such a motion would say that
Clinton was guilty of the charges as alleged in the articles of
impeachment, but not remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue such a maneuver would be unconstitutional, and
some Republicans have expressed skepticism about such a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Daschle worked throughout the day Thursday to come up
with a mutual agreement that would see the trial to conclusion. But
gaping differences emerged on the question of videotape testimony,
the prospect of live witnesses and the fixing of a firm end date to
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders called off their negotiations in the afternoon and
headed to a vote at about 5:30. The Democratic amendment to
preclude videotape testimony and additional witnesses was defeated
54-44, with Sens. Barbara Mikulski (D-Md.) and Wayne Allard
(R-Colo.) absent.
</P>
<P>
   The second Democratic motion to short circuit the trial and move
to closing arguments was defeated 55-43, with Sen. Russ Feingold
(D-Wis.) voting with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Final passage of the Republican plan prevailed 54 to 44. On this
vote, Feingold voted with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats were quick to characterize the vote as ``the
Republican plan,'' neither party engaged in much overt sniping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody got 100 percent of what they wanted,'' Lott said. ``I'm
smiling. I'm not ranting and raving and .... blasting (Democrats)
for this or that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Chris Dodd (D-Conn.) said,''It's become a partisan
matter. It never should have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Democrats want to end it,'' said Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy (D-Mass.). ``The Republicans want to extend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
