<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CAMPBELL-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESSMAN FEELS CONSTITUENTS' IRE OVER HIS IMPEACHMENT VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (bl) 
By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Rep. Tom Campbell knew his vote to impeach
President Clinton would make some people unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   In December, when he was part of a small group of moderate
Republicans who had not declared which way they would vote, the
majority of the thousands of calls to his office were against
impeachment. His vote to impeach in, Campbell acknowledged then,
might hurt him politically in this traditionally Democratic
district.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Campbell, who was handily re-elected in November in a
district that includes parts of San Jose and the rest of Silicon
Valley, is beginning to see how unhappy people are with him, and
just how much it might hurt.
</P>
<P>
   As he described it, he has been inundated with protest calls and
e-mail, and not just from Democrats. Some local Republicans are
switching parties and organizing to defeat him in 2000, convincing
him that the impeachment vote will be an issue here in the 15th
Congressional District in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition my vote has engendered is by far the most I've
ever received on one vote,'' Campbell said. ``The only vote that
comes near it is when I voted for the Persian Gulf war.''
</P>
<P>
   His situation may be a sign that there is trouble ahead for
other Republican moderates, who are usually in districts with a
high proportion of swing voters. Campbell has long been known as a
political independent who could be relied on to rise above partisan
politics _ voting against Newt Gingrich's re-election as House
speaker, for example. Now, voters who have relied on him in the
past say he bowed to political pressure in what he himself said was
the most important vote he could cast.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable among his angry constituents is Republicans Against
Campbell, made up, thus far, of a core group of 12 professors at
Stanford University, where Campbell is on the law school faculty.
Gerald Fisher, a visiting professor of physics, said the group,
which believes that Republicans have used the president's affair
with Monica Lewinsky as an excuse to try to subvert his
re-election, considered Campbell ``a lame duck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of my colleagues put it, we're his base,'' said Fisher,
who is creating a list of potential contenders for Campbell's House
seat. ``If he has lost the confidence and support of his home base
_ and I don't know anyone who isn't disgusted with him _ then he's
finished.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials of the Democratic Party in Santa Clara County, which
includes a large part of Campbell's district, are a little more
circumspect. But they said that in recent weeks they had been
flooded with calls from Republicans who said they wanted to switch
parties, so many that the Democratic Party is planning ``conversion
registration days'' in front of Campbell's district office as soon
as next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really angry,'' said Steven Preminger, the party
chairman. ``They're not simply angry at the Republicans; they're
angry especially at Tom Campbell because they think that as a
moderate, he paved the way for the president's impeachment by
giving the vote credibility, leading to what Clinton is facing now
in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Campbell, Republican Party officials in the district
(where Democrats hold a 45 percent to 37 percent advantage over
Republicans in party registration ) said they had not seen any
significant backlash against the congressman or the party.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Abbott, treasurer of the Santa Clara County Republican
Party central committee, said he had not noticed a swing in the
party's registration, though the county registrar has reported a
recent drop of 643 Republicans (and 247 Democrats).
</P>
<P>
   ``People are dropped from rolls for all kinds of reasons,''
Abbott said. ``People move. There are deaths. There are all kinds
of reasons. But a switch of that few voters will not affect the
standing that Campbell has in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes are small for a district with a quarter million
registered voters. But interviews with a dozen Republicans in
Campbell's district who have switched parties or plan to suggests
that disenchanted voters will not forget the impeachment come the
next election.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Pinther of San Jose, a 68-year-old retired restaurant owner
and lifelong Republican, said he would like to actively campaign
against Campbell. ``What does `representative' mean, anyway?''
Pinther said. ``Does it mean they represent us? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dumas, 48, a sheet metal worker in Santa Clara who plans
to switch parties before the next election, said he thought the
last straw was when the president was actually impeached. ``I
didn't think it was going to happen,'' Dumas said. ``But now, it
has just dragged on and on. It has reached ludicrous proportions. I
think this is going to be remembered for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Isom, 65, a mother of three in San Jose who said she
comes from a long line of Republicans, voted a straight Democratic
ticket in November ``as a protest'' and switched parties after
Campbell's impeachment vote. ``I've really had it with the
Republicans,'' Ms. Isom said. ``They think that people are going to
forget about this in 2000, but I know I'm not. I've never actively
campaigned, but I think I may. I think all the Republicans should
be voted out and replaced with people who don't just follow the
herd.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the impeachment vote, Campbell enjoyed a reputation as a
true representative of Silicon Valley, where voters tend to be
fiscally conservative but socially progressive. Campbell was one of
only nine Republicans who voted against Gingrich's re-election as
the House speaker in 1996. He has supported civil rights bills that
mandated racial quotas, and a bipartisan campaign finance reform
bill that was killed by Republican House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He was first elected to the House in 1988 in the 12th District,
where he became known as the most liberal Republican from
California. In 1992, he left the House to run for the Senate, lost
in a primary, and was elected to the state Senate. He returned to
the House in the 15th District in 1995 after a special election and
was elected to a full term in 1996. In California, he is most
famous for drafting an initiative (passed as Proposition 198 in
March 1996) that allows voters of any party to vote for the
candidates of their choice in any primary.
</P>
<P>
   Although every Republican in the House voted for Clinton's
impeachment and every Democrat voted against it, Campbell said that
in his case, he was not voting the party line. He voted for
impeachment, he said, because Clinton broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never received one iota of pressure from the Republicans,''
he said. ``All the pressure came from the Democratic side. I got
calls from two Cabinet members, Steve Jobs and Robert DeNiro, all
telling me the White House asked them to call.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he still believed he voted the right way: ``Oh,
absolutely. Without a doubt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
