<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK CUTS OFF LOANS TO 2 BRAZILIAN STATES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The World Bank on Thursday froze
development loans to two Brazilian states that are locked in an
economic war with the central government.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear bid to support the beleaguered government of
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, the lender held up $209
million in development loans for works already in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it was cutting off the states of Minas Gerais and
Rio Grande do Sul for a series of projects, including programs to
improve education, reduce pollution and combat poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Minas Gerais, former Brazilian President Itamar
Franco, triggered the crisis by suspending payments on $13.5
billion of debt to the federal government for 90 days. Olivio
Dutra, governor of Rio Grande do Sul from the opposition Workers
Party, is paying his state's debt into an escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   The two state governments defend their actions by saying that
they inherited deficit-ridden administrations after elections last
October, and that they risk not being able to pay their normal
operating expenses. The challenge of Franco, who has gone from
political ally to foe of Cardoso, set off a wave of defiance by
other governors.
</P>
<P>
   Cristina Menzes, a spokeswoman for Franco, said that state
officials were awaiting a Supreme Court ruling concerning federal
funds that are being withheld from Minas Gerais, and that the bank
had not commented on the World Bank's decision. Dutra could not be
reached for comment, but his office said earlier that it would seek
a judicial ruling to bar the federal government from telling
international agencies that there was a risk of default.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank said the money for projects in both states would
be withheld for 60 days, and would be reviewed if the states
restored direct payments on their debt to the federal government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
