<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS29-CO     01-28 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witnesses to be grilled on past words
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican prosecutors prepared Thursday to
question a trio of witnesses in the impeachment trial of President
Clinton as a dispute raged over whether those witnesses would be
allowed to testify in the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Senators met behind closed doors to settle the growing discord
over whether the prosecutors should be allowed to call former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, presidential confidant Vernon Jordan
and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats sternly oppose live testimony, while the
Republican conference appeared divided on whether live testimony
should be heard after the depositions are taken.
</P>
<P>
   And the Senate is divided along partisan lines over whether to
allow the videotaped depositions to be shown on the floor.
Depositions begin Monday with Lewinsky. Jordan follows on Tuesday
and Blumenthal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say the difference between live testimony and a
videotape of a deposition is immeasurable. They have been lobbying
senators for permission to bring the witnesses to the floor to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   They are now focusing their attention on winning approval for
videotaped depositions to be played on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live testimony from the witness would make the case,'' said
Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R.-Ark.), one of the prosecutors in charge of
the deposition of Vernon Jordan, the presidential confidant and
golfing partner. ``It limits the interaction between the questioner
and the witness. It's a little frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson flew home to Arkansas on Thursday, planning to spend
the weekend with his family and preparing questions for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said he planned to ask Jordan about what he did to
help Lewinsky land a job in New York City after her affair with the
president had gradually come to a close in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most complex area in the obstruction charge,'' said
Hutchinson, a former U.S. attorney. ``I am going through the
transcripts looking for new areas that will be assessed. I want to
present the facts in a way that will tell a story.''
</P>
<P>
   That story will begin with Dec. 19, 1997, the day Lewinsky
received a subpoena to answer questions in a civil lawsuit filed by
Paula Corbin Jones, the former Arkansas state employee who alleged
that the president made an unwanted sexual advance toward her.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, Lewinsky met Jordan and they rode to her attorney's
office. En route, she discussed the subpoena and her job search.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Lewinsky contacted Jordan to discuss the
subpoena. He put her in touch with a private attorney who prepared
her affidavit for the Jones lawsuit. In that affidavit, Lewinsky
denied having a sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson will then go through the subsequent twists and turns
in her job search.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinksy will be questioned by Rep. Ed Bryant (R-Tenn.), a
former U.S. attorney for the Western District of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also flew home Thursday. Before he could attend to his
questions for Lewinsky, he had to deal with the damage caused by a
tornado that ripped through Clarksville, Tenn., last week. Bryant
spent most the afternoon talking to federal officials about
assisting residents and business owners.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewinsky testifies, Bryant is expected to ask her about the
affidavit that she filed in the Jones lawsuit. Specifically, Bryant
will try to use her testimony to rebut the White House lawyers'
defense of the president that he did not lie about never having
``sexual relations'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal will be questioned by Rep. James Rogan (R-Calif.).
Rogan is expected to interview him about what the president said to
him in a private conversation on Jan. 21, 1998, the day the scandal
broke in the media.
</P>
<P>
   In that conversation, according to Blumenthal's earlier
testimony, the president denied having an affair with Lewinsky and
characterized her as a ``stalker.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan is expected to also question Blumenthal about what
Republicans describe as the White House conspiracy to defame
Lewinsky by planting spurious stories about her in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get to the truth. The truth will come from the
witnesses, not the lawyers covering the case,'' said Rogan, a
former state prosecutor and judge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
