<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3101 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT &LR;      01-28 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS APPROVE PLAN FOR FINISHING IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a party line vote, Senate Republicans forced
through a plan on Thursday for finishing President Clinton's
impeachment trial that opens the door for Monica Lewinsky, or her
videotaped image, to appear before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan also keeps alive a proposal to vote on a
finding of facts that the president committed perjury and
obstructed justice, separate from the vote on whether to convict
him and remove him from office. Democrats have called the idea
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic proposal to move directly to a vote on the two
articles of impeachment themselves, was rejected 55-43, with a
single Democrat, Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, opposing the
effort to halt the trial. A Democratic plan that would have barred
display in the Senate of videotaped testimony was also defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden series of showdown votes, which ran virtually along
party lines, came after two days of behind-the-scenes negotiations
failed to produce a bipartisan plan to depose Ms. Lewinsky, Vernon
Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal and bring the trial to an end by Feb.
12.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican trial plan was approved 54-44 after an
alternative Democratic plan was rejected by an identical vote. Two
senators _ Wayne Allard, R-Colo., and Barbara Mikulski, D-Md. _
were absent.
</P>
<P>
   The White House complained bitterly. ``This resolution is
written in a way that leaves the doors wide open to extend this
trial for an indefinite future and on any issues the majority
chooses,'' Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said.
``The Republican majority had a chance today to test the case the
House managers and independent counsel had made and vote up or down
on the articles, and once again they chose to extend the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Threatening that the White House itself would now delay the
process, he said the president's lawyers would prepare for a
vigorous defense, including the possibility of extensive discovery
and defense witnesses. He said the White House would make no
concessions to accelerate the trial and reach a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, insisted,
however, that there was now the ``likelihood'' that the trial could
be finished on Feb. 12 unless ``various and sundry motions
intervene.'' He said, ``That's our goal, and we have set in motion
a process that very likely would get us there.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for depositions to be taken on Monday, Tuesday
and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial will reconvene on Thursday, when it can
take up a motion to receive the videotaped depositions in evidence.
While the Senate can still hear a motion for more witnesses or
evidence to be heard before the Senate, Democrats won the
concession that such a motion can only be made by Lott and Daschle
jointly. That in effect gives the Democrats veto power over any
push by House prosecutors for another round of witnesses. THe White
House is then granted up to 24 hours to decide whether it wants to
propose new evidence or witnesses for a Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   The plan sets Feb. 12 at noon as the target for a final vote on
the articles of impeachment but leaves open the possibility that
the schedule could slip if witnesses are called.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate acted Thursday night only after it had convened and
recessed twice as Republicans and Democrats huddled in party
caucuses and Lott and Daschle handed proposals back and forth.
``We're making progress,'' Lott said at midday. He said the
disputes had narrowed to two or three points which he described
as``very esoteric, legalistic sort of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats called the areas of contention quite serious and
said they were determined to try to block the videotaped
depositions from public view and close off the possibility of
witnesses appearing in the Senate chamber. They were particularly
concerned about Ms. Lewinsky, whose testimony, with investigators
or before the grand jury, recounting the story of her affair with
the president, has never been seen by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about salacious material, material that has no
place on the Senate floor,'' Daschle said. ``We don't need to have
Monica Lewinsky or anyone else talking in the well of the Senate
about these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said the votes of 44 Senate
Democrats in favor of ending the trial indicated that Clinton would
not be convicted. ``So it isn't a question of whether removal or
conviction is on the table any longer, it's whether we're going to
engage in the spectacle of moving this into the public domain and
trying to move public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered that the Democrats were trying to
pre-emptively block the Senate from making Ms. Lewinsky or her
videotaped image public, without even knowing whether she would say
anything that would add to the trial or should be aired. Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, called the stance ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said, ``Videotaping is an additional tool in this modern
era that senators can use to review what the witnesses have to say.
We don't say that it will be used on the floor. We don't prejudge
that. We say that it would be up to the Senate to decide. The
Democrats don't want that to happen, and I don't understand their
alarm about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The other major point of division was over whether to bar the
Senate from considering ``findings of fact'' that Clinton had
committed perjury and obstruction of justice, separate from the
final vote on whether to convict him and remove him from office.
The findings could be approved by 51 senators and would not require
the 67 votes needed to convict the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican left this possibility open while the Democrats
wanted to block it. ``We strongly believe that this notion,''
Daschle said, ``is just not one that may even be constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House spoke out even more strongly against it. ``It
would establish a terrible precdent for the future,'' said James E.
Kennedy, a White House spokesman, ``making it easier for future
congresses to contemplate punishing a president when they disagree
with him or her. In addition it's really a political vehicle to
exact as much punishment of the president without having to meet
the two-thirds requirement for conviction and removal set forth in
the Constitution.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
