<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-AGREEMENT-BOS     01-28 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AGREEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIPARTISANSHIP SLIPS AWAY WITH WITNESS VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As party leaders squabbled, Senator Herbert Kohl
sat alone in the cafeteria late Thursday, sipping coffee and
staring at the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The day had been a complete waste: no bipartisan agreement, no
progress toward peacefully ending the president's impeachment
trial. As the afternoon slipped away, Kohl waited for a 6 p.m. vote
on how the trial would proceed, hoping Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott would compromise with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Then he considered the math.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public wants this over. The final vote is clear,'' said
Kohl, a Wisconsin Democrat. ``But they can do anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Voting strictly along party lines, Republicans won a motion
proposed by Lott to proceed with the impeachment trial, laying down
their own rules for videotaping witness depositions and possibly
showing them on the Senate floor. The vote, which followed another
party-line defeat of a Democratic motion to end the trial, capped a
day of partisan haggling and increasingly bitter negotiations that
signaled what some had feared most: the end of bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the GOP has hit an iceberg and is sinking,'' said
Senator Edward M. Kennedy after the votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a Republican trial,'' agreed Senator Paul Wellstone,
a Democrat of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the differences seemed mostly procedural and
relatively insignificant. The Republicans wanted to videotape the
depositions, whereas the Democrats did not. The GOP wanted to leave
open the possibility of pursuing new evidence if it came along,
while Democrats wanted a fixed end date in place. Nothing in
question, everyone agreed, threatened to change the final outcome
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the votes came about _ at the end of a long day, in
an easy victory for the Republican majority _ left some Democrats
discouraged about their attempts at cooperation across the aisle.
Even as they admitted the votes had been stacked from the start,
some Democrats held them up as further proof of Republican
insistence that the trial continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of working together, and we got where we
got,'' Senator John F. Kerry said curtly after the votes.
</P>
<P>
   That did not preclude bipartisan camaraderie on a personal
level. Immediately after the votes, senators from both parties rode
the underground subway together, chatting, discussing the next
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry stepped into an elevator with Republican Senator John
McCain of Arizona, deep in conversation about running for
president. Republican Senator Charles E. Grassley of Iowa soon
joined them, as did Democratic Senator Joseph R. Biden Jr., of
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just remember, if anybody ever says there's too much
partisanship, that's only within three feet of a camera,'' Grassley
joked. ``When we're together, we agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy made his own attempts at bipartisanship, riding the
underground trolley with Republican Senator Phil Gramm of Texas.
When the pair spotted Republican Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah,
Kennedy slapped Gramm on the back and shouted, ``Orrin, look what
you've missed out on here!''
</P>
<P>
   But the conversations belied the rift that obviously had
developed during the afternoon, as leaders in both parties went
from predicting an eventual agreement to admitting failure with the
party-line votes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle
told the Democratic caucus about his ongoing negotiations with
Lott. Daschle made it clear that he would not budge on certain
points _ allowing the videotaped depositions to be made public or
proceeding without an absolute end date _ and heard support from
other Democrats, several senators said.
</P>
<P>
   Most, including Kohl, left the meeting with the impression both
parties were working toward a bipartisan conclusion. Many Democrats
said they believed Republicans, fearing low approval ratings in the
polls because of the ongoing impeachment trial, wouldn't dare
steamroll the Democrats and lose further public esteem.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans stayed firmly committed to their position.
Throughout the afternoon, several senators said they believed
Democrats were being hypocritical _ insisting on keeping the
depositions secret, for example, after having voted to open
deliberations just days before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, what's partisan is their trying to get this
information out to the public,'' said Hatch. ``These are the same
people who voted for open proceedings. My gosh, it's very
inconsistent, and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Kennedy said he believed the bipartisan spirit
could be restored, particularly in the Senate, and particularly if
the power of the Republican managers from the House could be
removed. He said ``everyone is too committed'' to let the
atmosphere dissolve as it had in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us want fairness. All of us want a conclusion of it,''
Kennedy said. ``Because, I think, the House managers have been
driving the process, we got the outcome we got today.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``It's like a bad movie. We know the ending, but
they insist that we continue running the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one person, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, seemed
comfortable reserving judgment on the motions. Responding to a
question from Hatch about Lott's motion, Rehnquist leaned over to
ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parliamentarian tells me it is never the function of the
chair to interpret a resolution,'' Rehnquist answered. No
objections were raised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
