<HEADLINE>
70.2 RISE ON NASDAQ LEADS GAINS ACROSS THE BOARD
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Buoyed by Intel's fourth split since 1993 and other
evidence of prosperity for high-technology companies, the Nasdaq
stock market rocketed to a gain of nearly 3 percent Thursday,
pacing a broad market rally.
</P>
<P>
   Prices gathered strength throughout the session, exhibiting less
of their recent volatility as investors digested fresh news of a
strong, low-inflation economy, more upbeat earnings reports and
some big takeovers along with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan's latest remarks about valuations.
</P>
<P>
   In comments before the Senate Budget Committee, Greenspan did
not repeat warnings about irrational exuberance but did compare
investing in Internet stocks to playing the lottery. His remarks
did little to dampen enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index, resuming its sharp
advance that now amounts to 13 percent so far this year, climbed
70.20 points, to 2,477.34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Techs are the sector,'' said John Snyder, executive vice
president of John Hancock/Sovereign Investors. ``The feeling among
many people is that if they're underweighted there, they've got to
get in.''
</P>
<P>
   But lesser strength was found across a broad front, reflected in
a hefty 1.53 percent advance for the Wilshire 5000 and a 1.79
percent advance for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which
rose 22.20 points, to 1,265.37.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finished with a gain of 81.10
points, or nearly nine-tenths of 1 percent, though close to half of
the increase was the result of surges in two stocks: AT&AMP;T, up 4|,
to 89 15/16, and J.P. Morgan, up 4 5/16, to 104].
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of good news out there today,'' said Peter
Cardillo, research director at Westfalia Investments. ``We're on
our way to Dow 10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cited among other things government reports of a
surprisingly big jump in orders for durable goods and of contained
employment costs, the latter likely to reassure Federal Reserve
policy-makers, who meet next week, that inflation remains well in
check.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which late Wednesday announced strong earnings
and a stock split, climbed 8 15/16, to 174 7/16, but many other
computer-oriented companies did even better. Yahoo, which said it
was buying Geocities , rose 31~, to 367}; Geocities soared 42\, to
117\. Infoseek rose 12{, to 83 15/16, and Lycos shot up 11|, to
123[. .
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 4~, to 137 3/16, as the company announced a 2-for-1
split and a 50 percent dividend increase.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay, however, slumped 10~, to 292|, as it responded to news
reports about possibly fraudulent items sold by other companies on
its auction site, and Amazon.com eased 2}, to 122~.
</P>
<P>
   The relative sluggishness of the Dow industrials, still only up
1.09 percent in 1999, and other traditional market favorites was
said to reflect their big run-ups over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors may still be around to buy the dips,'' said
Christine Callies, chief strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston.
``But they're clearly having second thoughts about chasing high
valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer stood out in the drug group, rising 5|, to 127 9/16. It
said directors would vote on a 3-for-1 split.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 852.4 million shares changed
hands, with advancing issues holding only a small margin over
declining ones, 1,561 to 1,454. New 52-week lows outnumbered new
highs by 86 to 65.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks rose 3.90 percent in Sao Paulo, 2.48 percent in
Paris and 0.8 percent in Frankfurt. Prices were 3.69 percent lower
in Hong Kong, 0.7 in Tokyo and almost 0.1 percent in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
