</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STODA29-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Value of accurate observation an ageless idea
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The biggest fear among the NFL's front-office suits in
this year of fractured officiating is that a blown call will
determine who wins and who loses Sunday in Super Bowl XXXIII at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Such a circumstance would be unfortunate in any of these
Roman-numeralized extravaganzas, of course, but it would be
especially calamitous after a season dotted by so many significant
mistakes made by the men wearing striped shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the blunders, however, Denver and Atlanta _ teams
with a combined 32-4 record that are, arguably, the league's two
best squads (Minnesota remains in the debate) _ have managed to
advance to the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if the folks in charge of interpreting and enforcing the
rules can, for example, correctly determine what is or isn't a
fumble or what is or isn't a touchdown or what's in-bounds and
what's out-of-bounds . . . well, then maybe no one will have to
worry about second-guessing. Or would this be first-guessing?
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a precious seeing to the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare wrote it, but he was probably dating Gwyneth
Paltrow at the time and it's for sure he had never watched an NFL
game. Even then, though, Bill the Bard was prescient enough to
understand the advantages of instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``To err is human, to forgive divine.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Pope was, apparently, a compassionate sort. But let
him sell the idea to the poor saps who lose when somebody's head is
misidentified as a football. Hey, it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``War begun without good provision of money beforehand for going
through with it is but as a breathing of strength and blast that
will quickly pass away. Coin is the sinews of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois Rabelais was absolutely correct, but only if someone
can call the toss in proper manner so as to begin the combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horse! A horse! My kingdom for a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, again, who must never have understood the value of
a reliable zebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are men in the world who derive as stern an exaltation
from the proximity of disaster and ruin, as others from success.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Winston Churchill might as well have been talking about
flag-happy referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a decision was made, I did not worry about it
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Please meet Harry S. Truman, head linesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``An argument needs no reason, nor a friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   So, circa 580 B.C., did Ibycus efficiently summarize the
relationship between those who play or coach the games and those
who judge them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is natural for man to indulge in the illusions of hope. We
are apt to shut our eyes against a painful truth, and listen to the
song of that siren till she transforms us into beasts . . . are we
disposed to be the number of those who, having eyes, see not, and
having ears, hear not? . . . For my part, whatever anguish of
spirit it may cost, I am willing to know the whole truth; to know
the worst, and to provide for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a concluding reminder, borrowing from Patrick Henry, that
for all their mistakes, officials do usually get things right.
</P>
<P>
   Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
