<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BARR29-COX     01-28 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BARR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr, facing long odds, brings battle to Georgia
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The roaring impeachment process is slowly grinding to
a conclusion, with it all but certain President Clinton will hang
on to his job. U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, perhaps the most ardent foe
Clinton has in Congress, knows this all too well.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Thursday, Barr, an obviously frustrated warrior, made the
media rounds in Atlanta, steadfastly telling all who would listen
that he will continue to fight until he has fired his last legal
cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is making our job virtually impossible to do,''
complained Barr, referring to the Senate's vote Wednesday to limit
the witness list to three. ``It's really frustrating, the lack of
opportunity we're getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting to compare 1868 (when President Andrew
Johnson was impeached) with 1999,'' he said. ``Today's world is
`Let's hurry up. Let's get it done quickly.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barr jetted to Atlanta for a 36-hour respite from Washington
after Senate voting that made it clear the two-thirds vote needed
to remove Clinton is a virtual impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   His rounds Thursday in Atlanta were an attempt to get his gospel
out and practice a little damage control in the wake of the
prodigious spin cycle emanating from the White House. He went from
talk radio to an Internet chat room to CNN's ``Burden of Proof,''
and then finally to a Chamber of Commerce dinner in Cartersville.
He also took some time out to celebrate his wife Geri's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia congressman knows what he's up against. Clinton's
approval ratings hover above 70 percent, while Republicans' have
sunk. Barr was personally rocked when Hustler magazine publisher
Larry Flynt accused Barr of helping a former wife obtain an
abortion, a charge Barr calls ``scurrilous.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr claims his quest has never been to be liked: He's not the
warm-and-fuzzy lovable type, like his nemesis Clinton. Barr's
demeanor _ stern and focused _ rarely changes. His mantra Thursday
was: It's the Constitution, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay attention to the polls. They are absolutely
meaningless,'' said Barr while heading to his Chevy truck with an
NRA sticker and congressional plates. ``The polls exist in sort of
a Never-Never Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr started his rounds with WSB radio talk-show host Neal
Boortz, like-minded in his antipathy toward Clinton. On the Boortz
show, Barr spent 45 minutes preaching to the conservative choir.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, Barr was online for a 75-minute ``Internet town
hall meeting'' on AccessAtlanta, where he personally answered 66
questions. Barr for the past year has plugged in to the chat room
every month to answer questions. He spent the entire time Thursday
hunched over, in shirt-sleeves, pecking at the computer keyboard,
rarely looking up.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, monitors for AccessAtlanta _ which like The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution is owned by Cox Enterprises _ get a couple
hundred questions. On Thursday, they received more than 500 and had
to screen the queries to keep them decent, along a certain thread
and to prevent them from repeating.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't merely toss Barr softballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob, how can you criticize the president's personal life when
you yourself are on your third marriage?'' asked someone identified
as ``just me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is the president has violated federal laws. ... It
has nothing to do with whether he or anyone else is single, married
or divorced. You may see the connection but I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   An equal number of Clinton-bashers were online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriot'' commented: ``It appears to me that the Democratic
senators could easily qualify as jurors in the O.J. Simpson
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good point,'' responded Barr, with a fleeting grin, one of the
few he flashed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Barr admitted to a questioner that Clinton's
removal is ``pretty remote'' given that ``a number of senators have
apparently prejudged his acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   After posing for a photo with the AccessAtlanta staff, Barr
headed to his truck to make a Buckhead lunch with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   His image, repeatedly flashed on the news and talk shows, has
made him something of a celebrity. Several passers-by did
double-takes when they saw him.
</P>
<P>
   At a Wal-Mart in Cobb County on Wednesday night, Barr said, he
was constantly interrupted by fellow shoppers passing on
``attaboys.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was about to get into his truck, a middle-aged man walked
up, slapped Barr's shoulder and said: ``Thank you, keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will,'' said Barr, with another rare smile. ``I will.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
