</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CONFUSING AS FOX CHASES HORSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Silver Charm runs Saturday at Gulfstream Park
near Miami in the Donn Handicap, the first leg of a national series
that marks horse racing's latest attempt to pull in fans through
the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   The series has a lot going for it, including the participation
of the nation's leading active racehorse, the enthusiasm of the Fox
network and the industry support that past efforts missed.
</P>
<P>
   Its weakness is a contrived format that might only confirm the
public's belief that racing is too complicated for anybody without
the study habits of a nuclear engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the name, ``NTRA Champions on Fox'' _ a brand-name
stew that's hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the complex points system that will determine the
series champion.
</P>
<P>
   In most series, points are awarded for high finishes and the
competitor with the most points at the end of the season is the
champion. That's how it worked in the American Championship Racing
Series, which crowned Farma Way in 1991, Strike the Gold in '92 and
Devil His Due in '93 before self-interested tracks killed it.
</P>
<P>
   The National Thoroughbred Racing Association series is not that
simple. Pay attention; we're only going to say this once.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 races, for 3-year-olds and up, are divided into two
groups.
</P>
<P>
   There are five ``Super Series'' races, to be televised on the
Fox network (Channel 11 in Los Angeles): the Donn, the March 6
Santa Anita Handicap, the June 27 Hollywood Gold Cup, the Aug. 1
Whitney at Saratoga, and the Aug. 29 Pacific Classic at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   The six other races are to be shown on Fox Sports Net cable: the
April 3 Oaklawn Handicap, the May 29 Metropolitan Mile at Belmont
Park and Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs, the June 12
Stephen Foster at Churchill Downs, and the July 5 Suburban at
Belmont and Iselin at Monmouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some races are on the same days, but that's not a big
problem because horses aren't expected to run in all 11 anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Points will be 20 for a victory, 12 for second, 8 for third in
the ``Super Series'' races; 10-6-4 in the Oaklawn and Met Mile and
6-4-2 in the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Any horse who sweeps the five ``Super'' races will earn a $5
million bonus automatically.
</P>
<P>
   As for the points, each one is worth $5,000 _ but there's
nothing automatic about it.
</P>
<P>
   To earn any bonus money for his owners, a horse must finish in
the top five in the Pacific Classic. The Pacific Classic winner
will keep 100 percent of his cash, the runner-up 80 percent, the
third horse 60 percent and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Also _ still with us? _ a horse who wins three of the five
``Super'' races gets $500,000. But only if the Pacific Classic is
one of the victories.
</P>
<P>
   Just as a horse could win more than $5 million on top of the
individual race purses, he also could dominate the series and
squander the huge bonus by getting hurt or going off form before
the Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than that apparent inequity, the all-or-nothing emphasis
on the Del Mar race could tempt an owner to run an injured or
fatigued horse in the series finale, risking disaster that could
undermine the benefits of the TV exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The format demonstrates how far the NTRA, beginning its first
full year as the sport's ``league office,'' will go to win the
favor of TV. Without such draconian rules, there would be no
climactic race. Without a climactic race, there would be no Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The network should be happy with the first race. Silver Charm
and jockey Gary Stevens will face 11 horses in the Donn. He'll
start from the far outside in the 1[-mile race and carry 126
pounds, six more than Sir Bear (Jerry Bailey) and Puerto Madero
(Kent Desormeaux).
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the Fox announcers will have time to
explain the rules and show the Donn in the same telecast (1 p.m.
PST). After all, it lasts only an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Only 92 days to go: Contenders for the May 1 Kentucky Derby will
be in action on three fronts this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At Santa Anita: Sunday's Santa Catalina Stakes sends Bob
Baffert's 2-of-2 General Challenge against Bright Valour, Mr. Broad
Blade, Brave Gun, Buck Trout and Light Fingered at 1 1/16 miles.
First post time Sunday is 11 a.m. so the races will end before the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At Gulfstream Park: The swift Texas Glitter, 5-for-5 Bet Me Best
and D. Wayne Lukas-trained Cat Thief head the 7-furlong Hutcheson
Stakes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fair Grounds: Answer Lively, with Louisiana-based Robby
Albarado replacing Jerry Bailey in the saddle, makes Saturday's
1-mile Lecomte Handicap his first start since he won the Breeders'
Cup Juvenile. Bailey rides Sir Bear in the Donn that day.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita's Saturday stakes is the 6-furlong Palos Verdes
Handicap, another chance for 5{-furlong track record holder Kona
Gold to prove he's the fastest sprinter in America, as trainer
Bruce Headley boasts.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie D. countdown: Eddie Delahoussaye won two races Wednesday
at Santa Anita to draw within six of 6,000. He'll be the 14th
jockey to reach that milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye, 47, plans to ride as long as his health holds up
but doesn't expect to get to 7,000. He has battled sinusitis the
past few years and always fought weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year, it's starting to get a little tough,'' he said
recently. ``Your body starts changin' and things start spreadin'.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Alex Solis, 28
wins; David Flores, 19; Kent Desormeaux, Chris McCarron and Gary
Stevens, 17. Trainers: Bob Baffert and Bobby Frankel, 10; Ron
McAnally, 8; Richard Mandella, 7; Wally Dollase, 6. &QL; 
Handicapper's helper: Laffit Pincay, not normally known as a speed
jockey, has more wire-to-wire wins (6) than anybody else at Santa
Anita. Solis, once known for his front-running tactics, has rallied
from sixth or worse to win more races (7) than anybody else. &QL; 
On the stakes' schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $200,000 Palos
Verdes Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 6 furlongs; Sunday, $100,000
Santa Catalina, 3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles. At Gulfstream Park:
$500,000 Donn Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1[ miles; Sunday,
$150,000 Hutcheson, 3-year-olds, 7 furlongs. At the Fair Grounds:
Saturday, $100,000 Lecomte Handicap, 3-year-olds, 1 mile. &QL; 
Mileposts: Not to be outdone by the ``NTRA Champions on Fox''
series, an international committee announced plans for a series
linking races in seven countries. The series would start with the
Dubai World Cup, end with the Hong Kong International, and include
the Canadian International and the Breeders' Cup Classic and Turf.
Needed: a sponsor.... Oaklawn Park's 52-day season opens today. The
Hot Springs, Ark., track was barely touched by last week's storms.
The Oaklawn Handicap is April 3, the Apple Blossom April 9 and the
Arkansas Derby April 10.... Del Mar Futurity winner Worldly Manner,
who's been in Dubai since being purchased by Sheikh Mohammed, will
try to win the May 1 Kentucky Derby without a prep race, a
spokesman was quoted saying in the Daily Racing Form. The whole
thing would be a first.... Gulfstream Park executives vowed to find
out why the official timing system reported inaccurate fractional
times for races earlier in the season.... San Fernando winner Dixie
Dot Com had surgery, as scheduled, to speed healing of a hairline
fracture in his left foreleg.... Malibu winner Run Man Run, fourth
in the San Fernando, will run in the Feb. 6 Strub. A sprint had
been considered.... Classic Cat, the Ohio Derby winner, has
switched trainers, from David Cross to Bob Baffert.... Jockey Emile
Ramsammy broke with agent Vince DeGregory and hired Brian Beach....
Laffit Pincay's streak ended after he rode winners on seven
consecutive Santa Anita cards.... About 20 Japanese reporters were
at Santa Anita to cover Seeking the Pearl's fourth-place finish
behind Stop Traffic in the Santa Monica on Saturday. The filly is
going back to Japan.... Free House, named the state's 1998 champion
older male by the California Thoroughbred Breeders Association, is
scheduled for his 1999 debut in the Feb. 7 San Antonio.... SLM Big
Daddy was voted the quarterhorse world champion for '98, becoming
the breed's first repeat winner since Refrigerator in '93....
Walter Case Jr., 37, was named harness driver of the year for the
third time after winning a record 1,079 races.... Unlucky trainer
Marty Jones has one victory and 15 seconds since Sept. 1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
