A3116 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     01-28 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUPER BOWL TV QUIZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think you know everything there is to know about television's
role in Super Bowl XXXIII? Then take this carefully presented
eight-question quiz.
</P>
<P>
   1. Name the network that by the end of business Sunday will have
aired 80 separate Super Bowl programs spanning 150 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pat Summerall and John Madden will do the play-by-play Sunday
for Fox's game telecast. What other Super Bowl showdown will they
broadcast this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   3. Name the recluse who will lend his voice to a special
post-Super Bowl episode of Fox's ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Who will Madden interview as part of his ``All-Madden
All-Millennium'' special during the pregame show?
</P>
<P>
   5. What network will try to steal away Fox viewers during
halftime?
</P>
<P>
   6. Fox has a promotional arrangement with an ice cream company
in Miami that has vendors giving away washable tattoos of a Fox
personality. Name him.
</P>
<P>
   7. With an estimated 150 million tuning in, and three-fourt5'q$G
</P>
<P>
   No tabular columns defined Y+d during the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   8. Name the number of sportscasters, within three, who will take
part in Fox's (set ital) seven-hour (end ital) pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: 6-8, you cheated. 4-5, you know Stu Nahan. 2-3, you
want to meet Stu Nahan. 0-1, you are Stu Nahan.
</P>
<P>
   Answers: 1, ESPN. The Disneyites will even air a special edition
of ``Monday Night Countdown'' -- on Saturday. 2, Saturday's
Sylvester vs. Tweety showdown on Cartoon Network. Expect a lot of
bams and booms from Madden. 3, Top Fox Rupert Murdoch in a rare
speaking appearance. 4, Vince Lombardi, via special effects.
</P>
<P>
   5, USA will air a live, commercial free, 20-minute WWF title
match beginning as the first half ends. It will have a game clock
so you'll know when to switch back to the football game. 6, Keith
Olbermann. Was covering Monica Lewinsky as bad as having your face
tattooed on someone's rear? 7, Victoria's Secret first quarter ad
which will reveal its new web site. 8, 15 -- Ray Bentley, Terry
Bradshaw, James Brown, Cris Collinsworth, Jerry Glanville, Suzy
Kolber, Howie Long, Ronnie Lott, Bill Maas, John Madden, Matt
Millen, Keith Olbermann, Pam Oliver, Ron Pitts and Pat Summerall.
</P>
<P>
   The point of this is obvious. The Super Bowl has become the
poster child for America's culture of wretched excess, now
synonymous with retailers hanging Christmas decorations before
Thanksgiving dishes are cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for Fox to use the Super Bowl as a branding iron.
It paid for the game and has every right to sell-sell-sell until
the clock gongs. Fox will earn about $150 million in revenue from
the game telecast, and as much as $50 million on its (ital)
seven-hour (end ital) pregame show (beginning at 8 a.m.) Factor in
recognition profit for the network and its Fox Sports News cable
arm, and you have a day worth all of the work.
</P>
<P>
   It's the bandwagoning that is specious. Lacking the game itself,
other TV outlets go into hyperdrive to steal some of the glory,
leading to attempts that are generally more crass than creative.
But then crass is one of TV's founding principals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides letting ESPN and its cousins air 150 hours of Super Bowl
programming, the Disney Channel will air three sports-themed movies
before kickoff starring Christopher Lloyd and Tony Danza.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon has set aside the whole weekend as a sports and game
festival, including NFL stars like Troy Aikman and Brett Favre
lending their voices to an episode of ``Kablam!'' The Golf Channel
will also air a special halftime episode of ``Golf Central.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comedy Channel has its own special tonight, and CBS has a
``Comedy Blitz'' prime time special Saturday featuring comedians,
NFL players and de rigeuer appearances by CBS prime time stars,
like Her Nasalness, Fran Drescher.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial inventory during the Super Bowl has become as
much a party of the show as the game. Fox's 30-second spots sold
out at $1.6 million per, and there will be as many Monday morning
reviews for the ads as there will be for John Elway and Chris
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   American Express has signed on for one 60-second ad in the third
quarter, the finale of a two-month ad tease featuring Jerry
Seinfeld. Visa and Mastercard will also try to impress you. Four
different companies will try to sell you a car.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi's in and Coke's out, much to the consternation of the
Atlanta-based cola company. Budweiser signed on as the exclusive
beer of the Super Bowl and will nine-plus minutes of frogs and
lizards. There will also be a ``Star Wars'' prequel trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Fox admits the seven-hour length of its pregame show is
excessive, but these shows will continue to grow as long as the ad
market shows an interest. It's profitable football muzak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can sell it, I'll produce it,'' said Ed Goren, the
executive producer of Fox Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect a huge part of the audience to watch all seven
hours,'' said Scott Ackerson, the show's producer. ``My mom and dad
might be the only ones who will. But I don't think anyone who does
will consider it a waste of time. I feel bad saying it, but we
actually could use an extra half hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as bad as we feel hearing it.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame highlights differ depending on what you're looking
for. A big 90-minute chunk will be the ``All-Madden, All-Millennium
Team,'' which will have Madden interacting with Lombardi and a
computer-generated game between his All-Millennium team and the
NFL's best current stars.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will also air anniversary retrospectives on Super Bowls
played 30, 20 and 10 years ago. The Super Bowl III piece will
include a Joe Namath interview and look at what that landmark game
did for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   For Super Bowl XIII, ex-Steeler Terry Bradshaw will reminisce
with ex-Cowboy Hollywood Henderson. It was Henderson who launched
Bradshaw's reputation with his infamous ``he couldn't spell cat is
you spotted him the C and the A.'' Foxies had to twist Bradshaw's
arm to do this piece.
</P>
<P>
   For Super Bowl XXIII, Cris Collinsworth will talk with his
former Bengal teammate Stanley Wilson about his shooting heroin and
being arrested the night before the Super Bowl. ``This is a story
the NFL probably isn't going to like,'' said Collinsworth, ``but
it's a big part of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   For the more socially inclined, Fox will offer live music
performances by Ice Cube, Mack 10, the Black Crowes and KIIS in
half-hour chunks, and send ``Beverly Hills 90210'' alum Jason
Priestly on a tour of Miami nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the other end of the Super Bowl as a fan, and a
lot of people Super Bowl parties with the TV on,'' said Madden.
``Is someone going to sit down and watch the whole show? I don't
think so. But what else would you rather have on leading up to the
game?''
</P>
<P>
   The other networks will test that thought with other sporting
events. ESPN2 will air a stock car race, ABC has the last round of
the Senior Skins game and UCLA-Washington basketball. CBS will also
counter with golf (Phoenix Open) and college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   At kickoff, when 75 percent of the country is tuned in, local
outlets will switch to programs as different from football as
possible. KCBS will air ``Charade,'' a Cary Grant-Audrey Hepburn
movie. KABC has a British mystery movie starring Michael Cai.NTLA
runs a ``Saved by the Bell' marathon and TBS has an Andy Griffith
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE SUPER NEWS: Fox is projecting a 45.0 Nielsen rating
for the game ... It will have 30 cameras at its disposal for game
coverage but will take a more-is-less approach to using them. ``The
key to a good broadcast is making those 30 cameras look like 12,''
said director Sandy Grossman ... Madden isn't projecting a winner,
but he does think it will be a high-scoring game. ``If I had to
pick the best team, I'd say the Vikings. That sounds stupid because
they're not here, but they looked like the best team before they
lost to Atlanta.'' ... Madden on the feud between Dan Reeves and
Mike Shanahan: ``It won't have an impact on the game. No one will
be running down the field saying `my coach hates their coach.' ''
... Fox and 68-year-old Pat Summerall blew off retirement
questions, with Summerall, who has two years left on his contract,
saying he plans to do the 2002 Super Bowl ... Howard David and Matt
Millen call Sunday's game for Westwood One/CBS Radio (KNX 1070 and
XTRA 690).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
