<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON29-COLU     01-28 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON29-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tackle has family on his mind
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As he's prepared for Sunday's Super Bowl, Tony Jones has
found himself spending more time on the phone than the football
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver tackle has been nervously calling his wife Kammy back
in Denver at least four or five times a day. He's also made daily
long distance checks on his mom in Royston, Ga., and then, for much
needed respite, he's made the occasional call back to some of the
folks who have long embraced him in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I've got a lot on my mind and I'm not just talking
about the Falcons,'' the 290-pound lineman said of the Broncos'
Super Bowl XXXIII matchup with Atlanta. While his job is to open
holes for running back Terrell Davis and provide protection for
John Elway in what likely will be the quarterback's last game, he
said he feels no pressure: ``Actually, Sunday's game will be three
hours of peace for me. It's kind of an escape. It's after the game
that real life will begin again. The Super Bowl is simple compared
to what I'm facing off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kammy _ who has had nine previous miscarriages _ is pregnant
with twins and has been having another difficult pregnancy. She's
been bedridden nearly a month and wasn't able to make the trip to
Miami until late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I've been calling,'' Jones said Thursday morning.
``I think I should be there with her and our little boy (3-year-old
Tony Jr.) She tells me she's fine, but I'm not sure if she's lying
to me just so I don't worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she could use me back there. Until I came here with the
team, I was being mother, father, the maid and the cook . . . Well,
not really the cook 'less you count getting carry out. We've had
Pizza Hut, Subway and McDonald's. The old Happy Meal boxes been
stacking up. See, growing up, I learned plenty 'bout eating, but
nothing 'bout cookin. My mom took care of all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Mom's ailing, too. Marlene Jones has heart and foot problems
due to diabetes. She had part of a toe removed and until recently
it looked as if she'd lose her foot. In a few weeks, Jones said,
his mother also must undergo open heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the November death of Jones' uncle, a man Tony
said was like an older brother. Although initial reports coming out
of Hartwell, Ga., labeled the death a suicide, Jones said an
investigation is ongoing: ``There are a lot of strange
circumstances. They say he died of a rifle wound at close range,
but people who were there are telling two different stories.
Something's wrong and I promised my mom I'd find out what happened
to her brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's why _ trying to get through all these storms _ I've
been glad to hear from some people in Ohio. All week, I've been
getting calls and cards and letters from Cleveland Browns fans.
They're telling me to hang in there. They're wishing me luck in the
Super Bowl and they're asking me to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Bronco's Pro Bowl left tackle said he wants to end up a
Cleveland Brown again. He played in Cleveland the first eight years
of his career _ until Art Modell moved the team to Baltimore _ and
was a fan favorite. He does, though, have two years left on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to end my career in Cleveland where it all started,''
he said. ``I'd like to retire in front of the Dawg Pound. Taking
nothing away from Denver, but there's no better fans than those
people in the Pound. We could be getting beat to death and they'd
cheer us on. They're the wildest fans I've ever seen. They're
throwing dog biscuits _ and maybe a few D batteries at the other
team _ and they stand up there with no shirts on when it's minus
degrees. There's more fights in the stands than on the field. I'm
telling you, if you can't play football for fans like that, you
can't play anywhere. That's why I want to go back. That town was
good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field . . . and off.
</P>
<P>
   Denver might be giving him his chance at a second straight Super
Bowl ring, but Cleveland is where he found romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a bookstore and knocked a rack of books over on the
foot of Kammy's aunt,'' he said with a laugh. ``She said, `I got a
beautiful niece I'd like you to meet.' Well, I wasn't falling for
that one, but she eventually got her niece in touch with me and we
set up a blind date.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a pairing. Kammy was from East Cleveland, Jones
from tiny Royston, Ga., a town, he said, that has three stop
lights, a park and a street named after him and his family's
chickens picking through the dirt in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time Kammy saw that, she said, `Lord have mercy!
They're loose.' I said, `Don't be surprised This is the South.
You're liable to see anything in the front yard.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Though he came from humble beginnings, Jones, at the urging of
his wife _ they married on Valentines Day 1992 _ has made a
sartorial splash in the NFL. ``I'm a flashy dresser,'' he said.
``I've got every color suit. There's a pink one (jacket 56-long,
pants 44 waist) with pink shoes (size 14). I've got a lime green
suit and matching derby. There's a purple Barney suit, a bright red
one and even one with Denver colors . . . People thought I was the
door man in that one.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other extravagance he wears is a tattoo on his right
leg. ``It's my family tree,'' he said pointing to branches held
together with red ink hearts and blue padlocks. ``A couple of years
ago, I had four hearts put on here. One's got my wife's name in it,
the other, my son's and two are open. Now my wife's pregnant with
twins.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly quieted at the thought: ``I don't want to dwell on
it. You always worry about something bad happening. I'm so scared
right now. I worry about my wife. For a while I've even wrestled
with just quitting football. I don't want to be off at a game and
something happens at home or with my mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I just want to see everybody here. I want to be
able to see for myself that my wife's OK. Same with my mom (who is
flying in today). I want to hug 'em both.''
</P>
<P>
   As he thought about each embrace, he began to smile:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell you this before, but my wife and I almost didn't
meet. The first time her aunt had her call me, I asked her to
describe herself. She said she was not an attractive girl, so I
started thinking she was ugly and kept avoiding her. Then one day
we agreed to meet. I was gonna hide at first, but then I saw this
chick coming up the walk. I went `Ho-le-o!' She was beautiful. I
was supposed to go back to Georgia the next day, but I cancelled
everything and we just hit it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you now what? She thought I was the perfect guy. She
thought we made a good couple. She said, `Where you been all my
life, big boy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was grinning now. ``I told her not to worry, I'd never be
far away again.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why he held that small cell phone in his big,
battle-scarred hand
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Archdeacon is a columnist for the Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
