NYT-01-28-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OFFICIATING     01-28 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OFFICIATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a tough call
 &HT;    By Ethan Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The most scrutinized team in Super Bowl XXXIII may not
be one coached by Dan Reeves or Mike Shanahan, but the one chiefed
by Bernie Kukar, a 15th-year referee whose regular job is selling
employee benefits plans.
</P>
<P>
   Few American employees could benefit from a sell job more than
the NFL's officials. Rarely did a game day pass this season without
an official's call _ or non-call _ drawing mockery and reproach.
</P>
<P>
   Calling pass interference on Buffalo. Mistaking Vinny
Testaverde's head for a football. Ruling Jerry Rice down on a
fumble. Botching the Pittsburgh-Detroit overtime coin flip, which
prompted Atlanta's Reeves to send linebacker Jessie Tuggle out the
next week with a sign that read ``heads'' and prompted the league
to require the visiting captain to call ``heads'' or ``tails''
before a flip, and three officials to watch.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, facing the scary possibility of a Super Bowl turning on
a gaffe, the NFL did nothing to alter its post-season officiating
plan, which includes assigning the top people to the biggest game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' replied George Young, the NFL's senior VP of
Football Operations, when asked if he was comfortable with the
officiating. ``In the playoffs, we've had 1,500 plays, and the
officials probably botched one. How much controversy have we really
had?''
</P>
<P>
   A hasty December motion to reinstate instant replay for the
playoffs failed in the NFL's competition committee, 7-1. ``People
recognized that in the post-season, (the officiating) is especially
good because we have the best people out there,'' Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue said then.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos and Falcons were not represented on that
eight-person committee, which was chaired by then-Packers coach
Mike Holmgren and Buccaneers executive Rich McKay. Denver and
Atlanta were among the 21 teams that voted for replay last March,
when it failed by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   When asked this week, the participating players and coaches were
clearer than a Thanksgiving coin flip: They understand the
officials have a difficult job. All the more reason to have replay
as a supplemental tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been for instant replay, and I think if the
commissioner is really sold on it, we can get it done,'' Reeves
said. ``In my opinion, he is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, like Miami Dolphins
coach Jimmy Johnson, favors replay in any form, even the one in
which coaches must decide whether to challenge a call at the
expense of a timeout. ``The game is too fast for the officials to
make all the right calls, and teams don't make the playoffs, and
coaches get fired,'' said Brooks, who was head coach in St. Louis
in 1995 and '96. ``Underline it, put it in bold print. It's
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's irrelevant until the next owners' meetings in March.
Then teams must decide not only whether to implement a system, but
what kind. The one used from 1986 to 1991 (with an official in the
press box) had jurisdiction over out-of-bounds calls and
questionable fumbles and interceptions. That system did not review
pass interference calls, the source of many controversies this
season, and a future replay system likely will not review
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   So replay would not have averted the biggest officiating
controversy in Super Bowl history, when field judge Fred Swearingen
ruled that Cowboys cornerback Benny Barnes interfered with Steelers
receiver Lynn Swann, and awarded a 33-yard penalty. The Steelers
converted for a touchdown to go ahead 28-17, then withstood a
Dallas rally to win Super Bowl XIII by four. The Dallas Morning
News later published a letter Commissioner Pete Rozelle wrote to a
fan, admitting the call was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Several times this season, Jerry Seeman, the league's director
of officiating, admitted publicly that his officials had goofed,
sometimes on plays that would have been reviewable under the old
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many bad calls this year,'' Tuggle said. ``Not
to blame the refs, because they're human and they're not perfect.
We've got the technology, why not use it?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Falcons quarterback coach Jack Burns: ``We can put men on
the moon, we have stations in space, surely we have enough
intelligence to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cleveland back (a definite yes vote) in the league, replay
needs two more March votes. Last year's nine dissenters included
many of the old-guard owners: the Giants, Chiefs, Bears, Cardinals,
Raiders, Bills, Chargers, Bengals and Buccaneers. ``It's a few
people in the league who have their way,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   McKay has indicated the Buccaneers may change their vote. So
might the Bills. Owner Ralph Wilson was fined $50,000 for
criticizing the officials for two calls _ including the phantom
pass interference _ that cost Buffalo a Nov. 15 game against New
England. ``It was a key game,'' he said in December. ``It was a
terrible, terrible call, and I don't know how anybody in their mind
could make a call like that, in this league, in the midget league,
in any league.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was before Buffalo was damaged by a questionable ball
spot and ejection in its playoff loss to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Doug Flutie, replay proponents must wait until next
year, and hope that Kukar's crew _ which includes umpire Jim
Daopolous, head linesman Sanford Rivers, line judge Ron Baynes,
field judge Tim Millis, side judge Gary Lane and back judge Don
Hakes _ doesn't err. All have at least 10 years of NFL experience
(the minimum is five years), and four have been in at least one
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   They were tabbed after an exhaustive process, through which the
league's 113 officials in 16 crews are graded weekly by Seeman, a
staff of full-time supervisors and retired game officials. Every
play is graded from 1 to 7, based on judgment and mechanics. Seeman
maintains the officials get more than 98 percent of the calls
right.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 officials at each of the seven officiating positions
qualified for the playoffs, only one of each for the Super Bowl.
Officials' take home between $1,431 and $4,330 per game depending
on their experience, but the Super Bowl pays close to $10,000.
That's the top reward for a process including background checks,
psychological and physical tests, a July clinic and a four-hour
training session.
</P>
<P>
   None of the NFL's officials is full-time _ Steelers owner Dan
Rooney recommends the league hire at least one full-time official
per crew, but Seeman has repeatedly said that more worked games,
not more practice days, is all that might help. Some officials are
executives, some teachers, some attorneys, some probation officers,
some dentists.
</P>
<P>
   Some salesmen. Like Kukar.
</P>
<P>
   May choosing him be a better call than many of his colleagues
made this season.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
