<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESS-NYT &LR;      01-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERROGATORS AND WITNESSES PREPARE FOR FACEOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after the Senate voted to summon three
witnesses in President Clinton's impeachment trial, the inquisitors
honed questions they hoped would turn their case around, and their
targets prepared to say nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican prosecutors assigned to interview the
witnesses _ Monica Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal _
met separately on Thursday morning with their aides and the lead
prosecutor, Rep. Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, to map strategy and
plan questions for depositions that are to begin on Monday with Ms.
Lewinsky. Jordan and Blumenthal will follow on Tuesday and
Wednesday, but as of Thursday night, the sequence had not been
decided.
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team, even as it argued for a quick end to
the proceedings, continued to prepare for extensive discovery and
the possible calling of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   After their meetings on Thursday, some of the House managers
jumped on airplanes to tend to business back home. Rep. Ed Bryant
of Tennessee, who will interrogate Ms. Lewinsky, surveyed tornado
damage in western Tennessee. And Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas,
who will question Jordan, is scheduled to speak at a Chamber of
Commerce banquet in Booneville, Ark., on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On his flight home, Hutchinson said he was planning to re-read
Jordan's grand jury testimony. He wondered aloud how he would crack
the polished Washington insider and million-dollar superlawyer whom
House prosecutors have contended helped Ms. Lewinsky get a job to
buy her silence in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan is an experienced lawyer who is extraordinarily
poised,'' said Hutchinson, a former federal prosecutor. ``It's
going to be difficult to handle in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hutchinson played down expectations of any new
bombshells exploding from the upcoming depositions, and said the
House managers' goal is to persuade the Senate to take the next
step in the trial: calling the three witnesses to testify on the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting any grandiose revelations from these
depositions,'' Hutchinson said in an interview. ``There may be a
few new areas, but they won't be earth-shattering. We'll make a
case for live witnesses on other than new information. It has to
come out of the conflicting testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors prepared for the interviews of their professional
lives, they waited all day for word from the Senate on the
logistics for the depositions.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition ground rules adopted on Thursday night restrict
the scope of the questioning to the Senate record. Senate leaders
were still negotiating time limits on each deposition, with the
House managers and the White House counsels each receiving from two
to four hours per witness.
</P>
<P>
   Two senators, one from each party, will preside over the
depositions and rule on any questions. Objections raised by either
side would be noted and decided by the full Senate after all of the
witnesses were questioned.
</P>
<P>
   As the House managers watched the roller-coaster day unfold in
the Senate, the witnesses themselves, not yet served with Senate
subpoenas, were also preparing to give yet more sworn testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a 63-year-old Clinton confidant, was reportedly out of
town. His lawyer, William G. Hundley, did not return several phone
calls on Thursday. But an associate of Jordan said he would be back
in time to have lunch on Saturday with his mentor and law partner,
Robert S. Strauss, a former Democratic national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For Blumenthal, Thursday was sort of a normal day. The
50-year-old presidential aide whom House prosecutors contend helped
plan a possible smear campaign against Ms. Lewinsky, spent the
morning at the White House and the afternoon with his lawyer in
Baltimore, and was planning to attend a dinner at the British
Embassy on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say the same thing he's already testified to,'' said
William A. McDaniel, Blumenthal's lawyer. ``If the managers ask him
something new, like about the smear campaign, his answer will be,
`No, I didn't do it.' They are just lost in a fog of fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's interrogator, Rep. James E. Rogan of California,
was busy on Thursday preparing the questions he would put to his
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, long reviled by Republicans as championing the
``right-wing conspiracy theory'' against the Clintons, told the
grand jury that the president first described Ms. Lewinsky as a
``stalker'' and said she ``threatened'' to tell people ``they'd had
an affair.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors have sought to use these descriptions to prove
that the White House engaged in a campaign to smear its opponents,
and have accused Clinton of lying to his aides because he suspected
that they would become witnesses and would relate his denials of
the affair.
</P>
<P>
   In and out of meetings most of the day, Rogan popped up on CNN
early on Thursday evening, just as the Senate was preparing to vote
along party lines on rival ground rules for depositions, to made
another urgent plea to the Senate to allow live testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had almost three weeks of lawyers bloviating about what
the facts in the case are,'' Rogan said. ``Wouldn't it be easier to
bring the witnesses? Those witnesses should be heard in the well of
the Senate. The truth comes from the witnesses, not from the
lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Lewinsky, the witness who is central to the entire case,
was making arrangements to return here from Los Angeles, less than
a week after she flew in for a two-hour court-ordered meeting with
three of the House prosecutors. Her lawyers have insisted that she
has nothing new to add to the record.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who met with Ms. Lewinsky last Sunday and was impressed
with her as a potential witness, faces the task of reconciling what
the prosecutors said earlier this week was an ``almost complete
disconnect'' between the president's testimony and Ms. Lewinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in pretty good shape to go ahead with the questioning,''
said Steve Susens, Bryant's spokesman. ``His main priority is that
the tornado cleanup effort goes ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
