A3131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GEORGE-COLUMN-COX     01-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GEORGE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough to shine in the LPGA
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The youngest player on the LPGA Tour told the oldest story in
golf Thursday, the one about a couple of tough breaks costing her a
great score instead of a 71, and somehow she managed to smile about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm only 21,'' said Miami's Cristie Kerr, already in her
third season on tour. ``I've got the rest of my life to play this
game as a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be long enough, unfortunately, to master a field
like the one at the Office Depot, an invitational LPGA tournament
that's making noise at Ibis Golf &AMP; Country Club for a few more
days.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Kerr's skills, mind you. She thoroughly
dominated junior competition in Florida, where golf courses
outnumber public beaches by a sizable margin, and made the cut at a
couple of LPGA events while still an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Immaturity isn't holding Kerr back, either. Korean sensation Se
Ri Pak won two majors as a rookie last year and she's just 20 days
older than Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is commitment a problem. Kerr changed her entire outlook
on life for golf, learning to play the game right-handed even
though does everything else from the left.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, what prevents American prodigies like Kerr
from achieving instant success is the absolute saturation of the
LPGA Tour by international players. The pool of potential winners
is swimming with Swedes and Brits and Aussies and Japanese and
representatives of 16 other foreign lands. Every week out here it's
the Olympics of golf, but without the free money.
</P>
<P>
   Everything a player gets at an LPGA tournament, she earns. And
most of what she earns gets converted at some point to a different
currency. Six of the past seven LPGA Rookies of the Year have been
international players, including defending Office Depot champion
Helen Alfredsson, two-time U.S. Open champion Annika Sorenstam and,
of course, Pak.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has gone from interesting to absolutely overwhelming.
Of the 26 rookies who begin their LPGA careers this season, only
seven are American. These are the demographics that keep the Disney
World turnstile spinning all year long, but for an ambitious U.S.
star all this waiting in line can be trying.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr takes it all in stride, like the approach shot she dropped
into the water on No. 17 Thursday when the leaders were only a few
shots away. Five birdies to the good, but not good enough. The
field is too deep out here, the pace too swift. Kerr, who averaged
72 strokes per round last year and finished 74th on the money list,
is playing well this week but still stands eight strokes off the
lead of Karrie Webb, an awesome Australian, and LPGA Hall of Famer
Betsy King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fierce out here,'' said Kerr, who skipped college golf
because she believed herself ready for the LPGA. ``It's a lot
tougher than people think. Every day, when you tee it up on the
first hole, you know that somebody is going to shoot a low
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer Island's Michelle McGann, a former U.S. Junior Girls
champion, got the same education. A seven-time winner on the LPGA
Tour, she turned pro at 18 in 1988 but needed seven grueling
seasons to get her first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez, winner of nine LPGA events in her second
professional season, might not have smiled as much if she were
starting out today. It's a whole new world in women's golf, with
trouble coming from two dozen time zones and not just 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy came on tour in 1977,'' Kerr said. ``That's the year I
was born. I'll bet she was just trying to win one tournament, not
thinking beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anymore, one tournament is more than most top U.S. newcomers can
manage at the start of their careers. Pat Hurst, the last American
LPGA Rookie of the Year in 1995, didn't break the ice until her
third season. Meg Mallon, winner of two major championships in
1991, needed four seasons to get her LPGA cleats under her.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA's foreign legion, meanwhile, marches faster and harder.
England's Laura Davies won the 1987 U.S. Open while still an
amateur. Sorenstam won six LPGA events in her first three seasons.
Pak won four as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's great that the international players do so well,''
Kerr said. ``We're all females, after all, so why should it
matter?''
</P>
<P>
   At 21, very little matters enough to set one's jaw against it.
Plenty of money to go around, plenty of time to collect it.
</P>
<P>
   However, the odds against the arrival of a genuine American
phenomenon, something along the order of Tiger Woods, lessens with
the induction of each new LPGA rookie class.
</P>
<P>
   Please, in the name of international goodwill, won't anyone let
our kids play through?
</P>
<P>
   George writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
