<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DISPUTED MOVE, NETANYAHU CREATES A NATIONAL SECURITY COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced Thursday
the creation of an American-style national security council to
coordinate military and intelligence strategy, a change long urged
by defense analysts here but criticized now as a last-minute
political maneuver by a government entering its final months in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Military experts said the new council could represent a
significant structural change for the government, with potentially
serious policy ramifications, including the subordination of
military arguments to broader diplomatic considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The council, Netanyahu said at a news conference Thursday,
``will increase and tighten coordination and cooperation between
government offices in national security issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowing the substantive implications of the move, however,
is Netanyahu's electoral battle against his former defense
minister, Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he would have set up the council sooner had it
not been for the opposition of Mordechai, who retorted Thursday
that the plan was ``a charade that will cost a fortune'' but
accomplish little.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed last week for disloyalty and insubordination,
Mordechai promptly announced his own candidacy for prime minister.
He was replaced by Moshe Arens, who twice before has served as
defense minister and who is known for his consistently hawkish
views.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli military analysts have long advocated a
coordinating body of senior military officers, intelligence
specialists and civilian geopolitical advisers, contending that
dispassionate, long-range strategic analysis is often
short-circuited by crisis management and short-term military
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national security council could be an important correction
of a serious flaw in Israel,'' said Yehuda Ben-Meir, a former
defense official who has published two books advocating a more
coordinated approach to defense and foreign policy. ``But this is
something that should be done by an incoming government, not an
outgoing government.''
</P>
<P>
   On his first day in office, in 1996, Netanyahu announced plans
to create a national security council, under the leadership of
David Ivry, a defense ministry official and former air force
general. The proposal died a quick death at the hands of Mordechai,
his newly appointed defense minister, who led fierce army
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mordechai felt that the council would be in competition with
the defense ministry, and he wasn't the first defense minister to
feel that way,'' David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's chief spokesman, said
Thursday. ``The prime minister didn't want to have a confrontation
with his defense minister in his first weeks in office, so he
withdrew the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Mordechai gone, Netanyahu has suddenly revived his
proposal, including the appointment of Ivry, but this time with the
public support of a hard-line defense minister. Support for a
national security council approach cuts across the usual
hawk-vs.-dove divisions in the Israeli military establishment, as
does opposition, noted Joseph Alpher, an Israel-based
representative of the American Jewish Committee. ``This is not a
left-right issue, but an issue of national security concepts, and
of turf battles,'' Alpher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
