A3133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-AD-COLUMN-NYT     01-28 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL GENERATION PRESENTS FRESH MARKETING CHALLENGES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To effectively reach the youngest generation of Americans, whose
lives are being shaped by digital media, marketers must deliver
smarter, more sophisticated messages and build brands with them
rather than for them, a new study by Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, a unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, based its
study on interviews by child psychologists with 84 people ages 6 to
20 across the United States. They were asked what they thought
about digital media like personal computers, the Internet, CD-ROMs,
video games and cellular phones and other communication devices,
and how these media affected their lives. Cultural anthropologists
also observed 10 families at home for 50 hours each.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agency, the digital media serve several
functions for the 80 million Americans born since 1977, the largest
generation in the nation's history. The media serve as toys for
these young people but also provide developmental challenges.
Digital media also function as a virtual hearth at home, the study
said. It found that ``most families have their digital media set up
in a public room of the house; consequently, a lot of digital
activities are shared by the family, making these media a center of
family life.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study found that the new media could function
as a ``cool library'' for the new generation, known as Generation
Y. ``Generation Y uses digital media as an extension of self
socially, intellectually and emotionally,'' the study said. ``By
extending the self in these ways, the new media help young people
find their identity.'' It concluded that digital media act as
``power tools'' for Generation Y, giving them tremendous access to
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   According to Saatchi, digital media have collectively made
Generation Y members more positive and optimistic than Generation
X, instilling in the former greater confidence in mastering their
destiny. The agency thinks digital media also enhance Generation
Y's intellectual and social sophistication by increasing its access
to information.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the study found that Generation Y's values include
``connexity,'' which Saatchi defines as the importance of staying
connected to the outside world in order to grow; ``coolness'' of
knowledge, and the importance of self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the death of the nerd,'' said Myra Stark, senior vice
president at Saatchi. ``Knowledge is power for Generation Y, who
know that people like Bill Gates rule the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that ``kids are still kids and fun is still
what matters most,'' said Anne Adriance, executive vice president
at Saatchi. ``Being a kid is still about fun, even if it's an
edgier fun today.''
</P>
<P>
   To respond to this new sense of fun, Saatchi recommends that
marketers ``advertise up,'' by pitching Generation Y more adult
messages. ``If advertising sounds too young, they will tune out,''
Ms. Adriance said. One campaign that effectively delivers such a
message to children and teen-agers, the Saatchi executives said, is
the television campaign by Arnell Group Brand Consulting last fall
for Tommy Jeans, a division of the Tommy Hilgifer Corp. ``The
advertising speaks to kids in an adult fashion, and Usher, the
rapper who appears in it, is a teen icon,'' said Johann Wachs, a
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Successful marketing to Generation Y will also challenge their
intellectual abilities, the study said. Good examples of this,
according to agency executives, include Home Depot Inc.'s ``Homer's
Workshop,'' a syndicated how-to television program for children,
and its in-store children's workshops, as well as the public
television program ``Where in Time Is Carmen Sandiego?''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Saatchi also recommends that advertisers
create campaigns that speak Generation Y's language, which is
visually and verbally sophisticated. One example they cited was a
1998 television spot by Thomas &AMP; Perkins for the Denver Zoo. The ad
featured a ``gigapet,'' a portable computer some children treat
like a digital pet, footage of live zoo animals, and the tag line
``Denver Zoo, interactive by nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the agency urges marketers to build connexity brands.
``These brands go well beyond a simple product, they facilitate who
the child wants to be,'' Ms. Adriance said. ``Nickelodeon's `Big
Help' volunteer program and `Kids' Choice' awards envelop and
empower children. These validate them and give them tools to be
what they want to be. Nickelodeon doesn't speak down to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides stimulating what many consider positive social changes,
Saatchi said digital media had also created a potential ``digital
divide,'' a division between families and schools that can provide
high technology and those that cannot.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mediamark Research Inc., in 1993, 18.6 percent of
United States households had computers, while 24.3 percent of
households with children younger than 18 had this equipment. In
1998, 35.3 percent of households had computers, including 46.4
percent of households with children younger than 18. However, as of
last year, more than one-half of all households with children did
not have a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Saatchi study raises the possibility of two-tier
marketing to children _ one set of messages for children with
access to computers and a second for those without _ agency
executives declined to make any definitive conclusions about the
need for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a wait-and-see mode,'' Ms. Adriance said. ``Part of
it depends on the economics of technology and what technology
manufacturers can do to drive their prices down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
