<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MARTIN-COX     01-28 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's not so super journey
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Three days before Super Bowl XXXIII, and Tony Martin has
everything under control.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the former Miami Dolphin is home. He is surrounded by
the family and friends who watched his star rise from the mean
streets of Liberty City to the game-winning catch against the
Steelers that put the San Diego Chargers in Super Bowl XXIX.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Martin is back for another NFL championship,
this one as a starting wide receiver for the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Martin was greeted at the Hilton Miami Airport and
Towers hotel with a kiss and an ``I-miss-you-so-much'' from his
fiancee, an actress freshly arrived from her latest film project in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Then a cavalry of media arrived for the Falcons' daily press
conference. Questions, answers, sound bites, then off to the
University of Miami for practice, then to South Beach to tape an
interview with Johnnie Cochrane for today's Johnnie Cochrane
Tonight Super Bowl Special on Court TV.
</P>
<P>
   Distractions? ``He's totally focused on the Super Bowl,'' said
LisaRaye, Martin's girlfriend who won warm reviews earlier this
year for her debut as a stripper in The Players Club.
</P>
<P>
   Distractions. Does Tony Martin even know the word?
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is a guy who found himself answering questions
last fall, when Falcons started turning heads in the football
world, about a childhood friend whom the FBI suspects of having
ties to Central and South American drug lords.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, Rickey Brownlee, is in a lockup a few miles across
town at the Federal Detention Center, awaiting trial on seven
counts of cocaine and heroin trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey Brownlee is the kind of guy who casts a lot of
shadows,'' said Milton Hirsch, Brownlee's former attorney. ``Some
people will tell you he's the Robin Hood of Opa-locka.''
</P>
<P>
   Also known as the ``Mayor of Opa-locka,'' Brownlee owns a car
wash, several buidlings and the popular Brownlee's Home Style
Restaurant in the south Dade County town. He has helped hundreds of
people in the community through his businesses, barbecues and
Christmas turkey giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee, 41, also is a twice-convicted drug dealer who
reportedly moved 80 to 100 kilos a week. Authorities have struggled
to trace the profits.
</P>
<P>
   When authorities caught up to Brownlee again in January 1998, he
was driving a black Mercedes SL 500 that was leased in Martin's
name. In need of money for quality legal help, Brownlee turned to
his old friend Touchdown Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was a student at Miami Northwestern High School when he
met Brownlee, who was dating Martin's aunt. Despite the eight-year
age difference, the two forged a friendship. When Martin worked the
night shift pumping gas at a Miami fill-up, Brownlee helped him
make ends meet, supplying small handouts for football equipment and
helping put him through college.
</P>
<P>
   So on Feb. 10, a few weeks after Brownlee's arrest, Martin
signed a retainer agreeing to pay $175,000 for Brownlee's legal
fees. A few days later, however, authorities subpoenaed Martin's
financial records and Martin stopped payment on the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help (Brownlee),'' Martin told the Atlanta Journal
and Constitution in October, ``but my lawyer said that wouldn't be
the smart thing to do because it would get me into the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch, Brownlee's lawyer at the time, sued Martin for breach of
contract. Although he dropped the lawsuit when authorities removed
Hirsch from Brownlee's case, it only drew more attention to
Martin's involvement with Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Martin is being investigated by at least two federal
agencies, the U.S. Attorney's Office in Miami and the Drug
Enforcement Administration. His name also is in a FBI file on
Brownlee and the Mercedes is part of the federal probe, according
to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are looking into whether Martin may have helped his
old friend launder any drug money. The Mercedes is believed to be
one element of that investigation. Martin has not been charged with
a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy to launder carries a prison term of 10 years. If
Martin is charged with a crime, it could jeopardize his NFL
standing. The NFL is aware of the investigations but is not
commenting, although spokesman Greg Aiello has noted that
``improper associations'' by any player would be ``a cause for
concern'' that could spur action by the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee ``helped me when I was younger,'' Martin said. ``I was
trying to help him. I don't know how all this mess occurred
really.''
</P>
<P>
   The mess certainly hasn't affected his performance on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was traded from San Diego last June, had 66
receptions during the regular season for 1,181 yards, 24 yards
short of a career best. He averaged just under 18 yards per catch
and scored six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Randy Moss and Cris Carter of Minnesota, the 33-year-old
Martin and 31-year-old Terance Mathis were the NFL's most
productive pair of receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about being the best tandem in the league,''
Mathis said. ``We just talk about being the best old guys at our
position.''
</P>
<P>
   For Martin, it is a bittersweet payback. He was cut by the New
York Jets after being drafted in the fifth round in 1989, then
waited another year before playing his first NFL game for the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He spent five seasons in Miami before being traded in 1994 to
San Diego for a fourth-round draft choice. (The Dolphins used that
choice in a deal with the Arizona Cardinals that ultimately allowed
Miami to draft starting center Tim Ruddy).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they gave up on me,'' Martin said of the
Dolphins. ``When I was there they brought in O.J. McDuffie in the
first round of the draft and they had Irving Fryar and Mark
Ingram.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 30, Martin finally became a full-time starter with
the Chargers. But when he and then-coach Kevin Gilbride ``didn't
see eye to eye,'' Martin said, he wound up in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad it happened because it gave me a chance to start
fresh,'' said Martin, whose contract pays him $1.45 million this
year. ``It's a place I want to end my career, here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's next big move is to plan a wedding with LisaRaye, who
believes her fiance is concentrating on Sunday's game, not legal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doesn't even think about that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's mother and father declined requests to be interviewd
for this story. Martin's attorney, Kieran Fallon, said his client
hasn't been questioned about Brownlee since October. Asked if he
thought the investigation was on Martin's mind, Fallon laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather just say no comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Capozzi writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
