<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAHOO-GEOCITIES-ART-N     01-28 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-GEOCITIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO BUYS GEOCITIES FOR $3.6 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A handful of leading companies will come to dominate cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   That snippet of rhetoric has become all the analytical
underpinning there is to justify the unprecedented stock market
values of the prominent Internet companies like Yahoo, America
Online and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, that well could be true. On the other hand,
the Internet may make it easier for new competitors to constantly
challenge the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one of the byproducts of the irrational exuberance in
Internet stock prices is that the prophesied greatness of certain
companies becomes self-fulfilling. Their huge market values allow
them to grow by acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the $3.6 billion purchase announced Thursday by the
investors' darling Internet site, Yahoo, of Geocities, the leading
creator of electronic communities organized around people's
hobbies, passions and peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   Geocities is, in fact, an extreme example of the sort of
tantalizing potential implicit in many Internet companies. It is
the fifth most trafficked Web site, on which 3.5 million people
have created home pages that were viewed 53 million times a day in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Geocities has the right to put advertising on or next to all of
those pages, but in all of 1998, its revenues totaled a meager
$18.4 million. (Profits? Nah. It lost $19.8 million last year,
double the loss of a year before.)
</P>
<P>
   Those modest (to be generous) fundamentals did not stop
investors from valuing Geocities at $2.2 billion on Wednesday,
before the acquisition was announced. With that price tag,
Geocities was essentially too expensive for any company, no matter
how big, for whom traditional rules of finance applied.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo, which has a market value of $38 billion, an infinite
multiple of its just more than break-even earnings, was easily able
to exchange its shares for those of Geocities without breaking a
sweat. Indeed, Yahoo's offer of stock worth $113.66 for each
Geocities share, was a 52 percent premium over the company's share
price Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, because Yahoo's value is so high _ and the price it
paid represents only about 10 percent of its shares _ Yahoo is
telling investors that the deal will have no effect on its
per-share earnings after it closes in the second quarter. Indeed
Yahoo is promising that it can turn around Geocities and make it
add to earnings next year.
</P>
<P>
   As is usual with Internet stocks, investors leapt at any sign of
motion. Yahoo's stock surged by $31.875, to $367.75. Normally,
companies' stocks fall when they announce expensive acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the market is in many ways encouraging the big companies
like Yahoo to buy up other Internet companies. The same economics
has been behind the other Net deals recently, including the
purchase of Excite by At Home and of Netscape by America Online.
And many analysts expect Amazon to make some big acquisitions, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   But while the mystical multiplication of the stock market limits
Yahoo's risk from buying Geocities, the potential rewards from
turning the site's huge audience into profits will come much
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo's plans to seek incremental revenue from Geocities are
difficult to see,'' said Brian C. Oakes, an analyst at Lehman
Brothers. ``If I have a Web page that says I love the New York
Jets, who will want to advertise there if they don't control the
content?''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo does have a bigger advertising sales staff than Geocities
does and has technical resources that can cut that company's costs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Jeff Mallett, Yahoo's president, says the company sees
two areas beyond advertising on the home pages for growth at
Geocities. First, it hopes that people who publish home pages will
include links to related stores on their pages. For example, a page
on cooking would have a link to a kitchen supply site, which in
turn would pay a commission on any sales that would be split by
Yahoo and the creator of the site.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Yahoo sees Geocities as a great source of
information about the interests of both the creators of the home
pages and the people who look at them. It hopes to use this
information to expand the profiles it is creating about people's
interests _ profiles it uses to send people electronic mail with
advertising customized to their particular interests.
</P>
<P>
   Yet whether or not Geocities ever produces much in incremental
profits for Yahoo, the acquisition may well pay for itself simply
by bolstering Yahoo's perceived ``leadership'' in the market. Most
important, Geocities will substantially strengthen Yahoo's position
in the highly watched Media Metrix rating of how many people visit
a Web site at least once in a month, a measure they call reach.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's sites now rank third, reaching 48.2 percent of the
Internet audience. All of America Online's properties combined
reach 54.5 percent of the audience, while Microsoft's sites reach
48.4 percent. Geocities, by itself, reaches 33.4 percent of Web
users.
</P>
<P>
   Though Yahoo's reach has mostly been flat, Lycos, another
Internet service known as a portal because it is a gateway to other
online services, has been climbing the rating charts. The main
reason is that it has been buying up other sites including many of
the community sites that compete with Geocities. All of the Lycos
sites in December had a reach of 46.5 percent of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid constant speculation that Lycos will soon be acquired,
it is worth $5.3 billion, a huge number but a small fraction of the
value of Yahoo. Many Lycos investors, as well as its management,
were hoping that if it were able to surge past Yahoo, it might well
gain some of the market value accorded to leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never have too much cash or too much reach,'' said
Chris A. Kitze, the chairman of Xoom.com, a community site that
competes with Geocities. No such luck, Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   With Geocities, Yahoo says its reach will increase to 58 percent
of the Web audience, an undisputed top position, for now. And that
will allow the magic multiplication of Internet stock values to
keep working and let the company make even more acquisitions, just
maybe allowing it to fulfill the prophecies of its cyber-dominance.
</P>
</TEXT>
