<SLUG> BC-UNIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 State Labor Unions Gain 87,000 Members  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Labor unions gained 87,000 new members in California in 1998 _ the
first time in nearly a decade that the unionized share of the
state's workforce expanded.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO officials said yesterday that 16.1 percent of
California's approximately 14 million workers were union members
last year, up slightly from 16 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said the slight increase is a sign that their
movement is on the rise after years of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step on a long staircase,'' said Sharon
Cornu, spokeswoman for the California Labor Federation. ``The labor
movement is reorganizing and restructuring to be a lean, mean
organizing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of organized labor downplayed the significance of
the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any evidence of a trend that unions' efforts at
revitalization have been successful on a large scale,'' said David
Durham, managing partner of the San Francisco office of Littler
Mendelson, a law firm representing employers in labor disputes.
``It's too early to tell if this is a trend or an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Union membership has been on a steady decline both in California
and nationally for about two decades.
</P>
<P>
   On a national level, union membership has fallen from 20.1
percent of the workforce in 1983 to 13.9 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, union membership dropped from 21.9 percent of
the workforce in 1983 to 16 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While the actual number of union members rose during some of
those years, California's population grew by an even larger margin
_ leading to continued declines in the unionized portion of the
workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1995, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney has
pledged to reverse this decline by promoting an aggressive focus on
organizing new members.
</P>
<P>
   With 87,000 new recruits last year, California unions added far
more members than those in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers said the increase in California union membership
had the same roots as labor's successful political fight last year
against Proposition 226.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 226 _ which was voted down by voters last June _
would have placed limits on labor's ability to use members' dues
for political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an unmistakable renewal in the California labor
movement, which we saw very visibly in the turnaround on 226,''
said University of California at Berkeley professor Harley Shaiken,
who studies labor issues. ``We're seeing grassroots organizing and
a real revitalization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON &LR;      01-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Trading Surge Has Schwab Beefing Up Staff  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
They call it ``Market Storm 1999.'' And it's Charles Schwab's
version of sending in the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly swamped by an unprecedented surge in stock trading, the
world's largest discount and online broker is taking emergency
measures to keep customer service from breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, the San Francisco company has
beefed up its 5,500-person customer service staff by shifting some
700 marketing, finance and administrative employees to the front
lines to handle clamoring clients. The program is dubbed ``Market
Storm 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is offering overtime pay to keep those employees at a
high pitch. Earlier in the month, it announced a special $500 cash
bonus to rank-and-file staff members. And it's thrown away price
tags at company cafeterias, giving away meals for free.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is commandeering office space to serve as impromptu
phone banks. In one case, 40 or 50 employees are being bussed
regularly at dawn from San Francisco to a back-up call center San
Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the mobilization is to shore up service strained to
the breaking point by trading demand greater than anything the
company has seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the month, service quality slipped to unacceptable
levels, Schwab officials admitted, though they said the company has
done better than most of its rivals which were also plagued by
breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``January has been difficult,'' said Steven Scheid, Schwab's
chief financial officer. ``Our service is not as good as it needs
to be and our employees are working like crazy.`'
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Nick Kouvis, a San Francisco engineer who likes
to buy stocks on dips and sell them a few hours later when prices
bounce back. Kouvis said his trading strategy was stymied because
he couldn't log on to Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   On January 12, he woke up at 6:30 to sell 700 shares of a stock
he bought the day before. He said it took him 40 minutes to get
through. By the time, he placed his sell order, the stock had
fallen about $2, wiping out his profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere on the account agreement does it say you won't be able
to get online,'' Kouvis fumed.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab officials said that reinforcements have significantly
improved service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our service levels are higher, our backlogs are smaller, and
customers are increasingly receiving the kind of service they
expect,'' co-chief executive David Pottruck said in an e-mail to
employees earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Schwab has declared a ``Market
Storm'' emergency. The company took similar measures on several
occasions, for example, when the stock market went through a
mini-crash in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But, fueled by the galloping mania for Internet and other
technology stocks, the latest surge outstrips previous periods of
heavy volume, company officials said. ``Volumes that seemed
extraordinary only a short time ago have suddenly become
ordinary,'' Pottruck noted in a previous message.
</P>
<P>
   One week earlier this month, Schwab received 150,000 telephone
calls per day, about 50 percent higher than normal, the company
said. And Internet activity soared even more, with as many 55
million hits a day on Schwab's Web site compared to around 7
million a day at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's telephone service has been hit especially hard.
Officials said waits of five to 10 minutes to get through to a
broker were common for customers who don't qualify for premium
services. Some clients got busy signals.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the firm keeps shoveling new computer capacity into
its network, its online system, which now handles nearly two out of
every three stock transactions, has buckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Internet side, it's mostly a question of slowness,''
said Susanne Lyons, the executive who runs retail client services.
Still, on at least one day, customers were thrown off Schwab's Web
site before they could past the home page, Lyons said. ``Normally,
we try to keep three-to-four times the capacity we need,'' Lyons
said. ``That's all been eaten up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
