<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PeopleSoft to Cut 430 Jobs  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PeopleSoft Inc. said yesterday it will cut 430 jobs, or 6 percent
of its workforce, with the firm expecting the Year 2000 problem to
further crimp already slowing demand for its business software.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs were the first in the history of the Pleasanton
firm, which had been growing so rapidly that it hired about 2,500
new employees since September 1.
</P>
<P>
   The world's second-largest business management software-maker
also reported yesterday that fourth-quarter revenue was $364.2
million, up 39 percent from the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for the fourth quarter, after a onetime charge of
$13.9 million for the purchase of Intrepid Systems Inc., was $26.1
million (10 cents a share) compared with $39.5 million (16 cents) a
year ago. Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected
earnings of 17 cents per share for the past quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Austrian, managing director at NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities, said PeopleSoft and other business software-makers have
benefited from an increase in technology spending as corporations
prepared for the Year 2000 problem. But now those same customers
will wait for the Y2K problem to play out before buying new
applications or starting new projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company obviously is facing a very difficult demand
environment,'' Austrian said. ``They're probably doing all the
right things, but it won't be easy for shareholders in the near
term.''
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft issued layoff notices yesterday to administrative,
sales support and marketing employees whose jobs were deemed
``redundant and unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the layoffs will occur in North America,
with about half of them in the Bay Area. About 2,500 employees work
in PeopleSoft's new headquarters at the Hacienda Business Park in
Pleasanton.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs will be completed by the end of the first quarter.
In addition, another 100 employees will be reassigned to divisions
developing new products for the Internet and for electronic
commerce ``that make the most sense for customers and future
customers,'' said company spokesman Andrew McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from software-licensing fees was $576.5 million for
1998, a 33 percent increase from 1997. But the growth rate for
revenue from software-licensing fees slowed to only 3 percent in
the fourth quarter compared to the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft makes finance, personnel and inventory management
software for corporations. The company has overtaken Oracle Corp.
as the second leading business software-maker, behind SAP AG of
Germany. However in a November interview, PeopleSoft CEO David
Duffield warned the days of the company's 60 percent annual growth
rate may be over.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, PeopleSoft said it expects 1999 revenue to increase
20 percent to 30 percent from 1998, and first-quarter revenue to
increase 20 percent to 25 percent from the first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Saturation in the entire $14.4 billion enterprise software
market has slowed revenue growth for leader SAP, which earlier this
month reported pretax income increased by only 15 percent to $1.15
billion on sales of $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft shares have fallen about 39 percent in the last year.
Earnings were announced after the market closed. PeopleSoft shares
closed yesterday at $22.50, down 19 cents for the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
