<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Yahoo Buying GeoCities  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Yahoo, in a bid to solidify its lead in the frenzied Internet
market, agreed yesterday to buy GeoCities Inc. for $4.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The stock deal _ the latest in a rapid series of mergers that
resemble an online version of leapfrog _ pairs the leading Internet
guide with one of the most popular Web destinations for consumers
to create their own home pages. The combination could threaten
America Online's status as the No.1 site on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is about critical mass and extending our reach,''
Yahoo President Jeff Mallett said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies _ hell-bent on capturing the ``eyeballs'' of
cybersurfers to cash in on lucrative e-commerce and advertising
sales _ are in a mad dash to consolidate. In the process, most are
using their high-flying stock as currency to snap up competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Net company is talking to one another about doing a
deal,'' said Milo Medin, founder of AtHome, which was acquired by
Yahoo rival Excite for $6.7 billion last week. ``More will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett said the Yahoo-GeoCities merger creates a media giant
that will reach almost 60 percent of the Web's 100 million users _
rivaling AOL's anticipated audience once it completes its buyout of
Netscape. Yahoo, which boasts more than 35 million subscribers,
hopes to entice even more consumers _ and subsequently advertisers
_ by offering GeoCities' technology. The home-page-making software
is used by 3.5 million people. In December, GeoCities was the third
most-popular Web site, with almost 19 million visitors, according
to rating firm MediaMetrix.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo expects to offer integrated services by June.
</P>
<P>
   But the steep price that Yahoo paid for the money-losing
GeoCities underscores the stratospheric valuations of tiny
companies, many of which didn't exist a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 290-person GeoCities lost $8.4 million on sales of $7.5
million in the last three months of 1998, according to financial
results released yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo is buying reach. They're paying too much, sure, but so
is everyone else in the Internet market,'' said analyst Nicole
Vanderbilt of Jupiter Communications in New York. ``There is
tremendous pressure for Yahoo and its rivals to compete for
consumers online.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL kicked off the current Web wheeling-and-dealing when it
agreed last fall to purchase Netscape Communications Corp. for $4.2
billion. That deal begat the Excite-AtHome merger and Compaq
Computer Corp.'s decision this week &UR;  &LR; to spin off its Alta Vista
search-engine division, which in turn pressured Yahoo into making a
move, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, in 1997, Disney bought a 43-percent stake in
Infoseek Corp. _ the third most-visited search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Yahoo-GeoCities might force the hand of Lycos Inc. _ the
fourth most-visited Internet search engine and the only one still
independent _ to find a news or media partner to compete. The
Waltham, Mass., company has talked with a dozen companies,
including CBS, Time and Microsoft, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think the pace of consolidation is fast? Just wait,'' said
analyst Andrea Williams of Volpe Brown Whelan in San Francisco.
``There are lots of conversations. Lycos, Alta Vista, (Web
community sites) Xoom and Theglobe.com are all up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Xoom, a San Francisco company that recently went public, is not
for sale ``but if someone comes knocking on your door and offers a
bunch of money, you have to consider it,'' company Chairman Chris
Kitze said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Frasca, vice president and general manager of Lycos,
declined to comment on whether the company is for sale. ``We're the
only real hub on the Net to really embrace communities,'' he said.
Yahoo ``is reacting to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of yesterday's deal, Yahoo will exchange about 10.6
million shares of its stock for the 31.4 million shares of
GeoCities common stock. The deal is scheduled to close in mid-May.
Yahoo CEO Tim Koogle will head the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo of Santa Clara, which already owns 2.5 percent of
GeoCities, said negotiations with the Marina Del Rey (Los Angeles
County) company heated up in the past two weeks. Mallett
acknowledged that Yahoo had discussed deals with other companies
but declined to name them.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities shares jumped $42.25 to $117.25. Yahoo's stock rose
$31.88 to $367.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
