<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3148 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-SFCHRON &LR;      01-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Proposed laws to let disabled people work without
risking  benefits  By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
After three years on disability because of HIV, Bobby Tharp was
yearning to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   His health had bounced back due to the new generation of AIDS
drugs. His Social Security benefits were barely covering his rent
and food. And Tharp, a self-described workaholic, knew that getting
back into the job market would boost his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   But Tharp had one big fear _ losing his MediCal health coverage
if he started earning more income than the program allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worst fear was losing my doctor and my medications, since
without that, where would I be?'' said Tharp, who nonetheless took
a new job last month as an administrative assistant at Zephyr Real
Estate in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of disabled Americans share Tharp's fears of
being left without health coverage if they venture back into the
job market.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is especially acute for the Bay Area's large
population of people with HIV, many of whom have made amazing
progress in their health due to new drugs but face continuing
medication costs of $2,000 a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 1999 might be the year that public officials come to grips
with their dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Both in California and Washington, D.C., government officials
are proposing laws that would make it less risky for disabled
people to return to work _ letting them maintain their
government-subsidized health insurance until they can secure
permanent coverage through their employer or the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   On the state level, Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San
Francisco, is carrying a bill that would allow disabled people who
return to work to maintain their MediCal coverage by paying
premiums of $10 to $200 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would allow people who are disabled to return to work if
they feel able to do so, and not lose their health insurance,''
Migden said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Senators Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and James Jeffords,
R-Vt., are &LR;   &LR; backing a bill that would give states more leeway and
financial incentive to experiment with back-to-work proposals like
Migden's.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DISABLED (83195 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  President Clinton endorsed the Kennedy-Jeffords bill last week in
his State of the Union address, along with other ideas such as a
$1,000 tax credit to help disabled people pay for equipment or
services that allow them to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should have to choose between keeping health care and
taking a job,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The state and federal proposals would affect disabled people
who receive subsidized health care through the federal Medicare and
state MediCal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare usually covers most of the cost of hospital and doctor
visits, while MediCal covers other costs such as prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled people who return to work can keep receiving Medicare
coverage for up to 36 months, to ease their transition back into
the job market.
</P>
<P>
   But they lose their MediCal coverage entirely if they build up
more than $2,000 in assets such as savings and retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And once they earn more than about $600 per month, MediCal
requires them to funnel a significant portion of their income into
paying for their health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   The result? There's little financial incentive for disabled
people with significant medical bills to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``With HIV, the prescriptions alone can cost thousands of
dollars a month,'' said Irwin Keller, executive director of the
AIDS Legal Referral Panel in San Francisco. ``So people's salaries
would go just to pay for the cost of their drugs. Their quality of
life wouldn't improve at all from going back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill, AB155, would cover disabled people who return to
work and earn up to about $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would let them buy continuing MediCal coverage for
relatively modest premiums of $10 to $200 per month, until they are
able to find comparable coverage through their employer or the
private insurance market.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative analysts estimate that the bill would affect 2,000
to 4,000 Californians. They say it would cost the state an
estimated $12.3 million each year, of which $4 million would be
offset by recipients' premium payments.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DISABLED (83195 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Former Governor Wilson vetoed a similar measure by Migden last
year, warning that it potentially could be interpreted to include
tens of thousands more people who currently don't receive MediCal,
but might be eligible for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The potential price tag of the program is staggering,'' he
said in his veto statement.
</P>
<P>
   Migden is hoping for better luck this year with California's
newly elected Democratic governor, Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In Bobby Tharp's case, he couldn't afford to wait for passage of
either the state or federal back-to-work laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back to work became a financial necessity,'' Tharp said.
``Either I went back to work, or my partner had to find a second
job to support both of us, or we'd be out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Tharp found a welcoming workplace at Zephyr, where he's now
putting in solid 40-hour weeks. But the issue of health coverage
continues to worry him.
</P>
<P>
   If his new earnings end up disqualifying him from MediCal
coverage, Tharp still will be eligible for help from a separate
state program that provides AIDS drug subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   As a veteran, he also can turn to the Veterans Administration
for medical care. And in six months, he will be eligible for
Zephyr's group health plan.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't mean an end to Tharp's insurance worries.
Zephyr's plan would require him to change doctors _ a frightening
prospect for someone with a life-threatening medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I started back to work, I was afraid of not being able
to afford rent or food,'' Tharp said. ``Now, I have only one fear _
losing my medical care. You can't just go out and find insurance on
your own when you have this kind of preexisting condition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
