<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-QUAKE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSION AND SUFFERING INTENSIFY IN STRICKEN COLOMBIAN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMENIA, Colombia _ The Andalucia Apartments collapsed when the
first powerful tremor hit here on Monday afternoon. But under tons
of rubble where the five-story building once stood, someone was
still alive Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rescue dogs smelled somebody there, and when we banged on
the concrete that's in the way, whoever it is tapped back,'' said
Nelson Bravo, a fireman who was part of a 30-member team searching
for survivors of the earthquake that killed at least 883 people in
western Colombia and left more than 3,000 injured. ``We can't tell
if it's a man or a woman, but now we have to get this person out
before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Spanish and Colombian rescue workers struggled Thursday
morning to remove debris without causing further collapses,
relatives of residents of the building pawed through piles of
photographs, books and clothes, looking for memories of loved ones
who died in the quake. A crowd of onlookers, many made homeless by
the earthquake, also watched.
</P>
<P>
   Reynaldo Carvajal, however, had a more compelling reason to be
there. He was standing vigil for his aunt, Nellie Munoz Lopez, 38,
a resident of the building who is still not accounted for. Carvajal
said he had come all the way from Cali at the request of his family
with the faint hope that the trapped person just might turn out to
be his aunt. ``I'm staying until I know, one way or another,'' he
vowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a happy person who lives for her daughter, and always
enlivens our family gatherings,'' he said. ``So we owe her this
much.'' His aunt's daughter was rescued in the first hours after
the quake.
</P>
<P>
   There were reasonable grounds for Carvajal to cling to his
hopes, rescue workers said. Most of those who have been removed
from the rubble around this city of some 225,000 people _ the
hardest hit by the quake _ were already dead. But on Wednesday,
Andres Acevedo, 16, was rescued alive from the ruins of his
family's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lost hope, I really had,'' the youth said Thursday.
``I've been brought back to life to be able to make amends for my
past errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to aid tens of thousands of other survivors, however,
continued to encounter problems. Outside a Red Cross office where
several hundred people stood in line waiting for food to be
distributed, there were bitter complaints that the government was
doing much less to help than private relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth day now, and still no one from any
government organization has come by to help us or ask what we
need,'' said Robinson Angulo, whose family of four has been living
in the streets since their house was destroyed. ``They keep telling
us over the radio to wait, to be calm, but we have nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger and alarm at a lack of food led to the looting of dozens
of supermarkets here on Wednesday. ``But there are a lot of us who
don't have the heart to be robbers, and so we just stand in line,''
said Julio Cardona Muriel, head of a household with seven children.
</P>
<P>
   On the chance that she might be able to get some food, Gloria
Ines Narvaez walked halfway across this destroyed city Thursday to
stand in the same Red Cross line. ``The radio didn't say what they
were handing out, but since I have nothing, I decided to come,''
she said as she munched a cracker that relief workers had
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the growing discontent at the inefficiency of
official relief efforts, President Andres Pastrana flew here
Wednesday night to supervise the government's response personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of this tragedy exceeds all initial
calculations,'' Pastrana said in a nationally televised address.
The National Security Council, he said, will formally declare a
``state of economic and social emergency'' as early as Friday to
enable the government to deal more flexibly with the food problem
and with security.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that nearly 100 tons of supplies had
been flown here on Wednesday and that more were expected to arrive
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then where is everything?'' asked Luis Fernando Fuertes, 38, a
television repairman who has been sleeping in a park with his wife
and three daughters since their home was destroyed. ``Where is all
the milk and water and rice and beans they say has been sent? It's
not getting to those of us who need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The most widely requested item, however, is not food but plastic
sheeting. With so many people now homeless and living in the
streets, families use the material, when they can find it, to erect
makeshift tents.
</P>
<P>
   When it is not available, families are forced to turn to sheets,
tablecloths, towels and blankets to offer some protection from the
elements. But it has rained here every day since the quake, and
many of those tents are now soggy and smelly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Outside the temporary settlements that have sprung up, the
homeless have put up signs to call the government's attention to
their plight. ``We need help'' and ``Don't forget us,'' they plead.
</P>
<P>
   Leticia Zevallos, for example, had to move out of her house
after the back walls caved in. For the moment, she is living in
homemade quarters down the block, sharing an area no bigger than a
Boy Scout pup tent with her daughter, Diana Patricia, and
son-in-law, Victor Daniel Roman, and the couple's two children.
</P>
<P>
   Roman, 20, operates a food stall that was destroyed in the
quake. ``I couldn't make any money anyway,'' he said, ``because
nobody is selling food through normal channels to small fry like
me. It's all going to the speculators.''
</P>
<P>
   Security also continued to be a problem. Military reinforcements
poured into Armenia after Wednesday's spasms of looting, but many
areas were nonetheless left unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   Rosso Jose Serano, chief of the national police, said
restrictions on the movement of outsiders into Armenia would also
be put in place to reduce crime. A curfew and a prohibition on
liquor sales remain in effect here and in other cities in the five
provinces affected by the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood called Galan, residents responded to the lack
of police protection by forming their own security force. Armed
with machetes, sticks, pipes and an occasional rifle, some 500 men
erected barricades Wednesday night and patrolled their neighborhood
until dawn, stopping and questioning strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police said to us, `You have to organize yourselves
against the vandals,''' said Fernando Zuluaga, 45, a food salesman.
``They told us if we have to kill somebody, go ahead and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, there were new outbreaks of looting at
supermarkets and other stores here. But military policemen quickly
quelled the disturbances by launching tear gas, whose smell
lingered over downtown for hours afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the generalized confusion, residents of
several areas said, groups of armed men wearing the uniforms of
civil defense workers ordered residents of some buildings to leave
their homes on the ground they might collapse. The false relief
workers then returned to the buildings to loot them, these people
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the growing scarcities, prices of necessities are rising
daily. The price of a simple wooden coffin has soared from $70 to
$350 since Monday, residents said. Batteries and gas for cooking
have more than doubled in price, and the cost of a pound of rice or
a liter of milk has quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of one neighborhood said a local official had received
a shipment of milk for distribution in the area, but had turned
around and sold it elsewhere. There have also been reports of
people unaffected by the quake passing themselves off as victims so
they can then sell the milk and water they received free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are getting worse, not better,'' said Steven Ceballos,
a resident of Queens, N.Y., who has been here since Dec. 16
visiting his father. The solidarity of the first couple of days is
breaking down, he said, and ``people are behaving with no heart,
and think only of themselves now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
