A3157 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     01-28 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT COOL ABOUT CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ All those zeroes and commas, accented by
that big, fat dollar sign, stare Kobe Bryant in the face, but the
newly anointed $70.9 million man isn't sure how to react yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I'm trying not to think about it. I'm trying to
hold it back,'' a smiling Bryant said Thursday, calmly soaking in
the glory of a six-year deal with the Los Angeles Lakers that
averages $11.8 million a season through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But as the 20-year-old Bryant prepared to sign the deal _ a
formality he'll take care of this morning at the Forum _ his
friends and family already had plans for the windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and my sister were going crazy, especially my sister
Shaya,'' Bryant said. ``She's like, `Oh yeah, Rodeo Driiiiive.'
She's really pumped up about it. She jokes around a lot, but I like
to spoil my sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the predictable loan requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant coach Bill) Bertka asked for 50 dollars,'' Bryant
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But he has no plans for his first major NBA payday, other than
to say, ``It's gonna go right to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the deal done didn't take much thought either. Bryant
and agent Arn Tellem knew they would seek the maximum allowed under
the NBA's new labor deal. The Lakers knew what Bryant could command
as a free agent this summer and were ready to lock him up as soon
as possible, preferably before the season began.
</P>
<P>
   There was hardly anything resembling a negotiation. ``Just a
couple conversations, certainly no sit-down meetings,'' general
manager Mitch Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We evaluated the market for a player like him and we rather
quickly got to the point where we said, `Hey, this is a good deal
for us,''' he said. ``When it's a clear-cut decision, something
like this, there's really not a whole lot of thought required.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our mind, it was easy to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bryant, a budding superstar, but not yet a starter, is now
the Lakers' second-highest-paid player behind Shaquille O'Neal, who
he'll team with well into the next millennium as the franchise's
new core. Bryant's deal includes an opt-out clause in 2004, but he
plans to spend his career here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically told them, L.A. is a good spot for me,'' Bryant
said. ``I feel comfortable here. I love (Lakers executive) Jerry
West. I love the situation I'm in. So it's a good place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Del Harris, who's mulling a three-man rotation of Bryant,
Eddie Jones and Rick Fox in order to get starting time for the
young phenom, said the contract won't influence coaching decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches don't pay any attention to contracts,'' he said.
``Kobe's going to play a big role. He's played a big role the last
two years. He's not likely to play a lesser role than he's been
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   With big money comes big expectations, but Bryant said he's
comfortable in his sixth-man role _ for now, anyway _ and that the
money won't change his approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to think about (fan expectations),'' he
said. ``I have to think about what I have to do as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as living up to that $70 million price tag?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna be worth the $70 million,'' he said. ``Don't even
worry about it, I'll be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   About that rotation: While Harris ponders how to get playing
time for all his stars, he's sticking to an established trend for
tonight's exhibition game against the Clippers. The Lakers will
start the group that finished last season _ O'Neal, Robert Horry,
Fox, Jones and Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any reason to alter it,'' Harris said. ``You
can't change the lineup because there's a draw, it has to be a
knockout. Somebody has to knock somebody out before you change
something that's successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Rookie guard Sam Jacobson (strained left hip
flexor) did not practice Thursday and will not play tonight. Fisher
(sprained right ankle, right knee tendinitis) practiced for only an
hour but should play tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
