A3158 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  by2! &LR; AssociatedPress &UR; !dl     01-28 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 by2! Associated Press !dlim! 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; AMHERST, Mass. _ With Massachusetts winning its first
national championship, pressure is building to lift football to the
big time of Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``While everyone's attention is focused on it and they see how
much joy it brought to the campus, it really makes sense to do
that,'' said Dave Robinson, a former board member of the university
Alumni Association.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade project, which has stayed mostly in the background
since a burst of publicity in 1995, is getting a shove from the
team's 55-43 upset of No. 1 Georgia Southern last month in the
Division I-AA championship. With the victory, the Minutemen (12-3)
capped a remarkable turnaround from a 2-9 record the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
   The push to move to I-A by campus sports administrators also
picked up a nudge earlier this month when Connecticut applied to
join the Big East Conference. That Huskies intend to boost its
football program to I-A.
</P>
<P>
   UMass coach Mark Whipple calls the Big East a ``natural''
destination for his program, too.
</P>
<P>
   He said his team's surprise national championship has expanded
interest in the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people have asked me about it, and more recruits have
asked me about it than ever before,'' Whipple said. ``We would
certainly like to head that way,'' he said Thursday. ``Now it's
much more in my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the faculty Senate went on record with a vote against
moving to I-A in football, largely out of worry about the cost of a
new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   John Bracey, the Senate leader, said he agreed with its vote at
the time. He said many I-A programs lose money. But he said the
team's championship and the Connecticut plans may supply a new
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If UMass is going to move up to I-A, this might be a good time
to look at it,'' he said. ``As an aspiration of the athletic
department, I think they ought to pursue it.''!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
