<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-U.S.-NYT &LR;      01-28 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TALKS TO MODERATE ARABS ABOUT `REGIME CHANGE' FOR IRAQ  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ On every stop on her quick trip to moderate Arab
states, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright explained the
administration's new goal for Iraq: ``regime change.''
</P>
<P>
   The term, jargon for the overthrow of Saddam Hussein, has been
used since President Clinton announced last November that the
containment of the Iraqi president was no longer sufficient. The
aim, he said, was a change of leadership in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   During her talks in Egypt and Saudi Arabia and more briefly on
Thursday in Jordan, Albright was seeking the support of these
governments for the long-term policy of seeing Saddam toppled,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, said that the secretary had
found general agreement on the goal of the policy but that these
countries wanted to see the overthrow come from within Iraq rather
than from outside.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several months, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Jordan have
expressed serious doubts about the administration's plans to
finance Iraqi opposition groups that operate outside Iraq and that
have failed in previous efforts to penetrate Iraq and bring down
the government.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win support from these moderate Arab states for
the policy, Albright appeared to downplay the importance of seven
Iraqi opposition groups that became eligible last November for $97
million after Clinton signed the Iraq Liberation Act.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said no decision had been made yet on
how to assist these groups or whether to give them lethal or
non-lethal aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress focused on a particular approach _ to arm opposition
groups and inject them into Iraq to achieve an overthrow,'' said an
administration official. ``We've scrubbed that and developed a
broader, more integrated approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials said they would not talk about the
details of the Egyptian and Saudi responses to how they would
actually help the administration's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments in the region prefer to do rather than talk,''
said one official who insisted on anonymity. ``That's especially
the case when you're dealing with a fellow Arab country even when
there is complete disdain'' for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As a way of showing that the administration is in tune with the
desire of the moderate Arab states to see Saddam toppled from
within Iraq, Albright brought along with her Francis Ricciardone,
who was appointed earlier this month as the State Department's
special representative for transition in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Ricciardone, who was the political adviser to Turkish and
American commanders of the relief operation in northern Iraq that
began in 1991, is to oversee efforts to ``create the environment
and pressures inside Iraq'' that it is hoped will lead to the
overthrow of Saddam, an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were vague about how these conditions would be
created beyond broadcasts of Radio Free Iraq, which is paid for by
Washington, and mobilizing Iraqis outside Iraq as a lobbying group
on behalf of opposition groups inside the country.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright traveled in the Middle East, Gen. Anthony Zinni,
who commands U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, testifying before the
Senate Armed Services Committee, questioned the policy of
supporting opposition groups in the hope of deposing Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived in Egypt and Saudi Arabia just as those
governments have taken a much tougher line against Saddam. Earlier
this month, the Iraqi leader called on the people of Egypt and
Saudi Arabia to rise up against their governments, a move that
helped intensify the desire by the leadership in these two
countries to see him deposed.
</P>
<P>
   At an Arab League meeting in Cairo, Egypt, last weekend, a
senior Iraqi minister stalked out of the gathering in a
demonstration of the increasing isolation of Saddam in the Arab
world, administration officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
