<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SKETCH-NYT &LR;      01-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SKETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FRIENDLY MINGLING IN THE CHAMBER DESPITE A DAY OF HARD PARTY
DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Strom Thurmond slowly came down the aisle
Thursday with a wide smile and two pieces of candy sweets for
Cheryl Mills and Nicole Seligman, lawyers at President Clinton's
defense table. The 96-year-old senator regularly finds courtly
delight in chatting with the women when he is not sitting mutely in
judgment of the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the president's personal counsel, David Kendall, was
working on a Sunday crossword puzzle, in ink, with a backup puzzle
waiting in his briefing folder. It was 1 p.m. sharp, time for a
court session in the impeachment of Clinton, but nothing was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, an uncharted region of impeachment doldrums had been
entered. The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi,
said nothing about the increasingly embarrassing delay when,
smiling confidently, he rose and told the mostly empty Senate that,
yes, more time was needed for the party caucuses that were under
way elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   With the chamber forced to drift in recess, the most contentious
thing uttered on the trial record Thursday, as most senators
remained in heated dispute off the floor, was the insistence in the
opening prayer that ``at no time are we hapless or helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   In the party meetings, positions were hardening, and four hours
later Lott decided not to let another day pass with the Senate in a
standoff before the eyes of the watching nation.
</P>
<P>
   After a largely futile search for common ground, Lott called for
a round of voting on rival plans for ending the trial. The stark
vote tallies laid out the deep party divide as the court moved into
a controversial process for ending the trial that left Democrats
complaining that it would allow for a videotaped deposition
appearance by Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some feeling she ought not be on the same floor where
Webster and John Kennedy were,'' said Arlen Specter, R-Pa., in
criticizing the Democratic wariness and preferring Ms. Lewinsky to
appear in person, and President Clinton, too.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Capitol grounds, the president was attending a
memorial service for Lawton Chiles, the former senator and governor
from Florida, even as his fellow Democrats scrapped in his behalf
to bar any Lewinsky videotape on the Senate floor and to fix a firm
trial closing date of Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually failed, even as Republicans insisted there would
be no Lewinsky spectacle nor fresh leeway allowed the House
Republican prosecutors to push the trial in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fear the new party-line trial procedure will allow the
prosecutors to sensationalize and destabilize the proceeding,
whether new facts are discovered or not. The president, with his
political fate once more moving toward judgment, made no mention of
any of this as he mourned his old friend, Chiles, as a great
politician and quoted some lines of poetry:
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make our lives sublime,
</P>
<P>
   And, departing, leave behind us
</P>
<P>
   Footprints on the sands of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton incorrectly attributed the lines to Wordsworth rather
than Longfellow, and he omitted the opening stanza line: ``Lives of
great men all remind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Democratic caucus, Charles Schumer, the freshman
senator from New York, warily recited a scrap of Bob Dylan lyrics:
``What do I have to do to prevent from going through all these
things twice?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for me it's thrice,'' Schumer said, referring to his
final two votes last year as a member of the House and of the
judiciary committee. He was part of the Democratic minority that,
in a rancorously partisan struggle, failed to block the impeachment
of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the House, the far right kept moving the goal posts back,''
contended Schumer, now a member of the Senate court whose old House
instincts about cut-and-thrust political trouble have hardly seemed
to fade. ``Until today I thought that would not happen here. Now,
I'm worried it could.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lott made his move Thursday evening to end the standoff in
the trial, the public mood within the Senate, despite the day of
hard party division, was remarkably amiable. Jokes, bipartisan
mingling, friendly back slaps, waves and nods suggested a workable
deal had been struck even as three separate votes laid out the
partisan divide as the trial moved into a potential muddy
homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the Senate's odd spirit of public bonhomie Thursday
evening suggested that only the deposition results _ whether the
Republicans vote to put some fresh Lewinsky videotape before the
nation _ will settle the question of just how combative the trial
might become.
</P>
<P>
   As the votes approached, Thurmond came slowly down the aisle to
take his place in judgment of the president, grinning once more as
he paid court to the defense counsels for the impeached president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
