<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHING-REPORT-NYT &LR;      01-28 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS FEEL UNQUALIFIED FOR MODERN CLASSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a report that U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley says
shows ``a cry for help from the teachers themselves,'' only one in
five full-time, public school teachers said they felt well
qualified to teach in a modern classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Teacher Quality: A Report on the Preparation and
Qualifications of Public School Teachers,'' said only about 20
percent of more than 4,000 teachers surveyed nationwide said they
were confident in using modern technology or in working with
students with disabilities or from diverse backgrounds. Less than
half reported feeling very well prepared for the challenges facing
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Only 28 percent said they felt very qualified to use student
performance assessment techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``These data confirm our dramatic need to get serious about
better preparing for and supporting teachers in our classrooms,''
Riley said at a news conference in Washington Thursday at which the
report was released.
</P>
<P>
   Celia Lose, a spokeswoman for the American Federation of
Teachers, the nation's second-largest teachers union, said that
more is being demanded of teachers because of rising academic
standards, the importance of technology and the desire to integrate
in the classroom increasing numbers of students with physical or
learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lose said the survey is ``absolutely not'' an indictment of
teachers. ``Teachers are professionals and want to do their jobs
well. No one starts a job with the skills of a veteran. Teachers
need the sort of help and mentoring that doctors, for example, give
their peers. The schools are not supportive enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the news conference, Riley said that
although he was using his office mainly to call attention to a key
deficiency in the nation's classrooms, and that he expected state
and local governments to come up with remedies, the federal
government can help by attracting ``more bright and enthusiastic
people into teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levine, president of Columbia Teachers College in New
York, said teacher quality is ``a huge issue,'' exacerbated by the
fact that many teachers, especially teachers of math, science and
English as a second language, have not been trained in the subjects
they are required to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause of difficulty, Levine said, is that in the past
the field of education took advantage of very bright women and
minorities whose only career options were teaching and nursing, but
now that many of these people have been able to get higher-paying
jobs in business, ``the field of education has lost a captive pool
of potential teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The report arises from a 1998 survey of 4,049 full-time public
school teachers in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-WINDFALL-NYT &LR;      01-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-WINDFALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WINDFALL CITY  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 29:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even at this moment of prosperity, New York City faces mounting
budget deficits and municipal debt in the years ahead. Thursday
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani proposed some clever fiscal acrobatics to
address these problems and still meet the city's needs. He wants to
roll over a $1.6 billion budget surplus into next year to pay for
operating expenses. He also wants to use money expected from the
tobacco lawsuit settlement as collateral for $2.5 billion in loans
to build schools. Both steps raise questions that need to be
analyzed thoroughly before the City Council approves them.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's proposals came in his financial outline for the
fiscal year that begins July 1. Unfortunately, the day before, Gov.
George Pataki blew a $300 million hole in the mayor's plans by
proposing school aid cuts in programs the city was counting on and
that Pataki had promised to support. Giuliani was scathing in his
comments about the governor's reversed course, as he should have
been, setting up a battle over school aid that will pit a governor
with national ambitions against a mayor with statewide ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the mayor's financial plan keeps spending under
control for another year, but with questionable tactics. Giuliani
argues that 1,500 more police officers are needed to bring crime
down still further. He would have a stronger case if the city had
not failed to turn many Police Department tasks over to civilians
so as to move officers from desk jobs to crime-fighting. The mayor
also has set aside nearly $1 billion in receipts from the
commercial rent tax over the next five years to pay for sports
stadiums whose value has yet to be demonstrated, including a
possible new football stadium on the West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he engages once again in the cynical exercise of
proposing cuts in vital arts and youth services programs, knowing
that the Council will restore them in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has only three years left in office. But he has
figured out a way to spend nearly all the money the city expects
over the next 20 years from tobacco companies. He wants to issue
$2.5 billion in new 20-year ``tobacco bonds'' and pay them off over
20 years, using up most of the $6.7 billion the city expects in the
settlement. One problem is that the federal government might sue to
get a portion of the money unless the city sets aside more of it
for health purposes. It would be more prudent to use the tobacco
windfall as it comes in each year, and not borrow against it in
advance, as Council Speaker Peter Vallone has suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Even more dubious is the mayor's plan to use the current year's
surplus to support spending in the next year. Again, it would be
more sensible to use any budget surplus for capital needs or to pay
down the city's debt, and to find other ways to save money in the
next year. The mayor has a very poor record in achieving savings
through labor productivity improvements. It is also unacceptable
for him to sell the New York Coliseum and use the proceeds to pay
for ongoing budget expenses. Giuliani has done an effective job in
holding down expenses over the years. Tapping windfalls can get the
city from one year to the next, but more needs to be done to
address the underlying problems creating deficits year after year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-28 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Daughter Faces Status Question  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My daughter works as the personal assistant to a woman
who is wildly successful in the multimedia world. She works
exclusively for this woman, at this woman's office. Her employer
pays her by the hour as an independent contractor, so she receives
no benefits, no vacation and must pay self-employment tax on her
earnings. Is this proper and legal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The facts are pretty sketchy but, off the bat, I'd say
that your daughter is very likely being illegally misclassified as
a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Confusion over employee/contractor status is a
growing problem nowadays, from small startups to Fortune 500
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of years, we've been dealing with questions
like this a great deal,'' said Conley Baker of the Employers Group,
a California nonprofit that provides human resources help to its
member firms. ``I think it has to do with downsizing. Companies
need work to be done but don't want to hire people as regular
employees to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service used to have a checklist of 20
different criteria for telling whether someone is an employee or
independent contractor. Recently, they've boiled these down to
three major categories:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Behavioral control &LR; . &LR;   &LR; Contractors generally have great
freedom to do the work any way they want _ any time, any place, as
long as the job gets done. Employees, on the other hand, follow
directions from their employers about how, where and when to do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Financial control &LR; . Contractors are usually paid a flat fee
for an entire project and risk losing money if the job takes longer
than expected, while employees are paid a weekly, monthly or hourly
wage and incur little personal financial risk. Contractors also
tend to invest in their own tools and business materials, while
employees use equipment and materials supplied by the company.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Type of relationship. &LR;   &LR; Contractors tend to be hired for
limited amounts of time, while employees are hired on an open-ended
basis. And contractors tend to perform work that is not a key
aspect of the company's business: An accountant who is hired to do
a once-a-year audit is probably a contractor, while the bookkeeper
who handles day-to-day office finances is probably an employee.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that your daughter is an employee for a variety of
reasons. She's paid hourly on an open-ended basis, she's working
solely for this one woman, and I bet the boss directs her work and
sets her hours.
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter should approach her employer and politely explain
that she doesn't want the company to run afoul of the IRS or other
agencies by misclassifying her.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  And in fact, there are big financial risks to an employer who
messes up here _ such as liability for back payroll taxes,
unemployment taxes, disability insurance and other benefits, and
workers compensation payments.
</P>
<P>
   Want more information on how to determine if someone is an
employee or an independent contractor? See IRS Publication 15A, the
Employer's Supplemental Tax Guide. You can get it by calling (800)
TAX-FORM or visiting the IRS Web site at  &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; . You
may also want to read the excellent guidebook, ``Hiring Independent
Contractors: The Employer's Legal Guide,'' by Stephen Fishman (Nolo
Press).
</P>
<P>
   Burning Bridges
</P>
<P>
   Q: About seven months ago, I quit a job that I'd held very
successfully for five years. Now I'd like to return to the company,
but the human resources department isn't returning my calls. I
think that I'm being blacklisted because of critical things I said
about my old manager during my exit interview. At the time, I was
told the exit interview would be confidential. Is it fair to hold
my honest comments against me this way? Can they refuse to hire me
back because of things I said in a supposedly-confidential
interview?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Like much in the working world, this company's refusal to
hire you back may not be fair _ but it's completely legal.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have the right to hire or reject whomever they want,
as long as they're not discriminating on a basis such as race or
gender.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies even have formal policies against rehiring anyone
who's quit _ no matter how good their performance was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I hired back a woman who had left for four months and I
had a number of human resources people say to me, `I'm surprised
you had her come back,''' said Patricia Stansbury, CEO of Stansbury
Staffing Consultants and president of the Northern California Human
Resources Association.
</P>
<P>
   This company should, of course, have the basic civility to
return your calls and tell you what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hold your breath waiting for that. Write them off your
job-hunt list and move on to other employers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the meantime, try to draw some lessons from this episode.
</P>
<P>
   One is to avoid burning bridges when leaving jobs. It can be
tempting to say ``Whee-hoo! Take this job and shove it!'' the
minute you get an offer from a new employer.
</P>
<P>
   But six months or two years from now, the company you're leaving
may look awfully good again. So make sure you end your stay at any
job in a professional fashion _ giving plenty of notice, staying
engaged in your work through the end and offering to help train
your replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson is to remain equally professional during exit
interviews. Perhaps you did this, and the company just didn't want
to hear any criticism at all. But perhaps you let off steam in a
way that alienated them.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``It's good to tell the truth,'' Stansbury said. ``But be
circumspect. Keep your comments on very specific behaviors and
situations. If you talk about how a manager always came in late
while he was asking his employees to be on time, they shouldn't
hold that against you. But never get into character assassination.
If you bad-mouth a manager's personality, it will just be
considered gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MORE ON MATERNITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Last week's column included a question about maternity leave
rights from a woman who had been laid off from her job, became
pregnant and is now about to be called back to work. Attorney
Judith Kurtz of San Francisco points out that California's
pregnancy disability leave law applies to all pregnant employees,
regardless of how long they've been on the job. So if this woman
returned to work for even one day, California law would make her
eligible for up to four months of pregnancy disability leave,
including about six weeks off after childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
