<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBLICAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A REPUBLICAN BLUNDER  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 29:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans acted unwisely Thursday by exercising their
majority power to impose an open-ended and ill-defined set of
procedures for the remainder of the impeachment trial. They are now
perilously close to turning the trial into a purely Republican
spectacle that poorly serves the nation and demeans the Senate
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the trial was essentially sealed on Wednesday
when 44 Democrats voted to dismiss the charges, leaving the Senate
11 votes shy of the 67 required to remove President Clinton. Since
the evidence is well known, there need be no further presentations
before the Senate hears closing arguments by the House prosecutors
and White House lawyers and votes on the two articles of
impeachment. But instead of following that sensible course, the
Senate Republicans first insisted on calling three witnesses, then
compounded the error by leaving latitude for all manner of future
digressions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans rejected several legitimate concerns raised by
Tom Daschle and his fellow Democrats in the Senate in a day of
intense but ultimately unsuccessful bargaining. The Democrats
wanted to set Feb. 12 as a firm deadline for ending the trial, and
hoped to keep the witness list limited to Monica Lewinsky, Vernon
Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal, unless the White House concludes that
it needs to call other people.
</P>
<P>
   The trial record is voluminous, and needs no amplification. The
House managers offer no prospect of producing new evidence that
would nail down a constitutional case for removal. The nation long
ago reached the sound judgment that Clinton's conduct was repugnant
and that he should be rebuked but allowed to remain in office. All
that remains at this point is the finality of a Senate verdict. The
longer the Republicans stretch out the trial, the more they appear
to be indulging in a partisan exercise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
