</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SETS STAGE FOR CLASH WITH PATAKI AS HE OFFERS BUDGET PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stepped up his criticism of
Gov. George Pataki's spending practices Thursday as he proposed a
$35.4 billion budget for New York City, setting the stage for a
battle over school aid that could complicate the mayor's political
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Giuliani's spending plan was a proposal to
build new schools using $2.5 billion of the city's anticipated
share of the settlement with the tobacco industry. The city is to
receive $6.7 billion from the settlement, in installments over two
decades. Giuliani said the city would borrow the money to build the
schools over the next three years, then pay off the debt with its
annual payments from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also proposed using hundreds of millions of dollars to
expand art and reading programs, put computers in every middle
school and start an experimental tuition voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Pataki, a fellow Republican, of providing
insufficient state aid for such initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was angered last week when the governor ordered a
state investigation into the city's school construction practices.
And Giuliani used the opportunity of his budget address to amplify
a complaint that he has raised daily since Pataki announced the
investigation: that Albany repeatedly sends New York City less
school aid than it is entitled to get.
</P>
<P>
   The city has about 37 percent of the state's schoolchildren,
according to the mayor, yet it receives about 34 percent of total
state aid to schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the budget that the governor released,'' Giuliani said,
``that disparity would grow _ particularly with new dollars _ very,
very substantially. That doesn't make much sense if you're really
interested in children being educated more effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   As with previous budget plans, the mayor was generally
conservative in his proposals for new spending Thursday despite a
strong local economy that enabled the city to build a $1.6 billion
surplus this fiscal year. He wants to use the surplus to reduce
budget shortfalls, which are expected to increase in the coming
years because of tax cuts and labor settlements already approved.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called for $591 million in program cuts, including $37
million from the budget for public libraries, $23 million from
museums and other cultural organizations, and $19 million from
youth programs. Among the affected youth programs is an
after-school program that the city started last year with help from
financier George Soros. The mayor recommended cutting all city
funds for that program, a move that City Council officials vowed to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also proposed $338 million in new tax cuts, including
$51 million from eliminating the sales tax on all clothing and
footwear, which would require approval from Albany, and $166
million from extending a tax relief program for owners of co-ops
and condominiums. He also called for setting aside $100 million for
future tax cuts while a newly formed commission comes up with
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said during his address that the city had every reason
to be optimistic about his proposals, which he said held spending
below the rate of inflation. ``We are proposing a budget next year
that in essence, in terms of city funds, will be a no-growth
budget,'' Giuliani said. ``New York City is now setting the way for
fiscal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the mayor boasted that his spending plan was smaller
than the previous one, independent budget monitors said it was
actually 2 to 3 percent larger. The city is not projecting a
spending increase because under its own accounting rules, and the
surplus is counted as being spent in the current fiscal year, even
though the mayor is using it to cover next year's anticipated
shortfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
