<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SPEND-NYT &LR;      01-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WANTS TO SPEND $1 BILLION MORE ON JOB TRAINING, ADULT
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKTON, Va. _ To rare Republican praise, President Clinton on
Thursday proposed to narrow what he called a ``skills gap'' by
spending nearly $1 billion more next year on job training and adult
education, as well as programs to cut dropout rates and to prepare
poor children for college.
</P>
<P>
   The increased spending, which appeals not only to Republican
congressmen but also to core Democratic constituencies, is in the
budget Clinton plans to present Monday. He did not describe where
the money would come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to create a situation in America where people can keep
on learning for a lifetime, without regard to where they live, what
their job is, what their income is,'' Clinton said after touring a
job training center here for workers at AT&AMP;T and Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spending proposals were immediately hailed by Rep.
Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who is chairman of the House Committee on
Education and the Work Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will spar on a variety of education issues this year, but
not these,'' Goodling said in a statement. ``What the president is
talking about today should enjoy broad bipartisan support.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the White House and the Republican-led Congress
consolidated a raft of overlapping and sometimes outdated federal
job training programs, arriving at what both sides regarded as a
much-improved approach that would better match training to
employers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied with the results, Goodling and other Republicans are
now as willing as the president to invest more money in training.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance here was one in a series to promote his
initiatives in advance of his budget presentation on Monday.
Thursday, Hillary Rodham Clinton announced administration plans to
spend more than $100 million helping children's hospitals and
fighting childhood asthma.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in a speech before an annual gathering of mayors in
Washington, Clinton plans to announce that he will ask Congress to
approve a $2.5 billion increase, to $28 billion, in the budget of
the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Of the increase, the largest chunk _ $580 million _ would go to
pay for 100,000 vouchers for housing for the poorest renters,
including homeless people, according to administration officials.
In addition, Clinton hopes to spend $50 million on an initiative to
provide grants for the demolition of abandoned buildings to make
room for businesses or homes.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday, Clinton repeatedly warned of a widening
``skills gap,'' a phrase from his State of the Union message last
week. His grandfather, Clinton said, had a grade-school education,
while his stepfather did not finish high school. ``They all did
just fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, he continued, ``high school graduates are likely to get
jobs where their incomes drop over time,'' rather than increase.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has set a five-year goal of expanding federal services
for job training and searching until they are available for all
Americans who become unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   As a step toward that goal, he is seeking an increase in such
spending next year of $368 million, to $2.6 billion. Under the
system established last year, much of that money is made available
to workers in what Clinton calls a ``skills grant,'' which they can
then use to pay for the training they think they need.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced Thursday that he wanted to spend an
additional $405 million next year, or a total of $2.7 billion, on a
basket of programs intended to help low-income children. Most of
the money would go to existing programs, like one to find jobs for
young people, but the president is also proposing to spend $100
million on a plan to encourage schools to work with businesses and
other organizations to cut dropout rates.
</P>
<P>
   The third component of Thursday's proposal is an increase of
$190 million, to $563 million, in spending on adult literacy
programs, including grants to pay for more teachers and computers
in adult education centers. In announcing the program, Clinton
played on a previous speaker's joke that striking oil was a key to
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil today is in your noggin, not in the ground,'' he said.
``And everybody can strike oil today. But they have to have the
means to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling, a proponent of literacy programs, said that Clinton
tended to design his adult literacy efforts too narrowly, rather
than taking into account an entire family's needs. ``Illiteracy in
almost all cases is a family issue, where both adults and their
children can't read,'' he said. ``Federal literacy programs must be
linked so that they work together to serve the entire family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
