<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-QUAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANDALS ROB SUPERMARKETS, COLOMBIA QUAKE VICTIM'S HOMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMENIA, Colombia _ Bracing himself for the loss of 40 years of
hard work, Jose Mejia watched from behind a chain-link fence on
Thursday as a frenzied crowd broke down the door of his grocery
store in this earthquake-damaged city.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, army troops poured into the street and secured the
supermarket. But the would-be vandals, who carried burlap bags,
refused to immediately budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If no one gives us anything, we'll just have to break in,''
said one young man in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   To Mejia and other business owners here and in nearby cities, a
bitter aftershock to the killer earthquake that rocked western
Colombia on Monday has come in the form of looting. Cold, hungry
and still grieving from their losses, earthquake victims are
growing increasingly angry at delays in the delivery of emergency
aid.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they began breaking into Armenia's supermarkets _
many of which were closed because of damage suffered in the quake _
and carting off cooking oil, rice, bananas and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the looters, authorities said Thursday, were delinquents
and gang members from other regions who descended on Armenia, the
city hardest hit by the temblor, to take advantage of the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Red Cross, the magnitude-6.0 quake killed 881
people in the region around Armenia, injured about 3,500 and left
about 200,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Besides grocery stories, looters targeted banks, instant-cash
machines, designer-clothing outlets, compact disk stores, jewelry
shops and even lingerie boutiques. One looter was so eager to turn
a quick profit that he offered a cut-rate price on a package of
Huggies diapers to reporters covering the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations reported that con artists posing as building
inspectors ordered residents out of their quake-damaged buildings,
then made off with television sets, stereos and silverware.
Following shootouts with police, 10 people were treated for bullet
wounds at an Armenia hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a disgrace,'' said National Police Chief Rosso
Jose Serrano. ``I can't understand how people can take advantage of
such pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombian President Andres Pastrana on Thursday banned
out-of-town vehicles from entering Armenia, a city of 250,000, and
sent in about 4,000 police officers and army troops to patrol the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the reinforcements had no place to put arrested looters,
because the city jail had collapsed in the earthquake. Authorities
took pictures of suspects, issued stern warnings and then let them
go. Looters outnumbered police, and the break-ins continued.
</P>
<P>
   At the Armenia Grain Market on Thursday, angry crowds knocked
down warehouse doors and began carting off bags of rice until riot
police lobbed tear gas canisters at them.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Andres Serna inspected the ransacked supermarket owned
by his mother. The food, the paper products, even the cash
registers were gone. All that was left were a few bags of plastic
cups and packets of margarine melting on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have taken the walls if they could have,'' Serna
said. ``This is even worse than the earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people tried to justify the stealing.
</P>
<P>
   The sacking of one supermarket, for example, began after people
complained of price gouging. A package of rice, which normally
sells for 50 cents, was marked up to $2.50, said Licceth Almonacid,
as she kneeled on a sidewalk scooping up pills left behind by
someone who had looted a drug store.
</P>
<P>
   Like other earthquake victims, Almonacid said she has not yet
received any government help _ except for three buckets of water.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, whose supermarket has been closed since the quake, got
into a shouting match with one tearful woman who claimed that he
should open his business or give away his merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would just give us something, then the people would
leave peacefully,'' said Sandra Patricia Gomez. ``You people have
no conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mejia and others business owners argued that thieves were
piggybacking on the discontent of hungry earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't eat tennis shoes,'' said Paula Londono, as she
surveyed a looted shoe store.
</P>
<P>
   President Pastrana toured Armenia on Thursday and promised that
help is on the way. He decreed an economic emergency to facilitate
budget appropriations for the disaster zone and announced that
price gougers would be ``severely punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Huge lines formed at the Red Cross distribution center, where
volunteers handed out foam mattresses, blankets, clothes and bags
of food.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the looting victimized earthquake victims themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Perez Salazar, a nightwatchman at a bank, got into a
shootout Thursday morning with 40 gang members. He finally dove for
cover under a city bus, and the thieves stormed into the building
and hauled away everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I could,'' said a sobbing Salazar, adding that his
apartment collapsed in the earthquake three days earlier. ``This
has been a bad week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
