<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MUTUAL FUND DEPOSITS REMAINED LIGHT LAST MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa., Mass.)   (af)  
 By RICHARD A. APPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors remained relatively unimpressed last month
with the stock market's sharp rebound, pouring just $3.4 billion
into stock funds in December even as the market continued a steady
climb back from its late-summer sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials say that January _ traditionally a strong
time for mutual fund sales _ is shaping up much better.
</P>
<P>
   Capital-gains distributions typically keep many investors from
buying stock funds at the end of the year, but last month was still
the weakest December for net sales of stock funds since 1990,
according to the Investment Company Institute, an industry trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   It capped a particularly slow five-month period that began in
August, when the market was tumbling, that saw new net investments
in United States stock funds of just $13.3 billion, compared with
$145.5 billion during the first seven months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock market's rebound is making for a good January,
with strong flows of money to index funds and other funds that
invest in large-capitalization stocks, industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flows have been markedly directed toward large-cap equity
index funds and large-cap growth funds,'' said Robert Adler,
president of AMG Data Services, a company in Arcata, Calif., that
tracks trends in mutual fund sales. ``It appears more people are
jumping on that bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Group, the index fund leader, estimates it will have
record net sales of $4.5 billion for its stock funds this month,
beating the previous high of $4.2 billion that was set last April,
with most of the new money put into index funds.
</P>
<P>
   January fund sales often taper off toward the end of the month,
but this time they have not, ``which suggests February should look
very good as well,'' Brian Mattes, a spokesman for Vanguard, based
in Valley Forge, Pa., said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong recent performances by the big funds at Fidelity
Investments, a unit of the FMR Corp., helped the No. 1 fund company
post strong net stock-fund sales this month; $2 billion flowed into
Fidelity equity mutual funds through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, net stock-fund sales at Fidelity, which is based
in Boston, were flat in December and about $1.3 billion in January
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Trimtabs.com Investment Research, a company in Santa Rosa,
Calif., that tracks mutual fund sales, estimates that net
stock-fund sales will be about $16.2 billion for all of January,
the strongest month since July and slightly more than the $14.7
billion in net sales reported by the Investment Company Institute
last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the public is regaining confidence in the
market,'' said Carl Wittnebert, the director of research at
Trimtabs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Charles Schwab Corp., which held $143 billion in mutual
fund assets at the end of the year, investors have made $1.3
billion in new net investments in stock mutual funds this month
through Tuesday, including about $460 million in index funds. The
flows are ``a little bit higher than last January,'' said Greg
Gable, a spokesman for Schwab, based in San Francisco. ``January is
often a reflection of pent-up demand, with people waiting out their
investments in December, when capital gains are being
distributed.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, the Investment Company Institute reported that
stock mutual funds had net sales of $158.8 billion, down from the
record $227.1 billion set in 1997 and the lowest annual total since
1995. Stock funds now account for $2.98 trillion of the $5.53
trillion in mutual fund assets, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, bond-fund sales soared last year. Taxable-bond
mutual funds, which registered $2.4 billion in net sales in
December, took in $59.2 billion for the full year, raising total
taxable-bond-fund assets to $532 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal-bond mutual funds, which saw $1.2 billion in net sales
last month, posted $15.2 billion in net sales for the full year,
bringing total assets to $298.6 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
