</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MEASURE COULD PERMIT SHOWING OF LEWINSKY DEPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fractured Senate abruptly abandoned any
bipartisan approach to President Clinton's impeachment trial
Thursday night as the Republican majority pushed through rules that
could permit Clinton's accusers to show Monica S. Lewinsky's
videotaped deposition on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Propelling the solemn proceedings to the brink of partisan
acrimony, the GOP plan, approved on a strict party-line vote,
54-44, creates a blueprint for the remainder of the trial that
could extend the proceedings beyond a projected end date of Feb.
12.
</P>
<P>
   Over objections from the White House and Senate Democrats, the
Republican road map also could permit the Senate to conclude the
trial with a finding that Clinton committed perjury and obstructed
justice, without removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic alternative, which would have prohibited videotaped
depositions mandated the trial's completion by Feb. 12 and barred a
separate finding of Clinton's guilt, was defeated, also along party
lines, 54-44.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic motion to call for immediate votes on the two
articles of impeachment also failed, 55-43, with only one senator
breaking party ranks: Russell D. Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Two senators were absent for each vote: Wayne Allard, a Colorodo
Republican, who was home with his ailing father, and Barbara A.
Mikulski, a Maryland Democrat, who was suffering from an inflamed
gall bladder.
</P>
<P>
   The developments, which followed a failed attempt to strike a
bipartisan agreement to continue the trial, immediately triggered a
political melee, as Democrats accused the GOP majority of
jeopardizing Senate decorum and flouting public opposition to
prolonging the impeachment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good ship GOP has hit an iceberg and it's sinking,'' said
Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who proposed the motion to vote on the
impeachment articles. ``Each day we continue this trial is really
an impeachment of the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said Democrats were
``overreacting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ranting and raving and questioning any of their
motives or blasting them for this and that,'' Lott said, although
he did suggest that the Democrats had blocked a bipartisan
agreement by making too many demands on how to conduct the
remainder of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would nitpick a gnat to death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the GOP plan, the House Republicans who are managing the
impeachment case will take videotaped depositions next week from
Lewinsky and two of Clinton's allies: his friend, Vernon E. Jordan
Jr., and senior adviser, Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Lewinsky's deposition is scheduled for Monday. On
Tuesday and Wednesday, Jordan and Blumenthal would give
depositions. One senator from each party will preside over the
depositions, as the witnesses are questioned by House managers and
White House lawyers, who will split the time equally.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said they want to videotape the depositions
so they could show them on the Senate floor if they are blocked
from summoning the witnesses to testify in person, as several GOP
senators said they could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fair amount of sentiment against having Miss
Lewinsky testify as a live witness,'' said Senator Arlen Specter, a
Pennsylvania Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Although Specter said he would not oppose Lewinsky testifying
before the Senate, he said a substantial bloc of GOP senators ``are
saying that she ought not be on the same floor where Daniel Webster
and John Kennedy were.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is charged with trying to conceal his sexual affair in
the White House with Lewinsky, who was a 22-year-old intern when
the relationship began in 1995. If he is convicted of the charges,
he would be the first president to be removed from office after an
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Senate Democrats, arguing that no witnesses
are needed to resolve the case, fought to block the videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the spectacle of Monica Lewinsky or anyone else
brought into the forum that is anticipated in this resolution,''
said the Senate Democratic leader, Thomas A. Daschle. ``What little
dignity that Monica Lewinsky has left, we hope we can protect.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said Democrats were trying to deprive the
House managers of presenting a thorough case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want the depositions to begin with,'' said Senator
Orrin G. Hatch, a Utah Republican who is chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee. ``Then they wanted the depositions closed.
Then they wanted them only in transcript form. Then they didn't
want the videotapes shown on the floor . . . Gee whiz, it seems to
me something that important ought to be open.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the GOP plan, the House managers have an 18-hour deadline
before each deposition to provide Clinton's lawyers copies of all
the material that they will enter into the record during the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Transcripts will be made of the depositions, as well as
videotape recordings. But the material will remain confidential
unless the Senate votes to make it public.
</P>
<P>
   In some measure, Senate Democrats succeeded in blocking an
effort by the House managers to leave open the possibility of
calling additional witnesses, such as the so-called Jane Does who
have made claims about Clinton. The final agreement permits the
House managers to call additional witnesses only if Lott and
Daschle agree.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the managers will not be permitted to question the
witnesses about any women who have made claims about Clinton except
Lewinsky and Paula Corbin Jones, who sued the president for sexual
harassment and settled the case last year for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will be recessed until Thursday, when the Senate is
expected to take up a motion by the House managers to permit the
witnesses to testify in person. The videotaped depositions will be
made available to senators to view privately Tuesday and Wednesday,
as they prepare to vote on the witness motion and any objections
that might arise in the depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, who lashed out at Senate Republicans a
day earlier for refusing to yield in the negotiations, said
Thursday night: ``We believe this could be over with now. We
believe it could be over immediately after the depositions, and
they wanted to leave the window open for other possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the spirit of bipartisanship evaporated today, and
that this has become a Republican impeachment trial,'' said James
Kennedy, spokesman for the White House counsel's office. ``The plan
that was adopted is vague and it has no certain end. It appears to
contain trap doors that could significantly extend this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans countered the attack. ``This is not a deep,
dark plot on the part of Republicans to slip anything over,'' said
Senator Robert Bennett of Utah. ``It is not part of a preordained
railroad job in any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   After the House managers complete the witness phase of their
presentation, Clinton's lawyers will have 24 hours to ask for
permission to call their own witnesses and to make any motions
dealing with testimony or evidence presented by the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan calls for a final vote on the articles of
impeachment by noon on Feb. 12, unless the Senate approves motions
that could prolong the process. The Democratic plan would have set
Feb. 12 as an unequivocal deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the trial ends, the House managers and White House
lawyers each will have three hours for closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Looming as a potential flashpoint is the possibility that
Republicans will move near the end of the trial for a separate vote
on whether Clinton committed the perjury and obstruction charges.
The vote would be intended to cite Clinton for wrongdoing without
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   James Kennedy, the White House spokesman, described the proposal
as ``a political tool to try to damage the president in some kind
of end-run around the constitutional process.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Democrats were ``overly nervous and jumping to
conclusions'' that the proposal will be made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
