</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the Constitution.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republicans did make one significant concession to the
Democrats, however. House prosecutors have tried to retain the
option of introducing new evidence or calling for a second round of
witnesses later in the trial. In negotiations Democrats have tried
to foreclose such a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan leaves it up to Lott and Daschle to decide
jointly on whether to allow such a request by the House. That in
essence grants Daschle a veto. Lott said he thought that the
Democrats would not abuse this power and that if the depositions
produced some startling reason for new evidence or witnesses, ``he
or I would be very hard pressed to deny that option.''
</P>
<P>
   In a plea for good will and some trust between Republicans and
Democrats, he said, ``our colleagues have to have faith in us. We
have to have faith in him, and his conference has to have some
faith in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although their votes were strictly along party lines, the
senators seemed amiable on the Senate floor, exchanging backslaps
with friends in the other party, joking and showing no signs of
rancor. The scene suggested that some of the day's statements had
as much to do with the political needs of the two parties as with
the real mood.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have already sunk in opinion polls because of
their handling of the impeachment trial, and Democrats have every
incentive to continue painting them as unfair and as the party of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seized the opportunity again Thursday night. ``I
think it's fair to say that Democrats first and foremost want this
matter ended,'' Daschle said after the vote, which was the second
Democratic effort in two days to halt the trial.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Senate Republicans are trying not to seem as
fiercely partisan as Republicans in the House. So Thursday night
they sought to minimize the extent of the partisan strife. ``The
two sides are still talking to each other,'' Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash., insisted. ``I do not think we've damaged personal amity
across the aisle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
