<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AFRICA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLOUT FROM SCANDAL MAY LIMIT DREAMS OF AFRICAN ATHLETES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By JERE LONGMAN   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ In the West African nation of Senegal,
there is one all-weather running track, one indoor basketball court
and one Olympic-sized pool, filled with sea water and located not
at a training center, but at a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to arrange for the training of our athletes,'' said
Lamine Diack, the president of the Senegal Olympic Committee.
``Now, we are building our first swimming stadium. Our problem is
one of having not enough facilities, equipment and coaches. Our
dream is to have the same sports system in our schools that the
United States has. Then we will raise a lot of champions. But
without facilities and coaches, it is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee, under its president, Juan
Antonio Samaranch, has made the Games a truly global event.
Athletes from 197 nations took part in the 1996 Summer Olympics in
Atlanta, a wholesale reversal from the boycott-tainted 1970s and
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But the far-reaching Olympic corruption scandal could threaten
the long-term participation of athletes from developing nations,
particularly from Africa, which already struggles to support sport
while contending with more urgent problems of poverty, disease and
war. In these developing nations, a decent pair of training shoes
can be a luxury. Some of the teams arrive at the Olympics without
so much as uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Olympic committee members from Africa _ more than a third
of the continent's representation on the world's most influential
sports body _ have been dismissed, resigned or remain under
investigation in the Salt Lake City bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   An eighth member linked to the scandal died last year. One of
those ousted by Samaranch, Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic, was
perhaps the most influential of Africa's IOC members, serving as
president of the continent's association of national Olympic
committees. Replacements for the ousted members will not
necessarily come from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially more devastating than a decimated leadership is the
threat to aid programs operated by the IOC that provide training
scholarships, coaching clinics and equipment and are funded by
corporate sponsorships and television rights fees. If corporate
sponsors begin pulling out of the Olympic movement, and television
rights are devalued, the financial drought will begin to dry up aid
to developing nations who need it most, Olympic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real losers will be millions of kids and athletes who
won't be funded,'' said David D'Alessandro, president of John
Hancock Mutual Life Insurance, one of a dozen worldwide corporate
sponsors of the Olympic movement. ``This scandal, if not handled
right, could force governments all over the world to have to take
over the funding of these programs, and the quality of athletic
programs could be set back 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The international committee operates a little-known but much
appreciated program called Olympic Solidarity, which is budgeted to
spend $122 million from 1997 through the 2000 Summer Games in
Sydney, Australia. The money, generated by television rights fees,
is earmarked for the 198 national Olympic committees worldwide and
contains 12 programs designed to train and develop athletes,
coaches and administrators. The program has proved especially vital
in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, for instance, Olympic Solidarity is funding sprinters
at a training center in Senegal, and distance runners at a center
in Kenya, while negotiating to train athletes in judo and wrestling
in Ivory Coast and boxers in Tunisia. Among other things, Olympic
Solidarity pays at least $40,000 a year to each national Olympic
committee, and pays travel and accommodation costs for up to six
athletes and two officials from every country to attend the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Funds from Olympic Solidarity will be bolstered by another $110
million in corporate sponsorship money distributed by the IOC to
international sports federations from 1997 through 2000. Beyond
that, the financial pipeline is dependent on continued belief by
corporations and television networks in the ideal that the Olympics
can contribute to world peace through sport. This notion faces
tremendous skepticism at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If corporate sponsors pull back, you should see far fewer
athletes from underdeveloped nations in Athens in 2004,'' said John
Lucas, an Olympic historian and retired professor at Penn State
University.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in Olympic participation by athletes from developing
nations, particularly in Africa, would seriously erode one of the
pillar achievements of Samaranch's presidency. He took over in
1980, four years after African nations boycotted the 1976 Montreal
Games, rebuilt the continent's commitment to the Olympics and has
been commended by President Nelson Mandela for his role in edging
apartheid toward final collapse by readmitting South Africa into
the 1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain, after an absence of
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Because NBC has agreed to pay $3.5 billion for the five Winter
and Summer Games to be held between 2000 and 2008, Olympic
officials said they are confident that Olympic Solidarity will
continue to grow. Michael Payne, the committee's marketing
director, said the funding for Solidarity is expected to rise to
$200 million for the quadrennium between 2001 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But while he has attempted to create a global appeal for the
Games, Samaranch was also the one who appointed all eight committee
members from Africa who have been connected to accepting cash
gifts, medical treatment, tuition aid and lavish gifts from Salt
Lake City Olympic officials. Other African officials have joined in
the call for a housecleaning of the international committee,
although no one has called for Samaranch to step down.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations in Salt Lake City might even prove beneficial in
spurring the IOC to offer more training programs to developing
nations, said Sam Ramsamy, an IOC member and president of the South
African Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If more programs were in place, maybe these inducements
wouldn't be necessary,'' Ramsamy said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite an insatiable need for more financing and training
programs, African athletes distinguished themselves at the 1996
Summer Games in Atlanta, winning both the men's and women's
marathons, the men's 1,500, 5,000 and 10,000-meter runs, the
3,000-meter steeplechase, two women's swimming events and the men's
soccer competition.
</P>
<P>
   Elite athletes earn extravagant salaries and endorsement deals,
but they do it largely by leaving the continent. Soccer players go
to Europe. Distance runners, courted by agents and shoe companies
like Fila, Puma and Nike, have dispersed, at least part of each
year, to racing circuits and training camps in England, the
Netherlands, Italy, the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's better to get rid of these officials,'' said Jos
Hermens of the Netherlands, the manager of Ethiopia's Haile
Gebrselassie, the world's top distance runner, who won a gold medal
in the 10,000 meters in Atlanta. ``Corruption is a big problem.
Money always goes to the wrong people, ends up in private bank
accounts. It can't get any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But the neediest countries are the most vulnerable to financial
inducements, said Keba Mbaye, an international committee member
from Senegal, who was on the six-member commission that
investigated the Salt Lake City bid committee. It is not clear
whether the removal of a number of members will automatically
improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Charles Mukora, dismissed last Sunday as an IOC
member from Kenya for allegedly receiving payments of $34,650 for
his personal benefit, remains the head of his country's national
Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   Federico Rosa, a sports manager from Italy, whose family
represents such Kenyan athletes as Moses Tanui, a two-time winner
of the Boston Marathon, said he believed that Mukora had done a
commendable job in welcoming sports agents and shoe companies into
the East African nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood that the more companies were there to get
athletes, the more money there would be for everybody,'' Rosa said.
``It is not possible to know that if he loses power it will be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Senegal, Diack said he appreciated the $50,000 or so per year
his Olympic committee receives from Olympic Solidarity, but that he
could use four times as much. Senegal has taken a common approach
of cobbling funds from a variety of sources. The Senegalese
government pays for travel expenses, he said. China built the
national track stadium in Dakar, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The French government and the world governing body of track and
field, of which Diack is a senior vice president, constructed a
national training center for sprinters and jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money from the IOC must go to the countries to develop
sport, not to cities organizing the Olympics,'' Diack said. ``My
Olympic committee gets $40,000 or $50,000, and Athens is guaranteed
$1 billion to organize the 2004 Summer Games. Something is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Diack said that the IOC, wanting the cities that stage the
Olympics to use the billion-dollar guarantees to organize the Games
instea of to build stadiums and collect large profits, would
reduce the amount of television money given to the host cities in
the future by 10 percent and would place more funds into sports
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to develop in Africa, we need support,'' Diack
said. ``We are starting from zero. The first all-weather track in
Kenya was built in 1985. Before that they ran on grass or dirt. So
we are doing very well with nothing. But we would like to make a
fantastic move in all sports.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
