<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITOR REJECTS BID TO OVERTURN HOFFA VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (af)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal monitor on Thursday rejected appeals to
overturn James P. Hoffa's election to the presidency of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, but he barred a Hoffa
running mate from taking office.
</P>
<P>
   The election overseer, Michael Cherkasky, found that the
violations by the Hoffa camp were too minor to warrant voiding last
month's election, which Hoffa, son of the famed Teamsters leader
James R. Hoffa, won easily.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Leedham, Hoffa's main challenger, had sought to void the
election, asserting that the Hoffa slate engaged in campaign
finance violations. But Cherkasky ruled in Hoffa's favor on most
charges, and Leedham said he had to study the 76-page ruling
further before deciding whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Federal monitors had ordered last month's election after
vacating a 1996 election in which the previous president, Ron
Carey, had defeated Hoffa. The monitors also barred Carey from
running again after finding that three of his aides had diverted
more than $700,000 in union money to help his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Leedham's protest ``frivolous,'' Hoffa applauded
Cherkasky's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been two years since the members of this union had
legitimate, elected leaders,'' Hoffa said in a statement. ``I call
on the Leedham slate to accept his decision and not further delay
the inevitable with appeals.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky suggested that it would take three weeks for an
appellate officer to consider appeals on his ruling. If that
officer upholds the election, Hoffa is likely to take office in
late February or early March.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky voided the victory of J.D. Potter, a Texas Teamsters
official who was elected as one of 19 vice presidents on the Hoffa
slate. He was one of three vice presidents on the Hoffa slate who
faced charges.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the violations serious, Cherkasky also disqualified
Potter from running again, finding that he exceeded the $5,000
contribution ceiling by giving $10,000 and then lied about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
