<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-PRIVACY-NYT     01-28 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY ADVOCATES ASK FTC TO FORCE RECALL OF INTEL CHIPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)   By JERI CLAUSING  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Privacy advocates who object to Intel Corp.'s plan
to put identification numbers in its next generation of computer
chips went to the Federal Trade Commission Thursday to seek a
recall of the Pentium IIIs.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with the commission followed a visit by Intel
executives to the Capitol Hill offices of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, an online advocacy group. On Monday, the group
and two other organizations called for a boycott of the world's
largest chip maker, saying the new technology would compromise the
privacy of computer users.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the boycott threat, Intel said the company would
alter the software that turns the identification feature on and
off. But the privacy groups said that solution was inadequate. So
Intel executives flew to Washington for a meeting Thursday at which
they defended the alteration, saying it gives consumers both choice
and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``They met with us for almost two hours,'' said Marc Rotenberg,
director of the privacy center. ``We decided after the meeting that
we would actually extend the boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg said the privacy advocates wanted Intel to remove the
processor serial number from any future Pentium III chip, and to
recall all processors that had been shipped with the processor
serial number already enabled.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy advocates then headed to the trade commission to
plead their case for a recall of the chip, which Intel confirmed
was already being shipped to computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   The trade commission confirmed the meeting with the privacy
advocates, but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates are concerned that Intel's chips, which were
designed to enhance the security of electronic commerce and
safeguard against software piracy, would make it easy for
governments and online marketers to follow computer users around
the Internet and build profiles about their Internet habits.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Mulloy, a spokesman for Intel, said the team that met with
the privacy group included a security expert, a public relations
executive and an employee in the company's Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were grateful for the opportunity to explain our view of
the program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy said Intel believed its solution gave ``consumers both
the choice and control over whether or not to use processor serial
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel is the world's largest computer chip maker, with $26.2
billion in sales last year. On Thursday, it announced a 2-for-1
stock split effective April 11, news that moved the company's stock
up $4.4375, to $137.1875, on the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara, Calif., company, which makes about 85 percent
of the world's computer processors, unveiled the Pentium III chip
containing the so-called processor serial numbers at a trade show
in Silicon Valley last week.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, a coalition of privacy advocates began
discussions about a boycott of Intel. On Monday, as the protest was
announced, the company said it would alter software in the system
so that the serial number was disabled unless the computer user
turned it on. Originally, the feature would have been activated
automatically and it would have been up to the user to disable it.
</P>
<P>
   But the privacy advocates refused to end their protest, saying
the software patch was an unacceptable solution. Among other
things, they questioned whether it would protect against intruders
breaking in and switching the setting, even though Intel says that
is not possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
