<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-D.C.-RACISM-1STLD-WRI     01-28 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D.C.-RACISM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISUNDERSTANDING OF WORD EMBARRASSES WASHINGTON'S NEW MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete rewrite)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new mayor's decision to accept the resignation
of a white aide who upset a black colleague by using the word
``niggardly'' has turned into a major embarrassment for the young
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of the mayor, Anthony Williams, who is black, has
been widely criticized from all sides: blacks who already
questioned his loyalty, whites who see the move as pandering,
conservatives on a crusade against political correctness and gay
groups furious at his treatment of the aide, David Howard, the
mayor's first openly gay appointee.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who was the mayoral ombudsman, used the word on Jan. 15
in a budget discussion with two co-workers. ``I will have to be
niggardly with this fund because it's not going to be a lot of
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niggardly,'' which means ``miserly,'' is derived from the
Scandinavian and has no racial overtones or link to the racial slur
it sounds like.
</P>
<P>
   At a community meeting Thursday night, Williams walked away from
a reporter who asked him about the matter. A spokeswoman, Peggy
Armstrong, said only that ``his position is that in this
environment it may have been poor judgment for someone in his
position to use that word, and based on that, he accepted his
resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the gay groups, Williams has said he will
review the situation, to see if there was any wrongdoing by Howard,
and may offer him a different city post if there was not. The
review is to be completed by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Plotkin, a local radio commentator, said Williams finds
himself in the position of having to prove himself to the black
community, where his loyalty has been questioned by some who
wonder, in the words of a recent opinion article in The Washington
Post, whether he is ``black enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was strong in the black community,'' Plotkin said of the
mayor, ``he could have said, `This is absurd.'''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP, weighed in Thursday, saying
it was Williams who had been ``niggardly in his judgment on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to think you have to censor your language to meet
other people's lack of understanding,'' Bond said. ``This whole
episode speaks loudly to where we are on issues of race. Both real
and imagined slights are catapulted to the front burner.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Watters, past president of the mostly black National Bar
Association, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really know where the Norwegians got the word?'' Watters
asked. ``And how would another ethnic group react if you came close
to the line with a phrase inappropriate to that group?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Chavous, a City Council member who ran against Williams in
the November election, suggested that there must be more to the
story, or Williams would surely not have accepted the resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests some instability'' on Williams' part, Chavous
said. ``I don't think the mayor's being decisive enough on this.
Where does it end?''
</P>
<P>
   When Howard, a 44-year-old former restaurant manager who ran
Williams' volunteer office during the campaign, offered his
resignation, the mayor immediately accepted. Williams said later,
``I think it was appropriate that he resign,'' and he compared
Howard's use of language to getting ``caught smoking in a refinery
that resulted in an explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor received a letter of protest from 22 homosexuals,
including Rick Rosendall, a prominent local activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Howard is the one owed an apology,'' Rosendall said.
``The mayor has been making incredibly lame statements defending
the fact that he accepted his resignation without even looking into
it first. The fact that he would cave in like this doesn't bode
well for his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter reads, in part: ``The facts have to count. If we fail
to distinguish between decent people and bigoted people, if we
acquiesce in treating the former like the latter, then we send a
poisonous message to the people of this city, not to mention an
illiterate message to our schoolchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Howard, he is so contrite that he sounds apologetic about
even knowing the word. ``I learned it for my SAT test as a junior
in high school,'' he said, miserably.
</P>
<P>
   He said his use of a word that could be so misconstrued was
reason enough for him to be out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used bad judgment in using the word `niggardly,''' he said.
``It's an arcane word that's unfamiliar to a lot of people, and I
can see how someone not familiar with the word could perceive it
differently. You have to be able to see things from the other
person's shoes, and I did not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the mayor was premature. H. Patrick Swygert,
president of Howard University, the prominent historically black
university here, said he hoped people would realize that they
needed to ``at least count to three before jumping to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, we're at a point in time that even an official who
as far as I can see has no history of this kind of conduct still
has no opportunity to put this in context,'' he said. ``It would
appear there was no intent to inflict pain. Should this be fatal
for a budding public official? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become hot on conservative talk radio, where it
has inspired fresh outrage from Rush Limbaugh and others on the
excesses of political correctness. ``Some poor overeducated slob
loses his job over a Swedish word and Bill Clinton keeps his job
after perjury and obstruction of justice,'' Limbaugh said Thursday.
``Go figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sol Steinmetz, a New York lexicographer and former editorial
director of Random House's reference division, said the word goes
back to the 14th-century Scandinavian term ``niggard,'' meaning
miser, thus preceding by hundreds of years the entry of the racial
slur into the English language, which happened about 1700. The slur
derives from the Latin ``niger,'' or black.
</P>
<P>
   But in another recent dust-up over the same word, The Dallas
Morning News published an apologetic clarification last month after
using the word in a restaurant review that said a black chef had
been ``niggardly'' with his use of spices.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chunk of our readers apparently did not know what the word
meant and took it as a racial reference,'' said Stuart Wilk, the
newspaper's managing editor. ``It wasn't a good word to use. We're
in the communication business, and in 1999 that word does not
communicate as well as some other equally good words.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said that immediately after using the word, he saw the
startled looks on the faces of both of his colleagues in the
meeting, one white and one black. The white colleague, John
Fanning, seemed to accept his explanation, he said, while the
other, Marshall Brown, stormed out and would not let him explain.
(Neither could be reached for comment either at home or work.)
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Howard seemed heartbroken that he could have anything to
do with worsening already fragile race relations in Washington. And
certainly, he never intended to end up as a poster boy for a
crusade against political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Howard remains loyal to the mayor and is spending most of his
time at home kicking himself, he said, saying he deserves to be out
of a job over such an inelegant word choice. He said he had not
heard from anyone in the mayor's office since resigning on Monday,
but offered, ``I've been on the phone a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
