<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ROBINSON-     01-28 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-ROBINSON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BRONCOS DEFENSE _ STEPPING OUT OF ELWAY'S SHADOW
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-FALCONS-DEFENSE) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When you score 501 points, and your quarterback is a
legend, your running back amasses 2,000 yards, your tight end
redefines the position, does anyone care who plays defense?
</P>
<P>
   More important to the Broncos _ who are only a victory over the
Falcons away from their second straight Super Bowl triumph _ that
defense may finally have overcome its second-class status.
</P>
<P>
   Since John Elway burst into the National Football League in
1983, he has symbolized not only his team, but also virtually the
entire city of Denver. Given Elway's limelight, the fellows on the
Broncos' defense have been pretty much in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were second-class citizens,'' said the Broncos' defensive
coordinator, Greg Robinson, ``not a lot of esteem. It was low.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson arrived in 1995, fresh from being fired as the Jets'
defensive coordinator along with the rest of Pete Carroll's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this,'' Robinson said. ``From 1983, since John
Elway arrived in Denver, the focus from the outside world is on
John Elway and the offense. When Terrell Davis entered that thing
with Shannon Sharpe and the others, I think, it just heightened
that focus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson's unit is holding its own. His defense allowed an
American Conference low of 80.4 rushing yards a game, second in the
league to Atlanta's 75.2. The nonbelievers can argue that the
figure does not necessarily indicate a great defense, merely a
great offense. With the Broncos outscoring the opposition by almost
2 to 1 by halftime, opponents abandoned the run, started to pass,
and the rushing average plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' style places eight men in the imaginary box up
close to the line of scrimmage and dares you to run at them. It is
not a large defensive line, with no starter topping 300 pounds, so
won't Denver's linemen wear down? Won't it be tough to play
eight-in-the-box against the versatile Falcons?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be what we are,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   He comes by his confidence honestly. Robinson's defense has
progressed dramatically since he took it over. The first year he
joined the club, Denver's points-against improved by 51 points. By
1996, the Broncos had moved from 28th against the run to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In the four seasons before Robinson's arrival, the Broncos had
sent four defensive players to the Pro Bowl. In the four seasons
under Robinson there have been nine.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Robinson's defense has done well in the giveaway-takeaway
differential. It was second in the conference this season.
</P>
<P>
   In two playoff victories, this defense lowered the rushing
average to 60 yards a game. Now, the Broncos face an outstanding
runner in the Falcons' Jamal Anderson. He rushed for 1,846 yards
during the season, and another 180 in playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knows that some reporters perceive the Broncos'
secondary to be a weak link, that the cornerbacks Ray Crockett and
Darrien Gordon are beatable.
</P>
<P>
   There is some reality in the perception: The Broncos ranked 18th
in the league in interceptions. They yielded 28 passing touchdowns
while picking off only 19 passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in my ability to assess the
situation,'' Robinson said. ``I try to remedy it if I need to.''
The 47-year-old Robinson has a veteran defense, and he is a
big-game coach who has put together a game plan to halt two
receivers he knows very well.
</P>
<P>
   Terance Mathis was with the Jets when Robinson was there. ``He
supposedly didn't fit into our system, in that we wanted these big,
long receivers,'' Robinson said. ``He is more of scat-type. Also,
we defended Tony Martin for years when he was at San Diego. I was
surprised when he was traded. It was like a breath of fresh air for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Falcons, Martin and Mathis have teamed up to become one
of the rare receiving duos to gain 1,000 yards apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Denver will probably blitz to disrupt Chandler's timing with
Martin and Mathis. ``Look at Denver the last two games,'' said the
Falcons' offensive coordinator, George Sefcik. ``Their
aggressiveness at the line of scrimmage, and they go to the ball. I
think they'll blitz us a lot and we've prepared that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knows what his defense will give. ``I don't have any
problems any more. There hasn't been that discrepancy between the
offense and defense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
