A3398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT     01-28 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING CARS WITH STAR QUALITY, RAT PACK TO FAB FOUR
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ariz.)  (bl) 
By KEITH MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ This may be the biggest weekend of the year
in sports, but for car collectors, the Super Bowl has come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-day buying spree here last weekend at the 28th annual
Barrett-Jackson auction, nearly 600 highly desirable cars changed
hands at prices ranging from the expected to the extraordinary.
Size alone assures Barrett-Jackson a position of prominence among
aficionados. But beyond that, over the last four years the event
has accurately gauged the prevailing winds driving collectors and
investors, serving as an indication of the health of the collector
market.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett-Jackson has also evolved from a simple auction into a
spectator sport that draws a bigger on-hand audience than the Super
Bowl. This year, some 125,000 car buffs watched, at various times,
as more than 2,000 bidders vied in sometimes heated competition to
take home some of the world's most interesting and coveted cars. A
total of 734 cars were offered and 567 were sold. That 77.2 percent
selling rate compares with 65.5 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales reached $20 million, plus $1.7 million from the
big-ticket cars in the Exposition Tent, a separate area where cars
are sold one-on-one, allowing for more complicated transactions,
including trade-ins. Expo sales ranged from $126,500 to $1.2
million, for a 1931 Duesenberg Model J LeBaron Special Phaeton.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's economy is booming, America is where the money is,
and Americans are buying the dream cars from their youth,'' Craig
Jackson, owner of Barrett-Jackson Auction Co., said in summarizing
this year's results. ``There were plenty of Europeans in the
audience, but unlike four or five years ago, when they could
cherry-pick through the cars they wanted and take home the best
ones at bargain prices, this year they just couldn't match up to
what the Americans were bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest auction-block sale of the weekend, at $304,500, was
a 1973 Ferrari 365 GTS/4 Daytona Spyder, one of 124 built by the
factory. Authenticity plays a big part in the market value of
Daytonas; coupes were often converted to open cars by after-market
specialists; one such Daytona ``chop job'' sold here for $127,050.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest cheers of the weekend went to the buyer of an
immaculately restored 1957 Chevrolet Bel Air convertible who paid
$89,250, at least $30,000 above the normal price for this model.
Painted turquoise with a white top, it had a 283-cubic-inch V8 and
a rare factory fuel-injection setup, a three-speed manual
transmission and a limited-slip (positraction) rear end.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders were willing to ante up for vehicles that belonged to
celebrities, like three cars once owned by Hollywood's Rat Pack. In
their heyday in the 1960s, Frank Sinatra, Sammy Davis Jr. and Dean
Martin indulged their automotive desires as freely as they flaunted
their pursuit of wine, women and the good life. A car formerly
owned by each crossed the block here.
</P>
<P>
   A 1956 Ford Thunderbird two-seat roadster originally owned by
Frank Sinatra brought $159,600, easily $130,000 more than a
standard '56 T-Bird. The custom-colored metallic gunmetal-silver
car was laden with options, including a factory hardtop, wire
hubcaps, fender skirts, an external spare tire mounted in a
Continental kit on the back bumper, a spotlight and dual rear
antennas.
</P>
<P>
   Among car collectors, Old Blue Eyes commands the kind of premium
that ``dot com'' adds to common stocks. Last August, Christie's got
$178,500 for an ordinary 1989 Jaguar XJS coupe at Pebble Beach,
Calif. Without Sinatra's name on the title, such a car would be
worth barely $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The cars of Sinatra's cohorts didn't do as well. A 1962
Dual-Ghia L6.4 coupe once owned by Dean Martin, in slightly
disheveled condition with custom-fitted luggage, chrome wire wheels
and distinctive appointments including a gun holster under the
driver's seat, sold for $63,000 to the Blackhawk Collection in
Danville, Calif. Though it was among only 26 Dual-Ghia coupes
built, the selling price was in line with those of cars that lack a
celebrity connection.
</P>
<P>
   These exotics combined Italian coachwork with a powerful
383-cubic-inch Chrysler V8; they were built by Ghia in Italy and
distributed in the United States by Dual Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive of the Rat Pack cars did not find a new
home. Davis' 1964 Rolls-Royce Silver Cloud III convertible _ what
the British call a ``drophead coupe'' _ failed to sell despite a
bid of $305,000. With a body by Mulliner, the English coach
builder, and exquisitely restored with maroon paint and a tan
leather interior, this is one of fewer than 30 left-drive Silver
Cloud III convertibles built. A car in similar condition sold for
$247,500 in December 1997 at an auction in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis' and Martin's cars failed to move bidders' paddles,
Elvis and the Beatles set the crowd rocking. An enormous 1965
Rolls-Royce Phantom V limousine _ with a rare left-hand-drive
configuration _ brought $115,500, more than twice what these
behemoths normally fetch. The car's providence was extraordinary,
however, in that it had a double-Beatle history. John Lennon, the
original owner, sold it to Richard Starkey _ better known as Ringo
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Two cars once owned by Elvis Presley also did well. A mundane
four-door 1976 Cadillac Seville, two-tone blue with a custom grille
and garish gold trim _ typical of Elvis' cars _ sold for $30,450 to
the 120-car Klassix Auto Attraction in Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been looking for an Elvis car to go in our celebrity
section,'' said David Murray, the winning bidder. ``We already own
the Batmobile, the Munsters' Dragula, and the Flintstones movie car
driven by John Goodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray conceded that a seller ``would be lucky to get more than
$7,000 for the same Cadillac without the Presley history.''
</P>
<P>
   The second Elvis car brought more. A 1969 Mercedes-Benz
long-wheelbase 600 sold for $72,400, although its air suspension
seemed to have collapsed. That flaw was perhaps offset by the
gold-lettered ``TCB'' on the doors _ for ``taking care of
business.'' These cars have a reputation for being exceptionally
difficult and expensive to repair; $20,000 would be considered a
generous offer for a regular 600 in like condition.
</P>
<P>
   Several Mercedes-Benz 300SL Gullwings, with their trademark
flip-up doors, did well. A recently refurbished '55, in silver with
a black leather interior, sold for $189,000. The same car had sold
last March at an auction in Las Vegas for $138,600, demonstrating
that even for high-end collector cars, fresh paint and a wax job
pay dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many Corvettes sold, the most unusual was a 1963 coupe
that was customized by the General Motors styling staff and
presented to their long-time boss, the legendary designer Harley
Earl, in his retirement. Festooned with 16 gauges and adorned by
external exhaust pipes that resembled a bundle of snakes, it
brought $152,500. ``We've sold this same car four times now,''
Jackson said. ``And each time we get more money for it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the last car had crossed the block, the elaborate auction
tents had been taken down and tumbleweeds were again blowing across
the Sonoran Desert, Jackson reflected on the prospects for the
market.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw collectors moving into cars that are not
necessarily perfect, but offer good times. ``I'd keep an eye on
mid-'50s Chevys in driving condition,'' he said. ``People want cars
they can take to cruise-ins, relive the past and enjoy themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buyers we get at Barrett-Jackson, especially the
first-timers, aren't looking for show cars to pamper and admire.
They just want something they can have fun with.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990128.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-DEATHPENALTY-1ST     01-28 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-DEATHPENALTY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT POPE'S REQUEST, MISSOURI GOVERNOR COMMUTES A DEATH SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change Mease's age from 42 to 52, in what is now the 15th
graf. Inserts a new 9th graf; inserts a new 1st graf of 2nd take.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ After an extraordinary personal appeal from Pope
John Paul II, Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, a supporter of capital
punishment, commuted the death sentence of a convicted murderer on
Thursday to a sentence of life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said his decision was a one-time event and a
tribute to the pope rather than ``a signal'' that he had changed
his mind on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to say I was moved by his concern for this
prisoner,'' Carnahan said in an interview Thursday afternoon in
Washington, D.C., shortly before he was to receive an award from a
meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors. In a statement, he added:
``I continue to support capital punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's decision came one day after the pope concluded a
brief pastoral visit to St. Louis, during which he preached a
homily that included the strongest condemnation of the death
penalty he has made on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   After his final public event, a prayer service at St. Louis'
Roman Catholic Cathedral, the pope approached Carnahan, a Southern
Baptist, who was seated in a front pew, and, the governor said,
``asked me to show mercy'' to Darrell Mease, who was scheduled to
be executed on Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, a 64-year-old Democrat serving his second term, has
approved 26 executions since taking office in 1993. He said he had
commuted one other death sentence, that of a prisoner he described
as being ``very retarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Mease owed his life to a chance event, Carnahan said,
``You may wish to call it that. It is the coincidence of the pope
being there, taking a personal interest in him, making a personal
request that I chose to respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. Catholic Conference, which handles social
policy for the American bishops, said they could think of no
previous instance in which a direct appeal from a pontiff had
persuaded an American governor to grant clemency to a death row
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   In a previous case in Missouri in 1991, two years before
Carnahan became governor, the pope unsuccessfully sought clemency
for a man convicted of killing a state trooper. The man, Glennon
Sweet, was executed last year, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II issued an unsuccessful plea last year on behalf of
a condemned Texas prisoner, Karla Fay Tucker, who had become a
born-again Christian while in prison. In 1987, he spoke out on
behalf of an Indiana woman, Paula Cooper, who was sentenced to die
for a murder she committed when she was 15. Her sentence was later
overturned by an Indiana court and she is serving a life sentence
for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dieter, executive director of the Death Penalty
Information Center, a nonprofit research organization in
Washington, said it was ``certainly unusual'' for an elected
official to respond favorably to a religious leader's request for
clemency for a condemned prisoner. ``The clemencies themselves are
rare, about one or two a year since the death penalty was restored
in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. Supreme Court ruled the death penalty
constitutional in 1976, 510 prisoners have been put to death, with
the greatest number of executions taking place in Texas, Virginia,
Florida and Missouri, respectively, Dieter said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mease's lawyer, Laura Higgins Tyler, said she was
``ecstatic'' over Carnahan's decision, Jim Justice, who prosecuted
the case, said he was disappointed by it, although he said he
respected the governor's right to make it. Describing himself as a
``strong Christian,'' Justice said he believed all things happen
for a reason. ``If the pope would've come two weeks earlier, it
would have been the previous guy,'' he said, referring to another
death row inmate who was executed. ``It just happened to be
Darrell, and I guess there's a reason for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's decision brings a dramatic end to a controversy that
had shadowed preparations for John Paul's two-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Mease, 52, was convicted of the 1988 ambush slaying of a Taney
County couple, Lloyd Lawrence, 69, and his wife, Frankie, 56, along
with their disabled grandson William, 19. Mease, who killed the
trio with a 12-gauge shotgun as they rode all-terrain vehicles near
their rural Taney County farmhouse, alleged that the senior
Lawrence had been his former partner in a drug-manufacturing
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Mease had been scheduled for execution by lethal injection
Wednesday at 12:01 a.m., while the pope was in St. Louis. But
shortly after setting that day last November, the Missouri Supreme
Court, without explanation, re-scheduled the execution for Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's action drew strong praise from Bishop Joseph
Fiorenza, president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops,
the organization that represents the American prelates. ``The Holy
Father's plea for one man's life, someone who has been convicted of
having done great evil, reflects the church's concern for all human
life,'' Fiorenza, spiritual leader of the Galveston-Houston Diocese
in Texas, said in a statement. ``We oppose the death penalty not
just for what it does to those guilty of heinous crimes, but for
what it does to all of us; it offers the tragic illusion that we
can defend life by taking life.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show, however, that most Catholics do not agree with this
position, but rather support the death penalty by a roughly 2-1
margin. In this way, they do not differ much from other Americans
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pambianco, chief policy counselor at the Washington Legal
Foundation, a public interest law and policy center that supports
the death penalty, criticized Carnahan's decision because of the
nature of Mease's crime. ``It's exactly the sort of crime that the
death penalty was intended for,'' Pambianco said. In granting
clemency, he added, Carnahan was ``undermining the death penalty's
deterrent role, because he's weakening the consistency of the
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As of Oct. 1, 1998, there were 87 on Missouri's death row,
according to figures from the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational
Fund Inc. Missouri executions are by lethal injection or lethal
gas.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's intervention on behalf of Mease unfolded rapidly on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During a morning Mass attended by an estimated 100,000 people,
he called on Catholics to be ``unconditionally pro-life,'' a stance
in which he included opposition to the death penalty. ``Modern
society has the means of protecting itself without definitively
denying criminals the chance to reform,'' the pope said. He called
for ``a consensus to end the death penalty, which is both cruel and
unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican's secretary
of state, who was traveling with the pope, invited Carnahan to an
afternoon meeting at the residence of St. Louis Archbishop Justin
Rigali. ``The governor was asked to come to my residence, precisely
to discuss this case, and he very graciously agreed,'' said Rigali,
who also attended, along with Joaquin Navarro Valls, the pope's
chief spokesman. Carnahan was accompanied by Joe Bednar, his chief
legal counsel, and Angie Heffner, another state legal counsel.
Rigali said the meeting lasted 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Carnahan attended the interfaith prayer service with his
wife, Jean, sharing a front pew with Vice President Al Gore Jr. and
Tipper Gore. The service ended about 6 p.m., after which the pope
stepped away from the altar and came forward, blessing some
children, speaking to local religious leaders, then greeting Gore.
``And then he stopped and talked to me and asked me to show mercy
to Mease,'' Carnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an unusual circumstance, having a papal visit in St.
Louis,'' Carnahan said. ``It was a very high and emotional event in
itself. And the pope, during his time there, to show particular
interest in this individual, to seek me out to discuss that,
through his secretary of state and then personally, moved me very
greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sifford, the governor's spokesman, said Carnahan made up
his mind to commute Mease's sentence at about 9 p.m. Wednesday
night, shortly after the pope had departed on a return flight to
Rome. He signed the commutation order Thursday morning, Sifford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, the former Taney County prosecutor, said the governor's
office called him for his opinion Wednesday before Carnahan reached
a decision. ``I told them I felt when I prosecuted the case that it
was a death penalty case and I still think that,'' he said. He
added that he had prosecuted 20 murder cases and sought the death
penalty only twice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tyler, Mease's attorney, said she called her client at the
state correctional center in Potosi to share the news. ``He felt
much like I did, overwhelmed, grateful to the pope and to the
governor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lexie Mease, Mease's mother, said, ``Oh, there are just no words
to describe how thankful and happy we are!'' She also said she had
been expecting news like this since her son's sentencing. ``I've
been listening and looking for it and today it came,'' said Mrs.
Mease, 71. ``We knew God was on Darrell's side and God is the best
lawyer you can get. He's never lost a case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
