<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIP LATE, BUT ANDERSON READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He had grown up around greatness, and on draft day in
1994, Jamal Anderson decided it was time for his own ship to come
in.
</P>
<P>
   So, mama Zenobia hosted the first _ and likely last _
draft-watching party in Anderson family history.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal said he had heard from scouts to expect to be drafted
sometime in the first three rounds. But round two passed ...
followed by round three ... and then Mel Kiper and ESPN signed off.
And in the middle of the draft's second day, still unselected,
Jamal Anderson snuggled up to his napping mother and began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   For 21 years, he had held his own. He had playfully kept ``Uncle
Muhammad'' from hogging all the movie popcorn, and he had
out-wrestled a house guest named Tyson for the TV remote control.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 25 years, Jamal Anderson's father, James, has
served as a sort of Security Man for the Stars. The ``Uncle'' was
the Greatest, Muhammad Ali. The TV buddy's first name was Mike.
Actor/comedian Richard Pryor let him roller skate around the house.
Disco queen Donna Summer read him bedtime stories.
</P>
<P>
   But on that draft day in 1994, Anderson was reminded that
greatness wasn't a routine phone call.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Atlanta Falcons called, 200 other players and 23
other running backs had already been picked. It was the draft's
seventh round, the final round.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Uncle Muhammad'' would remind Jamal, that didn't mean the
fight was over.
</P>
<P>
   Far from it, as it turned out. On a bright morning in south
Florida, Anderson was beaming. The last shall be first. The
last-round running back rushed for 1,846 yards, and the eternally
grounded Atlanta Falcons are just hours from their first Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no bad days for Jamal Anderson,'' he assessed.
``We're here, and we're the only two teams playing for the world
championship. It's the greatest athletic stage there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is good, Anderson said. If the bright lights of Super Bowl
XXXIII are bringing a lump to some Falcons' throats, he is too busy
smiling, soaking it in, to notice it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has a lot to do with your foundation,'' Anderson
explained. ``My mother and father didn't allow us to live our life
in any special way. Regardless of who was around our house, we
treated everybody the same. Sugar Ray Leonard didn't eat before
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   James Anderson had worked as a policeman in Newark, N.J., and as
a lieutenant at a Muslim mosque. The senior Anderson met Ali at a
convention, and Muhammad was struck by the resemblance to the
champ's brother. He all but gave James a lifetime security contract
on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   When Jamal was seven years old, the Andersons left New Jersey
for southern California, and James' security business mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   Stars and celebrities-to-be began showing up on the Anderson
doorstep. Hall of Fame running back Jim Brown taught the
then-9-year-old Jamal to stiff-arm would-be kid tacklers. Ali made
him stand in line and buy 15 tickets for the entourage to see
``Return of the Jedi''.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal even thought about boxing _ once _ when that Tyson fellow
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of mock slap-boxing _ you know how you get with
your buddies?'' Anderson recalled. ``You duck, acting like you're a
boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamal's thespian skills, as it turned out, surpassed his boxing
ones. Tyson, for some reason, suddenly swung back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had kind of a flashback,'' Anderson said, who felt
a sudden stiff breeze knock him backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, like, `Twenty-second timeout. This game is over.' ''
He hasn't tried to box since.
</P>
<P>
   It took two stops for Anderson to finish his college football
career _ ``I had too many days like Ferris Buehler,'' he explained.
Some scouts saw him as a fullback type, or as a thick-legged
one-dimensional halfback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find yourself in a situation where you were either
unwanted or overlooked,'' Anderson said. ``So, it's a constant
motivator. Other people constantly remind you of things you aren't
supposed to do. People don't think players like myself or Terrell
Davis \Ranother late-round pick\S should be achieving these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely always prominent in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Those thick legs carried the football a record 410 times during
the regular season. The same scouts who once suggested he was
one-dimensional are now comparing Anderson to Earl Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons are to have a chance against the favored Denver
Broncos on Sunday, the ringing consensus is that Anderson has to
put on an MVP-caliber performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for us,'' said Anderson, who
doesn't shy from the notepads or minicams. ``This is the ultimate
stage. I've been a spectator for so many Super Bowls that I'm happy
to finally be a part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he was last, but on Sunday, Jamal Anderson will run for
first.
</P>
<P>
   He says it's his turn to be the star around the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
