<HEADLINE>
EX-TROJAN IACENDA TRANSFERS TO NEW MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Hart High and USC running back Ted Iacenda
has decided to transfer to New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda left USC last month, after wanting a fresh start because
of the stress he said he felt for more than two years after being
charged _ and subsequently cleared _ of sexual assault charges
brought during his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons Iacenda decided to attend New Mexico was
offensive coordinator Jim Fenwick, the former head coach at Cal
State Northridge and Valley College.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to run a new offense, kind of like what Hart
does,'' Iacenda said. ``And I like Jim Fenwick a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the stress-related circumstances of his case, the
NCAA waived Iacenda's residency requirements, which means he will
be immediately eligible next season at New Mexico. He will have two
years of eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda also considered Brigham Young, Fresno State, Nevada-Las
Vegas, Boston College and Colorado before selecting the Lobos.
Iacenda's father, Andy, said his son was prohibited by USC coach
Paul Hackett from going to another Pacific-10 Conference school or
any schools on future USC schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the schools that contacted Iacenda wanted him to enroll
in the fall, because he did not receive his official release from
USC until after schools had already begun their winter semesters.
New Mexico was willing to offer a scholarship immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Mexico was the only one who took a chance,'' Iacenda said.
``I didn't want to wait until the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda leaves for Albuquerque today and will be able to
participate in spring practice with the Lobos.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda led Hart to the Division II title in 1995 and was a
two-time Division II Player of the Year. Iacenda scored a Southern
Section-record 99 touchdowns at Hart, and had 604 points in his
career, second-most in state history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-28-99 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
