<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CBS-TAX-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CBS IS GRANTED MORE TAX CUTS TO STAY PUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six years after New York City granted CBS Inc. nearly
$50 million in tax breaks to stay in Manhattan until the year 2008,
the city has given it an additional $10 million in subsidies _
after being told the company was considering relocating to New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old deal, the company had pledged to spend $300
million to upgrade its studios on West 57th Street with digital
equipment. But it only started doing so 18 months ago. The new deal
extends the company's commitment to Manhattan for an additional 10
years, until 2018, and city officials said it contains new
assurances that the network will make the investment that it had
earlier promised.
</P>
<P>
   CBS told city officials last spring that it was considering
moving its studios to the Newport Office Center, on the waterfront
in Jersey City. That apparently sent the city scrambling to keep
the CBS jobs from heading to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Levine, the deputy mayor for economic development, said
Thursday that the city agreed to provide the additional benefits
because there was a real danger that CBS would have moved to New
Jersey, despite the company's 1993 pledge to remain in Manhattan
until 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat was very real,'' Levine said. ``We made this deal
competitive with the offer from New Jersey that they were
considering. The fact that we can secure their presence for the
next 20 years is very good for the city.'' CBS also committed
itself to keeping its corporate offices, now at 51st Street and
Avenue of the Americas, in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of such so-called corporate retention deals said that
the new subsidies amounted to a reward for a company that was
threatening to break its original agreement with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no standards,'' said Ronnie Eldridge, a city
councilwoman in whose West Side district the CBS studios are
located. ``They're just giving away benefits to large companies. If
we were as tough on corporations as we are on poor people, the city
would have more to spend on schools, bridges and subways.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana McClintock, director of communications at CBS, said that
the latest agreement, which he called an ``amendment'' to the
original deal with the city, recognized that CBS had undergone many
changes in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal with CBS requires the network to maintain at least
as many employees in New York City as the 1993 agreement: a minimum
of 3,862 full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   Real-estate developers and economic development officials in
Jersey City said they doubted that CBS was serious about relocating
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gallagher, director of economic development in Jersey
City, said that Jersey City officials had met with CBS last spring.
But, he said, nothing came of it, and no offer was made to give CBS
any benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some conversations,'' Gallagher said. ``I wouldn't say
they were negotiations. At some point, we moved on to other
prospects. In their case, a New York location is probably better
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have come under increasing criticism for granting
tax breaks to a multitude of companies that have threatened to flee
New York without assessing whether the threat is real. Critics say
the subsidy packages shift the city's tax burden to small and
medium-sized companies and rob the city's treasury of desperately
needed funds.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of moving is not always illusory. CIGNA Healthcare
and U.S. Trust Co. announced Thursday that they would move about
1,000 employees from Manhattan to the Newport Center.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Giuliani administration, the city had given 43
companies, including Conde Nast, Bear Stearns and Reuters, a total
of more than $1.5 billion in tax breaks, cash and subsidized
electricity. The New York Times received a similar tax break, for a
printing plant in College Point, Queens, during the Dinkins
administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
