<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL BETTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to respected Las Vegas gambling figure Jimmy Vaccaro,
the wagering on Super Bowl XXXIII is unfolding much like in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is looking to lay the points and the wise guys are
looking to take them,'' says Vaccaro, a wise guy himself who is
going against his brethren and taking Denver and laying seven
points against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the spread on Sunday's match is now up to 7{ at many
betting parlors, which is not surprising to Vacarro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say four of the five tickets written at the sports books
are on Denver,'' says Vaccaro. ``The public simply overpowers the
wise guys on this game. And I think about 15 out of the past 20
games, the public has been right. The favorite usually covers the
spread in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaccaro says the one betting proposition that has been most
enticing for the wise guys in this Super Bowl has been the
unders/overs, which had held steady at 54 but now is down to 53{.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-four is the highest unders/overs total in the history of
the Super Bowl,'' says Vaccaro ``Almost all the wise guys I know
took the unders at that number. I took it, and bet a lot more on
this than I did on the game itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaccaro, the former director of the Mirage's sports and race
book who now has his own sports betting tout service, predicts a
record amount will be bet on this Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many new casinos in Las Vegas, and that means
more people will be in town to bet on the game,'' he says. ``It's
going to be a zoo here in Las Vegas on game day. I'll watch the
game from the comfort of my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too.
</P>
<P>
   And I won't become depressed no matter what happens during the
game.
</P>
<P>
   I've beaten the bookmakers every year now since Jan. 1, 1991 in
the only way it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   I don't bet. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The old Long Beach sporting gentleman, Mike Economou, now
doing his betting quite legally in Las Vegas, has perhaps the most
interesting wagering proposition on the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He has one bet on Denver plus 3{---this is not a misprint---and
another on Atlanta plus 7{, as he's looking to middle the game.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to get points on the Broncos when the sports books
around Las Vegas posted the AFC Super Bowl entrant as a 3{-point
underdog before the Minnesota-Atlanta match, figuring the Vikings
would be representing the NFC on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons upset the Vikings, giving those bettors like
Economu who sensed that would happen a huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Economou, a colorful character who once was this city's highest
profile bookmaker until chased out of town in 1986 by an obsessive
Long Beach vice cop named Big John Stolpe, is a 1961 Wilson High
graduate whose best friend, former major leaguer Bob Bailey, also
now resides in Las Vegas. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Down in Dominica, a small, tropical island in the Caribbean,
Paul (The Librarian) Lisenby, still another Long Beach native
heavily involved in sports gambling, reports business has been
brisk for him this week on the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time ever, there will be more money wagered on
this Super Bowl with the off-shore sports betting places than in
the Nevada sports books,'' claims Lisenby, who's in charge of the
World Wide Wagering outfit. ``We're expecting it to exceed $600
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisenby, one-time owner of the old Naples Grill and Sports
restaurant and a 1978 Jordan High graduate, has been in Dominica
for the past 3{ years.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been an easy gig for him, as he routinely puts in
12-hour shifts, seven days a week and has been away for long
periods from his wife and two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, finally, it's starting to pay off,'' he says. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Snow's annual preseason Dirtbag banquet turned out to be
quite a success Wednesday night at the Hyatt, although I held the
ignoble distinction during the uplifting event of being the only
person to be booed when introduced.
</P>
<P>
   I heard later the jeers came from the Dirtbag's most zany
booster, Craig (Cucumber) Vestermark, which figured. The guy who's
usually pickled wasn't. In fact, it was learned through anonymous
sources he was on the wagon, and had been so for at least 24 hours!
No wonder he hooted at me. He had nothing better to do. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Malone was the keynote speaker, and, after he gave the
obligatory praise to Snow, he gave the obligatory praise to the
Dodgers and, in essence, to himself for bringing in Kevin Brown,
Devon White, Todd Hundley and the those other high-priced
off-season acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to see the Dirtbags in the College World Series in
the early summer and the Dodgers in the World Series in October,''
said Malone, who I thought came off well. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Sportscaster Ed Arnold, a Long Beach State graduate, did his
usual competent job in handling the emcee duties. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ But Does He Make As Much As Don Dyer? Long Beach State
president Dr. Robert (Fightin' Bob) Maxson had the funniest line of
the evening when he said: ``Long Beach State is the first school
I've worked at where I'm making more money than the athletic
coaches.''.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Maxson will throw out the first ball on Long Beach
State Night on April 21 at the Dodger-Atlanta game at Dodger
Stadium. The NCAA-winning women volleyballers will be honored in
pregame ceremonies. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The Long Beach Fun Couple, ex Olympian Susie Atwood and ex
Secret Service agent Daring Dave Butler, just back from a weekend
rendezvous in San Francisco, was a noticeable presence at the
Dirtbag affair. When is Daring Dave going to live up to his
nickname and pop the marriage question to Susie?. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ If the Long Beach Convention Bureau chief, Linda
Howell-DiMario, ever wants to go into another vocation, she should
become an auctioneer. She was terrific in that role during the
Dirtbag silent auction, raising several thousand dollars with her
persuasive, non-stop rhetoric. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Are the Lakers now seeking the Charlotte power forward,
Anthony Mason, in lieu of missing out on Tom Gugilotta? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ I made one huge mistake in my recent European visit. I went to
Prague. The only way I'd ever return to this overrated city is if I
was guaranteed all its thieving taxi cab drivers had been thrown
into jail. I did make one terrific choice: Dresden. Known as the
Florence by the Elbe before it was needlessly destroyed at the end
World War II, this German city still is a great art center. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ For those of you who love Bill Clinton and despise Kenneth
Starr, who love Larry Flynt and despise Bob Barr, who love Geraldo
Rivera and despise Patrick Buchanan, then tune in to KABC radio
(790 AM) between 7 p.m. and 10 p.m. Saturday night and listen to
The Big Liberal, Joe McDonnell, do a general talk show. If you
thought Joe was entertainingly insane when doing sports---and I
did---he's even more wacko in this format. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ San Pedro real estate mogul Van (Hate `Em All) Barbieri,
former Olympic Auditorium boxing publicist and George Allen aide,
has shed 35 pounds in the past two months by going on the only diet
that works. He stopped eating so much food. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ I don't care about Lawrence Taylor off-the-field activities.
On the field, he was the best linebacker ever to play in the NFL
and he belongs in the Hall of Fame. So does George Allen, who never
had a losing season and definitely ranks among the top coaches in
NFL history. . .
</P>
<P>
   I haven't spoken to one person in football I respect who thinks
the Atlanta Falcons will beat the Denver Broncos. Therefore, I'm
going with the Falcons. . .
</P>
<P>
   Phil Trani, the Godfather of UCLA quarterbacks, was all smiles
the other evening when he welcomed back to his restaurant one of
his ``sons,'' Rick Neuheisel, now a millionaire football coach at
Washington. . .
</P>
<P>
   What would the unders/overs totals be on the number of freebies
accepted over the years by IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch and
WBC president Jose Sulaiman? I'd place it at, oh, 50,000, and take
the overs.
</P>
</TEXT>
