u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-TV-ANCHOR-SUIT-N     01-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-TV-ANCHOR-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS ANCHORWOMAN $8.3 MILLION IN SEX BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Challenging the common television practice of
choosing news anchors on the basis of their sex, a federal jury
awarded $8.3 million Thursday to a Hartford anchorwoman who
contended that she lost her high-profile and high-paying job
because she was a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The anchorwoman, Janet Peckinpaugh, had charged that the
managers of the CBS station here had decided not to renew her
contract in 1994 because they had three anchorwomen and two
anchormen, and decided in advance to drop one of the women to make
the pairs come out even. Ms. Peckinpaugh, who is now 48, had also
accused the station of jettisoning her because of her age.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of five men and three women in U.S. District Court here
found that Post-Newsweek Stations Inc., the owner of the Hartford
station at the time, did not discriminate against Ms. Peckinpaugh
on the basis of age.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury ruled that the company and in some cases three of
its executives discriminated against her on the basis of gender,
breached her contract, made false statements to her suggesting she
could be assured of long-term employment, and retaliated against
her for complaining about an incident in which she said she had
been sexually harassed by her male co-anchor. The jury's award was
twice the amount that Ms. Peckinpaugh had sought.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict sent a jolt through an industry built on the nearly
universal pairing of attractive men and women to read the news at 6
and 11 o'clock. ``Good grief,'' said Barbara S. Cochran, the
president of the Radio-Television News Directors Association, when
told the size of the award. She said broadcasters made such
pairings because they replicate ``the man and woman in the
audience.'' She added: ``That helps the audience feel the whole
newscast is relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   David A. Klatell, the director of the broadcast journalism
program at the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism,
estimated that 90 percent of evening news programs in the United
States feature male and female co-anchors. He said news directors
seem to have ``a religious certainty'' that such pairings are the
best. ``I get a lot of calls from employers asking about our alumni
who say, `I need a male,' or `I need a female,' '' Klatell said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, during the trial, the president of Post-Newsweek
Stations, G. William Ryan, testified that male-female couplings of
anchors are common and even desirable. ``We don't have such a
policy, but it is a general practice in the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing 18 witnesses during the eight-day trial, the jury
deliberated for just four hours. One juror, Bernard F. Woodard,
said in a telephone interview that he found the evidence clear.
``Most everyone understands it's the industry practice _ male and
female,'' he said. ``But you can't discriminate on the basis of
sex, and they were blatant about that from their own records.''
</P>
<P>
   The gender issue arose when the station, WFSB, Channel 3, asked
its three female anchors to tape auditions with a new male anchor,
then did not renew Ms. Peckinpaugh's contract after she scored the
lowest with viewers on several key measures. The other two women,
both younger, were paired with the two male anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Peckinpaugh testified that station executives never
considered pairing two women, but rather were intent on keeping the
male-female teams. In addition, Ms. Peckinpaugh testified that
several executives told her that the station had ``too many
women.'' On the stand, those executives testified that they
actually said the station had too many anchors.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the jury found that Ryan and two other
Post-Newsweek executives ``aided and abetted discrimination,'' and
that the company ``acted with malice or with reckless indifference
to Ms. Peckinpaugh's federal right against gender discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-Newsweek Stations, a division of The Washington Post Co.,
had contended that it had no obligation to Ms. Peckinpaugh beyond
her four-year contract, which ended in 1994. She remained on the
air, although in an assignment she considered a demotion. After the
verdict, Ryan, the Post-Newsweek Stations president, said that
discrimination laws apply to hiring, not to pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should have been a simple case about whether management
had a right to let a contract terminate,'' he said. ``All these
other things got spun onto it as satellites. They did a very good
job of spinning a web of confusing facts and dates.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the company would appeal the award.
</P>
<P>
   Out of her job at the CBS station, Ms. Peckinpaugh saw her
annual salary drop from $250,000 to $45,000 when she accepted a job
in 1995 as the early-morning anchor at the NBC station in Hartford.
She still has that job, and is now paid $80,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major victory for every woman in television, and
every woman who wants to go into television,'' Ms. Peckinpaugh said
outside the courthouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
