u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON29-COX     01-28 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson pushes for `access to capital,' youth mentoring
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There are two sides to the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson
Sr.
</P>
<P>
   There's the charismatic orator who speaks in hypnotic rhythms.
There is Jackson the nomadic politician who in 1988 made an
unsuccessful, but impressive pitch for the Democratic U.S.
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Like a series of intertwined electrical wires, it was difficult
to tell where part of the man ended and another part began as he
spoke Thursday night at the United Theological Seminary in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   After the singing and praying, Jackson touted his latest
initiative: to link 1,000 U.S. churches by the Internet to create
investment and consumer clubs. Jackson also wants church leaders to
establish relationships with juvenile court judges to mentor
troubled youth as part of his ``Reclaim Our Youth Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow/Push Coalition leader said while blacks are free of
chattel slavery, legal segregation and now have the right to vote,
the final frontier to conquer is ``access to capital.'' He favors
building bridges between Wall Street and poor whites and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all of the first three and still starve,''
Jackson told the nearly 200 people during his one-hour pitch. ``You
have the right to vote but you're too weak to get to the voting
booth because you're hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to fight this economic fight.''
</P>
<P>
   With massive investments in corporations, Jackson explained,
comes clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose each church bought 10 shares of Microsoft and went to
the next board meeting, which is all white,'' Jackson theorized.
``That would change. There's no corporation who can say ``no'' to
us with this degree of organization. ``
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was as fiery about youth mentoring and education as he
was about investing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jackson, it costs $51,000 to imprison an individual
in Ohio, but $6,000 a year to educate a student. In addition, the
average school building in Appalachia is 46 years old and half of
southern Ohio schools hold classes in temporary locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``And not far away are these first-class jails,'' he added. ``It
costs so much less to educate them on the front side than to
incarcerate them on the back side. Let's teach them how to read the
stock page and not just the sports page.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Schools superintendent James Williams, present at the
event, lauded Jackson's efforts, saying the two initiatives go
hand-in-hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stronger our economic clout, the better our institutions
will be in our communities,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
