<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-OLINE-HNS     01-28 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-OLINE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ The average sports fan likely hasn't heard of Calvin
Collins or Gene Williams or Ephraim Salaam. They might not have
heard of Robert Tobeck or Bob Whitfield.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the Atlanta Falcons will tell you Jamal Anderson wouldn't be
the second-leading rusher in the NFL and Chris Chandler wouldn't be
going to the Pro Bowl if not for the improved production from these
five, Atlanta's starting offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The group boasts no superstars, though Whitfield was added to
the Pro Bowl roster at left tackle this week. Tobeck, the center,
began his career in 1993 on the developmental squad. Salaam, a
seventh-round draft pick, not only made the team but starts as a
rookie at right tackle. Texas A&AMP;M ex Collins, a sixth-rounder in
1997, was converted from center to starting left guard this season.
Williams, at right guard, is in his eighth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got drafted in the seventh round,'' Salaam said. ``There are
a lot of guys who got drafted in the first through sixth rounds who
have millions of dollars but haven't played a snap in the NFL, and
I'd rather be in the situation I am in right now. I wouldn't trade
this situation for millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The season began with Collins and Tobeck exchanging positions.
Throw in one new face _ Salaam _ and only two positions remained
solid. It was not surprising the line was awful. Salaam was
manhandled by Kevin Greene, Carolina's perennial Pro Bowler, in
Week 1. By the end of Week 3, Atlanta had allowed 16 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that with Art Shell as our (offensive line) coach, a
Hall of Fame player who had been to four Super Bowls, we'd
eventually come around if we'd listen to what he had to say,''
Collins said. ``He was successful. He knows how to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins has improved as much as anyone. The Beaumont native
received one of those draft-day surprises as he waited and waited
and waited but didn't hear his name called. The four-year starter
for the Aggies had been predicted to be a late-third- or
early-fourth-round draft pick, but many teams thought he was too
short, at 6-2 and 307 pounds, to be an NFL lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happens to your psyche, your whole mindset,''
Collins said. ``And I have ESPN2 (which shows the late rounds), so
I saw everybody get drafted in front of me. I kept thinking, `Wait,
I'm better than him. I'm better than him.' And every time you hear,
`offensive lineman,' you think, `maybe, maybe, maybe' then they say
somebody else's name. By the time I got drafted, it was just, `Oh,
thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   But when Collins got to Atlanta before the 1997 season, he found
he knew no more or no less than anybody else. It didn't matter that
he was a rookie, because the team was switching from the
run-and-shoot that it ran under former head coach June Jones to a
more traditional run-oriented offense under new coach Dan Reeves.
Everybody was just as lost as he was.
</P>
<P>
   Four games into the season, he won the starting center job and
called the plays for the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a rookie at the quarterback position of the offensive
line _ that didn't help,'' he said. ``I had some growing pains.
There were a couple of times out there when I'd try to make a call
and I'd be like, `OK, what do I do?' I'd look around, and they'd be
quiet, too. They didn't know what to do, either. There were some
definite growing pains, but I think toward the end of the year we
started to play better. Then this year, we took it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta allowed 54 sacks last season as the line struggled to
learn the schemes. But as the season progressed, the line became
more comfortable. And as the line got more comfortable, the Falcons
started winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the New Orleans game (game 12) last year,''
Collins said of the turnaround. ``I think we played with some
emotion and we had some success and we discovered, `Hey, we can be
a good offensive line. We can run the ball. We can impose our will
on people.' It was a confidence thing. I think that game was
crucial for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why Anderson rushed for 1,002 yards in '97, most of those
coming in the second half. Chandler threw for 2,692 yards. He had
seven 200-yard passing games from Week 7 on. But those numbers
don't compare to this season, when Anderson rushed for 1,846 yards
in the regular season and Chandler threw for 3,154 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our record and offensive production has gone, it's really
based upon how the offensive line has played,'' Chandler said.
``They really struggled the first half of last season, (but) they
played awesome the second half of last season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
