<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3433 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-OLINE-HNS     01-28 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-OLINE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Broncos guard Dan Neil used to hate quarterback John Elway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why? Because Elway engineered the winning field-goal drive in
the second round of the 1991 playoffs that pulled out a victory
over Neil's favorite team, the Houston Oile &QL; 
rs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I was cussing John like crazy,'' Neil says about that
26-24 Denver victory. ``I just knew the Oilers were going to pull
that one out, but they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil is a Houston native who attended Cypress Creek High School
and the University of Texas. Neil's favorite players were Oilers
offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never stood up in football,'' he says, laughing. ``I've
played my entire career in a three-point stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's why I loved to watch guys like (Bruce)
Matthews, (Mike) Munchak, (Dean) Steinkuhler and (Jay) Pennison.
When Munchak, Matthews and Steinkuhler were the No. 1 picks three
straight years, they were the foundation for those playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked watching Matthews best. He was such a great player.
Still is. I really admired Munchak, too. I've never told them that.
I'm sure that's the last thing they'd want to hear from a
second-year guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Matthews and Munchak might want to hear about the
Super Bowl XXXII ring Neil got as a rookie. Or perhaps they would
like to hear about his goal of earning rings in his first two
seasons with the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was what every veteran hates _ a rookie in the
Super Bowl,'' Neil says. ``For me to get a ring as a rookie and
think how Matthews and Munchak have never been in this situation,
well, it makes me feel sorry for them because of everything they've
accomplished individually.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil shouldn't feel sorry for anyone. He has earned the right to
be where he is. With the Longhorns, he was a four-year starter. The
Broncos drafted him in the third round, but a groin injury
curtailed his rookie season. When he was active, he played on
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, veteran guard Brian Habib signed with Seattle,
leaving a spot available. Neil stepped in, and the offense has been
even better this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason we're able to plug in other guys is because of
Alex's philosophy,'' Neil says, referring to line coach Alex Gibbs.
``He lets the second- and third-team linemen get almost as many
reps as the veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pro Bowl left tackle Gary Zimmerman retired, backup Harry
Swayne moved into the lineup on the right side and Tony Jones moved
from right to left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tribute to the guys in this room that we made
those changes, and the results have been as good or better,'' left
guard Mark Schlereth says. ``We've got great study habits, and
we're a cohesive unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play real hard for each other. We're a tight-knit group.
Any change isn't going to be dramatic for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Individually, the Broncos' linemen are not stars. Jones and
center Tom Nalen are going to the Pro Bowl. Collectively, though,
they make up the best line in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the linemen block well enough to help running back
Terrell Davis rush for 2,008 yards and score 23 touchdowns in the
regular season, but they allowed only 25 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work well together,'' Neil says. ``We do an excellent job
of communicating. We know how to adjust. We have an answer for
anything the defense might try against us. Because we communicate
so well, we do a good job of making adjustments. The truth is,
Terrell's become a better back this season. He's a great all-around
back, and we're an all-around team.''
</P>
<P>
   No Broncos offensive lineman missed a start this season. Even
Schlereth, who has undergone surgery on his knees more than 20
times, didn't miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get hurt, you keep playing because you don't want to
let one of your teammates down,'' Neil says. ``How can you get hurt
and miss a game when you see Mark over there busting his butt after
all those surgeries?''
</P>
<P>
   No one appreciates the effort and determination of the linemen
more than Davis. He rewarded them with Rolex watches after last
season. He's planning something special again after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have the kind of success I do without them,'' Davis
says. ``When I get the ball, I try to be patient and wait to see
where the hole is. Then, I try to burst through it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have the lightest line in the NFL _ the starting
five average 287 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some systems, I'd have to play center,'' says Neil, 6-2 and
281 pounds. ``But I came to the right system to take advantage of
my size and talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The system belongs to Gibbs, who has been one of the better line
coaches in the league for years. He wants his players to rely on
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Alex is a great coach,'' head coach Mike
Shanahan says. ``He likes guys who can move. Quickness is
essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, his guys have to be strong enough to
pass-protect and yet have the mobility and agility to block for the
running game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
