<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REGENTS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME NEW YORK SCHOOLS FIGHTING NEW REGENTS EXAMS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To earn her diploma, Vanessa Gravenstine, a senior at
the Beacon School, a small alternative public school in New York
City, has been going through a process more familiar to doctoral
candidates at a university than to most teen-agers: To prove that
she met the New York state foreign-language requirement, she wrote
a play in French and presented it to a committee of teachers,
speaking French the whole time.
</P>
<P>
   To show that she is proficient in math, she will tell another
committee how she sat on a street in Manhattan and plotted the
probability that buses run in clumps rather than on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Now, schools like Beacon _ along with hundreds of private and
many traditional public schools across New York state _ are
fighting a new state decision to abolish homegrown and sometimes
idiosyncratic graduation requirements like portfolios and oral
examinations and to require every high school student in the state
take tough new Regents exams as a condition of graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The state's decree has led to fierce lobbying campaigns by New
York City's top private schools, religious schools, alternative
public schools and even some affluent suburban school districts to
be exempt from the new tests.
</P>
<P>
   The school leaders _ supported in New York City by Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew _ complain that the new state requirements
will impose stifling uniformity on curriculums and teaching styles,
forcing teachers to teach to the test and students to memorize
facts and figures rather than understanding material in depth.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials fear that granting exemptions could
undermine their efforts to make sure that all schools meet the same
high standard for graduation. And they worry that any move to relax
requirements for some schools will lead to dozens more requests for
exemptions from the state tests and perhaps even to lawsuits by
parents angry that their children have to take state tests while
others do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regents exams clearly represent high standards,'' Richard P.
Mills, the state education commissioner, said in an interview. ``I
don't see how taking a Regents exam or one of the fourth-grade
exams can be anything but good.''
</P>
<P>
   Regents exams, on a menu of subjects from English to physics to
Italian, have been given in New York state schools since 1865 (or
as James A. Kadamus, the state's deputy education commissioner, put
it, since the time of the Gettysburg Address). But until now only a
minimum competency test has been required for graduation. Only a
minority _ fewer than 25 percent of graduates in New York City _
have received diplomas certifying that they passed the more
difficult Regents exams.
</P>
<P>
   But Mills and the State Board of Regents, which oversees public
and private schools, say the competency tests allowed thousands of
students to graduate from high school woefully prepared for life
and work. The new exams are harder _ so much so that many educators
fear that they will lead to widespread failures and paralyze the
school system.
</P>
<P>
   The new exams are being phased in, beginning this June, when
11th-graders will be required to take the two-day, six-hour
reading, writing and listening test in English. The class of 2003
will be required to take five subject exams _ in math, science,
global studies, American history and government, and English.
</P>
<P>
   The dissident schools include a handful of affluent,
high-performing suburban school districts, including Scarsdale,
Bronxville, Mamaroneck and Chappaqua in Westchester County and
Brighton High School near Rochester, that do not award Regents
diplomas. Instead, they have relied on standardized tests like the
SAT and Advanced Placement tests, on tests written by their own
teachers and on their record of placing students in good colleges
to demonstrate their high standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an anti-Regents move,'' said Sherry P. King, the
superintendent of schools in Mamaroneck. ``It is absolutely schools
in support of higher standards, and looking for multiple ways that
we might be able to demonstrate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those schools admit that they may face painfully high
failure rates, as much as 25 percent, if their students are forced
to take Regents exams, said Michael V. McGill, the superintendent
in Scarsdale.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the independent schools, most Jewish and Catholic
schools have administered Regents exams to their students, but they
want to keep them voluntary, said Rabbi Martin Schloss, chairman of
a state advisory committee on nonpublic education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
