<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS, NELSON SAY THEY CAN BE CONTENDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Forward Cedric Ceballos submitted Wednesday that the
Mavericks have the makings of a playoff team. The re-signing of
Ceballos and the acquisition of forward Gary Trent and center John
``Hot Rod'' Williams also have generated playoff talk in and around
the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The closest coach Don Nelson came to predicting a playoff
journey for the Mavericks this season was after practice yesterday
when he broke down the playoff situation in the NBA's Western
Conference by groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson put Utah, the Los Angeles Lakers, Houston, Seattle and
San Antonio in the top tier in the West and lumped Portland and
Phoenix in the middle group. Then he casually mentioned that the
Mavericks should battle Minnesota for the eighth and final playoff
spot, with the addition of Chris Webber and Vlade Divac giving
Sacramento an outside chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at those other bottom dwellers, and Minnesota made
the playoffs the last two years,'' Nelson said. ``We should be able
to compete with those guys, and make a run at \Rthe playoffs\S
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we're not a playoff team; I'm saying I don't
know. We're still young, we haven't played together, and we're
going to have a hard start. There's a lot of questions we haven't
answered yet. But we're very confident. I love our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent time the Mavericks reached the playoffs was 1990
when they finished 47-35 and were swept by Portland in three games
in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   When the NBA's shortened season opens Feb. 5, Nelson likely will
start Michael Finley at shooting guard, Steve Nash at point guard,
Dirk Nowitzki at small forward, Samaki Walker at power forward, and
Williams at center. That leaves a second unit of Robert Pack and
Hubert Davis in the backcourt, Ceballos and Trent at forwards, and
Shawn Bradley in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't even take into consideration A.C. Green, Erick
Strickland, Chris Anstey and rookie Greg Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a situation where our second team will be better
than our first one,'' Nelson admitted. ``We may have one of those
kind of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Williams, Trent and Ceballos in the past week
give the Mavericks playoff-caliber depth. Williams is a solid
rebounder and defender, and Ceballos is a proven scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Trent is a powerful rebounder and swift enough to drive to the
basket or shoot over the sleek small forwards on the perimeter. But
even Trent, who played on a playoff team in Portland, hesitates to
link the Mavericks and playoffs in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential to go to the playoffs, but it depends on
our chemistry and how we play together and how we gel as a unit,''
Trent said. ``We have to understand each other and get a feel for
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Michael Finley said he knows why Nelson isn't flat-out
saying the Mavericks are a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're young, and youth is usually that factor that
either makes or breaks you,'' Finley said. ``Hopefully it can be
something we don't use as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a deep team, and depth goes a long way in this league.
Hopefully we can gel together and put some victories together and
be a team that earns some respect.'' REEVES IN LIMBO Guard Khalid
Reeves remains in limbo, because Don Nelson said he has been unable
to find a team to trade him to.
</P>
<P>
   ``No offers; nothing,'' Nelson said. ``He's an NBA player ...
but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nelson said Reeves' playing time would be drastically
reduced if he remained with the team, so he would do him a favor
and trade him just for a draft choice or a small amount of money.
</P>
</TEXT>
