<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     01-28 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GO WINDOW SHOPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bob Gainey might not be ready to order, but
he'll at least take a look at the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Today and Monday, the Stars general manager will get a
first-hand view of two of the players who are expected to be
auctioned off to the highest bidder before the March 23 trade
deadline _ left winger Wendel Clark of the Tampa Bay Lightning and
right winger Theo Fleury of the Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
   Stars president Jim Lites has acknowledged a need to add another
goal scorer, preferably one who can play left wing. Although Gainey
said he is not actively seeking a trade for any player but is
staying abreast of all trade talk, much of it centering on Fleury
and Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the NHL, there always has been and there always will be
ongoing discussion on players and where they might or might not
fit,'' Gainey said. ``As a group, we try to be aware of all of
those discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   That could mean face-to-face meetings with Lightning GM Jacques
Demers today and Flames GM Al Coates on Monday, but Gainey wouldn't
confirm that he would be talking to anyone within the next few
days. Gainey declined to speak to specifics concerning the interest
the Stars might have in any player, including Clark and Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   However, team president Jim Lites said fans shouldn't expect
Gainey to pull the trigger on any deal soon, especially if it
concerns a request for any of the Stars' younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very good team, and we have the ability to be a very
good team for years to come as long as we don't do something
stupid,'' Lites said. ``We're not going to mortgage the future to
take a chance on a player who might not even be here next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The caveat on the three major players available to the Stars is
that all three have contracts that expire at the end of the season.
Fleury and Mark Recchi of the Montreal Canadiens will be
unrestricted free agents, and Clark has an option year remaining on
his contract that would likely allow him to become a free agent
this summer. That could mean the Stars would trade a top prospect
and then risk losing the player they acquired.
</P>
<P>
   That's the main reason all three players are available. Fleury,
30, is a gritty, goal-scoring right winger who has said he will
test the free-agent market this summer even if traded before then.
Fleury, who is under contract for $2.4 million this season, is
expected to command between $5 million to $6 million on the open
market. The Flames can't pay that and likely will trade him rather
than lose him without getting anything in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens are faced with the same problem concerning Recchi,
30. The left-handed-shooting right winger, who played junior hockey
for Stars coach Ken Hitchcock in Kamloops, British Columbia, is
under contract for $4.5 million. If the Canadiens are in jeopardy
of missing the playoffs, they'll likely deal him.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clark, he is a bargain at $1.4 million this season.
However, the Lightning are trying to build with youth and are
expected to ask for a strong prospect in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendel has raised the price all by himself,'' Demers told the
Tampa Tribune of Clark's 19-goal season. ``We won't just be giving
Wendel Clark away, you can bet on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars might have the deepest group of prospects in the
league with defenseman Richard Jackman, winger Jason Botterill and
goalie Roman Turek among players the league GMs covet. Do not
expect Gainey to even consider dealing such players as Jamie
Langenbrunner or Richard Matvichuk, no matter how many GMs inquire.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars believe that if no trade can be made, Langenbrunner
playing out of position still is a solid left winger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are somewhat lopsided, but we still have talented players
playing the left side,'' Lites said. ``We've already given up Todd
Harvey and Jarome Iginla to improve the team, and that's already
eaten into the depth of our young players. We don't want to win the
\RStanley\S Cup and then be horrible in five or six years.''
</P>
<P>
   But they do want to win the Cup, and that could mean keeping
track of every trade scenario right up to the trade deadline _
although Gainey said he can't worry himself with what other teams
are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend your time trying to derail other teams, I don't
think you have your focus in the right area,'' Gainey said. ``If we
can make a move to improve our own roster, we'll look into it, but
not to take something from someone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
